<HEADLINE>
CANDIDATES FOR MAJOR OFFICES WIND UP NEW YORK CAMPAIGNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Scrambling for attention in the shadow of a
presidential visit, Democratic candidates for Senate and governor
brought their primary campaigns to a quiet close Monday, ending
contests that was notably short on acrimony and appeared to stir
little interest with the public.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates fanned out to traditional last-day campaign stops
_ subway stations and shopping malls, homes for the elderly and
television studios _ on a day when New York City was in the grip of
a visit by a president in the midst of a political crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, the candidates were resigned to winning only the
scantiest of attention on the final day of the race _ and then only
when answering questions about President Clinton's problems, or
appearing with Clinton at one of the Democratic fund-raisers staged
in New York on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Democratic primary voters will select candidates to run
for governor, senator, lieutenant governor and state attorney
general this November, and both major parties have primaries in
some local races as well. The contests that have drawn the most
attention have been to choose challengers to Sen. Alfonse D'Amato
and Gov. George Pataki, both Republicans seeking re-election.
</P>
<P>
   In this unusually subdued atmosphere and with party leaders
predicting that the primary would be distinguished by a low turnout
of voters, the candidates did what they could Monday to remind
voters that there is, in fact, an election Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   At the 72nd Street subway stop on the Upper West Side Monday
night, in the heart of a Manhattan neighborhood that has displayed
an unwavering interest in Democratic politics for almost 50 years,
they campaigned almost elbow to elbow, handing out literature to
people streaming up the narrow steps and onto the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hello, everybody, I'm Chuck Schumer,'' Rep. Charles Schumer
said, his shirt rumpled and without the jacket he had worn to one
of Clinton's receptions. The congressman from Brooklyn who is
running for Senate shared the small strip of sidewalk with James L.
Larocca, a candidate for governor, and Charles King, a candidate
for lieutenant governor, along with four television cameras.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am basically a meat-and-potatoes Democrat,'' Schumer said,
summing up his race at another stop earlier in the day. ``I talk
about issues that matter to people in their daily lives.''
</P>
<P>
   In Bedford-Stuyvesant in Brooklyn, another Senate candidate,
Mark Green, the New York City Public Advocate, slipped behind a
cash register at a local supermarket and began bagging groceries.
``I have been outadvertised and outfamed,'' Green said, referring
to Schumer's heavy television advertising and the celebrity of the
third candidate, Geraldine A. Ferraro. ``But I have not been
outworked or outissued.''
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Ms. Ferraro, a former congresswoman, spent the day
warning that she could be hurt if there wa a low turnout Tuesday.
She said repeatedly and publicly that her natural supporters, whom
she identified as elderly, minority and upstate voters, were less
likely to turn out automatically, especially if the weather was bad
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the ones who hug you, they're the ones who say, `We
really need you,' '' Ms. Ferraro said. ``But are they the ones who
always go to the polls? No.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If it ends up being a primary decided in Manhattan, I'll be
standing with my microphone in my hand the day after tomorrow,''
said Ms. Ferraro, who was a television commentator before she began
her second race for the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of a relatively hectic day, Schumer, Ms. Ferraro
and Green all took time to join Clinton as he helped national
Democrats raise close to $4 million in New York, a gesture that the
president took appreciative note of in his remarks at one of the
fund-raisers, an early dinner for 400 people at the Supper Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``All three of the candidates for the United States Senate in
New York on our ticket tomorrow have come here tonight,'' Clinton
said. By contrast, he made no mention of the four gubernatorial
candidates, presumably because only one of them _ Betsy McCaughey
Ross _ had planned to join Clinton Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Peter F. Vallone, the city council speaker and the best-financed
of the candidates for governor, said he was skipping Clinton's
fund-raisers because of the press of preprimary campaign demands.
But Vallone's public schedule listed no evening events, and the
speaker, talking to reporters, suggested another explanation for
his absence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm going to relax with my wife,'' Vallone said.
``It's not that I'm too busy to go. Everything I'm doing is geared
to my primary. The big thing for me is having dinner with my
wife.''
</P>
<P>
   Larocca, a former state commissioner, and the other Democratic
candidate for governor, Charles J. Hynes, the Brooklyn district
attorney, also skipped the event.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Democratic candidates had objected to Clinton's
visiting New York on the eve of the primary even before they knew
that he would be coming three days after the release of the report
by Kenneth Starr, the independent counsel, detailing allegations
about Clinton's affair with a White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   The original concern was that Clinton would siphon money out of
the state that could go to the gubernatorial and Senate races, as
well as obscure the candidates for office in the final hours of the
contest.
</P>
<P>
   But with Clinton's political situation so volatile, and with the
president historically popular in New York _ particularly among
Democrats _ some of the Democrats actually seemed to be going to
modest lengths Monday to actually align themselves with him.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer, for example, made his way to the front of the receiving
line where, the congressman later told reporters, he offered words
of support to the president. ``I told the president what I heard on
the street the last few days, which was far more support for him
than detraction of him,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Green, speaking to reporters after campaigning in Great Neck on
Long Island and then riding the Long Island Rail Road back into New
York City made a point of announcing that he would squeeze in a
visit with the president between subway stops and his own less
ambitious fund-raiser, which featured Chinese food and a
performance by Peter, Paul and Mary at the home of Peter Yarrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's my friend, he's my president,'' Green said. ``He erred,
he acted inexcusably but not impeachably.''
</P>
</TEXT>
