<SLUG> BC-MILLER5-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Knees or not? Nicole Miller goes for cover-up
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Which came first: the ``chicken'' or the leg?
</P>
<P>
   Put another way: Are women prone by nature to prefer the modest
look of long skirts, or are the lower hemlines that will carry over
from this fall/winter season into spring/summer merely a designer
dictate women follow against their wishes?
</P>
<P>
   That's the question to ponder now that the spring/summer '99
women's wear previews are under way. And it's a question Nicole
Miller appears disinclined to answer definitively.
</P>
<P>
   Miller's show Monday led off this week of presentations by a
splinter group of New Yorkers daring to unveil their collections
before the Europeans get their chance. And rather than make a
declarative statement on hemlines, Miller sought a compromise
between her own preference for shorter skirts and the industry's
fixation with length.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're showing a lot of longer looks,'' Miller's national sales
manager, Lisa Brigham, said, ``but we're not giving up on short.''
</P>
<P>
   If she's not giving up, Miller's collection of skirts and
dresses cut to the knee or midcalf indicate she's giving in. The
abundance of satiny ballerina shoes that Miller's models wore was
another sign that the designer who'd scoffed at flats during a
recent visit to her Lenox Square boutique can't resist following
the trends entirely.
</P>
<P>
   Miller's main fabrications were synthetics, and her colors of
choice were blue (pale, Pacific and ink), pistachio green and
pomegranate red. Her prints were floral, reptilian or wafflelike.
She designed a number of simple separates in stretch denim,
loosened the silhouette of Capri pants to make them look more like
gauchos and offered a large sampling of sweater sets with eyelet
detailing.
</P>
<P>
   Other designers showing collectively Monday at the Fashion
Coterie trade show were much more resolute in their adherence to
dominant trends.
</P>
<P>
   Clingy knit tops and dresses _ in cutting-edge synthetics or
cashmere _ and long skirts as well were everywhere. Rebecca
Danenberg, a New Yorker who's developed a star-studded clientele
that includes Courtney Love, Claire Danes and Jennifer Lopez,
showed knits that featured plunging necklines, sheer tanks under
matching, buttonless cardigans, hooded short-sleeved pullovers and
strapless body dresses.
</P>
<P>
   Diane von Furstenberg, who _ according to daughter Alexandra _
is ``still in discussion'' over whether to stage a runway show in
November, showed her trademark temptress dresses in subtle prints
shaded blue or pastel pink in either silk or jersey knit. Most
dresses were long enough to skim the calf, and all sleeves were
cropped just below the elbow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sweaters are tighter, skirts are looser and pants are
shorter,'' Julie Chaiken of Chaiken &AMP; Capone announced as she
sifted through racks of knits colored pink, purple, mint and
yellow, A-line skirts with elastic waistbands and drawstring pants
cropped at the ankles. ``Since skirts are getting roomier, you need
that tight sweater so you have something fitting close to the
body.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
