<SLUG> BC-LASCHOOLS-MAYOR-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOS ANGELES MAYOR CALLS SCHOOL BOARD `EVIL,' `CRIMINAL'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Will also move in the ``n'' California news file.) 
BY RICK ORLOV AND TERRI HARDY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Mayor Richard Riordan has stepped up his attack
against the Los Angeles Board of Education, calling the current
system ``evil (and) criminal'' in failing to educate children as he
seeks candidates to run against four incumbents in next year's
election.
</P>
<P>
   ``The No. 1 crime in Los Angeles and California today is our
education system,'' Riordan said Monday. ``We need to find people
who are willing to put children ahead of politics. The only policy
we should have is what is best for our children.''
</P>
<P>
   Riordan said the four members he wants to replace _ David
Tokofsky, George Kiriyama, Jeff Horton and Barbara Boudreaux.
</P>
<P>
   ``Individually, I like them,'' said Riordan. ``But they aren't
giving enough authority to (Superintendent) Ruben Zacarias. We
don't know if Zacarias is a good superintendent, because he isn't
given the authority to manage the district.''
</P>
<P>
   But as the mayor unveiled his plan to reform the LAUSD, many
civic and school leaders were skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   Former Assemblywoman Paula Boland, who is leading the movement
to break up the LAUSD, says the mayor's efforts won't fix the
district's problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``The LAUSD is broken, period,'' said Boland, chairwoman of
Finally Restoring Excellence in Education. ``Change is needed, but
chewing gum and bailing wire will not be enough to fix it.''
</P>
<P>
   Tokofsky said the mayor's push for reform will only be
significant if it becomes a debate on how children are educated,
not governance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Changes in power will do nothing to help kids do better in
school,'' said Tokofsky.
</P>
<P>
   But Riordan believes the first step toward reform is empowering
the superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The board should just rubberstamp his proposals and deal with
the broader issues. They shouldn't be bothering him with getting
kids in one school or interfering with his running of the
district.''
</P>
<P>
   Riordan's prime example is the board's refusal to allow Zacarias
to discipline principals.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a principal and you know the superintendent doesn't
have any authority over you, you're not going to listen to him,''
said Riordan.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the administrators' union has complained that
principals are not given enough authority, but are being placed on
the front lines of accountability for a school.
</P>
<P>
   But, Eli Brent, president of the Associated Administrators of
Los Angeles, said he doesn't trust Riordan's motives.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like the mayor is looking to give control and get
control,'' said Brent. ``I think the mayor should be more concerned
about running the city and doing that well.''
</P>
<P>
   Brent disagrees with Riordan's assessment that Zacarias has not
been given enough authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing that the superintendent has asked for that
the board has not given him,'' said Brent. ``The board has told the
superintendent: Do what you want.''
</P>
<P>
   Kiriyama agreed and said he has urged the superintendent to
discipline and dismiss poor performers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people are not doing their job, the superintendent should
get rid of them,'' said Kiriyama. ``My thoughts about this are
well-known, and I hope it's a sentiment that is shared by the rest
of the board.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor said he and the coalition debated but then dismissed
the idea of pushing through changes in the state constitution that
would empower the mayor to choose school board members. Instead,
they modeled their changes on what's been done in the troubled
Sacramento school district, where that city's mayor headed a
successful effort to oust a majority of the board. Now, Sacramento
school officials say the district is on the right track, with a
reform plan in place and a new superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   Riordan said he will be setting up a special telephone line for
people interested in running for office to contact him.
</P>
<P>
   He said the task force of business leaders he has formed will be
expanded to include other interested people to decide on a final
slate of candidates for next April's election.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we want to do is decide on who we think could be the best
person to begin the revolution we need in our school system,'' said
Riordan.
</P>
<P>
   Details on how the final candidates will be selected are being
worked out, but Riordan said he has been overwhelmed by the public
response he has received since reports of his plans surfaced
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the No. 1 issue for people,'' said Riordan. ``This is
what they are concerned about. I've had parents come up to me and
tell me they aren't waiting for Goals 2000 that the state wants.
They want to take care of their kids here and now.''
</P>
<P>
   Riordan said improving the school system is his top priority in
promoting the area's economic competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things that keeps the middle class in Los Angeles
is having a good education system,'' said Riordan said. ``If they
don't think their children will get a good education they won't
stay here and they won't move here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
