<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-OFF-LINE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDS THINKING ABOUT EXECUTION  
 PICKING UP BLITZ MAY EARN A REPRIEVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   What does a coach do when his 0-2 team has given up an average
of 35.5 points a game and is facing a must win in its home opener?
</P>
<P>
   Does he cure mental malfunctions by taking the troops to the
practice field and pounding the heck out of the them?
</P>
<P>
   Does he make changes aimed at catching their attention?
</P>
<P>
   Coach Vince Tobin, whose Cardinals meet NFL East foe
Philadelphia, also 0-2, on ESPN's Sunday night game, is thinking
execution _ i.e. blitz management.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure just going out and beating up each other in
practice is the answer,'' Tobin said. ``We'll have a good practice
Wednesday. Whether it's more intense, I don't know. The goal is
high intensity on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we make any changes we'll make them on Wednesday, but to
make a change, you have to feel you're changing for the better.
We're not at a point where we have to shake things up. The worst
thing is to panic and make wholesale changes in search of something
positive. It's better to be positive, look at the things we did
well and those we did poorly, and work on correcting them with
better execution.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Cardinals are looking at a four-game stretch
against four opponents _ Philadelphia, St. Louis, Oakland and
Chicago _ with a combined 1-7 record and can see reason to harbor
hopes of being 4-2, naysayers see the two embarrassing losses and
wonder why the season must be so long.
</P>
<P>
   While rookie defensive end Andre Wadsworth overstated his own
play as horrible in Sunday's game, he isn't about to throw in the
towel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a long season,'' said Wadsworth, who never lost more than
two games in a season during his career at Florida State. ``There
are 14 games left and people can say we're going to have a losing
season, but until those 14 are played out, there's a chance we'll
only lose two this year.''
</P>
<P>
   The trouble with optimism is it's wasted on youth, but
inexperience isn't. Most of the Cardinals problems against Seattle
centered on a young quarterback and an offensive line that knew
when and where Seattle was blitzing, but didn't have the cohesion
to stop it.
</P>
<P>
   The net result was seven sacks of quarterback Jake Plummer,
whose 11th start saw him throw two touchdown interceptions _ one
while being sacked by his own blocking back _ and fumble the ball
away once.
</P>
<P>
   `We're a bad offense right now,'' said Plummer, who labeled the
first interception return by Willie Williams as a dumb play on his
part. ``If you look at the game tapes, we're not that good. But
we're close to being real efficient. Just one or two plays here or
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Plummer claims it's a fine line between being good and mediocre.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to realize what that is and get it done in practice,''
he said. ``Then go on the field and get over that hurdle and make
those third-and-five blitz pickups happen. Make a big play to break
a team's back if it wants to blitz us.
</P>
<P>
   ``The positive thing though, in the fourth quarter we were
getting our butts kicked and they were still blitzing, but we were
still busting our butts and learning. The effort is there. We need
the execution.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
