r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-ARIZ.ST.-SNYDER-A     09-15 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ARIZ.ST.-SNYDER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SNYDER WANTS ASU TO BE AGGRESSIVE, NOT STUPID 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, ARIZ. - It's not exactly a category Arizona State strives
to lead.
</P>
<P>
   After two games, no one in the Pac-10 has more penalties or
penalty yards. The Sun Devils have 22 for 200 yards. By contrast,
Arizona has 10 for 90 and Washington State 15 for 114.
</P>
<P>
   Penalties have plagued ASU during Coach Bruce Snyder's reign,
and Saturday's loss to Brigham Young was no exception. The Sun
Devils committed 11 for 105 yards; five of the infractions were
personal fouls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really dislike stupid penalties,'' Snyder said. ``The stupid
ones kill you.''
</P>
<P>
   ASU never has finished better than seventh in league penalties
in the past six seasons. In four of those seasons, it has finished
ninth or 10th.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils are on a worse pace this year than the previous
six, although teams tend to commit fewer penalties as their play
improves over the course of the season. The low-water mark for that
span is 982 penalty yards, accumulated in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   How much it affects their success is debatable. They accumulated
more penalties during their 1996 Rose Bowl season than during a 3-8
season in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem, Snyder said, is that he coaches his teams
to play aggressively and to hit hard. Blitzing, which often leads
to offsides penalties, is a big part of the defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's really a fine edge there,'' he said. ``I admire BYU.
They play hard, and they hit right at the end of the play. I like
that, and that's the way you should play the game. You've got to
figure out when that whistle blows.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensive coordinator Phil Snow said he often has this
conversation with his players:
</P>
<P>
   Snow: ``If a runner is running down the sideline inbounds, what
do you do?''
</P>
<P>
   Player: ``Hit him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If he's out of bounds?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't hit him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're not sure?''
</P>
<P>
   Snow said: ``You have to hit him. We tell them they have to be
smart ``and'' aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   But Snow also said ``a lot of penalties are reputation anyway.
Because we've hit hard over the years anyway, it's `They play
physical.' Well, we played liked BYU.''
</P>
<P>
   Snow said free safety Mitchell Freedman may be a victim of his
reputation as a hard hitter. If a play is borderline, the call
probably is going to go against him.
</P>
<P>
   The five personal fouls in the BYU game included a roughing the
passer and roughing the punter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first game (against Washington) _ I'm not as concerned . .
. because most are things that can be corrected,'' Snyder said.
``But this game, we were more frustrated because of the game, the
crowd, some of the dialogue on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Ryan Kealy said: ``The penalties are simply mental
errors, lapses in judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   True, but Snyder doesn't like them. And the team is getting an
earful this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one way,'' he said. ``If it's really habitual, you can
change players.''
</P>
<P>
   The coaching staff will be re-examining all facets of the team
before ASU hosts North Texas on Saturday, from personnel to
strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going back to square one,'' Snyder said. ``We've got to
make sure and not assume anything.'' &QL; 
Notes &QL; 
Gov. Jane Hull has sent a letter to running back Gerald Green,
commending him for overcoming adversity in his life. ``You are an
example to all of us of what can be achieved through determination
and courage.''
</P>
<P>
   With Randy Leaphart sidelined because of a knee injury, redshirt
freshman Scott Peters will start at left guard. Word on Leaphart's
status is expected today.
</P>
<P>
   Kealy said ASU's 0-2 start is a definite wake-up call. ``It may
be just the kind of thing we need to get going. We may have been up
in the clouds a bit. That brought us down to reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Snyder said the blame for the team's early struggles should be
shared. ``It's not just the players. I, we, need to coach better.
All of our fingerprints are all over this game.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
