<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOPE IS LOST IF CARDINALS FAIL SUNDAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - So, after two full seasons, after a grace period
and a lost cause, after 34 games to clean up the wreckage and get
the truck back on the road . . .
</P>
<P>
   Here it is. The first must-win game of his tenure. The week when
you'll learn everything you need to know about Mr. Beige.
</P>
<P>
   Because if this football team can't beat the Philadelphia
Eagles, there is no hope.
</P>
<P>
   Not for this season, a year in which Jake Plummer predicted 10
victories, minimum. And not for the future of Vince Tobin, who
probably needs to win seven games to keep his job.
</P>
<P>
   Here it is. Sunday night on ESPN. The beginning of a new era. Or
the beginning of the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``After this game is over, there are still 13 left,'' said
Tobin, proving if nothing else, his math skills are still intact.
``But it's a very important game for us.''
</P>
<P>
   As the pavement becomes littered with fans leaping off the
bandwagon, remember that nothing is lost just yet. The defeat in
Dallas was understandable. Getting blistered by a revved-up Seattle
Seahawks squad full of mercenaries was completely expected. So
they're 0-2, just like 10 other teams in the league.
</P>
<P>
   But now they must turn the corner, put up a fight. They must act
like a team on the rise, not in reverse. As the Cardinals go from
the deep end of the schedule into the baby pool, a four-game
winning streak would be nice. Three out of four would be
satisfactory. Anything less would spell trouble.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it would signal serious underachievement somewhere
along the ranks. And it always starts with the coaching staff. &QL; 
Mind control &QL; 
``Obviously, our confidence is not as strong as it was going into
the season,'' Tobin said. ``They felt like we were going to get out
of the gate and be 2-0 at this point in time. And we're not. And we
haven't played close to the expectations we had for ourselves, and
I'm sure that affects them.''
</P>
<P>
   You will learn much about Tobin because some psychological
tweaking is necessary. His players are hurting emotionally,
wondering if things will ever change. It's Tobin's job to address
that problem, to change the mind-set.
</P>
<P>
   You will learn much about Tobin because, well, the coaching
hasn't been exactly stellar up to this point. Week 1 was a
three-and-out debacle. Week 2 wasn't much better, raising questions
about the effectiveness and implementation of Marc Trestman's
offense.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the offensive line had its troubles, and Plummer
hasn't had a good game yet. But when a team is blitzing every other
down, you have to counterattack. There must be simple plays to burn
an overzealous defense. So far, the Cardinals have shown no
intuition, no clue how to handle such pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, there has only been this tell-tale sign of desperation:
In the second quarter, Tobin took over the offense. He ordered his
``Tens'' package on the field. A combination of Michael Pittman,
Jarious Hayes and two tight ends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't call the plays,'' Tobin insisted. ``I just called the
formations.''
</P>
<P>
   Which, of course, is splitting hairs. If the head coach inserts
that foursome into the game, there aren't many options other than
handing off to Pittman. And even if he isn't calling the plays, a
new offensive coordinator is likely to get the hint. &QL; 
Righting a sinking ship &QL; 
Tobin's choice isn't the issue because Pittman deserves some
playing time. What's troubling is the lack of faith _ and results _
from Trestman's offense.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing is more troubling than this: Trailing,17-0, at the
two-minute warning of the first half, the Seahawks had a first and
goal from the 5. The Cardinals never called a timeout. The Seahawks
kicked a field goal as time expired, and the Cardinals kicked off
to start the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Either a terrible coaching blunder or a staff that didn't want
the ball back.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't all gloom and doom,'' Tobin said. ``There are some
positives to build on.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the schedule. And starting Sunday, it could either save the
season or sink the coach. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at 602-444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
