<HEADLINE>
TKACHUK HOLD OUT MAY SPUR LEGAL FIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. -  &UR; Keith Tkachuk already has lost more than
$30,000 because of his holdout, but he possibly could lose more,
according to a scenario suggested by Coyotes General Manager  &UR; Bobby
Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Should Tkachuk, the team's captain and leading scorer, decide to
sit out the 1998-99 season, he still might be obligated for the
final two years of his contract, which is worth $2.8 million this
season and $3 million the next.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the star left wing could be facing the same
situation a year from now.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's certainly going to be our position, and that of the
lawyers at the NHL, that if Keith sits out the entire year, at
year's end, he'll still have two years left in his contract,''
Smith said Monday, the third day of Tkachuk's holdout. ``It's
something that could happen after a certain number of games, too,
before the season is complete.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure this is something Keith and the Players Association
will file a grievance over, but we'll be prepared for that.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Bob Murray, Tkachuk's Boston-based agent, could not be reached
for comment. Earlier in the day, however, he talked for the first
time about his client's suspension on Saturday and daily forfeiture
of pay, which reached $30,543 through Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not surprised by the Coyotes' course of action,'' Murray
said. ``We were fully prepared for them to do what they did. The
team had a choice, and they decided to act within the rules of the
league's (collective bargaining agreement).''
</P>
<P>
   Murray hedged when asked whether Tkachuk, third-leading goal
scorer in the league (205) the past five seasons, was prepared to
sit out the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather not comment on that,'' he said. ``All I'll say is
the Coyotes have taken a position where they keep threatening Keith
in the media, and we've refrained from doing that. We'll keep
refraining because threats are counterproductive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will say this, Bob Smith's statement that he he doesn't
intend to have any more (negotiations) with Keith, I find a little
bizarre. Don't they want this guy in their lineup?'' &QL; 
JR on mission &QL; 
Star center  &UR; Jeremy Roenick punctuated his first day of camp by
saying he will have no comment on the Tkachuk situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely not. That's because I have my own job to do this
year,'' said Roenick, who missed the opening day of camp to tend to
personal business in Boston. ``I have high expectations of myself,
and I'm sure lots of other people have high expectations of me. I
can't be worried about who's getting what or what's happening
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just need to do what I need to do. I have to prove to myself
and I have to prove to a lot of people that I'm still a great
player, and I can still do a lot of damage in this league. I've
worked hard physically, and now I'm working hard mentally in a lot
of different areas.''
</P>
<P>
   Roenick's goal and point totals have dipped in each of the past
three seasons, including to a career-low 24 and 56 last season. &QL; 
Happy camper &QL; 
The biggest surprise in camp has to be  &UR; Adam Dewan, a non-drafted
left wing from Peterborough of the Ontario Hockey League, who was
given a tryout and got invited to stay with the veterans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't expect to stay, but I'm the happiest kid alive right
now,'' said Dewan, 18, a teammate of Coyotes draft pick  &UR; Robert
Fancz who scored 14 goals and 32 points last season in 62 games.
``Whatever happens, this is going to help my confidence, and I can
just take all this experience back to the OHL and have a good
season.''
</P>
<P>
   And he can get decent autographs while he's here, no doubt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, most definitely,'' Dewan said, laughing. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
