<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YANKS-REDSOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES SHUT OUT RED SOX, 3-0 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York Yankees won 100 games faster than any
team in history because they were scared. They played hard because
they feared what would happen if they did not play hard.
</P>
<P>
   They have lost half their games in the last month, and this
scares them.
</P>
<P>
   Under no circumstances, then, would Yankees Manager Joe Torre
relieve Orlando Hernandez on Monday night. Torre intended to use
his bullpen in the late innings, but Hernandez had stifled Boston,
and the Yankees needed some reassurance. Hernandez finished his
first complete-game shutout, a three-hitter with no walks and nine
strikeouts and a badly needed injection of pitching excellence at
just the right time for the Yankees, who ended their three-game
losing streak. In beating Boston by 3-0, they beat Pedro Martinez
(18-6) for the second time in less than a week.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees drew a crowd of 42,735, pushing their season total
to 2,657,785 and eclipsing their single-season record of 2,633,701,
established in 1988. The Yankees (104-44) have nine home dates
remaining in the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   From Torre to Bernie Williams to Hernandez, the Yankees talked
about how this was an important victory. The Yankees are 104-44 and
lead the American League East by a club-record 21 games, and they
were saying that this was an important victory. Because of the
fear: the Yankees do not want to win 110 to 115 games and then
crumble in the playoffs because of a late-season pitching slump.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have to have all phases of our game sharp for
the playoffs,'' Williams said, ``and pitching obviously is one of
them. It was great to see Orlando dealing.''
</P>
<P>
   Hideki Irabu has allowed 30 runs in his last 201/3 innings, Andy
Pettitte has a 6.75 earned run average in seven starts dating from
July 30, and even David Cone has accumulated a 4.70 era in his last
302/3 innings. Hernandez had a 5.52 era in the four outings before
Monday night's game, and he had all but given away a 5-0 lead to
Boston in the fourth inning last week in Fenway Park, frustrating
Torre, who thought Hernandez's pitch selection had been terrible in
that game.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, the English-speaking Torre approached the
Spanish-speaking Hernandez and, with his hands held head high,
pretended to remove Hernandez's head and then throw it against the
wall. The message was clear: clear out your brain and think about
what you're doing.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez nodded and smiled, and adjusted. ``I understood his
point when he did that,'' Hernandez said through an interpreter.
``He gave me the confidence to go ahead and clear my head.''
</P>
<P>
   Given another chance against the Red Sox last night, Hernandez
threw more strikes and changed speeds more often, utilizing his
curveball and changeup to greater effect than he has in weeks. He
would throw a fastball inside and then maybe a curveball or a
slider, or maybe a changeup, all at different speeds. Making a
pitch to the slugger Mo Vaughn with the count three balls and two
strikes, Hernandez cut loose with a fading, dying change of pace
that fell into the dirt, and Vaughn was completely fooled, swinging
over the ball. All night, Boston hitters were caught between the
poles of velocity, and the Red Sox were 0 for 6 with runners in
scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pedro pitched a strong game for us,'' said Jimy Williams, the
Boston manager. ``But the other kid really stood out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees could not muster a run in support until the fifth
inning, when Darryl Strawberry _ who had looked overmatched against
Martinez, a Cy Young award candidate _ smacked a single to right.
With Vaughn holding Strawberry at first, Jorge Posada managed to
pull a ground ball through the hole in the right side of the
infield. Trot Nixon, Boston's right fielder, charged the ball and
the safe play appeared to be for Strawberry to stop at second.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody had scouted Nixon's arm, however.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry's stride became choppy as he made the turn at second,
and past the bag, he gained speed and slid into third, from where
he would score on a fly ball.
</P>
<P>
   Torre planned on using Jeff Nelson in the seventh or eighth, and
Mike Stanton or Graeme Lloyd. Mariano Rivera warmed up before the
ninth inning. But the Yankees have lost 15 of their last 30 games,
and Torre decided to stay with Hernandez, to keep a good thing
going, to stay one step ahead of the fear.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put a lot of plans on the back shelf,'' Torre said. ``I
wasn't going to mess around with that game.''
</P>
<P>
   When Williams caught the final out in the final inning,
Hernandez grinned broadly and draped his arms around teammate Luis
Sojo. A big hug. A bigger relief for the Yankees. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
