r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DBACKS-NOTEBOOK-A     09-15 0503
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GILKEY TO HAVE EYE SURGERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Outfielder  &UR; Bernard Gilkey is in Canada, where he'll
undergo laser surgery Wednesday to correct his vision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe he'll end up being the Comeback Player of the Year (next
season),'' Diamondbacks Manager  &UR; Buck Showalter said of Gilkey, who
is far-sighted.
</P>
<P>
   Infielder  &UR; Jay Bell, who wears glasses for astigmatism, said
he's thought of having surgery on his eyes. He says his vision is
20-20 without glasses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether that can take care of that with surgery or not, I
don't know,'' Bell said. ''It would be nice not to wear glasses.''
</P>
<P>
   The outcome of Gilkey's surgery will not be a determining
factor, Bell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to talk to an ophthomologist before anything,'' said
Bell, who is bothered by contacts. ``There has been enough data on
the surgery. It could be the thing of the future.'' &QL; 
Something to play for &QL; 
Closer  &UR; Gregg Olson and reliever  &UR; Alan Embree both played on teams
that lost 100 games. Olson was part of the 1988 Baltimore Orioles
and Embree with the '92 Cleveland Indians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going to the park every day was a nightmare,'' Embree
recalled. ``They couldn't give away tickets. That was not fun.
There wasn't anything to shoot for.''
</P>
<P>
   Embree said the Diamondbacks' pennant race is against 100 _
avoiding that ominous number of losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we do that, we've accomplished something,'' he said. &QL; 
Un-locked in &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Olson looked unfazed in picking up his 28th save Sunday, but he
said it was difficult to come on after  &UR; Andy Benes lost a no-hit
bid in the ninth inning against the Cincinnati Reds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost track of what I wanted to do,'' Olson said. ``It was
like the ninth inning, and suddenly he walked somebody and they've
got me up. I tried to watch him and get ready at the same time.'' &QL; 
Serving suspension &QL; 
San Francisco Giants pitcher  &UR; Julian Tavarez withdrew his appeal
and began serving his three-game suspension Monday. Tavarez, who is
4-3 with a 3.83 ERA, was suspended for his part in an argument with
homeplate umpire  &UR; Sam &UR; Holbrook last Wednesday in San Deigo. &QL; 
Fall ball &QL; 
Some current Diamondbacks will participate in the first Arizona
Fall League ``Diamondbacks'' series every Wednesday night,
beginning Sept. 30 at Scottsdale Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Matt Williams, Benes, Devon White, Travis Lee, David Dellucci,
Andy Fox and Showalter will make personal appearances at a
designated Fall League game. Fans will have a chance to win one of
100 autographed baseballs during lucky number drawings each half
inning. Diamondbacks broadcaster  &UR; Thom
 &UR; Brennaman and  &UR; Joe Garagiola, Sr., also will make appearances.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks will have major league prospects playing for
the Scottsdale Scorpions, who will be managed by  &UR; Chris Speier.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; They are infielders  &UR; Danny Klassen and  &UR; Junior Spivey,
outfielder  &UR; Jason
 &UR; Conti and pitchers  &UR; Vladimir Nunez, Steve Randolph and  &UR; Russell
Jacob. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
