<HEADLINE>
CITY TO REVIEW PLANS TO CRACKDOWN ON SMOKING-BAN SCOFFLAWS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Will also move in the ``n'' California news file.) 
BY RICK ORLOV AND DAVID R. BAKER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The city is failing to enforce a state ban on
smoking in bars and restaurants, with only three citations issued
so far by the Los Angeles Fire Department, a city panel has
complained.
</P>
<P>
   Councilwoman Laura Chick, chairwoman of the council's Public
Safety Committee, said Monday she had received a number of
complaints from the public about bars that were violating the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city is doing a terrible job of enforcing this,'' said
Chick after the meeting. ``We're basically crossing our fingers and
hoping people will comply voluntarily.''
</P>
<P>
   After hearing testimony, the committee called for a review of
ways to step up enforcement of the law, including possibly
transferring responsibility to the Los Angeles Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   The committee is scheduled to reconsider the issue Oct. 19.
</P>
<P>
   Complaints of smoking in bars are handled by the same
eight-person Fire Department office that inspects buildings for
fire-code violations. The inspectors work regular daytime shifts,
meaning they rarely see bars in full swing when responding to
complaints, said Capt. Michael Little.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue isn't one of (handling) dozens and dozens of
complaints _ it's a matter of getting staff positions for the times
when these violations happen,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Councilman Richard Alarcon suggested that the LAPD, with its
Operation ABC unit that inspects bars for other problems, take over
enforcement of the smoking ban. The units are available for use on
a citywide basis, rather than the one inspector the LAFD wants to
hire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to question if the Fire Department should enforce
this,'' said Alarcon. ``It is very tough for them to enforce a law
like this in bars at 11 in the evening. And I don't know if we have
enough people available to enforce it from the Fire Department.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the current system, the City Attorney's Office sends a
notice to the bar owner after a first complaint. On second
complaints, the city notifies the Fire Department to conduct an
inspection.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the city received 408 complaint calls between the time
the law took effect Jan. 1 and the end of June. The city mailed out
105 warning letters in response. Thirteen cases were referred to
the Fire Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``What that suggests to me is that people grow frustrated when
they see a lack of response by the city,'' said Councilman Mike
Feuer.
</P>
<P>
   Chick said if the city wants to keep responsibility for
enforcing the ban with the Fire Department, it must also make sure
the department has the tools to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be fair to the Fire Department, they clearly have not been
given the resources they need,'' she said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
