<SLUG> BC-BBN-CARDS-PIRATES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDINALS TOP PIRATES, 7-4; MCGUIRE IS HOMERLESS
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By IRA BERKOW   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Cardinal fans are concerned that the spectacular
home run race between Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa that was supposed
to be finished is heating up again, and perhaps not entirely to
their liking.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are saying Sosa will pass McGwire,'' said Daren Gatton,
a bartender at the Adam's Mark Hotel here. ``Sosa's on a roll, and
Mark's back is hurting.''
</P>
<P>
   There had been a question whether McGwire, who had suffered a
back spasm in Sunday's game against Houston and was taken out in
the fifth inning, was going to play at all on Monday night as the
Cards played host to the Pirates in the first of a four-game
series.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all depends,'' McGwire had said, ``on how I wake up.''
</P>
<P>
   But before the game, McGwire reported that his back was fine. He
hit several balls out of the park in batting practice, and he was
at his customary station, first base, as the game began.
</P>
<P>
   He did not do his customary damage, hitting no home runs in four
times at bat against the last-place team in the National League
East.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire went 2 for 4, with two singles, two runs batted in, one
strikeout and no walks, as the Cardinals won, 7-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think his back is O.K.,'' Cardinal Manager Tony LaRussa said
after the game. ``There were no complaints.''
</P>
<P>
   As to whether McGwire would play both games of a doubleheader on
Tuesday, LaRussa said: ``I doubt he'll be out there for 18 innings
with an ouchy back. He'll play one of the games. Which one will
depend on who the pitchers are.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire was removed from Sunday's game ``for cautionary
reasons,'' LaRussa said. McGwire, who had had back problems
throughout his career, was taken out of one game on June 1 in San
Diego and missed three games against the Dodgers, June 2-4, because
of back spasms.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire had recalled a time a few years ago when he was washing
his face in a sink and sneezed. ``I threw my back out and missed
seven games,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since McGwire hit his record-breaking 62nd homer last Tuesday,
he is 3 for 18 in six games, with three walks and seven strikeouts.
In that time, Sosa has hit four home runs to tie him. McGwire had
been on an astonishing home-run streak until then, hitting 15
homers in 22 games. And in the last two months, McGwire had showed
a particular proclivity for hitting homers whenever Sosa hit one or
two to get too close for comfort.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire has now gone six games without hitting a home run. The
longest he has gone this season without a homer is 10 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think McGwire's getting over the relief of doing it,''
said Gratton, referring to the pressure of chasing the Maris mark.
``I think he'll come back and hit 66 homers.'' And Sosa?
``Sixty-five,'' he said. ``I think it'll be that close.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
