<HEADER>
A5258 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     09-15 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOSA DOESN'T FEEL SLIGHTED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ The day after reaching Mark McGwire's place in
baseball history, Sammy Sosa received a congratulatory telephone
call from the leader of the free world.
</P>
<P>
   To which some people a tad-too-skeptically replied, what, aside
from his world of troubles, took President Clinton so long?
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that Clinton was dialed into McGwire's achievement,
calling the St. Louis slugger the same night he surpassed Roger
Maris as the single-season home run leader. It's ridiculous to
raise the race card to explain why McGwire's 62nd blast this past
Tuesday unleashed more gaiety than Sosa's on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   No way should baseball's richest rivalry since Maris and Mickey
Mantle teed off on Babe Ruth in 1961 be consumed by creed or color.
To say Sosa was denied a coronation fit for a home run king because
he's not American-born is a reach, the rational equivalent of
swinging at a pitch that's well outside the strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs outfielder's accomplishment was not downplayed because
he grew up dirt poor in the Dominican Republic instead of
comfortably middle class in the Los Angeles suburbs like McGwire.
Sosa was relegated to a scaled-down celebration for the same reason
John Landy received less fanfare than Roger Bannister for breaking
the four-minute barrier in the mile.
</P>
<P>
   If you've never heard of Landy from the Land Down Under, it's
not because of any built-in bias against Australia. Rather, it's
simply because he had the bad timing to cover the distance in 3
minutes, 58.0 some seven weeks after Bannister, a Brit, had shown
the world the unthinkable was indeed possible with a clocking of
3:59.4.
</P>
<P>
   Being the first to scale heretofore unreachable heights has its
privileges. How many people remember who followed Sir Edmund
Hillary up Mt. Everest, besides his Sherpa? Sosa accepts this
natural order of celebrity without reservations or rancor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The attention I've been having all year is good enough for
me,'' Sosa said before Monday's Cubs-Padres game at Qualcomm
Stadium. ``Mark did it first. He was the man. I'm just so happy to
be playing in the United States. I'm not looking ... to make some
more friends. I'm pleased with what I have right now.''
</P>
<P>
   That might be so, but Sosa's sphere is mushrooming and there's
no reason to believe he won't be lovingly and lavishly embraced if
he passes McGwire by the season's end.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa's bandwagon reached groaning levels Monday, with 150 media
credentials distributed, all but 15 of which were requested in the
hours between sundown Sunday and high noon Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The multitude that squeezed into the San Diego Chargers locker
room two hours before the opening pitch seemed to push most of the
air molecules out into the hallway. About the only person who
didn't appear to be breaking a sweat in the claustrophobic
conditions was Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   He started his 30-minute pregame press conference by thanking
everybody for coming, proving once and for all he is not a disciple
of the Albert Belle school of manners.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, it must be difficult at times to navigate a sea of
scrutiny in your second language. There's always the danger your
words or nuances will get lost in your translation. The late
Roberto Clemente, one of the greatest Latin American players ever
to grace the major leagues, had a chilly relationship with the U.S.
press because of what he saw as an impenetrable cultural divide.
</P>
<P>
   That's not a problem for Sosa, whose smile can thaw any snub. He
tips his cap to the people in his adopted country, saying, ``People
in the United States give me the opportunity to be who I am.'' Yet
he remains ever-mindful of his roots.
</P>
<P>
   He said Monday that everything he does is for his mother,
Mireya, who was widowed when Sosa was 7 yet somehow managed to rear
seven children _ with Sammy doing his part by shining shoes and
selling fruit _ in a two-room dwelling that contained enough love
to fill a mansion.
</P>
<P>
   He hits homers for his mother and wears the jersey number 21 in
honor of Clemente.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa recognizes that, to a lot of people back in his homeland,
he was an idol on par with Clemente, who was a Puerto Rican, even
before he reeled in Babe Ruth and Roger Maris.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't want to wait for so long (for the next Clemente),''
Sosa explained with a twinkle in his eye. Later, he added that as
much as he admires Clemente, his idol is God.
</P>
<P>
   There are athletes who worship at the altar of the almighty
dollar, and for a long time Sosa's teammates had reason to wonder
if he wasn't one of them. When he first broke into the big leagues,
with the Chicago White Sox, he swung at bad pitches, wore gaudy
gold jewelry and seemed inordinately interested in his own
statistics. As recently as last year, Cubs manager Jim Riggleman
chastised him for foolishly trying to steal a base in an effort to
reach the 30-homer, 30-stolen base plateau.
</P>
<P>
   If Sosa in the past seemed inordinately interested in his own
performance, it was because he saw his individual numbers as his
family's ticket to financial freedom. Having inked a four-year,
$42.5 million contract midway through last season, Sosa came into
this season focused fully on team goals.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-two home runs later, nothing's changed. ``I have to go out
there every day and work hard. I can't think about (the home run)
chase,'' Sosa said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a responsibility to finish strong and take Chicago to
the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether he gets the Cubs there or not, he already has taken an
entire continent along for one wondrous ride.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-98 0058EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
