<SLUG> BC-FBN-SKINS-49ERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
49ERS CRUSH REDSKINS, 45-10 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LANDOVER, Md. _ It was not just Trent Green versus Steve Young.
No, that alone was not the problem for the Washington Redskins on
Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was it just Garrison Hearst versus Terry Allen or Jerry Rice
versus Michael Westbrook. And it was not just the Redskins' shaky
offense versus the 49ers' muscular defense or the Redskins'
overmatched defense trying to keep pace with the 49ers' primed
offense.
</P>
<P>
   No, the problem was simply the Washington Redskins versus the
San Francisco 49ers. The game. The teams. The talent. The schemes.
The focus. The execution.
</P>
<P>
   It was a blowout, a 45-10 victory for the 49ers _ Norv Turner's
worst loss in his five-year tenure in Washington and the Redskins'
worst home loss since 1948. The 76,798 fans at Jack Kent Cooke
Stadium must be wondering what is next for Washington after it
crashed to 0-2. Here is what: two 2-0 opponents, the Seahawks in
Seattle and then the Denver Broncos back here.
</P>
<P>
   Green, the Redskins' quarterback, made his first start ever,
under the glare of ``Monday Night Football.'' He connected on 14 of
24 passes for 201 yards and 1 touchdown, but it was not nearly
enough. After leaping ahead by 7-0, Washington fell behind by 21-10
at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Fullback Marc Edwards caught a 2-yard pass from Young in the
third quarter that made it 28-10. Then in the final quarter, San
Francisco scored 17 consecutive points.
</P>
<P>
   Young was masterly (21 for 32 for 303 yards with 3 touchdown
passes), Garrison Hearst was colorful (22 carries, 138 yards) and
the 49ers' offense over all was sensational. They managed this
against a revamped Washington defense. The Redskins paid $57
million in the off season for two defensive tackles, the former
49er Dana Stubblefield and the former Bengal Dan Wilkinson.
</P>
<P>
   The first half was one of opportunities gone sour for the
Redskins. And it was one in which San Francisco kept applying
pressure.
</P>
<P>
   With 1 minute 57 seconds left, Washington appeared to have
scored on a 3-yard pass from Green to Leslie Shepperd that would
have cut the deficit to 21-17, but Westbrook had grabbed the face
mask of cornerback Antonio Langham. So, Washington tried again for
the end zone, failed and then attempted a 34-yard field goal. Scott
Blanton's kick hit the left upright, though.
</P>
<P>
   Washington then forced a punt and took possession again at its
own 33 with 34 seconds left. Green hit passes of 6, 11 and 16 yards
and then scrambled for 5 more. Five seconds were left in the half,
and the ball was on the San Francisco 29. This time, Blanton's
47-yard attempt hit the crossbar.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers had seen Green open the scoring with a 9-yard strike
to Shepperd. But San Francisco took the kickoff and zoomed down the
field, covering 83 yards in 8 plays. The drive featured hard
running by Hearst and a third-and-5 catch of 17 yards by Terrell
Owens that put the ball at midfield. From the 20, Owens managed the
rest, running a picturesque post pattern on the veteran cornerback
Cris Dishman. That helped tie the game at 7-7.
</P>
<P>
   To open the second quarter, Allen fumbled at the Redskins' 30
and Hanks recovered. Six plays later, San Francisco led by 14-7
after Young's 3-yard keeper with 10:10 left in the half.
</P>
<P>
   Blanton made a 37-yard field goal with 5:37 left that made the
score 14-10, but the 49ers then scored the final points of the
half. Rice beat Darrell Green for 57 yards to the Washington 16.
Tight end Irv Smith scored on a 16-yard catch on the very next
play. San Francisco 21, Washington 10.
</P>
<P>
   Young was 13 of 18 for 191 yards in the half. Green was close,
going 11 of 16 for 170 yards. Young threw for two touchdowns, Green
for one, and neither was intercepted. Each team ran 32 plays.
</P>
<P>
   But in the half as for the entire night, San Francisco produced
much more with its chances.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
