<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-REDUX?-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON BASEBALL: ARE THE RED SOX RELIVING THEIR PAST? 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Twenty years ago Tuesday, the New York Yankees and
the Boston Red Sox began a three-game series at Yankee Stadium that
was well noted at the time but little remembered since.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Chambliss, for example, hit a two-run home run against
Luis Tiant that supported Ron Guidry's two-hitter in a 4-0 Yankees
victory. But asked about the hit, Chambliss said, ``I don't
remember that one.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Remy didn't remember that one or anything else about the
series. ``I don't remember much,'' said the Red Sox second baseman
turned Red Sox broadcaster. ``Maybe I don't want to remember.''
</P>
<P>
   Willie Randolph, who played in the infield with Chambliss on
that team and coaches with him on this one, tried to pull that
series out of the recesses of his memory, but nothing surfaced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember the massacre and I remember the playoff, but I
don't remember that one,'' Randolph said. ``I thought the massacre
was the last time we played them until the playoff.''
</P>
<P>
   Talk about that series, as well as the massacre and the playoff,
was popular Tuesday because the Red Sox are in town, and _ guess
what? _ they were doing it again.
</P>
<P>
   The best second-place team in the American League all season,
better than the other first-place teams, in fact, the Red Sox find
themselves with a shrunken wild-card lead.
</P>
<P>
   It stands at three games on Monday night following their 3-0
loss to the Yankees and Orlando Hernandez, who stifled them on
three hits. It could have been a mere two games, but Toronto
couldn't hold a lead against Cleveland and lost, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays were 12{ games behind the Red Sox on Aug. 26, only
three weeks ago. By this time 20 years ago, the Red Sox, who had
led the Yankees by 14 games in July, had already tumbled out of
first place.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees had tied them for first place a week earlier by
destroying them in what became known as the Boston Massacre: 15-3,
13-2, 7-0, 7-4. Game, set and match. The Red Sox then came to New
York a game and a half behind the Yankees and, losing two of three,
left two and a half back.
</P>
<P>
   With their dying gasp, the Red Sox caught up with the Yankees
and forced a playoff whose outcome made their collapse only more
excruciating. They didn't blow it just once, but twice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got nothing to do with the history,'' Mo Vaughn quietly
protested Tuesday. ``Collapses are collapses. I have nothing to do
with it. Each situation and each year and each team are
different.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the Red Sox, though, this year and this
situation look all too familiar.
</P>
<P>
   They arrived at Yankee Stadium last night with 12 losses in
their last 17 games.
</P>
<P>
   The lowlights of that stretch: a four-game sweep by the Blue
Jays in Toronto the first week of this month, and losses of two of
three games in Boston this past weekend with the Detroit Tigers,
who have the worst record in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Collapse was written all over those series.
</P>
<P>
   Saying the Detroit games were ones the Red Sox should have won,
Mike Stanley, who played the first four months with the Blue Jays,
said: ``It's one of those funks we seem to be in and can't seem to
right ourselves out of. Nobody ever knows why these things
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   But everyone does know why these particular things have
happened. These are the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   The most agonizing aspect of the collapse-in-progress is
watching their prospects of playing the Yankees next month wither
away. Because they are in the same division, the teams cannot play
in the first round of the playoffs. But the Red Sox, who had
dominated the wild-card race, looked eminently capable of beating
either of the other division winners, as did the Yankees, of
course.
</P>
<P>
   That would have set up a showdown in the league championship
series, the one before the World Series, and a Red Sox victory
would exorcise all of the ghosts of the past, including 1978.
</P>
<P>
   But as the season dwindles down to a precious few games, the Red
Sox don't even know if they'll be playing next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still ahead,'' Stanley pointed out. ``We just have to
remind ourselves of that, that we're the ones people are chasing.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn, the burly first baseman and team leader who may not lead
or play for the team after its last game this year, said the worst
thing the players could do was add pressure on themselves as they
try to pull out of their funk.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've played with a lot of character and a lot of heart and a
lot of guts all season,'' Vaughn said. ``That's what's going to
carry us through this thing. We can't get caught up too much in
this situation. There's really no time as a player to think about
getting down because there's such a short time left. Just go out
and play the game the way it's supposed to be played and have fun
with it. You're still in the lead. That's how you have to look at
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox, Vaughn added, are not an inexperienced team. ``If
people feel uptight, I'm surprised,'' he said. ``This team has
enough veterans who've been places and know what they gotta do.
We'll know soon.''
</P>
<P>
   But will the Red Sox be able to handle the answer when they get
it?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-98 0106EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
