<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-ASTROS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS DEFEAT ASTROS, 7-4 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Try as he might, Mike Piazza cannot win the wild-card
race by himself. And while it took more than eight innings on
Monday night, the rest of Piazza's teammates finally chipped in,
just when the New York Mets' post-season hopes seemed almost lost.
</P>
<P>
   First, Brian McRae tied the score with a two-run homer in the
ninth, one batter after Piazza had delivered his fourth hit of the
night. And then McRae did himself one better with a tie-breaking,
one-out double that scored Edgardo Alfonzo and Piazza with the
go-ahead runs in the 13th, keying a three-run rally that gave the
Mets a come-from-behind 7-4 victory over the Astros, who
nevertheless clinched the National League Central division when the
Cubs lost.
</P>
<P>
   And so, with 11 games remaining in the regular season, the Mets
(84-67) once again moved into a tie with the Cubs in the National
League wild-card race. For McRae, who threw out the potential tying
run to end Sunday's game in Montreal, it was his second
game-winning hit in two days. And John Franco closed out the game
with his franchise-record 37th save.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't really appreciate our team and they definitely
don't appreciate Brian McRae,'' Manager Bobby Valentine said after
the game.
</P>
<P>
   McRae's extra-inning heroics came a dozen innings after Piazza
had given the Mets a two-run lead with a prodigious first-inning
home run to dead center, his 31st of the season. It was a moment
Valentine did not forget after the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lost in the whole thing was the hardest home run I've ever
seen,'' Valentine said. ``480 feet? I guarantee you the only way
that ball is coming down is if it hits something.''
</P>
<P>
   Eight innings later, with Piazza on first after a leadoff single
and nobody out in the ninth, the switch-hitting McRae, batting
right-handed, drilled a two-strike pitch from the Houston closer
Billy Wagner over the fence in left center field for a game-tying
home run.
</P>
<P>
   And then, after both teams squandered chances as the innings
wore along, Alfonzo opened the 13th with a double to right off Mike
Magnante, one that Derek Bell kicked around long enough for Alfonzo
to take third base. Magnante retired John Olerud on a grounder to
third with the infield in.
</P>
<P>
   But after an intentional walk to Piazza, who finished 4 for 5 on
the evening, McRae greeted Doug Henry with a double to right
center, took third on a fly out to right and later scored on a wild
pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams squandered opportunities after McRae's 21st home run
had tied the score at 4-4.
</P>
<P>
   With the Mets threatening to add to their rally, pinch-runner
Jermaine Allensworth was doubled off second base with runners on
first and second on pinch-hitter Luis Lopez's line-out to short to
end the top of the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in the bottom of the 10th, Turk Wendell retired Bell and
Jeff Bagwell with runners on first and second to end that threat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-98 0120EDT &QL; 
