<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 01:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5286 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-CUBS-PADRES-NYT &LR;      09-15 0598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CUBS-PADRES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOSA'S WEST COAST SHOW STAYS IN THE BALL PARK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (js) 
 By ED GUZMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ The great home run chase came to Qualcomm Stadium
Monday night in the form of Chicago Cubs right fielder Sammy Sosa,
the newest member of the 62 home run club.
</P>
<P>
   But initiation of a 63-home-run fraternity would have to wait
another day, as Sosa went 0 for 4 with four strikeouts in a 4-3
loss to the Padres.
</P>
<P>
   A crowd of 60,515 came to watch Sosa, although only 23,948 were
paying customers. It was part of a promotion in which fans could
use unused tickets from previous Padres games. The promotion was
scheduled long before Sosa made baseball history, and fans took
advantage of it for a feel of the home run fever. Paying or not,
the crowd was lively and rambunctious, filling the air with chants
of ``Sammy! Sammy!'' Every time he struck out, Padre fans would
both cheer and boo, cheering Sosa for his efforts and booing the
pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   The evening came to a dramatic climax in the eighth inning.
After the Cubs tied the score at 3-3 on a one-out home run by Jose
Hernandez, Mark Grace reached on an error to bring Sosa up to the
plate. Padres manager Bruce Bochy countered with the right-hander
Dan Miceli, who had given up Sosa's fourth home run of the season
in April.
</P>
<P>
   Miceli wasted no time, challenging Sosa with fastballs and
striking him out on four pitches, the last one swinging, to keep
the score tied. Ken Caminiti then led off the bottom of the inning
with a homer that would give the Padres the victory.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa had already faced a crowd earlier on Monday, with more than
150 members of the news media crowded into a locker room Monday
afternoon for a pre-game news conference. Sosa entered the room
with a smile and, after staring out at the waiting crowd,
sheepishly said into the microphone: ``Hi. Sorry I'm late.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, just as a reporter began to ask a question, Sosa promptly
cut him off to talk about an important phone call he fielded Monday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, I want to say that I had a beautiful phone call
from Bill Clinton, congratulating me,'' Sosa said. ``It was
something that made me proud of myself. I was jumping up and down
afterwards thinking, `I just talked to Bill Clinton.' It was a very
nice thing for him to do, and I want to say, thank you, Bill
Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me he was a Chicago Cub fan and to take Chicago to the
playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa also mentioned that he just gave the bat with which he hit
his historic home runs to the Baseball Hall of Fame, despite
reservations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit 59, 60, 61 and 62 with it,'' Sosa said. ``But when they
told me that it would be close to the bats of Mark McGwire and
Roger Maris, I said, `OK' ''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa's situation is quite different from the one that the St.
Louis Cardinals' Mark McGwire is in. The Cubs are in the the
National League wild-card chase, tied with the Mets. Whereas
McGwire has been the main focus in St. Louis, Sosa is helping
Chicago's post-season chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Sammy has helped us a lot,'' said Cubs center fielder
Lance Johnson, who threw out a runner at home to end the second
inning Monday night to preserve a 1-0 Cubs lead. ``He's taken
attention away from other players so we don't have to deal with any
of this, or the media, and we could play great ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Leading off the second inning, Sosa walked to the plate to a
standing ovation and, amid blinking flashbulbs, the public-address
announcer introduced Sosa as ``one of only two players to hit 62
home runs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
