<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONDAY-NFL-1stLD-Writethru-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONDAY NIGHT GAMES LOSE HOUR, TAVERN ATTENDANCE, L.A. BAR OWNERS
SAY
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attention editors: Adds quotes to TV show ``Monday Night
Football'') (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Will also move in the ``s'' sports news file.) 
BY ENRIQUE RIVERO  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The hour-earlier start of ``Monday Night Football'' may have
East Coast tavern owners cheering wildly, but their counterparts in
the West think someone fumbled the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Area bar operators who traditionally have counted on Mondays
during football season for a large chunk of their income say
business has dropped as much as 25 percent because of the new 5:10
p.m. game start.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say we're probably down 15 to 20 percent,'' said Dave
Flemming, general manager of the Corbin Bowl Sports Bar in Tarzana,
a Los Angeles suburb. ``It seems like (previous customers are) just
(going) straight home and are not coming out.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Football League agreed this year to start its
showcase Monday night games an hour earlier to appease East Coast
viewers who have complained that previous years' games ended too
late.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with kickoffs at just after 8 p.m. in the East, a typical
game will end in time for viewers to watch their local 11 p.m. news
or get home from the neighborhood bar before midnight.
</P>
<P>
   The change may be good for business for bars out East, West
Coast bar owners say, but the new kickoff is just too close to
quitting time for many people.
</P>
<P>
   George Salameh, owner of The Bull's Eye Grill &AMP; Tavern in
Northridge, an L.A. suburb, said he saw a nearly 25 percent drop in
business during this season's first ``Monday Night Football'' game
Sept. 7. Before the change, the Monday night crowd accounted for up
to 20 percent of Salameh's weekly revenues.
</P>
<P>
   This year, people are ``just getting out of work, they don't
have time to go to a local tavern and watch the game,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the quality of competition doesn't have anything to do
with the smaller crowds. The Labor Day game was between the Denver
Broncos _ who won the Super Bowl in January and is considered one
of the best teams this year _ and the New England Patriots, a
playoff team last season. Monday's game was between the San
Francisco 49ers and the Washington Redskins, two of the NFL's most
popular teams.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Tracy, owner of the MVP Sports Bar and Grill in Simi
Valley, Calif., said it's still too early to tell how much business
will fall because of the time change.
</P>
<P>
   But he fears it could drop as much as 20 percent, in part
because the tavern offers electronic interactive football games in
which patrons compete with other bars across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys that have been playing for years, it's very
difficult for them to play and have a fair chance, because the game
now starts an hour earlier,'' said Tracy. ``So it causes a pretty
big problem for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Tracy said that those responsible for the time change could have
kept in mind the needs of West Coast football fans who are just
getting out of work at kickoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could have done a happy medium and maybe started the game
at 5:30,'' said Tracy.
</P>
<P>
   Business also has dropped a little bit at The Broiler in
Northridge, but not enough to worry manager Chris Watson too much.
</P>
<P>
   Some fans, he said, seem to be waiting until about the game's
third or fourth quarter to show up at the bar. ``The crowd still
comes, but it's just a later crowd,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But since they're coming later, they're buying less. ``There's
less money spent,'' he conceded.
</P>
<P>
   Anticipating the change, The Broiler and other area taverns are
offering dinner specials or other promotions to entice customers to
stay longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game used to do it pretty much, but you have to
improvise,'' said Watson.
</P>
<P>
   Salameh said he thinks fans will adjust to the change and start
coming back to the Bull's Eye to catch the games on his big-screen
television or the seven other TVs scattered throughout the tavern.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's not going to bring it up to the same volume that
we've had in past years,'' said Salameh said.
</P>
<P>
   Flemming said Corbin Bowl doesn't depend to a great extent on
Monday night crowds so his business will do OK, even though
attendance at this year's first Monday game dropped about 25
percent from the previous year's.
</P>
<P>
   The tavern has a number of bowling leagues and other activities
that bring in paying customers. ``It's just a small part of
business,'' Flemming said about the ``Monday Night Football''
crowd. ``It's not going to crush the bar.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-98 0133EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
