<SLUG> BC-FBC-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUSKIES HOPE TO GIVE BYU GOOD WAC-ING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ On display Saturday at Husky Stadium is the equivalent
of Pavarotti singing at the rodeo.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about out of character. Brigham Young University, home to
the greatest passing offense in NCAA football history, will offer
for the Washington football home opener
three-yards-and-a-cloud-of-beehives.
</P>
<P>
   Behind a running back named Ronney Jenkins, whom UW coach Jim
Lambright likens to Napoleon Kaufman, BYU has gone Ground Chuck.
</P>
<P>
   In its two games, a close road loss at Alabama and a home win
over Arizona State, BYU has thrown a total of 51 passes. In the
past, BYU could throw 51 passes between ``Oh, say can you see ...
'' and ``... rocket's red glare ...''
</P>
<P>
   BYU quarterbacks occupy the first five spots in the NCAA's
career pass efficiency ratings: Ty Detmer, Steve Sarkisian, Jim
McMahon, Steve Young and Robbie Bosco. John Walsh is No. 8.
</P>
<P>
   Last week against ASU, current Cougar QB Kevin Feterik completed
six passes. The only way he can get into a meeting of the BYU QB
alumni club is through the federal witness protection program.
</P>
<P>
   What's next? BYU coach LaVell Edwards in drag?
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the Huskies, as gracious hosts, will attempt to
keep the expected sellout from staring rudely all afternoon at
their guests' disfigurement.
</P>
<P>
   Washington is coming out in a role reversal of its own _ a full
WAC.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, the Western Athletic Conference, of which BYU is a
member, has been home to the throw-first-and-ask-questions-later
offense. WAC teams pass from second-and-one, they pass from
7-Eleven, they pass from 21 points ahead, they pass from punt
formation and once in a while on a kickoff.
</P>
<P>
   It's football as the Roman god Mercury would have played it.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's the way the 1998 Huskies will play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up in the Big Sky Conference, the little brother of the
WAC,'' said UW offensive coordinator Scott Linehan, a former
University of Idaho quarterback under then-coach Dennis Erickson.
``To me that was football, 50-40 games. That's the way football is
supposed to be played.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little different than what folks are used to here.''
</P>
<P>
   A little different? Scott, you are sandbagging, if the 42-38 win
over Arizona State Sept. 5 was an example. This is not Don James
football, where the Huskies put their best athletes on defense and
special teams and double-dared the offense to screw it up.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't even Jim Lambright football, which took the James
style and added hairier arms and thicker necks.
</P>
<P>
   This is BYU, with faster guys.
</P>
<P>
   Against the Sun Devils, Husky quarterback Brock Huard threw a
personal-high 47 passes and completed 27, three shy of Sonny
Sixkiller's school record. He threw to a group of receivers whose
most experienced pass catcher was a running back with eight
previous receptions. But at times there seemed to be dozens of
receivers.
</P>
<P>
   They ran past the local guys with a preposterous final-seconds
touchdown pass, at nearly 11 on a Saturday night, lifting every
college football fan off his or her bar stool, beer spilling up and
down the West Coast.
</P>
<P>
   The full WAC.
</P>
<P>
   ``That,'' said Linehan, ``was the best one-game experience I
ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because he was the only guy in purple who was certain it
would work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The God's-honest truth is that there were nine coaches, 10
counting Lambright, that were sitting there wondering what we were
putting out there,'' he said. ``They'd seen it in practice. But
when the lights kicked on, who was going to come to play? We had
confidence in them, and kinda turned over the game plan to the
players.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the way it's going to be this season, more or less.
Linehan knows that surprise was a one-time weapon now lost, so the
Huskies are going to have to show a little something else Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm smart enough to know that if a team says it will double-
and triple-team our receivers, and use lots of nickel or dime
coverage, we'll abandon our pass-first game,'' he said. ``It'll be
fun to see, as the year goes on, how the opponents view us. Our
opener was a little new for Arizona State, as far as throwing the
ball around. But we have to come up with a guy who can put a
hundreds yards on the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   That's all well and good coach-think. Still, it's obvious you
can take the boy out of the Big Sky, but ...
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kinda fun to throw the ball 70 percent of the time on
first down and not even think about it; to have the ability to
throw six times in a row,'' he said. ``It's so unlike anything
that's been done here.''
</P>
<P>
   He's quick to credit his boss for walking with him to the edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lambright goes from a defense/special teams guy who tries not
to lose on offense, to a no-holds-barred offense that keeps
possession with the pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``Talk about coming out of a comfort zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Lambright and the Huskies couldn't look more different if they
wore Easter bonnets. Presuming they could get the headgear away
from BYU.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-98 0145EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
