<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 01:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5294 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN     09-15 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHEFFIELD: MONDESI DEMAND NO WORRY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Gary Sheffield returned to the Los Angeles Dodgers
dugout Monday night but just for a visit. His season ended two
weeks ago with a sprained left ankle.
</P>
<P>
   But his 1998 plans already have an interesting wrinkle now that
Raul Mondesi wants his spot back in right field.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't the only thing going on at Dodger Stadium, where the
Dodgers defeated the Colorado Rockies 4-1, but it certainly was the
most interesting.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Eric Young sprained his right foot in the first inning and
could be lost for the final 12 games of the season. But the Dodgers
already have been through that with Sheffield and Jose Vizcaino.
</P>
<P>
   And Carlos Perez, who suffered a sprained ankle of his own
before Sunday's game in San Diego, returned to pitch his third
consecutive complete game and came within two outs of pitching a
shutout before Kurt Abbott hit a pinch home run.
</P>
<P>
   But Sheffield and Mondesi are the two best players on the team.
They also are the highest paid. To avoid a repeat of this season,
new Dodgers GM Kevin Malone needs to get the situation solved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know something can be worked out,'' said Sheffield, who will
have a soft cast removed from his ankle today. ``Whether I go to
left or Mondy goes to left, it will be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for one thing. Mondesi has said he only wants to play
right field, where he won Gold Gloves the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield began his career as a shortstop in Milwaukee and
played third base in San Diego. He is the team's highest-paid
player, just finishing the first season on a six-year deal totaling
$68.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi, the club leader with 30 homers and 88 RBI, moved to
center when Sheffield came over from Florida in the May 15 Mike
Piazza deal. But he also developed lower-back pain from the extra
running and has told the team there is no way he is going back.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a great thing he did,'' Sheffield said. ``A lot of
people, myself included, think he can be a Gold Glover out there,
too. But it does take its toll physically.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday's victory also took its toll.
</P>
<P>
   Young, the only member of the Dodgers' starting lineup to play
on Opening Day, walked to open the first inning but was picked off
by Rockies starter Bobby Jones (7-8). He raced to second but caught
his right foot on the bag as he slid. Young, who missed 34 games
earlier this season with a strained left thigh, was helped off the
field and taken to the hospital for X-rays.
</P>
<P>
   Young's replacement, Juan Castro, started the winning rally in
the eighth inning after Perez and Jones each pitched seven
scoreless innings.
</P>
<P>
   Castro opened with a single and thought he was moving to second
on a sacrifice by Trenidad Hubbard. Jones fielded the ball, but his
left knee collapsed attempting to throw to first and the ball
sailed down the right-field line.
</P>
<P>
   Castro never broke stride and scored easily. Hubbard took
second. Karros walked and Bobby Bonilla doubled to right for the
Dodgers' second run. Two outs and an intentional walk later, left
fielder Roger Cedeno singled home Karros to make it 3-0. With the
bases loaded, Perez walked for the fourth run of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Perez, who had allowed just two runs in his previous 18 innings,
showed no ankle problems. Until the ninth, only one batter, former
teammate Mike Lansing, reached third.
</P>
<P>
   Perez, like Sunday's starter Ismael Valdes, is eligible for
salary arbitration at the end of the season and could be in for a
hefty pay raise if he finishes strongly. After coming over from
Montreal with Mark Grudzielanek on July 31, Perez has been streaky.
He was winless in his first six decisions, including three losses.
But ever since he became angry when manager Glenn Hoffman removed
him from his Aug. 28 start with a 4-1 lead, he has been dominant.
</P>
<P>
   He pitched a two-hit shutout against Philadelphia on Sept. 2 and
allowed just two runs to Arizona in his next start.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel more comfortable now,'' Perez said. ``When you come
from a different organization, it takes two or three starts to get
a feel for the team. But now my confidence is great. The coaching
staff is letting me pitch my game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
