<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 01:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5295 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGNOTE-LADN     09-15 0516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGNOTE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HASEGAWA DELIVERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Shigetoshi Hasegawa did it again. The
Anaheim Angels' set-up man pitched two scoreless innings Monday
night, relieving starter Omar Olivares and setting up Troy Percival
in the Angels' 4-2 win.
</P>
<P>
   And he did it the hard way.
</P>
<P>
   After an infield single and an error by second baseman Randy
Velarde on a potential double play ball, the Devil Rays had runners
on first and second with nobody out in the seventh inning, leading
2-0.
</P>
<P>
   But Hasegawa struck out Quinton McCracken, Wade Boggs and Bobby
Smith to get out of it. After the Angels took the lead in the top
of the eighth, Hasegawa set down the Rays 1-2-3 in the bottom of
the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's awesome, Percival said. ``Tonight was as good as I've
seen him in a while. He's fresh again. He gets worn down and never
says anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Said manager Terry Collins: ``One thing about him, he's not a
strikeout pitcher. When he strikes out the side, you know he's
bearing down.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Erstad getting better: Darin Erstad is smiling again.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad, who strained his left hamstring Sept. 2, had moped
around the clubhouse with a frown for days, refusing to talk about
his injury. But because the hamstring has made rapid improvement,
his mood is better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have to spend 16 hours in the training room every day
any more,'' he explained. ``It's better.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's not good enough to play. Though he's taking ground
balls and batting practice, he's running at only 20 percent, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seriously, I can't run,'' he said. ``Acceleration is the big
thing. I need to build confidence in it.''
</P>
<P>
   It is possible Erstad could get a pinch-hitting appearance in
Texas later this week, but he probably won't be back in the
starting lineup until sometime during the final homestand, Sept.
18-23.
</P>
<P>
   __ Koufax in the house: As he did the last time the Angels were
in town, Hall of Fame pitcher and ex-Dodger Sandy Koufax made the
drive from his home in Vero Beach to St. Petersburg to visit
Collins, a longtime friend, at Tropicana Field.
</P>
<P>
   With Koufax around, the Angels are 4-0, all four wins coming in
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we can take him to Texas with us,'' Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Also: Gregg Jefferies reinjured his right hamstring Monday
night beating out an infield hit in the eighth inning, getting the
Angels started on their game-winning rally. ``I've played through
it before, I'll do it again,'' Jefferies said.... Third baseman
Troy Glaus was named the Minor League Player of the Year by Howe
Sportsdata International. In 109 minor-league games this season
split between Double-A Midland and Triple-A Vancouver, Glaus hit
.307 with 35 homers and 93 RBI.... The Angels won coin flips with
Boston, Toronto and Texas in case of a tie for the wild card spot
(with Boston or Toronto) or the AL West title (with Texas). Winning
the coin flips mean the Angels would host a one-game playoff
against any of those teams on Monday, Sept. 28.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
