<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DINOSAUR-HEADBASHING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DINOSAUR STUDY SHOWS THICK-SKULL SPECIES DIDN'T BASH HEADS 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID PERLMAN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Dinosaur fantasies die hard.
</P>
<P>
   And now a study of the notorious head-butting creatures called
Pachycephalosaurs, who are so often likened to modern bighorn
sheep, establishes clearly that they did nothing of the sort,
according to a team of fossil hunters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to kill the myth,'' said paleontologist Mark Goodwin
of the University of California at Berkeley, who has collected
fossils of the ancient beasts and recently led a team that analyzed
skulls of Pachycephalosaurs in great detail.
</P>
<P>
   Embattled members of the plant-eating Pachycephalosaur family
may well have used their heads to attack each other on their
flanks, or even flailed away against each other with their
unusually stiffened tails. But their skulls were surely not built
for ramming each other, no matter how fierce their competition,
Goodwin says.
</P>
<P>
   So there is no truth to the theory that one recent authoritative
book described like this:
</P>
<P>
   ``Like a great crash helmet, the thick skull could have absorbed
tremendous impact as rival males butted each other, head-on.''
</P>
<P>
   The skulls of those dinosaurs were nothing at all like crash
helmets, according to Goodwin's analysis. Thin shavings from the
fossil skull of one species, called Stegoceras, show that although
their dome-shaped heads _ often round like bowling balls _ appear
to be solid bone, the bony structures are laced like honeycombs
with the remnants of blood vessels that actually made the skulls
porous rather than rigid.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly wouldn't be in their own best interests to ram
heads in a fight,'' Goodwin said. ``They would have killed each
other, and a couple of bowling balls would hardly make good
targets.''
</P>
<P>
   There is also no evidence from the fossil skulls that the
animals Goodwin's team analyzed bore any scars indicating healed
injuries from a head-on fight, Goodwin said.
</P>
<P>
   Nor are the fossils _ gathered primarily from Montana and North
Dakota _ anything like the skulls of head-butting animals like
bighorn sheep, he said. Bighorns have broad, flat heads with
spreading horns and air-filled chambers in their skulls that can
absorb head-on blows.
</P>
<P>
   Goodwin is a principal scientist at UC Berkeley's Museum of
Paleontology, and has reported his team's new findings in the
Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology. His colleagues include Emily
Buchholtz, now at Wellesley College, and Rolf Johnson of the
Milwaukee Public Museum.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
