A5297 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-QUARK-SFCHRON &LR;      09-15 0525
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUARK-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Quark Drops Unsolicited Bid for Adobe   By Benny Evangelista  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
Quark Inc., facing opposition even among its own customers,
yesterday announced it has dropped an unsolicited bid to buy rival
desktop publishing maker Adobe Systems Inc. of San Jose.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chairman Tim Gill said Denver's Quark decided to stop pursuing
the purchase of its larger rival because Adobe founders John
Warnock and Charles Geschke have rejected a sale and refused to
even discuss a friendly takeover.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hostile takeovers don't work in high tech,'' Gill said.
``There would be no point in pursuing it at this time. If Adobe's
opinion would ever change, we would like to talk to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Quark's withdrawal ended a brief takeover drama that had upset
desktop publishers, many of whom feared Quark taking over its only
major rival and dominating the market.
</P>
<P>
   Some industry watchers saw the bid as a publicity stunt by
Quark, but one analyst said the takeover attempt spotlighted the
strengths and weaknesses of both companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day, we were left with much ado about
nothing,'' said Craig Cline, an analyst and vice president with
Seybold Seminars in Foster City. ``On the other hand, it caused us
to start sitting up and looking at these companies again and we
found both of them wanting.''
</P>
<P>
   Adobe issued only a brief statement that Warnock and Geschke
were pleased with Quark's withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very grateful for the tremendous support we have
received from our business partners, customers and our employees.
We continue to focus on the exciting opportunities available to
us,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   Privately held Quark made the announcement after the stock
market closed. Adobe stock closed at $28.50, up 50 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Quark revealed last month it had tried to approach Adobe with an
offer, which was flatly rejected. Quark never announced how much
money it was prepared to offer, but Gill had said the company had
the needed financing.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the offer, Adobe's stock value was slumping
toward its 52-week low of $23.63 per share on September 4. Adobe's
low stock price was one reason Quark tried for the friendly
takeover, Gill said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Adobe's stock has started to rebound, making a
potential deal more expensive.
</P>
<P>
   And, Gill said, Adobe's ``poison pill'' stock repurchase plan
designed to thwart a hostile takeover would have made the deal too
costly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was clear they wanted to stay on their own,'' Gill said.
``It just wasn't worth pursuing.''
</P>
<P>
   Quark also found it had only lukewarm support in the publishing
industry. At a major publishing convention sponsored by Seybold
Seminars this month in San Francisco, attendees at a special panel
discussion on the potential Quark-Adobe marriage griped about
Quark's past history of customer service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody in the room voted in favor of the merger,'' said Cline,
one of the panel moderators. ``They railed against Quark and its
support policies, which to be fair to Quark, they have recently
taken steps to address. But they have a long history of ticking
people off.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
