A5298 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-ALEX-SPI     09-15 1108
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-ALEX-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RODRIGUEZ'S NUMBERS BETTER THAN GRIFFEY'S AFTER FIRST 500 GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM STREET  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ They entered the major leagues five years apart
under entirely different circumstances. One was a franchise messiah
coming to a last-place team, while the other had the luxury of
breaking into a division championship lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Griffey Jr. was the Mariner trailblazer, the team's first
superstar.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Rodriguez has walked in those same tracks.
</P>
<P>
   As the Mariners' disappointing season enters its final two
weeks, the team's brightest stars are winding up productive
seasons. They aren't the reasons the M's will finish third or
fourth in the American League West but are largely responsible for
turning a bedraggled franchise into one of the most popular in
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   And based on a 500-game comparison, the standards Griffey
established since he became The Franchise in 1989 have been
exceeded by Rodriguez, in numbers if not stature.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey still is The Man. Rodriguez is The Man II.
</P>
<P>
   They are among the most prolific twosomes in the majors the past
three seasons, batting second and third in the Mariner lineup,
feeding off each other's love for the game and burning desire to
succeed and win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know them personally or get a chance to see them play
every day,'' longtime American League scout Gordon Lakey said,
``but I think they push each other. They are good for one
another.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He pushes me,'' Rodriguez said of Griffey. ``When I look up
and see what he has done, I want to do the same things. It's
natural, like what Sammy Sosa and Mark McGwire have done for each
other this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It think playing together has been great for both of us.''
</P>
<P>
   It is because they reached the majors under such different
conditions that comparisons are difficult.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Griffey reached the 500-game plateau, 64 games into
his fourth big-league season in 1992, the Mariners were still three
years away from becoming a postseason contender. Rodriguez, who
played in his 500th major league game Monday, became involved in a
pennant race almost immediately. The Mariners were a combined
297-351 in Griffey's first four seasons, 303-277 in Rodriguez's
first four.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Alex would do well in any environment,'' manager Lou
Piniella said. ``He is very headstrong, confident and works very
hard for success.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time, playing with guys like Junior, Jay Buhner
and Edgar Martinez to name a few didn't put him in a position where
he had to be the main guy. He could blend in, utilize his skills
and be a contributor. When Junior came in, he became the franchise
guy by himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Any team would be delighted to have either player in its lineup,
and the Mariners realize their good fortune of having both. They
are arguably the best 1-2 punch in the majors, combining for 90
home runs and 243 RBIs this season.
</P>
<P>
   Although Rodriguez, 23, has batted in every lineup position
during his brief major league career, he has excelled as the No. 2
batter, hitting in front of the 28-year-old Griffey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are very flattering numbers,'' said Rodriguez, as he
looked at the numerical comparison after 500 major league games.
``To match up with a guy like Griff is very flattering. I have
benefited greatly by hitting in front of him. Any time you have a
Ken Griffey Jr. hitting behind you, you are going to get good
pitches to hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Case in point: Despite hitting a career-high 39 homers this
season Rodriguez hasn't received an intentional walk this season.
Griffey has 11, even with two-time AL batting champion Martinez
hitting behind him.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez has taken advantage of this ideal situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The numbers don't surprise me,'' Lakey said. ``Griffey didn't
have the same caliber of players on the team when he broke in that
Alex did. (Rodriguez) had the best player in the game already in
place, and that took a lot of pressure off him. Griffey was so
highly touted he made the transition for Alex much easier. But both
are tremendous players, and you don't see that kind of talent on
the same team very often.''
</P>
<P>
   Timing isn't everything. But it helps. Both broke in as
teenagers. Griffey won a roster spot in 1989 spring training when
he was 19 years old and the Mariners were perennial losers.
Rodriguez was called up for 17 games in 1994 as an 18-year-old and
then for 48 games in the division championship season of 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been fortunate to play with some great players. Not only
Griff, but Edgar and Jay,'' Rodriguez said. ``I've been a
beneficiary of this lineup and so has Junior.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially the past five seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't compare us,'' Griffey said. ``A better comparison is
Alex and Gar (Martinez). Nothing against Alex because he plays the
game the way it's supposed to be played, like every game is your
last, but you have a guy, number one, who didn't have a guy like me
hitting behind him.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey broke in batting second ahead of Alvin Davis, the
Mariners' best hitter at the time. But Davis was no Griffey.
</P>
<P>
   When Griffey arrived, the M's had one winning season in
franchise history. ``There were some established players, but no
superstars,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Alex got here, it was totally different. Alex didn't have
to create baseball in Seattle. All he had to do was go play and
have fun. That's all we wanted him to do. He already had myself,
Jay and Edgar on the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Although both have performed superbly in their lineup spots,
Piniella is considering a different look for next season, moving
Rodriguez from second to fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we do depends on what we can get done over the winter,''
Piniella said. ``One of our top priorities is to get a (prototype)
leadoff hitter. I can see (Carlos) Guillen fitting into the second
hole. Or, we could put (David) Segui there. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Alex basically is not a second hitter. He's a 3-4 guy, and we
have a pretty fair guy in the three hole already. The fourth spot
is a nice spot for him to settle into. I think after a couple of
years in the major leagues and with the success he's had, I think
he's ready for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Rodriguez, ``I like hitting second because you come to the
plate a lot. Hitting fourth will allow me to drive in more runs,
but also will take some at-bats away.''
</P>
<P>
   Wherever they are in the lineup doesn't figure to alter their
hitting styles or production.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, my next 500 games will be better than the first
500,'' Rodriguez said. ``But I have set some pretty high standards
for myself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
