<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 01:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5299 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHARPER-SFCHRON &LR;      09-15 1697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHARPER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Sharper Image Gets Serious  &HT;       
 By Carol Emert  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
One sure sign it's not the 1980s anymore: Richard Thalheimer, the
once high-flying chairman of Sharper Image Inc., has sold his
corporate jet.
<P>
   After years of taking guff about living lavishly while his
company stagnated, Thalheimer bowed to pressure and sold off the
company's leather-upholstered nine-seater this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I happen to believe it is an incredibly cost-effective
business tool, but it is also true that, for many people, the
corporate jet is a lightning rod of emotion,'' Thalheimer said in a
recent interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some investors have said that if I'm serious about the
business I would get rid of it. If this sets the tone that we're
serious about saving money, then so be it.''
</P>
<P>
   The move signifies just how much Sharper Image, known as a
purveyor of expensive toys for middle-aged boys, and its founder _
who is often described as an autocrat _ have changed the way they
do business.
</P>
<P>
   Worn down by years of erratic financial performance and a stock
price that is languishing in the basement, Thalheimer, the creative
mind behind the company, has ceded control of Sharper Image's
day-to-day operations.
</P>
<P>
   The company faces daunting challenges such as updating its
image, avoiding inventory shortfalls, developing one-of-a-kind
proprietary products and keeping unique merchandise flowing into
stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think I wake up smug and happy, but in fact I wake up
... with tremendous shame that we haven't achieved the kinds of
sales and earnings we should have,'' said Thalheimer, who launched
Sharper Image in 1978 after earning degrees at Yale University and
Hastings College of Law.
</P>
<P>
   Thalheimer accepted only $150,000 of the $257,500 bonus he was
eligible for last year because, with earnings weak, ``I just didn't
feel I earned it,'' he said. (Thalheimer, the company's chairman
and chief executive still isn't hurting _ his 1997 salary totaled
$479,134.)
</P>
<P>
   While Sharper Image profitably operates 85 U.S. stores, a
catalog division and an up-and-coming Web site
( &LR; www.sharperimage.com &LR; ), last year's sales of $210 million weren't
appreciably higher than its 1989 revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from a rumor-driven bump in April, Sharper Image's shares
have been stalled at around $3 to $4 _ compared to the 1987 initial
public offering price of $10. This state of affairs hurts no one
more than Thalheimer, who owns two-thirds of the outstanding
shares.
</P>
<P>
   Sharper Image has suffered from a range of chronic problems over
the years, from inventory shortfalls and product development delays
to a repeated lack of focus.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the company has tried new concepts including
children's catalogs and a bath and body business called the SPA
Collection. In the Sharper Image stores, it experimented with such
noncore lines as clothing and mainstream brands of consumer
electronics.
</P>
<P>
   None of these ideas had staying power. In the early 1990s, a
combination of economic weakness and merchandising mistakes
contributed to two annual net losses. In 1996, the retailer a took
an $8 million charge to close the SPA catalog and six SPA stores.
</P>
<P>
   Behind these problems stands Thalheimer's propensity to govern
by whim rather than strategy, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a classic entrepreneur,'' said one former Sharper Image
executive. ``He comes in the room and says `Let's stop going south,
let's go north. A few minutes later he comes in again and says,
`Why aren't you all going north? The decision has been made.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to tell you that it is highly unusual for a creative
person to have any significant management skills,'' added Kenneth
Gassman, an analyst with Davenport &AMP; Co. who is one of the few
stock analysts who bother to follow Sharper Image these days. ``If
you print that, Richard'll probably be pissed, &UR;  &LR; but he'd probably
say privately, `You're right.'''
</P>
<P>
   Still, people who know Thalheimer well credit him with having
extraordinary merchandising vision.
</P>
<P>
   He can see unimpressive, even bizarre products, such as a tiny
air conditioner people wear around their necks (10,000 of these
Personal Cooling Systems were sold last month alone for $49 each)
or gel shoe inserts &UR;  &LR; (at $15, one of the company's most profitable
products ever), and sell millions of dollars of them.
</P>
<P>
   Thalheimer conceded his strengths and his weaknesses a year and
a half ago when he brought in Barry Gilbert, a former Warner Bros.
Studio Stores executive who manages Sharper Image's day-to-day
operations.
</P>
<P>
   While Thalheimer had hired managers before, he had never
relinquished authority to them as he has with Gilbert, people close
to the company say. Thalheimer now spends four days a week in
Sharper Image's Novato engineering laboratory developing new
products.
</P>
<P>
   ``For him to walk away from (hands-on management) is a hell of a
step,'' said the former executive.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert's major changes at the company include replacing top
managers and focusing on more practical gadgets rather than pure
toys &UR; . &LR;  (Think air purifiers instead of life-size Darth Vader
dolls).
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; He also is establishing a system for measuring the performance
of each of the company's divisions so that profitable units can be
cultivated and unprofitable ones eliminated, a seemingly obvious
step that led to the closure of the SPA division.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert, the company's chief operating officer and vice
chairman, said he continues to monitor an upscale furniture catalog
business, the Sharper Image Home Collection, which was launched two
years ago and is expected to generate revenues of at least $10
million this year.
</P>
<P>
   Under Gilbert, Sharper Image's performance has improved
dramatically. In the first half of the year total revenues grew 12
percent and the year-to-date loss is running 8 percent lower than
in the first half of 1997. Like many retailers, Sharper Image
generally loses money until the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Sales this year are projected at $240 million to $250 million
with growth driven mostly by sales from the newly redesigned
Sharper Image catalog.
</P>
<P>
   But just as results appeared to be improving, the company ran
into trouble last month. August same-store sales declined 2 percent
as the company struggled to ship merchandise from Asia. It also
faced an old nemesis: an inventory shortage of some products.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Asia problem weren't there I'd be pounding the table on
the stock and the stock ... would probably be $5 to $7,'' said
Gassman.
</P>
<P>
   To add to the challenge, Sharper Image, widely seen as a symbol
of the conspicuous consumption of the 1980s, continues to fight a
dated image. Most of the company's stores, which account for about
70 percent of total sales, have not been renovated for years and
are stuck with a gray 1980s look.
</P>
<P>
   Sharper Image this fall is opening redesigned test stores, which
employ a new floor plan and are painted in 1990s white instead of
1980s gray, in Orlando, Fla., and in Manhattan. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Sharper Image plans to open future stores in this style,
including six this year and 10 in 1999, &UR;  &LR; but it is still faced with
more than 80 stale-looking stores. Finding the $40 million that
Thalheimer estimates is needed for renovations will not be easy and
may not be possible.
</P>
<P>
   Introducing a new look piecemeal also has its dangers, warned
William Dean, a San Francisco direct mail consultant. To avoid
consumer confusion, ``Sharper Image needs to be very careful to
maintain the same image across all media,'' including catalogs, the
Web site and stores, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the company's biggest challenge is to increase its
offering of company-developed products, which are sold under the
name Sharper Image Design.
</P>
<P>
   Some currently hot proprietary items include the Personal
Cooling System; the Ionic Breeze, an air purifier with no moving
parts ($199); and the Ionic Hair Wand, which cleans and conditions
hair without shampoo or water ($39).
</P>
<P>
   Proprietary products carry wider profit margins than merchandise
bought from outside companies. They also ensure that the company
has the kind of unique gizmos it needs to keep shoppers browsing
the stores and skimming the catalogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time our (comparable store) sales aren't good, it's
because products are late,'' said Thalheimer. Late gadgets mean
lower sales, lower profits and angry investors _ which translates
into lower share prices.
</P>
<P>
   But conceiving of unique high-tech items that will catch on in
the marketplace _ and developing them on time and on budget _ is
much trickier than, say, selling mainstream brands of consumer
electronics or designing and selling apparel.
</P>
<P>
   ``You really need the next big thing nobody's ever heard of to
make this business successful,'' said a former Sharper Image
executive. ``It's not like changing a skirt length from season to
season.''
</P>
<P>
   After years of struggling to increase its selection of
house-designed goods, Sharper Image finally made some progress this
year, with the percentage of sales from proprietary products
doubling to a still-modest 16 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Thalheimer said he would like to see the share grow as high as
50 to 70 percent; Gilbert said he's not certain it will ever be
higher than one-third.
</P>
<P>
   Among the uncertainties hovering over Sharper Image is a major
question mark about Thalheimer's future with the company.
</P>
<P>
   For years, he has talked about selling his shares to a
deep-pocketed investor, according to his colleagues. But he is
faced with the fact that he owns most of the company's stock and
its market value is extremely low.
</P>
<P>
   Sharper Image's market capitalization today is just one-sixth of
annual sales, while the going rate for recently acquired retailers
has been about equal to their annual sales or a little higher,
Thalheimer noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if I got a 100 percent premium ... it won't impress me
that's very fair,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   People close to Thalheimer said he has spoken as recently as
this year about devising an exit strategy. But given the state of
the market, Thalheimer said, ``While at some point in my life I
would want to do that (sell shares), it probably is five to 10
years out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
