<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WELLS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Wells CEO's Parachute Is Not as Golden   By Peter Sinton  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Although Wells Fargo Chief Executive Paul Hazen won't head the new
bank resulting from the merger with Norwest Corp. of Minneapolis,
he will receive whatever the new CEO makes in salary and bonus for
five years.
<TEXT>
<P>
   In addition, Hazen will receive 500,000 shares of new restricted
stock currently worth about $16.5 million and options to buy
another 1 million shares.
</P>
<P>
   Wells Fargo's 56-year-old boss will receive a minimum of 25
percent of his $2,850,000 salary and bonus last year in annual
retirement benefits. He also will receive lifetime medical and
dental benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Hazen's employment package benefits are spelled out in proxy
materials being mailed out this week to those who own stock in
either bank.
</P>
<P>
   On October 20, shareholders will vote on the plan to create the
nation's seventh-largest bank with $191 billion in assets, branches
in 21 states, about 20 million customers and more than 90,000
employees. Norwest CEO Dick Kovacevich will head the new bank from
San Francisco and Hazen will be chairman.
</P>
<P>
   When there is a change of corporate control, top executives are
commonly guaranteed salary and bonus for three years whether they
stay or leave. But chief executives of acquired companies
increasingly are getting five-year deals. In the Wells-Norwest
deal, Hazen also is the only Wells or Norwest executive to receive
new stock grants and options.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, his so-called golden parachute package is not
particularly opulent. Bank of America Chief Executive Officer David
Coulter not only was granted the same five-year pay and bonus as
NationsBank CEO Hugh McColl, he was granted far more generous
retirement benefits. The 51-year-old CEO of BofA will receive 95
percent of his $5.24 million salary and bonus last year.
</P>
<P>
   Hazen's retirement package will provide just 25 percent of his
annual compensation with no spousal benefits. (Hazen is in the
process of getting a divorce.)
</P>
<P>
   Some observers question whether top executives should continue
to receive years of CEO pay for less responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It turns the principles of fair pay on its head,'' said
compensation critic Graef Crystal. ``Why should you get the same
pay for doing a lot less work?
</P>
<P>
   ``Becoming chairman is like going from the helm of a sailing
ship to the carved figurehead on the bow; it's pretty but not very
functional.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells Fargo and Norwest have yet to disclose the specific
responsibilities of Hazen. Kovacevich says that it is best to work
out his and Hazen's duties after completing an analysis of the two
organizations and their best business practices, not before.
</P>
<P>
   In increasingly more mergers, companies are subsidizing the
extra tax liabilities of their top brass following a takeover. But
this probably will not be necessary in the Wells/Norwest deal
because it is not legally considered a takeover since Wells
shareholders will maintain control.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, if an executive's total compensation is more than
three times his average over the previous five years, the federal
government imposes a 20 percent excise tax on everything the
individual makes over his annual average. Companies also are not
allowed to deduct such compensation, or additional payments to
cover the taxes, as business expenses.
</P>
<P>
   But Wells Fargo and Hazen should avoid these tax problems
because even though Wells is being acquired by Norwest, Wells
shareholders will retain 52 percent control of the combined
company.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
