<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HACK-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Hack Attack Shows Web's Vulnerability   By Jon Swartz  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
Computer hackers who invaded the New York Times' Web site and
turned it into their own political bulletin board on Sunday could
just as easily have cracked an e-commerce site and stolen personal
information, security experts said.
<TEXT>
<P>
   A group calling itself Hacking for Girlies posted nude photos
and obscenity-laced language in support of Kevin Mitnick, a hacker
convicted of computer-related fraud charges and imprisoned in Los
Angeles since 1995. It singled out Times reporter John Markoff, who
wrote ``Take-Down,'' a book detailing the search for Mitnick.
</P>
<P>
   The virtual takeover forced the Times to shut down its home page
for nine hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any Web site _ no matter how secure _ can be hacked,'' said
Ira Winkler, a former National Security Agency expert and author on
Internet security. &UR;  &LR; ``Do I care the New York Times was hacked? No.
If this were Amazon.com and I was a customer, though, I would be
concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Cyber-intruders apparently found a chink in the Times' computer
server to gain illegal entry to the Web site, sources said. The
Washington Post incorrectly reported that hackers bypassed the
paper's ``firewall,'' security software designed to block
intruders.
</P>
<P>
   Times spokeswoman Nancy Nielsen declined to comment on how
hackers broke into the newspaper's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Times incident proves again that high-tech security is no
better than the alertness of the administrators overseeing it,''
said Donn Parker, author of ``Fighting Computer Crime'' and an
expert in computer security at SRI International, a Menlo Park
market research firm. ``You can have the best security tools
imaginable, but that does not excuse poor security of individual
computers and Web servers.''
</P>
<P>
   Winkler added that the failure of network administrators to
frequently update their systems with security software patches
usually leads to break-ins. He said Sun Microsystems and Microsoft
typically post free monthly software fixes for their server
operating systems.
</P>
<P>
   The latest attack could come as sobering news to
computer-security personnel at banks, corporations and the
government who are instituting technology to keep hackers off their
Web sites and their internal networks. Most employ firewalls and
encrypted code, which scrambles information. Some even turn to
hackers to safeguard their systems.
</P>
<P>
   But their best efforts aren't stopping an online assault by
hackers.
</P>
<P>
   Security experts estimate annual losses from computer crime
range from $55 million to more than $1 billion. Many U.S.
businesses don't report losses because they weren't aware of an
intrusion or out of fear of bad publicity.
</P>
<P>
   The alarming rise in electronic burglary comes just as
cyberspace is becoming a major artery for commerce. Time Warner,
for example, is among the latest corporations aggressively pursuing
a Web retail strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Financial transactions over the Internet could balloon to $37.5
billion this year, according to market researcher Jupiter
Communications.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for the Times, it was propaganda _ not money _ that
motivated this weekend's hacker takeover of its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's virtual diatribe is the second major hacker break-in in
support of Mitnick. In December, Mitnick sympathizers cracked
Yahoo's site and claimed to have planted a computer virus that
would cause widespread damage on Christmas Day if Mitnick was not
freed from jail. The threat turned out to be a hoax.
</P>
<P>
   Mitnick's trial date has been set for January.
</P>
<P>
   Mitnick is discouraging disruptive online protests in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kevin Mitnick appreciates the support and good wishes of those
who speak out against his continued incarceration for years without
bail,'' Donald Randolph, Mitnick's attorney, said in a statement
yesterday. ``However, he does not encourage any individuals to
engage in hacking pranks on his behalf.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
