<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Now May Be Time for Small-Fry Investment Bankers to Shine   By Tom Abate  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
It's a toss-up as to which will be the hottest topic at the
NationsBanc Montgomery Securities Conference in San Francisco this
week _ the companies that strut their financials to institutional
investors or the mergers that are redrawing the city's
investment-banking landscape.
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the wake of Monty's messy marriage to NationsBanc, and
Robertson Stephens' shotgun wedding to BancBoston, some of the
city's small-fry investment bankers think that it's the perfect
time to be niche bankers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shops that grew up on the (high-tech and biotech) niches
have now gotten absorbed into national banks that want them to do
everything from steel to cement,'' said Tom Volpe, founder of
Volpe, Brown, Whelan. ``They're not going to be able to focus on
high tech and biotech like they used to.''
</P>
<P>
   As Volpe sees it, Monty and Robbie, with the blessings of their
new corporate parents, are trying to equal the top-rung
investment-banking firms like Morgan Stanley, Goldman Sachs or
Lehman Brothers, who do deals in every industry, including
technology.
</P>
<P>
   As Monty and Robbie quit being tech specialists, Volpe said,
they open an opportunity for existing tech bankers, like VBW or the
Soundview Financial Group, to make a killing in tech IPOs.
</P>
<P>
   Wishful thinking, replied Rex Sherry, a senior banker at
Montgomery. Although Nations wants Monty to add banking experts in
a host of new fields, it isn't gonna do something dumb, like ignore
the small tech startups that made it famous.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything, the reverse is true,'' Sherry said. ``The
Goldmans and the Morgans are chasing the same $20 million IPO as us
because everybody wants to find the next Oracle or Microsoft.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee Hanson specializes in recruiting investment bankers for
Heidrick &AMP; Struggles in San Francisco. She agreed with Sherry that
it would be unlikely that the new and enlarged Monty or Robbie
would ignore tech startups.
</P>
<P>
   But she did lend credibility to the other half of Volpe's thesis
_ that the local investment-banking scene is about to see a
resurgence in new firms, the likes of which hasn't been seen since
the late '60s and early '70s, when Montgomery, Robertson Stephens
and Hambrecht &AMP; Quist made tech-banking a speciality.
</P>
<P>
   With some 30 local investment-banking firms and offices
employing 600 bankers, Hanson's instincts tell her that more than a
few bankers will get ambitious enough to hang out their own
shingles.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _Economic alert: &LR;  An economic forecast from a Santa Monica
think tank warns that real income and job creation could stall in
the Bay Area next year, as the Asian crisis damages the region's
export-driven economy.
</P>
<P>
   The report by economist Ross DeVol of the Milken Institute, a
research outfit founded by the former junk bond king, is the most
serious warning to date that Asia's woes could throw a monkey
wrench the region's high-tech economy.
</P>
<P>
   DeVol looked at a series of scenarios from the best-case _ a
quick recovery _ to worst-case _ a prolonged crisis that drags down
China, which so far has been Asia's bright spot. In the worst case,
job growth in San Francisco, which was above 3.7 percent in 1996
and 1997, slows to 1.3 percent this year and 0.4 percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Demi-Web? &LR;  As Netscape and Microsoft vie for market share,
open standards have become &UR;  &LR; casualties of the browser wars, said
Glenn Davis, chief technologist at Project Cool, a Web-development
firm in Palo Alto.
</P>
<P>
   The people who build and run Web sites are fed up with creating
two versions of their content to deal with the idiosyncrasies of
browsers that do their own thing instead of following the
standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``If things continue like this,'' Davis said ominously, ``one
day people using one or the other browser to access the Web will
only be able to get to half of the content that's out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Madder than hell and not gonna take it anymore, some 150 Web
designers will meet tomorrow night at Cisco headquarters in San
Jose. The gathering, organized by the Association of Internet
Professionals, will hear Davis and two other speakers, Dan Shafer,
a Cnet editorial director, and Jeff Veen, a Web guru at Wired
Digital, explain how ordinary Websters can stand up to the browser
bullies. See  &LR; webguild.org &LR;  for details.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got a tip, gripe or brainstorm? Tom Abate wants to hear it by phone
(650-961-2689), fax (650-961-5023) or e-mail ( &LR; abate(at &LR; 
 &LR; sign)sfgate.com &LR; ). &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
