<SLUG> BC-HP-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 HP Device Captures Printed Text, But Can It Capture Market?   By Carolyn Said  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Hewlett-Packard Co. unveiled a handheld device this week that lets
users easily capture printed text _ from a newspaper, book,
magazine, letter or any paper source _ and print, fax or e-mail it.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The HP CapShare 910, about the size and weight of a portable CD
player, holds up to 50 pages and is powered by two rechargeable AA
batteries.
</P>
<P>
   HP said the device is the most portable way yet to get hard copy
into digitized form so that you can send it. Unlike existing
handheld scanners, the CapShare doesn't have to be tethered to a
desktop or laptop computer.
</P>
<P>
   HP hopes ``mobile professionals'' will find the device a
time-saver. For example, a business traveler could use the CapShare
to capture proposals or reports and send them back to the home
office, eliminating the hunt for a copier and fax machine.
</P>
<P>
   To use the $699 device, you swipe it across a page and it
automatically captures a picture of the text in bitmap format _
meaning that, like a fax, it can't be edited.
</P>
<P>
   You can use it on any size page; the CapShare has built-in logic
that detects your freehand swipes and stitches them together into
one cohesive page.
</P>
<P>
   A test unit supplied by HP was a bit clunkier to use than
advertised and had some problems stitching together text.
</P>
<P>
   Once you capture text, you can zoom in to read it. But you can't
fax or e-mail directly from the CapShare.
</P>
<P>
   To transfer scanned data, you press a button that sends an
infrared beam from the CapShare into an infrared port on a PC,
laptop, printer or ``smart'' phone. The CapShare eventually will
work with Windows CE devices, too, HP said.
</P>
<P>
   HP DeskJet printers and many others on the market now come
equipped with infrared ports, as do most new computers. If your PC
or printer doesn't have one, you can use a serial cable included
with the scanner to transfer the data.
</P>
<P>
   Then you can e-mail or fax it, or use an optical
character-reader program to turn it into text that can be edited.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that this doesn't have its own integrated (faxing or
e-mail capability) is a big Achilles' heel,'' said Matthew Nordan,
an analyst with Forrester Research in Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   He also dings the CapShare for its cost: It's likely to find an
audience only ``among people wealthy enough to pay that $699 price
point,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite those stumbling blocks, Nordan said he thinks that the
CapShare is a harbinger of future, single-function devices. Most
portable devices, like the Palm Pilot or smart phones, provide an
array of text-entry, computing and communications functions
</P>
<P>
   CapShare ``is a corkscrew, not a Swiss army knife. It's designed
to do one thing really well, not a lot of things at once,'' Nordan
said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; HP started a special division in Greeley, Colo., to design a
new line of ``information appliances,'' which the CapShare kicks
off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Technologically, there's nothing out there like this,'' said
Charles LeCompte, president of Lyra Research in Cambridge. Despite
the price, he added, `` I'm sure there are people out there who'll
think this is the cat's whiskers. There's certainly a market. The
big question is, `Is it big enough?' ''
</P>
<P>
   HP will begin taking orders for the CapShare on its Web site
beginning October 1 and will ship the device starting December 1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
