<SLUG> BC-CURSOR-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Straight-Arrow Cursors Turn Into Web Ads   By Carol Emert  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
No longer content with boring old arrows, some Web sites are paying
hefty fees for a new technology that turns their cursors into tiny
advertisements.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Comedy Central is the first to license the technology. After
downloading a plug-in, visitors to  &LR; www.comedycentral.com &LR;  find
their cursor turned into Ben Stein, Kenny from ``South Park'' or
other comedic personalities.
</P>
<P>
   Other applications of the cursor-changing technology are more
blatantly commercial. On a financial site, for example, the cursor
could flash up-to-date ticker prices as it passes over company
names. Or it could show sales prices of compact disks at a music
site, or tidbits such as ``Grammy winner!''
</P>
<P>
   Comet Systems, the New York startup that invented the ``Comet
Cursor'' is charging $1,500 a month to license its software to a
single URL, or $3,000 for one company's use on multiple sites.
</P>
<P>
   That price tag is raising eyebrows in the advertising world,
where executives say they could rent seven or eight South of Market
billboards for the same price.
</P>
<P>
   ``$3,000 a month? To make the cursor into a Barbie's head? That
seems kind of high,'' said Andrew Hayman, executive vice president
of Publicis Technology in San Francisco. ``That seems ludicrous.''
</P>
<P>
   David Burk, president and chief executive of Walnut Creek Web
developer Clear Ink, can see the morphing cursor as a cool addition
to entertainment sites. But the fee is a problem, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``For entertainment value, it's a great thing, but I probably
wouldn't recommend it to my clients,'' Burk said. ``For $1,500 a
month, I could hire a crack programmer to do some pretty neat stuff
on a Web site.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Comet Systems, which spent $2.5 million
developing the technology, begs to differ. ``The cursor is the most
important piece of real estate on the screen because you can't move
without it,'' said Dean Margolis, chief executive of the Silicon
Alley venture.
</P>
<P>
   Banner ads, the standard form of Web advertising, easily can be
scrolled past or simply ignored, he noted.
</P>
<P>
   Comedy Central Vice President Larry Lieberman said he considers
$1,500 a good price for the software, though he admits that he got
a special deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gotten hundreds of wildly favorable e-mails, and I think
800,000 downloads of the plug-in since we launched'' about three
weeks ago, Lieberman said.
</P>
<P>
   The morphing cursor allowed Comedy Central to add lots of images
to its home page while scaling down its size, which had made it
cumbersome for surfers to download, Lieberman said.
</P>
<P>
   Many more applications for the changeable cursor now are under
development at Comedy Central, including messages such as ``On TV
tonight at 10!'' or ``This week's guest star, Gary Shandling!''
Lieberman said.
</P>
<P>
   Comet Cursor says it already has signed up Mattel, AT&AMP;T
WorldNet, 1-800-FLOWERS and other Web marketers. But to convince
the doubters, the company has hired a market research firm to study
how the recall rates of Comet Cursors compare with banner ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``We suspect there will be much better recall rates,'' Margolis
said. ``If that's the case, then we've created value for the cursor
and advertisers are likely to be willing to pay for it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
