<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUZUKI SHINES IN MARINER ROMP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM STREET  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ The Mariners might not have to put out an
all-points-bulletin this offseason to find another capable starter
in their rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Mac Suzuki continues to make a strong pitch for next season.
</P>
<P>
   The right-hander showed plenty of poise while pitching out of a
first-inning jam Monday night at the Metrodome. He later allowed
two tainted runs but was rewarded with his first major league
victory. The 23-year-old pitched into the seventh inning for the
second time in his three big-league starts as the Mariners pounded
the Minnesota Twins, 10-3, before 9,711 fans.
</P>
<P>
   Edgar Martinez, recovered from a stomach ailment that kept him
out of two games in Kansas City, provided Seattle with the go-ahead
run in a five-run sixth inning. Martinez slugged his 27th homer of
the season, but the bottom third of the Mariners' lineup provided
most of Suzuki's support.
</P>
<P>
   --Seventh-place hitter Russ Davis went 3-for-5, including a
three-run homer in the fifth inning that broke open the series
opener.
</P>
<P>
   --Ryan Radmanovich, batting eighth, had two hits and drove in
three runs.
</P>
<P>
   --Shane Monahan, batting ninth, went 2-for-4 and drove in a run.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the big story is our young pitcher,'' said manager Lou
Piniella of Suzuki. ``A few of them (young pitchers) are pitching
for next spring and he has given us three quality starts.''
</P>
<P>
   This one had a different look.
</P>
<P>
   In his previous two starts, Suzuki took shutouts into the sixth
inning but wobbled when he reached the 90-pitch count. He threw 104
pitches Monday night and appeared to get stronger as the game
progressed.
</P>
<P>
   But not strong enough in his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five or six innings is good, but I want to go seven or eight
every time and finish strong,'' he said. ``I've never pitched more
than 100 innings in my career and it seems as though when I get to
about 100 pitches, my arm feels good but my body feels tight and
tired.''
</P>
<P>
   Suzuki, 1-1 since being promoted from Class AAA Tacoma,
surrendered five hits, walked four and struck out eight. He almost
walked Chris Latham leading off the seventh, falling behind
3-and-0, but worked the count full before Latham flied to Ken
Griffey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   When Suzuki walked Alex Ochoa, pitching coach Stan Williams
pulled the starter and brought in Jose Paniagua. The right-hander
zipped through that inning and the eighth before Steve Gajkowski
finished up.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I like about Suzuki and Paniagua is they have no
fear,'' Williams said. ``Mac had good command of all of his pitches
and showed me something in that first inning.''
</P>
<P>
   The Twins had a run in and the bases loaded with one out.
</P>
<P>
   Suzuki met the challenge, retiring Todd Walker on a fly ball and
struck out Terry Steinbach.
</P>
<P>
   Radmanovich delivered a two-run double and Monahan followed with
a run-scoring single in the second inning to erase the deficit.
</P>
<P>
   Monahan also figured in Minnesota's get-even, two-run third
inning.
</P>
<P>
   The rookie left fielder sat in the visitors' dugout before the
game listening to teammates stressing the importance of watching
the flight of the ball from the moment it is hit.
</P>
<P>
   Many outfielders have lost sight of balls in the gray, teflon
ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   Monahan did fine when he looked up. It's when he didn't look
down that caused an embarrassing pratfall.
</P>
<P>
   With a runner on first base and two outs, Walker laced a double
past a diving Davis at third base. As Monahan prepared to stoop for
the ball, his feet hit a puddle of water near the Twins' bullpen
and he landed on the seat of his pants.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he regained his feet, and composure, both David
Ortiz and Walker had scored. The official scorer credited Walker
with a double and Monahan with his first error.
</P>
<P>
   Piniella complained that Walker should have been credited with a
ground-rule double but didn't get his way and departed quietly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even touch the ball,'' Monahan said. ``The ball hit
the heel of one of the pitchers out there. There was water and all
kinds of nasty stuff out there, like tobacco juice. I take a lot of
pride in my defense and to get an error ... ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-98 0153EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
