<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 01:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5310 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMMIGRANTS-MENTALHEAL     09-15 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMMIGRANTS-MENTALHEALTH-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN CULTURE LOWERS IMMIGRANTS' MENTAL STABILITY, STUDY SHOWS 
</HEADLINE>
   By CARL T. HALL  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Adapting to the American way of life can make
immigrants sick in the head, researchers reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Despite low incomes and the strains of moving to a foreign
country, immigrants typically arrive in the United States
remarkably free of alcohol or drug problems, mood disorders and
other psychiatric ailments.
</P>
<P>
   But a new study of 3,012 adults of Mexican origin living in
Fresno, Calif., found that the immigrants soon become just as
messed up as the rest of us.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers speculate that immigrants gradually lose the support
of strong extended families and other cultural tonics against
mental distress. Although it's unclear just what the protective
aspects of life in Mexico may be, the study suggests that they
don't travel well across the border.
</P>
<P>
   ``American culture has other priorities,'' said the study's lead
author, William Vega of the University of California at Berkeley's
School of Public Health. ``In this country, economic and social
mobility compete with family connections and cohesiveness.''
</P>
<P>
   Findings were based mainly on lengthy face-to-face interviews,
conducted in either Spanish or English, with equal numbers of
U.S.-born Mexican Americans and Mexican-born immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   Respondents also were divided in equal numbers of urban,
suburban and rural residents. Fresno County was picked as the focus
of the study partly because of its high Mexican American and
immigrant populations and its range of urban-to-rural environments.
</P>
<P>
   The study, published Monday in the American Medical
Association's Archives of General Psychiatry, debunks the
conventional wisdom that rapid ``Americanization'' brings surefire
psychological rewards.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it now appears that retaining Mexican cultural
traditions _ including large close-knit families, low rates of
divorce and healthy nutritional habits compared with U.S.-born
Americans _ pay off in fewer mood and anxiety disorders and far
less misuse of drugs and alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   A journal editorial that accompanied the study praised its
sophisticated research methods, which included elaborate diagnostic
tools and detailed cross-checking against psychiatric health
studies done in Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier studies that appeared to show positive effects of
acculturation in American society ``may reflect biases inherent to
studies that were done long before diagnostic criteria and
structured instruments became available,'' according to the
editorial.
</P>
<P>
   The new study looked for 14 specific disorders, including
depression, phobias, substance-abuse disorders and anti-social
personality disorder.
</P>
<P>
   In nearly every case, the recently arrived Mexican immigrants
were diagnosed with about half as much of those troubles as people
of Mexican origins born in this country. The longer the immigrants
lived in the United States, the more their mental-health profile
came to match those of the native-born Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, just 24.9 percent of the immigrants had any of the
disorders the researchers were looking for, compared with a 48.1
percent prevalence rate among the U.S.-born study subjects.
</P>
<P>
   Such findings strongly imply that genetic differences, if any,
are not a significant factor in explaining the higher rates of
mental illness in the United States compared with Mexico and other
immigrant ``donor'' countries.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever it is about life in Mexico that protects one's mental
health, those protections ``wear away in less than a generation,''
said UC Berkeley's Ralph Catalano, one of the study authors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
