<HEADER>
A5320 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HERITAGE-AZR &LR;      09-15 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERITAGE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERITAGE MONTH HIGHLIGHTS HISPANIC PIONEERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIE AMPARANO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Marcie Gorman points to a slice of Arizona history. A modest
four-room adobe home built 106 years ago, where a pioneer laid down
roots, raised a family and tilled the land.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike other frontiersmen, this one didn't make his way to
Arizona from eastern lands. He came through Mexico and represents a
fact many people don't realize: Hispanics were among Arizona's
first settlers.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Latinos around the country begin celebrating their past,
the richness of their culture and their place in American history
as part of National Hispanic Heritage Month, which runs through
Oct. 15.
</P>
<P>
   National Hispanic Heritage Month began as a week in 1968. But in
1989, a presidential proclamation expanded the observance into a
monthlong event to mark more than one-third of the major Hispanic
holidays that fall during this time.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican Independence Day begins on the night of Sept. 15. The
Central American countries of Nicaragua, Honduras, Guatemala, El
Salvador and Costa Rica celebrate Sept. 15 as the day they declared
their independence from Spain in 1821. Oct. 12, known in the United
States as Columbus Day, is El Dia de la Raza _ ``The Day of the
Race'' _ in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very proud to be a descendant of a pioneer family,'' said
Gorman, 63, who is the granddaughter of Vicente Elias, a farm
laborer who built the dirt-floor adobe home one room at a time to
accommodate his growing family. ``But our history and contribution
to American society is just starting to be recognized.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Tempe, Ariz., is restoring the home in its midst. City
officials are hoping it will eventually become a Hispanic heritage
museum and a memorial to the Mexican-American families who helped
settle the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``History in the Southwest began long before the non-indigenous
explorers came to this area,'' explains Lydia de la Vara, vice
president of the Tempe Hispanic Heritage International Corp. ``Too
often, people think that all Hispanics are new immigrants. That's
not true.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hispanic influence can be traced to 1774, when Juan Bautista
de Anza led an expedition from the interior of Mexico to what is
now Arizona, said Santos Vega of Arizona State University's
Hispanic Research Center.
</P>
<P>
   The expedition ended in San Francisco, but many people decided
to make their fortune mining, farming and ranching in the Arizona
region, particularly in the area where Clifton and Morenci now
stand, he said.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, Vega says many people forget that southern Arizona
was part of Mexico until 1854, when the Gadsden Purchase granted
30,000 square miles of Mexican territory to the United States. When
the dust settled, Mexicans living in the region became Americans by
order of treaty.
</P>
<P>
   That's how Gloria Medina's family came to be Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so funny when people ask me when my family immigrated to
the United States,'' said Medina, a 59-year-old Phoenix homemaker.
``They don't understand that many of us have been here all along.''
</P>
<P>
   Medina says she came from a family of ranchers outside of
Tucson. Later, as the family grew, they moved to different parts of
the state. Some took jobs in the mines in Clifton. Others became
farm laborers. Her father took a job in construction in Phoenix and
moved the family to that area when she was 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't all that unusual,'' explains Medina. ``But people
are always shocked and tell me, `You mean your family has been here
as long as we have?' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just look at them and say: `Longer.' ''
</P>
<P>
   It's because of these early influences and continued immigration
that the Hispanic population continues to boom.
</P>
<P>
   As of July 1, the Census Bureau reported an estimated 30.4
million Hispanics living in the United States, with 1 million
residing in Arizona. Hispanics are expected to overtake Blacks as
the nation's largest minority by 2010 and may account for almost 25
percent of the population by 2050.
</P>
<P>
   Irene Hormell, another descendant of an Arizona pioneer family,
marvels at the growth and success of Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up in a small sleepy town. We were such a small part of
the community. Now we see Hispanics and their advancement and
growing,'' said Hormell, who is a 61-year-old bilingual speech
pathology assistant.
</P>
<P>
   Her paternal ancestors were cowboys and ranchers. Her maternal
relatives came to work the mines but later became farmers and
business owners.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Hormell said her maternal grandmother, Marina Ceballos
Soto, was among Arizona's first cotton farmers. When the government
passed out free cotton seeds, she stood in line to get some, even
though she didn't own any property.
</P>
<P>
   Renting some land, Hormell said, her grandmother planted the
seeds, grew the cotton and made enough money to buy her own land.
However, there wasn't enough money to build a house. The family
lived in a tent, then built a tin house and finally an adobe home.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was ahead of her time with a vision,'' said Hormell,
reflecting upon her heritage. ``Few Hispanic women had such
vision.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
