<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS KEEP STUMBLING WITH FINISH LINE IN SIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Fresh from an underwhelming weekend along Tampa Bay,
the Texas Rangers remained at large Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   They are fugitives, running from a division title.
</P>
<P>
   At noisy, throat-tightening Oriole Park at Camden Yards Monday
night, the big out-of-town scoreboard in right field seemed to
taunt the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw it,'' designated hitter Luis Alicea said. ``We saw that
they scored, what, four runs in the eighth? We knew it came down to
us winning.''
</P>
<P>
   What the scoreboard showed was that ``they,'' the first-place
Anaheim Angels, had come back from a gamelong deficit to defeat the
Devils Rays with four runs in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   You can check the box scores.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels' Tim Salmon, run-scoring single. Jim Edmonds, RBI on
a sacrifice fly. Todd Greene, run-scoring double. Garret Anderson,
run-scoring double.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, back at Camden Yards:
</P>
<P>
   Ivan Rodriguez, 0-for-4.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Stevens, 0-for-4.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Zeile, 0-for-4.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone in red shoes, with runners in scoring position,
0-for-7.
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly a mad dash to the pennant, is it?
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, the 1-0 loss to the Orioles in the opener of a
two-game series was a brutally wrenching defeat. But no more
wrenching, you could argue, than the 3-2 loss in Tampa Bay last
Friday that launched this treadmill of a road trip.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, they all run together. The two defeats in
Chicago. The 12-8 stumble in Detroit. The two losses to Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers are 31-31 since the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly a mad dash to the pennant, is it?
</P>
<P>
   The manager says we are too pessimistic. He doesn't say it in a
mean or contentious way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt back in '96 that people back home just assumed we
weren't going to do it,'' manager Johnny Oates said before Monday
night's defeat. ``I thought we were over that, after we won that
year, but I feel like it's there again.''
</P>
<P>
   It's just an observation, he says. Oates doesn't understand why
Rangers fans must eternally think the worst.
</P>
<P>
   The explanation would take 26 years, the franchise's lifespan on
the turnpike. But in the meantime, let's simply take Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   You had your starting pitcher Aaron Sele come into run-friendly
Camden Yards and shut out the home team for nearly seven full
innings. Yet the effort was wasted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating,'' Alicea said. ``(Juan) Guzman is the type
of guy you have to get before the fifth inning. You've got to get
him early.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had him on the ropes early, and we couldn't take advantage.
To lose a game 1-0 with the kind of offense we have is tough to
swallow _ especially in the position that we're in.''
</P>
<P>
   The position is second position. Second place. Second gear. The
Rangers are in dire need of some roadside assistance.
</P>
<P>
   But on the pennant-race road, things happen. Your veteran first
baseman breaks a big toe. So the fill-in first baseman hacks at the
first pitch he sees in the sixth and leaves a runner stranded on
third base. Then, in the field, every critical ground ball seems to
come his rusty way.
</P>
<P>
   Should Stevens have stepped on the first base bag and tried to
double off the Orioles' pinch runner in the telltale eighth? Not
even shortstop Royce Clayton, who took the shaky throw, was sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a pretty tough double play to turn,'' Clayton said.
``But if the throw is on the bag, yeah, we've got a decent shot.''
</P>
<P>
   The irony is that, for the past two weeks at least, the Rangers
have been playing dependable defense. Plus, for 12 of their
previous 15 games, their starting pitchers have taken them into the
sixth inning with a chance to win.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, alas, are 8-7 in those games.
</P>
<P>
   They are also 3-for-31 with men in scoring position over the
past four games _ even though they lead the American League in that
category for the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd like somebody to step up,'' Oates said after the 1-0
defeat. ``But then, you'd have liked to have pitched better in
Florida on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just pick your story.''
</P>
<P>
   On the out-of-town scoreboard, bad news from Tampa Bay stared
the Rangers in their faces.
</P>
<P>
   On a night when any clutch hit would do, the Rangers themselves
remained missing. They fell to 1-3 on this treadmill of a road
trip.
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly a mad dash to a pennant, is it?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-98 0215EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
