A5342 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FISHER-COLUMN-TEX     09-15 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FISHER-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRONCOS' DAVIS CONTINUES PROVING TALENT SCOUTS WRONG
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE FISHER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He was an afterthought in the 1995 NFL draft, a guy none of the
talent evaluators thought belonged in the same class with Napoleon
Kaufman and Sherman Williams and Curtis Martin and Travis Jervey.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it had to do with how rarely he was used at Georgia. Or
maybe it had to do with how he came to big-time college football,
as a San Diego native who landed at Long Beach State, a college
that had given up on football and was destined to do so again.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe the NFL was scared of a running back who came from a
background of poverty, crime, drugs and prison.
</P>
<P>
   One brother, Bobby, did prison time after his attempted robbery
resulted in him shooting a pregnant woman, killing the fetus. His
late father, Joe, did four prison stints on robbery and weapons
charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it came to living with Pops, my brothers and I saw guns
so often it became as routine as seeing the ice cream truck,''
asserts the running back, who recalls a story of his father's idea
of discipline. ``He pulled each of his four boys out of bed, lined
us up against the wall, pulled out his .38 special with black
electrical tape around the grip and just started shooting right in
our direction. He wasn't shooting at our heads but right above
them. Putting holes in the damn bedroom wall. Not one of us jumped
or moved or ran under the bed to hide and start crying. We knew
Pops wasn't going to kill us, not his four youngest boys. He wasn't
trying to. He was shooting at us, which was crazy, but we knew Pops
was a good shot _ an excellent shot. All he was doing was
toughening up his boys, making it so that nothing would ever scare
us.''
</P>
<P>
   The running back's well-chronicled problems with migraine
headaches are probably a result of his childhood, experts say. And
maybe predictably, his childhood contributed to the running back
spending time in jail, too, for grand theft.
</P>
<P>
   All that is reason enough for NFL teams to have been scared off,
to lean toward guys like Kaufman (first round, Oakland), Williams
(second round, Cowboys), Martin (third round, Patriots) and Jervey
(fifth round, Packers). NFL teams were and are frightened of the
notorious, worried about behavioral problems, petrified not only at
the thought of getting 4 a.m. phone calls from the police, but of
having to explain the details of the phone calls to the public the
next day.
</P>
<P>
   So maybe the Denver Broncos weren't more brave than the rest.
Maybe they were just lucky, lucky that Kaufman and Williams and
Martin and Jervey were gone, lucky that circumstances allowed them
to take a sixth-round flyer on a guy who would rush for more than
1,000 in each of his first three NFL seasons, who would win Super
Bowl MVP, who would be recognized as one of the top two runners in
the sport, a guy who would deserve to be rewarded with a nine-year,
$56.1 million contract, a guy who now works tirelessly with young
people to prevent them from following his early-life example.
</P>
<P>
   Brave? Lucky? Smart? You decide. The Broncos don't care. They've
got Terrell Davis. ALMOST PERFECT
</P>
<P>
   The Chiefs must now aspire to go 15-1 after Derrick Thomas and
others foolishly talked of going undefeated in the days leading up
to Sunday's loss to Jacksonville. TRIVIAL PURSUIT
</P>
<P>
   In 1927, when Babe Ruth hit 60 home runs, the New York Giants
finished first in the NFL. The Green Bay Packers finished second.
</P>
<P>
   In 1961, when Roger Maris hit 61 home runs, the Packers beat the
Giants for the NFL title.
</P>
<P>
   There. Two historical reasons to believe the NFC Championship
Game will feature the Giants against the Packers. QUOTABLE
</P>
<P>
   At 2-0, maybe the Saints have something to be cocksure about.
Let's go to linebacker Brian Jones, an aspiring actor and model,
inspired by the short-lived Magic Johnson TV show. ``After watching
Magic's show,'' Jones says, ``any doubts I might have had about my
abilities are gone.'' CHECK OUT ...
</P>
<P>
   The rumor from San Francisco that says Bill Walsh's decision not
to re-join the 49ers organization was not Walsh's decision at all,
but instead was the result of owner Eddie DeBartolo failing to
return Walsh phone calls. Look for Walsh to now turn his attention
to involvement with an eventual Southern California expansion
franchise. THE BUZZ
</P>
<P>
   You take your good Bears news where you can get it: They're 0-2,
but they've lost two close games to Super Bowl aspirants
Jacksonville and Pittsburgh, and all of Chicago's draft picks made
the team, and four start. ... San Diego has replaced special-teams
coach Frank Novak (an assistant to head coach Kevin Gilbride) with
Wayne Sevier (a longtime crony of GM Bobby Beathard), and you
thought Jerry Jones was the only GM who picked assistants. ... NFC
East followers can't make fun of the NFC West for now. The division
includes the 49ers and, in the Saints and Falcons, two 2-0 teams.
... The difference between the monthlong injury losses of QBs Troy
Aikman in Dallas and Brad Johnson in Minnesota? Dallas' No. 2,
Jason Garrett, is an extremely valuable member of the club from
Mondays to Saturdays. But on Sundays, Randall Cunningham is the
best backup in the NFL.
</P>
</TEXT>
