<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-ORIOLES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS BOTCH CHANCE, LOSE TO ORIOLES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Perhaps Texas Rangers first baseman Lee Stevens made
the correct decision.
</P>
<P>
   Those who witnessed Monday night's events from Oriole Park at
Camden Yards never will know the answer.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens, though, acknowledged that his poor throw on an
eighth-inning, double-play ground ball led to the game's only run
and the Rangers' third loss in four games.
</P>
<P>
   Outfielder Eric Davis, whom Orioles manager Ray Miller utilized
as an eighth-inning pinch hitter, parlayed that extra out into what
proved to be the game-winning, sacrifice fly ball that scored left
fielder B.J. Surhoff.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the Rangers frittered a gutsy performance from
right-hander Aaron Sele _ who pitched 62/3 scoreless innings _ and
fell two games behind the American League West-leading Angels.
Anaheim defeated the expansion Tampa Bay Devil Rays, 4-2, Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a lousy throw,'' a disgusted Stevens said.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Xavier Hernandez (6-6) induced a ground ball from
Surhoff with Eugene Kingsale at first base. Kingsale, who possesses
good speed, replaced third baseman Cal Ripken Jr. as a pinch runner
after Ripken's leadoff single.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens fielded the well-hit ball perhaps as close as a step
from first base, but he chose to try for a 3-6-3 double play
instead of retiring Surhoff at first before attempting his throw to
shortstop Royce Clayton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to get the fastest runner off the bases,''
Stevens said. ``It's a double play if I make a good throw.''
</P>
<P>
   The throw, though, pulled Clayton toward right field. Clayton
managed to keep his right foot on the bag to retire Kingsale, but
the throw forced him face-first into the infield dirt without the
possibility of a return throw.
</P>
<P>
   Did Stevens, who is playing in place of the injured Will Clark,
make the correct decision to throw to second base before retiring
Surhoff at first?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' Rangers manager Johnny Oates said. ``He may
not have a chance at the runner at second if he touches the bag.''
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Lenny Webster then delivered a one-out single to center
field, and Surhoff _ running with the pitch _ advanced to third.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm rusty,'' said Stevens, despite accumulating 27 innings at
the position in the past eight days. ``I'm just rusty. I haven't
been over there.''
</P>
<P>
   Sele, who surrendered six hits, kept the Orioles scoreless
despite six walks. The Orioles do not present a favorable matchup
for Sele, and the right-hander issued one intentional walk, then
two unintentional-intentional walks to left-handed hitters Brady
Anderson and Harold Bailes in the seventh inning.
</P>
<P>
   Oates summoned left-hander Greg Cadaret to retire first baseman
Rafael Palmeiro for the final out of the seventh inning with the
bases loaded, and the game remained scoreless. Orioles right-hander
Juan Guzman matched Sele, as the Rangers went 0-for-7 with runners
in scoring position. No at-bat, though, stung as much as the one
during the sixth inning by Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   Right fielder Juan Gonzalez led off the inning with a double and
advanced 90 feet on a ground ball by catcher Ivan Rodriguez. The
Orioles played their infield in, and Gonzalez could not score on
Stevens' one-out ground ball to second baseman Roberto Alomar.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers went 0-for-12 during their final 12 plate
appearances with the final six coming against right-handers Alan
Mills and Armando Benitez, who retired the side on strikes during
the ninth inning for his 21st save.
</P>
<P>
   Sele's appearance represented the rotation's 12th quality start
in the past 15 games, yet the Rangers won only eight of those
contests.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said we'll win if we pitch well,'' Oates said. ``Is that
the kiss of death?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
