A5363 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r n &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOVRACE-CLINTON-SFCHR     09-15 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOVRACE-CLINTON-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SCANDAL A HOT TOPIC IN CALIFORNIA GOVERNOR RACE  
 BY CARLA MARINUCCI 
</HEADLINE>
   and LOUIS FREEDBERG  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ President Clinton's personal sex scandal quickly
became the hottest topic in the California governor's race Monday
as both sides wrestled to take control of the issue and turn it to
their advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic gubernatorial nominee Gray Davis told an enthusiastic
San Francisco gathering of 500 women that the president deserves
punishment for personal conduct he called ``embarrassing and
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   But he argued that his GOP challenger, state Attorney General
Dan Lungren, was heading down ``a tricky path'' by trying to give
it center stage, because Californians are still grateful for
Clinton's public agenda on health care, the environment and
education.
</P>
<P>
   Lungren _ who started running ``character counts'' ads earlier
this month _ took time out from a Washington fund-raising tour to
slam Davis for not speaking out sooner about Clinton's relationship
with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are few people who have stood as strongly beside the
president as he has,'' Lungren said of Davis. ``It's not leadership
to wait until the parade has passed by and then run to try and
catch up.''
</P>
<P>
   With seven weeks to go before the Nov. election, the frenzied
back-and-forth on the character issue underscored how quickly
Clinton's current troubles have taken center stage in California _
3,000 miles from the Lewinsky hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   But a new poll released yesterday by the Public Policy Institute
of California showed that state voters are more interested in
policy than in either of the candidate's character or experience.
That poll, a survey of 1,616 registered voters conducted statewide
during the first week of September, also found Davis leading
Lungren by 9 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Voters seem to be saying, `Don't brag about your sterling
character, just tell me what you plan to do,' '' pollster Mark
Baldassare said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, who only last month raised a record $3.6 million with
Clinton at his side, said he would welcome the president again. He
argued Monday that Republicans like Lungren will be on slippery
ground if they attempt to run against Clinton's character issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's private and there's public character,'' he said.
``(Lungren) voted against school lunches, . . . against the clean
water act, the safe drinking water act. People want to know how you
behave in your public conduct. That's what they hire us to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis chose Monday to release a sobering ad reminding California
voters _ who remain strongly in favor of abortion rights _ that ``I
am pro-choice. My opponent is not.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If (Lungren) wants to make this about character, we'll make it
about character,'' said Davis' campaign manager Garry South. ``What
kind of character does it imply that a male politician _ who can't
get pregnant last time I checked _ voted time after time after time
to deny even innocent victims of rape and incest the right to an
abortion.''
</P>
<P>
   Lungren's campaign manager Dave Puglia fired back with a
blistering statement charging that Davis is misrepresenting the GOP
candidate's position ``as the Clinton scandal threatens to
overwhelm (his) candidacy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If Davis wants to discuss this issue, he is going to have to
explain to the people of California why he thinks that a teenage
girl who must get her parent's permission to use a tanning salon
should be able to get an abortion without them ever knowing about
it,'' Puglia said.
</P>
<P>
   In a measure of how aggressive the GOP may continue to be on the
character issue, Davis competed for press attention at his San
Francisco appearance with GOP strategist Dan Schnur, who took
reporters aside to argue that ``character has emerged as the single
greatest issue'' in voters' minds.
</P>
<P>
   Schnur, in a strategy sure to be repeated throughout the
campaign, said Davis' recent fund-raising appearances with the
president raise clear questions about ``Gray Davis and the company
he keeps.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Character is not just about summer interns,'' said Schnur,
asked how Davis' character relates to the California campaign.
``Character is about being able to stand up to the trial lawyers
and labor unions.''
</P>
<P>
   But many of the Democratic loyalists in the crowd said that the
use of Bill Clinton as a campaign issue was ``a stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Clinton's private character is not a Democratic Party
issue,'' said an angry San Francisco Supervisor Leslie Katz. ``We
don't hold the whole GOP responsible for (House Speaker) Newt
Gingrich serving his cancer-stricken wife with divorce papers on
her death bed.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jane Harman, the Democratic representative who opposed
Davis in the June primary, said that raising the character issue is
``legitimate for anyone'' in a political race. But Lungren's
attempts will not have traction, she said, because ``both people
running in this race have character.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Clinton's personal problems have nothing to do with Gray
Davis.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis, who raised $100,000 in his hourlong stop in San
Francisco, praised Clinton's performance on such issues as
education, the economy and the environment. But, ``his private
conduct is embarrassing, indefensible and should be punished,''
Davis said. ``That punishment will be determined by the House of
Representatives after all the facts are in.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis said that he wrapped up a major fund-raising tour with
Clinton last month, and did not expect to be given more time with
the president before the election. But asked if he would shy away
from appearing with Clinton in the future, he said, ``Listen, if
he's out to help other people, or for the party, and my schedule
permits, I'll be there.''
</P>
<P>
   (Chronicle staff writers Greg Lucas and Robert B. Gunnison and
Chronicle news services contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
