<HEADER>
A5593 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EYMAN-ON-BOOKS16-COX     09-15 0582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EYMAN-ON-BOOKS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'Fifth Avenue' gives fascinating view of the city
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jerry Patterson's ``Fifth Avenue: The Best Address'' (Rizzoli,
$29.95) is for all those who loved ``Time After Time'' or ``The
Alienist.'' Although it's well-written, the glory of the book is
its photographs _ of long-gone mansions and their overstuffed
Edwardian interiors, complete with potted palms; of the art
collections cramming every inch of the galleries, of the Astor
house, of the newly constructed Flatiron building.
</P>
<P>
   And the people; black-clad nannies pushing trams across the
street, two schoolgirls riding bicycles down a Fifth Avenue without
cars; the Washington Square arch outlined and illuminated by white
lights in 1909; the heavy Italianate lobby of the old
Waldorf-Astoria.
</P>
<P>
   A must-have for anyone who is romantic about New York.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK TV A WELCOME ADDITION ON WEEKENDS
</P>
<P>
   This weekend marks the beginning of Book TV, which is what
C-Span 2 is calling itself every weekend. Basically, Brian Lamb is
turning over all of the channel's broadcasting time to serious
discussions of serious books, predominantly nonfiction. There will
be call-in shows, interviews with authors and editors, etc.
</P>
<P>
   There have been discussions about establishing cable channels
devoted to books, some enlisting the names of prestigious writers
like E.L. Doctorow as bona fides, but they've always foundered over
the problem of advertising support.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Lamb deserves our gratitude, as well as our time.
</P>
<P>
   LIGHTS . . . CAMERA . . . ACTION!
</P>
<P>
   Southern Illinois University Press has published the screenplay
of ``The Bad and the Beautiful'' ($16.95), a deeply entertaining
and intelligent movie about Hollywood, with one of Kirk Douglas'
signature SOB performances.
</P>
<P>
   The volume features an introduction by the late John Houseman,
who produced the picture, and a foreword by Matthew Bruccoli.
Besides Charles Schnee's script, the volume also offers the short
story that Schnee based his script on, a rejected ending, and a
short piece about David Raksin's wonderful score for the film.
</P>
<P>
   Now, would somebody please publish the script for ``Sunset
Boulevard,'' the only great movie about Hollywood?
</P>
<P>
   SOMETHING COMPLETELY DIFFERENT . . .
</P>
<P>
   Publisher's Weekly reports that Broadway Books has bought
``Beethoven's Hair,'' a true story about 582 strands of the
musician's hair that were yanked out by the roots shortly after he
died (Ah, the dignity of death . . .). The hunk of hair was passed
down until it was auctioned off at Sotheby's. The buyers were two
Beethoven fanatics who have submitted the hair to extensive DNA
analysis.
</P>
<P>
   THE DECLINE OF WESTERN CIVILIZATION . . .
</P>
<P>
   Bantam is paying Ray Romano $2.3 million for a book from the
star of ``Everybody Loves Raymond.''
</P>
<P>
   STRANGE BUT TRUE . . .
</P>
<P>
   According to Bookselling This Week, 5.8 percent of all adult
hardcovers bought in this country are mystery or detective fiction.
</P>
<P>
   DECLINE OF WESTERN CIVILIZATION, PART 2 . . .
</P>
<P>
   Frederic Forsythe is working on a sequel to ``The Phantom of the
Opera,'' a novel that Andrew Lloyd Webber will adapt for a
continuation of his commercially successful musical.
</P>
<P>
   QUOTE UNQUOTE . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``The artist cannot be concerned with politics, for a regime may
change each year, but a work of art remains.'' _ Ned Rorem
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
