<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 10:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5595 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN16-COX     09-15 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Sundays offer peace; but the rest is up to us
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Sunday mornings are peaceful in our village.
The bells at the Catholic church down the street toll their gentle
reminder; it's six o'clock. The rest is up to us.
</P>
<P>
   Just before daylight, the paper boy thumps a Sunday edition onto
my front porch. The weather's still warm enough for me to take my
first cup of decaf outside to read it. Automatically, I flip to the
comics and my favorite Viking, ``Hagar the Horrible.''
</P>
<P>
   In a little while, the bells over at the Lutheran church begin
chiming hymns - this morning it's ``Onward Christian Soldiers'' and
``Flow Gently Sweet Afton'' - I think. A gaggle of cute kids,
scrubbed and dressed to the nines, walks in the direction of the
music. Time for Sunday School.
</P>
<P>
   The minister across the street heads for his pulpit carrying a
briefcase so commodious I suspect him of packing a lunch.
</P>
<P>
   A few white-haired couples holding hands walk by and wave. Some
are walking off bypass surgery; for others their daily strolls are
preventive maintenance. A few cling to the old habits and head to
the bakery for a bag of donuts or cream sticks.
</P>
<P>
   Squirrels are racing up and down the trees in front of my house
and scampering noisily across the porch roof. Upstairs in an open
window, my cats are giving them what for. That brings to mind the
raccoon who's been trying to lease my house for the winter and I
wonder if Roger from the hardware store has been there yet to
screen the chimney. As cute as the little varmints are, I don't
relish coming home from school one day to meet up with one in my
living room.
</P>
<P>
   There's no wreath on the funeral home door across the street;
that means nobody has died in the night. It's reassuring because a
couple of my friends have parents in precarious health. That's kind
of always on my mind when I glance over there.
</P>
<P>
   A migrant family passes by, probably on their way to mass at St.
Michael's. Maybe one of their kids is in my English class. Good
kids. Tough life.
</P>
<P>
   In somebody's kitchen nearby, pans are rattling and I'm thinking
what a happy sound that is. Does it get much better than lying in
bed, smelling the coffee and bacon, and listening as the silverware
settles onto the table top?
</P>
<P>
   Somebody has left a bag of tomatoes and zucchini from a backyard
garden in the basket beside my front door. It's the last of the
crop. I don't know who to thank - I may never know, but that
doesn't matter. A friend just wanted to share.
</P>
<P>
   Most folks in our village would describe themselves as
Christians - some practicing and some, as they called it in the
church of my youth, backsliding. We don't steal from one another
and for the most part we get along. Like my neighbor and I who
share a flower bed and water each other's plants when one or the
other is out of town. On Tuesdays he always brings my empty garbage
can in from the curb and I appreciate it every time.
</P>
<P>
   There may be a couple of rich folks in town, but we don't know
about it. Most of us are getting by and feel pretty lucky to have a
bank account and own a little property. I don't know anybody who
was sweating the Dow dip.
</P>
<P>
   More than big city folks can imagine, life is still pretty good
in small villages like ours. It's simple and straightforward and we
like it that way. We've chosen our laid-back lifestyle. We don't
like being messed with unless it's crucial.
</P>
<P>
   And the Starr Report that has just flopped out of my morning
paper is, in my opinion, not crucial. It is however, salacious and
long, but not enough of either to warrant the millions of
taxpayers' dollars this political evangelist has blown on getting
down to the nitty gritty of our president's sex-life.
</P>
<P>
   Who cares? The country was still running, and from what I can
tell, running rather well.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American public has the right to know,'' is the
sanctimonious cry of the political talking heads who are enjoying
the hell out of this garbage that is now passing for not only news,
but grounds for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Politics is not my game and I am not a card-carrying member of
any party. I am, however, a voter, a taxpayer, and an American. I
am not a fool. The Starr Report is not for the good of our country.
There's little need to speculate on who wins in this one.
</P>
<P>
   No one.
</P>
<P>
   (Elizabeth Schuett, a writer and teacher in Gibsonburg, Ohio,
writes for
</P>
<P>
   Cox News Service. Her e-mail address is
eschuett(at)nwonline.net.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
