<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Buckeyes expected victories
 &HT;    By Susan Vinella
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ Ohio State's opening game at then-No. 11 West
Virginia was considered by players and coaches alike as the
Buckeyes first true test of their No. 1 worthiness.
</P>
<P>
   But despite a victory there and another last week vs. Toledo,
OSU cornerback Ahmed Plummer isn't all that impressed with the
Buckeyes so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really haven't done anything spectacular as far as beating
a big, big team,'' he said with a shrug. ``(West Virginia) is a
good team but we know we're going to face better teams _ and
Missouri is one.''
</P>
<P>
   Missouri, No. 21 in the Associated Press poll, comes to Columbus
to face an Ohio State team that, at least outwardly, doesn't seem
all that smitten with its opening victories against West Virginia
(34-17) and Toledo (49-0). Don't get them wrong: They're pleased
they won, but hey, that's what they expect.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have more of an attitude this year,'' running back Joe
Montgomery said. ``Last year, we didn't have that go-get-'em
attitude. I think sometimes when we'd get down, everybody was
hanging their heads.''
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver Dee Miller of Springfield agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, we were confident but there were some times when
things weren't going our way and people just let up,'' Miller said.
``This year, we have a lot more to lose. So we're not cocky, we're
just confident. We're ready to just keep defending this No. 1
ranking.''
</P>
<P>
   The Buckeyes say they're determined not to let what happened to
last week's No. 2, Florida State _ 24-7 losers to 25-point underdog
North Carolina State on Saturday _ happen to them. ``We don't worry
about being upset,'' Montgomery said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Buckeyes don't appear to have too many worries
right now. They're healthy, hungry and for the most part, humble.
</P>
<P>
   Some players attribute their confident but cautious attitude to
letdowns they've experienced in the past. Too many times, they say,
this senior class has had a legitimate shot at No. 1 only to see it
washed away in the wake of a loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my fifth year here and maybe two or three years, we
were a game or two away from being national champions,'' Miller
said. ``(The seniors) don't want to feel like that our last year
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Some already may have felt a twinge of pain when they've looked
at the polls and they have seen how other top teams have fallen.
But many say they try not to get too caught up in the rankings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be lying if I said I didn't pay attention to the polls,''
strong safety Damon Moore said. ``But it really doesn't mean
nothing. You don't hear guys talking about it in the weight room or
walking around saying, 'It feels great to be No. 1.'
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a challenge in front of us and we have to go out every
day and try to improve and get better and try to meet that
challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   This week, the challenge is the Tigers, a top 25 team that
employs a dangerous option offense run by quarterback Corby Jones.
The Buckeyes simply say: Bring him on.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
