<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BENGALS-ODONNELL16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    O'Donnell ``fought'' for victory
 &HT;    By Chick Ludwig
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI, Ohio _ Every time they step on the field, the
Bengals learn something new about quarterback Neil O'Donnell.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, he commands attention in the huddle. Sure, he can
throw the deep ball. Yes, he's one tough customer.
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell played a nearly flawless game in the Bengals' 34-28
overtime victory over the Detroit Lions on Sept.13, completing 25
of 36 passes for 303 yards, two touchdowns and no interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   His scoring strikes of 70 and 36 yards to Darnay Scott were
impressive. So was his toughness.
</P>
<P>
   Taking more shots than a prize fighter in a Caesars Palace
boxing ring, O'Donnell hung tough in the pocket and, despite three
sacks, spread the ball to eight receivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's definitely a competitor,'' center Darrick Brilz said. ``A
lot of guys would have probably gone down. But he didn't. He kept
coming back. He fought. I know we can count on him.''
</P>
<P>
   Right tackle Willie Anderson said there were times he drove
Detroit's stunting end, Robert Porcher, to the inside. O'Donnell
read the moves, stayed poised and managed to escape without panic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most quarterbacks would get rattled and throw the ball away,''
Anderson said. ``But he had the patience and the durability to stay
in the pocket.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear coaches and commentators talk about how the great
quarterbacks are the ones who can stand in the fire like that and
take the licks. He showed a lot of courage under fire.''
</P>
<P>
   After negotiating only his fourth 300-yard passing game in the
last three seasons, O'Donnell expressed confidence in head coach
Bruce Coslet's sophisticated offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more I play in this system, the more comfortable I am,''
O'Donnell said. ``I'm starting to get a feel for the receivers. Big
plays are what it's all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Coslet is impressed with that kind of talk from a guy who has
undergone a crash-course in learning the offense since he was
signed July 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a guy that's only been in this offense for two months,
he's still got a long ways to go, but his experience shows,''
Coslet said. ``He is poised. He stood in there tough. He got hit.
He did some good things.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needs to continue that, which I know he will because that's
his style _ the style we signed him for as a free agent. We knew he
was a tough guy and accurate. We just have to keep bringing him up
to speed on how we run our offense ... all the things he'll learn
as he gets more comfortable with what we do.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very aware during the game. He knows exactly what's going
on around him. He gives us a lot of good information on the
sidelines between series.''
</P>
<P>
   Coslet ripped the offensive line for a poor performance against
the Lions, but O'Donnell wouldn't go that far.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the guys in front of me,'' he said. ``They're fighters.
I'll be all right. I'll stand behind them. I have no complaints.
I'm a tough guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
