<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-PANTHERS-NIEDER16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Niedermayer keeps his head while all around inquire
 &HT;    By Brian Biggane
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUNRISE, Fla. _ Everywhere Rob Niedermayer goes nowadays, people
have the same question: How's the head?
</P>
<P>
   When Toronto Maple Leafs Assistant General Manager Mike Smith
finally opted not to make the trade that would have sent Felix
Potvin to Florida for Niedermayer and Rhett Warrener, he cited
concerns over the head injuries Niedermayer incurred last season.
</P>
<P>
   First-year Florida coach Terry Murray had no such worries after
watching Niedermayer score a goal in the Panthers' first
training-camp scrimmage at National Car Rental Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not paying any attention to the problems he had last
year,'' Murray said. ``It's just an injury. It's over with. It's
done.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray phoned Niedermayer at his off-season home near Cranbrook,
British Columbia, in mid-August and got caught up on his recent
history. Niedermayer told him he had been headache-free for almost
two months and team doctors had told him that if he took certain
precautions, chances of a recurrence would be small.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors and trainer Dave Smith have Niedermayer wearing the
safest helmet on the market with a broader, more secure chinstrap
as well as a face shield and mouthpiece.
</P>
<P>
   But Niedermayer knows he'll be a target when opponents choose to
learn for themselves if he's really 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just like being a rookie in this league; I'll be tested a
bit,'' he said. ``That's fine. I got that the first time I got back
from a concussion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have all the confidence in the gear I'm wearing, the head's
feeling fine, so I'm not worried about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Niedermayer's confidence got a boost last week when he underwent
rigorous stress testing with no complications.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really pushed it in some of the tests, like on the
(stationary) bike, going to extremes, and everything is fine,'' he
said. ``So it's very encouraging.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray was encouraged by what he saw Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a good day,'' he said. ``He had some contact, handled
the puck well, came through the mid-zone with good speed and
attacked into the offensive zone to make a play at the net. That's
the kind of play you want from him. It states very clearly that
he's back.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't hurt that Murray had Niedermayer centering a line with
Scott Mellanby and Johan Garpenlov on his wings, the Panthers' No.
1 line from two years ago that, because of injuries, was rarely
seen last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important for him to get his confidence going again,''
Murray said, ``and that's why I put him where I did _ to have some
automatic read off guys he's played with in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Niedermayer missed 49 games last season because of injuries that
included three concussions, a dislocated thumb, arthroscopic knee
surgery and post-concussion syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a big part of our team,'' Mellanby said. ``He's a kind of
player who, even if he's not scoring, if he can be healthy and play
70-75 games, that's 75 nights (opponents) have to contend with a
guy who's 6-foot-3 and 210 pounds, with speed, who can create some
offense and is strong in his own end.''
</P>
<P>
   Noteworthy: Murray said Garpenlov, who also assisted on a
Mellanby goal, was the best forward in the scrimmage, while GM
Bryan Murray said rookie Jaroslav Spacek was the best defenseman. .
. . Sean Burke allowed a soft shot by rookie Dave Duerden through
his legs. . . . Bill Lindsay got into what he said was his first
training camp fight as a Panther, decisioning rookie Curtis Doell.
In a heavyweight bout, John Jakopin took care of youngster Mike
Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
