<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   COMMENTARY: Diarist's death leaves less life on paper
</P>
<P>
   By Mark Lane
</P>
<P>
   c. Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   ``Edward Robb Ellis, diarist,'' the headline read.
</P>
<P>
   By custom, obituary headlines are a name, sometimes an age and
in better ones, a label. No verb, since ``dies'' is always
understood. Its repetition would depress readers and vex headline
writers.
</P>
<P>
   The labels in obituaries tend to be job titles. Seeing
``Diarist'' in such a headline last week was a novelty. It's not a
job, a club or a government appointment. It's a self-imposed
mission.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis, it turns out, kept a diary since 1927. He filed away 22
million words. Like the reporter he was for 35 years, he took each
day as an assignment, made notes, typed his account, then did it
all again the next day. Fifty cartons of days. Seventy-one years of
cartons. He donated them to New York University, according to the
obit.
</P>
<P>
   ``An ordinary man who has done one extraordinary thing,'' was
how he summarized his life in an interview with Salon on-line
magazine last year.
</P>
<P>
   Diarist. Like armorer, cooper or loblolly boy, it's not a label
you expect in a present day obit.
</P>
<P>
   Which is sad. It is easy to pity any future graduate student
stuck with the study of the time we now inhabit. Assuming these
researchers can run our videotape, work our disks and wade through
our data, sound bites and photography, they'll simultaneously know
too much and not enough. Welcome to the club.
</P>
<P>
   But that will be mere data-mining and image surfing. It won't
make up for the lack of diaries and letters. Future grinds will
know everything we saw and heard but little of what we thought and
felt. They won't have any idea of what we thought in private. If
they go by the televised and published evidence, they may not think
we even had a concept of ``private.''
</P>
<P>
   They'll know the oddest of our perversions and the goofiest of
confessions courtesy of shock-autobiographers who write with the
uninhibited self-serving gusto of a Jerry Springer guest. But they
won't know the price of a cup of coffee at a breakfast place where
the waitress calls everyone ``hon.'' They won't suspect there's a
guy who spends his time patrolling middle school corridors yelling
at kids for not tucking-in their shirts. They won't imagine that
despite everything posted on the Web, advertised on television and
featured in newspapers, there are people of this time who, without
being Amish, are perfectly content with dial telephones,
televisions with antennas and computers that run on Intel-386
chips.
</P>
<P>
   Turn-of-the-century specialists of Capt. Kirk's generation won't
hear of the joys of cheering for a losing baseball team on the last
perfect summer night on the last day of the season. Won't know when
birds migrated. Won't know what senators said over drinks. Won't
know what the sermon topic was. And won't glimpse the habitual
daily rhythms that make the rest of politics, economics, faith and
art intelligible.
</P>
<P>
   They won't know these things because nobody keeps diaries any
more and few people mail letters.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail is well and good and can make even the heart of a midlife
newsman go pitty-pat. But they seldom go to a printer and are never
stacked and sealed and tied together with a red ribbon that is sure
to fade.
</P>
<P>
   And diaries describing public events not only are unlikely from
leaders elected because they can bite sound rather than write
words, they would be downright dangerous when special prosecutors
and interest-group lawsuit specialists roam the land. In the
present political atmosphere, leaders don't write their frank
assessments on anything more durable than a Post-It Note.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, I must report that we -- regular folks and leaders
alike -- are going to look goofy and unfathomable to our
descendants, people who already have good reason to hold us in low
esteem.
</P>
<P>
   All that stands between us and them are a few low-tech holdouts
like Edward Robb Ellis, diarist. In 200 years, if people are still
writing the kind of narrative history that makes any sense, he
could be better known than Springer, O.J. Simpson or Madonna. Or
one may hope.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Lane is an associate editor for The Daytona Beach (Fla.)
News-Journal. He may be reached at marklane(at)n-jcenter.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
