<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Peyton Jr.' to lead Horns against the No. 5 Wildcats
 &HT;    By Mark Wangrin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ He's freckle-faced, red-headed, nicknamed
``Opie'' and not especially thick of limb or quick of foot, an
unlikely college quarterback who on his recruiting visit to Texas
was accused by a future teammate of being a frat-boy hanger-on
looking to see what prospects were in town.
</P>
<P>
   He's a former offensive lineman who loved the Alabama Crimson
Tide with a passion; who as kid made time every afternoon to not so
much watch football tapes as devour them; who went to 25 football
camps in nine summers; whose personal trainer called him Peyton Jr.
because his mental skills reminded him of another of the man's
clients.
</P>
<P>
   He's a self-made Division I starter who had his father run
routes for him when no receivers were available; who turned himself
into a major-college quarterback to the music of a jump rope
hitting his garage floor in sets of 500 _ after coming home at
midnight from a date.
</P>
<P>
   This week Major Applewhite is also something else _ designated
sacrificial lamb. The fill-in starting quarterback will lead the
Texas Longhorns on the road against the team that's the best in the
country in scoring offense and scoring defense, fifth-ranked Kansas
State.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell him his old coach says to spread out so they don't get
you in one volley,'' laughed Boots Garland, the speed specialist
who worked with Applewhite and Peyton Manning at the Manning
Passing Academy over the past few summers.
</P>
<P>
   With starter and Big 12 passing-efficiency leader Richard Walton
out four to six weeks with a broken hand, Applewhite will be called
upon to hand the ball to Ricky Williams, the Horns' Heisman Trophy
candidate halfback. He'll also face an imposing pass defense that
allowed only a 41.1 completion percentage and four touchdown passes
all last season.
</P>
<P>
   If there are tougher spots in which to make a debut, the list is
short.
</P>
<P>
   ``Except for the national championship game,'' flanker Kwame
Cavil said, ``This is really one of the best opportunities. If he
succeeds, he's a hero. If he fails, well, everybody expected
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not everybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect to go in and play well. I expect to move the
offense,'' Applewhite said. ``I'm not going in with a carefree
attitude, like nobody is expecting me to do well so I have nothing
to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   High hopes for a guy who played center, guard, tackle and tight
end in grade school before getting his chance at quarterback when _
how's this for irony _ the eighth-grade starter broke his hand.
</P>
<P>
   Since then he's built himself into a quarterback, more with
brains than brawn. ``When people talk of talent, they usually mean
physical talent,'' Garland said. ``Major has as much mental talent
as anyone I've worked with, and that includes (former Tennessee and
current Indianapolis Colts quarterback) Peyton Manning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids will say their goal is to play at LSU, or wherever, but I
tell them your goal is to find out what it takes to do that.
Major's as good a practitioner of that as anybody I've seen.''
</P>
<P>
   That knowledge, that confidence, has created a leadership aura
his teammates respect, once they get past his Howdy-Doody
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw him I asked, `What position does this kid play?' ''
recalled linebacker Dusty Renfro. ``Then I saw him play and I was
really impressed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a Michael Bishop type,'' Applewhite said, referring to
his mercurial counterpart this week. ``I won't run around and make
the big play and I'm also not the type who can kill with the pass.
My attribute is keeping a level head, avoiding big mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He won't win any decathlons, but he can play quarterback,''
said his high school coach, Dale Weiner, who watched him throw 47
touchdown passes with only four interceptions in his two seasons as
a starter.
</P>
<P>
   Applewhite was a life-long Crimson Tide fan _ he's got photos of
himself with former Alabama quarterback Jay Barker, Sugar Bowl MVP
Derrick Lassic and ends Eric Curry and John Copeland, all from
Alabama's 1992 national title team. But Alabama, which had just
parted ways with Coach Gene Stallings, told Applewhite they weren't
recruiting any quarterbacks, and Applewhite turned to Texas A&AMP;M
because he felt offensive coordinator Steve Ensminger had a plan
for him. A&AMP;M had a different plan for Ensminger. The school fired
him a week later.
</P>
<P>
   Applewhite visited Texas the weekend the Horns hosted Notre Dame
in '96, and the school won his heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him he was meant to be a Longhorn,'' his father, Larry,
said, ``because God gave him burnt-orange hair.''
</P>
<P>
   After redshirting last season, Applewhite became the backup
(over Greg Cicero, who injured his knee) and then the starter when
his competition was injured. During the UCLA game, he was fairly
oblivious to his turn in fortune until reserve quarterback and
clipboard operator Ryan O'Neill came over and told him Walton had
hurt his hand. Applewhite picked up a ball, got in a quick warmup
with Adam Dunn, then lipped a prayer as he ran out on the field:
``Whatever is your will, Lord, let it happen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure they said, `Oh yeah!, more meat!' '' flanker Kwame
Cavil said of the Bruins. ``I wasn't sure how he'd react . . . but
I was proud of him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt confident with my game experience, but there was still
some doubt,'' Applewhite said. ``I hadn't been in a big situation
with heat. When I went into the game, I looked over and, `Yeah,
they still had the first-team guys in.' After the first play, it
was, `Yeah, they're still coming after us.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Applewhite stood firm, completing 3 of 5 passes for 35 yards and
leading the Horns on two scoring drives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've really been impressed with his composure,'' Coach Mack
Brown said. ``He played well against New Mexico State, but there
were a lot of friendly people around and we had a big lead, so it
was, `OK. . . .'
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, against UCLA, it's in the Rose Bowl, we're trying to
come from behind and he didn't even have a chance to get loose. We
just had time to say, `Major. . .' It probably helped that the
first play he handed off to Ricky (Williams) for 17 yards.''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt he'll do the same Saturday in Manhattan, after reciting
Ephesians 6:11, which talks of putting on the ``armor of God,'' and
Philippians 4:13, and after listening to a Champions for Christ CD.
Then he'll walk on the field, warm up and prepare for the Wildcats
blitz _ ``That's what I'd do if I knew a redshirt freshman was
playing quarterback'' _ and whatever else awaits the unlikely
quarterback in the ungodly situation.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
