<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Seagrass next on threatened species list
 &HT;    By Jim Reeder
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT PIERCE, Fla. _ A rare seagrass found in the Port of Fort
Pierce has been added to the threatened species list, a move that's
likely to require extra care in dredging operations.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's seagrass has been found in the Indian River near the
mouths of Taylor Creek and Moore's Creek, two tributaries that the
county may dredge to remove polluted sediments.
</P>
<P>
   It's been found only between the Sebastian Inlet, north of Vero
Beach, and Biscayne Bay near Miami, according to the National
Marine Fisheries Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's rare and exhibits one of the most limited geographic
distributions of any seagrass,'' NMFS spokesman Chris Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   It provides food for manatees and green sea turtles and seagrass
beds provide habitat for juvenile fish.
</P>
<P>
   While the federal agency said it expects the listing to have
little effect on dredging and other marine-activities, Reps. Mark
Foley and E. Clay Shaw urged the NMFS to delay adding the seagrass
to the threatened species list.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will have a severe impact on routine maintenance dredging
projects in the Intracoastal Waterway, the three major ports in
South Florida as well as the rights of private property owners,''
Shaw said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the grass is not threatened with extinction and ``some
research actually appears to thrive in areas where dredging
occurs.''
</P>
<P>
   St. Lucie County's most recent study of the Taylor Creek area
found Johnson's seagrass on the outer fringe of a seagrass bed at
the northeast corner of Harbour Pointe.
</P>
<P>
   The county is considering dredging Taylor Creek to deepen it by
removing sediment scientist said is contaminated.
</P>
<P>
   Consultants have told the county they'll have to be sure not to
dredge the seagrass and to insure it isn't affected by silt stirred
up during the dredging, Acting Port Director Jack Karibo said.
</P>
<P>
   Morris Adger, the county's former port director, came under fire
from commissioners in 1996 because he lobbied to keep Johnson's
seagrass off the threatened species list.
</P>
<P>
   Adger said he was supporting the position of the Florida Ports
Council.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
