<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 10:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5604 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRUMP-RESORT16-COX     09-15 0443
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRUMP-RESORT16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Tim O'Meilia
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ What's an ocean-to-lake club without so much
as a lounge chair on the beach?
</P>
<P>
   It's Donald Trump's Mar-a-Lago Club.
</P>
<P>
   Hardly seems worth the $75,000 membership fee if members have to
tote their own beach chairs and snacks through the tunnel beneath
State Road A1A from the former Majorie Merriweather Post mansion to
the beach.
</P>
<P>
   Trump wants to change that. He has plans to build a 100-foot
long seaside pool, 14 cabanas with showers, a snack bar, bathrooms
and two decorative fountains on the club's 360 feet of beachfront.
</P>
<P>
   These cabanas are no canvas lean-tos. They will be
air-conditioned, have seating, French doors and patios.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the Mar-a-Lago Club,'' said project manager Wes
Blackman. ``We really think this is a beautiful amenity for the
members. It's something they've asked for.''
</P>
<P>
   Trump needs approval from the state, because the pool and
cabanas are east of the state's coastal construction line, and from
the town council.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been expecting it,'' said Town Councilman Leslie Shaw.
The club has submitted plans to the state. With state permits, the
club will apply to the town, probably next year.
</P>
<P>
   To gain approval for the club from the town in 1993, Trump
deeded ``preservation easements'' to the National Trust for
Historic Preservation, guaranteeing the view from the main house to
the lake and to the ocean would not be obstructed.
</P>
<P>
   Trump got that approval this spring. ``Our interest was ensuring
the structures be kept north and south of the central vista,'' said
Paul Edmondson, an attorney for the Washington, D.C.-based National
Trust.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen of the cabanas would be clustered in two stories at the
north end of the property and the remaining one above the snack bar
and bathrooms at the south end of the split-level beach.
</P>
<P>
   That will leave a 192-foot wide view in the center for the pool
and a ramp leading from the existing four-foot seawall down to the
lower level of the beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``A swimming pool and cabanas seem to go with a beach,'' said
Councilman Sam McLendon, ``I'm more concerned about how it fits
with the neighbors. I don't think it's a problem unless it's a
major obstruction.''
</P>
<P>
   The club's cabanas would be shoulder-to-shoulder with the
cabanas of its next-door neighbors, the Bath and Tennis Club,
another private club.
</P>
<P>
   Trump's club has yet to reach its 500-member limit and Blackman
does not anticipate an increase in traffic, a concern of the
council in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
