<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 10:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5607 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLAFIRES-GEL-COX     09-15 1289
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLAFIRES-GEL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wonder gel is barricade against fires
 &HT;    By Paul Reid
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JUPITER, Fla. _ Firefighter John Bartlett had better lengthen
the dock behind his Jupiter house. A ship's coming in. His.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago Bartlett had an idea about how to protect homes,
utility poles, timber, you name it, from advancing fires. He turned
the idea into a product _ Barricade fire gel.
</P>
<P>
   The world took notice _ ABC News, firefighting journals, fire
chiefs, Good Morning America.
</P>
<P>
   And customers. Lots of customers.
</P>
<P>
   Sales went from zero to $250,000 in two years. All packaging,
shipping and order-taking is done from the garage next to his
father's house in south Martin County. They're running out of
space.
</P>
<P>
   Bartlett's idea _ which was of the Eureka sort _ flashed into
being in 1993 as he sifted through the charred remains of a trash
fire in Jupiter. Distinct among the melted bottles and crisp embers
were unburned baby diapers _ smoldering but still white.
</P>
<P>
   Bartlett, 44, wondered why the diapers didn't burn. He chatted
it up with a family friend, a chemist.
</P>
<P>
   The answer was polymers, the Velcro-like molecules of the
chemical world. Things stick to polymers. Polymers absorb moisture,
which is why they're used in diapers. They're used in acrylic
paints, medicines, anyplace where you want thickening or a bond
that holds up under assault by other chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took the diaper principle to its logical conclusion,'' says
Bartlett. ``Enough polymers absorbing enough water applied to a
house will make the house very, very fire resistant _ for a
while.''
</P>
<P>
   Long enough to keep 20 homes treated with Barricade in Flagler
County from burning down during July's wildfires.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994 and '95 Bartlett, his father, who had worked 44 years in
fire departments, and the chemist got down to work to perfect the
idea. They tried granular polymers but soon found that a liquid
base was the way to go. They adjusted the ratios of the six
molecules that make up a polymer. The result is a non-toxic white
gunk that Bartlett is happy to apply to his hand to demonstrate its
effectiveness. With a 3500-degree blowtorch.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Bartlett and his wife, Bailey, his dad, Bill, and partner
Bruce Hill work seven-day weeks to keep up with orders, requests
for demonstrations and bookkeeping.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not anywhere near rolling wheelbarrows of money to the
bank,'' says Bailey. ``We're hanging on. But we're gonna make it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bartlett, who has served with Palm Beach County Fire and Rescue
for 16 years, is plowing through accrued vacation time in order to
get the new company off the ground. He and Bailey once enjoyed wind
surfing on weekends. Now, says Bailey, they've been on the water
maybe twice in two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our time is consumed by the business,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Barricade, meanwhile, assures that houses are not consumed. It
will protect a structure for up to 30 hours, depending on weather
and humidity, says Bartlett. That gives homeowners or firefighters
time to spray on the protection and retreat to safety. About 4
gallons of the stuff mixed with water from either a pumper truck or
garden hose will cover a two-story home. Cost: around $150.
</P>
<P>
   Hal Ellis, 80, is one of the country's leading researchers in
fire barriers. The Palm Beach Gardens resident has spent a lifetime
developing chemical products that protect wood and textiles, and
slow or suffocate advancing fire. Barricade is a giant evolutionary
step for firefighters, he says. Applications will include movie
sets, military uses, protection of utility poles ... anyplace
something can burn.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis is not an investor in Bartlett's company but, at his own
expense, has traveled the South offering his expert opinion of the
gel.
</P>
<P>
   ``A polymer can hold 400 times its weight in water,'' says
Ellis. ``That makes the mixture a strong defensive weapon. It
shields the house or tree line from advancing fire .... It denies a
fire access. It's remarkable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's not as simple as adding water to just any polymer,''
says Ellis. ``I know John Bartlett has tweaked and adjusted his
formula almost 60 times in order to get the right mix. To work, the
gel can't slide off a house, but it can't stick on it forever,
either. It has to be viscous enough to adhere, but not sticky
enough to clog the fireman's equipment. It works, and it will save
more homes and more money than you can count.''
</P>
<P>
   A wildfire can move at 30 miles per hour. It can burn at over
1200 degrees Fahrenheit. It can consume a wood-frame house in
minutes. It can outrun and kill firefighters. The only way to stop
it is to deny it fuel, by cutting dry fire breaks with bulldozers
or applying wet breaks with water. Or a polymer gel like
Bartlett's.
</P>
<P>
   The exact chemical configuration of Bartlett's product is a
secret. He has patents pending that will protect the process of
applying Barricade, and he has an exclusive purchasing arrangement
with the German chemical company that supplies his polymers. He
doesn't have a patent on the polymers themselves. His situation is
somewhat akin to a person who discovers that mixing three common
household products produces a cure for the flu. That person might
not be able to patent the three household products but could patent
the unique use that results from mixing them.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, Barricade has arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Martin County Emergency Services Director, Steve Wolfberg, has
stocked the gel on all 10 of the county's first-line firetrucks.
Los Angeles County is putting Barricade on board its trucks,
especially those that fight the wildfires that arrive each year
with the hot Santa Ana winds.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995 3,000 homes burned in Malibu when fires leaped highways
and canyons. Firefighters there perform triage on houses _ they
pick those they think they can save and let flames take the others.
Barricade will allow them to quickly protect all the homes in an
area and then get down to the business of containing the fire. It's
already being used in Northwest forest fires and California
wildfires.
</P>
<P>
   Indianapolis Airport Fire Chief Bill Cramer bought a new
2,500-gallon pump truck that will do nothing but spread Barricade
gel. Last year his men were asked to help at a junkyard fire where
thousands of old tires, gas tanks and `` a mess of other
materials'' were burning. The Barricade stopped the fire's spread
like nothing he's ever seen, he says.
</P>
<P>
   All this means Bartlett needs a few more days in his work week.
</P>
<P>
   ``When lives are at stake you don't want to put your money on an
untested product,'' says Bartlett. ``I expect the scrutiny. I'll
work the long hours. But I hope the day comes when every truck in
the country carries Barricade, when every homeowner has some in the
garage. We're going to save lives with this. And I'm not blowing
smoke.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he apologizes for the bad pun.
</P>
<P>
   That might sound like a guy who wants his ship to hurry up and
dock. But everyone who knows John Bartlett attests to his love of
the fire service and his belief in public service. Jeff Alter,
Martin County training chief, has known Bartlett for 15 years. He
says Bartlett's goal isn't personal riches but public safety. Hal
Ellis says the same thing. So does the chief up in Indianapolis. So
does Bailey Bartlett.
</P>
<P>
   ``If John could get the stuff for free and give it away, he
would,'' says Alter. ``But he saw something nobody else did, and
went after it. He deserves everything he's going to get.''
</P>
<P>
   What he's already gotten is a pile of thanks-a-million from
homeowners who have houses to go home to thanks to Bartlett.
</P>
<P>
   What he's going to get is a lot more.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
