<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980915.0071 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 10:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5609 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-COSTARICA16-CO     09-15 2663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COSTARICA16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Biking through the mountains of Costa Rica
 &HT;    Photos available
 &HT;    By Dale Fuchs
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALAJUELA, Costa Rica _ How did I get myself into this?
</P>
<P>
   I was the kid who still had training wheels on her bike at the
age of 9. When I was a teenager, my parents didn't let me ride my
purple 3-speed with the flowered basket off the sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   Yet here I am, pedaling a 21-speed ``hybrid'' bike up and down
the mountains of Costa Rica. I'm bouncing along jagged roads and
squeezing the hand brakes at every downhill turn.
</P>
<P>
   My butt is numb despite my $50 padded bike shorts. My thighs
feel like I am punishing them for all those times they refused the
StairMaster.
</P>
<P>
   And all the while, as I push past the emerald-green coffee
fincas (plantations), the waterfalls and the pulperias, candy
stands with their displays of pretty penny candy, I do not feel the
urge to take a single picture. All I want to do is make it to my
hotel alive.
</P>
<P>
   Did I mention that I'm on vacation? I had wanted to do something
different this year: to practice my Spanish, explore exotic places,
get some exercise. A saner person might have chosen Club Med. I
signed up for a weeklong bicycle tour of Costa Rica. ``Butterflies,
bicycles and beaches'' is the name listed on the ExperiencePlus!
brochure.
</P>
<P>
   It sounded like a good idea at the time. . . .
</P>
<P>
   I don't own a bike _ if fact, I've ridden a bike only a few
times since I was a teenager _ but how hard could this be?
According to the computer on my exercycle, I can do 30 miles in a
little more than an hour. In Costa Rica, I'll have all day to do 20
to 40 miles. That should give me plenty of time to wander around
the small villages, maybe have a picnic or search for all the
tropical birds that Costa Rica is famous for. I've never seen a
toucan besides Froot Loop Sam.
</P>
<P>
   The tour packing list calls for a helmet, gloves, three ``padded
Lycra cycling shorts,'' three ``cycling jerseys specific for
bikers'' and an optional rearview mirror, so I've already spent
most of my souvenir money _ almost $200 _ on gear.
</P>
<P>
   I may be a bit clumsy riding a bicycle, but at least I'll look
good. This is going to be a ``singles'' tour, after all. You never
know who you might meet over rice and beans.
</P>
<P>
   Not that I expect to meet the man of my dreams while sweating my
armpits off and wearing shorts that make my derriere look twice its
natural size. But I don't have any friends who are crazy enough to
pay $1,600 for the chance to spend a week switching gears and
guzzling Gatorade. And at least I know I won't be cycling solo in a
kissy-face crowd of bicycles-built-for two.
</P>
<P>
   There's just one thing I'm afraid of: riding with traffic. Four
years ago, I was in a bad car accident that left me with a
more-than-healthy fear of being anywhere near cars.
</P>
<P>
   But I'll have the supervision of four tour guides, plus the
company of more experienced riders. Besides, how much traffic could
there be in the mountains of ecology-friendly Costa Rica? A Central
American country smart enough to abolish its army surely must have
a law against rush hour.
</P>
<P>
   I imagine quiet country roads traversed by slow-moving ox carts
_ the hand-painted kind you see in postcards _ and maybe a few
passing sheep.
</P>
<P>
   Day 1: Meet the jocks
</P>
<P>
   A party of gung-ho bikers has already left on a practice ride to
a zoo and nearby volcano when I arrive at our hotel in Alajuela,
known as ``the city of mangoes'' and ``home of the three-toed
sloth.'' I fit into the second category.
</P>
<P>
   I am assigned a roommate, another sloth named Karyn, a nurse
from Chicago. She's 33 (a couple of years older than I am) and
athletic but surely no superjock. She, too, would rather skip the
ride to the local volcano today _ we'd ride to a much better one
later that week, now wouldn't we? We hit it off right away and
discuss the chances of meeting a cute guy.
</P>
<P>
   After a dinner that included the three main Costa Rican food
groups (rice, beans and fried sweet plantains), I meet the other
bikers and am heartened to learn that, in case of an accident, two
doctors and a lawyer are on this tour.
</P>
<P>
   There are 17 of us, ages 12 to 63. The youngest is chaperoning
his dad, a nurse from Seattle who's in the process of getting a
divorce. The oldest, a Titusville retiree, had triple bypass
surgery 15 months before.
</P>
<P>
   Even the 12-year-old has had more biking experience than I have.
When I admit with a laugh that I don't actually own a bike, eyes
pop. I hear several vulgar variations on ``Holy cow!'' followed by
an awe-filled chorus of ``You're very brave.''
</P>
<P>
   I did not intend to be brave. I'm starting to get nervous.
</P>
<P>
   Day 2: A smashing start
</P>
<P>
   This is nothing like the exercise bike at home. For the first 3
miles, we're pedaling single file, close together _ stop and go,
stop and go _ through Alajuela, where I have yet to spot a mango
tree or a sloth because there are so many people, cars, buses _
stop, go, stop, ouch! _ and traffic lights. The congestion wouldn't
be such a problem if I knew how to get on and off my bike. Which I
don't.
</P>
<P>
   The seat is too high for me to mount with my feet flat on the
ground so I have to jump up a few times to get started, and when I
stop _ whack! _ those padded bike shorts crash right into the seat.
</P>
<P>
   I am certain that I am going to be hit by a car in this clogged
downtown. At home, I drive a Volvo because it is the closest thing
to a tank; yet here I am, with cars darting around me, spewing
exhaust in 95-degree heat, and I have no protection but a gray
metallic helmet (with visor, as per ExperiencePlus!
recommendation).
</P>
<P>
   One of the other riders, a 50-year-old psychologist, takes pity
on me, stops and lowers my seat. Together, we pedal through the
exhaust fumes of Alajuela into the countryside.
</P>
<P>
   Here, the scenery is beautiful: humble yet tidy cottages rimmed
by tropical flowers. Lush mountains. Endless rows of coffee plants
more appealing than a Starbucks double latte.
</P>
<P>
   If you listen closely, you can hear monkeys howling from the
treetops. If you can afford binoculars after buying all those
biking ensembles, you might even see the monkeys, too.
</P>
<P>
   But I don't have much time to admire the view. I'm more
interested in looking for potholes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You find them in the shadows always,'' warns Jose, one of our
young Costa Rican tour guides, in the
slightly-awkward-but-remarkably-clear English that can be heard
often in Costa Rica, which has the highest standard of living in
Central America and where many people, like Jose, have attended
European- or American-run schools.
</P>
<P>
   Jose told me a woman on the last tour flipped off her bike when
she hit a pothole at the bottom of a hill. So I'm using my brakes
constantly and studying the ground on every downward slope. And
there are many _ we're talking curves so sharp you can't see
whether a car is coming until you're halfway through the turn.
</P>
<P>
   I've lost sight of my roommate, Karyn, for about a half hour
when, in a series of downhill turns, the likes of which I've seen
only on skis, she starts picking up speed and passes me.
</P>
<P>
   But I know that some poor soul must be even slower than I am
because I do not enjoy the privilege (or disgrace) of pedaling with
a professional escort.
</P>
<P>
   On this tour, you see, one guide leads the 17-member group and
marks the route with white chalk arrows while another accompanies
the person bringing up the rear. A third guide rides in the middle,
and a fourth drives a van carrying water, Gatorade, snacks and _ in
the event of utter exhaustion _ you and your bicycle _ to the next
hotel along the route.
</P>
<P>
   With neither van nor guide in sight, I suddenly come upon a
traffic jam. In the mountains? This was not a good sign.
</P>
<P>
   I walk my bike along the shoulder until I see the cause of the
commotion. Someone in a turquoise shirt is lying on the road.
There's a bicycle lying beside her.
</P>
<P>
   It's Karyn. Her head and shoulder are bleeding. She has a black
eye. She doesn't know who I am.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where I am? What happened?''
</P>
<P>
   ``You're in Costa Rica, on a bicycle trip. I'm your roommate,
Dale. You just fell off your bike and hit your head.''
</P>
<P>
   Two minutes later: ``Where am I?'' Five minutes later: ``Who are
you? What happened?''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe she saw a car, swerved too fast and veered off the side of
the road. Maybe she hit a pothole. No one knows. A driver, I learn,
found her on her back, struggling for breath, her helmet dented but
still strapped around her chin. He says an ambulance is on its way.
</P>
<P>
   The very last biker is on her way, too. Her name is Cindy, and
she's a doctor. She takes charge, and when the ambulance shows up,
she rides with my roommate to the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   I, meanwhile, feel like throwing up. The scene brings back
memories of my car accident. I accept a ride in the Gatorade van to
the city of Grecia, where I meet the other riders outside a red
church, a simple 19th-century wonder that cuts cleanly into a blue
sky.
</P>
<P>
   We eat mariscos (shellfish), for lunch, adjust bikes, let the
local kids play with our shiny helmets.
</P>
<P>
   And before we pump on to the town of Sarchi, handicraft capital
of the country and our final destination for the day, I sneak back
into the Church of La Mercedes and, although I'm not religious, or
even Christian, I gaze at the life-size Virgin Mary and pray.
</P>
<P>
   Day 3: Birth of a biker
</P>
<P>
   Today is the longest day. We have 40 miles to cover as we cross
the Continental Divide and head into the rain forest. After fueling
up with a traditional ``gallo pinto'' breakfast (scrambled eggs,
rice and beans), I am tempted to ride in the Gatorade van with my
roommate, who has returned from the hospital with a nasty headache,
most of her memory, several oozing sores that bikers call ``road
rash'' and her arm in a sling.
</P>
<P>
   But a woman named Ruth, a neurosurgeon from California, promises
to ride slowly and wait for me if I give it the old college try.
And it is indeed a college try: Ruth and I, it turns out, not only
went to the same college but lived in the same freshman dorm. (So,
it's true: Though the cute guys on the tour are too far ahead of us
to suggest a game of spin-the-water-bottle, you just never know
whom you might meet.)
</P>
<P>
   The first leg of the journey is almost all uphill, along cliffs
that I'm sure would offer breathtaking views if I had the guts to
look over them. While the jocks push ahead of us, we inch along,
sweating and breathing in through the nose 2-3-4 and out through
the mouth 2-3-4 and in 2-3-4 . . .
</P>
<P>
   Did I forget to mention (gasp) that on this week in the usually
pleasant month of February (grunt), there is a heat wave in Costa
Rica? Yes, temperatures top 100 degrees. ``Ah, but it's a dry
heat,'' offers Mario, the tour guide.
</P>
<P>
   Last day
</P>
<P>
   ``What? That's it? I can still go for at least another 20
miles.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm riding with the big boys now _ two veteran bikers, John from
Vancouver and Peter from Colorado, and they are both shocked that I
can keep up with them as we ascend the Cuesta Grande, ``big hill''
in euphemistic Spanish, breeze past melon fields and sleepy
villages and head for Samara Beach on the Pacific Ocean. That's our
last stop, and we are so nonchalant about the whole affair that we
actually carry on a conversation while pedaling. We take stock of
the tour:
</P>
<P>
   Accident count: Nine, including my roommate's. Karyn left the
tour on Day 4 after a valiant attempt to resume riding despite a
separated shoulder. (ExperiencePlus! refunded her money, I
learned.)
</P>
<P>
   Cindy the Doctor, who woke up every hour to check Karyn's pupils
on that first night after her concussion, took four tumbles
herself. During one spill, Cindy broke her finger when her bike
fell into a 4-foot rut in the road. Luckily, my riding buddy, Ruth
the Surgeon, was on hand to set her finger.
</P>
<P>
   I escaped without injury, except for a few blisters, which had
nothing to do with the bicycle and everything to do with wearing a
pair of new tennis shoes without socks.
</P>
<P>
   Cool, touristy activities: Six, including an hourlong hike
through a rain forest; an afternoon raft down the Corobici River
(which included a quick dip in alligator-infested water); a
nighttime swim in volcanic hot springs; a nighttime bus to the
smoldering side of the volcano Arenal (which last erupted in 1968,
killing about 80 people).
</P>
<P>
   Hottest day: 108 degrees
</P>
<P>
   Coolest day: There weren't any.
</P>
<P>
   Most treacherous stretch: Ten unpaved kilometers around Lake
Arenal.
</P>
<P>
   Most beautiful stretch: Ten unpaved kilometers around Lake
Arenal.
</P>
<P>
   Most useless piece of equipment: Rearview mirror. I saved it for
my Volvo.
</P>
<P>
   Howler monkey sightings: Twelve that I could see without
binoculars.
</P>
<P>
   Toucan sightings: None in the wild; two injured critters in a
cage at Hotel Hacienda in La Pacifica, which is a ``model of
sustainable development'' according to the ExperiencePlus brochure.
It has its own ``tropical dry forest,'' with trails along a river.
The hotel also had a great pool but the worst mosquitoes.
</P>
<P>
   Tour romances: None. Hard to believe, but true. Cindy, the
accident-prone doctor, however, came the closest. She was one of
the few people on the tour who could speak Spanish and dance salsa.
Naturally, she met a Costa Rican dancing machine at the disco in
Nicoya. Her Spanish was good enough to get her through the evening
with him, but when he escorted her back to our hotel and wanted to
spend the night, her vocabulary failed her. I know this because she
knocked on my door at 2 a.m., looking for help with the
translation.
</P>
<P>
   Worst language blunder: The honor goes to Cindy. She met a
handsome Costa Rican man at a roadside restaurant. Then she met the
woman he intended to marry. Trying to make light of the situation,
Cindy winked at the lucky bride-to-be and tried to say, in Spanish,
``good catch.'' She used the words buen cogido, which means, to put
it politely, ``good sex.''
</P>
<P>
   An appropriate end to an adventure
</P>
<P>
   If you thought I was panicking on the bicycle, you have never
seen me board a plane. This fear of flying probably started after
my second car accident. I have an anxiety attack nearly every time
my plane hits turbulence.
</P>
<P>
   So you can imagine my delight when I find out that there are
only two ways to travel from the Pacific coast to the international
airport in San Jose: 1) a 30-minute flight on a puddle jumper; or
2) a seven-hour bus ride on those curvy mountain roads I had just
cycled on. I choose the puddle jumper.
</P>
<P>
   I'm puzzled when the taxi driver pulls up to an empty field and
stops. ``Esta aqui, el aerpuerto?'' I inquire. Yes, this is the
airport, the driver assures me. Gulp. And the cute specimen
touching down like a ride in an amusement park is the plane. It has
room for about 10 people, including the pilot and someone who looks
like his teenage son but who is apparently the copilot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you tip your wings at our friends?'' a couple asks, the
plane's only other passengers. Oh no, not that! ``Sure, no
problem!'' says the pilot. ``Please don't tip your wings,'' I beg.
``No te preocupes, don't worry,'' the pilot says with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   And above the turquoise Pacific waters and the white sand and
the little house with a little swimming pool, where a bunch of
expatriate Americans salute us with their afternoon drinks, we tip
our wings once, twice, then fly low, beneath the clouds and over
the mountains. And I'm not afraid.
</P>
<P>
   I had just biked through Costa Rica. After that, nothing else
seems scary.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   _ Bike tour: If you want to ride the rough roads of Costa Rica,
contact ExperiencePlus! Specialty Tours at (800) 685-4565 or
E-mail: tours(at)xplus.com. The tour rate for 1999 is $1,695 and
includes bike, hotels, most meals and guides. . . . The company
also offers a 12-day walking tour in Costa Rica _ $1,895.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
