<HEADER>
A5610 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOMER-CONFLICT16-COX     09-15 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMER-CONFLICT16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Homer king will be perfect guy for it
 &HT;    By Dave George
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chasing history, catching history and now wrestling over it.
Mark McGwire couldn't possibly have known what he was getting into
when he took serious aim at baseball's brawniest record. Even at
the end of the rainbow, 62 home runs in one sparkling pot, he is
joined by Sammy Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   Even after getting a congratulatory call from the president, he
understands that the final word has yet to be spoken on the
subject.
</P>
<P>
   This thing is bigger than Mark and Sammy. It's bigger than you
and me. And, needless to say, it's got Bud Selig totally baffled.
The ball that Sosa hit for his 62nd homer Sunday at Wrigley Field
bore no special authenticating mark. As a matter of fact, I'll be
offering it at my next garage sale, right next to an old tube sock
that might have been worn by Wilt Chamberlain the night he scored
100 points or by me the last time I mowed the lawn.
</P>
<P>
   How simple it was a week ago, when Big Mac was running around
hugging Cardinals and Cubs alike on the occasion of his 62nd and an
entire nation sat basking in the glow of a baseball blessing
broadcast live.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, all that's clear is the conflict within.
</P>
<P>
   I want McGwire to have the eventual record, whatever it may be,
because he performed so valiantly in running down both Ruth and
Maris for the home fans at the end of a Cardinals homestand.
</P>
<P>
   I want Sosa to have it because he didn't begrudge McGwire the
moment.
</P>
<P>
   I want McGwire because St. Louis, the best baseball city in
America, knows how to appreciate the record and all that went into
earning it.
</P>
<P>
   I want Sosa because Chicago deserves a sure-fire celebration
before the Cubs, always a heartache waiting to happen, take another
wild stab at the post-season.
</P>
<P>
   I want McGwire because the tremendous emotional release of
reaching 62 first has cost him the fine mental edge that made it
possible. He'll have to restoke the fire now, even as Sosa benefits
from the daily rush of the Cubs' stretch drive.
</P>
<P>
   I want Sosa because he never surrendered his shot at the record,
even after McGwire's premature coronation.
</P>
<P>
   I want McGwire because he finally appears to be enjoying the
record run more than any of us. That wasn't always the case this
summer, back when Mac had 30 or 35 homers and was getting asked
every night to comment on the eventuality of doubling that.
</P>
<P>
   I want Sosa because he somehow has been able to keep the whole
carnival in context. He's won more big games for the Cubs with
clutch base hits than he has with home runs and cut way down on his
strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   I want McGwire because he has gone out of his way to show
respect for Roger Maris.
</P>
<P>
   I want Sosa because Babe Ruth, ruler of a sports world
restricted to white Americans, could never have believed a
Dominican major leaguer possible.
</P>
<P>
   I want McGwire because the Cardinals train in Jupiter. To have
baseball's new single-season home-run champion signing autographs
along the rail at Roger Dean Stadium next spring would be the most
exciting thing since Hank Aaron, the all-time king, trained with
the Braves in West Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa and the Cubs, they train in Arizona. No crime in that, but
something's got to break the tie. I'll take McGwire, in the end,
knowing that a 6-foot-5 giant with a fiery red goatee will sound
even grander one day to the grandkids.
</P>
<P>
   What I really want, though, is for this baseball season to go on
forever. That's the power of this rivalry and the pleasure of
admiring the players involved.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
