<HEADER>
A5612 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-FALLPREVIEW16-COX     09-15 2385
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FALLPREVIEW16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fall TV '98
 &HT;    By Kevin D. Thompson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   So you're Holding the Bay and watching That '70s Show, wondering
about the 7 Days of fall TV. With 36 new shows, it's a virtual
Fantasy Island of choices. All these new people to meet _ The
Hughleys and DiResta and Maggie Winters and Buddy Faro and Conrad
Bloom, not to mention Costello and Jesse. So many questions: Are
Trinity and Legacy just Two of a Kind? Will you be Charmed by
Felicity or struck by Cupid? And Will &AMP; Grace, are they L.A.
Doctors or on that Army Show? Before you declare Martial Law and
seek Vengeance Unlimited (or even cry out Encore! Encore!). Our
television critic Kevin D. Thompson is here to help.
</P>
<P>
   KINGS OF THE HILL
</P>
<P>
   THREE NEW SHOWS TO WATCH
</P>
<P>
   _ Cupid (ABC, Saturdays, 10 p.m.): A wonderfully enchanting
romantic comedy about a psychiatric patient (Jeremy Piven) who
believes he's Cupid. His story: He was sent back to Earth to
relearn his craft. The twist? He actually might be the Roman god of
love. Smartly written and beautifully acted, with serious chemistry
between Piven and Paula Marshall, who plays a smitten relationship
expert. Could be the next Moonlighting . . . or Relativity.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hyperion Bay (WB, Mondays, 9 p.m.): A thoughtful and
intelligent relationship drama about two odd-couple brothers, one
white-collar, one blue-collar, who battle each other while defining
their roles in life. Forget the much-hyped Felicity. This is the
WB's best drama.
</P>
<P>
   _ Fantasy Island (ABC, Saturdays, 9 p.m.): A stylish and
deliciously sinister remake of the campy '70s series. Not only does
Malcolm McDowell's Mr. Roarke not wear white suits (he likes Armani
gray), you get the sense this guy's in cahoots with the devil, or
something. Helping Mr. Roarke are a trio of loyal assistants,
including the yummy Madchen Amick (Twin Peaks), who can morph into
anything.
</P>
<P>
   JUST SHOOT ME!
</P>
<P>
   THREE NEW SHOWS TO SKIP
</P>
<P>
   _ Brimstone (Fox, Tuesdays, 9 p.m.): Oh, just your average drama
about a New York ex-cop (Peter Horton) who died in the line of duty
and was sent to Hell by the devil for killing his wife's rapist.
But after a mass jailbreak in Hades _ no, we're not kidding! _ our
hero is dispatched back to Earth to round up those ornery demons.
His reward if he succeeds? A first-class ticket to heaven. A
shameless X-Files rip-off that's dark, brooding and boring.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wind on Water (NBC, Saturdays, 8 p.m.): If TV shows were
judged on looks alone, this sappy, Dallas-like soap would get four
stars. There's lush Hawaiian scenery, hard-bodied studs surfing and
Bo Derek in a bathing suit! Jeez . . . even the horses look great.
But this ho-hum, woodenly acted drama about Hawaiian cattle
ranchers is nothing more than glorified eye candy.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sports Night (ABC, Tuesdays, 9:30 p.m.): A show within a show
that gives us a behind-the-scenes look at a crazed ESPN-like sports
show. But is it a comedy? Is it a drama? The producers don't seem
to know. And you probably won't care. The Larry Sanders Show did it
better.
</P>
<P>
   DEJA VIEW
</P>
<P>
   Why do so many new shows look familiar? Well, because they are.
</P>
<P>
   OLD SHOW: The Jeffersons (CBS): Middle-class black family movin'
on up to a de-luxe apartment on Manhattan's mostly white East Side.
</P>
<P>
   NEW SHOW: The Hughleys (ABC): Middle-class black family movin'
to a de-luxe house in an all-white suburb. George and Weasie are
better in repeats.
</P>
<P>
   OLD SHOW: Fantasy Island (ABC): Suave-looking Mr. Roarke
(Ricardo Montalban) and midget helper Tattoo (Herve Villechaize)
make people's fantasies come true.
</P>
<P>
   NEW SHOW: Fantasy Island (ABC): Same premise, but Mr. Roarke
(Malcolm McDowell) is creepy and sinister-looking. No ``de plane,
de plane,'' either.
</P>
<P>
   OLD SHOW: ER (NBC): Fast-paced medical drama that explores the
lives of passionate and talented doctors treating patients with
nasty-looking wounds.
</P>
<P>
   NEW SHOW: Mercy Point (UPN): Fast-paced medical drama that
explores the lives of passionate and talented doctors treating
nasty-looking . . . aliens in outer space. Dr. Ross, meet Dr.
McCoy.
</P>
<P>
   OLD SHOW: Ally McBeal (Fox): Good-looking, highly introspective
woman (Calista Flockhart) struggles with work, life and guys.
</P>
<P>
   NEW SHOW: Felicity (WB): Good-looking, highly introspective teen
(Kerri Russell) struggles with college, life and guys. But without
David E. Kelley writing dialogue for her. And no Dancing Baby!
</P>
<P>
   OLD SHOW: The Equalizer (CBS): Former government agent (Edward
Woodward) operates one-man security force to help people in need.
</P>
<P>
   NEW SHOW: Vengeance Unlimited (ABC): Whacked-out psycho (Michael
Madsen) operates one-man security force to help people in need. The
difference? Woodward could act.
</P>
<P>
   OLD SHOW: Full House (ABC): A single dad (Bob Saget) raises twin
daughters (the Olsen twins) with the help of his brother-in-law and
pal.
</P>
<P>
   NEW SHOW: Two of a Kind (ABC): A single dad (Christopher Sieber)
raises scheming twin daughters (the Olsen twins again!) with the
help of . . . you get the idea. Someone find these kids a mom _
quick!
</P>
<P>
   TOUCHED BY AN ANGLE
</P>
<P>
   THIS YEAR'S TRENDS
</P>
<P>
   _ The Odd Couples return: More buddy shows. NBC's Will &AMP; Grace
about mismatched roommates (he's gay, she's straight!); ABC's
Brother's Keeper; UPN's Guys Like Us.
</P>
<P>
   _ Blacks in the 'burbs: ABC's The Hughleys and Fox's Living In
Captivity both have black folks ``movin' on up.'' If we're lucky,
both shows will soon move on out.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mr. Moms: Who says single men don't raise kids? They do on
Fox's Holding The Baby; UPN's Guys Like Us; ABC's Brother's Keeper
and ABC's Two of a Kind.
</P>
<P>
   _ Irish guys are smilin': NBC's Wind on Water; Fox's Costello;
CBS' To Have And To Hold and NBC's Trinity all revolve around Irish
families and characters.
</P>
<P>
   _ Living large: If you're fat and can act, get to Hollywood . .
. now! TV's big guys include comic John DiResta in UPN's DiResta;
Nathan Lane in NBC's Encore! Encore!; David Anthony Higgins on the
WB's The Army Show; Kevin James on CBS' The King of Queens and
Sammo Hung on CBS' Martial Law.
</P>
<P>
   SAMMO WHAMMO!
</P>
<P>
   THE YEAR'S MOST UNLIKELY STAR
</P>
<P>
   Sammo Hung, the star of CBS' cop drama Martial Law, looks more
like a kindly sumo wrestler than a lethal, martial-arts killing
machine. The 5-foot-7-inch, 220-pound Hung plays Sammo Law, a
karate-chopping, back-flipping, high-kicking Shanghai cop who joins
forces with the L.A.P.D. What's he like? Ever see a human bowling
ball kick butt?
</P>
<P>
   Here are capsule descriptions of the new fall shows by
television critic Kevin D. Thompson. means Kevin recommends it.
</P>
<P>
   SUNDAY:
</P>
<P>
   Holding The Baby (Fox): A workaholic single dad (Jon Patrick
Walker) raises his baby with his skirt-chasing brother (Eddie
McClintock) and a cute nanny (Jennifer Westfeldt) after his wife
skips town. Yet another formulaic and cliche-ridden sitcom where
poor ol' dad is a bumbling dope.
</P>
<P>
   That '70s Show (Fox): A sweet and often hilarious look at a
group of teens growing up in the '70s. Think a more adult version
of The Brady Bunch.
</P>
<P>
   The Army Show (WB): A silly military comedy about a band of
misfits at a forgotten Army compound. The only thing you'll want to
forget is this lame sitcom.
</P>
<P>
   MONDAY:
</P>
<P>
   The King of Queens (CBS): A UPS-like delivery man (Kevin James)
watches his basement paradise invaded when his loud-mouthed
father-in-law (Jerry Stiller) moves in and wreaks havoc. Stiller is
a scream _ literally.
</P>
<P>
   The Brian Benben Show (CBS): Brian Benben stars as a demoted
L.A. anchor who schemes to get back his cushy job from the living
and breathing Ken doll who took it. Benben better get stronger
writers or he'll get bumped in real life, too.
</P>
<P>
   L.A. Doctors (CBS): Four doctors get fed up with red tape HMOs
and open up their own practice where the patients matter more than
the bottom line. CAT scans are more exciting.
</P>
<P>
   Conrad Bloom (NBC): A rising New York ad exec (Mark Feuerstein)
has a lot of women in his life, but none of them is the one special
lady he seeks. Oh, goodie, yet another NBC sitcom set in an office.
</P>
<P>
   Will &AMP; Grace (NBC): Two roommates (gay Will, straight Grace)
enjoy poker, French films and The $10,000 Pyramid. Boasts likable
leads and could be NBC's only new hit.
</P>
<P>
   Guys Like Us (UPN): Two hip roommates (Bumper Robinson, Chris
Hardwick) share their swinging bachelor pad with a 6-year-old kid
(Maestro Harris) who talks like he's 42. Yeah, the kid is cute and
perky. Too cute and perky, though. You wonder if he runs on
batteries.
</P>
<P>
   DiResta (UPN): A New York City transit cop (John DiResta)
juggles career and family. DiResta's a likable lug, but we can't
help but think we've seen all this stuff before.
</P>
<P>
   The Secret Life of Desmond Pfeiffer (UPN): TV's most original _
and silly _ idea. A White House butler (Chi McBride) unwittingly
becomes a confidant for a womanizing President Lincoln (Dann
Florek). Yeah, it's dumb, but it's also pretty funny _ and, uh,
timely.
</P>
<P>
   Hyperion Bay (WB): A gripping and sensitive family drama about a
guy (Mark-Paul Gosselaar) who moves back to this small town to make
sense of his life. One of TV's most promising new dramas.
</P>
<P>
   TUESDAY
</P>
<P>
   The Hughleys (ABC): What happens when a middle class black
family moves to an all-white suburb? Not much in this unfunny and
mostly unrealistic sitcom starring stand-up comic D.L. Hughley.
</P>
<P>
   Sports Night (ABC): A behind-the-scenes look at a
Sportscenter-like show. ABC's promos are funnier.
</P>
<P>
   Encore! Encore! (NBC): Nathan Lane is a former opera singer
forced to give up his career and move back with his family in Napa
Valley. The show's riddled with problems, but we're counting on the
Frasier folks, who created this series, to make it work.
</P>
<P>
   Costello (Fox): A loud, spirited bartender (Sue Costello) hangs
around a bunch of loud, foul-mouthed friends in south Boston.
Tacky, crass and downright vulgar.
</P>
<P>
   Brimstone (Fox): A dead ex-cop (Peter Horton) is sent back to
earth by the devil to round up 113 evil souls who escaped from
Hell. If he gets the job done, the scowling cop gets heavenly
redemption. We think he'll get canned before capturing, say, three
souls.
</P>
<P>
   Mercy Point (UPN): ER meets Star Trek: Voyager. A team of
doctors, led by the reliable Joe Morton, treat humans and numerous
aliens in an out-of-this-world medical facility. Sometimes icky,
sometimes interesting.
</P>
<P>
   Felicity: A naive teen (Keri Russell) takes charge of her life
by moving to New York from California. The most hyped new drama of
the season _ and we still don't know why.
</P>
<P>
   WEDNESDAY
</P>
<P>
   The Secret Lives of Men (ABC): Three guys get together each week
to play golf (oooh, how exciting!) and wax poetic about life. We
call it The Boring Men's Club.
</P>
<P>
   Maggie Winters (CBS): Think Ally McBeal goes back home. Faith
Ford moves in with her mom (Shirley Knight) after her big city job
doesn't work out. Ford is appealing and could grow on you.
</P>
<P>
   To Have And To Hold (CBS): A romantic comedy drama about a
public defender (Annie Cornell) and a Boston detective (Jason
Beghe) who love each other _ and their jobs. We don't love them,
though.
</P>
<P>
   7 Days (UPN): Remember Timecop? It's back, only now it's called
7 Days. Jonathan LaPaglia stars as a cocky ex-CIA agent who goes
back in time for seven days to undo present-day catastrophes. Slick
and action-packed.
</P>
<P>
   Charmed (WB): Three good-looking sisters who just happen to be
witches. With cool special effects, snappy writing, Shannen Doherty
and the sexy Alyssa Milano, Charmed should hook the Buffy crowd.
</P>
<P>
   THURSDAY
</P>
<P>
   Vengeance Unlimited (ABC): The Equalizer gone over the edge. A
mumbling, so-called do-gooder (Michael Madsen) helps people get
revenge on bad guys. As a quietly deranged vigilante, Madsen has
too much fun.
</P>
<P>
   Jesse (NBC): A single mother (Christina Applegate) juggles her
job, dreams and all the guys hitting on her. While Married . . .
With Children's Applegate is likable, Jesse is just another
run-of-the-mill comedy.
</P>
<P>
   FRIDAY
</P>
<P>
   Two of a Kind (ABC): Once again the Olsen twins are being raised
by a harried single dad (Christopher Sieber). Cute and funny, this
show could help revive ABC's once-mighty TGIF lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Brother's Keeper (ABC): Two odd couple brothers (one's a stuffy
English professor, the other's a wild professional football star)
live together while raising an 8-year-old. Another charming ABC
comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Buddy Faro (CBS): Dennis Farina has a grand time as a one-time
brilliant Los Angeles investigator who's having a tough time
working in the '90s. Smart, visually arresting and funny. This
one's a keeper.
</P>
<P>
   Trinity (NBC): A drama about a working-class Irish family from
New York's famed Hell's Kitchen. Although the pilot wasn't
gripping, we'll give it a shot since ER Executive Producer John
Wells is behind it.
</P>
<P>
   Living In Captivity (Fox): Three diverse couples try to do the
Rodney King thing, you know, just get along, while living in the
suburbs. Murphy Brown producer Diane English should be ashamed
she's an executive producer on this witless comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Legacy (UPN): Imagine if Dynasty took place on the rolling blue
grass hills of post-Civil War Kentucky. Then it'd look a lot like
this soap, which follows the triumphs and struggles of a close-knit
family. While not riveting entertainment, it's mildly pleasing, and
with a great-looking cast, very easy on the eyes.
</P>
<P>
   SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   Fantasy Island (ABC): You know the premise . . . people come to
an exotic island to have their fantasies come true. Malcolm
McDowell is deliciously dark and sinister as the mysterious Mr.
Roarke.
</P>
<P>
   Cupid (ABC): A man (Jeremy Piven) claims he's Cupid and that he
must bring together 100 couples to get back to Mount Olympus. Is he
or isn't he the Roman god of love? You'll have fun finding out.
</P>
<P>
   Martial Law (CBS): A butt-kicking, karate-kicking Shanghai cop
(Sammo Hung) joins forces with the L.A.P.D. to do more butt-kicking
and karate-kicking. A delightful, rock 'em-sock 'em treat.
</P>
<P>
   Wind on Water (NBC): A Dynasty-like drama about a bunch of
cattle ranchers, surfers and sky divers who live to the extreme in
Hawaii. Bo Derek heads the mostly no-name cast, most of whom look
like walking Tiger Beat covers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
