 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE WEDNESDAY FEATURES BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These feature stories for release Wednesday, September 16, 1998,
are moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports, business and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. All stories have moved
except those with an ETA.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS (e category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-FALLPREVIEW _ So you're Holding the Bay and watching That
'70s Show, wondering about the 7 Days of fall TV. With 36 new
shows, it's a virtual Fantasy Island of choices. (Thompson, Palm
Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NEWSSTAND _ ATLANTA _ As expected, all three newsmagazines this
week are Starr-struck. (O'Briant, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   EYMAN-ON-BOOKS _ Jerry Patterson's ``Fifth Avenue: The Best
Address'' (Rizzoli, $29.95) is for all those who loved ``Time After
Time'' or ``The Alienist.'' Although it's well-written, the glory
of the book is its photographs. A must-have for anyone who is
romantic about New York. (Eyman, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SOUNDSHOPPING _ With the release today of ``Musical Chairs,''
Hootie &AMP; the Blowfish show off the band's flexibility, with tunes
ranging from country (``Desert Mountain Showdown'') to R&AMP;B
(``What's Going on Here'') and '80s rock (``Wishing''). (DeVault,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED 9/14.
</P>
<P>
   USHER _ ATLANTA _ Feature on Atlanta R&AMP;B star Usher. We look at
his success from the inside out. We go inside his fan
club/management office/home to talk to his mother, see how he lives
during the rare instances he's home, and detail how mom and staff
manages all the fan mail, movie offers and other things that come
to their suburban home. (Murray, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA:
7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   TV-SURFER _ Party of Five and Beverly Hills 90210 start their
new seasons this night. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA: 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE (l category)
</P>
<P>
   SIBLEY-COLUMN _ Alabama Gov. George Wallace wasn't exactly a
stainless knight most of his life. He did some shocking and some
shabby things before, disabled and in pain, he took another hold on
life. But I read of his death with sadness. So much of life in the
South has been contending with demagogues and even as you deplored
their actions and attitudes you valued them for their colorful
ways. (Sibley, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA: 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   SAVANNAH-CORONER _ SAVANNAH, Ga. _ Profile of Dr. Metz, the
Savannah coroner, who will be leaving on Saturday to go to Poland
to open a grave to get DNA material to compare with that from
remains found in Savannah, to see if said remains are those of
Casimir Pulaski, the Revolutionary War hero. Whew, despite all that
he's a pretty interesting character. Metz was mentioned in
``Midnight in the Garden of Good and Evil.'' He lives in a
converted funeral home on a square in Savannah, and he works as
coroner even though he's wealthy enough not to work at all.
(Hendrick, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTOS. ETA: 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   FASHION-DKNY _ Day 2 of the New York Fashion Scene. Designers:
Tahazi (4 p.m.); DKNY ( 5 p.m.); Jil Stuart (6 p.m.); Louis Vutton
(7:30 p.m.). (Walton, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA: 9 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   FASHION-RUNWAY _ Runway report. (Walton, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA: 9 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY-LIST _ Sidebar on other Southern and Eastern hot spots.
(Thrasher, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA: 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY-FESTIVALS _ Southern Happenings. (Thrasher, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA: 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COSTARICA _ ALAJUELA, Costa Rica _ How did I get myself
into this? Here I am, pedaling a 21-speed ``hybrid'' bike up and
down the mountains of Costa Rica. I'm bouncing along jagged roads
and squeezing the hand brakes at every downhill turn. It sounded
like a good idea at the time. . . . (Fuchs, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SPUDS _ Fresh potatoes aren't much to look at, but their taste
will knock you out. (Heller, Dayton Daily News) ETA: 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   SPUDS-RECIPES _ Potato recipes. (Heller, Dayton Daily News) ETA:
8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   SEAGRASS _ FORT PIERCE, Fla. _ A rare seagrass found in the Port
of Fort Pierce, Florida, has been added to the threatened species
list, a move that's likely to require extra care in dredging
operations. (Reeder, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ROOFIES _ Roofies, the Mickey Finn of the '90s, are now easier
to spy after they've been slipped into a drink. Drug manufacturer
Hoffmann-La Roche has reformulated the powerful sedative Rohypnol
so that it turns clear liquids blue and dark liquids cloudy,
thereby alerting unsuspecting people. Roofies is a street name for
Rohypnol, or flunitrazepam, which is legal in Europe and South
America, but not in the United States. (Kim, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA: 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
