<HEADER>
A5627 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMMENTARY-BJT16-COX     09-15 0411
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMMENTARY-BJT16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE WEDNESDAY COMMENTARY BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release Wednesday, September 16, 1998, are
moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ OK, so sometimes a cigar isn't just a cigar, but
even so, if anything can rehabilitate the Clinton presidency, the
Starr report's excesses and flimsy charges may do the trick.
(Teepen, Cox News Service) MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ And, so, we again are about to send out
Diogenes and his lantern in search of a person who can lead a life
of self-control and, although probably too much to ask, free of all
desire for material things and pleasures. Colin Powell may be that
person. Howard Kleinberg is a former editor of the Miami News.
(Kleinberg, Cox News Service) MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES _ Speculation rose that if a fan caught a
McGwire home run ball, and gave it to McGwire, the IRS would levy a
gift tax of 40 percent of a presumed value of $1 million. It's not
that the IRS actually threatened such mind-boggling chintziness but
that it was careful not to deny it. For the IRS to even hint that
it would not collect a tax just sitting there was too much for it.
(Rosenfeld, Cox News Service) MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   MURRAY-COLUMN _ DRUSKININKAI, Lithuania _ I feel better just
being in this town with its curative mineral waters. For a fact I
feel right at home. Druskininkai, 75 miles southwest of Lithuania's
capital Vilnius, is a community surrounded by pine forests, lakes
and rivers, same as my little hometown of Lufkin, Texas. (Murray,
Cox News Service) MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ GIBSONBURG, Ohio. Sunday mornings are peaceful
in our village. The bells at the Catholic church down the street
toll their gentle reminder; it's six o'clock. The rest is up to us.
(Schuett, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LANE-COLUMN _ ``Edward Robb Ellis, diarist,'' the headline read.
The labels in obituaries tend to be job titles. Seeing ``Diarist''
in such a headline last week was a novelty. It's not a job, a club
or a government appointment. It's a self-imposed mission. (Lane,
Daytona Beach News-Messenger) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
