<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 10:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5636 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-N     09-15 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATORS TO STRIP OFF ANTI-ENVIRONMENTAL RIDERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (EDITOR'S NOTE: Charles Levendosky, editorial page editor of the 
Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune, has a national reputation for First
Amendment commentary. His e-mail address is
levendos(AT-sign)trib.com.) 
(gm) 
 By CHARLES LEVENDOSKY   c. 1998 Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune   The
current Senate Interior Appropriations bill is piled high with more
than a dozen anti-environmental riders. These riders are intended
to carve out exceptions to environmental law or lower the level of
environmental protections for public lands. ``Mugging the
environment,'' The New York Times called the process _ carried out
in the darker recesses of Capitol Hill, hidden from public view.
<TEXT>
<P>
   A few senators will step into the light this week and introduce
amendments to strip off the worst of these riders.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Max Baucus, D-Mont., the ranking Democrat on the Senate's
Environment and Public Works Committee, will lead the charge
against the environment muggers. He plans to introduce an amendment
to strip eight riders from the Interior spending bill.
</P>
<P>
   One of the provisions in the Baucus amendment clashes with his
fellow senator from Montana, Republican Conrad Burns. Burns added a
rider that would terminate the ongoing public process of grizzly
bear reintroduction into the Selway-Bitterroot wilderness area of
Idaho and Montana. The Burns rider eliminates the state-level
public discussion and process to create a successful grizzly bear
plan. The Baucus amendment will strip off that rider _ in effect,
leaving grizzly recovery plan in the hands of those citizens living
closest to the recovery area.
</P>
<P>
   The Baucus amendment, if passed by the full Senate, will peel
off a rider that would prevent the National Park Service from
enforcing regulations to protect wildlife and to phase out
commercial fishing in Glacier Bay National Park in Alaska.
Commercial fishing is prohibited in all national park units.
</P>
<P>
   The Baucus amendment would pluck off a rider that would
authorize the construction of a $30-million road through the middle
of the Izembek National Wildlife Refuge in Alaska. The road is
opposed by 56 Native Alaskan villages in the region, taxpayer
groups and sportsmen.
</P>
<P>
   Baucus also targets a rider that would override the Endangered
Species Act in managing the Columbia River dams and ecosystem _
thereby severely restricting efforts to restore endangered and
threatened Pacific salmon.
</P>
<P>
   And four riders that would profoundly impact our national
forests could be scraped off by the Baucus amendment:
</P>
<P>
   1. Tongass National Forest rider that requires the U.S. Forest
Service to offer 240 million board feet of timber a year for sale,
or allows the timber companies to sue the USFS. It also requires
the agency to pay local communities 25 percent of the value of the
timber not harvested.
</P>
<P>
   2. A rider that would prevent the USFS from using prescribed
fire to remove brush until all commercial timber has been cut from
the area. The economic value of the stronger, fire-resistant trees
would cause them to be the first to be logged. The loss of these
trees undermines the point of a prescribed burn to restore balance
in the ecosystem.
</P>
<P>
   3. A rider that would prevent the USFS from removing dangerous
and environmentally damaging roads until all roads that were
created by illegal off-road vehicles have been closed or upgraded.
Many of these unauthorized roads are unrecorded and an inventory
would cause lengthy delays in the process.
</P>
<P>
   4. A rider that would prevent the USFS from updating plans to
manage national forests.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Richard Bryan, D-Nev., will introduce an amendment to
reduce taxpayer subsidies for timber sales and logging roads. A
rider on the Interior spending bill would increase these subsidies
by well over $24 million.
</P>
<P>
   An amendment by Sen. Dale Bumpers, D-Ark., targets a rider that
prevents the Secretary of the Interior from updating environmental
regulations governing hardrock mining on public lands.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Land Policy and Management Act of 1976 requires the
secretary of interior to ``take any action necessary, by regulation
or otherwise to prevent unnecessary or undue degradation on the
federal lands.'' The rider interferes with this law and puts a
moratorium on any revisions to the regulations. Taxpayers are
paying for cleaning up abandoned hardrock mines to the tune of $70
billion.
</P>
<P>
   The amendment offered by Sen. Max Cleland, D-Ga., will restore
the $6.4 million from funds appropriated in the fiscal year 1998
for the acquisition of lands within the Cumberland Island National
Seashore. The money comes from royalty payments from offshore
drilling and is put into the Land and Water Conservation Fund. The
$6.4 million is an overdue payment on a purchase agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Sens Bob Graham, D-Fla., and Dirk Kempthorne, R-Idaho, will seek
to increase the level of funding for the operations and maintenance
of National Wildlife Refuges to the level requested in the
president's budget.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J., will act to restore funding to
the Land and Water Conservation Fund. States use money from this
fund to purchase new recreational areas.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed amendments do not solve all the environmental
problems with the Senate Interior spending bill. For instance,
drastic cuts in funds for the Florida Everglades jeopardizes the
restoration plan. So far no senator has stepped forward to rectify
the situtation.
</P>
<P>
   If some of the key pro-environment amendments do not pass, the
president may veto the Interior Appropriations bill. In the last
Congress, Republicans attempted to eviscerate environmental law
using riders to appropriations bills _ but the public knew who was
to blame when Clinton vetoed them and brought federal agencies to a
halt.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the president's current problems, the public will
not be fooled into blaming him for a veto that blocks any serious
move to gut environmental protections. More than 70 percent of the
American public support strong environmental laws.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-09-14-98 1613EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
