   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HMO-REPORTCARD (San Francisco) _ A new survey of health
maintenance organizations in California gives high marks to Kaiser
Permanente for both preventive care and customer satisfaction,
while low scores went to fast-growing Blue Shield of California. By
ULYSSES TORASSA.
</P>
<P>
   IMMIGRANT-SMUGGLING (San Francisco) _ A federal judge sentenced
the West Coast ringleader of a group that smuggled 281 Chinese
immigrants on two crowded fishing boats to three years and nine
months in federal prison. By JIM HERRON ZAMORA.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-GOV (San Francisco) _ Blasting an effort to link him to a
wounded President Clinton, Lt. Gov. Gray Davis said California
voters are less interested in candidates' sex lives than in their
stands on public policy issues. The Democratic gubernatorial
nominee said his opponent, Republican Attorney General Dan Lungren,
may see his attempt to use Clinton's character as a campaign issue
backfire. By ZACHARY COILE.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DECLINING-EXPORTS (San Francisco) _ U.S. exports of high-tech
products are on the decline, a new report says, and increased
demand for American goods in some parts of the world offers little
hope for improvement. By GEORGE RAINE.
</P>
<P>
   MONEY-COLUMN (Undated) _ The year 2000 computer problem has
spawned a community of survivalists convinced that bad software
will have apocalyptic consequences. Although they are entitled to
their beliefs, this isn't a time for financial planning
Armageddon-style. By PAMELA YIP.
</P>
<P>
   INVESTMENT-CLUBS (Saratoga Springs, N.Y.) _ For this investment
club, the devil was in the details, not in the Dow. The Willow Tree
Stocks Investment Club, an all-female group, is cashing out its
joint investments just a couple of years after organizing. By
JO-ANN JOHNSTON.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   STUTTERING (Albany, N.Y.) _ Joy Emery has been married for 26
years. Only in recent years was she able to say her husband's name.
That's because Emery, 59, stutters. Today, after more than 50 years
of therapy, frustration and fortitude, Emery is finally speaking
with a fluency she never imagined possible. By SYLVIA WOOD.
</P>
<P>
   PET-NEUTICLES (Undated) _ The idea of implanting fake testicles
in a pet sounds like something the characters on ``Seinfeld'' might
joke about. It's no joke. In the past three years, more than 14,000
pairs of Neuticles have been implanted in dogs and cats, says Gregg
Miller, inventor of the product and president of the Missouri-based
company that makes them. By CLIFFORD PUGH.
</P>
<P>
   POP-ART (Houston) _ Stephen Keene, an artist from Brooklyn, is a
one-man assembly line. He takes himself and his painting seriously,
he asserts, but he also wants it to be fun. He estimates that by
the time his residency ends in Houston on Oct. 18, he will have
sold some 1,000 original works of art, most costing about $2. By
PATRICIA JOHNSON.
</P>
<P>
   GARDENING-COLUMN (Undated) _ Squirrels are driving gardeners
nuts. Here's how to deal with the critters. By KATHY HUBER.
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN'S-RIGHTS (Albany, N.Y.) _ Imagine the boldness of Julia
Blanche Stover Clum, who lived in the village of Valley Falls in
the late 1800s. Clum and her husband sheltered Susan B. Anthony,
the famous suffragist who was passing through town, when another
family would not. This story of women, some of whom do not have the
household names of Susan B. Anthony or Elizabeth Cady Stanton, is
precisely the point of a statewide celebration marking the 150th
anniversary of the first Women's Rights Convention. By MICHAEL
LOPEZ.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-REVIEW-TOMCAT (Undated) _ Tim O'Brien's ``Tomcat in Love,''
the seventh book by the author of ``Going After Cacciato'' and ``In
the Lake of the Woods,'' is the story of a self-deluding,
skirt-chasing, revenge-obsessed professor of language who wallows
from one love-starved episode to another. Sometimes he's funny.
Sometimes he's not.
</P>
<P>
   CARLOS-PONCE (Undated) _ Actor/singer Carlos Ponce's debut album
has yielded big hits. And so has his career. Ponce guest stars on
an upcoming Beverly Hills 90210 and is fielding offers on Broadway.
By JOEY GUERRA.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COLUMN (Undated) _ I was visiting some time ago with a
fellow travel journalist whose main expertise is the Caribbean. Her
favorite island is Jamaica. ``Don't you find some people there a
tad aggressive toward tourists?'' I asked. ``Oh, they don't bother
me ... I only go to the all-inclusive resorts and never leave until
it's time to fly home.'' How sad. By HARRY SHATTUCK.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HOMER-SWING (San Francisco) _ In a week when home run kings Mark
McGwire and Sammy Sosa are tied at 62 each, it's time to reflect on
how they do it. It's not just a matter of raw power: The tolerances
are so minute that many consider a major league home run the most
difficult feat in all of sports. By ULYSSES TORASSA.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-MARIS (Albany, N.Y.) _ Roger Maris had a sublime season in
1961, and he deserves credit and recognition for what he did. He is
on display in a Hall of Fame exhibit alongside Mark McGwire and
Sammy Sosa. He deserves nothing less and nothing more. By STEVE
CAMPBELL.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ According to a number of
doom-intoning news stories that I have read, Democrats and
Republicans alike believe that President Clinton's disaster can't
help but become every Democrat's disaster. Because of hurt
feelings, disgust, a sense of betrayal _ name your victimhood _
tens of thousands of Democrats are supposed to simply ``stay home''
on Nov. 3. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   ROBISON-COLUMN (Austin, Texas) _ I wish Texas Secretary of State
Al Gonzales a lot of luck, and he probably will need every bit of
it. As the state's chief elections officer, Gonzales has taken on
one of the most difficult jobs in state government right now _
encouraging people to get out and vote in the fall election. By
CLAY ROBISON.
</P>
<P>
   LYING-SEX (San Francisco) _ Almost everyone lies about sex; it
is the one area of our lives that it is appropriate to lie about.
And if a person lies about sex, it doesn't mean at all that he or
she lies about anything else. The truth is that, like the males of
most species, the human male is not naturally a physically
monogamous animal. By FRED FLAXMAN.
</P>
<P>
   CLACK-COLUMN (San Antonio) _ President Clinton's highly touted
plan to beef up child-care programs has withered on the vine in a
development that could have damaging repercussions. Clinton
introduced the plan with much fanfare and praise, but it is
expected to die quietly during the final weeks of the current
Congress. By CARY CLACK.
</P>
