<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOW-TO-COOK-EVERYTHING-VEGGIES-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 DISHES THAT WILL CONVERT VEGGIE HATERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _
the rate is not prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales
representative CONNIE WHITE. Call her at 1-800-444-0267 or
816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 (FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE) 
 North American rights. 
 By Mark Bittman  
 FROM ``HOW TO COOK EVERYTHING'' by MARK BITTMAN  
 Copyright 1998 Mark Bittman 
 Published by Macmillan, a trademark of MacMillan, Inc.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The typical supermarket produce section has grown by a factor of
about four in the past 15 years. Where there was once spinach,
there are now kale, bok choy and half a dozen other greens for
cooking. Where there were all-purpose potatoes, there are now Yukon
gold, little red and several more.
</P>
<P>
   Many people find this overwhelming, but the truth is that
cooking vegetables is simple. Of course, you need to identify the
vegetable and know the general rules for preparing it. But once
you've done that, there's not much more you need to do to put a
nicely finished vegetable dish on the table.
</P>
<P>
   Few vegetables cannot be simmered or steamed to tenderness and
then lightly dressed, with something as simple as lemon juice or
vinaigrette. And few vegetables cannot be cooked in a little olive
oil, either over high heat so that they become crisp, or with some
liquid, covered, over lower heat, so that they become meltingly
tender.
</P>
<P>
   If you buy super-fresh, super-high-quality vegetables, you can
give them the minimalist treatment and they'll be singing with
enough flavor to please even a vegetable hater.
</P>
<P>
   Most vegetable haters are simply vegetable lovers who haven't
realized it yet. These dishes can move the process along.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STIR-FRIED BROCCOLI &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (makes 4 servings)
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   You need not precook the broccoli for this stir-fry, but if you
have leftover or extra simmered or steamed broccoli, by all means
use it. Just keep the cooking time to a minimum, no longer than it
takes to heat the broccoli through.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; About 1 1/2 pounds broccoli, trimmed &QL; 
 &UR; 2 tablespoons peanut (preferred) or other oil &QL; 
 &UR; Salt to taste &QL; 
 &UR; 1 teaspoon sugar &QL; 
 &UR; 1 cup chicken, beef or vegetable stock, or water &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cut the stalks of the broccoli into thin slices. Separate the
florets into small sections.
</P>
<P>
   Place the oil in a wok or large, deep skillet over medium-high
heat. Two or three minutes later, add the broccoli, raise the heat
to high and cook, stirring, until it becomes bright green and
glossy and begins to brown, about 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Add the salt, sugar and stock or water. Stir and continue to
cook until almost all of the liquid evaporates and the broccoli is
tender, about 5 minutes more. Serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUICK-BRAISED CARROTS WITH ORANGE AND GINGER &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (makes 4 servings)
</P>
<P>
   Time: about 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Best with butter, but still delicious when made with oil. Simply
cooked carrots are good spiked with spices. In addition to ginger,
try ground cardamom, cinnamon, cumin or coriander.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1 pound carrots, peeled and cut into 1/4-inch-thick slices &QL; 
 &UR; 2 tablespoons butter or 1 tablespoon canola or other neutral oil &QL; 
 &UR; 1/4 cup orange juice &QL; 
 &UR; 1 tablespoon minced orange zest &QL; 
 &UR; 1 teaspoon sugar or 1 tablespoon maple syrup &QL; 
 &UR; Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste &QL; 
 &UR; 1 tablespoon peeled and minced fresh ginger &QL; 
 &UR; Minced fresh parsley, mint, chervil or cilantro leaves for garnish &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Place the carrots, butter or oil, orange juice, orange zest,
sugar, salt and pepper in a medium saucepan over high heat; bring
to a boil and cover. Turn the heat to medium-low and cook for 5
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Uncover and raise the heat a bit. Add the ginger. Cook, stirring
occasionally, until the liquid has evaporated and the carrots are
cooking in butter or oil. Lower the heat and continue to cook,
stirring occasionally, until tender, a couple of minutes longer.
</P>
<P>
   Taste and adjust the seasoning if necessary, then garnish and
serve.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OVEN-BAKED RATATOUILLE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (makes 4 servings)
</P>
<P>
   Time: About 1 1/4 hours
</P>
<P>
   Combining vegetables can turn a simple dish into a dramatic one
_ or even into a main course. This mixture of soft vegetables,
gently baked in layers until very tender, is sensational.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 10 cloves garlic &QL; 
 &UR; 2 large onions, thinly sliced &QL; 
 &UR; 2 large eggplant, about 2 pounds total, sliced 1/2-inch thick (If
time allows, salt both sides of the slices, let drain in a colander
for at least 30 minutes, rinse and squeeze dry between paper
towels.) &QL; 
 &UR; 4 red or yellow bell peppers, stemmed, peeled if desired, seeded
and sliced into 3 or 4 pieces each &QL; 
 &UR; 4 ripe red tomatoes, cored, skins and seeds removed, and cut into
thick slices &QL; 
 &UR; 1 teaspoon fresh thyme, rosemary or savory leaves &QL; 
 &UR; Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste &QL; 
 &UR; 2 tablespoons minced fresh parsley, basil or chervil leaves for
garnish &QL; 
 &UR; 1/2 cup extra-virgin olive oil &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees Fahrenheit.
</P>
<P>
   Either of these techniques will make the garlic easier to peel:
Drop it into boiling water, leave it there for 30 seconds, then
remove. Or toast it in a dry skillet over medium heat, shaking
frequently, for 3 or 4 minutes. Peel and cut each clove in half.
</P>
<P>
   In a casserole, make a layer of onion, followed by one of
eggplant, peppers, tomatoes, herbs, salt, pepper and garlic cloves.
Repeat. Drizzle the ratatouille with the olive oil and place in the
oven.
</P>
<P>
   Bake for about an hour, pressing down on the vegetables
occasionally, until they are all completely tender. Garnish and
serve, hot or at room temperature.
 &UR; Distributed by New York Times Special Features &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
