<SLUG> BC-CLACK-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS SHOULD REVIVE CLINTON'S CHILD-CARE PROGRAMS 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CARY CLACK  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ President Clinton's highly touted plan to beef up
child-care programs has withered on the vine in a development that
could have damaging repercussions.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton introduced the plan with much fanfare and praise. Now,
fingerpointing is under way as observers expect the proposals to
die quietly during the final weeks of the 105th Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press reported that lawmakers are not planning to
fund Clinton's proposed $21 billion child-care proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The president's programs would have provided subsidies for poor
working families, tax credits for the middle class and other
attempts to make child care more accessible.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton lacked the focus or the muscle to push through this
big-ticket spending item.
</P>
<P>
   One congressional aide told The Associated Press that the
Clinton administration provided a lot of steam but not much engine.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, Clinton planned to fund child-care programs with
money from a mammoth tobacco settlement, but Congress failed to
approve the settlement, thanks to obstructionism by the Republican
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Congress should pick up the issue again next year because it is
too important to drop.
</P>
<P>
   Without child-care assistance for the nation's working poor,
welfare reforms will ultimately be unsuccessful and millions of
single parents will never have a chance to pull themselves out of
poverty.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Cary Clack is a columnist for the San Antonio Express-News,
P.O. Box 2171, San Antonio, TX 78297.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-98 1241EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
