<DOCNO> NYT19980915.0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 12:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5826 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LYING-SEX-HNS &LR;      09-15 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYING-SEX-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LYING WAS THE HONORABLE THING TO DO 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRED FLAXMAN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Since no one else has done this, I'm going to
tell you the truth, the whole truth, and nothing but the truth on
the subject of President Clinton's affair with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   It is true that they had an affair, that it was sexual and that
it was inappropriate and wrong, and that Clinton lied to everyone
about it. But it is also true that lying was the honorable thing to
do. Almost everyone lies about sex; it is the one area of our lives
that it is appropriate to lie about. And if a person lies about
sex, it doesn't mean at all that he or she lies about anything
else.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is that, like the males of most species, the human
male is not naturally a physically monogamous animal. But there are
huge social pressures favoring monogamy. This situation presents
conflicts for many men and they have sex outside of marriage.
</P>
<P>
   They may love their wives and children and want to maintain a
strong family life, but they also crave a bit of sexual variety.
Such activity is widely perceived as wrong, as Clinton admitted in
his address to the nation, and it certainly is dangerous to
marriages and family life. Therefore, men (and women) who cheat on
their spouses but care about them and their children usually cover
it up. Truth is, that is the right and honorable thing to do if
they don't want to hurt the people they love.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton carried on his affair in a study off the Oval Office of
the White House. It sure wasn't very wise to have sex on sacrosanct
public property. It would have been much wiser not to have carried
on with a White House intern at all. But sexual appetite is not a
matter of wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   And given that these two were so sexually attracted to each
other and that neither of them wanted the rest of the world to know
about it, where could they go? The White House family quarters? A
motel? You've got to admit that Clinton's options were rather
limited, and that if you had done what he did, you would want to
cover it up as well.
</P>
<P>
   Almost everything Clinton said in his speech to the nation was
correct, as far as it went, and he should not have gone any
further. He was right that one's sex life should be a private
affair as long as it is between consenting adults. Monica Lewinsky
has not charged Clinton with sexual harassment or with using the
power of his office to obtain sex. Paula Corbin Jones, the one
woman who did make such charges, had her case dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   What Clinton has said about independent counsel Kenneth Starr
was also correct. Starr's investigation of Clinton's sex life was
as wrong and inappropriate as Clinton's affair in the Oval Office,
but what Starr has done is far more damaging to the country.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't Clinton's affair in the White House that embarrassed
the country, it was Starr's revelation of that affair. It wasn't
Clinton's lying and coverup of the affair which got him in trouble,
it was Starr's forcing him to come clean. It was Starr, not
Clinton, who used the power of his office to compel Monica Lewinsky
to do something she didn't want to do _ tell the truth about her
affair with the president or face prosecution for perjury.
</P>
<P>
   It was Starr who forced the president's lawyers and advisers and
Secret Service agents, who were supposed to protect the president,
to testify against their will under oath. It was Starr who wasted
millions of dollars of taxpayers' money investigating the private
sex life of a sitting head of state, damaging the president's
credibility and capacity to govern, harming the nation, and
attempting to overrule the will of the American people who elected
Clinton, not Starr.
</P>
<P>
   I don't question Clinton's motives for trying to cover up his
affair, but I sure do question Starr's for going after Clinton's
private life. It appears as though he was out to get Clinton for
purely political reasons, and when he couldn't find anything in the
Whitewater affair he was originally hired to investigate, nor in
any other aspect of Clinton's nonsexual behavior, he decided to
check below the belt, where, as we now know all too well, he found
something he had no business looking for to begin with.
</P>
<P>
   A special prosecutor should be hired to investigate Kenneth
Starr's leaks of grand jury testimony to the press. If it can be
proven that he was responsible for some of those leaks, he should
be prosecuted to the full extent of the law. If there is
insufficient evidence to prosecute him on this account, the new
special prosecutor should thoroughly investigate Starr's sex life _
and see how he likes that.
</P>
<P>
   Chances are he has something there that he has lied about,
covered up, or at least not revealed to anyone else. Most men do.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Fred Flaxman is the editor of ``The Timeless Tales of Reginald
Bretnor,'' published by Story Books.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
