<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-BILLS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON WOES REDUCE CHANCES FOR SEVERAL BILLS IN CONGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The release of salacious details of President
Clinton's affair with Monica S. Lewinsky has lowered the odds that
Congress will pass several major pieces of legislation, some of
which are top priorities of consumer groups or control the way US
companies conduct billions of dollars in business.
</P>
<P>
   Some business lobbyists say the president now seems unwilling to
push for one of their favored bills _ a measure that would lead to
more free-trade treaties. They speculate that Clinton may be leery
of angering Democratic groups that oppose the legislation and may
be needed as allies during an impeachment fight.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of a ``patients' bill of rights,'' which would impose
new regulations on health-maintenance organizations, say only fear
of a voter rebellion this November forced Republican leaders to
move the bill through Congress. ``What's changed is some
Republicans may be feeling that the Lewinsky issue is consuming
enough of the public's attention that they can get away without
passing any managed care legislation,'' said Ronald Pollack,
executive director of Families USA, a consumer group backing the
bill.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Congress faces tough and time-consuming negotiations
over a Republican-proposed tax cut, a major overhaul of banking and
insurance rules, and a proposal to send more money to an
international agency charged with calming the Asian financial
turmoil _ all while time is in short supply.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers plan to adjourn Oct. 9 to prepare for the November
elections. Much of their remaining time must be spent passing a
federal budget for the next fiscal year, which starts in only 16
days.
</P>
<P>
   The spending plan for next year is contained in 13 separate
bills, and only one has made its way through Congress. ``If time is
a currency in limited supply, clearly all this talk (of the
Lewinsky affair) takes away from it,'' said Frank Coleman of the US
Chamber of Commerce, which lobbies for business interests. ``This
has clearly derailed action, to a degree, on the things we're
working to accomplish.''
</P>
<P>
   One top priority for the chamber is a bill that would grant
Clinton so-called ``fast track'' powers, which would make it easier
for him to sign the type of free-trade treaties the United States
already has with Mexico and Canada. Clinton has long fought to
renew his fast-track powers, which lapsed in 1994, but he lost a
major battle for them in the House last November.
</P>
<P>
   The House is scheduled to vote on fast track again on Sept. 24,
but business lobbyists say the president is not leaning on
lawmakers this time to support the measure. Some blame the
administration's focus on the Lewinsky matter and the possibility
of impeachment procedings.
</P>
<P>
   ``At best, it has left the administration distracted. At worst,
it has left the administration working against us in order to curry
favor with labor union leadership and extreme environmentalists''
who oppose fast track, said William Morley, lead lobbyist on the
issue for the US Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Congress is also running out of time to solve disputes between
the banking, brokerage and insurance industries _ and among
different constituencies within each industry _ over a major
overhaul of rules that control how those businesses operate.
</P>
<P>
   The overhaul would rewrite Depression-era laws that prevent or
make it difficult for banks, securities firms and insurance
companies to merge with each other or compete in each other's
businesses. Congress has tried unsuccessfully nearly a dozen times
in past two decades to rewrite the laws.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, lawmakers were faced with a new challenge when the
Independent Insurance Agents of America withdrew their support of
the bill over complaints that it would give banks an advantage over
individual agents in selling insurance. The bill has overcome
similar hurdles in the past, but its passage is in doubt because
the agents' group has members in every congressional district and
wields significant clout.
</P>
<P>
   While some bills, including the new regulations for managed-care
health insurers, appear to be stalling, several other bills have
gathered new momentum in recent days and may find their way through
the legislative maze.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Edward M. Kennedy, during speeches on the Senate floor
last week that totalled nearly five hours, had complained that the
Republian leadership was blocking votes on the managed-care bill,
which he strongly supports, and on a plan to raise the minimum wage
by one dollar over two years, to $6.15 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday, Kennedy said he had won the right to a Senate vote
on the minimum wage bill. If he is successful Tuesday, the minimum
wage hike would be attached to a bill that would make it harder for
people to escape their debts by declaring personal bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy also said Republicans will be sure to move other bills
through Congress, such as a measure to reauthorize $40 billion in
college loan and other higher education programs, because the GOP
cannot be seen as impeding those programs.
</P>
<P>
   The House is expected to vote as early as this week on a
contentious bill that would allow high-tech companies, and certain
other businesses, to hire more skilled foreign workers for US jobs.
The measure is bitterly opposed by labor unions and high-tech
worker groups.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
