<SLUG> BC-CONN-SUBS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONNECTICUT SUB WORKS HAS THAT SINKING FEELING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS FARRAGHER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; GROTON, Conn. _ It's out there somewhere, running quiet and
deep in the Atlantic, working out final bugs that separate it from
joining the Navy's fleet and placing a melancholy punctuation mark
on a shipbuilding tradition humbled by peace.
</P>
<P>
   The USS Connecticut _ the first submarine named for a state
synonmous with submersible ships _ will be commissioned late this
year. It will notch the end of an era when almost limitless
Pentagon budgets meant bountiful paychecks and full-speed work
schedules on a waterfront whose heritage dates to 1900 and the
nation's first submarine.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one time, everybody's father worked there. Your brother
worked there. You're uncle worked there,'' said John Yates, a
retired submarine-builder, sipping a cold beer at the Sea Romer
Cafe, up the street from the Electric Boat shipyard here. ``And it
was all guaranteed work.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the Cold War, we made all kinds of money. But when the
Berlin Wall fell, everybody started to save money. You look at that
shipyard today and it's kind of sad.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, along Eastern Point Road, where generations of workers
have assembled submarines with names like Scorpion and Skipjack,
Catfish and Carp, Baltimore and Boston, a leisurely rhythm outside
Electric Boat's main gate has supplanted the pell-mell shift change
tableau that symbolized the shipyard's heyday of the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Its payroll has been cut from a Reagan-era high of 18,500 to a
post-Cold War 7,800, a seismic downsizing whose epicenter here
still struggles to adjust to life in a world without superpower
villains.
</P>
<P>
   ``When World War II was over, you had a big party and everybody
wanted to go home,'' said John K. Welch, a 48-year-old Waltham
native who is EB's president. ``At the end of the Cold War, there
wasn't that euphoria. People were asking, `What's next?' It's been
a rough transition. The hardest part for everybody is dealing with
changes that have been required.''
</P>
<P>
   Economists, union leaders, and ex-shipyard workers said those
changes mean more stress and more uncertainty as the demand for a
highly skilled manufacturing work force is eclipsed by a premium on
technology and a more service-oriented economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The boom times of the '80s were euphoric. They were unnatural.
They were giddy,'' said Will McEachern, an economics professor at
the University of Connecticut. ``The region is doing pretty well
now, but that doesn't mean that certain people didn't take a great
hit because they did.''
</P>
<P>
   McEachern said some casual observors assume that laid off
shipyard workers simply shifted their morning commute slightly
north and west and exchanged their pipefitters' wrenches for the
roulette wheels and gaming chips at the nearby Foxwoods and Mohegan
Sun casinos. In fact, said McEachern, only a fraction of EB's
workers ended up in the casinos, with most settling for other less
well-paying jobs in southeastern Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our folks are working two or three jobs now, and their
standard of living has changed,'' said Kenneth DelaCruz, president
of the 2,000-member Metal Trades Council, a blue-collar union whose
membership once topped 10,000. ``It's deceiving when you pick up
the paper and see that unemployment in this region is low. That's
probably true, but the quality of life for these folks and for
their families has changed dramatically.''
</P>
<P>
   As a testimonial to those displaced workers and to the
generations of welders, boilermakers, painters, carpenters,
machinists, electricians, engineers, and designers who preceded
them, the Navy has designated the second of its three Seawolf
submarines for the state that turned out 85 submarines for World
War II, built the world's first nuclear-powered submarine, the USS
Nautilus, in 1955, and has designed 15 of the 18 classes of nuclear
submarines.
</P>
<P>
   Only Electric Boat and a shipyard in Newport News, Va., build US
submarines. And the Navy, which in the 1980s would sometimes order
three or four subs a year, has drastically cut back. In fiscal year
1999, one sub is being requested. The following year, none is.
</P>
<P>
   ``The greatest moment will come Dec. 11, when we commission her
and that crew runs aboard that ship and the Navy takes command,''
said Dee Hauber, a former Groton mayor and a member of the USS
Connecticut's commissioning committee. ``That's genuine tradition.
I mean I get goose bumps just thinking about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The $2.5 billion, 353-foot submarine will be the fifth ship
named for the fifth state of the union, but the first submarine to
carry the name Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Now on the second of its sea trials off the New England coast,
where its propulsion plant and engines are tested, the Connecticut
will carry a crew of 130. And when it joins the fleet, it will be
armed with Mark 48 antisubmarine torpedoes and Tomahawk cruise
missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Once the Navy takes over the Connecticut &UR;  &LR; in December, Electric
Boat shipyard will not deliver another submarine to the Navy for
three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It represents the end of a very robust nuclear construction
program that went throughout the Cold War and then overlapped into
the years after the Cold War,'' said Welch. ``It's a tribute to the
heritage that the whole state has had in support of the military
for centuries.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in a state that made cannons for the Revolutionary War,
gunpowder for the Civil War, and helicopters for the Persian Gulf
War, workers along the Thames River waterfront worry that
submarines are becoming more a part of history than an economic
fixture of the future.
</P>
<P>
   So, they say, the upcoming commissioning ceremony, with its
spit-and-polish pomp, marching bands, balloons, and confetti, will
be a bittersweet moment for the workers who for generations worked
in numbing cold and searing heat to turn out sophisticated
submarines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Electric Boat is never going to be the way it was before,''
said James Gula, who worked in the warehouses for 25 years before
retiring recently. ``But we build the best submarines in the world
and we should be recognized for that. But I think it's a shame to
lose all those skilled workers over there.''
</P>
<P>
   DelaCruz said many workers are haunted by the view of the
shipyard's waterfront, once jammed with ships under construction,
but now nearly vacant.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's very sad,'' he said. ``That's the only thing we do ...
build submarines. You walk through the yard and it's a skeleton of
what it used to be.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Navy announced last week that it was naming an entire
new class of fast-attack submarines for the state of Virginia, home
to EB's submarine-building competitor, some workers here said they
were further demoralized.
</P>
<P>
   ``The future looks dim,'' said Melvin E. Olsson, president of
the Marine Draftsmen's Association, a white-collar EB union.
``It'll be exciting to see the Connecticut commissioned, but it's
disappointing to see what's happening.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very quiet in the yard now. You can walk through and you
don't see many people. The work force is much older. The younger
people have been laid off. Your neighbors used to work there. Your
grandfather used to work there. It's not going to be like that
anymore. Now, your relative is just as likely to be a blackjack
dealer up at Foxwoods.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-98 1309EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
