r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-MARIS-HNS &LR;      09-15 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-MARIS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARIS DOESN'T NEED A PLACE IN THE HALL OF FAME 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE CAMPBELL  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Mark McGwire was holding history in his hands. As
McGwire squeezed the 37-year-old Roger Maris bat, which had been
resting comfortably in a glass case at the baseball Hall of Fame,
tears came to his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire took the barrel of the bat that delivered home run No.
61 in 1961, rubbed it over his heart and looked skyward.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roger,'' McGwire said, ``I hope you're with me tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Hours later, McGwire hit his record-setting 62nd home run of the
season. One of the lingering moments of that magical, mystical
night in St. Louis came when McGwire climbed into the stands to
embrace Maris' children. During a post-game ceremony honoring
McGwire, the crowd showered the Maris children with the sort of
cheers and affection and understanding that so often eluded their
father when he was alive.
</P>
<P>
   Life dealt Roger Maris the sort of hand you might wish on an
Internal Revenue Service auditor. Maris broke Babe Ruth's season
home run record, and people didn't take kindly to a mere mortal
having the audacity to put a chink in a legend's armor. Injuries
subsequently prevented Maris from having the sort of career that he
might have had. Then cancer came along and robbed Maris of the
golden years ahead of him. Maris died when he was only 51, leaving
behind a wife and six children.
</P>
<P>
   Any heart has to melt when confronted by a family that will
never be whole again in this lifetime. The natural impulse is to
try to heal all the scars the Maris family has accumulated. The
resulting clamor to bring closure by inducting Maris into the Hall
of Fame is as understandable as it is ill-conceived. Emotion, not
reality, is the only thing that can fuel a campaign to put Maris in
the Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake: What Maris did in 1961 was monumental. Denny
McLain had a similar breakthrough in 1968, when he became the first
pitcher in 34 years to win 30 games. Nobody has come close to
winning 30 in a season since, but that didn't get McLain in the
Hall of Fame. McLain doesn't belong there, because his entire
career (131-91, on Most Valuable Player award, two Cy Youngs, three
All-Star selections) doesn't have enough substance.
</P>
<P>
   Hall of Fame status is based on the body of work of an entire
career. Maris played 12 seasons in the major leagues. He hit 275
home runs, drove in 851 runs, batted .260. He won the American
League MVP award twice, made four All-Star teams, played in seven
World Series, drove in 100 runs three times, won one Gold Glove.
</P>
<P>
   Maris had an enviable career, but he couldn't sustain his
greatness long enough to earn enshrinement in at the Hall of Fame
in Cooperstown, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   One of Maris' contemporaries was fellow right fielder Rocky
Colavito. In just two more seasons than Maris, Colavito accumulated
374 homers and drove in 1,159 runs. Colavito made the All-Star team
five times, drove in 100 runs six times. When it comes to the Hall
of Fame, Maris needs to get in a long line that by no means starts
with Colavito.
</P>
<P>
   Del Ennis had more homers and runs batted in than Maris. Does
anybody really think Del Ennis is a Hall of Famer? Maris had a
lower career home run total than the likes of Bob Johnson, Rudy
York, Jimmy Wynn, Kent Hrbek, Roy Sievers, Willie Horton and Joe
Adcock. Fine players, all of them, but hardly Cooperstown-worthy.
</P>
<P>
   Boog Powell, Bill Buckner, Vic Wertz, Mickey Vernon, Al Oliver
and Darrell Evans aren't beating down the doors to Cooperstown, and
they all drove in at least 300 more runs than Maris.
</P>
<P>
   Whether injuries or anguish kept Maris from accomplishing more
isn't relevant. He did what he did, with no apologies or excuses
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Maris used to say, ``I just wanted to be one of the guys,
an average player having a good season.'' He had a sublime season
once upon 1961, and he deserves credit and recognition for what he
did. He is on display in an exhibit alongside McGwire and Sammy
Sosa. He deserves nothing less and nothing more.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-98 1310EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
