<HEADLINE>
SO MANY GREAT PLACES TO VIEW FALL'S FINERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everyone's favorite question at this time of year: ``Where's the
best foliage?''
</P>
<P>
   Vermont and New Hampshire may be the states that first come to
mind, but Maine claims it not only has spectacular color but is
promoting the state as a ``welcoming, must-see destination, with
lots of interesting and unique things to see and do,'' according to
Dann Lewis of the Maine Office of Tourism. ``We want to show people
there is more to do in Maine than simply look at leaf color.''
</P>
<P>
   The many activities, Lewis says, set Maine apart from its
``competitors'' (and you know who they are). Maine is out to be the
``Outdoor Adventure Capital of the East'' and as such offers a
bountiful list of autumn activities, from white-water rafting and
windjammer sailing to hiking and biking.
</P>
<P>
   One of the hits of Maine's foliage season is the ``leaf lady.''
If you're on the Internet, check out the state's Web site at
www.visitmaine.com, where you can get in touch with Susan Benson,
the ``leaf lady,'' who will answer just about any foliage-related
question you can think of. In 1996, her site on the Web generated
just 4,700 hits all year; this August alone, there were 73,000
hits.
</P>
<P>
   For those not on the Web, head for Maine and stop at the
Interstate 95 information center just across the border in Kittery
where you'll find lots of ideas for foliage viewing and things to
do. Last year while attending a wedding, I was throughly impressed
with the early October colors along the coastal route between York
and Ogunquit. For Maine information and foliage reports, call
888-624-6345.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile in ``competitor'' Vermont, reports of pockets of
colors emerging in higher elevations and in scattered wetlands are
growing. Among a couple of routes with good color now are Route 9
from Brattleboro to Wilmington and Route 100 to the Mount Snow ski
area. For foliage reports, events, and vacation planning kits, call
800-VERMONT or visit www.travel.vermont.com. Vermont also offers an
automated fax service that provides foliage information by calling
800-833-9756.
</P>
<P>
   Vermont, by the way, claims its foliage is better than others
because the state has good soils that favor tree species such as
maples and a climate said to be conductive to foliage coloration.
Vermont has a fairly long season of cold nights and warm days,
which are needed for good color production.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire has, perhaps, the most famous foliage road in the
county, the Kancamagus Highway, or Route 112. This 34-mile stretch
of White Mountain National Forest road that runs between Lincoln
and Conway has views that are second to none _ towering mountain
peaks, wonderfully clear streams, and scenic vistas that offer
spectacular views. While in the area, take the Loon Mountain
gondola ride in Lincoln for more great views or head to North
Conway for a ride aboard the Conway Scenic Railway and then take in
some outlet shopping.
</P>
<P>
   Call the state's foliage line at 800-258-3608 for the latest
color report. Or, for a 215-page guide to the state, call
800-FUN-IN-NH, ext 200.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly one of the most enjoyable areas of New Hampshire is
the Monadnock Region, an area of picturesque villages (Fitzwilliam,
pictured on the front of the Travel section, is one of the classic
towns), antiquing, the arts, scenic drives, and rolling hills.
Mount Monadnock, easily reached from Boston, is known as the most
climbed mountain in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The area abounds in wonderful inns and bed-and-breakfasts. The
Fitzwilliam Inn (603-585-9000), which has been welcoming guests for
200 years, reports it still has some space during foliage season.
Also in Fitzwilliam are the Ashburn House (603-585-7198), Hanna
Davis House (603-585-3344), and the Amos A. Parker House
(603-585-6540). Fitzwilliam is convenient for those without cars
because the Vermont Transit Bus Line offers service from Boston to
the Fitzwilliam Inn (call 800-451-3292). For other information,
call the Chamber of Commerce in Keene (603-352-1303), Jaffrey
(603-532-4549), or Rindge (603-899-5051).
</P>
<P>
   ``The foliage in Connecticut could be the best ever this year,''
said Don Smith, chief of the state bureau of forestry. And, adding
to the confusion as to where the best color is, Smith says
Connecticut's geography makes it the perfect destination for lovers
of fall foliage. ``Just as northern New England's fall foliage is
winding down, Connecticut's colors are getting ready for their big
burst of color.''
</P>
<P>
   The state's tourism hot line, 800-CT-BOUND, ext. 88, allows
travelers to book accommodations of every type, as well as provide
information on events during foliage season, and there are plenty,
ranging from the Bristol Mum Festival, Sept. 25-Oct. 11; the Durham
Fair, now in its 79th year, Sept. 25-27; the Southington Apple
Harvest Festival, Oct. 3-4 and 8-11; to the Chowderfest at Mystic
Seaport, Oct. 10-12.
</P>
<P>
   While there are many driving tours to catch the state's foliage,
one of the best ways to enjoy it is on foot. Every Columbus Day
weekend, the state's northeast corner, or ``Quiet Corner,'' holds a
Walking Weekend with more than 50 guided itineraries for every
fitness level throughout 25 towns. For information, call the
Northeast Visitors District at 888-628-1228.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts, too, has great colors in the fall. And the
easiest way to catch some great views is to get on Route 2 in
Cambridge and head west. The only problem with Route 2 is that,
especially on Columbus Day weekend, the road can become jam-packed
in the Mohawk Trail region, which has its beginnings in Orange.
Last year, I tried to get to Greenfield's Fall Festival on the
Common (Oct. 10, 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. this year) and gave up just
after the French King Bridge in Erving because of traffic. But
then, I see this area weekly on shopping trips to Greenfield, so
don't give up _ its worth the slow going. More on that festival and
others in the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   As in Connecticut, the Bay State's colors seem to peak on
Columbus Day weekend and continue for almost the rest of the month.
The best part of being in the Boston area is that you don't have to
drive far to catch the colors. Leaf peepers need only head to the
Blue Hills Reservation, a 5,000- acre wilderness less than 10 miles
from the city proper. Drive through the reservation, easily reached
from either the Southeast Expressway or Route 128 in the
Canton-Randolph area, then drive back into the city via Canton
Avenue and you'll think you're in New Hampshire, especially when
you pass the classic white churches near Randolph Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   In central Massachusetts, one thing to do is to get lost in a
maze _ a four-acre field of tall sorghum grass. There are some 2.2
miles of pathways at the Davis' Farmland in Sterling. The design of
the maze is inspired by a Celtic dragon motif, the work of Adrian
Fisher, an English maze designer. The field will be open until
frost or tramping feet push it under. The maze is on Route 62 on
Redstone Hill Road in Sterling; admission is $7.50 for those 13 to
59; $5.50 for the 4-to-12 set and those over 60. There is also a
petting zoo with a separate admission. For information, call
978-422-6666.
</P>
<P>
   Not far away in Princeton is Mount Wachusett, perhaps best known
for its handy ski slopes in winter. But in foliage season you can
drive to its top for stunning views. Or you could hike it as Henry
David Thoreau did in 1842; he then dreamed of Homer on Mount
Olympus and read Virgil in the original Latin. Mount Wachusett
rises 2,006 feet, so you might want to drive up.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts, though, has something special when it comes to
colorful fall shows _ the cranberry harvest, where you'll see
flooded bogs where berries float to the surface, forming a
brilliant red carpet of color. The Cranberry Harvest Festival, Oct.
10-12 takes place at two sites: at the Edaville Cranberry Bogs off
Route 58 in South Carver (call 508-295-5799) and at Cranberry World
on the waterfront in Plymouth (call 508-747-2350). While in the
area, take in King Richard's Faire, where Renaissance swordplay,
music, entertainment, crafts, and food are featured (call
508-866-5391). The faire is held weekends through Oct. 18.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Foliage hot lines
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Vermont _ 802-828-3239
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire _ 800-258-3608 or 800-262-6660.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts _ 800-447-MASS, ext. 300
</P>
<P>
   Maine _ 888-MAINE-45
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut _ 800-282-6863, ext. 88
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Foliage express
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The first luxury rail (and motorcoach) tour through New England
will begin Sept. 26. Great Train Escapes, a Seattle-based operator,
will relocate a luxury train to take travelers throughout New
England. The service out of Wareham station in Portland, Maine,
will allow travelers to go by rail through the villages of Maine,
New Hampshire, Vermont, Connecticut, and Rhode Island. The trip
will begin in Boston where passengers will travel by motorcoach to
Portland. The eight-day trips will depart Saturdays, Sept. 26-Oct.
17. For information, call Great Train Escapes Rail Tours at
800-895-2554.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Internet foliage
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another way to check on foliage is through Internet services
such as Expedia. Expedia offers a one-stop source for trip
planning, with detailed maps and weather forecasts along with
advice on making the most of this season's foliage. For those
taking off on a foliage or other outing, Expedia is offering anyone
purchasing a Northwest or Continental ticket through the service a
$99 companion award certificate to use with the next Expedia
purchase of a ticket on one of those airlines. Check out
www.expedia.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
