<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLEDSOE'S TEAMMATES PLAYING FOLLOW THE LEADER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ It's an intangible, so it cannot be
measured. It's a subtlety, so it can be felt more than diagrammed.
Drew Bledsoe does seem to be a different quarterback this season.
</P>
<P>
   Two games does not a season make, but Bledsoe seems to be
playing much more within himself. A different level of poise seems
to be there, as well as a higher degree of maturity. Most of all,
Bledsoe seems to be in full control of New England's offense,
making plays but not mistakes. In short, Bledsoe seems more what a
quarterback must be if a team is to go to the Super Bowl: a leader.
</P>
<P>
   The change seems so evident that Vincent Brisby went home after
Sunday night's 29-6 win over the Colts and ``I was telling my mom
that Drew is in more control this year,'' said the Patriot wide
receiver. ``He's the leader out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Fans might be able to sense from afar a change in Bledsoe's
quarterbacking, but that change is more clear to those most close
to Bledsoe, such as his pal and backup quarterback, Scott Zolak.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see it in his eyes this year,'' said Zolak, ``as
opposed to last year or the year before. You could really see it in
his eyes before the Denver game.''
</P>
<P>
   Before that Denver game, the season opener, the media and
chatterers ``talked about his big-game jinx and all that, which is
a bunch of malarkey,'' said Zolak. At Mile High Stadium, though,
``you could just see _ he had a fiery disposition about himself.''
</P>
<P>
   And when things didn't go well early for the Patriots in Denver,
said Zolak, ``Drew was actually pretty ticked off when somebody
made a bad play or we had a bad call go against us. That's
something you hadn't seen before. He seems a lot more fiery this
year, more intense.''
</P>
<P>
   It is imperative, of course, that Bledsoe be a leader for this
offense that is, as coach Pete Carroll put it Monday, ``still a
work in progress.'' New England's running game is sporadic, at
best, and impotent at other times.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know when you've got a fiery leader _ a Brett Favre type _
that the other guys play harder,'' said Zolak. ``And I think that's
what we've been doing, playing harder.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Bledsoe also seems to be playing well within himself. In
Denver, he threw one pass to Ben Coates into nearly triple coverage
(which Coates caught), but overall Bledsoe's decisions through the
first two games have been sound. He has thrown no interceptions,
while he has thrown many passes demonstrating Bledsoe at his best,
such as the TD pass to Brisby late in the Denver game and a
perfectly timed stop-and-go pass to Shawn Jefferson along the right
sideline for 38 yards in the Colts game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is playing within himself,'' said Zolak. ``And he's doing a
good job of not looking at Ben on those third-and-5s or
third-and-7s, or just looking to Terry (Glenn). He's spreading the
ball around real well, using the underneath guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Zolak also noticed a change in that ultimate intangible, poise.
</P>
<P>
   ``When something bad happens,'' said Zolak, ``like last week in
Denver when we were down, 17-0, Drew kept his poise real well. When
things are going bad, he's not getting rattled. He's a leader and
that's the onus he has to put on himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Patriots say much the same. Jefferson said Bledsoe now
enters the huddle and tells receivers, ``This ball is coming to
you.'' Brisby said Bledsoe ``is more of a competitor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see he's more fiery,'' said receiver Troy Brown.
``He's just being Drew Bledsoe to me. He's making great throws and
he's doing a great job of making the defense move.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe, said Brisby, ``now is challenging the guys in the
huddle _ like Favre does _ and the guys love it. Drew is telling
guys to step up and in the huddle he's saying, `I'm bringing this
play to you, so you'd better be ready.' I'm just thinking that he's
feeling more comfortable about everything and himself.''
</P>
<P>
   In short, said Brisby, ``Drew knows that he's the key to making
us get to the next level.''
</P>
<P>
   And, for the first two games at least, Bledsoe is playing
exactly that part.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
