<HEADLINE>
SOSA A BIG HIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ You couldn't blame Sammy Sosa for feeling at home in
Qualcomm Stadium Monday night. The voices he heard were in both
English and Spanish. The affection he felt was genuine. Move over,
Mark McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa may be running No. 2 in the baseball popularity contest,
but he went into Monday night tied in the home run race with
McGwire at 62. The tortoise had caught the hare, and don't be
surprised if it's Sosa out in front at the finish line, with the
home run title and the hearts of baseball fans to call his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a beautiful phone call from President Bill Clinton,''
said Sosa in a press conference before the Cubs-Padres game that
drew nearly as many Spanish media as English-speaking reporters.
``It's something that makes me real proud of myself. In fact, after
I hung up, I was jumping up and down.
</P>
<P>
   ``He congratulated me,'' continued Sosa, who belted homers No.
61 and 62 Sunday in Chicago. ``He saw an interview that my mother
had and liked it. He said he was a Chicago Cubs fans. He told me he
wanted me to take the Cubs to the playoffs. I told him I'd do my
best.''
</P>
<P>
   After losing the race to Roger Maris's mark of 61 a week ago to
McGwire, the St. Louis Cardinals slugger, Sosa has risen from a
premature burial by many of the nation's media and fans. This is
the same Sammy Sosa who once trailed McGwire, 24-9, yet pulled into
ties at 47 and 55. All told, Sosa hit four homers over the weekend
to draw even again after McGwire had belted his 62d to establish a
new record and set the nation afire last Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Understand that this will be a fight to the finish. Sosa is
having too much fun to have it go down any other way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know people want to know if I think I haven't gotten as much
out of this as McGwire,'' said Sosa. ``The attention I have been
having all year has been good enough for me. Mark did it first. He
was the man. I'm just so happy to be playing in the United States
and be the person that I am. I'm pleased with what I have right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   With Mexico only 20 miles away, Sosa devoted more than half of
his pregame remarks to a Spanish-speaking audience. The questions
took a different tone, more about Sosa's inner feelings than his
battle with McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I say to the whole Latin American community, and the people in
the United States who gave me the chance to be who I am, that this
is unbelievable,'' said Sosa, a native of the Dominican Republic.
``I've only got one way to go. Maybe after it's over, I can look
back.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that makes this a nice situation is to be in a
wild-card race. I don't have to go out there and think about home
runs. Somebody asked me who is my idol. My idol is God.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sammy loves it,'' said Cubs teammate Mark Grace. ``I don't
blame him _ I'd love it, too. He's an outgoing, fun-loving type of
person. He likes to share his accomplishment with his family and
friends. He doesn't close himself off. I think he's enjoying the
heck out of this and this is what makes him tick.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he did this year compares to two Hall of Famers, Ryne
Sandberg and Andre Dawson. What he's doing this year makes those
guys look like kindergarteners.''
</P>
<P>
   Grace said he didn't know what it will take for Sosa to get the
kind of recognition that McGwire does.
</P>
<P>
   ``I imagine it will be when he hits more home runs than
McGwire,'' said Grace. ``Whoever does that has the record and for
Sammy to get the all-time record, that is what has got to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very strange situation. Whoever thought two guys would
do it? It's been an amazing year. The postseason is where you
shine. Sammy needs to get to the playofffs and he deserves to get
there. It's up to the rest of us to pull our load.''
</P>
<P>
   The people of San Diego tried to do the right thing Monday
night. Sosa was given a glowing introduction and a standing
ovation. But such things, he says, are just icing on the cake of
life. His goal is simple: help the Cubs reach the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``My teammates are 100 percent behind me,'' said Sosa. ``They
know that I try to do my best and help this team reach the
playoffs. That's why the home runs aren't a distraction.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa says his day is coming. He heard from McGwire Monday.
Comissioner Bud Selig, who skipped Sunday's exploits in Chicago
against his Brewers, also checked in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark is still the man,'' said Sosa. ``We are two people who
are working so hard and out chasing history. But we're not enemies.
We have a good relationship. I think that Mark McGwire is one of
the good friends that I have. He called me to congratulate me and
told me to keep going. Let's see how it goes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
