<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-WATERGATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME FIND LESSONS IN WATERGATE FOR CLINTON'S TROUBLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Leonard Garment, who was President Nixon's counsel
during the darkest days of the Watergate scandal and is now keenly
watching President Clinton's impeachment troubles, finds himself
humming the old song, ``Who's Sorry Now?''
</P>
<P>
   Garment, 74, is one of many former Nixon aides watching the
unfolding Clinton saga with a combination of bemusement and
bitterness. Without any prompting, he notes that two of the
``archetypal lawyers'' on the staff of the House Judiciary
Committee in 1974 were Hillary Rodham _ she didn't use the name
Clinton then _ and Bernard Nussbaum, Clinton's former White House
counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Just as the current members of the House Judiciary Committee say
they are reluctantly considering the possibility of impeachment,
Garment said the committee staff and members in 1974 expressed
``all the piety and the sanctimony, that `it breaks our heart to do
this.'''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Garment said, ``We lived in a high-altitude climate of
anger, a world of enemies. They had a sense of mission, not a sense
of justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Fair or not, it is inevitable that comparisons are being made to
Nixon's experience with impeachment proceedings. While there are
major differences between Watergate and Clinton's current
predicament, there are lessons for both the president's defenders
and detractors in what happened during a summer that forever
changed American political life 24 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Representative Henry J. Hyde, the Illinois Republican
who is chairman of the House Judiciary Committee, said last week
that he is using the committee's work in 1974 _ which led to a
bipartisan vote for articles of impeachment against Nixon _ as a
model for dealing with the allegations against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pledge that the same courtesy extended to President Nixon
will be extended to this president,'' Hyde said.
</P>
<P>
   For Clinton, this is not necessarily good news. Republicans hold
a majority in the House and thus are more inclined to vote against
Clinton, just as the Democrats controlled the House in 1974 and
were more likely to vote against Nixon. The move toward approving
the articles of impeachment grew as Nixon lost Republican support,
and the same could happen to Clinton if Democrats start abandoning
him.
</P>
<P>
   While some of the old Nixon hands have bitter memories of the
House Judiciary Committee, one Democrat who served on the panel in
1974 said that Nixon was treated better than Clinton has been so
far.
</P>
<P>
   Former Representative Elizabeth Holtzman, the New York Democrat
who sat on the Judiciary Committee in 1974, said that Hyde already
has dealt unfairly with Clinton by voting for the release of the
independent counsel's report about the president's relationship
with Monica S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``During Watergate, the impeachment effort came about because
the American people demanded it when Richard Nixon had (special
prosecutor) Archibald Cox fired and the attorney general resigned
and the country said, `Enough is enough,''' Holtzman said. ``Here
you have impeachment proceedings being triggered by one person, the
independent counsel, about whom serious questions of conflict of
interest have been raised.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Holtzman said, ``The report is being made public
before the commmittee has a chance to review it. During Watergate,
the House Judiciary bent over backwards to be fair to the
president. We always gave him the benefit of giving us his views.
Here you have a report by a special independent counsel who is
defining impeachable offenses for the country.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not what Holtzman imagined would happen when she helped
write the law that allows an independent counsel to present
evidence of possible impeachable offenses to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am one of the authors of the special prosecutor law, I am
ashamed to say,'' Holtzman said.
</P>
<P>
   The report by independent counsel Kenneth W. Starr highlights
the major difference between the way Congress handled the Clinton
and Nixon cases
</P>
<P>
   During Watergate, a committee led by Senator Sam Ervin of North
Carolina spent much of 1973 investigating and holding hearings into
the allegations against Nixon before the House considered
impeachment. A parade of witnesses testified and were questioned by
Nixon's supporters and opponents on the committee. In the Clinton
case, the witnesses have been questioned _ and in some cases,
compelled to testify _ only in secret before a grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   ``Starr is trying to force the committee's hand and act as if he
is the chairman,'' said former federal prosecutor Bruce Yannett.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the nation has learned about the Lewinsky saga slowly,
through leaks to the news media, until the Friday release of the
Starr report, which was stunning in its lurid detail but lacking in
new blockbuster revelations. If the report doesn't lead to a public
call for Clinton's ouster, the question is whether Congress will
try to mold public opinion through Watergate-style hearings.
</P>
<P>
   If the Watergate experience is a guide, a months-long series of
dramatic hearings could rivet the nation's attention, especially if
new information is revealed about Clinton. Lewinsky, for example,
has uttered barely a word in public. Eventually, she could be
called before a congressional committee and be cross-examined.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the president's secretary, Betty Currie, who
facilitated many of Lewinsky's meetings with Clinton and took
possession of gifts he gave to the former intern, could come under
intense pressure to tell the committee what she knows. Some
Republicans view her potential testimony as the equivalent of that
by John Dean, the former Nixon counsel who delivered up many of
Watergate's more devastating revelations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
