<SLUG> BC-MINN-OPEN-COURT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILD ABUSE CASES OPENED TO PUBLIC IN MINNESOTA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MITCHELL ZUCKOFF  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Her jaw is clenched and her Champion sweatshirt
looks too big, or maybe she just seems to grow smaller when the
state lawyer says her toddler twins recoil at the sight of her.
</P>
<P>
   Under raw fluorescent lights in a cramped courtroom, the state
is hellbent on taking away the twins, permanently. But today the
question for the judge is simply whether the drug-addicted mom with
a violent past should lose her weekly, two-hour, supervised visits.
</P>
<P>
   The case is as sad as it is routine. What is anything but
routine is that this week in a Minnesota courthouse, this family's
worst moments were open to public view.
</P>
<P>
   Testing the time-honored notion that noncriminal cases of child
abuse and neglect should be decided behind closed doors _ away from
the prying eyes of neighbors, the media, and the idly curious _
Minnesota has launched an experiment under which such cases are
being heard in open court, with records open as well.
</P>
<P>
   The three-year pilot program, under way since June, is the
brainchild of the state's highest judge, inspired by her belief
that despite the best efforts of judges and caseworkers and often
the families themselves, too many children are suffering for too
long, and the system isn't accountable.
</P>
<P>
   A catalyst toward turning that belief into action was the
February 1997 death of 3-year-old Desi Irving. Outrage grew when
Minnesotans learned that Desi's abuse by her mother was well known
by several people who did nothing. Unable to gain access to a
closed system, they mistakenly believed that protective service
agencies were already involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a growing assessment by the public that children are
not protected to the extent they should be,'' said Kathleen Blatz,
chief justice of the Minnesota Supreme Court and the program's
driving force. ``With a closed court, nobody with objective eyes
can be present. Your critics are the most helpful to you. They ask
questions like, `Why is nobody representing the child?' They can't
ask those kinds of questions if they aren't allowed to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   But some of those very critics are outraged by Blatz's action.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a misguided way of trying to approach the very
real issue of accountability,'' said Professor Esther Wattenberg,
director of the Center for Advanced Studies in Child Welfare at the
University of Minnesota. She called the court openings ``a deluded
search for a simple solution'' that invades family privacy and
makes it harder to protect children and keep families together.
</P>
<P>
   The protection of children in Minnesota became a matter of
national interest last week after the strangulation deaths of six
children, ages 5 to 11, allegedly by their mother, Khoua Her. The
24-year-old St. Paul woman, a Hmong immigrant who married and had
her first child at 13, was charged with six counts of second-degree
murder.
</P>
<P>
   Child protection agencies said they had no previous contact with
the family, so no one is suggesting that open abuse and neglect
hearings might have somehow prevented the killings. Nevertheless,
the case has focused attention on the open court program, if only
because it is such a horrifying example of cruelty to children.
</P>
<P>
   This week at the Hennepin County Juvenile Justice Center, in the
shadow of the Metrodome, Becky Hoffman faced a state attempt to end
her overnight visits with her 7-year-old and 2-year-old daughters,
who are in foster care.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know who you are. You don't know me. And you come in
here if you want and intrude (on) my family's privacy. That's not
right,'' she said &UR;  &LR; to a reporter. ``Anybody can come in here off
the street, think they know me.''
</P>
<P>
   Judge Pamela G. Alexander, who minutes earlier had granted
Hoffman's request for continued overnight visits, agreed in
principle, noting that such cases often are complex and play out
over extended periods. She said a glance at records, or a visit to
one or two hearings, can leave a skewed impression.
</P>
<P>
   Others have expressed even stronger doubts, focusing on
everything from schoolyard taunts to humiliated families to damaged
future job prospects for children whose worst nightmares are made
public.
</P>
<P>
   ``To open the hearings, I felt, was to allow children to be
re-victimized,'' said Judge Gary J. Meyer, chief judge of the
state's second-largest judicial district, covering eight counties.
``Their names would be in the paper, and people &UR;  &LR; _ neighbors _
would have access to their files. These are children who would not
have any ability to help themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Meyer said a better argument could be made for opening
delinquency hearings, which are still closed to the public, because
at least in those cases the youth offenders did something to
trigger court involvement.
</P>
<P>
   Public defenders, who represent parents in most abuse and
neglect cases, have been almost unanimously opposed to the open
courts. ``Letting the public indulge its morbid curiosity is not
keeping our eye on what is best for the children,'' said Robert
Docherty, public defender in rural Watonwan County.
</P>
<P>
   Blatz responded to the criticism by noting that criminal cases
of neglect and sexual abuse are already prosecuted in open court.
``If a parent rapes a child, those cases are open to the press and
public. Where are the pictures on the news in those cases? The
media and the public have been responsible in those cases,'' she
said, and can be expected to act the same in these.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, in the three months since the pilot program began in 12
of the state's 87 counties, there has been relatively little
attention paid, agreed judges, lawyers, and child advocates. ``My
biggest disappointment is that nobody is coming. There seems to be
very little interest,'' said David Sanders, director of Hennepin
County Children and Family Services.
</P>
<P>
   But others fear that the media will descend en masse at the
first sign of a sensational case. Media leaders say that isn't the
plan. ``We have no intention of holding children and adults up to
ridicule. We're very sensitive about maintaining the privacy of
children whose situations are being scrutinized and adjudicated by
the court,'' said Pam Fine, managing editor of the Minneapolis Star
Tribune.
</P>
<P>
   So far, public notice has been limited to two occasions. Just
after the program started, a judge caused a stir by closing a court
hearing _ as allowed, under special circumstances _ but the next
hearing in the case was open, and no other closures have been
reported. Then US officials briefly threatened to withhold $60
million in funding, citing federal privacy rules that prohibit the
disclosure of information about foster care and child protection
cases. The threat was soon withdrawn and the crisis passed.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota is not the first state to open civil abuse and neglect
hearings; the program is based on a decade-old system in Michigan,
and Minnesota child welfare officials say more than a dozen other
states have taken similar steps, though the trend has yet to reach
New England.
</P>
<P>
   In Michigan, the system has been in place so long it is no
longer an issue, said Judge Freddie Burton Jr., presiding juvenile
judge in Wayne County, which includes Detroit. Unlike Minnesota,
Michigan even allows cameras in juvenile courtrooms, though photos
of children are barred.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever there is secrecy, it breeds suspicion. I think
(opening the courts) has given people confidence in the system,''
Burton said.
</P>
<P>
   Confidence, and hope, were on hand last week in Judge Robert
Blaeser's courtroom, though the only member of the public present
was a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   A pretty, 10-year-old girl in a flowered sundress sat nervously
with her mother and the father of her two half-brothers. Her mom,
with sunken eyes and a collapsed mien, has drug problems that won't
quit. The girl has been a ward of the county. Now, the judge was
being asked to give legal and physical custody to the father of her
two half-brothers.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone assured the judge it was what they wanted, though the
mother's face was drawn and pale. Blaeser quickly approved the
request, and the girl's shoulders sagged with relief. She smiled.
So did the man she calls Daddy. And so did her mother.
</P>
<P>
   It's what passes for a happy ending in these halls.
</P>
<P>
   As for the mom in the Champion sweatshirt, she retained her
weekly visitation. For now, the judge said, setting another court
date.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
