</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW PROPOSALS AREN'T SUCH A SUPER IDEA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The champions of 17 European countries will play this week in
the Champions League, a round-robin event concluding with an
eight-team elimination tournament and finals May 26, 1999. Another
103 teams will be involved in European cups, which provide the
model for soccer competitions world-wide.
</P>
<P>
   The Champions Cup, Cup Winners Cup, and UEFA Cup are open to all
comers, from the most obscure club in the Faroe Islands to the
giants of sport, such as AC Milan. The only qualification is that
places be won on the field.
</P>
<P>
   Those proposing a European Super League would put an end to
this. Rosenborg of Trondheim, Norway, which visits Athletic Bilbao
of Spain Wednesday, certainly would not be included in any Super
League. That is unfortunate, because Rosenborg provided one of the
most shocking upsets in sports history by eliminating Milan two
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   A Super League would not have upsets. Everything would be
predictable. Standards would be high, but what would be the point?
As English Football Association chairman Keith Wiseman said, ``I
don't think the fans in this country would have the slightest
interest in what would be exhibition games. It would be Harlem
Globetrotters stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Sports without upsets, without promotion/relegation, become
increasingly dull. They also become exclusionary activities,
legislating to eliminate potential challengers.
</P>
<P>
   Michel Platini believes a Super League would be ``a disaster''
because it would not provide places for young players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am worried,'' said Platini, president of the France '98
Organizing Committee and FIFA's director of sports, ``because our
sport should not serve the interests of business and television.
With a Super League, they would have clubs without young players in
the team and without programs for young players' development. This
could destroy everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Interviewed by L'Equipe in France, Platini expressed doubt that
such a league actually will be launched.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that the mentalities are ready to accept a
system that puts in danger national championships or national
teams. I believe the big clubs are interested above all in money.
If they can obtain the share of the profits they want, they will be
satisfied and everything will be all right.''
</P>
<P>
   The point is that a Super League would be redundant in Europe.
The Champions League already satisfies this demand, and does so
with precisely the elements that make such a championships
interesting: merit requirements and the possibility for upsets.
</P>
<P>
   There is a chance Rupert Murdoch understands this. For Murdoch,
whose News Corporation is offering $1.06 billion for Manchester
United, sports is a ``battering ram'' to promote his satellite
television ambitions around the world. Manchester United, the most
popular team in Asia, would be the entry into that continent for
Murdoch's Star TV.
</P>
<P>
   Nor would Murdoch have to remove Manchester United from the
Premier League to fulfill this goal. The club's popularity has
little to do with its success. Manchester United retained its
worldwide appeal even when all England clubs were banned from
European competitions.
</P>
<P>
   Super Leagues promoters are basing their campaign on a canard,
that domination and winning are crucial to popularity and success.
Manchester United, which won the European Championship only once _
in 1968 _ proves it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Rock 'n' roll soccer?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Manchester United fans have announced that they have recruited a
rock star to outbid Murdoch, and will announce his identity
Tuesday. This seems unlikely, but the club's board of directors is
obliged to seek a higher bid and Salomon Smith Barney has been
named to do just that.
</P>
<P>
   The marriage of media and sports has caused massive changes to
the way games are conducted in the US. But television has only
minimally invaded soccer throughout the world. A game played in
most countries today lasts 90 minutes, plus a 15-minute halftime,
just as it did 50 years ago. This is the best measure for
guaranteeing optimum athletic performances and fan involvement _
delays and instrusions from off-field factors are minimized.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, television's involvement with sport seems inevitable.
Carlton Communications is on the verge of a $450 million takeover
of Arsenal in England. And the Granada network has been rumored to
be interested in Liverpool.
</P>
<P>
   Electronic media and sport are used for all sorts of purposes,
from selling products to sponsoring ideol-ogies. The hope is that
the integrity of the game and its supporters are respected.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Tough games on tap
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The highlight Champions League games Wednesday are Manchester
United-Barcelona and Real Madrid-Inter in Seville.
</P>
<P>
   Manchester United should have a good chance against Barcelona,
which lost to Maillorca in the Spanish Super Cup and struggled
against Extremadura in a 1-0 victory Saturday. But they are in the
most difficult group, and must visit Bayern Munich Sept. 30.
</P>
<P>
   The top team from the six groups, plus the top two second-place
finishers, qualify for the quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
   This is a difficult week for Real Madrid, which forfeited
home-field advantage after a goal was pulled down by fans in last
year's competition, leading to the suspension of the 100,000-seat
Estadio Santiago Bernabeu. The defending Champions Cup champions
must play Inter, then Barcelona in a league match Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``In four days, you can regain your strength and the whole group
will return fresh,'' said Real Madrid's Dutch coach, Guus Hiddink.
``The problem is that, but the tension, the concentration, the
tactics.''
</P>
<P>
   Real Madrid also will be missing its Brazilian defender, Roberto
Carlos, who is suspended. But they have an adequate replacement _
Robert Jarni, a starter at left back for Croatia in the World Cup.
This illustrates how the rich stay rich and are able to stockpile
talent. It also shows how powerful clubs tend to find foreign help
instead of developing young domestic talent.
</P>
<P>
   This has led to worries in Italy about a decline in standards.
And worries were further fueled when the country's top two young
players, Andrea Pirlo and Nicola Ventola, were purchased by Inter.
But both played strong roles in Inter's rally for a 2-2 tie with
Cagliari in the Serie A opener Sunday. They replaced Youri
Djorkaeff and Roberto Baggio, and combined on both goals after
Inter fell behind, 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see how it would be possible for Ventola to go back to
the bench,'' noted La Gazzetta dello Sport.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
