<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET'S TALK ABOUT LYING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (k and w coding.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- Lying _ yes. Perjury _ no.
</P>
<P>
   Down the first road lies a nonpartisan accommodation to the
principled leadership of people like Senator Joseph Lieberman, the
Connecticut Democrat, who insist that President Clinton's conduct
that is wrong and immoral be subject to a public rebuke while also
taking the view that off the evidence that is known, talk of
impeachment or resignation is unwise and unjust.
</P>
<P>
   Down the second road lies a partisan insistence on the political
death penalty, which will produce a partisan defense against a
charge that cannot be proved in an adversary proceeding. It will
also produce months of ugly and disgusting proceedings that are
more likely to infuriate Americans of all persuasions than produce
a consensus for action that can withstand the stern test of
history.
</P>
<P>
   If it's about lying, we can talk. More than that, the case can
almost certainly be settled in a way that condemns the president's
behavior while respecting the country's solidly anti-impeachment
majority.
</P>
<P>
   But if it is insisted that we talk about the crime called
perjury, there will be a fight, with virtually no chance of a
widely accepted result.
</P>
<P>
   It should be clear by now that the president is prepared to
acknowledge more than his horrid behavior, that to keep his sexual
encounters with Monica Lewinsky secret he did something all of us
can understand in English as lying.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not clear yet to the country that perjury is a crime
that encompasses far more than lying, and far more than the facts
as known in the case will support.
</P>
<P>
   That will change.
</P>
<P>
   For now, most politicians and press commentators are lazily
sliding past the issue by confusing lying with perjury, and
ridiculing Clinton's lawyers for pointing out distinctions that are
central to hundreds of years of legal history and tradition. They
easily score political points.
</P>
<P>
   However, that momentary advantage is trumped by the card the
Clinton side can eventually play with a vengeance. At some point,
the sound bites about hair-splitting will be irrelevant and the job
will fall to somebody to prove perjury with evidence and witnesses.
And that simply cannot be done in this case without flouting some
precious principles that protect individuals from the long arm of
an irresponsible state.
</P>
<P>
   From Ken Starr's report and the two rebuttals by the president's
lawyers, it is clear that the core of the assertions of perjury in
Clinton's Jan. 17 deposition in the Paula Jones lawsuit and his
Aug. 17 testimony to Starr's grand jury is the allegation that the
president aroused Lewinsky sexually. Both sides agree that if he
did, that conduct falls within the tortured definition of sex
proposed by the Paula Jones lawyers and modified by the trial
judge.
</P>
<P>
   That allegation, for obvious reasons, comes only from Lewinsky,
and it is denied by the president in his Aug. 17 testimony.
</P>
<P>
   To proceed, the House Judiciary (and perhaps some months from
now the Senate in a trial) would have to produce Lewinsky to
testify about sex acts in even more detail than was gratuitously
summarized ad nauseam in Starr's report. And this testimony, unlike
her grand jury appearances, would include cross-examination and
other testimony putting her credibility in question _ which eight
months of madness around here has indicated is the size of Mt.
Everest.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, one of the basic elements of the US law of perjury is
that one witness doesn't make a case _ that at least one
independent form of corroboration, meaning it could stand
regardless of whether the other witness existed, is required.
</P>
<P>
   This is not hair-splitting. It is part of British and American
tradition to keep that state from using perjury as a back-door
means of getting ``something'' on a target or as a form of illegal
entrapment.
</P>
<P>
   For the same reason, it is settled US law that perjury is not a
strictly accurate statement that nonetheless implies something that
is false or masks the full truth; nor is perjury any answer to a
question found to be vague or convoluted such as the Jones lawyers'
sex query; nor is an incomplete answer perjury because the burden
is properly on the questioner to follow up.
</P>
<P>
   The classic illustration in the Clinton case is his lawyer, Bob
Bennett's entreaty to his Jones counterparts in the deposition:
``Why don't they ask the president what he did, what he didn't do,
and then we can argue in court later about what it means?'' They
never did. And yet, it is obvious that the president did not just
behave immorally, he lied.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge for grownups should not be to play perjury games
for another year, but to settle this case with the admission and
public rebuke that would make the sanction fit the offense and
produce not only justice but the ending the public ardently
desires.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
