<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPEN-ROAD-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOU CAN'T TOP THIS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NATHAN COBB  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rick Mahoney believes that most people have it wrong about
folks, himself included, who drive convertibles. They think we
lower our tops to let the sun shine in, he says. Which is wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about the sun,'' Mahoney pointed out one recent
afternoon as he relaxed behind the wheel of his 1990 BMW at
Wollaston Beach in Quincy, across the harbor from Boston. ``It's
about the sky.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it's about a lot of things. But Mahoney, a freelance
visual consultant who owns two other convertibles, knows that many
people look at a retractable top and see only a bad hair day.
They'd rather ride in a fully enclosed, climate-controlled box,
where the sounds and smells of the roadway _ and yes, the sky _ are
kept outside.
</P>
<P>
   But the convertible won't go away. Thirty-four models are on the
market this year, and so far they represent about 3.3 percent of
new passenger car sales. That may not sound like much, especially
when compared with the 7 percent figure of the early 1960s, but
don't forget that topless sales increased 11.4 percent last year
and 20.4 percent the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   Especially don't forget that the convertible nearly expired a
quarter of a century ago. During that dark hour, amid concerns
about auto safety and street crime, the Big Three US automakers
actually stopped making the toys of summer. There was even a novel
titled ``The Last Convertible.''
</P>
<P>
   But toplessness was reborn during the 1980s, first on the wheels
of Chrysler's K-car and later on Mazda's Miata. Now you see
convertibles at the beach, the mall, the PTO meeting, everywhere.
(But remember this: No self-respecting convertible owner refers to
his or her car as a ``ragtop,'' and hasn't since about 1958.)
</P>
<P>
   For Fred Taylor, convertibles never went away. It was as a
teenager back in the 1940s that Taylor, now a Boston music
producer, convinced his mother that what she really needed was a
Chevrolet convertible. A decade later he was able to purchase his
own Chevy, a classic '57 Bel Air, which began a string of five
topless cars. (Taylor concedes that he does not part with
automobiles easily, having owned them as long as 15 years.)
``Nothing has ever made me feel like the next car I buy would be an
enclosed car,'' he says, spitting out the last two words as if they
were the name of an ancient enemy.
</P>
<P>
   Like most owners of convertibles, Taylor does not easily put
into sentences the pleasures derived from driving a car without a
top. He talks about the ``openness'' of the experience, as do we
all. But he begins to cut to the core when he says: ``It's just ...
it's almost like you're walking. You're looking up at things, down
at things, sideways at things. You're more aware of what's going on
around you.''
</P>
<P>
   There's one other thing, adds Taylor: ``You can get a tan going
somewhere in a convertible. You don't have to actually be there.''
</P>
<P>
   But if there's one word that the serious owners of convertibles
inevitably fall back on, it is this: freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Meaning?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not easy to explain,'' sighs Goldie Muise, a postal clerk
who owns both a 1976 Chevrolet Corvette and a 1980 Ford Mustang
convertible. ``You don't feel like you're closed up inside a metal
crate. And there's a feeling of living to the fullest, of really
being able to enjoy life.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, people notice when we drive our convertibles. They
notice Oscar Guardado, a 24-year-old landscaper, and not just
because he recently had his 1989 Mustang painted a color that can
only be described as orange-on-orange. Or because the convertible's
trunk is chock full of heart-stopping sub-woofers.
</P>
<P>
   They even notice Guardado when he parks his car at Revere Beach
and sits proudly atop the seawall behind it. ``So many girls ask
me, `Take me for a ride, take me for a ride,''' he says, beaming.
``And some people stop and say, `Hey, you want to sell it?' But I
say, `No, it's my toy.' I call it `my honey.' And my girlfriend
says, `Oh, your car's your honey?' But she doesn't want me to sell
it either.''
</P>
<P>
   It cannot be statistically proven, but it appears likely that,
like Taylor, we convertible owners keep our cars longer than
non-convertible owners. There's some kind of mystical connection
between driver and car that can't be found with a sedan, a station
wagon, or _ God forbid _ an SUV. Dr. Richard Sullivan, who has
owned his 1959 Triumph TR3 for 14 years, talks about driving being
a more ``active'' process with the top down. ``You're more part of
the experience of driving,'' he contends. ``It's like riding a
horse. I truly, truly love doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in the 1950s and 1960s, Sullivan had several friends who
owned convertibles but who eventually abandoned the genre. ``I
guess they grew up,'' he notes sadly. Actually, the auto industry
feels that the principal customers for convertibles are not young
people, but older folks with the cash to buy them. They're seen as
``reward'' cars for hard-working baby boomers, or as midlife-crisis
cars for folks grappling with middle age. ``Image enhancers'' is
how George Pipas, Ford Motor Co.'s sales analysis manager,
describes them.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe, just maybe, convertibles are coming back simply
because they're fun to drive. That's what Jennifer Jacobs, a
20-year-old medical assistant _ no midlife crisis there _
discovered in April when she bought a 1996 Chrysler Sebring
convertible. At the time, Jacobs's idea of letting in the sky
consisted of purchasing a car with a sunroof. But she talked
herself into the real deal instead, and now the first thing she
does when she leaves work in the evening is put the top down.
</P>
<P>
   Like the rest us who drive convertibles, Jacobs is hooked. This
may be her first topless car, she declares, but it won't be her
last. ``I don't think,'' she says from behind the wheel, ``that I
could get used to a regular car after this.''
</P>
<P>
   Who could?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-98 1323EDT &QL; 
