<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SURFING-ELDERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GRAY-BEARDS OF SURFING. 
</HEADLINE>
   (l and s coding)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI DOTEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE COMPTON, R.I. _ Some folks pray for hurricanes, not
little storms with just a puff of breath in them. But mighty
tempests that can climb up the East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   The annual hurricane season prompts great glee among local
hard-core surfers. Not so much among the teenagers who surf after
school or on weekends, but among the middle-aged men who have been
obsessed with riding the waves for years and have lifestyles that
allow them to drop everything when the surf's up.
</P>
<P>
   These are men who, despite the march of time, the loss of hair,
and the growth of families, just won't let go of the surfer life,
no matter what.
</P>
<P>
   ``A bad day of surf is better than a bad day at work,'' says
Bill Gramm, 47, who's been riding the waves for decades. Despite
having two small children at home, he admits he has no plans to
stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all these years, every wave is still thrilling,'' says
Chris Kyricos, 46.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike surfers in Hawaii who can walk out their back doors on
any given day and find the swells they need, surfers along the East
Coast must be a patient lot. They can wait weeks, even months, for
strong surf to be up.
</P>
<P>
   There hadn't been good waves since March, so recent hurricanes
brought the network to life along the coast as surfers tuned in to
weather channels, shared information on the Internet, blocked out
free time for riding their boards, and talked to the dawn patrol
daily before heading out. The patrol is made up of surfers who
check out conditions at various beaches along the coast and then
use their cell phones to call other surfers about prevailing
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   In this area, the best waves are usually in Little Compton.
</P>
<P>
   That's where Gramm, Kyricos, and two other longtime surfer
buddies have been heading when the storms blow in. All four have
built lives that allow them to surf. Gramm co-owns a lumberyard in
Wareham, Mass. with his sister. Kyricos, of Cohasset, Mass., is a
consultant. Sean Egan, 40, of Hull, Mass., is a carpenter and
contractor, and Glen Riley, 35, also of Hull, is a musician and
house painter.
</P>
<P>
   They all sat down recently for lunch at the Common's Lodge
restaurant here before heading out for an afternoon of surfing.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the first good waves of the summer,'' says Riley,
who's divorced and has a son. He heads south during the winter
months to surf. ``I've traveled to Barbados, Mexico, and Puerto
Rico to surf. What keeps me coming back here is my son.''
</P>
<P>
   A passion for surfing can wreak havoc on a marriage,
particularly over time. Fortunately, Gramm and Kyricos have very
understanding wives.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife knows that surfing makes me happy and if she wants a
happy man around the house, she's got to understand that this is
what I want to do,'' says Gramm.
</P>
<P>
   What causes the most havoc is that the winds are so
unpredictable that a surfer cannot plan ahead. So there are times
of tension when the surf's up and there's a family wedding or other
gathering that has been planned for months and the pull of the
waves wins out over family.
</P>
<P>
   For Gramm, the fever started early. When he was growing up there
were four surf shops in Hull.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a rebellious, counterculture lifestyle, and there were
drugs involved,'' says Gramm. ``But it was all about freedom _
freedom to hang out on the beach and ride the waves. Surfing's very
physical. I stay in shape to surf. But you really can't take it all
too seriously. I mean the last stretch of waves was in March.''
</P>
<P>
   Gramm sometimes leaves his house at 5 in the morning, surfs for
three hours and then heads to the lumberyard for a day's work. He
owns five boards of various sizes and weights _ the larger the
wave, the longer the board needed.
</P>
<P>
   Egan says surfing is never boring because each wave is
different. There is so much mass involved in each wave that a
surfer must move as fast as the wave is moving through the water.
That is the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Kyricos agrees that the sensation of riding a wave never
diminishes. ``There's so much involved,'' says Kyricos. ``No other
sport has you interacting with such a variety of forces. It's a
matter of kinetics _ the forward and downward motions, the effects
of gravity and the winds. It's about putting oneself against the
earth's energy.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides the waves in Little Compton, the men enjoy the
comradeship of local surfers there because they aren't aggressive,
publicity-seeking hotshots like some they've encountered in Newport
or California.
</P>
<P>
   The men will surf all year if conditions permit _ they all have
wetsuits and wax for every kind of water temperature. They say that
what helped advance the sport in the '70s was the board leash that
is worn around the ankle and prevents a board from flying loose
when a surfer wipes out or ``kicks out'' (exits) the wave.
</P>
<P>
   And they all agree they are frequently scared. ``A wave is such
an unyielding, relentless mass and has its own agenda,'' says
Kyricos. ``The ocean has to be respected because a wave has the
ability to pulverize you when you wipe out.''
</P>
<P>
   Lunch is finished, and the no-longer-young surfers pile into a
van. They choose a spot away from other surfers and paddle out to
meet the waves. The ``session'' lasts several hours. The winds
aren't good, and the waves are relatively small. But better some
surf than none.
</P>
<P>
   They pile into the van again and head for another spot. They
surf until dark.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I was in the water a total of six or seven hours,''
says Gramm. ``Not bad for a 47-year-old man.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
