A5886 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTHOR-MERULLO-BOS &LR;      09-15 1115
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-MERULLO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROLAND MERULLO LOOKS HOMEWARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KENNEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   REVERE, Mass. _ It is a crisp morning, and Roland Merullo is
sitting in one of the pavilions along the shore, there to talk
about his new novel, ``Revere Beach Boulevard.''
</P>
<P>
   There are more sea gulls than people on the beach, and there is
a cool onshore breeze. But Merullo _ like any son of Revere
returning for a day _ wants to go for a swim.
</P>
<P>
   ``You didn't bring a suit, did you?'' he asks somewhat
plaintively. Deprived of a dip, he settles for the other thing one
does at Revere Beach: going for a roast beef sandwich at Kelly's.
</P>
<P>
   Merullo, author of two well-received novels set far from Revere
_ one in Micronesia, the other in Russia _ has now returned home,
novelistically, and with a vengeance. ``Revere Beach Boulevard,''
published this month by Henry Holt, is the first book in a
projected Revere Beach trilogy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could write 50,000 pages set in Revere,'' Merullo says. And
you believe him.
</P>
<P>
   At one point in his book, Merullo speaks through the
protagonist's sister, a Boston television news anchor, and writes:
``Once I actually reached the city, once I left the highway,
circled down the exit ramp, and began making my way through the
tired streets, the fake little gem of my Boston life seemed to drop
out of sight. The rain stopped as I turned onto Proctor Avenue. I
drove up the familiar street, past the familiar house fronts
standing tight together, and felt myself moving deep into a
darkness that swallowed everything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Merullo, 45, lives now in Conway, with his wife, Amanda, a
photographer _ she took the photo of Revere Beach at twilight on
the novel's jacket _ and their 8-month-old daughter, Alexandra. But
his family _ mother, two brothers, and a clan of uncles, aunts, and
cousins _ still lives in Revere, where he grew up. He insists that
the characters portrayed in ``Revere Beach Boulevard'' are
fictional, but the city is a character as important as any.
</P>
<P>
   The central figure, something of an offstage narrator, is pastor
at St. Anthony's, an imposing Romanesque building with a campanile
towering over American Legion Highway _ and the Catholic church
where Merullo's grandparents worshiped.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think what a priest's life must be like in a town like this,''
Merullo says. ``Walking down the street, seeing people with the
secrets he carries around in his head.''
</P>
<P>
   Driving around the city, Merullo points out the house a block or
two off Shirley Avenue. It's the house that he imagines the book's
protagonist, a real estate agent addicted to gambling and in hock
to Mafia loan sharks, has been ordered to torch.
</P>
<P>
   And on Proctor Street, where Merullo attended elementary school,
he points out the small ranch-type house where he imagines the
story begins _ the house that inspired the novel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really struggling with a book that I still haven't
finished,'' Merullo says. ``I was having a horrible time, two, 2
1/2 years of real frustration.'' So on the strength of having just
been hired to teach at Bennington College, he put the book aside
(although it may resurface later in the trilogy) and took off with
his wife for a vacation in Florence.
</P>
<P>
   But just before leaving, Merullo recalls, he had ``a very
powerful, very visceral sense of one moment. An old Italian guy
sitting in his back yard, watching the moon come up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew the yard,'' Merullo says, ``and I knew the guy, a very
humble, simple old Italian guy who drove my father to his tailor
shop in the North End and would also come and prune our
grapevines.''
</P>
<P>
   With that strong image in mind, Merullo took a stack of yellow
legal pads to Italy. By the time he returned, he had written 179
pages in longhand of what became ``Revere Beach Boulevard.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``old Italian guy'' became Vito, father of Peter, the
gambling-addicted real estate agent. In the novel, his wife is
dying of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Near the beginning of ``Revere Beach Boulevard,'' Merullo
writes, in Vito's voice, ``Before the phone call came that would
take my life and turn her inside out like the sleeve on a jacket, I
was sitting in the yard with the woman I had been husband and wife
with 49 years, the woman who was the other half of my body. We were
waiting for the moon to come up over Patsy Antonelli's roof. Big,
she would be coming up. You could tell by the light between the
houses that she would be coming up big on that night, the full
circle of her, the full, perfect face.
</P>
<P>
   ```Do you feel any pain, Lucy?' I asked my wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``And she said `No,' quiet, in a voice that meant don't keep
asking, Vito. So I didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Merullo's first novel, ``Leaving Losapas,'' published in 1991,
grew out of an illness-shortened tour with the Peace Corps in
Micronesia. His second novel, ``A Russian Requiem,'' published two
years later, drew on his studies in Russian literature at Brown
University and a stint with the US Information Agency in Moscow.
Both books were hailed as the work of a writer to watch.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the three novels, there have been a number of freelance
nonfiction projects, the most memorable a series on the 1996
presidential primaries for The Philadelphia Inquirer.
</P>
<P>
   From that assignment, Merullo recalls vividly a drive from Bob
Dole's Kansas to Bill Clinton's Arkansas, stopping to ask people
what words came to mind when he mentioned the names of the
candidates _ and being ``shocked at the vitriol directed at
Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   Merullo, who teaches English literature one semester a year at
Bennington, speaks analytically of his own writing.
</P>
<P>
   Some readers have found confusing Merullo's device of using a
number of first-person narrators _ Peter, his sister Joanie, their
parents, a Revere policeman, among others _ to tell the story of
``Revere Beach Boulevard.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I really worked hard to get the voices to be consistent and to
be different _ as much as possible with people from the same family
and the same town,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   But while he thinks that ``when people talk, they do reveal
something about themselves that they don't know they are
revealing,'' he says that the first-person narrator _ especially a
townful of them _ ``handcuffs the writer. There's so much that
people, especially people who aren't very introspective, just don't
say about themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   For a writer, he says, ``it's like writing with one hand tied
behind you'' and, he adds firmly, ``I'll never use multiple
first-person narrators again.''
</P>
<P>
   But he is firmly committed to the idea of a trilogy. ``There's a
lot of hubris there,'' he admits, ``but I'm not worried.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
