<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-PARENTING-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSERVATIVE COUPLE PENS STRATEGIES FOR PROTECTING KIDS'
CHILDHOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN MARSHALL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MERCER ISLAND, Wash. _ Meet the Medveds _ not the usual family
next door these days.
</P>
<P>
   They watch no television whatsoever, no news, no sports, not
even any public broadcasting specials, and the three Medved
children are permitted to only watch six hours of parent-approved
videos each week.
</P>
<P>
   The two parents also have personally screened all their
children's playmates ``from the earliest ages'' to make sure they
are not the sort to exhibit inappropriate behavior that might
provide unwanted peer influences. And an occasional spanking is
sometimes employed to provide discipline in the Medved household.
</P>
<P>
   ``We resist the argument that spanking is, by definition,
abusive,'' says Michael Medved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spanking,'' adds Diane Medved, ``is just one more tool in an
arsenal of disciplinary tactics, although we certainly do not do it
in any fit of anger.''
</P>
<P>
   The Medveds, who live in a spacious view home with a swimming
pool on Mercer Island, also are rigorous in the observance of their
Jewish faith, eating only Kosher foods and refraining from all
regular activities on the sabbath (including driving, cooking,
talking on the phone or turning on electrical devices).
</P>
<P>
   But however unlike other families the Medveds may be, they
firmly believe that far more parents would follow their example, or
at least part of it, if they just understood that it was an option.
</P>
<P>
   So the two Medveds have stepped smartly into the societal fray
to provide ``empowering'' support for parents from a couple with
established credentials. The Medveds are nationally known
conservatives, he as a film critic and a host of a syndicated radio
talk show that originates at KVI-AM in Seattle, she as host of a
multimedia show on the Internet, as a clinical psychologist with a
half-time private practice in her home and as a writer of several
books (including one on the American family co-written with former
Vice President Dan Quayle).
</P>
<P>
   Their prescription for parents is outlined in the Medveds' new
book, ``Saving Childhood: Protecting Our Children From the National
Assault on Innocence'' (HarperCollins, 324 pages, $24). This is an
unlikely and sometimes jarring mix of a parenting volume. It starts
with 200 pages of angry political diatribe and horror stories about
permissive and intrusive societal forces today. Then it follows
with 100 pages of heartfelt parenting advisories and strategies for
keeping kids as kids, at least a little while longer, with many
examples drawn from the Medveds' own experience raising 11-year-old
Sarah, 9-year-old Shayna and 6-year-old Danny.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter what their political affiliation, everyone in
America wants to have a conservative family,'' stresses Diane
Medved, 47.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of conservatives make the mistake of thinking that only
conservatives have conservative family values,'' adds Michael
Medved, 49. ``But no parent, no matter how partisan, wants to raise
kids that grow up to be like Bill Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   The Medveds' book has more boogeymen than a Goosebumps book by
R.L. Stine (another prohibited entity in the Medved household).
They zap everything from Power Rangers dolls to children who do not
know etiquette to ``the disastrous experiment in forced busing'' to
a society ``obsessed with the importance of self-esteem.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Medveds reserve their strongest salvos for what they
consider the most odious transgressors against childhood today:
</P>
<P>
   _ The mass media, with their purveying of frightening images,
graphic violence and casual sleaze.
</P>
<P>
   ``Call us elitist, self-righteous, self-appointed preservers of
our culture,'' write the Medveds, ``but hey, TV is goo.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The schools, with their graphic programs aimed at warning
children against adult dangers (sex, disease, drugs, strangers),
programs introduced at ages far younger than, the Medveds believe,
average children are ever likely to encounter such things.
</P>
<P>
   ``Schools,'' write the Medveds, ``teach children to worry.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Other children, who exert peer pressure with their rudeness
toward adults, their absence of moral behavior and their pursuit of
such dangerous fads as materialism, gothic cults and body piercing
and tattooing.
</P>
<P>
   ``A tattoo or brand,'' write the Medveds, ``is a permanent
statement that innocence is over.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Parents themselves, with their lazy abdication of the
responsibility for discipline and morality, are pushing kids into
too many choices about too many activities and showering them with
too many material goods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents would serve their children better,'' write the
Medveds, ``if they emphasized happiness over achievement, and
goodness over goodies.''
</P>
<P>
   The Medveds themselves are not immune from the dilemmas,
compromises and contradictions that bedevil their fellow baby
boomers as parents.
</P>
<P>
   At one point in their book, the Medveds include themselves among
``concerned parents of public school students,'' but this month is
the first time that all three Medved children have spent even
partial time in public schools after being educated exclusively at
home with hired teachers (in Seattle) or in private Jewish day
schools (in California).
</P>
<P>
   The Medveds, an openly affectionate couple, are particularly
critical about the effects of divorce today _ one of Diane Medved's
earlier books is ``The Case Against Divorce.'' But both Medveds are
on their second marriage, although neither had children previously.
</P>
<P>
   The Medveds have zealously guarded their children from the
excesses of MTV and current rock music, only to have their younger
daughter mention, to their horror, that she knew the names of the
Spice Girls. That unwelcome knowledge turned out to have come from
what she heard during her time in a group that Diane Medved has
long supported, the Girl Scouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to erase her mind,'' Diane Medved relates. ``But
by showing shock about such a thing (as the Spice Girls) that shows
her that it is not something I approve of. She gets the message, as
opposed to my just saying, `Oh, that's cool.' I talk a lot with her
about how I want her to remain my little girl. ... I know I cannot
keep her in the dark forever, but it should be a slow, gradual
process.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Medveds, who argue so strenuously about the need to
shield children from the damaging effects of the mass media (of
which they happen to be a part), do allow their children to listen
to talk radio, including their father's show, even at a time when
much political discussion there might once have been considered
X-rated.
</P>
<P>
   Which may be one reason why Sarah approached her father recently
and inquired, ``What's oral sex?''
</P>
<P>
   To which he replied, ``Do you really want to know? I don't think
you're going to like what you hear.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I do want to know,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK. It has to do with mouth-genital contact.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do normal people do that?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not prohibited in the Torah. But it's not normal to do
that with somebody you're not married to.''
</P>
<P>
   So it may not be too surprising that the Medveds _ amid their
recommendations for reading to children, imbuing patriotism,
teaching manners, honoring parents, preserving optimism, telling
Bible stories, sharing family dinners _ also evidence a fondness
for times gone by.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Ozzie and Harriet Nelson's life was celebrated rather
than scorned, TV messages championed rather than detracted from
wholesome ideals,'' the Medveds write. ``In days when women enjoyed
being home for the kids, peers came over for basketball in the
driveway and homemade lemonade rather than scattering for
unsupervised explorations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe `the old days' before the social changes of the '60s
weren't perfect, but they allowed a bevy of family-friendly forces
to surround parents with encouragement for their mission: to honor
God, country and family, to use that white picket fence to keep out
threats to childhood, and keep loved ones close at hand.''
</P>
</TEXT>
