<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMER-SWING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATTERS NEED MORE THAN BRAWN TO HIT HOMERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ULYSSES TORASSA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ After the ball leaves the pitcher's hand at 90
mph, home run kings Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa have only a
fraction of a second to put their muscles in gear, bring the bat
over the plate and connect dead-on with enough force to send it
over the fence.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire and Sosa have set the sporting world on its ear this
season with their awesome displays of hitting prowess, each topping
Roger Maris' single-season record of 61 homers. But it's not just a
matter of raw power: The tolerances are so minute that many
consider hitting a major league home run the most difficult feat in
all of sports.
</P>
<P>
   It involves everything from strong muscles to razor-sharp
reflexes and the ability to judge the speed and direction of a ball
well before it makes its way to the plate, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   And the muscles involved aren't just in the shoulders and upper
arms.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire, who plays for the St. Louis Cardinals, and Sosa, who's
on the Chicago Cubs, also call on their torso, hips and legs to
help move the bat at speeds approaching 70 mph. A right-handed
hitter's left leg alone will absorb 1.2 times his body weight when
he lunges for a pitch, said Duane Knudson, a biomechanics expert
and assistant professor at California State University at Chico.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he knelt down and just swung with his upper body, he
wouldn't do nearly so well,'' Knudson said. By including the other
muscles and the power they generate in the swing, ``you get quite a
bit of bat speed.''
</P>
<P>
   When it collides with a fastball, the bat creates 1,500 pounds
of force and sends the ball flying at 110 mph to 120 mph.
</P>
<P>
   But just any bodybuilder off the street wouldn't be able to
connect with a big-league pitch. A batter also has to know just
where the ball is heading and the exact moment to unleash his
swing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't pay them for their bodies, we pay them for their
minds,'' said A. Terry Bahill, co-author of ``Keep Your Eye on the
Ball: The Science and Folklore of Baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When that pitch is coming in, they have to predict where the
ball is going to be when it comes across the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   The swing itself takes just 150 milliseconds. And with pitches
arriving in less than half a second, it has been calculated that a
swing that is more than 10 milliseconds too soon or too late will
result in a pop-up or a ground out, leaving only the slimmest
window for the sweet spot of the bat to do its magic, Knudson said.
</P>
<P>
   He likens the skill to typing or walking _ complex, fast-moving
muscle coordinations that become second nature after many, many
repetitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have batting practice every day, and they just get better
and better at it,'' Knudson said.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball legend Ted Williams said he could actually see the ball
connect with his bat. But could he track it all the way from the
mound? No way, said Louis Dell'Osso, an eye movement specialist and
professor at Case Western Reserve University in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   The eye can track a fastball for only the first 15 to 20 feet,
Dell'Osso said. Then the batter has to switch his gaze to the plate
and wait the other one- to two-tenths of a second for it to whiz
by. Even with a slow pitch of 60 mph, ``anything inside 15 feet of
home plate, you can't track.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The ball is less than halfway to the plate when the batter has
to decide to look where the ball is going. He has to guess where
the ball is going to be, and the pitcher is trying to fool him,''
Dell'Osso said. ``The ball can do a lot of things in those last 30
to 40 feet, and you've already had to make your decision.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The weight of the bat also factors into a slugger's ability to
send the ball fast and far. A lighter bat travels faster, but
delivers less mass at impact, said Bahill, a professor of systems
engineering at the University of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most batters do better with lighter-weight bats, but a few
will do better with heavier ones,'' said Bahill, who has
exhaustively studied bat weight and performance data. He also
consulted with the San Francisco Giants in 1989, offering advice to
the club on which players should use heavier or lighter bats. The
team won the National League pennant that year.
</P>
<P>
   In general, taller players do better with heavier bats, but the
results are highly variable, and individual testing is required to
come up with a person's ideal bat weight, Bahill said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
