<HEADER>
A5901 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-MANSON-BOS &LR;      09-15 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-MANSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANSON'S `ANIMALS' OFFERS BEASTLY WORLDVIEW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Go ahead. Play the word association game with a teenage boy who
is into rock and heavy metal. You say ``Led'' and he'll say
``Zeppelin.'' But if you say ``Manson,'' dollars to dimes, he'll
respond ``Marilyn.''
</P>
<P>
   We have come to this: The nation's most-notorious Manson is
Marilyn, not Charles.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie, the war-monger wannabe in hippie's clothing, made a
career of evil. Marilyn, the nihilistic rock star as androgynous
cadaver, has made a career singing about evil. Marilyn Manson's got
the media at his fingertips. At the MTV Music Awards last week,
Manson appeared draped in leopard skin with his bare butt _ or a
prosthetic _ hanging out. Also, this boy who was initially named
Brian Warner, boasted plastic, nipple-free breasts. He's always
cast himself as a quasi-alien being or a mutant-of-the-monster. Now
_ and on the cover of Manson's new album, ``Mechanical Animals''
(Nothing) _ he adds this fillip of provocative disturbing
(a)sexuality. Poor Charlie is still in the can, working his
website.
</P>
<P>
   The new disc by Manson and his merry men _ guitarist/bassist
Twiggy Ramirez, synthist Madonna Wayne Gacy, drummer Ginger Fish _
is in shops today. (Well, some shops. Wal-Mart has once again
passed.) The followup to Manson's mainstream breakthrough,
``Antichrist Superstar,'' ``Mechanical Animals'' was co-produced by
Manson and Michael Beinhorn (Soundgarden, Hole). Beinhorn knows a
few things about sculpting rough sounds for maximum mainstream
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Figuratively speaking, glitter-era David Bowie, the original
cracked actor, was hovering over the whole project. It's as if
Bowie said, ``Take what I did with `Ziggy Stardust' and `Diamond
Dogs' and make it gnarlier, nastier.'' As such, Manson has dyed his
hair flaming chartreuse, and he's been infected by the glam vibe.
``I'm just a boy playing the suicide king,'' Manson sings on title
cut. (``You're just a rock 'n' roll suicide?'' Bowie might answer.)
On ``Rock is Dead,'' Manson sings about the numbing insularity and
isolation of stardom _ another Bowie theme from ``Ziggy Stardust.''
</P>
<P>
   The swaggering first single, ``The Dope Show'' is more of a nod
in T.Rex's direction. It swings like a pendulum and clanks like a
jail-guitar door. Manson has called it a ``We Are the World'' for
dopers, and he's right. It's a slippery, sleazy rock anthem, all
rebellion, damnation and self-exploitation. Manson is obsessed by
the dark side of stardom _ ``Show me the dead stars, all of them
sing,'' he sings in ``Posthuman,'' capping the song with ``All that
gilteres is cold, all the glitters is cold.'' Manson has gone to
Hollywood _ his new home is in Laurel Canyon _ and he cavorts with
a higher level of rock star peer. But he finds still finds rot and
decay wherever he looks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mechanical Animals,'' is, without question, a melodic kick
upwards from ``Antichrist Superstar,'' just as that album was a
kick up from the group's first two CDs, ``Smells Like Children''
and ``Portrait of an American Family.'' Manson's previous work had
more of an industrial/techno grind to it. The image was total shock
treatment. This album is more guitar-stoked, more hook-based and,
thankfully, less dependent on the Manson vocal hiss. But the
worldview is still harsh and nihilistic, albeit the focus more
inwardly directed. This is a my-world-and-welcome-to-it album, and
it's about as peachy keen as you'd expect. Manson mixes hedonism
and self-flagellation. Sex is never fun; it's messy or forced, an
ugly embrace. The drug scene is omnipresent, somewhere between a
stimulus, a backdrop and a scourge. Manson presents himself as both
the user and the used, the spitter and the spitoon.
</P>
<P>
   About the happiest Manson allows himself to get is in
``Fundamentally Loathsome,'' where he wants to ``wake up in your
white sun'' _ but, essentially, he's really just trying to attain
the state of being comfortably numb, to borrow from Pink Floyd.
(Manson also borrows from Pink Floyd in terms of texture and dark
grandeur.) In ``I Want to Disappear'' he proclaims himself
``vacant,'' ``a whore.'' In ``New Model No. 15,'' he begins by
singing ``I'm as fake as a wedding cake.''
</P>
<P>
   As has been said before, Marilyn Manson is Alice Cooper for the
end of the century _ but with more venom. There was a smile under
Cooper's makeup. Manson hasn't let us glimpse that yet. His guard
is up and his aim is truly corrosive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
