u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-HEARTS-BOS &LR;      09-15 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-HEARTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXAMINING THE BLOODSHED OF BOSNIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
HEARTS GROWN BRUTAL 
Sagas of Sarajevo 
By Roger Cohen 
Random House, 523 pp., illustrated, $27.95 
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even as the Starr Report threatened to bring the world to a
grinding halt, another drumbeat of ominous reports persisted in the
back pages of last week's newspapers. Busloads of Albanian women
fled western Kosovo, dragging their tattered suitcases, weeping.
Men of fighting age were scarce in this province of the former
Yugoslavia, feared ``cleansed'' from the ethnic population. Former
US senator Bob Dole, now heading the International Commission for
Missing Persons in the Bosnian and Croatian Wars, called it a
``humanitarian catastrophe in the making.''
</P>
<P>
   Like presidential indiscretion, this news was hardly new. And
after all, this is the Balkans. This is the region where in 1992,
writes author Roger Cohen, ``rather than confront the genocide, an
attempt was made to pretend it was not happening.'' This is a place
long misunderstood, and often ignored, but within the pages of
``Hearts Grown Brutal'' lies a sweeping account of the Bosnian war
that dissects every official excuse and breathes anguish into every
statistic. At the same time, it shines a heartbreaking spotlight on
the conflict at hand.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen weaves his central conviction _ that early US involvement
could have prevented the bloodshed in Bosnia _ through the stories
of four families. Each embodies the ethnic complexities of
Yugoslavia; each is destroyed by the war's end. After looking down
on the city of Sarajevo from the surrounding hills, from the
vantage point of the Serbian gunners, Cohen identifies the Bosnian
targets below with unnerving precision. There is Muris Zecevic, a
secular Muslim, shelled to death before his brother's eyes; there
is his mother, Bisera, shot in the stomach as she tries to flee the
city where her son died. In these intimate biographies, and their
violent conclusions, Cohen scripts a rich narrative of the
corporeal horror of war.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than lapse into sentimental laments, Cohen returns,
relentlessly, to the policies that allowed things to get that far.
He unleashes a scathing attack on the United States _ in his own
words and those of enraged officials who quit their posts in
disgust _ skewering President Clinton's election-year calls to
action in Yugoslavia. He recalls the 1992 satellite photographs of
Serb concentration camps at Srebrenica _ ones kept from the
Security Council at the time _ and he holds up an uncomfortable
mirror, reminding us that ``like America, Bosnia had been a
multi-ethnic state; it was dismembered through ideologies of ethnic
hatred that flouted the American ideal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But Bosnia did not satisfy the Pentagon's criteria for the use
of American power,'' he writes. ``The administration was presented
with an intractable mess, but it could find neither the
determination nor the moral conviction to rectify it. Bosnia's
dismemberment was consummated through this failure.''
</P>
<P>
   Equally misguided were humanitarian efforts. Lodged in the
20th-century ``victim syndrome,'' the United Nations refused to
identify an aggressor _ ``a poor substitute for foreign policy,''
Cohen writes.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Cohen never abandons another core mission of
the book: contextualizing the historical circumstances of the
Balkans, a region whose name has become synonymous with ``a mess.''
In the first third of the book, in a segment called ``The Lost
Century,'' he gives a painstaking account of the conflicts
preceding this one, reaching back past Tito's reign to Yugoslavia's
birth in 1918, continually wondering why it was, ``in the agonizing
vestiges of Yugoslavia, that memory and understanding were
inextricably linked.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere is this question more curious than in the myth of
Kosovo, Cohen believes. Oddly, its name is invoked victoriously by
modern Serbian leaders _ even though the 1389 ``Battle of Kosovo''
was one in which the Serbs were defeated by the Ottoman Turks. It
is turned on its head as a source of Serbian national pride. And in
this, it is a classic Serbian inversion. When Serbian leaders
complain of ``neo-fascist aggression'' against Serbs in Kosovo, as
they did in a 1986 memorandum, they are really talking about a
region in which, in the years preceding, ``no more than five Serbs
died,'' Cohen writes.
</P>
<P>
   As a reporter covering the war for The New York Times, Cohen lay
awake at night in his room in Sarajevo, troubled, and he ``came
away wounded at the war's end in 1995.'' The doublespeak of the
Serbs, particularly leaders Slobodan Milosevic and Radovan
Karadzic, clearly disturbed him, as he watched officials in the
West take them at their word. Cohen's clarity of convictions
courses through ``Hearts Grown Brutal''; it is one of the few
comforts in this devastating book. And as officials now face the
problem of how to deal with Kosovo, it remains to be seen whether
there will be an answer to the question posed at the start of the
book: ``Was the anguish of Yugoslavia that of our dying century?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
