<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5917 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-ROSEANNE-BOS &LR;      09-15 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-ROSEANNE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH SOME FINE-TUNING, `ROSEANNE' COULD BE FINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
THE ROSEANNE SHOW 
On: ABC 
Time: Daily at 10 a.m. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We all know Roseanne is not out to make friends. With her savage
honesty, her pretzel-logic feminism, her tabloid attention-getting,
and her crooked grammar, she has probably offended every American
at least once in the past decade. But filtered through her late,
great sitcom, ``Roseanne,'' the comedian's abrasive wit was as
culturally valuable as it was dear. For nine years, she provided us
with a TV role-model alternative to those countless blonde
bombshells and helped deliver the family sitcom from yuppie
frivolity.
</P>
<P>
   Can Roseanne make a successful return to TV without the sanded
edges and blue-collar dignity of her Roseanne Connor character?
Monday morning, the mud-wrestling, national-anthem-screeching,
much-face-lifted diva got down with the people to host the premiere
of her own talk-variety hour, ``The Roseanne Show.'' Set to air
daily at 10 a.m., the syndicated series arrived after a summer of
industry rumors that it was a directionless mess headed toward
creative disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Is it a mess? Despite a few unbearable moments, a format that's
clearly still in progress, and the fact that it will never be as
significant as ``Roseanne,'' ``The Roseanne Show'' exhibited a fair
amount of promise and enthusiasm. The show's writers need to do
serious rejiggering, but the most important element _ Roseanne's
persona _ appears to click in the daytime arena. Let me say
straight away that I prefer irreverence to irrelevance, and would
take one painfully candid Roseanne over five disingenuous Rosie
O'Donnells any day. Rather than put on false modesty and adulation
for her guests, Roseanne takes a spikier, more self-ironic route,
affecting mock grandeur as she opened her show Monday descending
from a crane, throwing rose petals and Polaroids of herself onto
the audience.
</P>
<P>
   The show appears to be mimicking a spectrum of daytime formats,
from traditional celebrity interviews and socially aware ``Oprah''
segments to raucous argumentation straight out of ``The Jerry
Springer Show.'' A short monologue opened the hour, with Roseanne
nudging the critics by saying to her audience, ``All I have ever
really wanted to do was to talk directly to you without any
middleman.'' Then she brought out Whoopi Goldberg, and the two
began some feisty political chatter.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, Whoopi is not ``Meet the Press,'' and her
opinions about Ken Starr and Bill Clinton are not especially
eye-opening. On the other hand, Whoopi is not ``Meet the Press,''
and as she got heated up, the conversation had an earthy,
``Politically Incorrect'' feel to it. ``I respect everything you
say,'' Roseanne chimed in, ``but you're full of (bleep) on this
issue.'' Certainly it was more fun than an entire segment on
Whoopi's latest endeavor, ``Hollywood Squares.'' Also, Whoopi and
Roseanne stayed at an unusual level of frankness as they talked
about their difficult daughters and Whoopi's role as grandmother _
a condition most celebrities try to hide.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Roseanne Show'' took an unfortunate turn as the two stars
recalled their years as welfare mothers, then greeted three teenage
single mothers for an empowerment talk. As Whoopi and Roseanne sat
on the edge of the stage with concerned expressions, the three
women answered condescending questions like ``What's the hardest
part of your day'' with lines like ``Sometimes I feel like I just
can't breathe.'' It was hard to watch, as Roseanne gave them money
and urged them to ``build a network of mothers,'' and it smacked of
wealthy Hollywood types processing their own feelings of guilt. It
also revealed the show's demographic intentions too obviously.
</P>
<P>
   In another failed bit, Roseanne tried for David Letterman-styled
absurdity, as a police sketch artist drew scenes from ``Ghost.''
And she conducted a far-too-lengthy interview with ``Linder
Tripp,'' as Nora Dunn sat wearing a horrible blond wig. ``You're a
big fat snitch,'' Roseanne yelled. Roseanne is eager to offer
strength to her mostly female audience _ she even had Sandra
Bernhard sing ``I Am Woman'' over the credits _ but first she needs
to offer them a more finely tuned show.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
