<HEADLINE>
VALENTINES, CRANBERRIES AND GYPSY MOTHS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We all know (or should) that the Pilgrims' arrival in Plymouth,
the Salem witch trials, the Boston Tea Party, and Paul Revere's
ride all happened in Massachusetts. But those are only a few of the
Commonwealth's claims to fame, as a new book clearly shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Massachusetts Legacy: 150 Landmark Events That Shaped Our
Nation'' by Christopher Kenneally (Adams Publishing, $16) explores
many events with Massachusetts connections you may not have known
about. For example:
</P>
<P>
   _In 1631, Boston court officials created America's first police
force.
</P>
<P>
   _In 1814, the Industrial Revolution began with steam-powered
mills in Waltham.
</P>
<P>
   _In 1816, Captain Henry Hall of Cape Cod became the first to
cultivate cranberries.
</P>
<P>
   _In 1850, the New England Valentine Co., the first mass producer
of valentines, was founded in Worcester.
</P>
<P>
   _In 1869, scientist Leoplold Trouvelot, living in Medford,
mistakenly unleashed the first gypsy moths in North America.
</P>
<P>
   _In 1887, the predecessor of the roadside diner was introduced
in Worcester.
</P>
<P>
   _In 1903, the Boston Pilgrims faced the Pittsburgh Pirates in
the first baseball World Series.
</P>
<P>
   _And in 1944, in a Cambridge laboratory, the 50-foot-long
Harvard-IBM Mark 1 Automatic Sequence Controlled Calculator ushered
in the computer age.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Travel Trivia: &LR;  Where besides Kentucky will you find Fort Knox?
(Answer at end of column.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Quotable: &LR;  ``Nowhere does death occur so spectacularly, so proudly,
as it does in New England in October.'' _ a reflection on foliage
in ``Gone, Baby, Gone'' by Dennis Lehane.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; In a name: &LR;  There is a pasta restaurant in Brunswick, Maine, called
the Great Impasta.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Travel bookshelf: &LR;  People who come to Northern New England to view
foliage have been known to take wrong turns, then say words that
are as colorful as the leaves. To help avoid that exercise in free
speech, DeLorme, a Maine-based mapping company, has issued three
easy-to-use books: the ``Maine Atlas and Gazeteer,'' the ``Vermont
Atlas and Gazeteer,'' and the ``New Hampshire Atlas and Gazeteer.''
In addition to routes, there is information on historic sites,
scenic drives, and camping, hunting, and fishing sites.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Yeah, right: &LR;  From a letter sent to the Orlando tourism people:
``Please send me four Disney World tickets _ I'll send you the
money later.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Busmen's holiday choices: &LR;  The American Bus Association has chosen
Branson, Mo., as the best all-around destination and the best value
for the money. Other selections: best small-town destination,
Lancaster, Pa.; hottest up-and-coming destination, Myrtle Beach,
S.C.; city that most needs to be nicer to groups, New York; and
most popular casino or gaming attraction, Atlantic City.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Today's fractured English lesson: &LR;  A sign on the railing of a
river-cruise boat in Guilin, China, advises: ``Please don't
leapoter the fence.'' (With thanks to Mary Mahoney of Beverly, who
notes, ``Seeing the murky water, we were very careful not to
leapoter the fence.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Museum of the Month:  &LR; The Rock and Roll Hall of Fame and Museum in
Cleveland has opened an exhibit dedicated to Elvis Presley _ the
first display in the hall that honors a single artist. The exhibit,
called the largest collection of Presley memorabilia outside
Graceland, contains much more than guitars and jumpsuits. Among the
items: crayons Elvis used when he was 8, his seventh-grade report
card (with an ``A'' in spelling and a ``D'' in science), an
application for a trucking company job (which he didn't get), a
high school band program that spells his name ``Prestly,'' and a
certificate listing heart disease as the cause of his death. For
museum brochures or more information, call 888-764-ROCK or visit
www.rockhall.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; And speaking of the hall of fame: &LR;  How did the Rock and Roll Hall
of Fame and Museum end up in Cleveland anyway? One reason was that
Alan Freed, who popularized the term ``rock 'n' roll,'' got his
career really going in Cleveland and staged perhaps the first rock
'n' roll shows there. Another reason was the enthusiasm of
Cleveland residents in wooing the hall of fame committee and
providing an excellent location for the building near the shore of
Lake Erie.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Did you guess it? &LR;  You'll also find Fort Knox in Prospect, Maine,
across the Penobscot from Bucksport. It's a former military post
from the Civil War era.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send comments and questions to Travel Tidbits, Boston Globe,
Boston, MA 02107. Send e-mail to carpen(at)nws.globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
