<HEADER>
A5923 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARSH-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      09-15 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO THE MATS? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So Bill Clinton is searching for a new field commander _ a
senior figure who could do for the last two years of his second
term what Leon Panetta did for the middle years of his presidency:
organize them and defend Clinton against an encroaching Congress.
</P>
<P>
   One possible option, bringing back former Senate majority leader
George Mitchell to serve as chief of staff, would be like throwing
gasoline on the fire. Whether you think that's a good idea or not
depends on your reading of the situation.
</P>
<P>
   Let us quickly retrace our steps. The roots of the current
crisis go back to 1980, when Ronald Reagan was elected president
over Jimmy Carter. But the origins of the partisan frenzy that has
led the Republicans to attempt to hound bill Clinton from office go
back mainly to 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan's 1980 election marked a change of course, America's
entry into a global right turn, toward market styles of
organization, away from increasing the powers of the state.
</P>
<P>
   The movement had begun elsewhere _ in Chile, Spain, and
Portugal, in China and the United Kingdom. In due course it would
spread throughout the rest of the world: to Europe, the Soviet
Union, Latin American, South Asia, and Africa.
</P>
<P>
   But in the zig-zag of American politics, the first year or so of
the Reagan presidency was a moment as profound as had been the
beginning of the New Deal in 1932 _ and before long the outlines of
his program achieved the same kind of broad consensus.
</P>
<P>
   For a dozen years the hapless Democratic Party struggled to
understand what had happened _ and resisted the developing mandate,
even when elections drove home the point. In 1984 Reagan buried
Walter Mondale in a landslide. In 1988 George Bush clobbered
Michael S. Dukakis.
</P>
<P>
   Only in 1992 did the Democrats nominate a candidate sufficiently
like a Republican to be trusted to serve as steward of the Reagan
consensus _ William Jefferson Clinton. He took office on much the
same terms as Republican Dwight Eisenhower had inherited the New
Deal from Democratic presidents 40 years before _ with a license to
tinker, but not to reverse.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, however, the bitterness of the rivalry between the
parties began to approach new highs. George Bush, who had come into
office promising a ``kinder, gentler'' version of the Reagan years,
found himself opposed by Democrats at every turn.
</P>
<P>
   The leader of the intransigent Democrats in those years was
Senate majority leader George Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   First Mitchell managed to torpedo Bush's promise to engineer a
capital gains tax cut. Then he turned on Bush after the 1990 budget
agreement to trim the deficit on the eve of the Gulf War, mocking
it as ``a flop of a flip of a flop'' _ despite the fact that Bush
had brought upon himself a storm of right-wing disdain by entering
into the agreement in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell then led the opposition to the Persian Gulf War. After
it was concluded sucessfully, he handed Bush a series of
legislative defeats that contributed to the popular image of a
president who had lost control of domestic policy. And throughout,
Mitchell was among those who sought the use of special prosecutors
to pursue both Reagan and Bush and their aides for their conduct of
foreign policy in Nicaragua and Iran.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, George Mitchell voluntarily stepped down from the
Senate. He declined Clinton's offer of a Supreme Court nomination.
He failed to get the job he had hoped for as commissioner of
baseball. Only then did Clinton name him chairman of the North
Ireland peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   In that job, of course, Mitchell was spectacularly successful.
The agreement he brokered has won him the intense admiration of
both sides _ and a place in history that he may be reluctant to
give up.
</P>
<P>
   If Mitchell were to return to serve Clinton, as The Los Angeles
Times has reported he might, he would be walking into a situation
whose intransigence, culturally adjusted, rivals that of the one
that he just left in the Emerald Isle. Only this time he wouldn't
be seen as a neutral.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment of fiercely partisan Mitchell would signal Bill
Clinton's intent to go ``to the matresses'' _ gang talk for all-out
war with Republicans. Still crazy after all these years? They would
deserve each other.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Warsh writes about economics for the Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)nws.globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
