<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVINGSTON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCK MARKET JABBERWOCKY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN LEVINGSTON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The gibberish resounding from Wall Street is so loud I can
scarcely hear myself losing money. Ever since this Jello market
began to jiggle, any pundit with a tongue to wag has raced before
the television cameras to declaim in the most sober and sapient
tones the foulest nonsense to hit the airwaves since Howard Stern
first panted into a microphone.
</P>
<P>
   These blind seers scatter their wisdom like fairy dust. For our
market woes, they say, blame Russia, blame earnings, blame
presidential prusience, blame Keiko the killer whale. The jabbering
is an institutional con suavely presented as a clarifying gaze deep
into the heart of our current troubles.
</P>
<P>
   Listen long enough to the jangle of contradictory alarms and
assurances and you soon realize that the bunco artists are into the
muck well over their heads, clueless as you and me, and are just
blowing mud bubbles at us.
</P>
<P>
   I managed to get my investment adviser on his cell phone as he
was shuttling between appearances on CNBC and the Game Show
Network. He's a big shot, a partner in the esteemed brokerage firm
Kidding Nobody &AMP; Co. Like Cher, my Wall Street wizard goes by only
one name: Merlin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Merlin, what do I do? What do I do?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do not panic, my friend. You are an experienced, long-term
investor, right?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Uh huh.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Then you know these market hiccups are soon digested,'' he
continued. ``But we may be witnessing something worse than a hiccup
_ something closer to intestinal poisoning.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What are you saying?!''
</P>
<P>
   ``We may be headed for an ugly case of market vomiting. You'll
be left wading knee-deep in a bucket of stinking losses.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What do I do?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Buy rubber boots.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the deal with Russia?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll put it to you this way: When was the last time you went
on a shopping spree at Brooks Brothers and paid in rubles?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I see your point.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Russia has a puny economy; it buys less than 1 percent of our
exports. Their mess can't touch us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Whew, what a relief.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But let's just suppose: The Russian economy is D.O.A., its
institutions are in a straight-jacket, its currency is toilet
paper, there's anarchy in the streets _ and someone over there has
an itchy finger on the nuclear button.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh dear, oh dear. What do I do, Merlin?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Best case? Bend over and kiss your you-know-what goodbye.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Come on, let's be realistic,'' I offered. ``Alan Greenspan
will never allow the world to plunge into catastrophe.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ah, the Omnipotent One. Yes, the Federal Reserve chairman will
always be there to protect us.``
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm feeling better already.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Omnipotent One has his itchy finger on a far bigger weapon
than any nuclear bomb: the money spigot. Turn the valve a touch
this way and flood the world with dollars. Another flick of the
wrist and the Omnipotent One can stop Russia from falling in the
punchbowl, can feed hungry mouths in Indonesia, can make us
stock-market gaga forever.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I'll sleep soundly tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Before you fluff your pillow, I must tell you one more thing.
The Omnipotent One may have had all his Omnipotence can take. He's
been heard muttering, `Amscray, amscray,' and has been seen in a
leather vest mounting a Harley-Davidson. The Omnipotent One, I
fear, is about to roar down the highway with a biker gang, and
we'll never hear his sacred mutterings again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doomed! What do I do?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Buy Harley stock.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Steven Levingston can be reached at leving(at)bu.edu.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
