<HEADER>
A5933 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ENTERTAINING-POLITICS     09-15 2871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENTERTAINING-POLITICS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW MUCH OF POLITICS IS ENTERTAINMENT? 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By DAVID M. SHRIBMAN  
 FROM: The Boston Globe Magazine  
 Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    It's a bright Saturday morning in Boston. Just off the Public
Garden, in the health club of the Four Seasons Hotel, two men climb
onto exercise bikes and fiddle with the little TV sets at the
consoles.
 &HT;    Barry MacLean, who runs a large family business in Illinois and
has had his share of frustrations with Washington bureaucracy,
tunes in to cartoons. At the next bike, William Neukom, Microsoft's
chief lawyer in its landmark legal battle with the Justice
Department, tunes in to a C-Span rebroadcast of a presidential
speech.
 &HT;    A moment later, Neukom looks at MacLean's console, then at his
own and mutters, ``What's the difference? It's all entertainment.''
 &HT;    A month later, in the swish setting of the Primi Piatti
restaurant, a few blocks from the White House on Washington's
Pennsylvania Avenue, Warren Beatty is poking at his pasta and
bantering with a handful of capital columnists and TV
correspondents.
 &HT;    There, amid talk of President Clinton's woes and Beatty's movie
``Bulworth,'' the actor has an epiphany: ``There is no difference
anymore between Hollywood and Washington. They are both totally
into the sound bite. One is no more superficial than the other.
Even this whole process of yakking to people about this movie is
really no different from what you'd be doing if you were running
for office.''
 &HT;    Politics. Entertainment. Politics as entertainment. The
distinction between the two, never sharp, is today less well
defined than ever. Once, the presidency was a documentary shown in
prime time; now it has degenerated into a soap opera for afternoon
television.
 &HT;    Once, campaign advertising complemented stump speeches and
position papers; in some races today, the ads virtually replace
stump speeches and position papers. Once, news shows provided a
sober intermission between situation comedies and full-length
feature films; now they have taken on characteristics of both.
 &HT;    ``We are now reaching a point,'' says Sen. Richard Durbin,
Democrat of Illinois, ``where the line between entertainment and
news is blurring.''
 &HT;    In technology as in entertainment, the word for this phenomenon
is ``convergence.'' And what politics and entertainment
increasingly have in common is not only that they reward style more
than content; not only that they seek to manipulate rather than
simply to persuade; not only that they pander rather than
challenge; not only that they reward celebrity and avoid searching
questions.
 &HT;    All those things are true, but the most important similarity
between modern entertainment and modern politics is what is, in a
sense, most un-American about them both: They are passive
experiences.
 &HT;    Like entertainment, politics is increasingly part of the
easy-listening background music of the time _ always present, not
particularly adventuresome, seldom very important. Like
entertainment, politics is increasingly a show of special effects.
Like entertainment, politics is increasingly modified by the word
``virtual.'' And, like entertainment, politics has become something
that other people do.
 &HT;    This movement of politics from the active mode to the passive
has grave implications for American civic life and for the health
of our democratic system. It is, moreover, an important departure
for a nation that was born in the activism of the 18th-century
revolutionaries, that conducted the signature debates of the modern
age in public, that at every turn decided to expand its visions of
freedom and liberty rather than to constrict them _ and that
throughout its history broadened, rather than diminished, its
definition of ``rights.''
 &HT;    ``We are in danger of becoming a nation of spectators,'' warned
The National Commission on Civic Renewal, based in College Park,
Md., which for a year studied American civic life.
 &HT;    There's always been a bit of entertainment in politics and a bit
of politics in entertainment. Indeed, in Elizabethan times the
theater was a public sphere, the place where, in the absence of
newspapers, television, talk radio or Oprah, the real issues were
debated _ with vivid, meaningful conflict over questions such as
monarchical succession, religious freedom, social and class
structure and economic mobility.
 &HT;    ``Entertainment was the very place where political ideas were
articulated and challenged and changed,'' says David Scott Kastan,
a Columbia University authority on Shakespeare and his time. ``It
was what made the theater exciting and entertaining and important,
and it is why we remember Shakespeare today. Now we have an
entertainment industry that doesn't engage in serious political
thought, but worse, we have a political system that doesn't engage
in serious political thought.''
 &HT;    In America too, politics has always had a big entertainment
element but in truth, it was far more entertaining in the past.
Politics was the great national sport at the turn of the century,
and one of the forgotten truths about 19th-century politics is that
many Americans voted for one party or another not because they
favored its politics but because they preferred its barbecues.
 &HT;    Even in more recent days, there was a greater flair and more
flavor to politics. John Lindsay slept overnight on a steelworker's
couch. Barry Goldwater flew his own campaign plane. Nelson
Rockefeller was a walking vaudeville act, traveling in helicopters
and seaplanes and boats, eating Oreo cookies all day long and
shepherding favored reporters to one of the best wine cellars in
the world.
 &HT;    Gov. John Rhodes of Ohio based an entire campaign on visiting
county fairs. One Pennsylvania congressman slept in his office,
surrounded by hundreds of bags of mail that were never opened. Gov.
William Scranton of Pennsylvania used to have roast swan for
Christmas dinner. Jimmy Tayoun, the last of the Philadelphia street
politicians, made a point of running red lights to attend a wake
for a Polish saloonkeeper in South Philadelphia.
 &HT;    ``We've always had great showmen in American politics,'' says
former Sen. George S. McGovern of South Dakota, the Democratic
presidential nominee in 1972. ``But the increased use of media
consultants and all these photo-op tactics lend themselves to false
drama and the creation of entertainment. That's the big
difference.''
 &HT;    American politics used to be a participatory sport, not a
spectator sport, and it was conducted by getting people to hold
signs and sit in phone banks. That is dying or, in some regions, is
dead already. Politicians have a keen sense of trends in American
life, and so they are telling us something when they no longer
devote countless hours to choosing their chief organizers. Now they
spend that time selecting their press secretaries, media
consultants and strategists.
 &HT;    ``Politics today is all media,'' says Michael Whouley, a
Boston-based political consultant who is close to Vice President Al
Gore. ``More than 10 years ago, you would compartmentalize a
campaign: media, fund-raising and field organizing. Now it's
fund-raising, and the fund-raising is all geared to the media.''
 &HT;    This hasn't changed only the way politics is conducted. It also
has changed the sort of people who run for office and, just as
important, the kind of people who are drawn to campaigns. The
organizers are passe. The media manipulators are king.
 &HT;    Listen to the view of Beatty, who grew up in the Washington
suburbs but whose work is done in Hollywood: ``It's impossible to
engage people in a complex issue. You've got to stop them from
channel surfing. You've got to give them a simple, vulgarized
version of things. And you're doing it all with a rearview mirror
that you didn't always have: You now know how people will react to
things.''
 &HT;    Maybe the best place to see the merging of entertainment and
politics is in the movies. Just recently, Michael Douglas, Jack
Nicholson, Gene Hackman, Kevin Kline, Jack Lemmon, James Garner,
Dan Aykroyd, Harrison Ford, Sam Waterston and John Travolta have
all played the president of the United States on film. The American
president isn't only a political figure. It's a movie.
 &HT;    ``Politics has always been show business,'' says former
Secretary of State James A. Baker III, who was a principal figure
in the presidential campaigns of Gerald Ford, Ronald Reagan and
George Bush. ``Today it's more show business.''
 &HT;    Show business _ complete with celebrities. The entire notion of
celebrity can, of course, be traced to the entertainment world, and
in truth celebrities have always been interested in politics _ and
vice versa.
 &HT;    Frank Mankiewicz, the veteran Washington public-relations
executive and a close adviser to both McGovern and Robert F.
Kennedy, likes to tell about how his uncle, Joe Mankiewicz, a great
director and writer who won four Oscars, called him and said he was
coming to Washington.
 &HT;    Mankiewicz offered to throw a dinner party for his uncle, who
requested that some of the senators in the middle of the Vietnam
debate _ McGovern, Frank Church of Idaho, Gaylord Nelson of
Wisconsin _ be invited. His uncle wanted to spend the evening
talking about reductions in troop strength and what the Chinese
were going to do about Vietnam; the senators wanted only to ask
about the casting couch and Marilyn Monroe.
 &HT;    This hasn't changed. ``Today, you get Barbra Streisand in
Washington, and she wants to talk about land mines,'' Mankiewicz
says, ``and everybody at dinner wants to talk about why she didn't
get nominated for `The Mirror Has Two Faces.'''
 &HT;    In the old days, there were two Hollywoods, one Republican and
one Democratic. The actors and actresses were almost all
Republicans, the writers and producers almost all Democrats. There
were no centrists. The conservatives were very far to the right,
and the liberals were very much to the left. The Hitler-Stalin pact
of 1939 split the left, but even then there was no middle ground.
And so the debates were furious. Hollywood was divided over FDR and
the New Deal and over Upton Sinclair's 1934 gubernatorial campaign
in California.
 &HT;    There's nothing new about someone such as Beatty being involved
in the presidential campaigns of RFK in 1968, McGovern in 1972 and
Gary Hart in 1984. But what is new is the melding of politics and
celebrity, and that began with John Kennedy.
 &HT;    ``Reagan may be the first movie-star president, but after all,
the Kennedys themselves made glamour an indispensable part of
American politics long before the host of `Death Valley Days' and
the `General Electric Theater' reached the White House,'' Michael
Knox Beran writes in ``The Last Patrician,'' the remarkable book
about Robert Kennedy published this spring. ``Joseph Kennedy was in
Hollywood, learning its lessons, studying its methods, financing
its movies, 10 years before Ronald Reagan showed up at Jack
Warner's studio in Burbank in 1937.''
 &HT;    But though Joe Kennedy had been drawn to Hollywood and its
melange of starlets and celebrity, his son John had a celebrity of
his own, a breezy insouciance, a touch of intellectualism, a quick
sense of humor.
 &HT;    ``We didn't have to make Kennedy a celebrity, and nobody in the
campaign _ Larry O'Brien and Kenny O'Donnell and Ted Sorensen _ was
a celebrity,'' says Joe Napolitan, who worked for Kennedy in 1960,
Johnson in 1964 and Hubert H. Humphrey in 1968 and may have been
the first person ever to call himself a political consultant. ``He
naturally had it all: He was a war hero, he was handsome, he had
just married a glamorous woman, he had a big name and he was a
senator.''
 &HT;    Today a lot of presidential candidates not only try to package
themselves (as 19th-century presidents did, invariably finding a
log cabin in their past) but also try to make themselves
celebrities in their own right.
 &HT;    Surely Bill Clinton has a bit of the entertainer in him. He can
play the saxophone on the Arsenio Hall Show, he can delight a group
of senior citizens, he can play to just about any audience. But
there's nothing entertaining about his plight since the Monica
Lewinsky story broke in January _ and yet the entire spectacle has
more in common with mass entertainment than with serious politics.
 &HT;    Some of that, to be sure, is Clinton's fault. There is little
dispute that the president has put himself in harm's way with some
of the women he has encountered over the years. And Clinton, a
fervent disciple of Kennedy's style, has merged the public and the
private in new ways. He opened his home to people he describes as
his ``friends'' but who also are big Democratic fund-raisers. He
willingly disclosed the sort of private details of his life _ not
only his preference in underwear but his mother's many marriages
and the alcohol and abuse that filled his home life as a youngster
_ that in other presidents' lives are often left to a sleuthing
biographer or historian.
 &HT;    But the storm that has engulfed the Clinton presidency since
January has been governed by the press as well, which has lunged at
unsubstantiated rumors, trailed Lewinsky and transformed her into a
woman of mystery, and added a sense of treacly melodrama to a sober
legal proceeding that has its own inherent drama.
 &HT;    This is all occurring at a time when there are few contested
issues in American life. With a strong economy, a deficit that has
disappeared and no great foreign threats, national life is quiet,
devoid of the great struggles that captivated Americans even in the
tranquil years of the 1950s, which had wars in Korea and the Middle
East, civil-rights battles in Little Rock, terrifying superpower
confrontations, a dramatic uprising in Hungary and the launching of
the space age with the Soviet Sputnik satellite.
 &HT;    Modern politics is infused with entertainment values because
modern politics is infused with media influences. The pace, tone
and timbre of the House and Senate changed once their deliberations
were televised; Gore and Newt Gingrich were among the first to
recognize the power that televised sessions provided, and both
became grandstanders _ and powerful figures _ as a result.
 &HT;    The advent of cable television, which was supposed to provide
``local access'' to lower levels of government, also changed the
way politics is conducted.
 &HT;    ``Because of that, politicians play to the camera,'' says State
Assemblyman Bill Campbell of California, a first-term Republican
who represents southeastern Orange County. ``More people speak, and
they speak longer than they would otherwise. People play to the
tube.''
 &HT;    Yet the rush to entertain has killed the entertainment in
politics _ and has made politics less appealing than ever. This
autumn as many as 100 House members may run unopposed. The major
parties simply were not able to find anyone to challenge the
incumbents in nearly a quarter of the House districts in the
nation.
 &HT;    ``It takes a major effort now to convince anyone to run for
public office,'' says Durbin, the Illinois senator. ``The intrusion
into your private life is too great. Politics has reached such a
low level that people just can't stomach the idea of going into
politics.
 &HT;    ``I spend time on the phone, begging people to run for all sorts
of offices,'' he continues. ``It's a very hard sell. They don't
know whether they want to put themselves or their families through
this. You either have to be flawless or prepared to see your flaws
on the front page of the paper.''
 &HT;    And then people don't think they can get anything accomplished
even if they are elected. ``People always ask: Do you get anything
done up there? Can you make a difference?'' says Sen. Bob Kerrey of
Nebraska, who heads the Senate Democratic Campaign Committee. He
says he answers yes.
 &HT;    He's probably right. This year the lawmakers have dealt with
issues such as the budget surplus, whether to overhaul the campaign
finance system, what the minimum wage should be and how much money
should be spent on thousands of line items in the 13 appropriations
bills that get almost no attention anywhere.
 &HT;    Those are real decisions involving real people. In the end,
that's politics. That's not entertainment.
 &HT;     c.1998 The Boston Globe Magazine  
