<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5943 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SIXTIES-AMERICA-EUROP     09-15 3524
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIXTIES-AMERICA-EUROPE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STILL LIVING WITH '68 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By MARK LILLA  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 &HT;    August was the cruelest month. After the Tet offensive and the
escalation of the Vietnam War in early 1968, after the
assassinations of Martin Luther King Jr. and Robert Kennedy, and
then riots and looting in several major cities, Americans ended the
summer watching the Democratic Party implode at its Chicago
convention while policemen beat demonstrators on the streets
outside. The country seemed to be coming unglued.
 &HT;    Or was it the whole Western world? The situation in Europe
certainly made it seem so.
 &HT;    In the spring, universities in Madrid and Rome were closed after
clashes between students and police, while in West Germany the
leader of the largest student organization was shot, setting off
arson attacks by a newly formed terrorist group called the Red Army
Faction.
 &HT;    The following month, a student strike at a suburban university
outside Paris metamorphosed into the now famous ``events of May,''
which began with marches and the occupation of buildings and ended
with barricades, Molotov cocktails, hand-to-hand street combat and
a general strike that brought the French economy to its knees.
 &HT;    In the summer of `68 it seemed safe to assume that America and
Western Europe were undergoing the same ``revolution,'' a word that
came easily to the lips back then. But within a few years it became
obvious that very different dramas were being played out on the two
continents.
 &HT;    After a brief but significant flirtation with armed violence on
the fringes of the ```60s movement,'' the American left began to
turn its attention from strictly political issues, such as
segregation and imperialism, to new cultural ones, such as
feminism. As the war in Vietnam de-escalated, a cultural war that
is still with us began at home.
 &HT;    In Europe, however, it was the political repercussions of `68
that remained most significant over the next decade. French
students and intellectuals made a fetish of Chairman Mao and
genuflected before it, while German and Italian terrorists
kidnapped, ``kneecapped'' and murdered leading figures in business
and government.
 &HT;    The coldblooded execution of the former prime minister, Aldo
Moro, by the Italian Red Brigades on the 10th anniversary of May
`68 was only the most spectacular of these attacks, which lasted
into the 1980s.
 &HT;    Given these violent political contestations, you might expect
passions about the `60s to run higher in Europe today than in the
politically stable United States. Instead, the tumult has
disappeared: the `60s are over in Europe.
 &HT;    This past spring, the 30th anniversary of May `68 was calmly
commemorated across the continent without bloodshed _ indeed,
without significant controversy. Conferences were held, TV specials
were broadcast, day-by-day chronicles of the events appeared in the
newspapers and hundreds of books (more than 80 in France alone)
were printed.
 &HT;    Yet as the French newspaper Le Monde reported, the anniversary
was a publishing disaster. It appears there was neither enough
nostalgia for, nor rage against, the `60s revolution to induce the
French to read about it _ especially the young, for whom it is
ancient history.
 &HT;    This indifference is common today, though not because Europe has
returned to some pre-`68 slumber. It is simply that Europeans have
made their peace with the revolution's successes and failures.
Unlike the United States, where pro- and anti-`68 factions continue
to militate in the worlds of academia, journalism and politics,
Europe has comfortably entered a post-`68 age.
 &HT;    Which raises the question: Why haven't we? Why do the American
`60s, whose political conflicts no longer rage in our streets,
continue to rage in our heads?
 -0- 
 &HT;    What distinguishes the American and European `60s is less the
nature of the political and cultural changes that eventually took
place than the spirit in which they were pursued.
 &HT;    Was the revolution, as Europeans seemed to believe, essentially
about bringing an end to an old political order that also supported
a stifling bourgeois culture? Or was it, as Americans appeared to
think, about extending the reach of a noble if imperfectly realized
political ideal into every corner of cultural life?
 &HT;    The European `60s were politically contentious from the start,
for reasons that lie in a half-century of ideological polarization.
Until World War II, much of the continent looked not much different
from the Europe of the 19th century. It was rural, religious,
socially conservative and, especially in German-speaking
territories, admiring of military virtues. This was the traditional
home of the European right.
 &HT;    The European left, on the other hand, was centered in the
rapidly growing cities and divided between Communists and Social
Democrats. These forces polarized European politics in the decades
leading up to World War II, and most observers expected the
continent to fall back into this pattern at its conclusion.
 &HT;    Yet in the three decades following the war, a social
transformation began that would eventually turn over the tired soil
that had nourished hostile political relations in Europe for so
long. Its causes were fundamentally economic and military: 30 years
of unprecedented growth in production and public investment under
the American nuclear umbrella.
 &HT;    As the bounty arrived, the centuries-long divide between urban
and rural mentalities that underlay the right-left split began to
close up. Villages across Europe were depopulated and, through
television, people who remained behind began to take part, at least
from a distance, in the life of the capitals.
 &HT;    As working-class families acquired more consumer goods, the
distinctions between classes came to depend more on taste than on
buying power. This is not to say that postwar Europe became a
classless continent, simply that traditional social divisions were
being replaced by more complex ones _ the most significant new one
being generational.
 &HT;    At bottom, ``catching up'' was what the European `60s were all
about. Although Western Europe managed to get on the
liberal-democratic rails remarkably fast in the 20 years after the
war, its ideological frame of reference was still that of the
polarized prewar era.
 &HT;    The new Christian Democratic parties were, to be sure, nothing
like the old right, yet neither were they committed to the
modernization of social institutions. The Communists came out of
the war strengthened by their (often exaggerated) role in resisting
fascism, but their language of ``class struggle'' and ``leading
role of the party'' rang hollow.
 &HT;    While European workers continued to give their ballots to the
Communists, with their wallets they _ and especially their children
_ were voting for consumer capitalism. Out of this gap between the
reality of postwar European society and its prewar ideologies a new
political force was born.
 &HT;    Because it appealed to so many of the traditional symbols of the
European left _ and even radicalized them, replacing class struggle
with generational struggle, Marx and Lenin with Mao and Che,
``socialism in one country'' with worldwide peasant revolution _ it
stood to reason that it was taken to be a ``new'' left.
 &HT;    But, in fact, it was not essentially a revitalized left but a
third force that helped to extinguish an established European left
that could trace its lineage back to 1917 and even to 1789. Its new
demands for hedonistic fulfillment and individual self-expression
had nothing to do with Marxism, as the nervous Communist parties of
Europe understood perfectly well. And its skepticism toward the
experiences of real existing socialism was such that disenchantment
with the entire revolutionary tradition was bound to set in.
 &HT;    And it did. The first shock came in 1972 with the murder of 11
Israeli athletes at the Munich Olympic Games by the Palestinian
Black September group. Suddenly it seemed that the celebration of
terrorism and unconditional support of Third World struggles by the
most radical of the `68ers had, at least indirectly, sanctioned the
death of Jews again in Europe.
 &HT;    Then in 1974 Alexander Solzhenitsyn's ``Gulag Archipelago''
appeared, convincing many younger intellectuals on the left,
especially in France, of the necessary connection between communism
and totalitarian repression.
 &HT;    The fall of Saigon brought the heartbreaking flight of the boat
people; there was the Cambodian genocide, and in 1979 a ``people's
revolution'' in Iran brought to power a reactionary religious
clique that repressed secular intellectuals, women and homosexuals.
 &HT;    Because the European left took seriously the possibility of
communism and Third World revolution, in the end it was forced to
reckon with their historical records. And while this was happening,
the leftist dogma that real reform was impossible within ``formal''
democracy was proving to be a myth. Socialist parties came to power
in Portugal and France, then in Italy and Spain.
 &HT;    The German new left, which had been Europe's most intransigent,
progressively made its peace with parliamentary democracy. This
political ``normalization'' of the European left was accompanied by
an intellectual ``normalization,'' and by the mid-'80s the radical
newspapers founded in the wake of the `60s agitation _ Libiration
in Paris, La Repubblica in Rome, Die Tageszeitung in Berlin _ had
become perfectly conventional publications.
 &HT;    Thus, when perestroika began, and as the regimes of the East
Bloc started to crumble on the bicentennary of the French
Revolution, the European left had already divested itself of its
holdings in the enterprise that had been founded in Russia in 1917.
It was now clear to almost everyone that a 50-year tradition of
thinking and living politics had come to a close. And with it ended
the political dreams of `68.
 -0- 
 &HT;    This dramatic story of the European left's political maturation,
of revolutionary promise and betrayal, of illusions embraced and
lost, was not the story that unfolded in the United States. And the
reason for this is quite simple: the fate of the Communist idea,
and even of the French revolutionary tradition, had virtually no
significance for American `68ers. Politically speaking, they were,
and by and large still are, provincials.
 &HT;    While European radicals such as Rigis Debray spent the `60s in
the jungles of South America spreading the revolutionary gospel,
students in the United States stayed on campus and demanded that
America ``come home.'' Home was where its heart was, even when it
foolishly denounced ``Amerika.''
 &HT;    What these `68ers originally demanded was that America fulfill
its own democratic promise, not that it take up a new revolutionary
mission. The temple of the American democratic ideal had to be
cleansed. A ritual cleansing began with the civil-rights movement
and resistance to the war, and was finished once Richard Nixon
resigned and the troops came home.
 &HT;    Yet it was these very successes that fed the American left's
passion for greater purification, for an extension of the `68
spirit from the strictly political sphere to the whole of American
culture.
 &HT;    Aspects of American life that hitherto had been spared the
exacting scrutiny of pure democratic principles _ family, marriage,
the regulation of morals, the authority of law, even the authority
of learning _ now seemed somehow suspect, if not illegitimate. For
the `68ers, it was perfectly obvious that the struggle begun in the
streets of Selma and Chicago's Grant Park should be followed by new
campaigns in the classrooms and bedrooms of America.
 &HT;    The line between politics and culture looked absurd to them for
the simple reason that they did not take the democratic idea to be
a merely political principle. It was, so to speak, an existential
one that deserved to be applied to every aspect of our lives.
 &HT;    This existential character of the American democratic faith has
been noted by alert European observers of our country ever since
Tocqueville and Mrs. Trollope began writing about us in the 19th
century. They immediately notice two things: that democracy in
America is considered not just a set of institutions and principles
but a way of life and that it is promoted with a unique sort of
passion.
 &HT;    We Americans have trouble entertaining the notion that there
might be aspects of life _ let alone whole parts of the globe _
where it cannot or should not apply. To suggest this might be the
case is to risk being burned by the fire of democratic passion.
 &HT;    The American Founders had a strong sense of the passions to
which democratic politics is subject, which is why they placed such
a high value on moderating and canalizing them in the system of
government they fashioned. What they did not anticipate was that
the American conception of democracy would become an existential
one progressively chipping away at the distinction between politics
and culture that they took for granted.
 &HT;    Nor did they imagine that once democratic political passions
spilled over into the morally and psychologically fragile sphere of
culture, they would be more difficult to moderate and their damage
more difficult to repair.
 &HT;    It is little wonder that since the `60s we have become such a
``sensitive'' nation, in every sense of the term, for we have
extended the democratic project into extremely intimate areas of
life: sexual identity, marital relations, authority in the family
and moral education, not to mention the eternal complications of
race and ethnicity.
 &HT;    This conception of democracy as an all-encompassing way of life
is utterly foreign to European society, in large part because its
own past, like that of most human cultures, was aristocratic and
hierarchical. Europeans have therefore been somewhat anxious about
this trans-Atlantic difference, wondering whether America is
exceptional or merely more advanced in fashioning a democratic
culture destined to spread across the globe.
 &HT;    Whatever one's views on these speculations, the Europeans are
right to think that American democratic passions are still unique
in the world. Although democracy is becoming more widely recognized
abroad as a political value, there is still only one nation on
earth that takes it to be an existential one.
 &HT;    Which is not to say that European culture has not been
transformed since the `60s, in many ways following the American
democratic example. There has been something of a continental
cultural revolution, though it has been carried out much more
slowly than our own and without our red-hot passion.
 &HT;    The list of legal reforms stemming from the `60s is long and
familiar: the legalization of abortion, the near abolition of
censorship, guarantees of sexual equality in the workplace, the
decriminalization of homosexual activity, the parity of husbands
and wives before the law and the loosening of parents' statutory
authority over their children.
 &HT;    Informal changes in cultural mores also took place after `68, as
life became more relaxed and flexible in the workplace and the
home. And, not surprisingly, many of the dispiriting repercussions
of the `60s that we have experienced have also followed this
transformation in Europe, including increased divorce and
illegitimacy rates, the decline in public civility, drug problems
and violent youth crimes.
 &HT;    Yet after the shock of `68 and the flood of accumulated cultural
demands it unleashed, the institution of these reforms in Europe
met with general social consensus, mostly because of unspoken
agreement about the limits to cultural democratization.
 &HT;    European feminists have won many victories over recent decades
without taking on the joyless militancy of American feminism,
without questioning the naturalness of family or upsetting the
psychologically delicate ritual of seduction.
 &HT;    European schools that used to be strictly hierarchical and
indifferent to laggards have become more attentive to students'
needs. The curriculum, however, remains much as it was 30 years
ago, and there are no agonizing debates about making it
``representative.''
 &HT;    In short, cultural issues Americans instinctively frame in terms
of nonnegotiable democratic principles have been treated in Europe
through an informal balancing of those principles with other,
nonpolitical ones.
 &HT;    Indeed, because the modernization of post-`68 European culture
was not brought about through the sort of messianic moral crusade
that has been so divisive in America, in certain ways its reforms
have gone further than our own, and with fewer untoward effects.
 &HT;    As the `68 anniversary was marked in France this spring, there
were calm public debates about two measures that would be
unthinkable in the United States even today. One would require that
half of each political party's candidates for office be women; the
other would establish a legal framework for recognizing homosexual
couples.
 &HT;    In short, despite the extreme political violence of the `60s,
there has been no post-`68 ``culture war'' in Europe. And the
culture warriors so familiar to us _ aging `68 professors promoting
the Glorious Revolution, agitated conservative journalists
portraying America as Gomorrah _ are nowhere to be found.
 -0- 
 &HT;    All revolutions inevitably face the same crisis: how to bring
themselves to a close. This is because revolutionary success
depends on stirring up passions that subsequently prove difficult
to cool. With modern revolutions such passions are even more
difficult to calm because they are accompanied by revolutions in
ideas, which have a way of digging in their heels and resisting
retirement after they have been overtaken by events.
 &HT;    To the extent that the European `60s revolution was driven by an
idea, it was an old conception of political revolution that had
been born in 1789, revived in 1917 and began collapsing after World
War II under the weight of a new social reality and its own evident
failures around the globe.
 &HT;    The `60s were about the end of this tradition in Europe, and
perhaps that is why they are finally over. European culture has
been, and continues to be, reformed in light of that experience,
but not in the shadow of the revolutionary ideal.
 &HT;    The American `60s were also about an idea, though not about
burying it. For better or worse, our cultural revolution has now
entered the pantheon of victories for the American democratic
project and there it will remain, flanked on one side by the
abolition of slavery and segregation and on the other by an empty
altar reserved for heroes of the next campaign.
 &HT;    Americans today see the `60s as continuing a native tradition,
not as departing from it, and in this respect our revolution was
more conservative than the European one. It does not, at least in
public perception, represent a break in our history.
 &HT;    Yet the reason this revolution continues to haunt us is that by
breaking down the last fences between democratic politics and
culture, it entered unexplored territory. And there it has begun to
lose its bearings and cause some harm _ to our families, our
schools, our cultural institutions, our public life and, indeed, to
our psychological well-being.
 &HT;    These harms are real, not the figment of the conservative
imagination. But they are virtually impossible for pro- and
anti-`68 partisans to consider dispassionately, so strong is the
grip of the democratic idea on us all.
 &HT;    Even American conservatives today can find no compelling
democratic reason to question the extension of the democratic
principle to the realms of morals, sex, family and education, which
means they can find no reason at all.
 &HT;    In this sense, our `60s are over too: We are all `68ers now. And
that is our problem. We are anxious about the America the `68
revolution has bequeathed us, but we avoid thinking too deeply
about it, fearing, perhaps with good reason, that our faith _ our
all-encompassing democratic faith _ might not stand the test.
 &HT;     c.1998 Mark Lilla  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Mark Lilla is an associate professor of politics at New York
University and the editor, most recently, of ``New French Thought:
Political Philosophy.'') &LR;
</P>
