<HEADLINE>
SPENDING ON HEALTH CARE EXPECTED TO DOUBLE IN DECADE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   America's spending on health care is expected to double over the
next decade to a whopping $2.1 trillion, straining both taxpayers
and companies that have to shoulder the tab, according to estimates
released by government actuaries Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Health care expenditures will also take up a greater portion of
the national economy, ballooning to 16.6 percent of gross domestic
product in 2007, from an estimated 13.7 percent this year, the US
Health Care Financing Administration projected in a study to be
published in this month's issue of Health Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   The projections are the strongest indication to date that health
care spending could return to the double-digit increases seen in
the late 1980s and early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most prominent cost drivers: consumer insistence on
access to more specialists; newer drugs and better medical
technology; a strong economy that is lifting both income and demand
for health care; and a tight labor market that forces employers to
offer generous health benefits to attract workers. The report also
cited the slowdown in the rush to managed care. With 85 percent of
the insured population already in managed care plans, much of the
savings from abandoning indemnity insurance have already been
realized.
</P>
<P>
   For Massachusetts, the news is a mixed blessing. The state's
employers and consumers will probably have to shell out more money
than ever for health care _ premiums, co-payments and deductibles
will all go up, the report projected. The added spending, however,
is expected to pump up the state's already substantial health care
sector, bringing more jobs to the state. About one in 10 workers in
Massachusetts is employed in health care.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lots of new jobs will be generated,'' said Paul Harrington,
economist with Northeastern University's Center for Labor Market
Studies. ``The question is, what will those jobs look like?''
</P>
<P>
   The study by HCFA, which oversees the federal Medicare program
for seniors, gave a few hints.
</P>
<P>
   Spending on hospital care will grow at a modest 3 percent a
year, the study said. With managed care and Medicare putting
pressure on hospitals to cut costs and send patients home sooner,
more care will be delivered in smaller clinics and at home. That
means physicians will be busier than ever with demand soaring 7.3
percent by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Prescription drugs will also eat up a larger share of health
care costs. Though the study put annual increases in drug costs at
just under 10 percent for the next 10 years, many health care
specialists believe the increases are likely to be much higher as
pharmaceutical companies continue to crank out must-have drugs such
as Viagra and Prozac.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drugs are a key driver of costs,'' said Susan Connolly,
principal at William M. Mercer Inc., a benefits consulting firm in
Boston. Connolly said some insurers are reporting up to 18 percent
annual increases for retiree drug costs and up to 14 percent for
those under 65.
</P>
<P>
   As dramatic as HCFA's projections are, many believe that the
actual increase in health care spending could very well top
government estimates.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are fairly conservative growth rates,'' said Stuart H.
Altman, professor of national health policy at the Heller Graduate
School at Brandeis University. ``The actual growths could be
substantially higher.''
</P>
<P>
   Altman said current political pressure to ease the restraints of
managed care could result in unfettered health care spending. ``The
more we reduce the power of managed care to control spending by
restricting services, the more we are going to take the pressure of
providers to constrain spending,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Altman also pointed out that the report, which projects to the
year 2007, does not include years that are likely to see the
biggest increases in health care spending, the period after 2010,
when millions of so-called Baby Boomers start hitting 65. ``The
really big growth is yet to come,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the HCFA report cited several factors that will
help cool spending, including efforts by US Congress in 1997 to
trim Medicare reimbursements.
</P>
</TEXT>
