<SLUG> BC-FBC-COLLEGE-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HURRICANES FORMING, BUT NO SERIOUS THREAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They're 2-0, which in years past would have meant an automatic
Top 25 berth.
</P>
<P>
   But these are different times, and the Big East is no longer
Miami's private playpen.
</P>
<P>
   The Hurricanes barely have gotten a sniff in the polls, but that
could change if they beat Virginia Tech _ something Miami has not
done in Butch Davis's three-year tenure _ in the Orange Bowl
Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Are the Hurricanes back to the form that won them four national
championships between 1983 and '91? Of course not. They may never
get to that level again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're closer,'' said Davis. ``But we still have only 10
seniors, and only four of them play.''
</P>
<P>
   To be an elite team, according to Davis, you need a nucleus of
at least twice that many seniors. But the Hurricanes, still feeling
the affects of NCAA probation, are not even at full scholarship
level; they have only 75, 10 below the NCAA maximum.
</P>
<P>
   How close is Miami to contending for national honors?
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple of years away,'' said Davis.
</P>
<P>
   The next two weeks should be this season's first litmus test.
With back-to-back home games against unbeaten Virginia Tech and
unbeaten UCLA, Davis knows that if Miami is 4-0 at the end of
September, his goal of getting the Hurricanes back into bowl
consideration will be halfway achieved.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Tech coach Frank Beamer naturally had words of praise
for the 'Canes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're real close to that dominating stage,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
No gimmes
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Boston College coach Tom O'Brien continues to preach caution
despite the Eagles' 2-0 record and two upcoming games against
winless teams, starting with Temple Saturday. ``They're an option
team,'' said O'Brien. ``We've not been a great defender of that
since I've been here. Our mission is to keep getting better each
week.'' ... Ask Pittsburgh coach Walt Harris the problems he'll
face against longtime rival Penn State this week and he minces no
words: ``Size, speed, and strength. That's about it.'' ... Syracuse
coach Paul Pasqualoni on the continuing development of quarterback
Donovan McNabb: ``There's improvement every week, there's
improvement every year. It's not like he's tapped out. If this
continues, there is no question in my mind, he's the best
quarterback in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Numbers do lie
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Go figure: Virginia Tech quarterback Al Clark was only 4 of 20
at the end of the first half in Saturday's game against Clemson,
yet the Hokies had a 34-0 lead. The 37-0 final marked the first
time Clemson had been shut out at home since 1979 ... With 104
points, Miami has tied the school's two-game record ... With 60
career touchdown passes, McNabb is one pass short of tying the Big
East record held by former BC quarterback Glenn Foley ...
Syracuse's 38-28 win over Michigan was its first road victory over
a ranked team since a 20-9 win over No. 20 North Carolina State
Sept. 2, 1995 ... Temple may be 0-2, but the Owls are not having
trouble running the ball. With 597 yards in two games, the Owls are
No. 4 in the country in rushing ... Virginia Tech has allowed only
3 points in two games, its best effort since 1927. The Hokies lead
the nation in scoing defense ... With three nonconference wins
Saturday, the Big East matched its best day since Sept. 10, 1994
... Clemson may want to think again before putting Big East teams
on its schedule. The last two times, the Tigers have been
outscored, 98-0 ... If BC beats Temple, the Eagles will be off to
their best start since 1992, when they began 7-0-1 ... Syracuse,
which meets Rutgers Saturday, has outscored the Scarlet Knights,
92-3, in the last two meetings ... Before the season, Temple fans
looked at a schedule that began with Toledo, Akron, BC, Maryland,
and William &AMP; Mary, and considered them all winnable games. But the
Owls are 0-2 and it is conceivable that they could be 0-5, which is
why Saturday's game against BC has become vital.
</P>
</TEXT>
