<HEADER>
A5961 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NIKE-IMAGE-NYTSF &LR;      09-15 2571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIKE-IMAGE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 THE SWOON of the SWOOSH  
 &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089.  By TIMOTHY EGAN  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 NOTE: Full-length article (3,800 words) available on request  
 &HT;    For some time now, the Nike swoosh has been showing up in the
oddest of places, dropped like an inadvertent product plug amid the
news of the day.
 &HT;    Just before 39 members of the Heaven's Gate cult swallowed a
suicide brew last year, they laced up their new black Nikes for a
post-mortem chase of a spaceship they believed was trailing the
Hale-Bopp comet.
 &HT;    Benjamin Walker, a victim of the Springfield, Ore., school
shooting in May, was so heavily swooshed in T-shirt and cap in the
photo released by authorities that media outlets felt compelled to
crop him to a tight facial mug.
 &HT;    And then there's O.J. Simpson, the last athlete any company in
the world wants to endorse its product, recently seen wearing a
Nike cap.
 &HT;    Sports are the heart of American culture, says Philip H. Knight,
Nike chairman and co-founder. He has believed this ever since he
started peddling waffle-soled running shoes out of his car trunk
more than 30 years ago. He spoke then in a language understood only
by people who could run a mile in less than five minutes.
 &HT;    Now his company slogans are uttered by presidents and
schoolchildren the world over. By Nike's own research, the swoosh
brand is recognized by 97 percent of Americans, and every man,
woman and child in the United States spends an average of $20 a
year on the company's products.
 &HT;    But be careful what you wish for: The swoosh, never more
ubiquitous, is in turnaround. Having plastered the world with a
corporate icon rivaled perhaps only by Coca-Cola's cursive, Nike is
trying desperately to tone it down, hide it, possibly even lose it.
The week before an anxious annual shareholders meeting, Nike still
looks in the mirror and sees a sleek rebel, but others see a bully
with a beer gut.
 &HT;    ``You can make a lot of mistakes around here, but the brand is
sacred,'' says Knight. ``I messed that up.''
 &HT;    Knight is pacing inside the John McEnroe Building, the
intensive-care ward for the ailing swoosh and the center of power
inside the earthen berm at Nike World Headquarters in Beaverton,
Ore. He is a reddish-haired, somewhat bulge-eyed hypercompetitor;
at 60, he still runs regularly.
 &HT;    When sneakers became a cultural force more than a decade ago,
Knight was dubbed the most powerful man in sports. But he has been
angry much of this year, hearing his company described as the
symbol for everything that is wrong not only with sports but also
with global capitalism itself.
 &HT;    Knight checks in frequently with Gordon Thompson, the company's
lead designer. Thompson's current challenge is the biggest yet: how
to persuade a new generation of consumers to latch onto a brand
trying to reinvent itself after two years of hard hits.
 &HT;    ``Hard to believe,'' says Thompson, showing a chart that
illustrates the evolution of the company logo. ``But the swoosh has
been a stand-alone logo for only four years. We were growing and
growing and growing here in Beaverton, and I guess we didn't
totally realize what happened to this thing that was supposed to be
just a sports logo.''
 &HT;    On new shoes, Thompson has started to shrink the icon down to
just a wisp of a swoosh, barely visible. ``The question we've been
asking ourselves a lot here,'' he says, is whether we should just
go ahead and take the swoosh off. That's been a pretty hefty
debate.''
 &HT;    Just a year ago, on Nike's 25th birthday, coming off the best
financial 12 months in the company's history, there was no hint of
a future without the swoosh. Its fate, the company said, was linked
to the march of sports into every corner of the planet.
 &HT;    ``The 'swooshification of the world' should more appropriately
be deemed the Sportsification of the world,'' Nike officials wrote
in the company's annual report for 1997. ``We will mature in tandem
with the inexorable penetration of sports into the global psyche.''
 &HT;    Brave words. But, as it turns out, the swoosh and sports do not
always move in tandem. Profits at Nike, the world's leading
athletic-shoe-and-apparel maker, plunged 49 percent this fiscal
year, despite record sales of $9.6 billion. More and more Nikes are
being sold by discounters, lowering the profit margin.
 &HT;    The stock price has dropped more than 50 percent this year from
highs of a year before. Two months ago, Nike reported its first
quarterly loss in 13 years, prompting the largest layoffs in
company history and a teary apology from Knight.
 &HT;    Nike still sells more than 160 million pairs of athletic shoes a
year, and nearly one out of every two pairs in the United States.
But the company had pegged its future growth to Asia, where Nike is
one of the most visible American victims of the ongoing economic
crisis.
 &HT;    Worldwide, Nike has about one-third of the total market for
athletic shoes. Its nearest competitors, Adidas and Reebok, are far
behind in the United States and abroad, but Adidas is gaining
ground. And with Michael Jordan, Nike's franchise player, bound for
retirement either this year or next, the company has yet to
discover, or manufacture, anyone even close to him.
 &HT;    Those are just a few of Nike's problems. Purists say that the
company has corrupted sport. Critics of Nike's overseas factories
abound, citing the more than 500,000 workers who often earn about
$1.50 a day. Some of these critics peg Nike's current woes to their
own efforts to tarnish the swoosh _ or the swooshsticka, as the
more rabid Nike-haters call it.
 &HT;    ``We figured out two years ago that the only way to make our
campaign against Nike's labor practices work was to try to make the
swoosh uncool,'' says Medea Benjamin, co-director of Global
Exchange, a San Francisco-based human rights group.
 &HT;    From Day 1, Nike has insisted it is a company for athletes. But
the greatest secret of the sports-footwear-and-apparel business is
that most of the product is bought by people who may want to be
like Mike or Ken Griffey Jr. or the Brazilian soccer star Ronaldo,
but seldom leave the couch.
 &HT;    ``The reason the basketball shoes have worked so well is because
80 percent of the people who buy them never set foot on a
basketball court _ it's a fashion statement,'' says Vince Francom,
a footwear-industry analyst in Seattle. ``The problem with fashion
is that tastes change very quickly. There's a big backlash against
Nike under way. The skateboard generation doesn't want to wear
Nikes because their fathers wear them.''
 &HT;    And it is the swoosh that has become emblematic of all of Nike's
troubles: a fashion statement losing its edge; a sports pyramid
that starts with cheap day labor and ends with poor kids trying to
pony up $140 for the shoes, and the lost innocence of young
athletes.
 &HT;    Knight and his closest executives have heard so much criticism
that they have started to parody it. They've hung anti-Nike
cartoons all over their walls and filled their annual report with
consumers' hate mail. So the inside question is not whether the
swoosh has gotten Nike in trouble, but how quickly to act.
 &HT;    ``We're a company founded by distance runners _ some of them
pretty slow _ so we have a certain amount of patience,'' wrote
Knight in his most recent letter to shareholders. ``Nonetheless, we
prefer to be timed by a stopwatch, not a calendar.''
 &HT;    Inside Nike's main laboratory in the Michael Jordan Building,
product developers are finishing a shoe modeled after a goat's hoof
_ the Goatster, they nicknamed it, designed to grip vertical rock
terrain. It's a niche-market shoe, of course, but who knows how
many eighth-graders might want to have the latest in extreme-sport
fashions.
 &HT;    Nike is also preparing to sell snowboards, boots, hockey sticks
and golf equipment but has dropped a curious new baseball glove.
About one-third of the company's sales last year came from clothes,
gear, watches, eyewear and other products not worn on the foot. The
swoosh is no longer being cloned along with fresh product; instead,
new logos, with separate identities, are sprouting forth.
 &HT;    A new line of Michael Jordan shoes will soon march out of the
factories, carrying the Jordan ``Jumpman'' logo. (For the recent
fiscal year, every major category of Nike footwear sold in America
suffered a decline in sales, except one _ the Jordan brand, which
increased 57 percent.) An Alpha line of shoes and clothing, vaguely
defined as ``innovative,'' will be unveiled later this year,
carrying a new logo _ five dots, a sort of elongated ellipsis.
 &HT;    Everything, it seems, is in play. Nike's most famous slogan,
``Just Do It,'' disappeared for a time this year after a
decade-long run. As it turns out, women did not take to the
admonition quite as enthusiastically as men. ``I Can'' worked
better with women, but it also sounded something like a Special
Olympics plug, and didn't go over so well with men.
 &HT;    ``The saying 'I can' sounds so weak!'' one man wrote to Nike
this year. ``And I ain't weak.'' Just what is the company slogan
these days? ``We use them all,'' says Lee Weinstein, Nike's chief
spokesman.
 &HT;    At a time when other shoe companies are backing away from
endorsements, Nike is still building its roster. It now has more
than 3,000 athletes in the fold worldwide, including 72 percent of
the players in the National Basketball Association, 60 percent in
Major League Baseball and half the players in the National Football
League. More than 200 universities fly the flag of swoosh.
 &HT;    The multipierced illustrated man of basketball, Dennis Rodman,
was once a Nike guy, but the company revoked his swoosh. ``He's a
great player,'' Knight says, ``but he's crazy.''
 &HT;    Shaquille O'Neal, the telegenic center with the high-wattage
smile, showed up a few years ago at the Nike campus for a
get-acquainted session _ swathed in Reebok gear. Things went
downhill from there.
 &HT;    Knight likes winners, of course, but rebels are closest to his
heart. The NBA tried to ban the first Air Jordans (they weren't
considered regulation sneakers), much to the delight of Knight.
There was cheering inside the John McEnroe Building when Casey
Martin, the disabled golfer whose cause Knight took up when it
looked like a long shot, challenged the golf establishment and
became the first man to play the United States Open in a powered
cart.
 &HT;    ``What we are all about,'' Knight says, ``is being against the
establishment.'' Yes, but what happens when you are the
establishment, when the swoosh shows up in more country clubs than
asphalt alleys?
 &HT;    Nike's response has been to try new ways of ``branding.'' Nike,
of course, is not alone in this pursuit. The idea is simply to
create a connection between consumer and product, a link often
having nothing to do with what is actually being sold. Nike has
always tried to sell something more than leather and nylon,
promoting the swoosh as a personal statement.
 &HT;    But the retail world is littered with once-thriving brandings
that have ended badly. L.A. Gear, for example, was an upstart
sneaker company that rode the aerobics craze to dizzying heights,
then crashed when it tried to put its label on too many other
things.
 &HT;    But if the swoosh does not light up advertising focus groups the
way it used to, Nike has another icon that has yet to show a
downside: Jordan. Last June, in the midst of Nike's deepening
troubles, came the most glorious 59 seconds of the year for the
company.
 &HT;    Just when it was said that the greatest person ever to play the
game was past his pull date, the old man did it again. In Game 6 of
the NBA Finals, Nike's franchise player singlehandedly pulled off a
victory _ and the championship _ while wearing a pair of Air Jordan
XIV's, which retail for about $150. The shoe sailed out of stores.
 &HT;    Clinging to Jordan as long as possible, Nike may bring out a
line of Jordan casual shoes, following up with everything from
Jordan socks to suits. Nike executives figure that if Tommy
Hilfiger and Ralph Lauren, neither of whom ever did anything
dramatic on a basketball court, can sell billions of dollars worth
of clothing, the world's best-known athlete can do the same, or
much better.
 &HT;    If Nike takes this step with Jordan, it would mark a huge leap
into relatively unfamiliar retail territory. The last time the
company tried such a thing, selling so-called ``brown shoes'' in
the mid-1980s, it was clobbered. Knight says the company learned
its lesson. Still, Jordan's name is so strong that Nike cannot seem
to resist what they see as his Midas touch.
 &HT;    Jordan, arguably the company's best asset, is planning to tour
the Nike factories in Asia, arguably the company's worst liability.
It was Jordan's idea, says Weinstein, the company spokesman. Jordan
has grown tired of all the questions about factory wages and says
he wants to see firsthand what the fuss is about.
 &HT;    Still, his tour is designed not so much to cheer up factory
hands in Hanoi as to connect with a particular brand of swoosh
consumers: females. The labor issue keeps coming up in focus groups
with girls as young as 12, Nike executives told me.
 &HT;    Knight has seen the future of his industry and it does not have
an Adam's apple. Twenty-five years ago, he says, only 1 in 30
school-age girls played sports; today it's 1 in 5. Nearly 40
percent of high-school athletes are girls. And so the Nike poster
athlete of the new millennium is a female American soccer player,
Mia Hamm.
 &HT;    I ran this name by many of my sports-loving friends, all of them
ESPN habitues, runners and soccer parents. We buy gear and
channel-surf with the best of them. Our reaction was the same: Who?
 &HT;    Then I asked my 11-year-old daughter about Mia Hamm, and she
looked at me as if I were as dumb as a fence post. With Hamm, Nike
has managed to go below adult radar, just as Tom Clarke alluded to
on our run.
 &HT;    Hamm is 26 years old, from Chapel Hill, N.C., winner of an
Olympic gold medal and a World Championship title. She is
beautiful. She can use a verb. She has the right hint of attitude.
And if enough people ever start watching women's soccer _ Nike is
heavily promoting next year's Women's World Cup, to be staged in
the United States _ she may be gold for the Beaverton sneaker
company.
 &HT;    ``Why shouldn't girls around the world say, 'I want to be like
Mia?''' asks Katherine Melchior Ray, the head of Nike women's
footwear.
 &HT;    At Nike, that refrain can sound like a prayer.
 &HT;     c.1998 The New York Times Magazine  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Timothy Egan is a national correspondent for The New York
Times.) &LR;
</P>
