<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-OPEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERVICE WITH A SMILE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Long Lindsay Davenport, US Open champion, walked the
walk.
</P>
<P>
   She gracefully stepped up onto the short wall around the
Unisphere just outside the National Tennis Center grounds and with
a half-dozen kids frolicking in the fountains behind her and a few
dozen photographers capturing the moment in front of her, she
walked this way, then that, on the wall _ showing her stuff.
</P>
<P>
   She raised high the silver cup that will now bear her name after
her straight-set win over Martina Hingis in Saturday's final. She
held it in front of her. She held it beside her. She kissed it. And
a rainbow formed behind her in the spray from the fountain.
</P>
<P>
   It was one of the feel-good moments of the 1998 Open.
</P>
<P>
   There was the rise of Australian Mark Philippoussis, who in 1996
showed all kinds of promise in blasting Pete Sampras out of the
Australian Open and is now adding the rest of the game and mindset
to go with a biggest-in-the-major-leagues serve.
</P>
<P>
   There was the fun-loving Patrick Rafter, who defeated
Philippoussis in the final. Gotta like a mate who seemed to get
nearly as much a kick out of the Pearl Jam and Ben Harper concert
he attended Thursday night between his quarterfinal and semifinal
wins _ ``one of the best concerts I've ever been to'' _ as he did
his second Open title.
</P>
<P>
   There was the good-natured and refreshingly forthright Carlos
Moya. After losing in the semifinals to Philippoussis, Moya said
he'd better not comment on the officiating in the match, and
proceeded to do just that. First, he said, there really was no need
for a chair umpire since they never overruled anything; things
might as well be left in the hands of the linespeople. But then he
remembered one of the calls that got him going and seemed to
reconsider.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry to say, but the woman was a little bit old,'' Moya
said. ``You know, the ball was like 130 miles. How can she see that
ball?''
</P>
<P>
   There was Hingis, smiling still, coming back from her loss to
Davenport to team with Jana Novotna to beat Davenport and Natasha
Zvereva for the women's doubles title, finishing off a doubles
Grand Slam. Hingis teamed with Mirjana Lucic to win at the
Australian Open and then joined Novotna for wins at the French and
Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   There was the balance in the world of tennis that this
tournament again demonstrated. With Rafter winning his second
consecutive title, there were four different men's winners of this
year's four majors _ the Australian Open won by Marcelo Rios, the
French by Moya, and Wimbledon by Sampras.
</P>
<P>
   Same thing on the women's side, with Hingis in the Australian,
Arantxa Sanchez Vicario in the French, Novotna at Wimbledon, and
now Davenport. The win in Australia gave Hingis three straight
majors, and it looked as if she was ready to dominate. That hardly
seems likely this morning.
</P>
<P>
   Not only must she contend with veterans Sanchez Vicario, Monica
Seles, and Steffi Graf, but there are Novotna, the Sister Williams,
and a host of others, especially Davenport.
</P>
<P>
   Ahh, Davenport.
</P>
<P>
   After getting back to the hotel Saturday, she reveled in her win
and the on-court festivities _ ``the stuff that happened on the
court, it's all a blur'' _ and caught about a half-hour for herself
before she and family and friends went out to celebrate her win and
her mother's birthday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thinking about what I had done, that I had accomplished the
goal I wanted to do,'' she said, ``you can't describe things like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a goal she achieved against most bets. At 6 feet 3
inches, she was too lumbering, not fit enough, not athletic enough,
many tennis followers said. She made herself plenty fit. She covers
the court.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport, 22, blew Venus Williams, 18, off the court in the
semis. She blew Hingis, 18 later this month, off it in the finals.
She never lost so much as a set in the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   And while handlers arranged this television appearance and
turned down that one Sunday, she was being whisked around the
Tennis Center grounds on a golf cart, from this press conference to
that photo opportunity, the US Open champion.
</P>
</TEXT>
