<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARR-CLINTON-PROBE-ADVISORY-NYTSF </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Pegged to the release of Kenneth Starr's report on the
investigation of President Clinton, The New York Times Syndicate is
offering a series of four articles based on ``Ken Starr Would Not
Be Denied,'' a feature story by Michael Winerip, a staff writer for
The New York Times Magazine. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   __ The articles have been released in the ``k'' commentary and
``a'' general news categories. __
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; PART I: ``What Drives Ken Starr?'' (1,500 words) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   During his early career, Ken Starr, a minister's son, was
considered too bland, cautious and reserved to have political
enemies. But Starr changed into a prosecutor so relentless that he
drove a U.S. president to admit his sins on national television.
What changed Starr is unclear. By now, however, Starr's character
has forever altered President Clinton's destiny. (slugged:
BC-STARR-CLINTON-PROBE-ONE-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; PART II: ``Ken Starr's Passions: Religion, Politics and the
Supreme Court'' (2,200 words) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``If it was fun, you couldn't do it,'' says a childhood friend,
recalling Ken Starr's religious upbringing _ no drinking, smoking,
dancing or musical instruments in church. It didn't keep Starr from
becoming fascinated with politics, though, and campaigning for
Nixon and Goldwater. Beyond that, Starr's driving ambition, one
that now he will never attain, was to become chief justice of the
Supreme Court. (slugged: STARR-CLINTON-PROBE-TWO- NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; PART III: ``Ken Starr's Search for Truth'' (1,600 words) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   When Ken Starr compared himself to Joe Friday, the detective on
TV's erstwhile ``Dragnet'' _``just the facts, ma'am; only the
facts'' _ it seemed laughable. But today, a search for truth is
probably one of the most charitable interpretations that can be
made of his dogged pursuit of President Clinton. (slugged:
STARR-CLINTON-PROBE-THREE-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; PART IV: ``The Shadow Bill Clinton Can't Shake'' (1,550
words) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Ken Starr has been willing to drive on in the Monica Lewinsky
investigation long after many other prosecutors would have stopped.
Some say he is driven by hate, others by religious values, others
by moral outrage at Clinton's escapades, others by his legal
temperament and love of the law. But at this point Starr's motives
are secondary. The question is, What is to be done with President
Clinton, and how badly has the whole affair fractured the American
body politic? (slugged: STARR-CLINTON- PROBE-FOUR-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (To publish this series _ which has already moved free to
clients of the Centerpiece package _ please contact one of these
New York Times Syndicate sales representatives: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
