<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5985 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-REVIEW-TOMCAT-HN     09-15 1218
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-REVIEW-TOMCAT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW O'BRIEN BOOK TACKLES LOVE OBSESSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDVINS BEITIKS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you approach Tim O'Brien's ``Tomcat in Love'' with an open
mind, with no preconceived notions, you're likely to rave about the
book.
</P>
<P>
   But if you come in with any kind of moral baggage, built up over
years of seeing people at their best and worst, ``Tomcat in Love''
may give you some problems. O'Brien knows that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tomcat in Love'' (Broadway Books, New York, $26, 347 pages),
the seventh book by the author of ``Going After Cacciato'' and ``In
the Lake of the Woods,'' is the story of a self-deluding,
skirt-chasing, revenge-obsessed professor of language who wallows
from one love-starved episode to another. Sometimes he's funny.
Sometimes he's not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say he's the kind of guy I'd want to have dinner
with,'' O'Brien said in a telephone interview from Cambridge, Mass.
``It's like going to a cocktail party and coming home to tell your
wife, `I can't believe the guy I met at this party _ he was
hair-splitting, equivocating, bombastic. I didn't like him, but I
was fascinated by him.'''
</P>
<P>
   The character, Thomas A. Chippering, grew out of O'Brien's
attempt to write a memoir about his Minnesota childhood. ``I
thought I was writing a nonfiction piece,'' he said. ``I was trying
to be faithful to the facts, to the dialogues. But the farther I
got into it, I had to resign myself to the fact I was writing
another novel.''
</P>
<P>
   Chippering, owning up to an age of 49, maybe more, is a tall,
raw-boned Abe Lincoln look-alike who fancies himself the pudding of
life for any woman half his age. He hits on them anywhere, any time
_ in a bar, in a shop, in the classroom _ while pushing away a
beautifully honest woman who's trying to give him the romantic life
he keeps saying he wants.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien didn't start out seeing himself in Chippering. ``He was
a totally separate character. But you work from your experience.
Certainly I like girls, and ... in the course of the novel, I felt
I became him.''
</P>
<P>
   With its narrative of a gentleman ranker on a lifelong spree,
there are bound to be comparisons between O'Brien's book and the
works of Elmore Leonard and Kingsley Amis. But O'Brien never gave
them a thought while he was pounding away, any more than he
anticipated the Clintonesque saga you can read into ``Tomcat in
Love.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien started a nationwide book tour earlier this month _
``three months on the road, selling your own brand of snake oil.''
Before he's through, O'Brien expects to get plenty of questions
about President Clinton, Monica Lewinsky and the women in between,
partly because there's a passage in the book that could have been
lifted verbatim from the post-confession dialogue surrounding
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   It reads, ```Thomas, for God's sake,' she said forcefully, out
of the feminine nowhere, `just this once I wish you'd stop
justifying everything. Just one time in your wishy-washy life! ...
I mean, Jesus, you're like some fickle, randy old tomcat,' Mrs.
Kooshof was saying, loud enough to attract the attention of a buxom
young businesswoman across the aisle. (Jade eyes. Toshiba computer.
A come-hither upper carriage that had caught my eye back at the
boarding gate in Tampa.) `I'm serious, you should be neutered _ no
morals at all. Can't you at least apologize?'''
</P>
<P>
   Of the presidential romances, O'Brien said, ``When I started
this book four years ago, none of this stuff was known. Chippering
is probably like Clinton, probably a lot like all of us. He craves
affection. He craves love. He'll tell little white lies for love.
He'll go to war for love. He'll do a lot of things for love, both
good and bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's why he's sympathetic,'' O'Brien said. ``For all
his bravado, he has a hole in the side of him that he's trying to
fill up with love, wherever he can get it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the book, Chippering argues that his craving for affection is
``like some horrid cancer ... the benign became malignant.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue is love, not sex, he says, pointing out he's had
carnal knowledge of ``a paltry four women. (Or three. Depending.)''
On the other hand, Chippering lists 128 near misses, 212 love
letters and ``well over five hundred significant flirtations and
alliances and dalliances. (I keep books. I do a rigorous monthly
tally. The count counts.)''
</P>
<P>
   ``And yet the quantities never proved sufficient,'' he says. ``I
had to keep fueling the furnace, refilling the hole, topping off my
leaky love tank.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien chuckled, remembering Chippering's comeback to women who
claim he ``just doesn't get it'' _ ``Hey,'' the professor says. ``I
get plenty!''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Chippering puts the moves on two hookers in a hotel bar,
only to wake up penniless in the pew of a plasticized church, it's
a bag of grins. But every scene like that is tempered by malevolent
ones like Chippering getting pantsed in front of his class, playing
the fool as a kids'-show host or walking around with Mason jars
filled with gasoline, threatening mayhem.
</P>
<P>
   The book's beginning, with young Chippering and his friend,
Herbie, moving to crucify Herbie's sister, offers no hint that
``Tomcat in Love'' is supposed to be a knee-slapper. Chippering's
courting of Lorna Sue, prom queen in a houseful of weirdsmobiles,
is a mix of mock horror and high-school humor, and the professor's
studied revenge on Lorna Sue, her brother and her new lover _ built
on a lie of incest _ winds up being both ugly and grotesque.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tomcat in Love'' also touches on Vietnam, in a tongue-in-cheek
search-and-destroy mission with Green Berets who leave Chippering,
a headquarters geek, alone in the jungle. Chippering finds them in
a dream villa on the edge of the paddies and calls an air strike
down on the position, leaving the Berets scorched and angry _
setting up later forays into Chippering's life that become, oddly,
some of the most moving moments in the book.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien, who served in Vietnam, has been labeled a Vietnam War
writer. ``But I think of myself more as a love writer than a war
writer. I use the war like other writers use the ocean ...
Everybody defines something that's singular and permanent in their
histories, and Vietnam was a huge part of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Going After Cacciato'' is filled with surprise passages of
almost-poetry _ ``Blue gunpowder haze produced musical sighs in the
gloom, a stirring at the base of Buddha's clay feet.'' So is ``In
the Lake of the Woods'' (``Tracer rounds corkscrewed through the
glare, and people were dying in long neat rows. The sunlight was in
his blood.'')
</P>
<P>
   There are fewer of those moments in ``Tomcat in Love,'' but the
book still has the O'Brien touch _ ``I am forever astonished at the
longevity of childhood. How it never ends. How we are what we were.
How turtles and engines and stolen kisses leave their jet trail
across our gaping lives.''
</P>
<P>
   There's an underlying heartbreak behind ``Tomcat in Love,''
O'Brien said. ``We're all blind to the bounties around us. That's
one blindness we all have. There's this incredible opportunity for
love and affection, and we can't see it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been there,'' he said. ``Most people have.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
