<HEADLINE>
NO NEED TO PANIC AS YEAR 2000 NEARS &HT;     

</HEADLINE>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PAMELA YIP 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   The year 2000 problem is a computer programmer's nightmare that
has spawned a community of survivalists convinced that bad software
will have apocalyptic consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Their fear is that computer programs unable to recognize the
year 2000 will paralyze the banking system, throwing our economy
into total havoc.
</P>
<P>
   They're entitled to their beliefs, but I don't see this as a
time to write a column for financial planning Armageddon-style.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are some bread-and-butter issues raised by what is
better known as the Y2K issue.
</P>
<P>
   While bankers said they've got the situation under control, it
could pay to hold onto paper records of bank transactions.
</P>
<P>
   It also wouldn't hurt to carry some extra cash on New Year's Eve
1999 _ just in case your money machine fails you.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Federal Reserve Board plans to stock up on cash in
case nervous Americans want more of it in their pockets on the eve
of the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   The concern is that Americans might worry about whether credit
cards and automated teller machines will still work after the new
century dawns and want to be holding more cash just in case.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
LOSING TRACK OF TIME &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Y2K problem, also known as the ``Millennium Bug,'' is the
name given to problems with computer programs that use only the
last two digits of the year to keep track of dates. Most older
programs, which were written this way to reduce the amount of code,
are unable to distinguish between the current century and the
previous one.
</P>
<P>
   If the problem isn't fixed, it could cause chaos in all sectors
of the economy, especially in the technology-dependent financial
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something about not being able to get your money
out,'' said Jerry Miller, president of Regcom in Geneva, Ill., a
bank consulting firm. ``It brings the highest level of panic and
fear into a person.''
</P>
<P>
   Banks, which use computer systems for such tasks as financial
calculations, tracking deposits and loan payments, transferring
funds and making direct deposits, said they've long been working on
eliminating the Millennium Bug.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're working very diligently as part of our plan to make Year
2000 pretty much a non-event,'' said Eroy Wilkins, vice president
and manager of the Year 2000 Program office of Chase Bank of Texas.
``We're not going to be losing any records. We won't lose any
service at all with any of our customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts said banks are more prepared than many other industries
for the Y2K bug because banking regulators have laid down a strict
schedule for bringing computer systems up to speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't foresee any major problems in the banking industry
with respect to anything that a bank can control,'' said Al
Watkins, a partner and banking attorney at Gardere Wynne Sewell &AMP;
Riggs in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators are conducting periodic examinations to ensure that
banks are working on the problem and are also requiring banks to
work with their suppliers and other outside partners to ensure that
their systems link properly when 2000 comes around.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
KEEP RECORDS, JUST IN CASE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you've ever had your bank records messed up, you probably
feel the need to be sure things will work right when 2000 arrives.
</P>
<P>
   Start keeping records of bank transactions made a few months
before Jan. 1, 2000. These records will help you resolve any
account errors that might occur.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am optimistic that there will not be significant problems
for customers,'' said Janis Gogan, assistant professor of
accountancy at Bentley College in Waltham, Mass., who teaches a
graduate course on Y2K projects. ``However, I would nevertheless
hang on to paper copies of bank statements, ATM slips, etc., in
order to easily reconstruct balances should systems fail and cause
erroneous data to show up on statements early in January 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the banks said they can't guarantee something won't go
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really too early for the prudent scholar or professional
to make any type of prediction on what can fail and what the impact
is,'' said Louis Barton, vice president and program director for
the Year 2000 at Frost Bank in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Banks are even preparing plans in case of a breakdown in power
or telecommunications lines, said Sally Pope Davis, an analyst at
investment bank Goldman Sachs in New York, which recently held a
conference on the Y2K problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the presenters at the conference emphasized that there
will be some failures post Jan. 1, 2000, and Electronic Data
Systems even applied a version of Murphy's Law: That which cannot
fail, will,'' Davis said in a report.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
To voice comments, telephone 713-220-2000 and dial in code 1003.
Send e-mail to pamela.yip at chron.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
