<P>
   THE CLINTON IMPEACHMENT INQUIRY
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton attends a military
readiness conference at Fort McNair in suburban Virginia on Tuesday
and preps for a Wednesday news conference that will be his first
since the Starr report was released. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-DEFENSE _ WASHINGTON _ With President Clinton under
pressure to abandon his defense that false statements under oath
are not necessarily perjury, the White House plans to name new
attorneys Tuesday to the team that is coordinating the response and
dealing with Congress. (Dart, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-JURY _ WASHINGTON _ Did the grand jury that heard
testimony on President Clinton's relationship with Monica Lewinsky
have any role in what went in or was left out of Independent
Counsel Kenneth Starr's report to Congress? Will the grand jury be
the one that ultimately decides what, if anything, is sufficient to
indict Clinton? What is the grand jury's role now? (Malone, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-JUDICIARY _ WASHINGTON _ The Judiciary Committee that
will conduct any impeachment hearings is composed of diverse
factions likely to go in many different directions once the
questioning begins. We handicap the committee, looking at who will
likely to be the defenders to the end, the harshest critics and
those in between. (Carr, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-GADELEGATION _ WASHINGTON _ Now that Congress has had a
chance to read the Starr report, what are the members of the
Georgia delegation saying and what are their constituents telling
them. (Foskett, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CLASS _ ATLANTA _ Oglethorpe University in Atlanta is
sponsoring a class called ``Love, Sex and Politics: From
Aristophanes to President Clinton.'' We take notes. (Smith, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BOB-DOLE _ SAN ANTONIO _ Bob Dole, whose lifelong dream of the
presidency was snatched away by Bill Clinton, speaks to university
students Tuesday evening about values and leadership in the 21st
century. (Greenberger, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   TELCOM-CONGRESS _ WASHINGTON _ Antitrust, business rights and
competition subcommittee holds a hearing on the effects of
consolidation in the telecommunications industry. (Glass, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   ADOPTION-RACE _ WASHINGTON _ A House subcommittee headed by Rep.
E. Clay Shaw, R-Fla., holds a hearing on interethnic adoption.
Witnesses include former Sen. Howard Metzenbaum, D-Ohio. (Monroe,
Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   FLAFIRES _ Florida's wildfire crisis may have been extinguished
two months ago, but some areas are still suffering the lingering
impact. Daytona Beach just closed out its normally busy summer
season with a disappointing Labor Day weekend that was hampered by
cloudy skies. Many merchants say the dismal business climate has
never recovered since the fires caused the wholesale cancellation
of the July 4 weekend, normally the summer's busiest. Some hope the
upcoming Pepsi 400 stockcar race, rescheduled from July 4 to early
October, will help them recover some of the lost business. We
interview business owners and officials. (Williams, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   REFUGEE _ Viep Le is the latest in a recent string of former
South Vietnamese POWs to settle in the Dayton area, with the
assistance of local churches. Story looks at hardships Le and his
family faced in Vietnam since the communist takeover, how they
eventually came to the U.S. and how Le feels about the U.S. taking
so long to rescue the South Vietnamese soldiers who often fought
side-by-side with American GIs. Story will include a box on how
local congregations can help in sponsoring other such immigrants.
(DeBrosse/Bennish, Dayton Daily News). 40. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   FLAFIRES-GEL _ JUPITER, Fla. _ Five years ago firefighter John
Bartlett had an idea about how to protect homes, utility poles,
timber, you name it, from advancing fires. He turned the idea into
a product _ Barricade fire gel. After it saved homes in July's
wildfires, the world took notice. (Reid, Palm Beach Post) WITH
PHOTO. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   UT-MINORITIES _ AUSTIN, Texas _ The University of Texas, trying
to build a diverse student body without affirmative action,
enrolled slightly more black and Hispanic freshmen this fall,
indicating that a law requiring state colleges to admit freshmen in
the top 10 percent of their high school class could be helping.
What is clear at UT is that a higher percentage of black and
Hispanic freshmen came from the ranks of the top 10 percent than
those enrolled in the past two years. (Roser, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
