<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PETS-NEUTICLES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PET OWNERS CONSIDER IMPLANTS FOR THEIR NEUTERED ANIMALS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLIFFORD PUGH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When it came time to have her pooch neutered, Glenda Nelson
decided to give him a couple of extra ``treats.''
</P>
<P>
   So while the chow lost his, er, doghood, he gained a set of
canine testicular implants known as Neuticles so he could still
feel intact.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he feels better about himself (with the implants),''
Nelson says. ``Animals are like people in many ways.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea of implanting fake testicles in a pet sounds like
something the characters on ``Seinfeld'' might joke about.
</P>
<P>
   But the product is drawing qualified praise from animal-control
experts for soothing the qualms of some people _ usually men _ who
might otherwise be hesitant to neuter their pets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it's a guy thing,'' says Spring veterinarian Debra
Garrison, the owner of Treaschwig Veterinary Clinic. ``They feel
their dogs aren't masculine unless they have something hanging
there.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past three years, more than 14,000 pairs of Neuticles
have been implanted in dogs and cats around the nation and in nine
foreign countries, says Gregg Miller, inventor of the product and
president of the Missouri-based company that makes them.
</P>
<P>
   Miller came up with the idea for the product after taking his
bloodhound, Buck, to the vet to be neutered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like many dog owners, I hesitated at neutering Buck because
Buck would no longer be Buck,'' he recalls.
</P>
<P>
   Miller went ahead with the procedure but asked his veterinarian
if there was an implant so Buck could look the same afterward. The
vet said he had never heard of such a thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that moment, Neuticles were born,'' Miller says. ``It's a
simple idea that has blossomed into a worldwide procedure.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, the jelly-bean-shaped implants are available in five sizes
_ to fit dogs ranging from Chihuahuas to Great Danes. They cost
from $25 to $32 a pair for the polypropylene version, which feels
like hard plastic, and $89 to $129 for a silicone pair, which has
the feel and texture of a Gummi bear.
</P>
<P>
   There are also miniature models for cats and extra-large models
for horses or bulls. Implanting the Neuticles occurs at the same
time the animal is neutered and adds only about two to three extra
minutes of surgical time, Miller says.
</P>
<P>
   He also maintains that the product is so close to the real thing
that the pet will not even know he's been neutered upon waking up
with a set of Neuticles, even though his sex drive will be gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``People underestimate the intelligence of dogs. Common sense
will tell you the dog misses his testicles,'' Miller says. ``If
he's hungry, he wants to be fed. When he has a flea, he scratches.
Why wouldn't he miss a familiar body part?''
</P>
<P>
   However, Lyn Johnson, a resident in companion animal behavior at
the College of Veterinary Medicine at Texas A&AMP;M University, scoffs
at the notion that the pet would know what he's missing. She says
the testicular implant replacements are for cosmetic reasons only
and have no medical value.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neuticles are definitely something for treating the owners and
not the pet,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who raises and breeds Pembrook Welsh corgis, says she
would never consider Neuticles when neutering her dogs that are not
of breeding quality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally don't care if I look between their hind legs and
see something there or not,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Yet she concedes that a lot of men are hesitant to neuter their
pets because they identify with the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   ``They put themselves in the dog's place (and think): `How would
I feel if I did not look like I was intact?' '' she says. ``The
dogs truly don't care.''
</P>
<P>
   So if the product encourages someone to neuter his pet, Johnson
sees nothing wrong with it. The Houston Society for the Prevention
of Cruelty to Animals agrees with her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thousands of animals die in Houston-area shelters every year
simply because people won't spay and neuter their pets,'' HSPCA
spokeswoman Stacy Fox says. ``If this will convince someone to
neuter their dog or cat and it doesn't harm the animal, then it
would be something we would certainly support.''
</P>
<P>
   Diana Blessman, a veterinarian at Kings Crossing Animal Hospital
in Kingwood, found that in at least one case where a dog needed to
be neutered for medical reasons, his owner was relieved when she
mentioned Neuticles.
</P>
<P>
   ``That made it easier for him to make the decision,'' Blessman
says. ``There's not a medical reason to do this, but I don't think
it hurts (the pet) in any way.''
</P>
<P>
   About 1 { years ago, Gene Pahnke had his German shepherd and
Labrador mixed-breed dog neutered and made a spur-of-the-moment
decision to have Neuticles implanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``My initial thought was that it was for him psychologically.
But after I got him home and thought about it, I said, `Wow, that
was kind of dumb.' What is he going to know? He's a dog,'' Pahnke
says.
</P>
<P>
   Although the dog has suffered no complications from the
Neuticles, Pahnke would not have them implanted if he had it to do
over again.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Pahnke has found that his decision to give his pet some
Neuticles has been a good conversation starter, although no one has
told him it was a silly thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Nelson, who won the Neuticles in a radio
contest two years ago, had no qualms about having had the procedure
performed on her chow named Bear.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't know the difference, and he still has big ideas
when other dogs come around,'' she says. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
