<SLUG> BC-POP-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARTIST TAKES A POPULIST APPROACH
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  with 4 photos 
 
By PATRICIA C. JOHNSON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Stephen Keene deftly choreographs his movements. With
a rhythmic dip, dab, dab, dab, he makes identical brushstrokes on
each of 20 or 30 plywood panels lined up around him. Dip, stroke,
stroke, stroke, and a thicker brush with a different color of paint
fills in another part of the pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the dips and dabs, strokes and sloshes coalesce into
a recognizable image _ a landscape, the corridors of Rice
University, a flower.
</P>
<P>
   The 41-year-old artist from Brooklyn is a one-man assembly line.
He takes himself and his painting seriously, he asserts, but he
also wants it to be fun. Not only that, but Keene also wants to
dissolve distinctions between Art with a capital A and art that
everyone can understand and afford. Price tags range from $1 to
$20, but most cost $2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want people to get a fresh idea of what art is, what an art
exhibit can be,'' Keene said. ``It's just what I do.''
</P>
<P>
   Keene has set up shop inside the Rice University Art Gallery,
where he will paint and sell his work over the next five weeks. The
gallery is already crammed floor to ceiling and wall to wall with
some 2,000 paintings and painted objects he brought with him as
start-up inventory. They create a kind of maze; at its center, the
paint-splattered artist works on 20 or 30 panels simultaneously.
He's arranged buckets of acrylic and house paint, in colors from
yolk yellow to hot pink and black, on a tarp on the floor for easy,
one-swoop reach.
</P>
<P>
   He estimates that by the time his residency ends in Houston on
Oct. 18, he will have produced _ and sold _ some 1,000 original
works of art. Because he works 10 hours a day, six days a week, and
churns out 40 to 60 paintings each day, can there be any doubt
he'll meet predictions?
</P>
<P>
   Born in 1957, Keene received his bachelor's degree in fine arts
from Virginia Commonwealth University in 1981, and his master's
degree from Yale three years later. He was once a more conventional
artist, spending a lot of time on a single landscape that might
sell for $400 _ until, as he tells it, he changed tactics primarily
to relieve his boredom.
</P>
<P>
   His friends are musicians, not visual artists. He's designed
numerous covers for CDs, and, until recently, he held his
exhibitions in rock clubs and performance spaces, not art venues.
His exhibition last fall at Moore College of Art in Philadelphia
was his first in a formal academic setting. It sparked a flurry of
publicity, including a one-page feature in Time magazine, with
everyone taking sides _ roughly, delighted buyers on one side,
outraged professors on the other.
</P>
<P>
   He's been called everything from cynical and mean-spirited to
the Johnny Appleseed of art. Keene shrugs it all off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not trying to be provocative. I don't feel connected to
any kind of artwork or movement,'' he says. ``I feel like a baker
making cakes, making a good-quality object that's affordable to
everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   There is neither pretense nor coyness in Keene's words and
attitude, just some welcome levity as he stands perfectly
camouflaged in paint-splattered T-shirt and jeans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think of this whole room as the work,'' he says, gesturing
at the painting-choked space, ``with the individual pieces as
souvenirs. I think of the paintings as props of a performance.''
</P>
<P>
   It's an apt analogy. At Rice, with its glass-fronted gallery,
it's art as sideshow. So, what's wrong with that? Nothing, really.
Keene is skillful in his performance, and his populist attitude is
refreshing. But there is an important caveat. The viewer should
understand that there is a difference between Art _ a painting by
Diego Velazquez, say, with its enduring impact on eye and psyche _
and Keene's pictures and antics, which elicit a momentary smile.
</P>
<P>
   Keene doesn't argue with the principle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the greatest art in the world,'' he says, ``it's just
my art.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Stephen Keene: Fresh Art Daily &QL; 
When: 11 a.m.-5 p.m. Tuesdays-Saturdays, until 8 p.m. Thursday
evenings, and noon-5 p.m. Sundays. Sales on Sunday only, limit two
works per person. Choose what you like and drop the money in the
box. &QL; 
Where: Rice University Art Gallery, Entrance 1 off Main Street and
Sunset to Rice campus, 713-527-6069. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
