<SLUG> BC-STUTTERING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUTTERS FIND DEFECT NO REASON TO PAUSE IN LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SYLVIA WOOD  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Joy Emery has been married for 26 years. Only in
recent years was she able to say her husband's name.
</P>
<P>
   That's because Emery, 59, stutters. And words that start with
``L'' or ``W'' _ like ``love,'' ``wedding'' and ``Wyman,'' the man
she married on July 14, 1972 _ are especially troublesome. Today,
after more than 50 years of therapy, frustration and fortitude,
Emery is finally speaking with a fluency she never imagined
possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had been brought up to think something is wrong with me,''
said the Clifton Park, N.Y., woman, who began stuttering at age 3.
``Even my family thought something was wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, studies show that the estimated 3 million Americans who
stutter do not suffer from nervous or personality disorders. They
are normal, except for their inability to speak fluently. The list
of notable people who stutter, past and present, confirms this:
Charles Darwin, Winston Churchill, James Earl Jones, Carly Simon
and John Updike, who summed up the condition in his memoir,
``Self-Consciousness'':
</P>
<P>
   ``The defect arises, it would seem, from self-consciousness _ a
failure to let the intricate muscular events of speech be
sub-conscious.''
</P>
<P>
   For reasons no one can explain, the problem usually goes away
when people sing, whisper, speak in chorus or do not hear their own
voice.
</P>
<P>
   If you've noticed that the above list is mostly men, you've
picked up another important fact: Stuttering affects four times as
many men as women. It has been around as long as the spoken word.
The effects can be devastating.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't go to parties,'' Emery said. ``I didn't feel like I
had any friends in school ... I didn't go to college because they
felt the stress of it was going to be too tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite decades of study, stuttering is still one of the most
misunderstood disorders, usually affecting children between the
ages of two and seven as they learn to speak.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say identifying the problem as early as possible is
important to treating it.
</P>
<P>
   ``An absolutely clean definition that fits everyone doesn't
exist,'' said Sister Charlene Bloom, who has made stuttering her
life's work at the College of St. Rose in Albany, where is a
professor of communications disorders and coordinates the Capital
District Council of Fluency, a weekly therapy session for people
who stutter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a complex, multidimensional disorder. There isn't an easy
answer or an easy cause,'' Bloom said.
</P>
<P>
   That hasn't kept researchers from trying to develop a cure based
on new evidence that stuttering may be caused by the part of our
brain that controls speech.
</P>
<P>
   Clinical trials are currently under way in California to test
the effectiveness of the drug Risperdal to reduce stuttering.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point in time, the studies have to be long-term and
with a greater number of people before I say it's the treatment of
choice,'' said Charles Diggs, of the American
Speech-Language-Hearing Association.
</P>
<P>
   The standard treatment is speech therapy. People who stutter are
encouraged to try various strategies, from stuttering as much as
they can to controlling the way they breathe.
</P>
<P>
   Becoming fluent has been a lifetime challenge for Dr. Robert
Brown, a retired Albany anesthesiologist and native of Scotland,
who practices at weekly meetings of the Capital District Council of
Fluency.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the 74-year-old speaks with only occasional hesitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nowadays, I love going on a journey, a plane, a ship and
finding someone to talk to. In my earlier life, I never would have
done that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Emery, too, said she's making up for lost time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a great deal more assertive now,'' she said. ``I can stand
up for myself now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
