<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SQUIRRELS DRIVE GARDENER NUTS &HT;    
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY HUBER 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   Q. I would like to know how to keep squirrels from digging the
plants in my flowerpots. I have tried red pepper and black pepper,
and it doesn't keep them away.
</P>
<P>
   _ C.L.D., Houston
</P>
<P>
   A. &UR;  &LR; You might try dusting the area with garlic powder. But you
may need to resort to a physical barrier such as 1- to 2-inch wire
mesh placed on the soil or stretched across the top of the pot. You
will need to cut and secure the wire. You might also stretch strips
of a green-colored tape across the top of your pots. Leave spaces
for air and water. Perhaps it would help, too, to lure the
squirrels away from your containers by placing a dish of seed
elsewhere in the garden. Maybe other gardeners can share home
remedies that have worked for them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am badly in need of advice as to what to plant in flower
beds that get lots of sun. I need plants that need little watering
as I use a cane and cannot move my hose constantly. It was
suggested to me that I use Mexican heather in the back of the
flower bed and use the purple wandering Jew (Tradescantia) as a
ground cover in the remaining space.
</P>
<P>
   Do you have any other suggestions?
</P>
<P>
   _ P.M., Freeport &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; A. This summer has certainly been a true test for plants that
will survive sunny, dry conditions. The two recommendations you
mention are among the toughest plants out there. I have seen them
live through total neglect. Freezing temperatures will take the
tops of both, so for a while following a cold winter you will have
bare spots. Mexican heather may or may not return from the roots,
but it does reseed to some extent. You may need to fill in with new
plants after a winter with several freezing spells. The
Tradescantia usually returns vigorously.
</P>
<P>
   You might consider an evergreen to use with these two plants.
Giant liriope is extremely durable. This is a larger version of the
liriope widely used to border walkways and flower beds. Giant
liriope is attractive in the landscape, can mature to at least 3
feet in height and form a large clump. It produces the purple
flowers as does the shorter version.
</P>
<P>
   Dwarf yaupon is a dense, compact globe that is also evergreen.
It, too, is tough, and would give your bed some texture as would
the giant liriope. Either or both would work well with the heather
and Tradescantia. Midsize nandina would also be a good choice.
</P>
<P>
   Purple coneflower is an excellent perennial that would mix well
in such a bed. These, too, go down in a freeze, but return in
spring. ``New Gold'' or ``Silver Mound'' lantana would be nice
perennial additions, too. The globelike blooms of purple or pink
gomphrena would work into the scene late spring until frost.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, even drought-tolerant plants need adequate moisture
until they are established.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Q. Could you please explain what is making my tulip tree or
pink magnolia bloom at this time of year? It also has new leaves
now since old leaves have dropped due to this year's intense heat.
</P>
<P>
   _ E.J.P., Rosenberg
</P>
<P>
   A. Saucer magnolias (Magnolia soulangiana) are one of the
earliest flowering trees here _ and one of the most beautiful. They
like an acidic loam that drains well. In summer, those exposed to
afternoon sun can suffer. Their leaves burn. They may shed foliage.
So it's a good idea to plant them where they will be protected not
only from the hot sun, but also from winter winds. Sometimes the
buds are destroyed in wind or freezing weather, and we get leaves
but no flowers.
</P>
<P>
   It is not too rare for deciduous saucer magnolias to put on a
second round of blooms in late summer/early fall.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL; 
 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have been given a beautiful esperanza, and I need all the
information I can get to take good care of it.
</P>
<P>
   _ N.W., Houston
</P>
<P>
   A. Esperanza, also commonly called yellow bells or yellow elder,
is botanically known as Tecoma stans. This vigorous shrub/small
tree has the potential of reaching 20 feet, but we mostly see it in
the 6- to 8-foot range. During the past few years it has become
more widely available, and Texas gardeners have been smitten with
this native.
</P>
<P>
   The multibranched shrub can be trained into a standard. The
foliage is arranged in leaflets; the vivid yellow blooms are
heavily clustered at the tips of the branches. Narrow green seed
pods form after the flowers. Remove these to encourage more of the
2-inch, flared, funnel-shaped blooms. Let some pods remain on the
plant until they turn brown; harvest and sow the seed if you wish
to propagate.
</P>
<P>
   You can trim this plant during the growing season to shape and
control height. It is generally root-hardy in Zones 9-10. If you
plant it in the garden, do so in a sunny spot in a well-draining,
decently fertile soil. Mulch the roots well during winter to ensure
protection. It is beautiful in a mixed bed with other summer
bloomers such as jatropha, hamelia, lantana and the blue butterfly
bush, Clerodendrum ugandense.
</P>
<P>
   If you keep it in a pot, you'll find you will soon need a large
container as this plant is a fast grower. Move to a protected area,
as you would tropical hibiscus, during cold weather.
</P>
<P>
   Esperanza/yellow bells is drought-tolerant once established, but
it appreciates moderate to regular watering. Container plants
especially will benefit from monthly applications of a balanced
fertilizer since they will be watered more frequently, therefore
more quickly leaching nutrients from the soil.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL; 
 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q: We planted lantana as a ground cover over a rather large
area. We chose the ones with yellow flowers in particular because
we found them literally bursting with blooms practically everywhere
_ around malls, gas stations, etc., apparently with little care.
However, we are not getting continued bloom.
</P>
<P>
   We also planted pink lantana that bloom in the cooler months but
not the summer.
</P>
<P>
   We have tried heavy watering, light watering, no watering,
feeding and no feeding.
</P>
<P>
   _ T.K.B., Galveston
</P>
<P>
   A: Lantanas have on-and-off bloom cycles. They flower, rest,
then flower again. Some are touted as blooming more of the time,
including ``New Gold'' and ``Silver Mound.'' Some, such as Lantana
montevidensis ``Imperial Blue,'' will carry on longer in the cooler
months.
</P>
<P>
   Try to practice consistent culture. Lantana will flower best
given full sun and well-draining soil. Do not overwater, but water
deeply from time to time during long, dry spells. Then let the soil
dry before watering again. Lantana blooms on new growth, and the
moisture will encourage this.
</P>
<P>
   You might also periodically trim the plants to remove old
blooms. It is especially helpful to remove spent blooms from those
lantana that berry, or seed, to encourage more flowers. Always cut
lantana back after winter, whether the plants have suffered freeze
damage or not.
</P>
<P>
   Do not overfertilize. You want to give the plants enough food so
that they will grow well, but often heavy applications of
phosphorus are wasted as this element becomes tied up in the soil
and unavailable to the plant. Fertilize in spring with a
long-lasting, complete and balanced formula. You might reapply
every couple of months during the growing season.
</P>
<P>
   Mail garden questions to Kathy Huber, Garden Editor, Houston
Chronicle, P.O. Box 4260, Houston 77210. The bulk of mail prevents
individual replies to all unpublished letters.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
