u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SINGER-PONCE-HNS &LR;      09-15 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SINGER-PONCE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATIN SUPERSTAR CARLOS PONCE ROCKETS TO STARDOM 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOEY GUERRA 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Even before the entourage of publicists, agents and
promoters ushering Latin music superstar Carlos Ponce through a
back door of the Astrohall were visible, the nonstop screaming
began.
</P>
<P>
   Two hits _ ``Decir Adios,'' his current single, and ``Rezo,''
the ballad that introduced Ponce to music fans and shot to the top
of the charts _ have made his a virtual household name in the
Latino community.
</P>
<P>
   Oblivious to the other scheduled acts performing onstage just
behind them during the recent all-day Mexican Independence Day
celebration, a few hundred fans _ most of them females of varied
ages _ threatened to pour through the gated barriers keeping them
within arm's reach of Ponce, whose self-titled debut album of pop
ballads, acoustic rhythms and Latin grooves has hovered near the
top of the Latin charts for nearly three months.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the confusion, a pair of ecstatic teen-age girls managed to
climb over the gates, only to be scolded back to their places by
security guards, who were visibly amused at the commotion.
</P>
<P>
   When the hysteria finally settled down to a dull roar, Ponce
signed autographs, shook hands and posed pretty for a barrage of
cameras. He even helped a few nervous fans who were having trouble
setting their flashes.
</P>
<P>
   Ponce, 26, clearly enjoys mingling with his fans, but the speed
of his success is something that still surprises him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew eventually I would be successful, because I put a lot
of passion into what I do, and I don't do it unless I know that
it's going to work _ or at least I think very positively that it
will get there. But I had no idea it was going to be so quick,'' he
said backstage after a three-song set.
</P>
<P>
   Ponce is no stranger to the spotlight, though. The Puerto-Rican
born entertainer moved to Miami with his family at the age of 14,
where he landed steady commercial work and attended the New World
School of the Arts.
</P>
<P>
   He stole quite a few hearts on the Spanish ``novelas'' (soap
operas) ``Guadalupe'' and ``Sentimientos Ajenos,'' and he served as
host and producer of the youth-oriented variety and music show
``Control'' in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   A perfectly timed acknowledgment of Ponce's burgeoning success
came in June of this year, when he was selected by People en
Espanol to grace the cover of their 25 Most Beautiful issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It came at a great time in my life, because it was just like
right smack in the middle of my CD coming out, so it was good
publicity.''
</P>
<P>
   While that high-profile exposure was a sure-fire boost, Ponce's
current career of choice is something that's been in the works for
a long time.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first intention was the music. Little things came here and
there, and I think it's just basically God giving me more
instruments to learn because each one of them complements the
others,'' Ponce said. ``In a way, I'm very thankful. I was looking
for the music, but now I can't pick. I tried that. I do love music
... and I don't do them all at the same time. It's been almost two
years since I've done a television show, with the exception of
little appearances here and there.''
</P>
<P>
   One of those ``little'' appearances included a stint on an
upcoming episode of ``Beverly Hills 90210,'' which airs Nov. 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``I play a rich guy who comes and takes one of the girls out of
the episode, but they leave it open for the option of both of us
coming back, because she is one of the lead roles. I take her away
to Paris,'' Ponce said with a slight grin. ``It was great. It was a
lot of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Ponce's success seems surprising, considering his peers in the
market _ Enrique Iglesias, Ricky Martin, Alejandro Fernandez _ each
have at least three albums under their belts. It's an intimidating
level of competition, but Ponce welcomes it with confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it doesn't sound too vain, but I wasn't too nervous,''
Ponce admitted. ``I just wanted to make sure it was what I wanted
to do and not what they (record company) wanted me to do. I knew it
was going to be good. I never dreamed that it was going to be so
quick. I just thought it was going to take me a little while _
maybe a second CD _ but that doesn't mean that I had lack of faith
in the content of this one.''
</P>
<P>
   The diversity on the album is refreshing, and it's a point Ponce
was concerned with from the beginning. The process of selecting
tracks for the album _ three of which were written by Ponce _ took
more than six months, while the recording was done in four months.
</P>
<P>
   ``My style is pretty eclectic, so that's what I did. I had fun
with each and every song because they were hand-picked.''
</P>
<P>
   Helping Ponce assemble a first-rate product were notable
writer/producer Kike Santander and Emilio Estefan Jr., who has
worked his magic on artists like Jon Secada, Thalia and, most
notably, his wife, Gloria Estefan.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I did bring my music to Emilio _ being probably one of
the most successful producers that I have met _ he was the only one
that told me what I wanted to hear, which was, `OK, what is it you
want to do, and I'll work around that,' instead of `This is what we
want you to do.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Along with artistic freedom, Ponce is hoping to reap another
benefit of working with Estefan: crossover success. He is currently
in the midst of recording three songs in English for the
international release of his album, and Ponce also performed a
``Spanglish'' version of ``Rezo'' a few weeks ago on ``Regis &AMP;
Kathie Lee.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been thinking about (a crossover) ever since I released
my record, and that was one of the main reasons why I wanted
Estefan to be my producer, because he's done Gloria, and he's done
Jon Secada,'' Ponce said. ``I don't know anybody else who has
successfully done strong crossovers.''
</P>
<P>
   Ponce already had the chance to realize another dream this
summer, when his theatrical background almost had him kicking up
his heels in two high-profile Broadway revivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything you want to do comes when you can't do it. I was
offered `The Pirates of Penzance,' which they're going to redo on
Broadway now. I was offered `On The Town.' I can't do it, either,''
Ponce said.
</P>
<P>
   The New York stage may have to wait a while while Ponce fulfills
his duties promoting his music, but it's likely he will find solace
in the adoration of his fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time I've come to Houston. You can tell you
have to make a little bit of an extra effort, being a ballad or a
pop artist, but the audience was very nice and very receptive,''
Ponce said. ``So I was very happy.''
</P>
<P>
   For the cheering fans who waved banners and sang along during
Ponce's set, the feeling was undoubtedly mutual. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
