<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOTING WORTH THE EFFORT, EVEN WITH SCANDAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ I wish Texas Secretary of State Al Gonzales a lot of
luck, and he probably will need every bit of it.
</P>
<P>
   As the state's chief elections officer, Gonzales has taken on
one of the most difficult jobs in state government right now _
encouraging people to get out and vote in the fall election.
</P>
<P>
   The low turnouts in the party primaries last spring already had
signaled that Gonzales had his work cut out for him. Now, the
Clinton scandal in Washington, which escalated last week with the
release of the independent counsel's report to Congress, has made
Gonzales' task even more formidable.
</P>
<P>
   But Gonzales is still trying, seeking a magic theme, public
relations slogan or other motivation that could somehow convince a
respectable number of Texans to exercise their basic right of
citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   In a pretty ironic case of timing, Gonzales plans to announce a
new emphasis for his get-out-the-vote campaign this week. He will
bring Texas children into the act, just as many Texas parents are
hustling their children out of the room when news of the highest
elected official in the free world comes on television.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to get children excited about the act of voting and
hope that they will talk it up with their parents. Gonzales will
kick off the initiative with a news conference at an Austin
elementary school, where 5- and 6-year-olds will report about
recent class votes on such relevant (for them) issues as favorite
ice cream flavors.
</P>
<P>
   They and other young students also will be featured in a public
service announcement to be distributed to network and cable TV
stations throughout Texas.
</P>
<P>
   There is no connection, of course, between Gonzales' election
awareness program and the scandal over Clinton's relationship with
former White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   And there certainly is nothing wrong with educating children
about the importance of voting. I'm all for it. But it's pretty sad
that our most identifiable government figure, who should be a hero
to our children, has become such a disreputable example of what the
act of voting can produce.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen whether the U.S. House will use Kenneth
Starr's report to impeach the president, but already there is a lot
of speculation about how Clinton's behavior will affect the
upcoming elections in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Many Democratic candidates are trying to put as much distance
between themselves and the Democratic president as possible. John
Sharp and Paul Hobby, who are waging uphill but potentially
winnable races for lieutenant governor and state comptroller,
already have sharply criticized Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   A notable exception is Democratic gubernatorial nominee Garry
Mauro, a longtime Clinton friend. Mauro said he still planned to
have the president, who already has raised a lot of money for
Mauro, appear at additional fund-raisers in Houston and San Antonio
later this month.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro, whose chances of unseating Gov. George W. Bush appear to
be slim-to-none, says friendship is friendship. And he apparently
believes he has little to lose anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Some political analysts predict that the Clinton scandal _
including independent counsel Starr's assertion that he has
compiled ``substantial and credible'' evidence of possible
impeachable offenses by the president _ will hurt Democratic
candidates in a number of congressional and other key races around
the country.
</P>
<P>
   If even a small percentage of Democratic voters are disgusted
enough to stay home on Election Day, or so the theory goes, the
party's candidates, particularly in close races, will suffer.
</P>
<P>
   Many Americans obviously are disgusted by Clinton's behavior.
Many others are less concerned about his affair with Lewinsky than
they are about his lies about it and attempts to cover it up. And
still others are tired of reading and hearing about it.
</P>
<P>
   What effect the scandal will have on voters won't be known, of
course, until Election Day. But the furor may very well turn off
people of all political persuasions from voting _ for anybody.
</P>
<P>
   This could particularly be the result in Texas, where the
governor's race, by far the most visible race on the ballot, is
perceived as a runaway anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, I believed it was premature to fret over the
lower-than-normal turnout in both the Democratic and Republican
primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it seems that the fretting may have been justified.
President Clinton and the tawdry details of Monica-gate may simply
reinforce the perception of millions of marginal voters that no one
in public office is worthy of their trust, confidence _ or votes.
</P>
<P>
   The country will recover _ with or without a presidential
impeachment or resignation _ but this Election Day may be a
difficult test for democracy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
