<SLUG> BC-INVESTMENT-CLUBS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAPERWORK TURNS INVESTMENT CLUB BEARISH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JO-ANN JOHNSTON  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ For this investment club, the devil was
in the details, not in the Dow.
</P>
<P>
   The Willow Tree Stocks Investment Club, whose members are all
women, is cashing out its joint investments just a couple of years
after organizing. A core group of members will reconvene as the
Willow Tree Friends, an information- and resource-sharing group for
women who want to learn more about personal finance topics.
</P>
<P>
   While investment clubs have earned lots of positive publicity in
recent years for bringing ordinary people together to learn the ins
and outs of investing, Willow Tree's experience demonstrates a
common pitfall: too much work for too few people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of the clubs that are started in the next 18 months, about
half will fold,'' predicted Thomas O'Hara, chairman of the board of
trustees of National Association of Investors Corp., which guides
37,000 clubs nationwide. That high mortality rate exists despite
the fact that the organization has computer software that helps
groups with record keeping.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble signs, if they are to appear, show themselves early,
O'Hara said. ``It's getting past the first couple of years,'' he
said. ``We have hundreds that are more than 35 years old.''
</P>
<P>
   A common problem among clubs that disband is that they have too
few active working members to share the administrative load, O'Hara
said.
</P>
<P>
   That seems to have been the quandary for Willow Tree Stocks.
</P>
<P>
   It had as many as 15 investors, including the silent partners
who didn't want to handle decision-making or bookkeeping chores but
only seven or eight active members. That ratio just didn't work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We probably needed more bodies than that for handling the
investments for that many people,'' said Bev LaBarge, one of the
organizers and a continuing member of the reincarnated group.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury functions are especially time-consuming, said Ann
Cunningham, another active member.
</P>
<P>
   Members must track dividends, savings accounts and follow IRS
rules. ``The paperwork is astronomical,'' Cunningham said.
</P>
<P>
   The women hadn't envisioned that their monthly meetings at the
community room in the local Kmart would be so dominated by
accounting intricacies. After all, they had wanted to learn about
the world of investing by talking about their holdings in Pepsi,
Maytag, Oracle and Rubbermaid _ some of their more successful
purchases _ and in Boston Chicken and Shanghai Petroleum, which
didn't fare so well.
</P>
<P>
   So the club is now in the process of cashing out and
redistributing holdings to individual members, many of whom will
invest on their own.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the exercise was useful in many ways, Cunningham said.
She went from being a semiretired grandmother who knew little about
finances to being a woman who now reads the business pages of
newspapers daily and Barron's.
</P>
<P>
   Other members, whose ages ranged from 30 to 70, also learned
more about finances.
</P>
<P>
   The revised format of the club opens up new possibilities,
LaBarge and Cunningham said. Now they don't have to stick just to
investing topics. They can discuss leasing a car, buying a home,
starting a business, funding health care or any of the other
financial decisions that women are increasingly making on their
own, said LaBarge, a widow who markets her own invention, a
traveling case for tournament-level chess players.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-98 1432EDT &QL; 
