<HEADER>
A6070 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR &LR;      09-15 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTABLE BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A survey of recently published books:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; THE TONTO WOMAN &QL; 
 &UR; Elmore Leonard (Delacorte, $23.95)
</P>
<P>
   Long before he hit it big writing crime novels, Elmore Leonard
supported his family by writing copy for an advertising agency by
day, and Western stories for pulp magazines at night. He didn't
know much about the West, so he subscribed to ``Arizona Highways''
magazine and cribbed from it when he needed to describe the
landscape. That technique doesn't sound very promising, so it comes
as a surprise that this collection of Leonard's early Western
stories is so much fun to read. The characters are essentially the
same as those in his later fiction _ only the names and places have
changed _ because they are written in accordance with Leonard's
conviction that, as he puts it, ``the bad guys aren't bad all
day.'' He (begin itals) likes (end itals) these people, and so do
we, despite the fact that they are as capable of violence and sin
as they are of humor and the occasional good deed. Most of the
stories here are set in Arizona. And the landscape? It's dusty and
gritty and everything you'd want it to be in tales of the Wild
West. Not a sign of ``Arizona Highways'' anywhere. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; THE BEST LITTLE BOY IN THE WORLD GROWS UP &QL; 
 &UR; Andrew Tobias (Random House, $23.95)
</P>
<P>
   On the dust jacket, under the author's name, are the words ``No
Longer Known as John Reid.'' That's a reference to Tobias'
coming-of-age memoir, ``The Best Little Boy in the World,'' which
was published 25 years ago under the Reid pseudonym because Tobias,
who was then 26, did not want to acknowledge his homosexuality
under his own name. He had not yet told his parents that he was gay
(he finally broke the news to his mother just as his book was
coming out in paperback _ her response was, ``Don't tell your
father.''). Here, the author of ``The Only Investment Guide You'll
Ever Need'' (never mind that he would later revise it) continues
his story with his familiar, funny, chatty tone and honest but
discreet approach. He covers the aftermath of the release of his
first book, his success as an investment adviser (and consequent
appearances on television talk shows), the AIDS epidemic and the
deaths of many of his friends, and the changes in his experience as
a gay man in America. To coincide with publication of this book,
Random House has released ``The Best Little Boy in the World'' in a
Modern Library edition. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; FIELD OF THIRTEEN &QL; 
 &UR; Dick Francis (Putnam, $24.95)
</P>
<P>
   Here is a collection of short fiction from the acknowledged
master of the racetrack tale. In ``Raid at Kingdom Hill,'' a bomb
scare at a crowded track provides a lucrative opportunity for two
unlikely thieves (Francis notes that the story, written in 1975,
presaged a bomb hoax that halted the running of the Grand National
Steeplechase in 1997). In ``Song for Mona,'' an elderly groom dies
a lonely death and her vindictive, social-climbing daughter suffers
comeuppance at the hands of her mother's employers. In ``Bright
White Star,'' Francis describes the theft of a prize colt from an
auction, and in ``Nightmare'' the theft of a brood mare and her
unborn foal. In ``Spring Fever,'' a middle-aged owner falls in love
with her 24-year-old jockey. In all there are eight previously
published and five new stories _ a fine field of 13. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; THE NEW ENCYCLOPEDIA OF THE AMERICAN WEST &QL; 
 &UR; Edited by Howard R. Lamar (Yale, $60)
</P>
<P>
   The pseudonym ``Mark Twain'' was first used in the early 1800s
by Mississippi river pilot Isaiah Sellers, who wrote letters to New
Orleans newspapers under it (Mark Twain was an old river term, the
call for a sounding of two fathoms, which meant safe water). Cowboy
hats were poorly made until 1865 when a fellow from New Jersey _
John B. Stetson _ opened a one-man shop in Philadelphia and began
making the hats that would come to represent the American West (by
1906, he had 3,500 employees and made 2 million hats a year). The
trivia is fun, but you have to dig for it in the more substantial
entries (the ``Mark Twain'' tidbit can be found under ``rivermen'')
in this big and valuable book. First published in 1977 as ``The
Reader's Encyclopedia of the American West,'' it has been revised
to include 2,400 entries on the history, geography and culture of
the West, arranged alphabetically by keyword. Includes a time line
of Western history and more than 600 maps and illustrations. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; LADIES AND GENTLEMEN OF THE JURY &QL; 
 &UR; Michael S Lief, H. Mitchell Caldwell and Ben Bycel (Scribner, $26)
</P>
<P>
   The authors have assembled a selection of what they consider to
be the finest closing arguments in American history. Each is
presented with a brief historical introduction, a biographical
sketch of the lawyer who delivered the argument, and an analysis of
the argument. Included are prosecutor Robert H. Jackson's closing
in the trial of Nazi war criminals at Nuremburg; Vincent Bugliosi's
closing in the trial of Charles Manson; Aubrey Daniel's closing
argument at the court martial of William L. Calley Jr. for his
actions at My Lai in Vietnam; Gerry Spence's arguments in the case
brought by Karen Silkwood's family against Kerr McGee Inc.; and
Clarence Darrow's argument that saved murderers Richard Loeb and
Nathan Leopold from the gallows in 1924. &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Anne Stephenson can be contacted at
amstephenson(at)worldnet.att.net) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-98 1441EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
