<DOCNO> NYT19980915.0163 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 14:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6074 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-CANYON-AZR &LR;      09-15 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-CANYON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CANYON' TAKES READERS ON GRAND TOUR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
HOW THE CANYON BECAME GRAND 
Stephen J. Pyne (Viking, $24.95) 
 
 By JERRY KAMMER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nervous Nellies who dread the approaching turn of the millennium
would do well to contemplate the story of the Grand Canyon, where a
millennium's laughable big-picture insignificance is revealed. A
millennium is to the Canyon what an ounce is to Moby Dick.
</P>
<P>
   In a new book, historian Stephen J. Pyne writes of ``the power
of the Canyon not to reveal time so much as to obliterate it
through sheer immensity.''
</P>
<P>
   That observation comes at the end of ``How the Canyon Became
Grand,'' in which the Arizona State University professor gives a
fascinating, often compelling account of the enormous scholarly,
artistic and political energies that the Canyon has inspired. It is
a sort of intellectual history of America's most evocative place.
</P>
<P>
   Those Canyon-born energies, in turn, have determined the
enormous place that the Canyon claims in the national imagination
as a sublime wonder and geological showplace.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a book for the casual reader of Canyon literature,
any more than a rim-to-rim hike is for the casual hiker accustomed
only to short jaunts on the rim. It is both a stimulating and
challenging journey, for Pyne is a student of intellectual history
who has read widely and studied the literature of the Canyon
closely.
</P>
<P>
   Pyne, of course, tells the Canyon tales of such widely known
Canyon figures as John Wesley Powell, the first to lead a
river-borne expedition through the Canyon, and Clarence Dutton, who
recognized the Canyon as ``a great innovation in our modern ideas
of scenery.''
</P>
<P>
   But he also explains how the Canyon shaped the science of
geology and the art of landscape. And he provides an excellent
account of how the Canyon shaped the modern environmental movement
_ through battles against those who would dam its eastern and
western ends.
</P>
<P>
   Those battles were some of the most important in the history of
the American West, for they shaped an aesthetic that some things
simply must be preserved, even in a region where supplies of water
and power sometimes demand the sacrifice of the natural world. As
Sierra Club head David Brower said, ``If we can't save the Grand
Canyon, what the hell can we save?''
</P>
<P>
   Pyne manages to tell most of his tale in language that is vivid
and imaginative. But at times he strains for an arresting image.
</P>
<P>
   Describing the period in the 1920s when Southwestern art
slighted the Canyon as it focused on New Mexico, Pyne writes
``Emblemat ically the defining Southwest novel of the era, Willa
Cather's `Death Comes for the Archbishop' (1927), ends with the
erection of a cathedral, not the evolution of a canyon.''
</P>
<P>
   But such awkward moments snag the book only briefly as Pyne
tells a story that begins with the Canyon's incomprehensibility to
the 16th century Spanish explorers and concludes with the Canyon's
emergence as a symbol of America.
</P>
<P>
   Just as the Canyon demands physical rigor for those who would
probe it deeply, ``How the Canyon Became Grand'' requires a certain
intellectual sure-footedness through complex terrain. Both
experiences are richly rewarding. For those who seek to understand
the Canyon's evolution as cultural phenomenon, the book is a must. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-98 1441EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980915.0164 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 14:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6083 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-AUTHOR-AZR &LR;      09-15 1270
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-AUTHOR-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALENTED NOVELIST PURSUES HIS CRAFT AS LABOR OF LOVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ethan Canin is on the telephone from Iowa City, where he and his
family are living out of boxes while he readies himself for the
fall semester at the University of Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've just accepted a tenured professorship,'' he says in a
deep, formal voice, making fun of his own announcement. He laughs,
but still sounds nervous. ``We're not even moved in. I'm sitting
here amid unpacked boxes, living in a wreck. I'm going to teach.
Yes. I'm going to see how that goes.''
</P>
<P>
   This is news. At 37, Ethan Canin is a writer, a physician and
now _ full time and with tenure _ a teacher. He is also one of
literary fiction's brightest stars, despite the fact that his
writing and his medical education have pulled him in different
directions for more than a decade. It wasn't until he had earned a
degree in English from Stanford University and was a student at the
Iowa Writer's Workshop that he decided to study medicine. He wrote
his first story collection, ``Emperor of the Air,'' while he was at
Harvard Medical School (it was published in 1988 to rapturous
reviews and several weeks on the New York Times bestseller list).
</P>
<P>
   He followed up with a novel, ``Blue River,'' and in 1994 ``The
Palace Thief,'' a collection of novellas that solidified his
reputation as a master of understated but remarkable storytelling.
</P>
<P>
   Now Canin has a new novel, ``For Kings and Planets'' (Random
House, $24). It's the story of Orno Tarcher and Marshall Emerson,
who meet in 1974 as freshmen at Columbia University and become
friends despite disparate backgrounds, talents and priorities.
</P>
<P>
   Canin sounds both excited and apprehensive about the new book
and about his decision not to practice medicine. But that, to all
appearances, is typical of Canin _ he has achieved much, but seems
to view everything he does with a curious mix of relish and angst.
</P>
<P>
   QUESTION: Why did you decide to go to medical school all those
years ago?
</P>
<P>
   ANSWER: I went to medical school because I figured I couldn't
support myself as a writer. I know that sounds like an intimidating
and overwhelming alternative. It was a failure of imagination,
really. I sat there and thought (begin itals) what can I do? (end
itals) A lawyer? I don't want to be a lawyer. But I'd always been
good in science, and I liked helping people. So I went to medical
school and spent 10 years being intimidated and overwhelmed.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You finished your residency. What's your status now?
</P>
<P>
   A: I'm still licensed as a doctor. I just paid the state of
California to renew my license, but I don't know why because I'm
not going to use it. At some point I realized that if I practiced
medicine I would be stepping into a $150,000-a-year job, 50 hours a
week, and I would never write again. I realized that if I didn't
need the money, I wouldn't write, and if I was a doctor I wouldn't
need the money so that would be the end of me as a writer.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Talk a bit about the new novel. Orno and Marshall are so
different. Why are they attracted to each other?
</P>
<P>
   A: That's hard to answer. I think those characters represent
warring instincts in myself. Ambition versus contentment. If I had
to explain it, I'd say that what Marshall sees in Orno is a
solidity, a solid center that he doesn't have. And Orno sees in
Marshall a grace and glamour that he doesn't have. I was interested
in writing about a friendship between two men over their entire
lives.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you become attached to your characters?
</P>
<P>
   A: No I don't, because I'll tell you, it's such misery to write
a book. I basically like and trust my characters, but I don't feel
any great spring in my step just from thinking about them. It's not
like that for me. I wish it was. I'm envious of writers who say all
they do is think about their characters. But for me writing is
pretty much agony.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why do you do it?
</P>
<P>
   A: I don't know. Maybe because over the years I've discovered
that I have an unquenchable spring. Even though it's possible to
quench it for years at a time, it seems to bubble up sooner or
later. It's a desire that comes from reading. When I read something
I like, I want to write.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If there's been a criticism of your writing, it's that it is
too understated. How do you react to that?
</P>
<P>
   A: I've written some stories that are sort of poetic _ you know,
that kind of language. I can do that. But it seems to me that it's
only when the content isn't there that I start jazzing up the
prose. Maybe it's a distracting mechanism, but if the content is
strong you're not thinking so much about the prose style. One
writer I admired when I started this novel was Peter Taylor. If you
look at his prose style, it doesn't seem like anything in
particular. I'd describe it as being articulate, with a ring of
truth to it. And that's sort of what I want to do.
</P>
<P>
   Q: After your first book of stories was so successful, you took
a leave from medical school and went to South America to write your
first novel. Why?
</P>
<P>
   A: I went to Ecuador because it was the cheapest country in
South America and they spoke fairly straightforward Spanish there.
Don't get me wrong, I loved the attention after ``Emperor of the
Air.'' I ate it up. But I also felt that I wanted to leave in the
middle of it rather than let it fizzle.
</P>
<P>
   I was terrified about the novel. I'd gotten this big advance. I
was only twentysomething years old. I tried to write every day
because I knew if I didn't I'd just disintegrate. I had no plan
whatsoever. I didn't even write from one scene to the next. I just
typed. And I came home six or seven months later with a suitcase
full of unrelated scenes that I spread out on the floor of my
apartment and then tried to piece them together. It was agony.
</P>
<P>
   For the new novel, I decided that whatever happened I would
write it in order, starting on the first page. I would never skip
ahead. I wrote it from first page to last, and it was instantly
easier. I had no idea where I was going, which is frightening but I
always do it that way. Don't get me wrong _ the word ``easy''
doesn't apply to this. It's not even in the lexicon. But it was a
hell of a lot easier than the way I wrote the first one. On the
next novel, I might even try to plot things out before I start.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What other writers do you admire?
</P>
<P>
   A: You admire different people over different periods of your
life. There have been dozens. During the writing of this book, I
liked John Updike at the start. Peter Taylor. I was reading Jim
Harrison for a while _ God, I love his prose. Just recently I've
been reading Philip Roth, who's a terrific writer. I read
``American Pastoral,'' and couldn't tear my eyes away from it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are you looking forward to doing publicity appearances for
``For Kings and Planets?''
</P>
<P>
   A: I'm dreading it. I used to love publicity, but there's this
kind of shame that comes with it. I've gotten so I'm pretty good in
front of a microphone, but you feel so (begin itals) false. (end
itals) Not only that, but the stuff that I'm hoping for with all my
heart _ like to make the bestseller lists and earn a lot of money _
well, it just seems so (begin itals) empty. (end itals) In the
sense that if you make No. 5 on the bestseller list you'll wish you
were No. 3. Nothing will ever satisfy you. No good review is good
enough and a bad review is devastating. It's a pretty miserable
time. On the other hand, I'm very glad I'm doing it. So there you
go. That's Orno and Marshall for you. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-98 1445EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
