<SLUG> BC-DECLINING-EXPORTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH-TECH INDUSTRY SEES DECLINE IN GLOBAL ACTIVITY 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GEORGE RAINE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ U.S. exports of high-tech products are on the
decline, a new report says, and increased demand for American goods
in some parts of the world offers little hope for immediate
improvement.
</P>
<P>
   During the first six months of 1998, exports of high-tech goods
from the United States to Asia fell 12 percent, or $3.7 billion,
according to the American Electronics Association. That decrease
was almost entirely offset by healthy increases to Europe, Canada
and even China.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting overall decline of U.S. electronics exports was
valued at $311 million, or 0.38 percent, compared with the same
period in 1997. The exports include computers, semiconductors,
consumer electronics and photonics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not bad, considering,'' said AEA spokesman John Hatch in
Santa Clara, Calif. ``Actually, we would like to see increases.''
</P>
<P>
   Economists say increases are unlikely to appear soon because of
worldwide financial troubles.
</P>
<P>
   The export figures have enormous importance to California,
because electronics and electrical equipment, industrial machinery
and computer equipment represented 53 percent of total California
exports during the first half of 1998, according to the state Trade
and Commerce Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Significantly, following a moderate 3 percent growth in 1997,
exports of electronics and electrical equipment declined 2.3
percent and industrial machinery and computers fell 2.1 percent
during the first half of the year, the state said.
</P>
<P>
   During the first six months, Mexican numbers were impressive.
There was a 16 percent growth, or a $1.2 billion increase, of
high-tech exports to that country, the AEA said.
</P>
<P>
   High-tech exports to the European Union were strong, up 5
percent, or $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   China was the notable exception in the general decline of
exports to Asia. High-tech exports to China grew by $500 million,
or 50 percent, from January through June, over the year-earlier
period.
</P>
<P>
   Asia's figures overall, however, were miserable. American
high-tech exports to Indonesia were down 64 percent; to South
Korea, down 37 percent; to Thailand, down 26 percent; and to Japan,
down 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
   There are no cures on the horizon for these and other troubled
markets, economists said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are going to get worse before they get better,'' said
Richard Carlson, chairman of Spectrum Electronics in Palo Alto,
Calif., management consultants to numerous Silicon Valley clients.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he noted, the AEA numbers represent shipments, which
lag orders, and, secondly, ``all the places we are relying on are
in trouble. Canada, Latin America and Europe are all in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   The AEA noted that exports to Latin America had been vigorous in
the first six months. Following a 31 percent surge between 1996 and
1997, high-tech exports increased 9 percent during the first half
of 1998. One harbinger of concern is Brazil, the largest export
market in Latin America, where high-tech exports fell 8 percent, or
$190 million.
</P>
<P>
   There were surges elsewhere, said the AEA. Exports to Costa Rica
doubled to $200 million, and to Venezuela they surged 61 percent,
to $640 million.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are widespread fears that the regional financial
crisis will deepen in Latin America, and no good news is expected
soon from elsewhere, Carlson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is turning around yet; that does not add up too well,''
he said. ``All major raw material-producing countries are really
being hit. Canada is on the top of that list, and that includes
Australia, much of Latin America, the Middle East. The question is,
`Does it turn around by the end of this year or the middle of next
year?'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are pockets of optimism, to be sure. Last week, bellwether
Intel Corp. said its third quarter should be better than expected:
about 10 percent higher than the $5.9 billion reported in the
second quarter. Its sales are up in North America and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Dell Computer Corp. chairman Michael Dell said his company was
having a great third quarter. And Hewlett-Packard Co. reported a 1
percent increase in net earnings and a 5 percent growth in revenue
for the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of reason for long-term optimism, but this is
going to be at least a tough six months, and I hope it is not a
tough 12 months,'' Carlson said. ``The only market worldwide that
is strong right now is the U.S. We are just dragging the whole
planet's economy, and that is a hell of a load.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
