<SLUG> BC-TX-CLINTON-POLL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOST TEXANS IN POLL WANT CLINTON TO STAY 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ALAN BERNSTEIN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Texans' views of President Clinton and his sex scandal were
virtually unchanged by independent counsel Kenneth Starr's report
to Congress, according to a poll conducted for the Houston
Chronicle and The Dallas Morning News.
</P>
<P>
   Most Texans continue to think Clinton should stay in office,
according to the poll.
</P>
<P>
   And most continue to separate Clinton's presidential actions
from his personality. They still approve of his job performance but
not him.
</P>
<P>
   On the question of what should happen to Clinton in light of his
sexual encounters with former intern Monica Lewinsky and his
subsequent testimony, 42 percent said the matter should be dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Another 14 percent said Clinton should be censured _ officially
condemned _ by Congress. Such action would allow him to remain on
the job.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-seven percent said Clinton should resign, and 11 percent
said he should be impeached _ an option under strong consideration
by Congress. The remaining 6 percent were undecided.
</P>
<P>
   The survey of 505 adult Texans has a margin of error of 4.5
percentage points. It was conducted by Blum &AMP; Weprin Associates
Inc. of New York.
</P>
<P>
   In a virtually identical poll of registered voters Sept. 3, 24
percent said Clinton should resign, and 9 percent said he should be
impeached.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's report was made public Friday on the Internet and
subsequently in newspapers across the nation. It contains
allegations that Clinton committed perjury, obstruction of justice
and abuse of power. It also contained graphic details of Clinton's
sexual encounters with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``However negatively Texans may feel about President Clinton as
a person, they clearly continue to approve of the job he is doing
as president and want him to remain in office,'' pollsters
Micheline Blum and Julie Weprin said.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas results mirror numerous national polls taken since the
Starr report was released. The Chronicle-Morning News poll also
showed no signficant split between men's and women's attitudes on
Clinton's fate and his ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-three percent of Texans surveyed said they approve of the
job Clinton is doing as president. Thirty-two percent percent
disapproved, and 5 percent were undecided.
</P>
<P>
   In the Sept. 3 poll, 60 percent approved of Clinton's
performance, 37 disapproved, and 3 percent were undecided.
</P>
<P>
   On the flip side, 61 percent said Monday they had a negative
opinion of Clinton _ a separate measure of the person rather than
his job performance. Thirty-one percent said they had a positive
opinion, and 8 percent were unsure.
</P>
<P>
   National polls that asked the same question came out slightly
better for Clinton after Starr's report went public. It was 56
percent negative, 37 percent positive in a national poll for CNN
and USA Today conducted by Gallup.
</P>
<P>
   In Monday's poll, Texans who want Clinton to remain on the job
saw the case as a sexual matter instead of a legal one, while those
who want his resignation or removal saw the case more as a legal
matter instead of a sexual one.
</P>
<P>
   Of those who said the case should be dropped, 83 percent said it
was mostly because the case concerns a private matter that has
nothing to do with Clinton's job performance. Another 8 percent
said it was because they do not believe Clinton broke the law.
Three percent said ``both.''
</P>
<P>
   Of those who said Clinton should resign, be impeached or
censured, 56 percent cited the belief that Clinton lied in his
testimony or encouraged others to lie. Fifteen percent said it was
because Starr's report shows he is morally unfit to be president.
Twenty-four percent cited both reasons.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, 53 percent of the total survey said Starr included
graphic sexual details in his report mostly to embarrass Clinton
rather than mostly to prove that he committed perjury.
</P>
<P>
   Texans still are split about the way Starr has performed as a
special prosecutor, according to the poll, with 45 percent
disapproving of Starr's performance and 44 percent approved. Eleven
percent were unsure.
</P>
<P>
   The earlier survey before the release of Starr's report showed
no significant difference on that question.
</P>
<P>
   One of the respondents to Monday's poll, retiree Agnes Bradley
of Sulphur Springs, said the case should end without any official
action against Clinton because Lewinsky's testimony has already
damaged the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am for him standing in there,'' she said, adding Clinton has
done a good job, especially with ``handling those foreign
countries.''
</P>
<P>
   The 89-year-old Democrat said she has vivid memories of many
presidents.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton ``hasn't done anything worse than all of the other
presidents that's been there,'' Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, ex-Marine Morris Halsey, an education student at
Sam Houston State University in Huntsville, said Clinton has
performed well as president but should be impeached for testifying
falsely.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he has done a good job; I can see that,'' said Halsey,
a 36-year-old Republican. ``But morally, with me going into the
profession that I am, which is teaching, I couldn't in any way,
shape or form come near what he has done and hope to maintain a
semblance of a job.''
</P>
<P>
   Halsey said that Clinton, in his explanations of the sexual
encounters, has acted as if the public lacked intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know what happened,'' he remarked. ``Don't dance around the
issue. Face it, take your licks and continue to march.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Williamson of San Antonio, a political independent, said
Clinton has committed a personal wrong but that he has also been
the subject of a vendetta by Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Explaining why he thinks Clinton should not quit or be punished
by Congress, the 34-year-old human resources consultant said,
``What really irritates me is that they have allowed (Starr) to
spend $40 million doing this ridiculous investigation when we have
a lot of things in the United States of America that are better
causes.''
</P>
<P>
   Whites and non-whites were split on their rating of Clinton as a
person, according to the poll.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy-four percent of blacks and 51 percent of Hispanics said
they have a positive opinion of Clinton as a person; only 20
percent of whites did. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
