<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-REBA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S HARD TO KEEP UP WITH REBA MCENTIRE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for Newport News, Va.; originally moved 8/2)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The ``new'' Nashville is a hotbed of changing scenes and faces,
so you can't blame some veteran country acts for having trouble
figuring it all out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very competitive, and there are so many new people in
here these days that I don't know half of them,'' says singer Reba
McEntire. ``I have to go to the awards shows and watch the CMT
(Country Music Television) videos to catch up and keep familiar
with everyone. It is scary.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, but here's the rub. The newcomers also have to keep up with
Reba -- and that's never been easy for anyone. She remains one of
the hardest-working entertainers in any genre. She always seems to
have a new record, a new movie, a new concert tour. If this woman
rests, it's not often.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a doer,'' she says with candid simplicity.
</P>
<P>
   These days, she's doing another concert tour with Brooks &AMP; Dunn.
Together, they had the top-grossing country tour of last year --
and decided to do it again after recording a duet, ``If You See
Him, If You See Her,'' for McEntire's new CD, ``If You See Him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have any plans to tour again until the song came
up,'' McEntire says of the track, co-written by Tommy Lee James,
Jennifer Kimball, and Terry McBride. ``But it's like family going
out with them. We toured together in 1992 and 1993 as well. They're
very easy to get along with. I know all of their crew and band.''
</P>
<P>
   McEntire, who has won numerous Grammy and Country Music
Association awards, is virtually country royalty at this point in
her 22-year career. She could likely demand constant headliner
status. Instead, she's willing to do a co-billing with Brooks &AMP;
Dunn, which means that they flip-flop the headlining role from
night to night. (There are also two opening acts, in Terry Clark
and David Kersh.) ``You have to get your ego out of the way,'' says
McEntire. ``But, you know, the best slot on the show is really the
third act. We all say that. So I think we're all flip-flopping for
that third slot instead of closing! It's not an ego thing with us,
because we get along so well. They understand what I've done and I
understand how successful they are. So we really respect each other
and like each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Happily, unlike last year, McEntire is again able to use a
large-scale stage production, complete with the choreography she so
loves. She had cut that way back last year in the wake of a skiing
accident in Park City, Utah, in which she broke her knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wait until you see the stage now! I've lost quite a bit of
weight running around that thing,'' she says. ``And I worked with
my choreographer, Jerry Evans, and got some new dance steps. My leg
is doing a lot better. It feels good. I've also had a personal
trainer and done a lot of physical therapy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes you appreciate coming back and just being able to
walk. You don't take anything for granted.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that's been her philosophy ever since she was a girl
in Oklahoma, the daughter of a rodeo competitor. It also explains
why she expects to return to skiing. ``Yes, I'll go back and try it
again,'' she says of skiing. ``It's kind of the way I was brought
up. If I got thrown off a horse, my daddy would always say, `Go,
get back on. No matter what, you got to get back on.' `` McEntire
also has starred in many movies, including ``Gambler IV'' (with
Kenny Rogers), in which she played a reformed madam. And she has an
upcoming film, ``Forever Love,'' due on CBS-TV in September, in
which she plays a woman who wakes up from a 20-year coma to
discover that her husband has changed radically and that hro
dramatic role, but I'm comfortable with it. And it has some funny
things in it. The writing is really good. . . . You cry and you
laugh.''
</P>
<P>
   The only misgiving of her recent career is that she had to give
up a role in the blockbuster film, ``Titanic.'' She auditioned for
director James Cameron and won the role of Molly Brown (later
played by Kathy Bates), but needed to give it up to fulfill some
concert commitments. ``I had the part, but then he needed me for
another three months beyond the three months we had already
scheduled. And I had my concert venues selected by that time,''
says McEntire.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I have no regrets. Everything happens for a reason,'' she
adds. ``It would have been a wonderful movie to be a part of,
because it will in the history books forever as one of the greatest
movies of all time. But you can't cry over spilled milk. You've
just got to keep going.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
