<HEADER>
A6157 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMMIGRANT-SMUGGLING-H     09-15 0463
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMMIGRANT-SMUGGLING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN ACCUSED OF SMUGGLING CHINESE IS SENTENCED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM HERRON ZAMORA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The West Coast ringleader of a group that
smuggled 281 Chinese immigrants on two crowded fishing boats has
been sentenced to three years and nine months in federal prison.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors described John Luong, 27, of Elk Grove, Calif., as
the leader of a gang that led the immigrants ashore south of San
Francisco, where they were to be taken to New York to work off the
price of their passage.
</P>
<P>
   Luong, who was sentenced Monday, was one of 23 people charged in
the case. Of that group, 17 pleaded guilty earlier while Luong and
five others were convicted in March after a nine-week trial.
</P>
<P>
   Luong ``supervised and directed the others'' in purchasing and
equipping the fishing boats used to smuggle the immigrants to
California, according to U.S. District Court records. In exchange
for $650,000, the records said, Luong arranged for the fraudulent
purchase of two vessels that met a trawler off-shore that had taken
the immigrants from China.
</P>
<P>
   ``Luong, in sum, was a ringleader in charge of a critical
component of the extensive smuggling operation,'' prosecutor Steven
Gruel said in court records.
</P>
<P>
   One boat landed at near Monterey, the other at Half Moon Bay on
the same day in June 1993. All the passengers were captured
immediately except for 19 who escaped and were found later in New
York, federal officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all of them were deported, except for a few who were
granted political asylum or married U.S. citizens, said Thomas
Schiltgen, district director of the Immigration and Naturalization
Service in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that we have made a dent in this organized alien
smuggling'' with the conviction of Luong and his co-defendants,
Schiltgen said. ``Clearly in 1993 we were seeing a large increase
in the number of boats smuggling people in. ... He was clearly one
of the main organizers of this group.''
</P>
<P>
   The passengers paid $27,000 to $30,000 each for the trip and
were expected to work off the debt in brothels or other gang-run
operations in New York, Gruel said.
</P>
<P>
   Gang members testifying for the prosecution said three New
York-based Asian gangs met with California gangs to plan the
operation, and Luong agreed to arrange the voyage.
</P>
<P>
   Luong's lawyer, Maureen Kallins, denied he was the ringleader
and asked for a sentence of about 2 1/2 years, the term given to
three other defendants in the case. She said he had a traumatic
childhood in wartime Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Gruel sought a five-year sentence, saying the immigrants were
forced to live in miserable conditions below decks during their
four-day voyage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-98 1524EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
