<DOCNO> NYT19980915.0173 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 15:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6162 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-DEFIANT-BOOME     09-15 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-DEFIANT-BOOMER-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON IS A DEFIANT BABY BOOMER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By FLORA LEWIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    PARIS _ Let the Congress vote a reprimand, or whatever it needs
to get the Clinton sex scandal out of the way. It's not a matter of
forgiving Clinton; he demeaned himself. It's a matter of whether,
in the desire to punish him, the country and indeed the rest of the
world should be punished by distorting or incapacitating the U.S.
political system.
 &HT;    The United States has had some incompetent, dishonest, dreadful
presidents, and the system has survived them because the formal,
official decision of the voters is not taken lightly. Clinton has
irreparably tarnished himself, but he is by no means one of the
worst.
 &HT;    This man's difficulty in telling the truth about himself was
already on display in his first presidential campaign and he hasn't
improved. Now, his decision to defend himself with semantic
arguments is more of the same, on a level with the tawdry details
of Kenneth Starr's report of his dalliance in the corridors of
power.
 &HT;    There's something sophomoric about it, a contrast with the
energy and earnestness Clinton brings to public issues such as
education, health, the budget, foreign affairs. If that becomes a
reason to get rid of him, what kind of personal failing or
unpopularity might the precedent be enlarged to justify the next
time around?
 &HT;    There is a strong undertone of revenge from the right for the
ouster of Richard Nixon in this case. But any comparison of the two
cases is unwarranted because this is not about the exercise of
public power entrusted to the highest office. It is about the sort
of man he is, still a kind of defiant baby boomer when much of the
country wants to swing back from the excesses of the
counterculture.
 &HT;    He apparently can't change that part of himself, too bad for him
but not a danger to the national well-being. The danger comes if he
is rendered incapable of doing the part of his job that he can do.
Americans cannot expect to be understood by the citizens of any
other democracy if they put distaste for Clinton's personal
behavior above responsibility for performance in office.
 &HT;    In a way, the whole issue and its salaciously insistent public
airing is in tune with the violence and sex that have come to
dominate entertainment. What are we looking for, what do we reward?
 &HT;    The outpouring of admiration for the baseball star Mark McGuire
shows how much the country yearns for a hero who epitomizes hard
work and skill. But Americans are not likely to get politicians
with the traits they seek if the winners risk exposure and disgrace
for private habits.
 &HT;    The issue is no longer Clinton's behavior and evident character
flaws. It is about governance and constitutional precedent, not so
much the president but the presidency. In what circumstances is the
duly registered decision of the American electorate to be set
aside, invoking the provision for his removal from office?
 &HT;    The paralysis of the White House sex-and-lies scandal is hurting
not only the United States but all the countries affected by its
role in the world.
 &HT;    It is not surprising that in France, where unsanctified sex is
no scandal, President Jacques Chirac said, ``At a time when the
world is confronted with serious political and financial
uncertainty, it is essential for all of us that the president of
the United States is able to carry out his duties fully.'' German
Chancellor Helmut Kohl and British Prime Minister Tony Blair echoed
the thought.
 &HT;    Everybody needs to know what Washington is up to. Everybody
wants Washington to pay attention to the major problems of wars,
nuclear risks and economic distress that are confronting the world.
Is that a reason for Clinton to resign or be impeached and tried?
 &HT;    I say no. The constitutional precedent is too dangerous. In
American history, only one president ever resigned because
impeachment was almost certain and conviction quite possible. That
was Nixon, who faced grave charges of abuse of public power.
 &HT;    To expand these grounds to forcing out a president because he
has been shown to be a moral embarrassment in his private affairs
and because of his tricky attempts to avoid admitting them in
public would be a big step toward changing the whole system and
opening it to further, more arbitrary reasons for overruling an
election.
 &HT;    The American system, unlike that of parliamentary countries,
relies on fixed election dates that cannot be changed. No lack of
confidence can unseat the chosen leader, and if he dies or is
unable to continue, there is a clear list of succession determined
by the previous election. Recourse is to be found in the next
election.
 &HT;    Of course, it is dismaying to find that a president does not
live up to the higher than average standards which the country
would like to see in its chief representative. Whether they approve
of him or not, people would like a president they can respect.
Maybe next time.
 &HT;     (Flora Lewis is the former foreign-affairs columnist for The
New York Times.) 
 &HT;     c.1998 Flora Lewis 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ------------ &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
