<HEADER>
A6177 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-BRIEFS-$ADV20-     09-15 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BRIEFS-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Sept. 20)  
(JT) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Through Customs In 15 to 20 Seconds &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The quick passage through immigration control that is now used
by business travelers at six airports may soon be open to leisure
travelers who re-enter the country at least three times a year. The
electronic recognition system gives the green light to an enrolled
passenger in 15 to 20 seconds; 70,000 business travelers are
enrolled now.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The system, which reads a plastic card, then recognizes a
traveler's hand inserted in a kiosk that looks like an ATM, is in
operation at international terminals at John F. Kennedy, Newark,
Miami, Los Angeles, Toronto and Vancouver.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Immigration offices at these airports approve business travelers
for a free one-year certification to use the system, which is
called Inspass: Immigration and Naturalization Service Accelerated
Service System. Inspass is free now, but Thomas Andreotta of the
Immigration Service says that eventually there will be a charge for
it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco will soon join the list of Inspass airports; in
1999, Honolulu, Seattle and Washington Dulles will, too. After that
will come, not necessarily in this order: Atlanta, Chicago,
Dallas-Fort Worth, Detroit, Houston, Minneapolis and Montreal.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Citizens of Canada, Bermuda and 26 other countries in the Visa
Waiver Pilot Program who enter the United States regularly may also
qualify for Ins-pass. Steps to open it to other frequent travelers
are planned for next year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to speed through travelers who are considered low
risk so the Immigration staff can concentrate on the rest.
Application information is available from the INS offices at the
six airports. INS form I-823 can also be obtained from the
Internet: www.usdoj.gov/ins/forms.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Minneapolis Celebrates Enlarged Art Museum &LR;
</P>
<P>
   After 10 years of renovation and expansion, the Minneapolis
Institute of Arts plans to make merry next Sunday with live bands,
food, street performers and carriage rides on its premises and in
the adjacent park.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There's a lot to celebrate. The institute's 1915 neo-classical
building, designed by McKim, Mead &AMP; White, has 33 new galleries
behind the original structure and 74 renovated galleries.
Exhibition space is up by 65 percent, making room for 4,000 works
of art, more than triple the number exhibited in 1988. The $150
million ``revitalization'' also included the restoration of the
museum's original Beaux-Arts ceiling and skylight, hidden since a
1930's renovation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All that building and scrubbing allowed for a reinstallation of
the museum's permanent collection. Along with the European and
American paintings, which include Rembrandt's ``Lucretia'' and
works by van Gogh, Cezanne, Poussin, Monet and Picasso, visitors
will see more art from Asia. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-two new galleries are devoted to some 1,500 Asian
objects, which range from Chinese paintings, sculpture, ceramics,
jade and textiles to paintings, screens and sculpture from Japan,
as well as Buddhist, Southeast Asian, Indian, Islamic and Himalayan
art. They opened in late August.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other highlights include a section of Frank Lloyd Wright's 1914
Francis W. Little house, which is being brought in from Deep-haven,
Minn., and 20 interactive computer kiosks that allow visitors to
custom-design tours.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Minneapolis Institute of Arts, which is closed on Monday, is
at 2400 Third Avenue So.; (612) 870-3000. Admission is free.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A Coming-Out Party for Grand Central &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, habitues of Grand Central Terminal had to think
hard to recall a time when the place wasn't a mess, first from
neglect, more recently as a construction site. But as the 500,000
people who pass through daily may have noticed, the vast two-year
project to restore and modernize the 85-year-old station is just
about over at last.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To celebrate, the station will be rededicated on Oct. 1 at 11
a.m. in an hourlong ceremony in the Main Concourse presided over by
E. Virgil Conway, chairman of the Metropolitan Transportation
Authority. Festivities will include a trapeze act by the Big Apple
Circus, a laser show, a documentary by the History Channel and a
performance by the Westchester Philharmonic of ``Grand Central,'' a
commissioned work replete with the sound of whistles and clattering
trains by Bruce Saylor, a New York composer. Antique trains will be
parked on the tracks from Oct. 1 through 5. And the Big Apple
Circus and artists from Music Underground will perform for
commuters in the Main Concourse on Oct. 2 at 7:30 p.m. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The station's most obvious improvements are those befitting a
world-famous architectural landmark. Every inch of the fabled Sky
Ceiling, Caen stone walls and Tennessee marble floors will have
been cleaned and repaired. A new staircase on the concourse's east
side, following the original design of Grand Central's architect,
Whitney Warren, will enhance the building's symmetry. The former
Main Waiting Room, now Vanderbilt Hall, will offer art exhibitions,
concerts and civic events. And the balcony will be home to a series
of restaurants that overlook the cleaned-up concourse. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   More restaurants and snack shops are due on the lower level,
which offers two public dining areas. And perhaps best of all,
Grand Central Terminal is now fully heated and air-conditioned.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
