<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980915.0176 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 15:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6214 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BONE-MARROW-2TAKES-NY     09-15 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONE-MARROW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIGGING FOR FATTY TREASURES IN ANIMAL BONES 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It is dinnertime at Judson Grill in midtown
Manhattan, and typically, a good number of customers have ordered
the grilled dry-aged sirloin with rosti potatoes, bone marrow, pea
leaves and carrots. The marrow comes tucked inside a section of
bone standing at attention alongside the steak, a tiny spoon at the
ready.
</P>
<P>
   There is more than just marrow in the bone. Beneath slices of
the tender, unctuous, delicately meaty tasting substance, there is
a bit of shallot-and-red-wine custard, a perfect complement to the
marrow's seductively mellow texture.
</P>
<P>
   ``About half the time the bones come back empty,'' William
Telepan, the chef, said. ``But plenty of people don't even touch
them; they just want the steak and potatoes. People either like
marrow or they don't.''
</P>
<P>
   I happen to love marrow, and can remember, as a child, fighting
with my mother over which one of us would get the marrow when she
made braised veal shanks. Later, as an adult, I would be
disappointed when my portion of osso buco in a restaurant had an
empty bone instead of one filled with what I considered to be a
treat.
</P>
<P>
   For everyone who loves marrow, indulging in it has suddenly
become easier. Judson Grill will even serve the
marrow-and-custard-filled bones separately, without the steak. One
of the most attention-grabbing appetizers at Michael Jordan's the
Steakhouse N.Y.C. in Grand Central Station is a plate of marrow
bones with coarse salt, wild herb salad and mustard-toasted
baguette.
</P>
<P>
   And for the last six years, the most popular dish at Blue Ribbon
in SoHo has been marrow bones served with oxtail marmalade, foie
gras on toast and salted parsley. Bring your own cardiologist.
</P>
<P>
   ``That dish is pretty tough to beat when it comes to fatty,''
Eric Bromberg, an owner of the restaurant, said. ``So many people
order it that we're starting to serve it at the bakery,'' he said,
referring to Blue Ribbon Bakery, his new restaurant in Greenwich
Village.
</P>
<P>
   Bone marrow is the soft, fatty substance found primarily in long
bones, like the shin and shanks. It is one of the richest foods. An
ounce of marrow has nearly 300 calories, and is virtually all fat,
according to statistics published by the Food and Agriculture
Organization of the United Nations and the National Institutes of
Health.
</P>
<P>
   Like foie gras, which is also buttery soft and fat, bone marrow
begs for a sharp counterpoint, like a few grains of salt or a touch
of acid, to balance the richness. The flavor is mildly meaty.
</P>
<P>
   When roasted inside the shank bone instead of being poached
separately, bone marrow sometimes takes on a slight nuttiness. And
depending on how it is prepared, its color can range from pale to
rosy to caramel brown.
</P>
<P>
   There seems to be little consensus, especially among chefs, as
to how marrow is best prepared and served. At Firebird in the
Theater District, Ari Nieminen, who uses marrow to enrich borscht
and places a bone marrow flan alongside roasted salmon, also serves
marrow bones simply roasted with toast, sea salt and a tangy bit of
parsley relish like a gremolata, the classic garnish for osso buco.
</P>
<P>
   At Citronelle in Washington, Michel Richard uses a hollowed-out
cylinder of a roasted potato instead of a bone as a container for
marrow.
</P>
<P>
   The easiest method is simply to roast it in its bone. Alain
Sailhac, the executive vice president of the French Culinary
Institute, recommends wrapping sections of marrow-filled bones in
foil and putting them in the oven for about 30 minutes. ``Keeping
it in the bone protects it,'' he said. ``The foil prevents it from
melting out.''
</P>
<P>
   The butcher will saw marrow bones to the length you want; two to
three inches is usually the best size. Longer than that and it
becomes difficult to extract the marrow.
</P>
<P>
   Julia Child, who applauds a return to foods in the classic
French tradition, like bone marrow, said that the French also opted
for simplicity. ``We just cracked the bones, dug out the marrow and
poached it,'' she said. ``But it wasn't something we'd do on a 90
degree day.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the French love marrow so much that an excellent little
restaurant in Paris is named L'Os a Moelle _ the Marrow Bone. Just
try a name like that in New York. You might as well call your
restaurant Tripe.
</P>
<P>
   The English and French often spread marrow on toast, but it is
not one of those items that shows up with any frequency in
cookbooks. And you have to be careful, because in cookbooks from
England, marrow, or vegetable marrow, is also the name used for for
green squash.
</P>
<P>
   Clear instructions for handling marrow are in ``La Varenne
Pratique'' by Anne Willan (Crown Publishers, 1989). The essential
point to remember, Ms. Willan writes, is that when poaching marrow
that has been extracted from the bone, the liquid must never boil.
</P>
<P>
   The cooking time is rief; otherwise the marrow will melt.
Poaching it in milk, as some chefs do, instead of in salted water
or broth, will keep the color whiter.
</P>
<P>
   Many chefs first soak the bones or the extracted marrow in
several changes of salted water for anywhere from several hours to
several days to remove the blood. Sailhac said that step is not
necessary for home cooks. ``Restaurants do that so the marrow will
keep better,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And these days, they need to keep marrow on hand, and not only
to serve in stately bones. Instead of a pat of seasoned butter, a
slice of warm marrow to garnish a steak is a time-honored
preparation that can be found at Chanterelle in TriBeCa and Patroon
in midtown.
</P>
<P>
   Many chefs, including Geoffrey Zakarian at Patroon, use marrow
to thicken a sauce, especially the classic Bordelaise.
</P>
<P>
   Marrow has also been a partner for seafood, typically rouget,
the assertively-flavored Mediterranean red mullet. I recall eating
baby turbot with marrow in red wine sauce at the Dorchester Hotel
in London in the mid-1980s. It was the first time I had marrow with
fish.
</P>
<P>
   Now at Aquavit in midtown, Marcus Samuelsson adds a puree of
marrow and shallots to his halibut. At La Fourchette, a new
restaurant on the Upper East Side, Marc Murphy tops seared sea
scallops with slices of lightly caramelized marrow and fresh
truffles, a dish he learned when he was working at Miravile in
Paris.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
