<DOCNO> NYT19980915.0180 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 15:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6218 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BONE-MARROW-2NDTAKE-N     09-15 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONE-MARROW-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: in Paris.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A tangle of salad in vinaigrette dressing helps marry the
flavors. Gilles Epie, the former owner of Miravile who has moved to
America, prepares a dish of scallops with marrow at Gilles, his new
restaurant in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   In Italy, where marrow lovers can count on osso buco, marrow is
used to enrich risotto, which Zakarian does at Patroon.
</P>
<P>
   Restaurants that serve marrow slices do not have to bother with
special implements. But for eating marrow in style, there are the
long narrow marrow spoons made in Europe. And about the only source
for them is Savoir Vivre, a company in Philadelphia that
specializes in hard-to-find utensils for cooking and serving. (The
Georgian-designed, silver-plated spoons are $38 each, or $400 a
dozen; for information, 215-625-7964.)
</P>
<P>
   An espresso spoon, which many restaurants use, is a reasonably
effective substitute. But now at Michael Jordan's, David Walzog,
the chef, has started splitting the marrow bones, roasting them
open-face and serving them flat on the plate instead of like tree
trunks. It is easier to eat, Walzog said, and the marrow becomes
more caramelized and tasty.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all this fancy presentation and cachet, bone marrow is
really pretty lowly stuff. We're not talking about caviar or
truffles here. A pound of bones, containing enough rich marrow to
sate at least three people, will set you back 99 cents at Oppenheim
on the Upper West Side.
</P>
<P>
   At Lobel's, a carriage trade Madison Avenue butcher, the bones
are $1.98 a pound. And they'll crack them for you and even scoop
out the marrow, if you prefer, at no extra charge. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BONE MARROW CANAPES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour 15 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   4 3-inch beef marrow bones
</P>
<P>
   One-third cup finely chopped shallots
</P>
<P>
   Two-thirds cup dry red wine
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon finely chopped parsley
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 baguette, about 2 inches in diameter. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Wrap bones individually in a
double thickness of cheesecloth, then in foil. Place in a roasting
pan, and bake for 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   2. While bones are baking, combine shallots and wine in a small
nonreactive saucepan. Bring to a simmer, and cook until almost all
the wine has evaporated, about 20 minutes. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   3. Allow roasted bones to cool until they can be handled. Remove
marrow, and discard bones.
</P>
<P>
   4. Chop the marrow finely, and place in a mixing bowl. Add
shallot mixture, parsley, lemon juice, and salt and pepper to
taste.
</P>
<P>
   5. From the baguette, cut 12 slices, { inch thick. Toast until
golden brown. Mound the marrow mixture on the toasts, and serve as
an hors d'oeuvre. The marrow mixture may also be served without
toast as a topping for filet mignon or grilled fish.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings (12 canapes).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BONE MARROW FLAN WITH STEAK &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Judson Grill &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 6 hours, including refrigeration &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   8 2-inch beef marrow bones, both ends cut to expose the marrow
(the bones should be smooth and cylindrical for the most attractive
appearance)
</P>
<P>
   { cup minced shallots
</P>
<P>
   1 cup dry red wine
</P>
<P>
   } cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   2 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1{ cups milk
</P>
<P>
   8 10- to 12-ounce boneless sirloin strip steaks
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Chill marrow bones at least one hour. Using a long thin
knife, cut around the inside surface of the bone and push out the
marrow in one piece. Place marrow in a bowl of cold water, and
refrigerate at least 3 hours and up to 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   2. While marrow is refrigerated, place empty bones in a pot and
cover with water. Simmer until all the fat and meat scraps can
easily be scraped away, about 2 hours. Remove bones from water,
scrape them clean and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   3. To prepare flan: In a small nonreactive saucepan, combine
shallots and wine. Bring to a simmer, and cook until almost all the
wine has evaporated, about 30 minutes. Remove from heat, and allow
to cool. In the container of a blender or food processor, combine
cream, eggs and shallot mixture. Puree until smooth. Season to
taste with salt and pepper. Strain through a fine strainer, and set
aside.
</P>
<P>
   4. Preheat oven to 300 degrees. Place teakettle of water over
high heat to bring to a boil. Wrap one end of each bone tightly,
first with plastic wrap, then with foil. Stand each bone up in a
deep roasting pan with the foil on the bottom. Pour the flan
mixture into the bones, filling them up halfway. Cover pan with a
lid or heavy-duty foil, and place in oven. Bake for 45 minutes.
Remove from the oven but keep in the pan.
</P>
<P>
   5. Prepare a hot grill or broiler. Remove marrow from cold
water, and cut into slices { inch thick. Grill or broil the strip
steaks to taste. While steaks are cooking, place milk in a small
skillet over low heat and bring to a slow simmer. Add marrow
slices, and poach until the surfaces are smooth and they are heated
through, about 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   6. To serve, place each steak on a plate. Carefully remove the
foil and plastic from each bone, and place a bone, flan side down,
on each plate. Fill the empty top halves of each bone with the
poached marrow slices. Serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 8 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
