<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 16:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6237 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWINDELL-BOOKSHELF-TE     09-15 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWINDELL-BOOKSHELF-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOO BUSY? SAVOR SAKI AS A CURATIVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY SWINDELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many people who once read much now read not at all. I hear their
complaints. They would like to read but are altogether too busy to
tackle a novel.
</P>
<P>
   Short stories, perhaps? Too busy even for that. Time enough to
skim the newspaper and that's all.
</P>
<P>
   I have a solution that will make happy readers of even the most
time-pressed folk, while also acquainting them with superior
literary fiction.
</P>
<P>
   Simple. They must read Saki.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't an Oriental liquid or vehicle conveyance. It's an
author, well nigh an inimitable one.
</P>
<P>
   Stories by Saki are short, shorter, shortest; and almost every
one is some kind of literary gem. In five or six pages, more often
three or four, sometimes only two, this once-to-a-world author
offers well-carpentered tales that have beginnings, middles, and
delicious endings. It's entertainment all the way as Saki parlays
Wodehousian drollery with O. Henry trickery. While en route, he
adds touches of Damon Runyon and Stephen King, always lacquering
the issue with an irony entirely his own.
</P>
<P>
   Who was he?
</P>
<P>
   Hector Hugh Munro was born in Burma (1870) of English parents,
both of whom died during his early childhood. He was raised in
England by two maiden aunts, but in adulthood he returned to Burma
as a military policeman. At age 29, he settled in London, intending
a career as a historian; and just before the century's turn his
``The Rise of the Russian Empire'' was published _ the only work
under his baptismal name.
</P>
<P>
   While roving Europe as a newspaper correspondent, Munro was
making a name for himself _ another name _ via short, fanciful
pieces that appeared in various periodicals. They were bylined
Saki; no one knows why. The early tales centered on an irreverent
young Englishman named Reginald; and in 1904 ``Reginald'' was
Saki's first published collection, followed six years later by
``Reginald in Russia.'' He abandoned Reginald in favor of Clovis, a
similarly constituted fellow; and 1912 brought ``The Chronicles of
Clovis'' as well as ``The Unbearable Bassington,'' the first of
Saki's two novels.
</P>
<P>
   The Reginald and Clovis vignettes were satirical high comedies.
But in 1914, the great collection ``Beasts and Super Beasts''
broadened Saki's range and made him a household name, as he dipped
into the supernatural and the malevolent powers of dogs and other
animals.
</P>
<P>
   Then, with fame assured, Munro/Saki at age 44 volunteered for
military service in the Great War and was killed in France two
years later, in 1916. The collections ``The Toys of Peace'' and
``The Square Egg,'' incorporating some of his war experience, were
issued posthumously.
</P>
<P>
   Reading Saki only fortifies the notion that he was a really odd
bird, odd but a delight to read. For a stylistic sample, here's the
opening of ``The Open Window,'' one of my favorite Saki charades:
</P>
<P>
   `` `My aunt will be down presently, Mr. Nuttel,' said a very
self-possessed young lady of fifteen; `in the meantime you must try
and put up with me.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Framton Nuttel endeavored to say the correct something which
should duly flatter the niece of the moment without unduly
discounting the aunt that was to come. Privately he doubted more
than ever whether these formal visits on a succession of total
strangers would do much towards helping the nerve cure which he was
supposed to be undergoing ...''
</P>
<P>
   The niece tells Nuttel of her aunt's ``great tragedy'' three
years earlier, when her husband and brothers perished in a bog,
their bodies never recovered. They left through the open window,
and the dotty aunt believes they will return the same way. And they
do! _ some swell nerve cure for Nuttel.
</P>
<P>
   In three pages, Saki gets the reader to shivering along with
Nuttel, until the sublime final sentence implicates the duplicitous
niece: ``Romance at short notice was her specialty.''
</P>
<P>
   Try Saki, even if you have lots of time to spare.
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Swindell is books editor for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7731. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
