<HEADER>
A6253 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LONERANGER-ART-AZR &LR;      09-15 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LONE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOULD-BE LONE RANGER GIVES MEMORIES FREE REIN  
 (ART ADV: PHOTO HAS BEEN SENT TO NYTNS CLIENTS) 
</HEADLINE>
 RANGER-ART-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By SAM LOWE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICKENBURG, Ariz. _ Tex Hill admits his time as the Lone Ranger
was little more than a single clop amid the thundering hoofbeats
from those thrilling days of yesteryear.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, his Lone Ranger got bushwhacked.
</P>
<P>
   Never got to Silver City. Never got to Dodge.
</P>
<P>
   Never got to television, either.
</P>
<P>
   Hill discusses that episode in his life quite readily in the
bookstore he and his wife operate here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was in 1960, after Clayton Moore and John Hart had both
retired from playing the Lone Ranger,'' he explains to those who
question his authenticity as the masked rider. ``I was picked to
play him in a television pilot called ``The Lone Ranger Rides
Again.'' But it fizzled. Nobody bought it.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the memory lingers.
</P>
<P>
   Hill proudly displays photographs of himself as the Lone Ranger
and as other Western movie characters in an area of the bookstore
designated the Tex Hill Movie Cowboy Museum. The pictures show him
in a variety of outfits, portraying both good guys and villains.
But mostly good guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clayton Moore was the Lone Ranger,'' he tells those who stop
by. ``The rest of us were simply actors playing the Lone Ranger.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he never got to ride a big white stallion and save the
West for millions of young fans on the TV tube, he has some fond
recollections of the attempt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The check didn't bounce, I got to ride in a limo and yell
`Hi-yo, Silver!' _ and best of all, I got to keep the costume,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   The bookstore is named Readers of the Purple Sage and offers a
good selection of memorabilia from the days of the B Western
movies. It may be the only place in Arizona that sells
black-and-white 8-by-10 glossies of Sunset Carson and Tim Holt,
books on the films of Johnny Mack Brown, and videos starring Allan
``Rocky'' Lane.
</P>
<P>
   As well as films and tapes featuring the work of Tex Hill.
</P>
<P>
   He said he had small roles in such upper-level oaters as ``The
Alamo,''``The Magnificent Seven'' and ``Bandolero,'' and in such TV
shows as ``Gunsmoke,'' ``Bonanza'' and ``Rawhide.'' He said he also
appeared in other flicks, all Westerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were small pictures,'' Hill says with a wide grin. ``The
budgets were the smallest part. They shot most of them with only
one camera, and they could afford to rent only four horses. So the
bad guys saddled up and rode past the camera, then they'd dismount
and walk the horses back to makeup. They'd spray-paint them a
different color, then we'd mount up and ride past the camera.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way I got my own horse was to shoot one of the bad
guys.''
</P>
<P>
   There were other dissimilarities between Hill's movies and those
starring the big heroes, such as Roy and Gene and Hoppy:
</P>
<P>
   Hill got to kiss the girl.
</P>
<P>
   At least he did once.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crew was a bunch of jokesters,'' he says. ``They told me
and my leading lady, Linda Leone, to hold the kiss until they said
stop. Then they all went to lunch. We could have been liplocked for
an hour if I hadn't opened my eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill bought some of his films and put them on video. He plays
the singing sheriff and the misunderstood gunslinger. He admits
they're not top quality but adds, ``They were family movies. Nobody
got killed real bad, not like today.''
</P>
<P>
   His last movie was another low-budget offering, made in 1976. He
left the movies after that to concentrate on a musical career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the last of the singing cowboys,'' he says, pointing out
the posters and still photos that bill him as ``The Rhinestone
Ranger.'' A display near the cash register offers his compact discs
and tapes, including ``How the West Was Sung'' and ``Song of the
Ranger.''
</P>
<P>
   And, although he admits to ``hair by Clairol'' and Social
Security payments, he's still a singing cowboy. He appears
frequently in Arizona, and has engagements in Texas, California and
Oklahoma this month. Then he'll settle back down for a while in
Wickenburg to tend the store and the horses he and his wife,
Claudia, raise and train.
</P>
<P>
   He can still yodel up a pretty fair country tune, and if asked,
can recite most of the Lone Ranger prologue that preceded every
radio and television show. The one that goes:
</P>
<P>
   ``A fiery horse with the speed of light, a cloud of dust, and a
hearty `Hi-yo, Silver.' . . . Return with us now to those thrilling
days of yesteryear. From out of the past came the thundering
hoofbeats of the great horse, Silver. The Lone Ranger rides
again!''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Hill tries to keep some of that era of make-believe from
vanishing like the hoofbeats and the buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good life,'' he says. ``I was in about 70 movies, and
I always got paid. But the best part was I got to grow up and be my
own childhood hero. Can't ask for much more than that.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
