<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-SCANDAL (Washington) _ House Majority Leader Dick Armey,
R-Texas, says many members of Congress believe that censuring
President Clinton over the Monica Lewinsky affair would amount to
``trivializing'' allegations that include obstruction of justice
and abuse of power. By BENNETT ROTH and GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   PROBE-COST (Washington) _ Independent counsel Kenneth Starr says
his office has spent $4.4 million investigating the Monica Lewinsky
affair. Overall, Starr has spent some $40 million in four years
investigating the Whitewater land deal and other allegations
against the Clintons. By STEVE LASH.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-LEGISLATION (Washington) _ The news out of Congress
these days dwells on how to proceed with allegations that President
Clinton committed impeachable offenses in trying to cover up a
lusty sexual affair. But there's plenty of national business left
on Congress' agenda, including tax cuts, budget issues and
health-care. By GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   BASE-CLOSINGS (Washington) _ Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, says
congressional Republicans will drop their opposition to shuttering
more military bases and approve two more rounds of base closures
after the 2000 elections. Gramm says the savings will be used for
pay increases and weapons modernization. By GARY MARTIN.
</P>
<P>
   MARIJUANA-MEDICAL (Washington) _ The House is expected to
overwhelmingly approve a resolution sponsored by Rep. Bill
McCollum, R-Fla., declaring the chamber is ``unequivocally
opposed'' to legalizing marijuana for medicinal use. By JUDY
HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TX-CLINTON-POLL (Undated) _ Texans' views of President Clinton
and his sex scandal were virtually unchanged by independent counsel
Kenneth Starr's report to Congress, according to a poll conducted
for the Houston Chronicle and The Dallas Morning News. Most of
those surveyed continue to think Clinton should stay in office, and
most continue to separate Clinton's presidential actions from his
personality. By ALAN BERNSTEIN. (Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   TX-IMMIGRANTS (Undated) _ The Border Patrol in the McAllen
sector _ the source of most illegal border crossings in Texas _
says it is releasing 1 out of every 4 suspected illegal immigrants
arrested. The reason is that more and more of those apprehended are
from countries other than Mexico and there is insufficient space
for holding them for background checks. By JAMES PINKERTON.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ The House is already politically
polarized over the question of impeachment; there is no prospect
that this will be handled impartially. The president is never going
to get off the hook; he will have to resign or accept a censure
resolution. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ASTROS (Houston) _ One day after sewing up their second
consecutive National League Central Division title, the Houston
Astros have little time to savor their conquest as they face the
New York Mets in a doubleheader at the Astrodome. Shane Reynolds
goes for his 19th victory of the season, which would tie him for
the league lead. By JOSEPH DUARTE.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-DIERKER (Houston) _ It was a joke from coast to coast when
the Houston Astros named longtime broadcaster Larry Dierker as
their manager before the 1997 season. But after guiding the Astros
to two division titles in his first twos seasons, Dierker and the
Astros' brass are enjoying the last laugh. By JOSEPH DUARTE.
</P>
<P>
   With: BBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN
</P>
