<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASTER-CHEF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SQUASH RISOTTO 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 (This is the fifth of eight columns by Charlie Palmer, chef and
owner of Aureole in Manhattan. Judith Choate collaborated).  
 By CHARLIE PALMER  
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When an Italian risotto maestro approaches the dish, it is
almost always with the intention of producing a risotto that has a
thick, creamy consistency. But some time back, I started
experimenting with a looser, lighter version that requires less
painstaking attention than the traditional approach.
</P>
<P>
   I've come to prefer it as a delicate first course or, garnished
with duck confit or sauteed seafood, as a satisfying main course.
(I haven't given up on the thicker classic, which I still think is
the better choice when served as a foundation for more substantial
portions of meat or poultry.)
</P>
<P>
   In an autumn frame of mind, and to simplify my light risotto
even further, what I present here is an uncomplicated, pure
showcase for sweet squash. Practically all parts of the spectrum of
hard-skinned squashes and little pumpkins are candidates for the
dish: Hubbard, turban, Australian blue butternut and delicata are
just a few of them. Their colors and mellow flavors sing fall at
the table.
</P>
<P>
   This risotto is enriched with a puree of squash, onion and
nutmeg. Then, in place of the duck or the seafood that I'd
typically lean toward in the restaurant, I garnish the dish with
only a bit of blanched squash and fresh herbs. The tender-crisp
squash crowning the risotto provides textural variation, of course,
but it is also a visual key to the soft flavors hidden in each
kernel of rice.
</P>
<P>
   Although I've taken some liberties with this dish, I don't want
to yield on the quality of the rice. This risotto still requires,
as the traditional version does, one of the Italian short-grain
rices, like Arborio, carnaroli or vialone nano. All of them possess
the starchiness necessary to produce a creamy, brothlike liquid,
which will embrace the firm, al dente center of the cooked rice.
</P>
<P>
   And I want to urge you to use a good homemade chicken stock,
knowing full well that you probably won't feel you have the time to
do it (unless you're one of those foresighted individuals who
prepare a big batch and then freeze it for recipes like this one).
</P>
<P>
   More likely, you're going to turn to one of the canned broths,
but be sure to stick to the low-sodium ones or you will lose any
chance of controlling the saltiness of the final dish. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WINTER SQUASH RISOTTO &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour 15 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   { pound (about 1{ cups) finely diced fresh winter squash
(Hubbard, butternut, kabocha or sugar pumpkin)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 cup finely chopped onions
</P>
<P>
   1{ teaspoons ground nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   1\ teaspoons freshly ground white pepper
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   } cup medium-dry California riesling
</P>
<P>
   7 cups chicken stock or low-sodium canned chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   1{ cups Arborio rice
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons chopped fresh parsley
</P>
<P>
   { cup freshly grated Parmesan cheese. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Bring a small saucepan of water to a boil, and add 3
tablespoons of the diced squash. Cook until barely tender, about 2
minutes; then drain, and rinse under cold water. Set aside. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2. In a medium saucepan over medium heat, warm the oil, and add
the remaining squash, { cup of the onion, nutmeg, white pepper and
salt to taste. Saute, stirring frequently, until the squash is
almost tender, about 7 minutes. Add the wine, and cook, stirring
occasionally, for 15 minutes. Remove from heat, and allow to cool.
In a food processor or blender, puree until smooth. Transfer to a
bowl, and set aside. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3. Place the stock in a medium saucepan, and bring to a boil.
Reduce heat to very low, just to keep the stock hot. In a medium
heavy-bottom saucepan over medium heat, melt 2{ tablespoons of the
butter. Add the rice and remaining { cup of onion, and stir well
with a wooden spoon until the onion is translucent, about 5
minutes. Immediately add about 1{ cups of hot stock or just enough
to cover the rice. Simmer gently for 10 minutes, stirring
occasionally, adding a cup of stock about every 3 minutes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   4. Add the winter squash puree, and stir well. Simmer for 9
minutes more, continuing to add stock every few minutes, until all
of the stock has been used. Add the remaining 2{ tablespoons of
butter and the parsley. Cook, stirring constantly, until the butter
has been completely absorbed, about 3 minutes. Adjust the salt and
pepper to taste. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   5. Spoon equal portions of risotto into 6 warm soup bowls.
Garnish the center of the risotto with reserved squash dice.
Sprinkle each bowl with Parmesan cheese, and serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
