<HEADER>
A6285 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-15 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOTERS AREN'T AS DUMB AS THE POLLSTERS THINK 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Maybe I put too little stock in instantaneous
telephone polls or just don't grasp the big picture. But I can't
accept the idea that ``disillusioned Democrats'' are likely to
react to the Monica Lewinsky scandal by refusing to vote for
Democratic gubernatorial and congressional candidates in the
November elections.
</P>
<P>
   According to a number of doom-intoning news stories that I have
read, Democrats and Republicans alike believe that President
Clinton's disaster can't help but become every Democrat's disaster.
Because of hurt feelings, disgust, a sense of betrayal _ name your
victimhood _ tens of thousands of Democrats are supposed to simply
``stay home'' on Nov. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Especially women Democrats, who helped Bill Clinton and Al Gore
vanquish the Republicans in '92 and '96.
</P>
<P>
   These predictions are based on vaguely-worded opinion polls
(usually taken six or seven minutes after the latest revelation
from Capitol Hill) and on the fact that congressional Democrats
took a drubbing in '94. As that theory goes, Democratic voters were
so disillusioned/disgusted or apathetic that they didn't bother to
get off their rear ends and vote for Democratic candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of Monica, the primary reason was the Clinton
administration's botched attempt at health care reform.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the supposedly sophisticated exit polls and
post-election analysis, do we really know why people decide to vote
or not? For all the hundreds or thousands who tell a pollster, ``I
stayed home because of botched health care reform,'' how many
people might answer, ``I was too busy.'' Or ``I meant to, but my
kid got sick.''
</P>
<P>
   In California, how many might admit, ``The number of ballot
measures finally paralyzed me.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, 11 days after the president's lame apology to the
nation, a Republican pollster named Ed Goeas told The Associated
Press: ``The Democrats are not as likely to be interested in the
(November) election. They are less intense about voting and about
supporting their candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   As evidence, Goeas pointed to ``his own detailed survey of voter
intensity.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to cast aspersions on that or any survey, but how can
someone feel comfortable generalizing about millions of voters,
possible voters and possible non-voters? Particularly in this day
of instant and incessant ``Whaddaya think?'' queries by everybody
from CNN to your neighborhood shopping monthly?
</P>
<P>
   As disgusted, disillusioned and betrayed as I might feel by Bill
Clinton _ and, to tell the truth, I'm still not sure what I feel
about him _ I can't imagine transferring any of that to the
November elections.
</P>
<P>
   Why would I?
</P>
<P>
   First of all, I'm a registered Democrat who tends to vote for
Democrats. Given the choice between the priorities I hear
Republicans and Democrats touting this year, I remain inclined
toward the Democratic philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   Second, I know that, whether he campaigns for them or not, Bill
Clinton is not Sen. Barbara Boxer or any other Democrat who is up
for election. And Clinton's penchant for illicit sex and lying
about it hasn't been adopted by the party as behavior to be
emulated by all.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, it would give me much satisfaction if Democrats picked up
the 11 seats they've got a shot at in Congress. And I would dearly
love to see a Democrat in the California governor's mansion for a
change.
</P>
<P>
   The only way to help make that happen, of course, is to vote.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe there really are millions of Democrats out there who would
feel worse going to the polls than they would at the prospect of a
Republican sweep. I'm not one of them. And it's hard to believe so
many people could be so dumb. Especially women.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
