<HEADER>
A6287 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KITCHEN-WARES-ART-2TA     09-15 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KITCHEN-WARES-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM ELECTRIC DRILLS TO RADIATOR GRILLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Kenneth Johnson, the chef at the Terrace restaurant
at Columbia University, uses pantyhose to strain consomme.
</P>
<P>
   It may sound bizarre, but actually, he says, it works better
than cheesecloth. The hosiery is so fine that it prevents any small
particles from filtering through and clouding the soup. And because
it fits so snugly _ he stretches a double layer over a bowl, and
ties it under the rim _ it is easier to work with.
</P>
<P>
   It is a clever little trick, one of many in the restaurant
world. And some of them are useful at home, too. Chefs are always
devising new ways to execute their ideas: they are under constant
pressure to be original, but time is at a premium, and so is money.
</P>
<P>
   So when conventional kitchen equipment can't accomplish what
they want it to do, they look for other ways to get the job done.
That may mean rigging together a few pans to make a smoker or using
a melon baller to make chocolate curls. Or it could mean heading to
the hardware or drugstore to hunt down a solution.
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, impromptu innovations have turned into standard
equipment. Take, for instance, the tower of salad, that perfectly
cylindrical, compact mass of greens that sticks up like a giant
thimble on the plate at Windows on the World and Monkey Bar.
</P>
<P>
   No, the leaves are not stacked one by one like bricks to make a
tower. Instead, a paper cup that has its bottom cut off or a short
section of plastic pipe is set on the plate, filled with salad and
then lifted off.
</P>
<P>
   But David Burke, the chef at Park Avenue Cafe, takes equipment
innovation to a new level. Take this man to a Home Depot, and you
may never see him again. He especially likes his power drill. Using
a doorknob bit, he blasts holes into blocks of ice to make what he
calls ``an abstract mountain of ice that has caves in it and
ledges.'' Oysters are served on this mountain. A smaller bit is
used to shave the kernels off the ends of an ear of corn to make
handles for holding it.
</P>
<P>
   Back on planet Earth, he also has a few more practical ideas _
like his method for oiling a griddle or grill. He uses a paint
roller with a tea towel wrapped and tied around it. This gives just
a thin coating of oil and when grilling, prevents fires from
flaring up.
</P>
<P>
   Regulars at Bouley Bakery, brace yourselves. That lovely,
fragrant steamed fish is, I'm afraid, wrapped and cooked in plastic
wrap. William Schutz, the chef de cuisine, lays the fish and
seasonings on a piece of plastic wrap, closes it and places it in a
stainless-steel steamer (normally, you would place the fish
directly in the steamer). He insists the plastic wrap seals in all
the cooking juices so that none are lost in the steamer.
</P>
<P>
   But chefs are amateurs when compared with pastry chefs: they are
innovation fiends. Perpetually discontent with the tools and molds
they have at hand, they are constantly fiddling and retooling. A
trip to a junk shop or even a Staples can send tremors of creative
energy through them.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look for something that will set your work apart,'' said
Krista Kern, the pastry chef at the Norwich (Conn.) Inn and Spa.
``So you're not using a mold that's mass-produced.''
</P>
<P>
   No kidding. Ms. Kern had curtain rods cut down to fit on a sheet
pan. She wraps them with 10-inch-by-12-inch rectangles of phyllo
and bakes them to make phyllo straws to fill with chocolate mousse.
</P>
<P>
   Jacques Torres, the pastry chef at Le Cirque 2000, molds
chocolate with bubble wrap, among other things. He pours melted
chocolate over the bubble wrap, then chills it. It hardens into a
heavily textured layer of chocolate that can be broken up into
jagged pieces and used for garnishing. He does the same thing with
the plastic covers used over fluorescent light fixtures.
</P>
<P>
   Any nonporous surface can be used for molding chocolate. ``You
go to any bath supply place, and anything made out of acrylic can
be used,'' said Richard Leach, the pastry chef at Park Avenue Cafe.
He makes chocolate pops in an acrylic holder designed for
lipsticks. He coats the long thin slots with chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Once solid, he fills them with a praline ganache, inserts a
Popsicle stick and freezes them. Then they come right out.
</P>
<P>
   Pastry chefs are also inclined to use almost anything as a
stencil. For cookies, Nick Malgieri, the director of the baking
program at Peter Kump's New York Cooking School, might cut a star
or some other design into the lid of a ricotta container. Then he
uses the lids to decorate the tops of cakes or cookies with
confectioners' sugar, or sets them on a baking sheet and brushes
tuile batter over them to form cookies in any number of shapes.
</P>
<P>
   For cakes, Torres likes to use the ornate grillwork seen on
prewar radiator covers. He lays the cover on an inch-deep baking
sheet lined with parchment and coats it with a sponge cake batter
tinted with food coloring. He removes the radiator grille, freezes
the parchment, then fills the rest of the pan with regular cake
batter and bakes it. When the cake is done, the geometric design is
baked into the cake. He inverts the cake and peels off the
parchment.
</P>
<P>
   Radiator stencils nothwithstanding, trying out an unconventional
tool is usually an effort at being practical, not flashy. ``A lot
of different things are for speed, but a lot are mostly out of
necessity,'' said Ms. Kern, the Norwich pastry chef.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, when coating puff pastry or phyllo with melted
butter, Ms. Kern uses a plastic spray bottle rather than a brush.
``You can spray an entire surface delicately and lightly,'' she
said, and it's much quicker.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Lomonaco, the chef at Windows on the World, used to
roast salmon on expensive cedar planks. So he went to the lumber
yard and found a cheaper solution: untreated cedar roof shingles.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, shingles. And, in fact, they get more pampering than the
fish. He soaks them in water for a few hours, then warms them on a
sheet pan in the oven and brushes them with oil. Finally the fish
is placed on top and roasted.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is that no object, no tool, no doodad is denied entry
into the restaurant kitchen if it does the job.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Chez Panisse in Berkeley, Calif., doesn't use
expensive pastry rings for baking, said Seen Lippert, who used to
cook there. ``Everybody brought in their empty cat food cans, and
we would cut off the bottoms,'' she said. In the dining room the
desserts were called flourless chocolate cakes. In the kitchen they
were known as cat-food tarts.
</P>
<P>
   Remember that the next time you pay $68 for dinner there.
</P>
<P>
   So was Johnson at Terrace Restaurant just saving money when he
sprung for the pantyhose? No, he said. Inspiration struck one day
when he ran out of cheesecloth. So he went to the drugstore to pick
up some gauze.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walked in, and I saw `sheer legs,' he said. ``And I don't
know why but a light went on.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Have you found cooking uses for unconventional tools or ways to
put kitchen equipment through some unusual paces? The editors would
like to know. Please write to the Dining section, The New York
Times, 229 West 43d Street, New York 10036-3959, or by e-mail to
dining(AT) &QC; nytimes.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
