<HEADER>
A6307 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT &LR;      09-15 0553
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FAST TOPPING FOR FRUIT  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARK BITTMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Take a soft, ripe fruit, and top it with creme anglaise (a thin
custard), sabayon (a frothy egg-and-wine mixture) or another sweet
sauce. Run the whole thing under the broiler, and you have a
four-star dessert. The only problem is, luxurious sauces like these
take a fair amount of time and attention to prepare.
</P>
<P>
   I wondered, what if the fruit was topped with something fast and
easy? Thus began a lengthy process of elimination that ended only
when I made just about the easiest topping possible: sweetened
heavy cream, whipped just enough so that it held some of its body
when broiled. Even simpler, I found next, was sweetened sour cream,
which barely needs to be whisked.
</P>
<P>
   The toppings produce markedly different results. Sour cream is
thick, rich, flavorful and, obviously, sour. The whipped cream is
thinner and more saucy in texture. It also browns beautifully, and
_ especially if you begin with really good cream _ has a fresh
subtlety that cannot be matched. I like both choices, and between
the two of them I feel that I may never produce another sabayon, at
least not for this purpose.
</P>
<P>
   Be sure that the fruit you use is perfectly ripe. You're going
to serve this dish with spoons, and the last thing you want to do
is have to reach for a knife and fork. In the past week, I have
used figs, pitted prune plums, strawberries, raspberries,
blueberries, peaches, and have also used them in various
combinations. They were all great, but if I had to pick a favorite
I suppose it would be peaches spiked with a few raspberries and
blueberries.
</P>
<P>
   Although this preparation is lightning-quick, cooking it takes
near-constant watchfulness. Get the broiler hot, place the dish
right under the heating element, and keep your eyes open. You want
the topping to burn a little bit _ it will smell like toasting
marshmallows _ but not too much. When the topping is nearly
uniformly brown, with a few black spots, it's done. The fruit will
not have cooked at all, but will have warmed slightly.
</P>
<P>
   10-MINUTE FRUIT GRATIN
</P>
<P>
   1 to 1{ pounds perfectly ripe soft fruit like peaches, plums,
berries, figs or a combination
</P>
<P>
   1 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract.
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat broiler; set rack as close to heat source as possible
(even 2 inches is not too close).
</P>
<P>
   2. Wash, pit, stem and peel the fruit as necessary. Cut stone
fruit in halves or slices, as you prefer. Cut strawberries in thick
slices; leave smaller berries whole. Place the fruit (at least 2
cups full) in a baking or gratin dish just large enough to hold it.
</P>
<P>
   3. Whip cream with 2 tablespoons of sugar until it is thick and
just barely holding soft peaks; stir in the vanilla extract. Pour
cream over and around the fruit. Sprinkle with remaining sugar.
</P>
<P>
   4. Broil carefully, allowing cream to brown all over and even
burn in a couple of spots; rotate baking dish during broiling if
necessary. Remove and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   Topping variation: Combine 1 cup sour cream with just enough
milk _ about \ cup _ so that you can whisk it smooth. Add 2
tablespoons sugar, and proceed as above, using 1 tablespoon brown
sugar for the topping.
</P>
</TEXT>
