A6335 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ADOPTION-RACE16-COX     09-15 0397
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADOPTION-RACE16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    STATES SLOW TO OBEY LAW BARRING RACE AS ADOPTION FACTOR
 &HT;    BY NICHOLE MONROE
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Not enough is being done to make sure states comply
with a law that makes it illegal to use race as a factor in placing
children adoptive homes, witnesses told Congress on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, adoption case workers have tried to place children
with parents of the same race. But a 1994 federal law said race
could not be used as the only factor in adoptions, and a 1996
amendment went further, outlawing race as factor except in rare
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, the legislation was intended to cut the length of
time children wait to be adopted. More than 59 percent of the
110,000 American children waiting to be adopted are African
American.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses told the House Ways and Means subcommittee on human
resources Tuesday that the U.S. Department of Health and Human
Services went to great lengths to implement the 1994 act, but acted
more slowly and did less to help states implement the 1996
provisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a tragedy and a travesty,'' said Rep. E. Clay Shaw
Jr., R-Fla., the panel's chairman. ``I have long been committed to
attacking this problem of unequal treatment of minority children in
state custody, and after reading today's testimony I am even more
strongly committed to doing everything I can to shorten their stay
in foster care.''
</P>
<P>
   Compliance with the amendments varies. Olivia Golden, HHS
assistant secretary for children and families, said while some
agencies and states have been quick to enact reforms, others
continue to be cited for non-compliance.
</P>
<P>
   But former Sen. Howard Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, the main sponsor of
the 1994 act, blasted the department, telling the hearing that
every state has been found in violation of the 1996 law and that
the department needs to get tougher on those who don't comply,
especially those who receive federal funding.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Nadel of the General Accounting Office, the auditing arm of
Congress, said HHS has done little to actually change the working
practices of adoption case workers. He said the department needs to
offer more practical advice to case workers and develop systems to
monitor how well states are complying.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
