<SLUG> BC-BASE-CLOSINGS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATOR EXPECTS MORE BASE CLOSINGS AFTER 2000 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GARY MARTIN  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. Phil Gramm said Tuesday that Republicans in
Congress would drop their opposition to closing more military bases
and approve two more rounds of closures after the 2000 elections.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm, R-Texas, said more bases need to be closed to slash
spending on facilities and redirect the money to pay increases for
armed services personnel and the modernization of weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will have two more base closure commissions, as painful as
it is going to be,'' Gramm told the group of 62 business leaders
from San Antonio, a city hard hit by the closing of the aircraft
repair facility at Kelly Air Force Base.
</P>
<P>
   Key Republicans in Congress have blocked the Clinton
administration's request for future rounds of base closings, citing
the president's involvement in decisions to close Kelly and
McClellan Air Force Base in Sacramento, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans have charged that Clinton played politics by
intervening to protect Kelly and McClellan from immediate closure
to gain electoral support in his 1996 re-election bid, a charge the
president denied. The base closure process, established at the end
of the Cold War, is intended to be nonpolitical.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm said ``Republicans are using Clinton's intervention as an
excuse'' to avoid the politically painful process of closing bases
no longer needed by the military.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm said he expects Congress, after the presidential election
in 2000, to ratify two additional rounds of closures to reduce
spending on installations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sobering news for any community with a military
installation,'' he said, while adding that continued funding of
unnecessary bases is ``consuming money for pay increases and
modernization.''
</P>
<P>
   The San Antonio business delegation organizes yearly trips to
the nation's capital to lobby the Pentagon and Congress for
military missions and to protect local interests that are
intertwined with the military bases.
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio lost the Kelly aircraft depot, then the largest
single-site employer in the region, during the 1995 round of base
closures. The Air Force plans turn the base over to the city in
2001.
</P>
<P>
   City leaders have lured the Boeing Co. and other tenants to the
facility as part of plans to redevelop Kelly as an industrial
facility.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, called those efforts a
success and pledged more help to shore up four other San Antonio
military bases that could be targets for future base closure
rounds.
</P>
</TEXT>
