<SLUG> BC-FOOD-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRISP QUICHE CRUSTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: My quiche crust is always slightly soggy. Is there a trick to
insure a dry crust?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, there is, and James Beard knew it. In his ``Theory and
Practice of Good Cooking,'' he explained that quiche crusts are
subject to sogginess, since the filling is quite liquid.
</P>
<P>
   His trick was to spread the bottom of a partially baked crust
with a thin layer of beaten whole egg, beaten egg white, egg yolk
or Dijon mustard, then to return the crust to the oven to dry. The
egg or mustard creates a barrier, which helps keep the filling from
seeping into the pastry.
</P>
<P>
   Beard's instructions are: Bake the pastry at 425 degrees for 14
to 16 minutes, then brush it with either mustard or egg. Return the
crust to the oven for two minutes. Do not fill the crust until just
before baking (it can rest on a cooling rack for several hours if
necessary).
</P>
<P>
   Quiche is best hot or warm, and should not be refrigerated
before serving. Melissa Clark &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
