<SLUG> BC-HMO-REPORTCARD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURVEY GIVES HMO HIGH MARKS FOR HEALTH CARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ULYSSES TORASSA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A new survey of health maintenance organizations
in California gives high marks to Kaiser Permanente for both
preventive care and customer satisfaction, while lower scores went
to fast-growing Blue Shield.
</P>
<P>
   The survey of service to about 80,000 customers, including
reviews of 60,000 patient charts, is by the California Cooperative
Healthcare Reporting Initiative, a coalition of businesses, health
plans, physician and hospital groups set up to monitor the quality
of HMOs. It was released Tuesday to coincide with the beginning of
open enrollment season, during which workers can switch among plans
offered by their employer.
</P>
<P>
   Ninety percent of customers surveyed had no recent complaints at
Kaiser Permanente North, which has 2.8 million members in Northern
California and is the largest in the region. Eighty-four percent
also said they'd recommend the plan to friends or family.
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser also scored above average for its rates of cervical and
breast cancer screenings, prenatal care, administering beta
blockers after heart attacks, and immunizing children and teens.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Michael Ralston, Kaiser's director of quality demonstration,
said the data show that the health plan's group model delivers
better care. Under it, health plan members go only to Kaiser
facilities and see doctors who are part of the Kaiser Permanente
medical group. Those doctors, in turn, see only Kaiser patients.
</P>
<P>
   The other HMOs surveyed use networks of doctors and hospitals,
who may treat patients from a variety of plans.
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser's close-knit nature and its automated patient files mean
it can keep track of members who haven't gotten recommended
check-ups. Gaps generate reminder cards that urge people to come in
for tests or immunizations, Ralston said.
</P>
<P>
   Customers of Blue Shield of California, while not tremendously
dissatisfied, gave their HMO less-than-average marks on its
referral process and on how well physicians explain tests and
procedures.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate review of patient files, the survey found
below-average rates for cervical and breast cancer screenings,
adolescent immunizations and check-ups for mothers after
childbirth. In only one category, administering beta blocker
treatment after heart attacks, did it receive an above-average
score.
</P>
<P>
   That could be because Blue Shield, which instituted two programs
in the last year, is feeling growing pains from adding 30 percent
more members, said Dr. Alan Feren, the plan's Northern California
regional medical director. One new program lets members see
specialists in the network without a referral and another offers
coverage for alternative treatments, including chiropractic visits,
acupuncture and massage therapy.
</P>
<P>
   An influx of new patients means it isn't as easy to locate files
containing reports of screenings and other preventive care. If the
file couldn't be found, the survey counted it as a service not
rendered.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Feren said the plan, which serves nearly 700,000 members
in Northern California, is concerned about the numbers and vows to
do better soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel strongly that when the dust settles, we will be equal
or better than our competitors,'' Feren said.
</P>
<P>
   The report card is the first of several HMO quality scorecards
expected to be released in the coming month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-98 1708EDT &QL; 
