<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALVADOS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALVADOS, THE SEDUCTIVE BRANDY OF NORMANDY'S EDEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic map is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (editors: recipe appears in 3rd take)  
 (bl)  
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST.-CYR-DU-RONCERAY, France _ Normandy is so close to Paris that
wise guys sometimes call it the 21st arrondissement. Which no doubt
explains why, in the old days, Normandy's Calvados, or apple
brandy, was the capital's favorite tipple. To a degree, it still is
_ not so much in the grand hotels and the restaurants showered with
stars, but in the bars, bistros and brasseries frequented by
ordinary folk.
</P>
<P>
   A coffee and a glass of Calvados _ a ``ti Calva'' _ conclude
many a jolly Parisian evening.
</P>
<P>
   Calvados resembles the applejack beloved by old-time Yankees,
but at its best, after careful aging in wood, it has far greater
finesse. The art lies in taming the fire of the newly distilled
spirit without losing the distinctive taste of the fruit. Some
inferior Calvados is aggressive; some is smooth enough but might
have been made of potatoes or grapes instead of apples.
</P>
<P>
   Normandy lies across the channel from England, which the Normans
famously conquered in 1066. It is too cold for the successful
commercial cultivation of wine grapes. Deprived of the vine, the
Normans turned early on to the apple for everyday drinks _ spritzy
lightly alcoholic cider, traditionally served cool from a stone
pitcher for quaffing with meals, and pungent, decidedly alcoholic
Calvados for sipping afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Calvados has never achieved the renown or aristocratic aura of
Cognac. Only in recent years has it appeared in stores and
restaurants outside France. No less eminent a figure than Marcel
Proust, who spent many seaside holidays at Cabourg on the Norman
coast, vouched for it in ``Remembrance of Things Past.''
</P>
<P>
   And the American journalist A.J. Liebling, a more dedicated
eater and drinker than Proust, if not a better writer, had this to
say, in ``Normandy Revisited,'' about Calvados and its ways:
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never wavered in my belief that old Calvados has a more
agreeable bouquet, a warmer touch to the heart and a more outgoing
personality than Cognac. It is less precocious, but that is only a
confirmation of its more profound character. The barrel of Calvados
laid down at an infant's birth matures with him; he is unlikely to
need it until he is at least 11, and by that time it will be
passable. If the boy is to drink Calvados at its best, however, it
is better to lay down several barrels, so he will still have some
when he is 50.''
</P>
<P>
   For centuries, Calvados was a farmhouse product, handmade by
peasants, but in this field as in so many others, the big boys are
taking over. Mass-produced brands like Busnel, Boulard and Pere
Magloire account for the bulk of the 11 million bottles sold
annually, half of them abroad (mostly in Europe, but also in Japan
and the United States). Most of this Calvados is young and
unsubtle. These are sluggers, not boxers.
</P>
<P>
   But some small-fries persist. One of the best is Marc de
Lesdain, a convivial, red-faced farmer who has been distilling
since 1959 in the hamlet of Ste.-Foy-de-Montgommery. (Yes, with a
double ``M'' in the middle. The family that produced Field Marshal
Montgomery, of World War II fame, lived there in the Middle Ages;
it dropped an ``M'' when it moved to Ireland.)
</P>
<P>
   On the main highway in Ste.-Foy, there is a big commercial
distillery, with tanks visible through a big picture window. To
find de Lesdain, you have to cross the railroad tracks and the Vie
River and look out for a charming, typically Norman half-timbered
house and barn on your left. That's where he produces, for a mainly
regional clientele, in his own still and with the apples from his
own 10 acres of trees, a smoky, fruity, perfectly balanced
15-year-old Calvados that is 45 percent alcohol, a few degrees
stronger than most.
</P>
<P>
   ``You must learn to taste before you distill,'' he said one
Sunday afternoon in July, sitting at a long table covered with
trophies, and offering me tempting topaz-hued tastes from a cluster
of bottles. ``You have to know how to tell when the fruit is too
ripe, when the blend is wrong, how to correct the faults. Every
batch through the still has a personality. Now, industrialists run
everything, with their technicians and their laboratories. In the
alcohol factories, nothing is ever really bad, nothing is ever
really good.''
</P>
<P>
   Calvados demands a certain deference on the part of the
consumer. In an otherwise-forgotten BBC situation comedy, the
hard-drinking hero warned his mate: ``It shouldn't be gulped down
by the mugful. If you do that you will lose the flavor and the
bouquet. You will also lose your power of speech.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, not quite, maybe, but I remember an international
conference in Normandy a decade or so ago at which the organizers
were silly enough to stock each participant's room with bottles of
the potent local hooch, and restock them when needed. The
discussions tended to wander even more than normal at such
gatherings, and a lot of us woke up every morning with a lively new
understanding of why the apple had been forbidden to Adam and Eve.
</P>
<P>
   The name Calvados is taken from that of one of the five
departments of Normandy, which extends inland from the seaside
resorts of Deauville and Honfleur and the invasion beaches of 1944.
It is a countryside of gentle green hills and shallow valleys, with
the Virgin or a crucifix at every crossroads, that seems to have
lost track of time. The department's name is said by local people
to be a corruption of Salvador, the name of a Spanish man-of-war
that was wrecked on the Normandy coast after the defeat of the
Armada by the British in 1588. Historians doubt that, but offer no
other explanation.
</P>
<P>
   In the spring, the region presents one of the loveliest pictures
in all of France _ more than 9 million apple trees, blossoming
pink-white around the picturesque old farmhouses, with
black-and-white and brown-and-white cows grazing underneath the
trees or nearby. Cheese (most notably Camembert, Livarot and
Pont-l'Eveque) is another significant Norman gastronomic product.
</P>
<P>
   Calvados is distilled from cider, the pressed juice of
particular varieties of apples, just as Cognac is made from grape
juice. Cider apples, often of small diameter, blotchy and
unattractive, are too sour to be eaten with pleasure. They are
grouped in four families: sweet, bitter, bittersweet and acid. To
make a successful Calvados, juices from several of these are
blended before distilling.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the best varieties came originally from the Basque
country, farther south, as early as the 13th century. (Some bear
names, like ``Bisquet'' or ``Marin Onfroy,'' that refer in one way
or another to their origins.)
</P>
<P>
   By law, Calvados can be produced only in a specified area of
Normandy, which includes the department of Calvados plus all or
part of the four other Norman departments _ Eure, Manche,
Seine-Maritime and Orne. Only cider that reaches a minimum of 4.5
percent alcohol may be distilled; most is between 5 and 6 percent.
In the region around Domfront, near the southern edge of the zone,
the cider can be made from a mix of pears (as much as 30 percent)
and apples; Calvados that includes pears is always labeled as being
from Domfront.
</P>
<P>
   The heartland is the Pays d'Auge, which lies on either side of
the little Touques River valley, running south from Deauville
through Pont-l'Eveque and Lisieux. In this area, narrowly delimited
by law, Calvados must be made in a traditional pot still. It is
always labeled ``Calvados Pays d'Auge.'' Elsewhere in the region,
more efficient columnar stills can be used. Their output, which is
usually coarser and less sophisticated, is labeled simply
``Calvados.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Why coarser? Partly because the pot still offers greater
control, and partly because the pot still's product takes better to
aging in oak casks. ``To be really good,'' Waverly Root wrote in
``The Food of France,'' ``Calvados requires aging even more than
does Cognac.'' He asserts that 15 years in wood is the minimum, and
the best producers in the Pays d'Auge agree. But that much age
costs the consumer a fancy franc _ up to $60 a bottle retail in
France and considerably more in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   You can see the whole process here at St.-Cyr, in the rich,
deeply rural triangle of farmland between Lisieux, Orbec and
Vimoutiers.
</P>
<P>
   This is the headquarters of the uncrowned king of artisanal
Calvados, the firm of Roger Groult, one of the few old-style
distillers, along with Adrien Camut of La Lande St.-Leger, who
produce enough to ship their wares around the world. (Most local
people pronounce the name ``grew,'' but Jean-Pierre Groult,
himself, says ``grewlt,'' with the final consonants faintly
audible.)
</P>
<P>
   A dapper, precise fourth-generation distiller, Jean-Pierre
Groult uses apples from his own orchards, which cover 65 acres,
plus others, about a third of the total, bought from other orchards
within six miles of here. They are shaken from the trees each
October by a cable linked to a tractor, sorted according to quality
and variety and then crushed in a large hydraulic press. The pulp
is used to feed livestock, and the liquid is pumped into
stainless-steel tanks, where it ferments into cider.
</P>
<P>
   When the moment comes, months later, to make the final product,
the cider passes twice through one of Groult's three alembics, or
stills, one of which belonged to his great-grandfather. These
handsome, glistening, hammered-copper vessels, heated by wood
fires, produce an alcoholic vapor that passes through a swan's-neck
tube and eventually through a coil of tubing immersed in a bath of
cold water. That condenses the vapor into a liquid.
</P>
<P>
   The first pass yields what distillers call petites eaux, or
little waters, which are 28 to 30 percent alcohol. The second
yields a rudimentary brandy, 70 to 72 percent alcohol. At the end
of each run, the harsher first and last parts of the output, called
the head and tail, are discarded.
</P>
<P>
   After aging in sheds filled with barrels large and small, and
the gradual addition of distilled water, the Calvados loses its
astringency and gains body and perfume. It has 40 to 45 percent
alcohol when it is bottled. Like all spirits and unlike wine, it
makes no further improvement while in glass.
</P>
<P>
   Groult sells only blends of various vintages, although other
distillers sell single-vintage Calvados. He thinks that they are
one-dimensional, that only by blending the produce of a number of
years can maximum richness and complexity be achieved. His own
Calvados is available in 3-, 8-, 15-, 20-, 30-, 40- and 50-year-old
bottlings, with the stated age the youngest in the blend.
</P>
<P>
   A glass of 20-year-old calva makes a refined after-dinner drink,
one in which ``there is the first happy flush of oak, a lingering
taste of fruit and no sting on the palate,'' in Groult's
enthusiastic (and accurate) words. But the Normans also use
Calvados in a surprising number of ways.
</P>
<P>
   They drink it in the middle of elaborate banquets to revive
flagging appetites, much the way fancy-pants American chefs serve
sorbets. They call this the ``trou Normand.''
</P>
<P>
   It is an essential ingredient in tripe a la mode de Caen, a
classic regional dish. It lends snap to the cream sauce in veal
cutlets or chicken Pays d'Auge. Liebling mentioned a partridge
poached in cream and Calvados in the style of Olivier Basselin, ``a
15th-century poet and drunkard,'' as the master described him.
Treated in this way, Liebling swore, the bird tastes ``like a
partridge that has been fed all its life from a bottle of Calvados
50 years old.''
</P>
<P>
   But on my most recent trip around Normandy with my wife, Betsey,
the gold star went to a towering Calvados souffle at La Bourride,
the Michelin two-star restaurant in Caen. When the waiter served
it, he lifted its top, decorated with an apple slice, and poured in
a little more Calvados, to make sure the flavor wasn't too wan.
</P>
<P>
   I barely finished the souffle, but the patron's redheaded wife,
with typical Norman solicitude, insisted on pouring me one final
glass of Calvados, a 13-year-old, 45-percent beauty from a farmer
she knew named Hubert. Its heady scent leaped from the glass to
meet my nose, and it was every bit as full-bodied as any Wagnerian
soprano. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. RECIPE FOLLOWS IN 3rd TAKE)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
