<SLUG> BC-INFERNO-THEATER-$ADV20-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTO DANTE'S PHANTASMAGORICAL VISION OF HELL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release on Sunday, Sept. 20.)  
 (HLW)  
 Celia Wren is an associate editor at American Theater magazine  
 By CELIA WREN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Abandon all hope, you who enter here.'' This motto,
inscribed on Hell's front door in Dante Alighieri's ``Divine
Comedy,'' might also serve as a warning to ambitious thespians
transferring the 14th-century masterpiece to the stage.
</P>
<P>
   A literary work whose mythic vision has made it a cultural
touchstone, the poem seems to defy theatrical interpretation. Its
three parts describe a tour through dizzying cosmic landscapes _
Hell, Purgatory and Heaven _ teeming with supernatural beings.
</P>
<P>
   The first section, the ``Inferno,'' is particularly fantastical.
Here the narrator (Dante) witnesses the ghastly punishments
tormenting damned souls, each of whom is assigned to one of Hell's
increasingly grim concentric circles according to the grievousness
of his or her sin. A rain of fire, a lake of boiling pitch,
centaurs, trees that bleed, a scorpion-tailed monster that swims
through the air: add to these visions scores of obscure allusions
to medieval villains and a dogmatic theology that by today's
standards seems downright brutal, and the assignment starts to
sound like a producer's nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the award-winning version of the ``Inferno,''
translated from the Italian by Robert Pinsky, the U.S. poet
laureate, has found its way to the footlights. Directed by Robert
Scanlan and produced by the Unterberg Poetry Center of the 92nd
Street Y, the play, following a brief run in Boston, begins
performances in New York on Saturday at Playhouse 91 and runs
through Oct. 4.
</P>
<P>
   The production has been in the making since shortly after
Pinsky's ``Inferno'' was published, in 1994. Critics hailed the
translation for its eloquent contemporary language and its use of
slant rhyme (tell/feel or night/thought) to reflect Dante's terza
rima rhyme scheme. The warning quoted above is Pinsky's version of
this famous line.
</P>
<P>
   The stage ``Inferno'' features four actors (including Bill Camp
as Dante) in modern dress, a classical violinist, original music by
two composers and a script adapted by Pinsky from his book-length
text. The project is the work of collaborators who fervently
believe that poetry can transcend the printed page and exhilarate a
live audience. Indeed, as Poet Laureate, Pinsky is developing an
audio-video archive of 1,000 Americans reading their favorite poems
aloud.
</P>
<P>
   ``Poetry by its nature is vocal,'' he said. ``Poets, in my
opinion, don't write for the page; they don't even write on the
page. Even if you're writing the words down, you're writing with
your voice.'' But he cautioned that ``vocal does not necessarily
mean dramatic; I write _ and I wrote that translation _ for the
reader's voice.'' As he waits for the theatrical ``Inferno,'' which
will rely on actors' voices, Pinsky said he was ``semi-wary.''
</P>
<P>
   The passage of the ``Inferno'' from page to stage began in the
fall of 1995, when Pinsky collaborated in a dramatic reading in
Cambridge, Mass. A prime force behind the project, even at that
stage, was Scanlan, an eminent director and president of the Poets'
Theater, which sponsored the reading. Old acquaintances, Pinsky and
Scanlan had both been deeply impressed by the theories of Francis
Fergusson, a literary critic who found in Dante's work ``the
perennial idea of a theater of human life and action.''
</P>
<P>
   Pinsky pieced together two acts of excerpts for the reading,
held in a Harvard University auditorium. He himself played Dante.
Derek Walcott, the Nobel Laureate, took the role of Virgil, the
Roman poet who guides Dante through Hell, while the actors Wallace
Shawn and Kathryn Walker portrayed assorted sinners.
</P>
<P>
   Positive reaction to that performance, Pinsky said, persuaded
him to attempt a more polished script, which he handed over to
Scanlan, with carte blanche to produce it.
</P>
<P>
   Scanlan, a renowned interpreter of Samuel Beckett, has long had
an intense interest in marrying poetry and theater, two disciplines
he views as, regrettably, ``mutually suspicious.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The poetry-reading circuit,'' he said, ``strikes a lot of
theater professionals as hopeless performance. And the poets are
usually horrified by the cheap histrionics of actors reading in
their stead.''
</P>
<P>
   That situation, he believes, requires correcting. ``We need
higher distinction, better language in the theater,'' he said.
``It's one of the great failings of the American theater, the world
theater even.''
</P>
<P>
   Scanlan elaborated: ``We all universally acknowledge that
Shakespeare is the greatest person in the theater and the greatest
poet. A perfect union should be a point of aim, and it seems no
longer to be. People don't even aspire to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Scanlan found a kindred soul in Jonathan Levi, a founding editor
of the literary magazine Granta, who has also worked in opera. Levi
is director of the National Literary Audience Development Project,
an initiative begun in 1997 by the Unterberg Poetry Center ``to
bring theatrical audiences to poetry and bring poetry audiences to
theater,'' in Levi's words. Supporting this mission is the
60-year-old tradition of the poetry center, which arranged for
Dylan Thomas to lead the first public reading of ``Under Milk
Wood'' in 1953. But the ``Inferno'' will be the center's first
fully staged theatrical production.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   To Scanlan, Levi and their colleagues, Pinsky's text presented
the ideal match between the poetic and the dramatic, the old and
the new. And Pinsky's distinction as Poet Laureate, along with the
attention the book received, have given the project a jazzy edge.
</P>
<P>
   Still, staging Dante's chapterlike cantos remains a tricky
proposition. In addition to representational difficulties, there is
the problem of the work's vast scope. ``The question is the sheer
range, the number of characters,'' said Giuseppe Mazzotta, a
professor of Italian at Yale University. The ``Inferno,'' he said,
includes enough material for dozens of plays; he pointed out that
just a few lines inspired Gabriele D'Annunzio's play ``Francesca da
Rimini.''
</P>
<P>
   An added difficulty for the stage is rhythm. ``In epic poetry,''
Scanlan noted, ``there's a sense that it's one damn thing after
another _ which applies more literally in this case than in any
other.'' One of his tasks has therefore been to insure that the
play has movement without being ``repetitiously episodic.'' At the
same time, the production needs to mirror the book's descriptive
power and its multiple meanings: Hell's lurid panorama, the
interplay of adventure, allegory and irony, and the tension between
Dante's initial pity for the damned and his ultimate affirmation of
divine justice.
</P>
<P>
   Scanlan has chosen to express these literary resonances largely
through music: a two-tiered acoustic ``soundscape'' of electronic
sampling and live classical violin. The electronic score, composed
by Christopher Walker, suggests the horrors of Hell by distorting
sounds, many of them abrasive or ominous. For example, a spooky
montage of pig squeals and resounding slamming noises accompanies a
gruesome scene of dismemberment.
</P>
<P>
   Tracing the perceptions and emotions of Dante against this sonic
backdrop is the violin (an instrument with a ``long history of Hell
associations,'' Levi noted) playing music by Bruce Saylor, a
composer of opera, orchestral, chamber and vocal works.
</P>
<P>
   After receiving from Scanlan a ``musical blueprint'' outlining
what parts of the script the score should illustrate, Saylor wrote
a multi-section composition to be performed by the violinist Gil
Morgenstern. The violin line, Scanlan said, is ``present
theatrically like a voice or a character.'' Accordingly,
Morgenstern will be onstage throughout the performance. In
rehearsals, Scanlan said, the actors took a musical approach in the
``balancing of their own voices, the sounding of the words and
finding the cadences, finding the verse, finding all of the
internal assonances.''
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, script and music coalesce, Scanlan suggested. ``You
can't handle the text the way text or dialogue is usually
handled,'' he said. ``You really have to handle it musically all
the way through.''
</P>
<P>
   But the look of the production is equally important, he said.
Camp, in the role of Dante, and Reg E. Cathey, playing Virgil, roam
over and in front of a two-story metal scaffold whose arms pivot.
Giving voice to the damned, Jack Willis and Leslie Beatty haunt the
compartments created by railings, platforms, inset gray doors and
strips of mirror that turn translucent.
</P>
<P>
   At the set's center, a screen catches projections of
expressionistic monotypes by Michael Mazur, who illustrated the
``Inferno'' hard cover. Despite the stark decor, the performance
includes playful sections, like a scene with puppets and colorful
monster masks (created by the designers Sarah G. Conly and John
Michael Deegan) and one that imitates a poetry slam.
</P>
<P>
   After the New York run the production will visit Montgomery,
Ala., Miami, Seattle, Kansas City and Los Angeles. ``The idea is
not to go to traditional theatrical venues,'' Levi said of the
tour. At each stop the local sponsors will emphasize the poem's
relevance today. In Montgomery, the play will be performed at the
King Memorial Baptist Church, where the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King
Jr. first gained prominence. The setting will cast light, Levi
said, on the ``Inferno'' ``as metaphor for civil rights.'' In
Kansas City, a consortium that includes the Jewish Federation of
Greater Kansas City will be the host of a discussion about the
text's relevance to the Holocaust and race relations. And in
Seattle, a literary community center, Richard Hugo House, will hold
a writing class in which adolescents, some recently homeless, will
rewrite Dante's cantos in their own words.
</P>
<P>
   Frances McCue, executive director of Hugo House, said that the
project involved ``looking around the city and seeing what sounds
there are around us that create our own little urban hell.'' The
young writers will read their work at the theater where the Pinsky
play will be performed.
</P>
<P>
   Just how much Hell can one city take? A lot, according to Ms.
McCue. ``There's sort of an `Inferno' buzz around Seattle right
now,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
