<P>
   FBC-STODA-COLUMN _ GAINESVILLE, Fla. _ These are difficult
football times at the University of Florida. Ignore, please, the
No. 2 national ranking, because that's pretty much what head coach
Stever Spurrier is doing...and asking everybody else to do, too.
The Gators are 2-0, which isn't the problem. Well, kind of it is.
The victories have come against The Citadel and Northeast
Louisiana, which means they count only in a mathematical sense. The
Bulldogs and Indians, quite frankly, couldn't beat the Gators if
they ganged up and played 'em together. Also, it seems the Florida
offense _ having scored a mere 91 points _ is anemic. Which is why
it would be no surprise whatsoever to see Spurrier, come Saturday
night on the road in Neyland Stadium against sixth-ranked
Tennessee's nasties in the first Southeastern Conference game of
the season, fire up the engine on quarterback Doug Johnson and
throw him out there against the Volunteers. Because things get
serious now. Perhaps too serious, in Spurrier's opinion, for any
one quarterback. (Stoda, Palm Beach Post) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   FBC-LONGHORNS-APPLE _ This week Major Applewhite is designated
sacrificial lamb. The fill-in starting quarterback will lead the
Texas Longhorns on the road against the team that's the best in the
country in scoring offense and scoring defense, fifth-ranked Kansas
State. (Wangrin, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FBC-BUCKEYES _ COLUMBUS, Ohio _ Missouri, No. 21 in the
Associated Press poll, comes to Columbus to face an Ohio State team
that, at least outwardly, doesn't seem all that smitten with its
opening victories against West Virginia (34-17) and Toledo (49-0).
Don't get them wrong: They're pleased they won, but hey, that's
what they expect. (Vinella, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FBC-GATECH _ ATLANTA _ One of several bright spots in Tech's
victory over New Mexico State was the play of linebacker Delaunta
Cameron, who had several key plays and returned a fumble for a
touchdown. (Rogers, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   FBC-LEWIS _ KNOXVILLE, Tenn. _ A year ago Tennessee could not
slow down the Florida rush on quarterback Peyton Manning. But a
year ago the Vols did not play running back Jamal Lewis. Lewis, a
true freshman, was not ready to block the various blitzing schemes
of Florida. Lewis started the next week against Ole Miss and ran
for 133 yards. Then the following week against Georgia he had 232.
If Tennessee is going to beat Florida, it will be because of Lewis.
(Barnhart, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   GLF-SOLHEIM _ To the ardent golf fan, the Solheim Cup is slowly
becoming one of the sport's premier events. But most casual
golfers' response to the Solheim is ``So what?'' The Solheim has
failed to capture the public's interest after four competitions
because, well, there hasn't been much competition. The United
States has thoroughly beaten Europe three of four times, and the
one time Europe won also was in ho-hum fashion. (Dolch, Palm Beach
Post) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   GLF-FEATURE _ Weekly golf feature. (Sheeley, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   GLF-NOTES _ Golf notes. (Sheeley, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   HKN-PANTHERS-MCLEAN _ SUNRISE, Fla. _ The Florida Panthers'
franchise-record losing streak was at 12 and counting when General
Manager Bryan Murray made a seemingly minor deal to acquire
goaltender Kirk McLean last March 20. ``At the time, I seriously
wondered if we would win another game,'' Murray said earlier this
summer. Three nights later, the slide ended at 13 games as McLean,
making his first start as a Panther, backstopped a 5-4 victory over
Montreal. McLean went on to go a respectable 4-2-1 in seven
appearances. So how did Murray reward him? He spent the whole
summer conducting a goalie search that ended with the free-agent
signing of Sean Burke last Saturday. Now McLean is hearing rumors
that he might be on the trading block yet again if Kevin Weekes
ends his holdout in time to make an impression in training camp.
``At this stage of the season, nothing is etched in stone,'' he
said. ``I'll be a free agent next year, and if they want to do
something, that's a business decision. All I can do is go out and
play hockey.'' (Biggane, Palm Beach Post) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   HKN-PANNOTE _ Sunrise, Fla. _ Panthers notebook. (Otterson, Palm
Beach Post) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   HKN-PANTHERS-NIEDER _ SUNRISE, Fla. _ Everywhere Rob Niedermayer
goes nowadays, people have the same question: How's the head?
First-year Florida coach Terry Murray had no such worries after
watching Niedermayer score a goal in the Panthers' first
training-camp scrimmage at National Car Rental Center. (Biggane,
Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
