<HEADER>
A6413 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-BITS&AMP;BYTES-NYT &LR;      09-15 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-BITS&AMP;BYTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE VIRTUAL KITCHEN WITH CORPORATE GIANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By S.A. BELZER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Only those of a certain age will remember the Velveeta-smooth
voice of Ed Herlihy reciting recipes between the acts of the
``Kraft Television Theater.'' They always seemed to be for ``simple
Lenten dishes'' in which cream cheese figured prominently.
</P>
<P>
   Forgotten (by many) but not gone, Kraft recipes live on in the
Kraft Interactive Kitchen (www.kraftfoods.com), one of a number of
Web sites run by large food manufacturers. (And in North America,
Kraft Foods, a unit of Philip Morris, is the largest of them all.)
</P>
<P>
   These sites are eager to help the hurried cook with weekly menu
planners, recipe searches and electronic recipe boxes to keep
favorites in. Of course, the recipes are built around the
manufacturer's products _ chemical shelf-life extenders and all.
</P>
<P>
   And some of these sites ask the user to register, which builds
customer marketing lists: even on the Net, lunch isn't exactly
free.
</P>
<P>
   For what Kraft offers, click on Cookbook. There are hundreds of
recipes, variable in quality and redolent of cooking eras past.
Fettuccine Alfredo with scallops and peas, for instance, includes a
cup of heavy cream to serve four, reflecting the heavy-on-fat style
that palled by the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Veal chops balsamico is more of a 90s recipe, using herbs and
relatively unfatty veal chops, but \ cup of shredded mozzarella.
There's an assumption here, call it the cheeseburger complex, that
Americans like nothing better than cheese with their meat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can can'' chicken includes a can of condensed cream of chicken
soup and two cups of Minute Rice, ideal for an old-fashioned high
school cafeteria. And among the ingredients for the 15 minute
Mexican chicken and rice dinner are a cup of Taco Bell salsa, two
cups of Minute Rice and a cup of Kraft shredded cheddar _ a
corporate merger on a plate. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Let Betty help'' is the motto on www.bettycrocker.com. Betty
provides weekly menu planners in five categories (Kids, Healthy,
Express, Adventure and Love to Cook), with recipes for entrees,
side dishes and desserts. The Adventure category includes, for
example, grilled swordfish with papaya salsa, a tangy dish made
with fresh, low-fat, low-calorie ingredients, like lime peel, lime
juice and grapefruit juice and, in the salsa, onion, red bell
pepper and cilantro.
</P>
<P>
   There is also ``easy roasted peppers and feta cheese pie,''
which lists among the ingredients } cup Bisquick baking mix. Two
nonpreservative substitutes for Bisquick can be found on
www.switcheroo.com. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Land O'Lakes (www.landolakes.com) keeps a lot of appealing
recipes in its Recipe of the Month Archives. The most appealing
call only for butter from the sponsor's product roster. Watch out
for recipes with frozen vegetables. Starburst casserole, with white
bread, chicken or turkey, and American cheese is one of the low
points. Acorn squash with savory pork, uniting the flavors of pork
tenderloin and orange, is one of the highs. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At www.lipton.com, click on Lipton Kitchens for ``recipe
secrets.'' The secrets usually involve envelopes of Lipton soup
mix: vegetable soup in a tortellini and vegetable salad,
onion-mushroom soup for ``quick 'n easy tetrazzini.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Is it all a wasteland, like television of old? For an oasis, try
www.treatsrecipes.com/home.asp, the Kellogg's Rice Krispies site.
The treats, squares of Rice Krispies baked with chocolate, banana
nut, butterscotch and other sweets, are fun. (Butter can, of
course, be used instead of the margarine called for.)
</P>
<P>
   The recipes for entrees are more sophisticated than those on the
Kraft site: for instance, salmon patties with mustard sauce, and
crab and shrimp appetizer balls. For the Rice Krispies in them,
bread crumbs will do very well instead, with only a loss of
sweetness. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the desert fairly bursts into bloom on
www.tabasco.com/html/tasterecipes.html, the site of Tabasco, the
fiery brand of hot pepper sauce that started in south Louisiana.
The site offers hundreds of spicy recipes made from fresh
ingredients, but its foot-stomping glory is the Cajun-Creole
section, with authentic versions of bayou staples like shrimp and
sausage jambalaya, crawfish pie and seafood gumbo. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Wright Ford's Web site (www.littleyellowhouse.com) is
devoted to food for thought and thought for food. Her passion is
cookbooks, which she reviews energetically. ``By the time I am
ready to write a review, the book usually has splatters and
scribbled notes on it,'' she said by e-mail. ``I test at least six
recipes from each one. If more than two recipes I try from a book
are bombs, I don't review it.''
</P>
<P>
   She has a warm spot for less-known cookbooks and has most often
bought or borrowed her copies. Her reviews have a personal, quirky
flavor and include excerpts and lists of the recipes she tried and
liked.
</P>
<P>
   Among the two dozen books reviewed on her site are ``Vegetarian
Cooking for Everyone'' by Deborah Madison, ``Desperation Dinners!''
by Beverly Mills and Alicia Ross, ``The Cook's Bible: The Best of
American Home Cooking'' by Christopher Kimball and ``Nicole
Routhier's Fruit Cookbook.''
</P>
<P>
   All may be bought from Amazon.com, which she doesn't hesitate to
say pays her about 5 percent of each sale, but she writes that she
hopes buyers will try their local independent bookstores first.
</P>
</TEXT>
