<SLUG> BC-MANHATTAN-CHERRY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAMING THE MANHATTAN CHERRY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating to append photo note)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By MARK BITTMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The maraschino cherry is a necessary evil in the
world of cocktails. No one may actually want to eat it, but what is
a manhattan without one?
</P>
<P>
   Peter Hoffman, the owner of Savoy restaurant in SoHo, decided to
find out. He served manhattans without cherries. Then he tried
reconstituted dried cherries. Finally, he created a cherry that
might be the best part of the drink.
</P>
<P>
   When sour cherries came on the market this summer, Hoffman began
preserving them, using traditional techniques. ``We make a simple
sugar syrup with pomegranate molasses and add lemon juice,
allspice, black pepper and a few other spices,'' he said. ``We
poach the cherries in the syrup, cool them and pack them into
jars.'' The result is a delicious natural cherry with a wonderful
balance of sweet and sour.
</P>
<P>
   Having conquered the cherry, Hoffman tackled the onion, pickling
tiny fresh pearl onions in vinegar, salt, mustard seed, chili, bay
leaf and cloves. These sour morsels go into his martinis
(technically Gibsons, as martinis have olives).
</P>
<P>
   On request, Savoy makes martinis with Junipero gin, an
ultra-fragrant gin that smacks of juniper berries. It is made by
the Anchor Distilling Co.
</P>
<P>
   Savoy is at 70 Prince Street, at Crosby Street; (212) 219-8570.
The manhattan and the martini are $9.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-98 1713EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980915.0217 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 17:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6428 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINE-TOP10-NYT &LR;      09-15 0181
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TOP10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARDONNAYS ANYONE CAN LOVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (sidebar with WINE-TALK)  
 (bl)  
 By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a highly personal list of chardonnays, all delightful to
drink, that should illustrate how universal the grape is. The wines
are listed by price, but the $30 bottle is not necessarily twice as
good as the $15, nor is the Australian wine six times better than
the St.-Veran.
</P>
<P>
   Georges Duboeuf St.-Veran 1997 (Southern Burgundy). About $8.50.
</P>
<P>
   Fetzer Vineyards Mendocino Barrel Select 1996 (California).
About $11.
</P>
<P>
   Edna Valley Vineyards 1996, San Luis Obispo (California). About
$15.
</P>
<P>
   Louis Jadot St.-Aubin Blanc 1995 (Burgundy). About $19.
</P>
<P>
   Mulderbosch 1996 Stellenbosch (South Africa). About $23.
</P>
<P>
   Cloudy Bay 1995, Marlborough (New Zealand). About $25.
</P>
<P>
   Faiveley Mercurey Clos Rochette 1995 (Burgundy). About $30.
</P>
<P>
   Antinori Cervaro Della Sala 1996, Umbria (Italy). About $30.
</P>
<P>
   E.&AMP;J. Gallo Northern California Estate 1995. About $30.
</P>
<P>
   Penfolds Yatterna 1995 (South Australia). About $50.
</P>
</TEXT>
