<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINE TALK: YES, THERE IS LIFE AFTER CHARDONNAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (also see sidebar, WINE-TOP10) 
 (bl)  
 By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are tennis fans who so love the U.S. Open that they devote
two full weeks each year to watching it. Not in the comfort of
their homes but in the stands in New York, day after day, broiling
like lamb chops in the pitiless sun. I don't envy them,but I don't
hate them for it. Nor do I harbor the slightest antipathy toward
bungee jumpers, crossword puzzle addicts or people who enjoy
Tex-Mex food. I don't care for any of those things, but I wish
those who do only the best.
</P>
<P>
   So the September issue of Wine Spectator magazine came as a
shock. In a column titled ``Hot Air and Chardonnay Don't Mix,''
James Laube, a senior editor, goes after ``wine snoots who gloat
that they're part of the `ABC' crowd _ the Anything but Cabernet
(or Chardonnay) roosters.''
</P>
<P>
   The ABC faction is a recent development among wine drinkers,
prompted, I thought, by the proliferation of mediocre chardonnay.
Laube includes cabernet sauvignon. So far as I know, it's a
loose-knit group, probably fanatics dedicated to the cause of
sauvignon blanc. But Laube knows the ringleaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chief among these loathsome ABCers are wine writers, some of
whom write for major publications and otherwise prominent
metropolitan newspapers,'' he asserts.
</P>
<P>
   Now that hurts. Of course, he may have been thinking of someone
at the Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung or Corriere della Sera, but I
doubt it. Laube continues: ``I don't care if they'' _ meaning the
loathsome ABCers _ ``don't like cabernet or chardonnay; just don't
disparage those who do.''
</P>
<P>
   Who's disparaging? A plug for some nice little riesling isn't
meant to insult some hapless chardonnay lover, however misguided he
or she may be. There are probably 700 California chardonnays on the
market; only a few truly bad, but far too many dull and
forgettable. At the same time, chardonnay is an almost overwhelming
presence in the wine world _ the winemaker and wit Randall Grahm
once observed that we live in a chardocentric society.
</P>
<P>
   Is it so wrong, then, to let it be known that there is life
after chardonnay, that there are other roads to take? In a mildly
confessional mood, Laube recalls _ with a shudder _ slogging
through a tasting of some 200 merlots. ``Right now, the mere
mention of merlot makes me cringe,'' he writes. But, he adds, ``you
won't catch me at a restaurant, wine bar or party trashing merlot
drinkers.'' Perhaps not, but I certainly hope he trashes a few of
those boring merlots.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with the ABC phenomenon is not that its adherents
disparage other wine drinkers; it is that, like most movements,
it's simplistic. There are excellent California chardonnays. As
recently as July, Wine Spectator, under Laube's direction, surveyed
some 420 California chardonnays from the 1995 and 1996 vintages and
rated about 120 of them ``outstanding.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the most ardent ABCer would have difficulty turning down a
glass of some of the top-rated wines from Beringer, Kistler, Villa
Mount Eden, Williams Selyem and Gallo.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are all those dull, overoaked, oversweet
chardonnays that deserve to be criticized. Some of these wines are
extremely popular. Newcomers to wine _ and more than a few old
hands _ love them because they are fizzy, colorful and sweet _ in
other words, very unwinelike.
</P>
<P>
   Should these wines be criticized when they are so popular? Yes.
The critic's job is to point to the best. A music critic bored by
an evening of Johann Strauss will offend people who like Strauss.
They may even feel that he is patronizing them. Is he? No, he's
just tired of Strauss.
</P>
<P>
   Laube confines his polemic to California wines, but of course,
chardonnay is not confined to our shores. Most of the world's best
white table wines are made from chardonnay grapes, and more than a
few come from France, Italy and Australia.
</P>
<P>
   The entire discussion of good and bad chardonnay illustrates a
serious flaw in our practice of identifying wines by the grape
they're made from. We ask for ``a glass of chardonnay,'' unaware
that the styles of chardonnay range from the soft, slightly sweet
stuff found in three- and five-liter bag-in-the-box containers to
Le Montrachet of the Domaine de la Romanee-Conti, which sells for
about $1,000 a bottle.
</P>
<P>
   A cheap chardonnay from the Languedoc can't be compared to a
great chardonnay from Burgundy or the Napa Valley, and yet they are
compared or, more precisely, lumped together.
</P>
<P>
   More and more, American winemakers are retreating from their
once almost total use of varietal names. Now, the label from a top
California chardonnay will name the viticultural region from which
the grapes came (Sonoma Coast, for example), the specific vineyard
and sometimes the block of vines within that vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   The French have altered their thinking to allow varietal names
on inexpensive wines, but thay retain geographical names for almost
everything else _ except in Alsace, where the varietal tradition is
an old one.
</P>
<P>
   As for the ABCers, like all dissidents they serve a purpose:
they stir up controversy. And with wine, as with so many other
things, there is nothing wrong with that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-98 1716EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
