<SLUG> BC-WOMEN'S-RIGHTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK CELEBRATES RIGHTS MOVEMENT BY HONORING FAMOUS WOMEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL LOPEZ  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Imagine the boldness of Julia Blanche Stover
Clum, a diminutive woman who lived in the tiny village of Valley
Falls in the late 1800s.
</P>
<P>
   Clum and her husband sheltered Susan B. Anthony, the famous
suffragist who was passing through town, when another family would
not. She once upset an officious ribbon-cutting by riding her horse
over a new bridge so that she could be the first to cross it. In a
vintage group photograph, in the middle of somber women clothed in
black, Clum posed with her chin in her hands, a slight grin on her
face. Spirited and strong-willed, Clum clearly embraced life, her
granddaughter, Julia Hoag, said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Hoag tells these stories with a good deal of relish and,
significantly, her 11-year-old grandson recently raised his hand
and offered Clum's tale when the social studies teacher asked for
examples of famous people.
</P>
<P>
   This passing down of the contributions of women, some of whom do
not have the household names of Susan B. Anthony or Elizabeth Cady
Stanton, is precisely the point of a New York celebration marking
the 150th anniversary of the first Women's Rights Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of relay runners will traverse a 500-mile course this
week from Buffalo to New York City's Battery Park, passing a torch
along the route to mark the women's rights sesquicentennial.
</P>
<P>
   Why a run?
</P>
<P>
   ``Women have been running and charging for the last 150 years,
to be heard and seen and have parity among men,'' said Barbara
Drago, a volunteer co-chairwoman of ``Women Run New York,''
sponsored by a governor's commission established especially for the
sesquicentennial.
</P>
<P>
   Besides a weeklong celebration, with church choirs, children's
speeches and a traveling mural for runners to sign, communities in
each county will permanently note the contributions of women with
metal markers of purple and gold, the colors of the suffragists.
</P>
<P>
   Among the nearly 50 women nominated by county historians are
Agnes DeMille, the great modern dance choreographer from Sullivan
County, and the artist Georgia O'Keeffe, who painted for a time in
Warren County.
</P>
<P>
   Westchester County is honoring C.J. Walker, the nation's first
black millionairess and a great philanthropist. Herkimer County has
Mary Myers, or ``Carlotta the Lady Aeronaut,'' known for her
balloon voyages. Schuyler County claims Queen Catharine, a Seneca
chief and matriarch in the Iroquois Grand Council.
</P>
<P>
   The accomplishments of each put them well ahead of their time.
The driven personalities behind those good works also make their
lives far more fascinating than those honorary markers could ever
explain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-98 1721EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
