help make the argument that President Clinton isn't above the law.
Gorman
</P>
<P>
   -- OXLEY-ANTI-BRIBERY. (Re-sent.) Emphasizing the importance of
leveling the international playing field for American businesses,
Rep. Mike Oxley, R-Findlay, chaired a subcommittee hearing last
week devoted to the International Anti-Bribery and Fair Competition
Act of 1998, which was introduced by Oxley in July. The bill is
intended to bring the United States into compliance with the
Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development Convention,
which sets an international agenda for eradicating the bribery of
foreign officials in order for companies to win contracts in the
international marketplace. Hurt
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS -- HUD. Millions of dollars in federal funds will flow
into the Rio Grande Valley next year to fund public works projects,
the Department of Housing and Urban Development announced this
week. Marlin
</P>
<P>
