<HEADER>
A6485 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-NOTES-NYT &LR;      09-15 0582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK FOOD NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pots, Pans and Food From Alain Ducasse
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ An impulse purchase at Bergdorf Goodman? It can often
be slipped into a shopping bag. But last Wednesday, James V.
Ruocco, a writer who was browsing on the seventh floor of the
store, fell for something considerably more imposing _ a massive
12-quart copper saucepan.
</P>
<P>
   The saucepan was part of a new line of cookware, tableware and
food products bearing the imprimatur of Alain Ducasse, the
multistarred French chef. It has just been introduced into this
country and is available only at Bergdorf.
</P>
<P>
   At $275, the epic saucepan (fill it with stew, and you'd need a
forklift to take it off the stove) was reasonably priced, as were
the other magnificently heavy, beautifully finished copper pots and
pans; they start at $95 for a small saucepan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought they had made a mistake on the price,'' Ruocco said
of his purchase.
</P>
<P>
   He might have spent his $275 on just one pair of silver-plated
Alain Ducasse lobster shears or his copper and stainless-steel
Japanese grater. Had he really wanted to splurge, there is a set of
six lethal steak knives for $695, or a huge granite mortar, which
would do nicely as a birdbath, for $1,875. Then again, he could
also have decided to outfit his kitchen with a genuine Ducasse
stove for $28,000 _ perhaps too gorgeous to cook on.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducasse food products include carnaroli rice for risotto
($15 for about a pound), and excellent minced dried tomatoes in
olive oil, and herbaceous pistou with a sharp, salty bite (each $12
for about 6 ounces). Ligurian extra virgin olive oil is $25 for
about 17 ounces. The tableware includes attractive glazed wicker
chargers for $35 each.
</P>
<P>
   Kosher Foie Gras From Israel
</P>
<P>
   It's not chopped liver. But the L'Oie Royale goose foie gras
from Israel could certainly get a Rosh ha-Shanah dinner off to a
sumptuous start. This is not a mousse or pate, but solid foie gras
that is also kosher. The best way to serve it is to chill it in its
glass jar and to then slice it with a sharp knife dipped in hot
water and serve it, not with brioche, but with the next best thing:
slices of toasted hallah. A six-ounce jar is $25.99 at Fairway,
2127 Broadway (74th Street) and 2328 12th Avenue (132nd Street).
</P>
<P>
   Parisian Bread in New York
</P>
<P>
   Lionel Poilane has bided his time in bringing his famous
Parisian bread to New York. Nearly 20 years ago he explored the
possibility of opening a bakery here. Nothing came of it. Since
then, the quality of the bread available in the city and elsewhere,
from many new bakeries, has improved at least 1,000 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But starting Thursday, his big, round, crusty four-pound
sourdough miches, his earthy currant loaves and his golden butter
cookies will be flown in once a week by Marc Strausman and sold at
his store, Campagna Home, 29 E. 21st St. The miche is $9.95 for a
quarter loaf, the currant bread is $12 a pound, and the cookies are
$21 a pound. They arrive on Thursdays and must be reserved in
advance: (212) 420-1600.
</P>
<P>
   A Balducci's on Long Island
</P>
<P>
   Balducci's has established a toehold on Long Island. A selection
of its products, including fresh pastas, sauces, cured meats,
olives, cheeses, olive oils and vinegars, are available in a new
Balducci's Boutique at Sutton Place Gourmet, Jericho Turnpike (near
Woodbury Road), Woodbury, N.Y. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
