<HEADER>
A6495 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-15 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENOUGH ALREADY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c. 1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Who could quarrel with the call from Senate
Minority Leader Tom Daschle and House Minority Leader Dick
Gephardt, the principal congressional Democratic spokesmen, for
political ``common sense'' in deciding President Clinton's fate?
</P>
<P>
   Wise counsel. But the president, Congress and the American
people will all be required to apply such fair-minded sobriety, and
that may take a miracle. We're not there yet.
</P>
<P>
   This sorry saga will never end until the president resigns, is
censured by both chambers or is impeached. The latter is absurdly
disproportionate to the sin, but not inconceivable. That
possibility makes one of the two other courses absolutely
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Common sense will have little to do with determining the
outcome. Politics will have everything to do with it.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott gave the game away Tuesday
when he said that impeachment would not even require Clinton to
have violated a law _ ``abuse of the public trust,'' however that
might be defined, would be sufficient. The Republicans have the
president on the ropes and they do not mean to let him up, even if
it results in the presidency of a presumably more popular Albert
Gore Jr.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, it is not clear what Daschle and Gephardt meant to
achieve, beyond venting their irritation at the president's
legalistic nit-picking to avoid admitting perjury.
</P>
<P>
   Both Democratic leaders have been ambiguous about how the
president should be punished for trying to cover up his reckless,
illicit affair with Monica Lewinsky. They want to resolve this as
rapidly as possible to avoid bringing down Democratic candidates in
November.
</P>
<P>
   But they don't have any magic formula for resolving the crisis,
short of sending Clinton to the political guillotine, which they
are not yet prepared to do.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the congressional process expected to lead to
impeachment hearings is already taking on an inexorable life of its
own, unstoppable and uncontrollable. And even in this preliminary
stage the GOP-controlled House Judiciary Committee is sharply
divided along party lines, quibbling about procedural questions
involving timetables, subpoena powers, document releases and the
like.
</P>
<P>
   That particular committee has a long history of partisan
brawling and there is little hope of a sudden bipartisan approach
now. Members have been known to shout each other down and yell
``shut up'' when challenged. One GOP member, Georgia's Bob Barr,
called for Clinton's impeachment last year long before the world
ever heard of Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional comment, cloaked in supposedly neutral language,
also reflects predictable partisan bias. Republicans tend to find
their constituents eager to have the president impeached, Democrats
to feel that constituents are reluctant to kick him out.
</P>
<P>
   Republican pollsters point to an ominous decline in the
president's credibility and character ratings; Democratic pollsters
point to his continued high job approval ratings.
</P>
<P>
   The country, like the Congress, is polarized. Nobody defends
what Clinton did. But nobody likes what Independent Counsel Kenneth
Starr did either. There is no consensus about what to do next,
except that SOMETHING must be done.
</P>
<P>
   The House Judiciary Committee will complete its review of
Starr's voluminous documents by Sept. 28, shortly before Congress
is scheduled to adjourn to allow members to campaign for
re-election. The panel is expected to recommend hearings into
potential impeachment, which could extend far into next year and
include testimony from both Lewinsky and the president.
</P>
<P>
   If the House voted for impeachment, the Senate would sit in
judgment in a lengthy trial to convict or acquit the president.
This ordeal could consume the entire two years remaining in the
president's second term.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, further Starr documents will be released,
including the president's secret grand jury videotaped testimony
vividly depicting the demeaning questions and evasive answers,
keeping the scandal and the political turmoil alive. The
Republicans, naturally, want everything disclosed and the Democrats
don't.
</P>
<P>
   This is not going to quietly fade into the woodwork. Even
censure will not make it go away, so long as Clinton remains in the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   He has tried to distract us with apologies, pastoral counseling,
Starr-bashing and a display of carrying out his governing duties.
It isn't working.
</P>
<P>
   For all the talk about sin, that isn't the basic problem. We
expected him to run the country, not direct our spiritual lives.
What he has lost is us. We are sick of this.
</P>
<P>
   The only solution for Clinton, his party and the country is his
resignation at that point when the political weight of his problems
becomes too oppressive to carry on.
</P>
<P>
   That time is not quite now, but it is coming _ sometime after
the House churns up more stuff and the November elections have
determined the shape of the next Congress that could be asked to
vote on impeachment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
