<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: PRYOR TO GET 1ST TWAIN PRIZE;   FREEBIES FOR VAN
GOGH SHOW;   CENSORS REJECT SADAT SCRIPT; TRIBUTE TO BERT PARKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   To recognize those who create humor from their uniquely American
experiences, the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts in
Washington is establishing a Celebration of American Humor and a
prize named for Mark Twain. The center announced Tuesday that the
first recipient of the Kennedy Center Mark Twain Prize will be
Richard Pryor.
</P>
<P>
   Pryor will be honored in the Concert Hall on Oct. 20 in the
culmination of three days of lectures, symposiums and master
classes beginning on Oct. 18. The center said participants in the
program, expected to be an annual event, will include Chevy Chase,
Morgan Freeman, Danny Glover, Whoopi Goldberg, Damon Wayans and
Robin Williams. It is to be televised in January on the Comedy
Central cable channel.
</P>
<P>
   Anticipation
</P>
<P>
   All advance tickets for a major van Gogh exhibition beginning
next month at the National Gallery of Art in Washington have been
issued, but as many as 2,500 free tickets for same-day entry will
be issued beginning at 10 a.m. daily to people who wait in line at
the gallery's West Building.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Ziska, the gallery's spokeswoman, said that while almost
197,000 tickets for ``Van Gogh's van Goghs: Masterpieces From the
van Gogh Museum, Amsterdam'' had been issued in just two weeks by
the gallery and Ticketmaster, arrangements had been made to provide
the same-day tickets. The show, from Oct. 4 to Jan. 3, is expected
to be among the most popular exhibitions ever mounted at the
gallery.
</P>
<P>
   Naysayers
</P>
<P>
   Egyptian censors have rejected the script of a film that would
depict the 1981 assassination of President Anwar Sadat by Islamic
fundamentalists. Agence France-Presse reported Tuesday that the
security services, empowered to approve or ban all scripts dealing
with military matters, had rejected the screenplay for ``The Day
Sadat Was Killed'' without explanation.
</P>
<P>
   The film's producer and director, Mahammad Radi, said the script
was based on ``The Assassination of a President'' by an Egyptian
author, Adel Hammuda, and that Omar Sharif had been chosen to
portray the defense lawyer in the trial of the assassins. Four men
found guilty of the slaying of Sadat, who governed Egypt for 11
years, were executed in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   There He Is
</P>
<P>
   A life-size bronze statue of Bert Parks, the longtime master of
ceremonies of the Miss America Pageant, is now on display in
Atlantic City. The $35,000 creation in the courtyard of the
Sheraton Atlantic City Convention Center is equipped with motion
sensors that, when tripped by the head of a visitor, activate a
recording of Parks singing ``There She Is,'' his serenade to each
year's winner. Parks died in 1992 at 77.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
