<HEADER>
A6504 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEXADDICT-CORRECT16-C     09-15 1105
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEXADDICT-CORRECT16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ANALYSTS DISAGREE OVER CLINTON 'SEX ADDICT' DIAGNOSIS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (l) lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    Editors: In a story distributed last week, Cox News Service
erroneously identified the author of the book, ``The Clinton
Syndrome,'' as Stanley Renshon. Renshon is not the author of the
book, and the views expressed in the story were incorrectly
ascribed to him. The views were expressed in an interview by Jerome
D. Levin, who is the author of the book. A corrected version of the
story follows.
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Even before details of President Clinton's
extramarital sexual activity were made public, some mental health
professionals have concluded that the cravings that supposedly
steamed up the Oval Office are those of a ``sex addict.''
</P>
<P>
   Other psychotherapists caution that understanding the mental
underpinnings of human behavior _ or even learning exactly what
happened _ usually takes hours of one-on-one exchange between
patient and therapist.
</P>
<P>
   And the American Psychiatric Association, in its mammoth
compendium of diagnosable mental disorders, ``Diagnostic and
Statistical Manual,'' does not even recognize ``sexual addiction''
as a mental illness.
</P>
<P>
   To those therapists who believe there is such a mental disorder,
sexual addition refers to repeated, constant and compulsive sexual
activity. ``Weird'' sex does not appear to be a necessary element
in any of the definitions.
</P>
<P>
   Those who believe Clinton is slavishly addicted to sex are
finding willing outlets for their views.
</P>
<P>
   From the rumor-relaying Drudge Report on the Internet to tabloid
newspapers and respected dailies to well-known book publishers,
media outlets are providing sex experts and other therapists space
to psychoanalyze Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   They are saying he did whatever he did because:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  His mother was a gambler and a very intelligent woman.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  His stepfather was abusive.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  He never knew his biological father.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  He has developed a lifelong habit of pushing the envelope of
disapproval to the limit, then escaping punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Psychodynamics are at play: The president compartmentalizes. The
president needs approval in the face of misconduct, a sort of
I-love-you-despite-anything-you-do reassurance.
</P>
<P>
   Sexual addiction ``is the only thing that really makes sense,''
said Jerome D. Levin, director of the Alcoholism and Substance
Abuse Training Program at the New School for Social Research in New
York. ``If you look at his biography, he has all of the
predisposing factors. Genetically, there was a great deal of
addiction on both sides of his family.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Levin believes, Clinton's abusive stepfather caused
the future president to ``yearn for a father'' and to develop
problems with self-esteem.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needs continual reassurance that he's lovable and loved,''
Levin said in a telephone interview during a pause in his tour to
promote his book, ``The Clinton Syndrome: The President and the
Self-destructive Nature of Sexual Addiction'' (Prima Publishing).
</P>
<P>
   For Clinton, he said, sex becomes a way of ``avoiding very
painful feelings of shame, guilt, rage.''
</P>
<P>
   Levin acknowledged that he does not know how many times Clinton
has had sex in the past 10 or 20 years or with whom. The total
number of alleged encounters, proven, acknowledged or otherwise,
would amount to far fewer than constant, repetitive, ``sex addict''
behavior would suggest, he acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's true. The fact that someone has an affair does not make
them a sex addict,'' he said. But ``the total disregard of
consequences, the willingness to ignore (Independent Prosecutor)
Kenneth Starr and the press, are further manifestations.''
</P>
<P>
   Levin also suggested that grief over the assassination of Prime
Minister Yitzhak Rabin of Israel, who he said was a ``father
figure'' to Clinton, may have combined with other political
pressures to make the president lose control of himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``This (the sexual addiction diagnosis) is obviously not the
only way to understand what happened, but it's one way, and I think
it is a reasonable way,'' Levin said. ``I had my doubts working on
the book. There's an enormous responsibility in making a public
statement of this sort. As events unfolded, I don't lack confidence
in my diagnosis now.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lonnie Barbach, a Mill Valley, Calif., psychologist who
specializes in treating sexual problems, does not buy the ``sex
addict'' concept.
</P>
<P>
   ``An addiction is something where you are physiologically forced
to continue,'' she said. ``In terms of sexuality, I don't think
that exists.''
</P>
<P>
   She added that ``there may be things that you get out of sex to
create this feeling that you can't make it if you're not sexual,
but that's not addiction.''
</P>
<P>
   In terms of Clinton, she noted, ``we don't know what happened.
If we knew what happened, we don't know how many times it happened
or under what circumstances. We don't know what his relationship
with his wife is. We just don't have the data, and without the
data, I don't see how you can jump to any conclusions.''
</P>
<P>
   Barbach, author of ``Going the Distance: Finding and Keeping
Lifelong Love,'' said she would have to ``have a number of sessions
with a patient before I could even find out what's going on, much
less being able to understand why it's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   David Marcotte, a Fayetteville, N.C., psychiatrist and spokesman
for the American Psychiatric Association on the subject of ``sexual
addiction,'' said that even if evidence eventually shows that the
president is the victim of a compulsive or obsessive disorder with
regard to sex, that is not the same as an addiction.
</P>
<P>
   Jed Diamond, a Willits, Calif., clinical social worker, goes a
step further than labeling Clinton a sex addict. In his view, the
president is a sex addict who is experiencing male menopause.
</P>
<P>
   Diamond, author of ``Male Menopause,'' (Sourcebooks), defined
that as a time when ``hormonally and physiologically men are sort
of going through puberty in reverse.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Men who are going through these hormonal changes need to pay
attention to them, President Clinton included,'' Diamond said. He
acknowledged that he had no specific knowledge of Clinton's current
hormonal status and does not know how many sexual liaisons the
president has had in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we're speculating here,'' he said, ``but I would
say from 35 years of clinical practice, I am seeing the tip of a
familiar iceberg.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
