<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 17:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6510 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLUE-DOG-2TAKES-NYT &LR;      09-15 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLUE-DOG-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ARTIST AND A DOG THAT BECAME A CULTURAL ICON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: La., Calif.)   (bl)  
 By RICK BRAGG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ The Russians did not ask for a Blue Dog when
George Rodrigue visited the Soviet Union with President Ronald
Reagan a decade or so ago, but they thought a horse would be nice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I painted Reagan on a white horse,'' said Rodrigue, the artist
from Cajun Louisiana who, before becoming so famous for his spooky,
comical and wildly prosperous renderings of cobalt-colored dogs,
painted other things, like heads of state. ``I painted Gorbachev on
the ground, holding out his hand in friendship.''
</P>
<P>
   Soviet officials, including those who Rodrigue swears were from
the KGB, were unhappy with that.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said it looked like Gorbachev was begging,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians wanted Mikhail Gorbachev painted on a horse, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know he had a horse,'' Rodrigue told them.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't,'' one Soviet official answered.
</P>
<P>
   People can say what they like about Blue Dogs, Rodrigue's
paintings of what seems to be the same dog stuck almost like a
postage stamp on various landscapes, portraits and situations _
works that some critics, with sneers intact, dismiss as fad or not
really art at all.
</P>
<P>
   What began as a man's painting of his long-dead dog _ actually,
three different dead dogs lent inspiration for Blue Dog _ has
become a lasting sensation, with more than 1,200 Blue Dog paintings
since 1984. They hang everywhere from the White House to Whoopi
Goldberg's house, in Tom Brokaw's house and in the houses of no one
in particular. A Blue Dog hangs on the set of ``Friends'' and
stares from Neiman Marcus and Absolut vodka ads. You can't swing a
dead cat without hitting a Blue Dog.
</P>
<P>
   Famous people buy them and rich people buy them and even a few
drunk conventioneers buy them when they stagger into Rodrigue's
gallery in the French Quarter and are captivated by the little blue
dog with the round yellow eyes, but no one buys them cheaply. They
can range from a few thousand dollars to $250,000.
</P>
<P>
   The artist has earned millions and created a cultural icon. And
year after year, those who do not see what the big deal is about
ask the same thing: Why?
</P>
<P>
   Even Rodrigue, whose sometimes dark and eerie landscapes of his
native state made him a respected artist decades before Blue Dog,
is a little surprised.
</P>
<P>
   Before his Blue Dogs, he was acclaimed by Le Figaro as the
``Louisiana Rousseau.'' Italy awarded him its Gold Medal for the
arts, and he was honored by the Salon des Artistes of Paris.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm surprised by people's reactions,'' he said. It is not
unusual, he said, to have people stare at the Blue Dog paintings
and cry. ``The yellow eyes are really the soul of the dog,'' he
said. ``He has this piercing stare. People say the dog keeps
talking to them with the eyes, always saying something different.''
</P>
<P>
   The critics' claims that Rodrigue has hit on a modern-day
version of soup-can art just slide off him. If it is fashion, it is
fashion that has lasted almost 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who have seen a Blue Dog painting always remember it,''
he said. ``They are really about life, about mankind searching for
answers. The dog never changes position. He just stares at you. And
you're looking at him, looking for some answers, `Why are we here?'
and he's just looking back at you, wondering the same. The dog
doesn't know. You can see this longing in his eyes, this longing
for love, answers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just a dog,'' he added, but a dog trapped in that
same uncertainty all people feel. And no matter how many landscapes
the dog travels to, its expression never changes.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps one of the most famous Blue Dogs is one commissioned by
President Clinton for his inauguration, showing him and Vice
President Al Gore striding confidently into the future.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Dog's creator comes from a people shackled by water. Drive
along the long, flat ribbons of asphalt through Cajun Louisiana,
and it often seems as if there is no dry land at all, just thin
stretches of road between black trees and swamps.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trees are always very dark,'' he said of his early
paintings, ``but the people are in white,'' almost glimmering in
contrast to their surroundings, their feet barely touching the
ground. They seem ghostlike, their eyes staring straight ahead,
searching the face of the person who is searching their own faces
from the other side of the canvas. They seem to hang suspended in a
landscape, but the spirit inside them shines through, like a
lighted window from a cabin surrounded by swamp.
</P>
<P>
   Rodrigue, the son of a bricklayer, was born in 1944 in New
Iberia, La. ``When I was in the third grade I got polio and had to
stay in bed a year and half,'' he said. ``That's when my mother
gave me some crayons and some clay.''
</P>
<P>
   When he was 18, he went off to study at the Art Center College
of Design in Pasadena, Calif., and came home to find the bayou
changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The culture was eroding and disappearing,'' he said. ``I
wanted to preserve that heritage, and I started painting the people
I knew.''
</P>
<P>
   He made a good living painting the dark trees, doing portraits,
some from old photos, of Louisiana legends like Huey Long and his
brother, Earl. He did coffee table books and collaborated on an
acclaimed book of poetry. Often at his side as he painted was his
dog Tiffany, who lived from 1968 to 1980, just a little dog with
pointy ears.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, he was asked to paint, for a collection of Cajun ghost
stories, a picture of a monster from his childhood, the ghost dog,
or werewolf, which appears blue in the moonlight. Here, people
called it the loup-garou.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Tiffany had not been very fierce, Rodrigue used the
little dog as his model. He painted her blue, gave her red eyes and
positioned her on a grave. The image haunted him, trapped in the
canvas, searching. He could never get the dog out of his head.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, he hung a Blue Dog painting with his other works at his
New Orleans gallery. People seemed to like it. The image of the dog
changed with time as memories of other dogs crept into his
paintings _ changed in its shade of blue (except when it is
possessed by spirits, and then it is red) and even a little in
shape.
</P>
<P>
   But it remained, well, a Blue Dog _ a Blue Dog with a naked
woman, a Blue Dog in a cowboy hat, a Blue Dog in a suit and tie, a
Blue Dog over the Manhattan skyline, a Blue Dog with . . . you name
it, you got it.
</P>
<P>
   Rodrigue paints in solitude at his cabin in the Atchafalaya
basin and always has to watch for floods. ``But I work from a
raised cottage. I'm on a platform about 12 feet above the water, so
I should be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   An art critic in Atlanta called the dogs ``badly painted,'' but
people drove to one Atlanta show from as far away as Myrtle Beach,
S.C. A critic in New Orleans called the images ``lowbrow,'' but a
tourist from New York recently stood beside a $25,000 painting and
wondered aloud if she could afford it.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1980s, when Rodrigue started painting Blue Dogs
almost full time, he was reported to have made $4 million in one
year. He bought Mercedeses and Rolexes and other baubles.
</P>
<P>
   ``People willing to spend $25,000 on a painting are in the
market for real art,'' he said. ``They know what they like. It
never was a fad. It's art.'' A Japanese buyer was said to have
spent $250,000 for one.
</P>
<P>
   When executives at Viking Studio Books saw a proposal for a book
about Blue Dog in 1994, they decided to raise the price, originally
no more than $19.95, to $45, convinced that it would sell
successfully at the high end. It did.
</P>
<P>
   The artist has no plans to stop painting Blue Dog, though he now
also enjoys doing Cajun landscapes in which no dogs appear. And he
likes to work on larger canvases now, some the size of pickups.
</P>
<P>
   Today, a few steps from his French Quarter gallery is a gallery
that sells, almost exclusively, red cats _ red cats with
sunglasses, red cats with cows jumping over the moon, red cats on
the Empire State Building. Rodrigue does not seem flattered.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gets $200 for a piece; I get $25,000,'' Rodrigue said. ``I
wish him luck, but a real artist wouldn't do that, you know.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
