<HEADER>
A6521 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FALLBOOKS-TEX     09-15 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALLBOOKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PREVIEW OF WHAT COULD BE THE BEST FALL IN YEARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Larry McMurtry. Alice Walker. Hunter S. Thompson with a novel.
Patricia Cornwell with a novella. One of the best best-known
American authors, Tom Wolfe, and perhaps the best of the
least-known, Pam Houston.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to fiction, this fall could rank with the best of
literary times.
</P>
<P>
   There will be some exceptional nonfiction, too, from the likes
of Stephen Ambrose, Edmund Morris, A. Scott Berg and former
President George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a month-by-month look at fall books:
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   SEPTEMBER
</P>
<P>
   _ Stephen King's ``Bag of Bones'' (Scribner, $28) arrives. The
one-time boy wonder of publishing has fallen on hard times,
saleswise, and has left longtime affiliate Viking to join Scribner.
King promises ``Bag of Bones'' will be both scary and literary.
</P>
<P>
   _ We also get ``The Loop'' (Delacorte, $25.95) from Nicholas
Evans, who apparently won't be a one-hit wonder with ``The Horse
Whisperer.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't miss Pam Houston's short-story collection ``Waltzing the
Cat'' (Norton, $23.95). A half-dozen years ago, Houston's ``Cowboys
Are My Weakness'' established her as a fine young writer.
``Waltzing'' proves she's fine, period. If fall '98 only marks
Houston's breakthrough with mainstream readers, that alone would
qualify it as a significant milestone.
</P>
<P>
   _ Historians will drool over A. Scott Berg's ``Lindbergh''
(Putnam, $30). Berg's biography of Max Perkins is considered a
classic, and advance word pegs this book as better.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``A World Transformed'' (Knopf, $18) teams President Bush with
Brent Scowcroft, his national security adviser. Big news here is
Bush's reasoning behind stopping Desert Storm troops short of
Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
   _ Though less heralded, Julia Alvarez's ``Something to Declare''
(Algonquin, $20.95) promises excellence. It examines the
deceptively simple appearance of being a writer.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   OCTOBER
</P>
<P>
   _ Michael Jordan is listed as author of ``For the Love of My
Game'' (Crown, $50), a photo-filled, ghost-written tome that
undoubtedly will outsell more scholarly titles like Paul Theroux's
``Sir Vidia's Shadow'' (Houghton Mifflin, $24), which detail's
Theroux's crumbling friendship with V.S. Naipaul.
</P>
<P>
   _ Melissa Muller's ``Anne Frank: A Biography'' (Holt, $23)
attempts to reconstruct Anne's brief life and even suggests which
informer might have betrayed the Franks to the Gestapo. It's
possible this book might be released in late September.
</P>
<P>
   _ John Updike reintroduces a favorite character in ``Bech at
Bay'' (Knopf, $23).
</P>
<P>
   _ Mary Higgins Clark has a Christmas mystery, ``All Through the
Night'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $17).
</P>
<P>
   _ Walter Moseley tries science fiction with ``Blue Light''
(Little, Brown, $25).
</P>
<P>
   _ Philip Roth returns with ``I Married a Communist'' (Houghton
Mifflin, $26).
</P>
<P>
   _ Alice Walker will please her fans with ``By the Light of My
Father's Smile'' (Random House, $22.95).
</P>
<P>
   _ Hunter S. Thompson finally publishes his long-rumored novel
``The Rum Diaries'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $25).
</P>
<P>
   _ Other _ ahem _ authors we'll be meeting again in October
include Anne Rice with ``The Vampire Armand'' (Knopf, $26.95) and
Nora Roberts with ``The Reef'' (Putnam, $23.95).
</P>
<P>
   _ Of special Texas interest are Dan Jenkins with ``Rude
Behavior'' (Doubleday, $24.95, may come out in September) and
Janice Woods Windle's ``Hill Country'' (Longstreet, $25).
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   NOVEMBER
</P>
<P>
   _ November is traditionally the best month for fall books, as
publishers care so much about making early Christmas shopping
convenient. It begins, of course, with Tom Wolfe's ``A Man in
Full'' (Ferrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, $27.50), which possibly will be
pushed to late October. Wolfe's ``The Bonfire of the Vanities,''
published 10 years ago, remains the literary masterwork of the
'80s. ``A Man in Full,'' chronicling an Atlanta athlete accused of
rape, is supposed to be as good or better.
</P>
<P>
   _ Barbara Kingsolver is back with ``The Poisonwood Bible''
(HarperFlamingo, $27.50).
</P>
<P>
   _ Alice Munro brings us ``The Love of a Good Woman'' (Knopf,
$24).
</P>
<P>
   _ Joyce Carol Oates attempts Gothicism with ``The Collector of
Hearts'' (Dutton, $23.95).
</P>
<P>
   _ Perennial bestseller-list presences James Patterson (''When
the Wind Blows,'' Little, Brown, $25) and Danielle Steel (''Mirror
Image,'' Delacorte, $26.95) also have new titles on sale.
</P>
<P>
   _ In nonfiction, Stephen Ambrose (highly influential in ``Saving
Private Ryan'') completes his World War II trilogy with ``The
Victors: Eisenhower and His Boys'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $28).
</P>
<P>
   _ Political junkies, rejoice; November also brings Edmund
Morris' ``Dutch: A Memoir of Ronald Reagan'' (Random House, $30)
and ``All Too Human: A Political Education'' (Little, Brown,
$27.95) from former Clinton White House senior adviser George
Stephanopoulos. One suspects Bill and Hillary won't like what they
read there.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   DECEMBER
</P>
<P>
   _ Larry McMurtry tries a third visit to Thalia with ``Duane's
Depressed'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $26).
</P>
<P>
   _ David Baldacci, a lesser talent but recent bestseller-list
presence, is back with ``The Simple Truth'' (Warner, $25).
</P>
<P>
   _ In nonfiction, Tony Bennett has an autobiography (''The Good
Life,'' Pocket Books, $25) and historians Robert Lacey and Danny
Danziger tell us about ``The Year 1000: What Life Was Like a
Thousand Years Ago'' (Little, Brown, $22).
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-98 1737EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
