<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-GOV-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRAT DECRIES LINK TO CLINTON'S CHARACTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ZACHARY COILE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Denouncing an effort to link him to a wounded
President Clinton, Lt. Gov. Gray Davis said California voters were
less interested in candidates' sex lives than in their stands on
public policy issues.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic candidate for governor said his opponent,
Republican Attorney General Dan Lungren, might see his attempt to
use Clinton's character as a campaign issue backfire.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't want candidates to talk about what the
candidate's personal life is about,'' Davis said after a
fund-raising luncheon in San Francisco on Monday. ``They want them
to talk about issues that affect voters. How can you improve the
schools? How can you make the environment better? Are you
pro-choice? Those are the issues people want to hear about.''
</P>
<P>
   But some Democratic women who attended the luncheon, which
raised $100,000 for Davis, expressed concern that female voters
disgusted with Clinton's character would stay away from the polls
in November, hurting Democratic candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to go back to women and remind them that voting is
about issues that matter in their lives,'' said Ellen Malcolm,
president of Emily's List, which raises money for Democratic
candidates who are women.
</P>
<P>
   Davis' comments came as a new poll released Tuesday showed him
with a lead of 9 percentage points. The poll of 1,046 likely voters
by the Public Policy Institute of California showed that 47 percent
supported Davis, while 38 percent backed Lungren.
</P>
<P>
   Lungren has sought to capitalize on Clinton's troubles, saying
he would make character a central issue in the race. In a
television commercial entitled ``Character,'' Lungren says: ``You
can't tell people to do one thing while you do another. From the
White House to the school house ... that's what we ought to be
talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   While he has not accused Davis of lying or adultery, Lungren has
criticized his opponent for, among other things, lacking the
character to take a stand on the North American Free Trade
Agreement because of his strong support from labor unions.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jane Harman, who lost to Davis in the Democratic primary,
said she thought the link to Clinton was tenuous at best.
</P>
<P>
   ``Voters are discerning,'' said Harman, who hosted the luncheon
for Davis. ``They certainly know that Gray Davis is not the same
person as Bill Clinton, and they also know that Bill Clinton's name
is not on the ballot.''
</P>
<P>
   On a campaign tour in San Francisco, Davis turned attention to
issues on which he believes Lungren is weak: abortion, education
and gun control.
</P>
<P>
   Davis spoke of his support for abortion rights _ which Lungren
opposes _ and his opposition to Lungren's plan to give parents
school vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   Davis joined state Assemblyman Don Perata, a Democrat from
Alameda, in urging Republican Gov. Pete Wilson to sign Perata's
bill to limit assault weapons. Wilson is expected to veto the bill,
which would ban copycat versions of illegal assault weapons and
magazine clips of 20 rounds or more.
</P>
<P>
   Davis also attacked Lungren, who has not taken a position on the
bill.
</P>
<P>
   Lungren spokesman Rob Stutzman said the attorney general was not
taking a position on the issue because he was defending the current
assault weapons bill, which is being challenged in the California
Supreme Court. Lungren has previously supported legislation
limiting the size of magazine clips on assault weapons, Stutzman
said.
</P>
<P>
   After the event, Davis told reporters that while he condemned
Clinton's private behavior as ``inexcusable, indefensible and
embarrassing to all of us,'' he continued to support the
president's agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would just urge all Americans not to come to a final
conclusion until all the facts are in and both sides have made
their case,'' Davis said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-98 1738EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
