<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6526 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX     09-15 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROAD TO LEAN, MEAN PAVED WITH PIE-IN-THE-THIGH HOPES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA ANDERSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like me, you've probably wondered why some women wear high heels
with shorts.
</P>
<P>
   I consider shorts casual clothing even if they are made of silk
or have some designer's name on them. Casual clothing calls for
casual footwear. Shorts and heels is not a bad look if the woman
has nice legs. It's just unusual, like a fellow wearing wingtips
with a warm-up.
</P>
<P>
   I believe in ``live and let live'' for the most part, but that
doesn't stop me from being puzzled about certain things. So, as
luck would have it, I recently had an experience that solved this
mystery for me and, because you and I are close, personal friends,
I'm going to share it with you.
</P>
<P>
   I mentioned in a previous column that I had surgery on my
shoulder a few weeks ago. I am considerably better now, but during
my recovery, I spent most of my time in bed eating and watching
television. In retrospect, it occurs to me that I could have
exercised my lower body even though my upper body was temporarily
disabled. Live and learn, eh? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, I'm going to bypass the chewing all together and
just slit my thighs and stick the pie and cake right on in there.
That's where it's going anyway. Why bother with all that swallowing
and digesting? If I get my doctor to install a zipper, I can reduce
my lunch hour to 30 minutes or less.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, I was at physical therapy the other day sitting on a
bench and struggling to lift a small weight over my head when I
happened to glance into the mirror beside me. I was wearing shorts
and a T-shirt because it was a warm day and I wanted to be
comfortable during my exercises. My eyes zeroed in on my thigh, and
I was so disgusted that I dropped the weight on the floor. My thigh
looked like it had hail damage! Cellulite city!
</P>
<P>
   When on earth did that happen, I wondered. It's amazing my
therapist didn't hurl. No wonder he kept walking away and talking
to other people.
</P>
<P>
   I had to finish all my repetitions with the weights. I couldn't
just stand up and run out of the room like I wanted to do. I
managed to lift my legs off the bench just a bit by raising the
heels of my athletic shoes off the ground. My legs looked
infinitely better, and mercifully, my calf muscles bulged just a
bit. That's better, I thought. That's when I noticed that all of
the other women in the room were wearing long pants except for this
one big-boned lady who was wearing shorts and high heels. When I
looked at her face, she winked at me and smiled. Live and learn,
eh?
</P>
<P>
   I went home and got on my stationary bike. I started pumping as
hard as I could, determined to reverse a month of idleness in a
half-hour. As so often happens on these occasions, my mind began to
wander. I thought seriously about changing my name. When folks hear
the name ``Monica'' now, they don't think of the saint or the
teen-age singing sensation. They think of the Starr report and
cigars. The odds of someday having a granddaughter named after me
are very unfavorable at this point.
</P>
<P>
   Then, I recalled the days when ``cool'' referred to moderately
cold temperatures. Now it means ``extraordinary.'' ``Funky'' once
meant ``foul smelling,'' and now it also defines something that is
``extraordinary.''
</P>
<P>
   Who knows, maybe someday the name ``Monica'' will again be
associated with extraordinary _ no, make that exemplary _ women.
Unfortunately, that event and my leaner, meaner body are gonna take
a while.
</P>
<P>
   (Monica Frazier Anderson is a wife, mother and dentist in
Arlington, Texas. You can call her at (817) 548-5564, or write in
care of the Arlington Star-Telegram at 1111 W. Abram St.,
Arlington, TX 76013. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on
the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
