<HEADLINE>
A CONAN O'BRIEN HIGHLIGHT REEL
</HEADLINE>
 
(Eds: Accompanies BC-TV-CONANTHECONQUERER) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   May 3, 1993: A pale, uncomfortable O'Brien faces the media for
the first time. When a reporter asks about the pressure of being a
virtual unknown, O'Brien quips, ``No, sir. I am a `complete'
unknown.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 13, 1993: ``Late Night With Conan O'Brien'' debuts on NBC
with Drew Barrymore, Tony Randall and John Goodman. O'Brien is
jittery, nervous and unable to conduct a conversation without
looking as though he's in pain.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   January 1996: O'Brien institutes running gags, such as one in
which he gets 22,000 people to phone in about the whereabouts of
the character Grady from ``Sanford &AMP; Son.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 13, 1996: ``Late Night With Conan O'Brien'' celebrates its
third anniversary with recurring sketches like ``If they mated,''
in which photos of celebrity couples are merged to see what their
children would look like.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 27, 1996: In what typifies the O'Brien humor, country
singer Kenny Rogers fails a blind taste test, choosing a batch of
chicken from an NBC cafeteria over his own Kenny Rogers' Roasters.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   April 7, 1997: NBC finally scratches the short-term renewals and
extends Conan's contract for five years, at $2 million annually.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 26, 1997: O'Brien brings on social activist the Rev. Al
Sharpton to perform James Brown's funk classic, ``Sex Machine.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 16, 1998: A self-assured O'Brien meets the media in
Pasadena, Calif. Asked how much he has changed, O'Brien quips, ``I
don't wet myself during every show.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Ken Parish Perkins &QR;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
