<HEADER>
A6535 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FIVE-EATING-WELL-NYT &LR;      09-15 1162
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIVE-EATING-WELL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRATEGIES FOR MAKING VEGETABLES PALATABLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MARIAN BURROS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is no better time than right now _ OK, you could have
started earlier in the summer _ to get into what nutritionists call
the Five-a-Day habit: eating five servings of fruits and vegetables
every day.
</P>
<P>
   This is a habit that scientists suggest can help prevent a host
of diseases, including heart disease, cancer and stroke. But it is
a habit that very few people have cultivated because most of us
prefer the taste of potato chips to fresh potatoes and
fruit-flavored candy bars to fresh fruit.
</P>
<P>
   That's stiff competition, but at this moment, when many fruits
and vegetables are local and at their peak of flavor, they have a
fighting chance.
</P>
<P>
   The recipes here suggest ways to bring out the best flavor of
what's in the market _ green beans and potatoes, tomatoes and
plums. You might also consider taking vegetable-hating children to
pick-your-own farms and letting them help harvest what you want
them to eat.
</P>
<P>
   Locally grown fruits and vegetables are better for reasons
beyond freshness. The varieties grown locally differ from what is
grown thousands of miles away because they do not have to withstand
a long arduous journey. They can be selected for flavor, rather
than hardiness.
</P>
<P>
   A fruit can be picked at the moment of ripeness, when it has the
perfect balance of sweetness and acidity; a vegetable can be picked
while it is immature, that is, young and tender.
</P>
<P>
   This makes perfect common sense but has been difficult to
document because little scientific work has been done on the taste
of fruits and vegetables picked at the right moment for eating,
versus those picked to travel well for thousands of miles.
</P>
<P>
   When I called the Produce for Better Health Foundation, which
was created by the produce industry and others to promote the
Five-a-Day plan, its president, Dr. Elizabeth Pivonka, sidestepped
the question of which tastes better, local produce or produce that
travels across the country or across the world. Instead, Dr.
Pivonka said, ``There is a lot of good fruit from Chile.''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt there is, and I'm sure the Chileans enjoy it at the
peak of flavor. With an increasingly global economy, we will get
more fruits and vegetables from the ends of the earth, but eating
nectarines in February and asparagus in November is no way to learn
how they should truly taste.
</P>
<P>
   At least one scientist, Dr. Alley Watada of the Agricultural
Research Service of the Agriculture Department in Beltsville, Md.,
has been studying the difference in taste and nutrition between
locally grown tomatoes picked when perfectly ripe and those picked
while ripening. Watada said, ``Without question, the red ripe
tomatoes had the most nutrients and tasted the best.''
</P>
<P>
   The taste was determined at the Horticulture Crops Quality
Laboratory by a sensory panel, a group of people trained to
recognize differences in taste. The ripest tomatoes also had about
5 percent more nutrients like vitamin C than those that were not
fully ripe, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, Watada has done work with honeydews, too. And
guess what he said? The locally grown honeydews now in the market
taste better than the ones that come from Chile in the winter.
</P>
<P>
   PLUM COMPOTE
</P>
<P>
   Time: 20 to 30 minutes, plus chilling  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   4 whole cloves
</P>
<P>
   1 3-inch stick cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   Zest of 1/2 lemon
</P>
<P>
   16 large, firm ripe red or black plums, stemmed.
</P>
<P>
   1. Combine the sugar, wine, one cup of water, cloves, cinnamon
and lemon zest in a saucepan large enough to hold the plums. Bring
the ingredients to a boil, and cook, uncovered, for 5 minutes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2. Add plums, and bring mixture back to a boil; lower heat, and
simmer plums for 10 to 20 minutes, depending on their ripeness,
until they are tender but still hold their shape. Some plums will
be ready before others; remove them as they are. Then when they are
all cooked, return the plums to the syrup, remove from heat and let
cool. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3. Chill plums in the syrup. Serve over vanilla ice cream or
frozen yogurt with some of the syrup, or serve with their syrup
topped with whipped cream or creme fraiche. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   GREEN BEANS AND POTATO SALAD  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 to 40 minutes  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds tiny new potatoes, scrubbed but not peeled
</P>
<P>
   1 pound young green beans or haricots verts (French green
beans), washed and trimmed
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup white wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons chopped fresh thyme
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup finely chopped red onion
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste.
</P>
<P>
   1. Cook potatoes in water to cover for 10 to 20 minutes,
depending on their size, until they are tender but firm; drain, and
cut in quarters or halves, again depending on size. Meanwhile,
steam the green beans 5 to 7 minutes, depending on their thickness;
drain, and rinse under cold water to stop the cooking. Cut in
quarters or thirds, depending on size.
</P>
<P>
   2. In a large bowl, whisk together the oil, vinegar, lemon juice
and mustard; stir in the thyme and onion. When potatoes are cooked,
stir them into the dressing. If the salad is not to be served
immediately, do not add the green beans: the acid of the dressing
will turn them gray. Cover the beans well, cover the dressed
potatoes and refrigerate separately.
</P>
<P>
   3. To serve, let the vegetables return to room temperature. Stir
the green beans into the potatoes and dressing, and season with
salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 to 8 servings.
</P>
<P>
   MEDITERRANEAN COUSCOUS SALAD &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 35 to 40 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3 cups vegetable or chicken stock or broth
</P>
<P>
   2 cups instant whole wheat couscous
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   2 large cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   Grated zest of 2 oranges
</P>
<P>
   1 or 2 jalapenos, trimmed, seeded and finely minced
</P>
<P>
   2 dozen green or black medium French, Italian or Greek olives,
pitted and finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped capers
</P>
<P>
   2 cups (about 10 ounces) julienned red bell peppers
</P>
<P>
   1 pound zucchini, cut into julienne strips
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup finely diced red onion
</P>
<P>
   1 cup diced fennel
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 medium-large ripe tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   1. Bring stock to boil in covered pot. Add couscous, remove from
heat and allow to sit for five minutes, until liquid has been
absorbed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2. Whisk oil, vinegar, mustard and garlic in a serving bowl. Add
orange zest, jalapenos, olives and capers, and mix well. Stir in
the red pepper, zucchini, onion and fennel, and season with salt
and pepper. Stir in the couscous. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3. If not serving immediately, refrigerate without the tomatoes.
No more than 30 minutes before serving, cut up the tomatoes and
stir in.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 to 8 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
