<SLUG> BC-MONET-ART-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOSTALGIA VIES WITH MODERNITY IN MONET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release on Sunday, Sept. 20.)  
 (HLW)  
 By MICHAEL KIMMELMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Not so long ago, 20 or 25 years maybe, Monet wasn't the
immensely popular figure that he is now. If you go back yet another
25 years, people were actually talking about the need to reconsider
his career, or part of it: in the early 1950s, American critics
looking for antecedents to what the Abstract Expressionists were
doing latched onto Monet's late works, like the Water Lilies, which
had been mostly disregarded for a quarter century. To the critics,
Monet suddenly justified Pollock, and vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't until the 1980s that a Monet show, like the one
opening here today, was guaranteed, no matter how good or bad it
might be, to bring in hundreds of thousands of people and to
require the whole elaborate system of advance sales, ticketing by
the hour, membership incentives, gift paraphernalia and group
tours.
</P>
<P>
   The progress of Monet's reputation says something, I suspect,
not just about ``Monet in the 20th Century,'' which is the name of
the show now at the Museum of Fine Arts, but also about the
public's relationship to 20th-century art generally.
</P>
<P>
   Why is he so popular? Lots of great artists aren't. He didn't
cut off any ears or fail to sell his paintings before he died _ in
fact for much of his life he was immensely rich and successful _ so
there's no obvious biographical angle, though when Giverny was
opened to the public in 1980 it did give a place to his fame. It
became a pilgrimage site, art's Graceland.
</P>
<P>
   But ultimately the answer must be in the pictures, and I think
it involves the essential soft core of the art: the way works like
the Water Lilies become passive receptacles for nostalgia. Monet's
popularity reveals our desire for art as both refuge and spectacle.
</P>
<P>
   Diderot famously distinguished between two kinds of painting.
One was all-over sharp-focus; he talked about ``the law of
universal finish.'' The entire surface of the picture was evenly
articulated, so that, as he put it, ``my relation to such a picture
is like my relation to the nature that was the painter's model.''
</P>
<P>
   The other kind of painting imitates what a scene looks like from
a painter's vantage point. Rembrandt was Diderot's example. Objects
are in focus or out of focus; they lose definition when you back
away from the picture or when you move in closer than the artist
was standing from the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Monet's late Water Lilies fit neither of these descriptions.
They're all-over evenly unarticulated and everywhere out of focus,
meaning your eye lands nowhere, it drifts, and the effect doesn't
really change as your position does. Nothing in them is more
important than anything else: everything, water, water lily, sky,
cloud, air, river grass and willow converge and are consumed in the
fluid surface.
</P>
<P>
   This sounds a little like what's sometimes said about Pollock's
art, but Pollock's drips make an impossible entanglement. There's
so much going on in them that you can't take them apart _ which is
to say that they're all-over evenly articulated. You eye races
restlessly over his busy, impenetrable surfaces.
</P>
<P>
   That's a crucial difference. With Monet's pictures we want to
immerse ourselves, to achieve a mood that is akin to theirs, which
is a kind of keen but hallucinatory state not unlike the condition
of memory.
</P>
<P>
   I do not mean by this that Monet was a nostalgic painter. He was
too rigorous to be nostalgic. But his images show reflections in
water and they themselves seem reflective: they suggest the quality
of experiencing a thing indirectly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should be a bit ashamed to be thinking about little
investigations into forms and colors while so many people suffer
and die for us,'' he said about the work he was doing during World
War I. This was precisely the criticism leveled at him then and
also between the wars: that in the midst of chaos, he retreated
into meditations on nature while more responsible artists were
turning to orderly forms of neo-classicism.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, we feel differently about order in art today. Among
other things, after having seen how Hitler and Stalin embraced
neo-classicism, Monet's eye candy no longer seems so bad. He is now
perceived by the public, I think, as a painter of sufficient but
comprehensible modernity and unthreatening beauty, which for many
people clearly comes as relief from all the aggressive and
incomprehensible art of the last few decades. His appeal grows as
the gap between new art and public taste widens.
</P>
<P>
   It's a cliche that Monet's expanding fame has created conditions
in which it's impossible to appreciate him: you can't lose yourself
in front of pictures with hundreds of other people jostling for
repose. No doubt Boston will be mobbed. At least ``Monet in the
20th Century'' isn't a flabby event like so many recent Monet
shows. It comes with an important catalog. Pictures are in the
exhibition that haven't been seen before. The show is intelligently
organized around a proper armature _ the chronological unfolding of
his work between 1900 and his death in 1926, at 86.
</P>
<P>
   From his paintings of London and Venice and his early views of
Giverny we're led past the big sketches and unfinished works on
which he spent the rest of his life. Most of them he never
exhibited; they were preparations for, or variations on the
Orangerie murals in Paris, his last great project, which got such a
tepid response when it opened.
</P>
<P>
   If there's a revelation here it involves the leap Monet made
from the London and Venice works to the later ones: his art became
both much wilder and monumental. At the end of his life he made
Impressionism serve a new purpose, not just to mimic the effect of
light in a landscape but also to approximate the actual scale of
the landscape: to place us in physical relation to an image that
is, as it is in nature, much larger than we are.
</P>
<P>
   I thought of Picasso translating Cubism to mural proportions for
Guernica. That work is iconic but awful: Cubist faceting, enlarged,
flattens into billboard planes, and the picture is a cartoonish mix
of symbolism and abstraction.
</P>
<P>
   Monet's art, by comparison, was much more adaptable to shifts in
scale. The reason is that it was about surface effect. And the
larger the surface the bigger the effect.
</P>
<P>
   Is this a way of saying it's superficial? Paul Tucker, the Monet
scholar, prefers to see symbolism in the late art. After the
Dreyfus Affair, he argues in the catalog, painting ravishing
pictures in France ``was not conservative escapism.''
</P>
<P>
   ``By returning to the fundamentals of his craft in 1899 _ to the
purity of touch, the clarity of light, the distinctiveness of form,
and the readability of space _ Monet was not retreating,'' Tucker
writes. ``He was providing a clarion call for France to re-examine
her building blocks, to encourage an honest accounting and to start
anew. It is appropriate, of course, that his vocabulary is an
intensified form of Impressionism. By 1899 Impressionism was hailed
as a national style, one that rightfully and properly represented
the best characteristics of the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, though the forms mostly look indistinct. Especially in
the very last paintings, space seems to collapse and fold. You
might as easily say that these pictures turned their backs on
everything else happening in the world then: that this is exactly
what makes them enduringly popular.
</P>
<P>
   They're decorative. There's nothing the matter with decoration.
In Monet's great view of Parliament at sunset, the building
dissolves in a sulphurous blue-gold haze, the soft paint like
brushed fur. ``Bridge Over the Water Lily Pond'' from 1900, the
version that belongs to the Art Institute of Chicago, captures
perfectly what happens in the late afternoon, when the low sun
picks out a willow behind the bridge, which is in shadow, and
creates an effect of back lighting.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest crowd pleasers here will no doubt be the final Water
Lilies. I prefer the sketches from a little earlier. A group of
unfinished works from the mid-teens, saturated in color, look as if
they're drawn with pastel, the lines like confetti streamers. In
``Wisteria,'' spaghetti squiggles float high against a sky-blue
ground, a virtual abstraction and a pure, simple pleasure. Guston,
Sam Francis and a slew of other painters come to mind. The picture
tells you everything you need to know about Monet's legacy to the
20th century.
</P>
</TEXT>
