<HEADER>
A6562 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIVENT-HAIMES-ART-2TA     09-15 1104
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIVENT-HAIMES-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TODD HAIMES PLAYS KNIGHT FOR TROUBLED LIVENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By ROBIN POGREBIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Todd Haimes used to be fat. He dropped 55 pounds
several years ago, down to a trim 170 on a 5-foot-10-inch frame,
resolving to live long enough to see his two children grow up. And
though he looks like he has always been fit, Haimes has never been
cavalier about conquering his weight problem. He keeps his fat
pictures around to remind him not to overeat, worried that without
absolute vigilance, the large man inside of him could easily emerge
again.
</P>
<P>
   This goes a long way toward explaining how Haimes, 42, has
become a success in the theater: not with great strides or grand
gestures, but through dogged, painstaking work and the sense that
at any moment it could all fall apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe these insecurities and these self-doubts make me work
harder,'' he said last week. ``All I know is, I feel about my job
the way I feel about my weight _ I never feel complacent.''
</P>
<P>
   This combination of confidence and caution may be what the
executives at Livent Inc., the financially troubled producer of
theatrical blockbusters, were banking on when they selected Haimes
earlier this month to be their new artistic director.
</P>
<P>
   Haimes has been cast in the most closely watched offstage drama
in theater. After running the nonprofit Roundabout Theater Company
for 15 years, he is now entrusted with a crucial role in the rescue
of Livent, the only major publicly traded company exclusively
devoted to theater, one known for extravagant productions and
expensive publicity.
</P>
<P>
   Livent, which owns and operates five theaters in the United
States and Canada, has seven acting companies in five productions
worldwide, including ``Ragtime'' in New York. The company also has
several new productions in the works, such as ``Parade,'' being
produced with the Lincoln Center Theater, and ``Fosse: A
Celebration in Song and Dance.''
</P>
<P>
   Haimes took the helm amid allegations that Livent's founder and
artistic director, Garth H. Drabinsky, along with the company's
co-founder, Myron I. Gottlieb, had kept two sets of financial books
to conceal excessive spending. Both were suspended by the owners
last month, the stock has been frozen since early August, and irate
stockholders have filed a class-action lawsuit against Livent.
</P>
<P>
   And Haimes, who has assumed the duties of the flamboyant
Drabinsky, is expected to somehow make it all better.
</P>
<P>
   Although Haimes pulled the Roundabout through tough times, this
is nevertheless new territory. He comes from institutional theater,
where he had to satisfy subscribers and a board of directors;
Livent, based in Toronto, has to show annual profit increases that
will please shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   The Roundabout has been known for featuring plays by Arthur
Miller and George Bernard Shaw in its two theaters in Manhattan,
which seat 500 and 400; Livent made a name for itself by producing
splashy musicals like ``Ragtime'' and ``Show Boat'' for theaters
that seat 1,800 and 1,900, with hopes of cloning them for touring
companies.
</P>
<P>
   The Roundabout has an $18 million annual operating budget and
pays actors between $650 and $1,000 a week, even stars. Livent's
budget last year was more than $250 million, not including the
amortization of pre-production costs and administrative expenses.
(A spokesman said it does not disclose actors' salaries.)
</P>
<P>
   Haimes has extensive theater experience and is widely credited
with making the Roundabout successful. But his experience in
commercial theater is limited to sending several productions to
Broadway houses, all of which failed to recoup their investment in
the hands of new producers, despite critical acclaim.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear whether Haimes' mandate from Livent's owners, the
New York investment banker Roy Furman and the Hollywood power
broker Michael Ovitz, is just to pick up the pieces or to take the
company in a new direction.
</P>
<P>
   Haimes said he thinks he is expected to do a bit of both. ``The
message I got from Roy and Michael was twofold,'' Haimes said. ``To
do what Livent has been doing but in a much more financially
efficient and effective way, and to be able to serve a wider range
of artists in different ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Some theater professionals see Haimes' leap to Livent as
dramatic, given the historically distinct worlds of institutional
and commercial theater. ``The whole motive of a not-for-profit is
to do worthwhile events that aren't necessarily commercial,'' said
John Breglio, an entertainment lawyer and chairman of the Theater
Development Fund. ``Therefore, the artistic imperative often comes
right up against the commercial reality. A commercial venture is
not necessarily set up solely for the public good; it's a different
discipline.''
</P>
<P>
   But others suggest that the two spheres have become increasingly
reciprocal and that Haimes' appointment reflects that shift. ``In
terms of the 90's and culture and the arts, it seems to be an
incredibly sensible move to me,'' said Neil Pepe, the artistic
director of the Atlantic Theater Company, a nonprofit theater in
Chelsea. ``Just look at some of the successful straight plays on
Broadway _ a lot have come out of not-for-profits. It's a clear
sign that the two should be working together.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Haimes insisted that artistic excellence and commercial
success need not be mutually exclusive and said he plans to bring
some of his Roundabout sensibility to Livent. `
</P>
<P>
   `Clearly the financial underpinning of Livent is the bigger
musicals that fill the bigger theaters that we own. There's just no
getting away from that and that's great,'' Haimes said. ``But one
of my interests is expanding the work of Livent to serve all
different levels of production. Five years from now I'd like to see
the same director who directs a large musical also direct a new
play for Livent in a 300-seat theater.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess my dream is to see whether there's a commercial model
for a large institutional theater,'' he continued. ``I don't know
the answer to that question.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the number of unanswered questions, the move to Livent is
also risky for Haimes. Many in the theater community question
Livent's very survival. Perhaps, cynics may suggest, this is why
Haimes is also hanging on to his post as artistic director of the
Roundabout through the 1998-99 season, as a hedge against Livent's
potential downfall.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But Haimes said he had confidence in Livent's longevity and that
he is staying on at Roundabout because he does not want to leave
the theater in the lurch, particularly as it prepares to move to
its new home in the Selwyn Theater on 42nd Street. ``My work is not
finished,'' he said. ( Furman said Haimes' commitment to the
Roundabout was fine with him.)
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Haimes will have to adapt to a new corporate
culture. He used to chat casually with reporters in his office at
his convenience, for example; now a Livent public relations person
schedules his interviews and sits in on them, taking notes.
</P>
<P>
   As for whether he is up to his new task, Haimes was typically
self-deprecating. ``I do sort of worry about my ability to do for
Livent what I want to do for Livent,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time Haimes knows he must have done something right
to get to this point, and says that Livent is really just the
Roundabout on a larger scale, although some might question that
perception. ``I have found that the only way I feel comfortable
doing this is to trust my instincts,'' he said. ``And up to now,
they've been more often right than wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Haimes said he has weathered worse than Livent's difficulties.
The Roundabout has endured bankruptcy, near financial collapse and
the recent construction accident in Times Square, which temporarily
closed three of his productions, including the highly successful
``Cabaret,'' causing losses of $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, having earned an MBA at Yale and come up on the
management side of the arts, Haimes makes no apologies for wanting
theater to make a profit. ``I truly believe that theater is a
business,'' he said. ``Artistic success is the most profoundly
moving, but I can't separate that from financial stability.''
</P>
<P>
   Haimes said the Roundabout has run in the black since he became
managing director there in 1983. Since then, the theater has grown
from a start-up in a supermarket basement to the second-largest
nonprofit theater after Lincoln Center's. Last season, the
Roundabout's three Broadway productions _ ``Cabaret,'' ``A View
From the Bridge'' and ``1776'' _ were nominated for 17 Tony Awards
in 14 of the 21 categories and won 6.
</P>
<P>
   Furman, who was instrumental in flagging Livent's financial
disarray and suspending Drabinsky, said Haimes was his choice for
two main reasons: ``He understands the bottom line, he's greatly
respected in the theater community.''
</P>
<P>
   As Haimes rides the fine line between what's good and what
sells, some people in the theater say he has already had
considerable practice at the Roundabout, which has generally staged
accessible works that please a broadly based audience of 35,000
subscribers, whose contributions make up 20 percent of the
theater's budget.
</P>
<P>
   But Haimes takes issue with the suggestion that the Roundabout
is risk-averse, saying that opening ``Cabaret'' in a small theater
was a major gamble and that, had ``1776'' failed to take off, the
results would have been financially devastating. ``I honestly feel
we pushed the envelope,'' he said. ``I have no apologies at all.''
</P>
<P>
   In a theater community often known for its backbiting
competitiveness, people had generous words for Haimes. ``I think
it's a great appointment,'' said Rocco Landesman, the president of
Jujamcyn Theaters. ``He's obviously very fiscally responsible and
realistic, he understands what a budget is and how it works, he has
good taste and he's a very personable kind of guy who I think
inspires confidence in the people he deals with.''
</P>
<P>
   Natasha Richardson, who starred in the Roundabout's productions
of ``Cabaret'' and ``Anna Christie'' and now serves on the
theater's advisory council, said of Haimes, ``He is a truly rare
thing in this business in that he is not an opportunist and he's
not an egotist.''
</P>
<P>
   Haimes said he knows he's in for a difficult year. He has
already been struggling to balance his intense loyalty to work and
to fatherhood (he has a daughter, 11, and a son, 10). And he
acknowledged that his career has strained his 16-year marriage to
Alison Bender Haimes, a neuroradiologist he met while working on a
college production of ``Kiss Me Kate'' at the University of
Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he said he looked forward to the work and that he
hoped his sense of self-abnegation would serve him well. ``I am
sort of a half-empty person, not a half-full person,'' he said.
``Even after this successful season at Roundabout, I never feel,
`Wow, I'm on top of the world.' I always feel, `How am I going to
keep this level up?'''
</P>
</TEXT>
