<HEADER>
A6592 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-JURY16-COX     09-15 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-JURY16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    STARR GRAND JURY POISED FOR INDICTMENTS
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For 23 ordinary Washington residents, the grand
jurors whose names have been kept secret as they have had a front
row seat for the biggest presidential scandal in a quarter of a
century, the most crucial decisions are still ahead.
</P>
<P>
   After listening to more than 70 witnesses as independent counsel
Kenneth Starr built his case for Congress to impeach President
Clinton, the grand jury could soon begin handing up criminal
indictments.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would certainly make sense for the grand jury to pursue
individuals who it believed were involved in efforts to obstruct
justice or suborn perjury,'' said George Washington University law
professor Jonathan Turley, who predicted Tuesday that indictments
would come within the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In his report, Starr told Congress that ``all phases'' of his
probe were near completion. Among the most likely areas for
indictments are allegations of obstruction of justice and witness
tampering involving:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Attempts to discourage White House volunteer Kathleen Willey
from testifying that she had been sexually harassed during a visit
in the Oval Office study with the president.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Efforts to encourage Monica Lewinsky's to conceal her sexual
affair with Clinton when the former White House intern became a
witness in the Paula Jones sexual harassment lawsuit against the
president.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton friend Vernon Jordan, who secured a job in New York at
Revlon for Lewinsky just as the Jones case was heating up, is
mentioned frequently in the report to Congress. ``It ultimately
depends on whether the grand jury concludes that Mr. Jordan's
conduct was poorly timed, but innocent, as opposed to part of a
criminal pattern,'' said Turley.
</P>
<P>
   The grand jurors could take action against Clinton himself,
according to legal experts. They could indict him, although the
courts have yet to rule on the constitutionality of indicting a
sitting president, or they could indict his aides and list him as
an ``unindicted co-conspirator.''
</P>
<P>
   And they could also focus on Linda Tripp, a central witness in
the Lewinsky matter.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Defense Department are under suspicion for
illegally releasing private personnel information about Tripp in an
apparent effort to damage her credibility. Tripp taped hours of
conversations in which her former Pentagon coworker and friend
Lewinsky described her sexual liaison with Clinton. Starr has used
a grand jury in Alexandria, Va., near the Pentagon, to investigate
that aspect of the controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Tripp herself is apparently a target, as revealed in the Starr
report. It raises questions about the reliability of her testimony
that the 27 audio tapes that she handed over to the FBI were
originals. Some were found to be duplications, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Starr could also wrap up his investigation by asking the
Washington grand jury for indictments on earlier phases of his
probe: the Whitewater real estate development in Arkansas, firing
of the White House travel office and the improper storing of FBI
files on 900 people by the Clinton White House. However, actions
resulting from those cases are considered improbable.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the issue of indictments, the grand jurors have
performed a crucial function for the investigation, said former
federal prosecutor Victoria Tonsing: ``They are also used a vehicle
for gathering evidence. In gathering evidence you need power. You
want to talk to me, I can tell you to 'kiss off.' But you get me
with a grand jury subpoena, and I've got to appear, or I'm subject
to arrest.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most juries, grand jurors are permitted to question
witnesses. When the president testified from the White House Map
Room Aug. 17, for example, the jurors who sat in their windowless
federal courtroom and watched a closed circuit video were active
participants. One juror relayed a question to the prosecutors,
asking the president why he had suddenly withdrawn his assertion of
executive privilege to block White House aides from testifying just
as the case reached the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't really want to advance an executive privilege claim
in this case beyond having it litigated,'' Clinton responded.
</P>
<P>
   Although grand jury testimony is considered secret at the time
it's given, it can be used in court once an indictment is returned,
Tonsing said. Or, in the case of Starrr's report, the grand jury
information became available for use after it was given to
Congress, as required by the independent counsel law. Starr took
the precaution of also securing a federal court order for release
of the material.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rationale for keeping it secret is so that people will not
hear nasty rumors, so reputations cannot be besmirched,'' said
Tonsing. ``But that falls to the wayside when there's sufficient
evidence for an indictment.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
