<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, Sept. 16, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(jt) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL FORECAST &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Showers and thunderstorms associated with a persistent plume of
tropical moisture emanating in the Gulf of Mexico will occur from
eastern Texas to the Delmarva Peninsula Wednesday. The showers will
be most widespread from the lower Ohio River Valley to northeastern
Texas where heavy rains associated with the remnants of Frances
instigated flooding. Wednesday's rains should not be widespread
enough to aggravate the flooding situation further. Thundershowers
will also douse sections of central and southern Florida as a
tropical disturbance combines with afternoon sea breezes to lift
the humid air over the peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   Unseasonably sultry air will plague the interior Southeast again
as expansive high pressure at 18,000 feet suppresses cooling
showers. High temperatures will reach into the 90s from Alabama to
Virginia. A weak cold front moving southward into the Middle
Atlantic States will temper the summery warmth and humidity that
has been controlling the region as of late. Clouds will be slow to
break behind the front, leaving only northern New England with the
likelihood of abundant sunshine.
</P>
<P>
   Sunshine will grace the upper Middle West, northern Plains and
northern Rockies as high pressure remains in place. Only in the
southern Rockies are isolated afternoon thundershowers associated
with the monsoon possible.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the West Coast States will be mainly sunny and
seasonably warm with the exception of low clouds and fog along the
immediate coast. Temperatures will range from near 70 at the coast
to the lower 100s in the deserts.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOCUS: PARCHED EUGENE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   School had only been out for a short time when the last
raindrops fell on Eugene, Ore. Tuesday marked a record 80th
consecutive day without measurable rain, a feat that has not
occurred since weather reports were first kept in 1890. Farther
north, in Portland, 45 days have transpired since the last showers
dampened the city, but this dry spell is only in 10th place of long
dry periods for Oregon's largest city. A large high pressure system
will give way late this week as a push of cold, moist air from the
North Pacific is likely end both dry periods during this coming
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-98 1810EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980915.0255 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6606 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECH-VISAS16-COX     09-15 0394
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-VISAS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HOUSE TO VOTE ON MORE VISAS FOR HIGH-SKILLED IMMIGRANTS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By CHRISTI HARLAN
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republican leaders in the House will try again
Thursday(cq) to win passage of a long-delayed increase in visas for
highly skilled foreign workers, House Majority Leader Dick Armey
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The promise of House action has kept high-tech lobbyists busy
during the last week, and they fanned out across Capitol Hill on
Tuesday trying to refocus House members' attention on an issue that
matters deeply to the computer companies and software firms that
have been complaining for months about shortages of engineers and
other specialists.
</P>
<P>
   At issue are H-1B visas, which allow companies to hire specially
skilled foreign workers for up to six years. This year's supply of
65,000 visas was supposed to last until Sept. 30, but was used up
by early May. Since then, Congress' efforts to create more visas
have stumbled over the insistence of the Clinton administration and
conservative Republicans in the House that the employers of foreign
workers be required to make more efforts to hire U.S. workers.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans worked out their differences in early August, but
Democratic support evaporated after President Clinton's top
advisers recommended that he veto any bill that did not require
employers to certify that they made substantial efforts to hire
U.S. workers and that no U.S. workers were laid off from jobs
filled by foreign workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought that we would bring that (legislation) to the floor
before the August recess, then the White House signaled the
Democrat members to vote against it,'' Armey said Tuesday. ``Our
vote count dissipated.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders and business groups, including the U.S.
Chamber of Commerce, now think they have enough votes in line to
pass an increase, which would raise the annual allotment of H-1B
visas to 95,000 beginning Oct. 1 and eventually reach 115,000 visas
in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've all worked hard, we think we've got it back together
and, hopefully, we'll get it passed,'' Armey said.
</P>
<P>
   The House bill is a compromise version of Senate legislation,
which passed in June.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
