<HEADER>
A6608 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECH-VISAS16-COX     09-15 0394
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-VISAS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HOUSE TO VOTE ON MORE VISAS FOR HIGH-SKILLED IMMIGRANTS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By CHRISTI HARLAN
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republican leaders in the House will try again
Thursday(cq) to win passage of a long-delayed increase in visas for
highly skilled foreign workers, House Majority Leader Dick Armey
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The promise of House action has kept high-tech lobbyists busy
during the last week, and they fanned out across Capitol Hill on
Tuesday trying to refocus House members' attention on an issue that
matters deeply to the computer companies and software firms that
have been complaining for months about shortages of engineers and
other specialists.
</P>
<P>
   At issue are H-1B visas, which allow companies to hire specially
skilled foreign workers for up to six years. This year's supply of
65,000 visas was supposed to last until Sept. 30, but was used up
by early May. Since then, Congress' efforts to create more visas
have stumbled over the insistence of the Clinton administration and
conservative Republicans in the House that the employers of foreign
workers be required to make more efforts to hire U.S. workers.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans worked out their differences in early August, but
Democratic support evaporated after President Clinton's top
advisers recommended that he veto any bill that did not require
employers to certify that they made substantial efforts to hire
U.S. workers and that no U.S. workers were laid off from jobs
filled by foreign workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought that we would bring that (legislation) to the floor
before the August recess, then the White House signaled the
Democrat members to vote against it,'' Armey said Tuesday. ``Our
vote count dissipated.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders and business groups, including the U.S.
Chamber of Commerce, now think they have enough votes in line to
pass an increase, which would raise the annual allotment of H-1B
visas to 95,000 beginning Oct. 1 and eventually reach 115,000 visas
in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've all worked hard, we think we've got it back together
and, hopefully, we'll get it passed,'' Armey said.
</P>
<P>
   The House bill is a compromise version of Senate legislation,
which passed in June.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
