<P>
   THE CLINTON IMPEACHMENT INQUIRY
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON _ WASHINGTON _ In his first meeting with reporters since
the Starr report was released, President Clinton will hold an
abbreviated news conference Wednesday with President Vaclav Havel
of the Czech Republic. As he prepared for that session, Clinton on
Tuesday vowed to help economically stricken farmers and to ensure
that U.S. military readiness remains high. (Deans, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   Editors: In a story distributed last week, Cox News Service
erroneously identified the author of the book, ``The Clinton
Syndrome,'' as Stanley Renshon. Renshon is not the author of the
book, and the views expressed in the story were incorrectly
ascribed to him. The views were expressed in an interview by Jerome
D. Levin, who is the author of the book. A corrected version of the
story follows.
</P>
<P>
   SEXADDICT-CORRECT _ WASHINGTON _ Even before details of
President Clinton's extramarital sexual activity were made public,
some mental health professionals have concluded that the cravings
that supposedly steamed up the Oval Office are those of a ``sex
addict.'' (Nesmith, Cox News Service 1000).
</P>
<P>
   MOVED in (w) Washington and (l) lifestyle categories.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-DEFENSE _ WASHINGTON _ With even Democratic leaders
warning that a legalistic, linguistic defense won't work on Capitol
Hill, President Clinton named a trusted team of attorneys and
lobbyists Tuesday with congressional ties to deal with the threat
of impeachment. To ``quarterback'' the response to Independent
Counsel Kenneth Starr's referral on the Monica Lewinsky affair,
Clinton picked Gregory B. Craig, who attended Yale Law School with
the president and First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton.(Dart, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-JURY _ WASHINGTON _ They are major players in the
biggest presidential investigation in a quarter-century, and yet
the role of the 23 grand jurors is barely visible in the report
released last week by Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr. For this
panel of ordinary Washington residents, whose names are kept
secret, the most crucial decisions are still ahead. After listening
to more than 70 witnesses, including the president of the United
States, as Starr built his case for his report to Congress on
possible impeachment of President Clinton, the grand jury could
soon begin handing down criminal indictments. (Malone, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-JUDICIARY _ WASHINGTON _ The Judiciary Committee that
will conduct any impeachment hearings is composed of diverse
factions likely to go in many different directions once the
questioning begins. We handicap the committee, looking at who will
likely to be the defenders to the end, the harshest critics and
those in between. (Carr, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-GADELEGATION _ WASHINGTON _ Now that Congress has had a
chance to read the Starr report, what are the members of the
Georgia delegation saying and what are their constituents telling
them. (Foskett, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CLASS _ ATLANTA _ Oglethorpe University in Atlanta is
sponsoring a class called ``Love, Sex and Politics: From
Aristophanes to President Clinton.'' We take notes. (Smith, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-BUSH _ AUSTIN _ Texas Gov. Bush speaks out about the
Clinton-Lewinsky scandal in a meeting with the Austin
American-Statesman editorial board. Story will be updated and
re-sent with comments from Bob Dole about values and leadership in
the 21st century. Dole has a 5 p.m. CDT press conference in San
Antonio and speaks to university students there at 8 p.m. CDT.
(Greenberger, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   TELCOM-CONGRESS _ WASHINGTON _ Congress may have to move soon to
foster competition in the nation's telephone markets, two key
senators said on Tuesday. After chairing a hearing on a spate of
new mega-sized telecommunications deals, Sen. Mike DeWine, R-Ohio,
said he would urge federal regulators to put the brakes on any
further consolidation in the phone business unless the government
can first ``guarantee that any mergers that are allowed will have
some clear pro-competitive benefits to consumers.'' (Glass, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   ADOPTION-RACE _ WASHINGTON _ Not enough is being done to make
sure states comply with a law that makes it illegal to use race as
a factor in placing children adoptive homes, witnesses told
Congress on Tuesday. (Monroe, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   REFUGEE _ Viep Le is the latest in a recent string of former
South Vietnamese POWs to settle in the Dayton area, with the
assistance of local churches. Story looks at hardships Le and his
family faced in Vietnam since the communist takeover, how they
eventually came to the U.S. and how Le feels about the U.S. taking
so long to rescue the South Vietnamese soldiers who often fought
side-by-side with American GIs. Story will include a box on how
local congregations can help in sponsoring other such immigrants.
(DeBrosse/Bennish, Dayton Daily News). 40. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   FLAFIRES-GEL _ JUPITER, Fla. _ Five years ago firefighter John
Bartlett had an idea about how to protect homes, utility poles,
timber, you name it, from advancing fires. He turned the idea into
a product _ Barricade fire gel. After it saved homes in July's
wildfires, the world took notice. (Reid, Palm Beach Post) WITH
PHOTO. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   UT-MINORITIES _ AUSTIN, Texas _ The University of Texas, trying
to build a diverse student body without affirmative action,
enrolled slightly more black and Hispanic freshmen this fall,
indicating that a law requiring state colleges to admit freshmen in
the top 10 percent of their high school class could be helping.
What is clear at UT is that a higher percentage of black and
Hispanic freshmen came from the ranks of the top 10 percent than
those enrolled in the past two years. (Roser, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
