<SLUG> BC-TV-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TBS BANKS ON `SEINFELD' RERUNS  
 EMMYS GET UNIMPRESSIVE RATINGS  
 LONGEST-RUNNING TV SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Might ``Seinfeld'' be the last great hit television show
produced by the broadcast networks?
</P>
<P>
   That possibility is one reason that Turner Broadcasting paid
more than $1 million per episode for the cable rerun rights to
``Seinfeld,'' even though TBS will not be able to carry the show
until four years from now _ and even though it will still be in
reruns on broadcast stations then.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to realize the scope of the hit that this show
is and the broadcast networks' inability to continue to generate
big, megahit shows like that,'' said TBS Superstation president
Bill Burke on Tuesday. ``This may be the last big hit sitcom to
come off the networks ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Burke based his comment partly on the erosion of broadcast
networks' prime-time audiences, which grow smaller as viewers
increasingly tune to cable networks as readily as to the
established broadcast networks, and partly on the broadcasters'
recent track record of not developing standout hit shows.
</P>
<P>
   Two other reasons for paying so handsomely for ``Seinfeld,''
Burke said, were the solid Nielsen ratings it has earned in
off-network syndication already, proving its continuing value, and
the fact that the show's humor isn't particularly topical.
</P>
<P>
   ``There aren't a lot of references to the present day,'' he
said. ``The only one I can think of is to George Steinbrenner.''
</P>
<P>
   He also pointed out that ``Seinfeld'' left NBC as the No. 1 show
on television and was only the third show in history to do that,
joining ``I Love Lucy'' and ``The Andy Griffith Show.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the deal stunned some television executives. The
show's syndicator, Columbia Tri-Star Television Distribution,
received not only $1 million per episode in licensing fee but also
two 30-second commercial spots in each episode to be shown by TBS,
spots that would be valued now in the vicinity of $300,000 a piece.
With 180 episodes, that could be worth at least $100 million more
to Columbia Tri-Star.
</P>
<P>
   And ``Seinfeld'' episodes will still be running in syndication
on broadcast stations when TBS's rights to run them start. (In New
York, Channel 11 has them until 2001, then Channel 5 has them for
five more years.) Many broadcast stations have ``Seinfeld'' rerun
rights until 2006.
</P>
<P>
   Still, TBS executives weren't the only ones who thought it was
worth it banking on ``Seinfeld'' to remain a valuable commodity
well into the next century; at least three other cable networks
also bid for the show.
</P>
<P>
   TBS also has rights to reruns of ``Home Improvement,''
``Friends,'' ``The Drew Carey Show'' and ``Roseanne,'' among
others. Burke said that adding ``Seinfeld'' to that lineup was part
of the cable network's ``ongoing pursuit of parity with the
broadcast networks.''
</P>
<P>
   Skeptics think it sounds more like parity with TVLand, the cable
network devoted to golden oldies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be if those shows were all 30 years old,'' Burke
said. ``But even in the year 2002, we fully expect `Friends' and
`Drew Carey' to still be on the networks. And `Seinfeld' would be
too if Jerry and the cast hadn't decided to move on and do
different things.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By LAWRIE MIFFLIN
</P>
<P>
   Blame It on Wise Guys
</P>
<P>
   Americans watch television in far bigger numbers and a lot more
often than they go to the movies or listen to record albums; but
that apparently does not translate into interest in seeing
television stars pick up awards.
</P>
<P>
   Or so it would seem from the less-than-stellar ratings for the
television industry's biggest award, the Emmy, which celebrated its
50th anniversary Sunday night with a party that, if not quite a
flop, was certainly far from the social event of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The ratings for the telecast, which NBC went to great pains to
turn into a special event this year, barely eclipsed the number
from last year's show, with a 13.6 rating this year compared with a
13.5 last year, when the show was broadcast by CBS. (This year a
rating point is worth a bit more, however, 994,000 homes, up from
980,000 homes last year.)
</P>
<P>
   Far more telling is this comparison: the last Oscar telecast, on
ABC, got a gigantic 34.9 rating. The Grammy Awards in February on
CBS scored a 17 rating. Even the once denigrated Golden Globe
Awards, which NBC has skillfully turned into a far more glittering
event, put the Emmy show to shame, with a 15.9 rating in January.
</P>
<P>
   Why is television's biggest award night so much less an event?
One reason may be sheer familiarity, on two levels. First, the
stars on the Emmy show are pretty much the same ones people see in
their living rooms every week. Second, the winners (and most of the
nominees) tend to be the exact same people every year.
</P>
<P>
   If this were ``Jeopardy,'' Kelsey Grammer would be a retired
champion by now. How many times do people really want to see Paul
Reiser have to stand up and kiss his co-star, Helen Hunt, winning
an award?
</P>
<P>
   Aside from an upset and surprise here and there (Andre Braugher
finally getting his due for ``Homicide,'' Garry Shandling winning
some long overdue recognition for writing ``Larry Sanders,'' David
Letterman re-emerging as a winner in the variety category), the
show is full of predictable moments and speeches from people who
gave pretty much the same speech several times before.
</P>
<P>
   With the other awards shows, the competition more or less leaves
the field rather than face the slaughter. With the Emmy Awards, the
networks not broadcasting the show that year (it rotates among the
four big networks) are expected not to drag out any heavy guns that
might embarrass the industry on its big award night. For the most
part, the other networks offer repeats as competition.
</P>
<P>
   But in the last two years, even under these restrictions, an
effective counterprogramming strategy has taken shape. Last year
Fox used a repeat of the action film ``True Lies'' and did some
serious damage to the Emmy show.
</P>
<P>
   Later a Fox executive called CBS to apologize for inadvertently
denting the award ratings, saying the intention was only to pick up
some of the male viewers known to be drifting to cable out of
disinterest in the Emmy show.
</P>
<P>
   But CBS apparently noticed how well the strategy worked and this
year scheduled a male-oriented film of its own, Martin Scorsese's
``Goodfellas,'' which also drew some male viewers away from the
Emmy show.
</P>
<P>
   Of course so did an NFL football game on ESPN. But one reason
the Emmy show also may have fared less well than NBC hoped was the
additional hour NBC added to try to underscore that this year's
show was an even bigger event than usual. The show ran from 7 to 11
p.m. instead of from 8 to 11. Some viewers apparently didn't get
the message. The show's lowest rating came in its first hour. But
the final hour, the Emmy show was even getting close to Golden
Globe territory.
</P>
<P>
   _ By BILL CARTER
</P>
<P>
   Si, No Repeats
</P>
<P>
   According to the Guinness Book of World Records, the
longest-running television series in history without a single
repeat episode is ``Sabado Gigante,'' the three-hour weekly variety
show, which has been a fixture on Univision, the Spanish-language
network, in the United States since the mid-1980s and in South
America since 1961.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it was not represented in the Museum of Television and
Radio, the nation's major television ``library,'' with branches in
New York and Los Angeles. This year, in honor of the 30th
anniversary of Channel 41, the Univision station in New York,
executives there decided to donate a wide array of Spanish-language
programming to the museum, including classic episodes of ``Sabado
Gigante.''
</P>
<P>
   The Univision network began in 1961, with San Antonio's KWEX
(also Channel 41, by coincidence) the first United States
affiliate. New York's Channel 41 joined in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   _ By LAWRIE MIFFLIN
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-98 1831EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
