<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6634 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONSUMER-SLOWDOWN-BOS     09-15 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMER-SLOWDOWN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLUGGISH AUGUST RETAIL SALES RAISE WARNING FLAG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sales at retail stores rose only mildly in August,
the government said Tuesday in a report that gave modest but not
compelling evidence that a slowdown in consumer spending is under
way.
</P>
<P>
   Economists are watching Americans' shopping habits closely these
days for signs that their free-spending ways are over. Many believe
that the volatile stock market and the global financial turmoil
will make people more wary of spending money, which would cause US
economic growth to slow. Consumer spending is responsible for about
two-thirds of US economic activity.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the Commerce Department said that retail sales rose 0.2
percent in August from the prior month, after falling a revised 0.6
percent in July.
</P>
<P>
   The August increase was less than many analysts expected.
However, some analysts said the numbers do not necessarily indicate
that a general slowdown in spending, or a poor Christmas sales
season, is at hand.
</P>
<P>
   Sluggish auto sales, possibly dampened by low inventory at
strike-addled General Motors, brought down the overall retail sales
figures. When autos are excluded, retail sales grew 0.3 percent in
August after rising 0.6 percent in July.
</P>
<P>
   Low inflation and cheap imports have made it hard for many
retailers to raise prices, which also dampen the increase in
overall sales.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, a late Labor Day this year meant that many
back-to-school shoppers who usually visit the stores in August
waited instead until September.
</P>
<P>
   ``That said, however, the general lackluster quality of August
is just a little more intense than we had anticipated,'' said Kurt
Barnard, president of Barnard's Retail Trend Report, a New Jersey
forecasting firm. ``We are essentially seeing a deceleration in
consumer spending.''
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, anecdotal evidence suggests that stores are
doing ``very well'' during this year's back-to-school season, said
Jon Hurst, president of the Retailers Association of Massachusetts.
``Is it way ahead of last year? I don't think so, but you have to
keep in mind that last year was a banner year from start to
finish,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``With inflation being so low, just meeting last year and
hopefully beating it is probably a good thing,'' Hurst said.
</P>
<P>
   The latest surveys show a slip in consumer confidence _ but from
record-high levels. The Conference Board, which tracks consumer
confidence nationally, recently said its index slipped in August to
133.1, down from 137.2 in July. The index had hit a 29-year peak of
138.2 in June.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, consumer confidence has also slipped slightly,
according to the Mass Insight-New England Economic Project
quarterly survey. The survey's index dropped to 122 in July from
129 in April, the second straight quarterly drop.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts said that consumers delayed their car purchases in
August because of a shaky stock market.
</P>
<P>
   The fall in stock prices ``was probably enough to explain the
drop in auto sales,'' William Wilson, an economist at Comerica
Inc., told Reuters. ``Autos are unlike most other consumer goods in
that their purchases can be deferred, and that's what probably
happened when we had the correction in equity prices.''
</P>
<P>
   But Barnard said that the up-and-down stock market and the Asian
financial crisis was not the major culprit in the spending
slowdown, though they might prompt wealthy shoppers to delay luxury
purchases.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Barnard blamed high consumer debt for the reported
shopping slowdown. People are spending nearly everything they earn
and more, he said, bringing total credit card debt to about $539
billion, up from $438 billion a year and a half ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are basically in the process of coming to our senses ...
and because of that people are beginning to curb their spending a
little bit,'' Barnard said.
</P>
<P>
   Several retail chains have reported lackluster sales gains or
declines in recent months. At Framingham-based TJX Cos., including
Marshalls, August sales rose 1 percent compared to the same month
last year at US stores open at least one year. Sales were up 7.1
percent at Saks, down 3.7 percent at Talbots, and down 0.7 percent
at the May department store chain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-98 1832EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980915.0266 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6643 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-LEWINSKY-BOS &LR;      09-15 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-LEWINSKY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SCANDAL'S IMPACT ON MIDEAST PEACE EFFORT WEIGHED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Just when the Israeli-Palestinian peace process
needs a firm US diplomatic hand, specialists said the Clinton
administration is too distracted by the threat of impeachment to
provide the strength to break an 18-month deadlock in the talks.
</P>
<P>
   US Mideast envoy Dennis Ross has been shuttling between both
sides over the last week to bring Palestinian and Israeli leaders
together on the next phase of Israeli troop withdrawals from the
West Bank. But both sides predicted Tuesday that Ross's trip would
end in failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems a failure, there hasn't been progress,'' said a
senior Israeli official. Added Palestinian Authority spokesman
Nabil Abu Rodayna, ``The effort has failed.''
</P>
<P>
   David Kimche, head of the Israel Council on Foreign Relations
and former director general of Israel's Foreign Ministry, said,
``The peace camps on both sides had been hoping that the Americans
would be a bit more insistent on seeing movement. But because of
what has happened in the White House, and the distractions in
dealing with it, there is the feeling on both sides that there will
be no such determination.''
</P>
<P>
   Ghassan Khatib, director of Jerusalem Media and Communication
Center and a former member of the Palestinian delegation that
produced the peace agreement, agreed that the Lewinsky scandal has
undercut hope for movement forward on the stalled peace process.
</P>
<P>
   ``It weakens the president and weakens his ability to apply the
pressure that is needed to push the process forward. So the
situation is worse than it has ever been,'' Khatib said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Netanyahu is making perfect use of this,'' he added. ``He
understands American politics very well. He senses that Clinton
cannot exert pressure on him, so I anticipate he will harden his
position further.''
</P>
<P>
   But some officials close to the talks, speaking on background,
maintained that the possibility of a breakthrough was still
possible. They suggested that the scandal could provide an added
incentive for the White House envoy to bring home a deal that could
trumpet Clinton's foreign policy and draw attention from the Monica
Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts of the peace process considered such comments
wishful thinking and remained largely pessimistic about the
possibility of any movement on the stalled talks.
</P>
<P>
   Five years after the peace accord was signed in Oslo, the
process is mired in mistrust by both sides.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has proposed a further withdrawal of Israeli
troops from 13.1 percent of the West Bank over three months.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians, who had anticipated a 30 percent withdrawal in
this phase of the peace process, agreed to the US proposal for 13
percent providing there was to be an additional phase of withdrawal
in the future. The Netanyahu government has refused to accept the
US plan, arguing that it did not provide adequate security
guarantees. The Israelis have also stated that this withdrawal
would be the final one before the so-called ``final status'' talks.
</P>
<P>
   Kimche said the continuing stalemate in the peace process poses
a threat to the region. If the deadlock continues, Palestinian
president Yasser Arafat has vowed to declare unilaterally a
Palestinian state by May of next year.
</P>
<P>
   The Israelis said such a declaration would be a breach of the
peace accord and would prompt them to respond militarily if
necessary. Analysts have predicted that the looming crisis could
result in open, armed conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a clock ticking toward May 1999, and Netanyahu knows
if there is not an agreement the scenarios that could unfold are
ominous. It is a time when all sides need movement forward,''
Kimche added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
