<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6657 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-DEFENSE16-COX     09-15 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-DEFENSE16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON ASSEMBLES DEFENSE TEAM FOR CONGRESS
 &HT;    480&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With even Democratic leaders warning that a
legalistic defense won't work on Capitol Hill, President Clinton
named a trusted team of attorneys and lobbyists with congressional
ties Tuesday to deal with the threat of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   To ``quarterback'' the effort, Clinton picked Gregory B. Craig,
who attended Yale Law School with the president and First Lady
Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Craig will report directly to Clinton and hold the title of
assistant to the president and special counsel. He is a former law
partner of David Kendall, Clinton's personal attorney, and worked
on Clinton's Whitewater defense team before going to the State
Department last year as Director of Policy and Planning last year.
</P>
<P>
   A veteran Washington attorney, Craig defended John Hinckley in
the 1983 attempted assassination of President Reagan. Hinckley was
found not guilty for reasons of insanity.
</P>
<P>
   Also joining the damage-control team is Steve Ricchetti and
Susan Brophy, two of Clinton's former lobbyists on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said Craig would coordinate the response to
Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr's referral on the Monica Lewinsky
affair. But the deep congressional experience of the new team
members suggested that their immediate goal would be to stop an
erosion of support among Democrats on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Chief of staff Erskine Bowles led presidential aides and lawyers
to the Capitol to join the weekly closed-door Democratic Senate
caucus. Afterward, Bowles gave an emphatic ``no'' when asked
whether any senator had called for Clinton to leave office, the
Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
   Normally talkative senators declined comment on the substance of
the meeting. ``We were just basically briefed,'' said Sen. Max
Cleland, D-Ga.
</P>
<P>
   However, another longtime Clinton backer joined a Democratic
chorus calling for the president to stop the semantic defense by
his lawyers, David Kendall and Charles Ruff. The lawyers insist
that while Clinton may have made misstatements to Starr's grand
jury, he technically did not commit perjury.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now is the time for the president to come clean and allow this
matter to be resolved,'' said Rep. Harold Ford, D-Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., and
House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., issued statements
criticized Clinton for relying on legal hair-splitting.
</P>
<P>
   But White House press secretary Mike McCurry said no shift in
strategy was planned.
</P>
<P>
   The president is ``not going to use any legalisms, and he said
that on Friday,'' said McCurry. ``His lawyers are going to defend
him against the narrow legal charge of perjury, if they need to.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Ruff represents the institution of the presidency as White
House legal counsel, and Mr. Kendall will continue to be the
president's primary attorney, representing him on the personal
matters that arise,'' McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The new members of the president's defense team have long ties
both to Clinton and to Democrats in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Craig, 53, graduated from Harvard University in 1967 and studied
at Cambridge University in England before going to Yale and
studying law with the Clintons, as well as with Kendall, his former
partner at the law firm of Williams &AMP; Connolly.
</P>
<P>
   He is a friend of John Podesta, the presidential aide expected
to become White House chief of staff when Bowles steps down at the
end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Craig is also close to the Kennedy political dynasty. He served
as a foreign policy adviser on the staff of Sen. Edward Kennedy,
D-Mass., from 1984 to 1988. After returning to Williams &AMP; Connolly,
he represented Kennedy in connection with the Palm Beach, Fla.,
rape trial of the senator's nephew, William Kennedy Smith. Two
year's after Smith's acquittal in 1992, Craig defended him in the
in aftermath of fight Smith had with bouncer in a Georgetown bar.
Smith pleaded no contest to assault charges and performed 100 hours
of community service.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Craig left his law practice after being recruited by
Madeleine Albright and Strobe Talbott to head the State Department
agency charged with taking a long-term, strategic view of foreign
policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a lot of expertise and a lot of wisdom,'' said McCurry.
</P>
<P>
   The other members are also familiar faces in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Ricchetti was Clinton's deputy assistant for legislative
affairs before leaving the White House last year to become a
lobbyist in private practice. During the 1996 presidential
campaign, he was one of those who portrayed Republican presidential
candidate Bob Dole in mock debates with Clinton in the 1996
campaign. Earlier, Ricchetti was executive director of the
Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee.
</P>
<P>
   _ Susan Brophy was also a Clinton lobbyist on Capitol Hill until
this year, when she moved overseas with her husband, Gerald
McGowan, the U.S. ambassador to Portugal and Clinton's former
roommate at Georgetown University. Clinton introduced Brophy to
McGowan, a widower with five children, on a presidential trip to
Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Brophy's career in Democratic politics stretches over 20 years
and includes work for former Lt. Gov. Thomas P. O'Neill III of
Massachusetts and in Michael Dukakis's 1988 presidential campaign.
Brophy was the White House point person in the unsuccessful
confirmation fight over Clinton's appointment of former Gov.
William Weld of Massachusetts, a Republican, to be ambassador to
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
