<SLUG> BC-WORKING-WOMEN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFERING BALANCE AS A BENEFIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILIAN MINCER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last week, Leasa E. Huffman needed to take her son to the doctor
because of an ear infection.
</P>
<P>
   It took Huffman, assistant vice president of the sales and
marketing support department at Security Benefit, about 10 minutes
to pick him up from the company child-care center and take him to
the on-site doctor.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, when Hallmark Cards Inc. employee Andrea Zeorlin
needed child care, she saved hours by calling Family Care Choices,
a child- and elder-care resource and referral agency.
</P>
<P>
   Programs such as these earned Hallmark Cards, Security Benefit
and St. Luke's Hospital a spot on /{Working Mother/} magazine's
best 100 companies for working moms.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, family friendly policies are the right thing to do,
but what these three have proved is that it's the only thing to do
if you want to attract and retain the best employees in a tight
labor market.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Howard R. Fricke, chairman and chief executive officer
of Security Benefit. Sure, his 3-year-old grandson attends the
company's day-care center, which has a sliding fee scale.
</P>
<P>
   But the reason the company has so many of these benefits is that
``it helps our bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It may cost the company something in the short run,'' he said.
``But by providing fair and reasonable benefits, we're able to
attract better people.''
</P>
<P>
   And the company is able to train and keep people such as
Huffman, who started as a secretary and is completing her MBA with
company tuition reimbursements.
</P>
<P>
   She has had calls from headhunters, but ``the family orientation
of the firm makes it the best place to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Zeorlin's flexible schedule and the programs she has
used, including sick-child care, have kept her at Hallmark.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like if I hadn't had the opportunity to work a
part-time schedule, I wouldn't be in the work force today,'' said
Zeorlin, work//family specialist at Hallmark.
</P>
<P>
   At St. Luke's, family friendly policies that include a
child-care center, flexible scheduling and part-time benefits have
enabled the hospital to attract and retain employees, something
especially difficult in many medical fields. Turnover of its
nursing staff is less than 7 percent, compared with a general
turnover rate of 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're able to recruit and retain high-quality staff,
you're able to provide high-quality care,'' said Patricia A. Soper,
senior operating officer for St. Luke's.
</P>
<P>
   St. Luke's, Hallmark and Security Benefit have proved that
people are more productive and more loyal if they work in places
that enable them to balance their work and family lives.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
