<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6661 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUSEWELLE-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      09-15 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUSEWELLE-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEWARD'S FOLLY TURNED OUT TO BE A BARGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By C.W. GUSEWELLE  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEWARD, Alaska _ When the Dutch slickered the Indians out of the
island of Manhattan in 1626, they paid for it with pots and pans,
axes and bolts of cloth.
</P>
<P>
   But by 1867, when Secretary of State William H. Seward
negotiated the purchase of Alaska from the Russians, sweetheart
deals like that weren't available anymore.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians had all the pots they needed, so he had to show
them the cash _ $7.2 million, which back then must have been
serious money. Critics and nitpickers called it Seward's folly.
</P>
<P>
   With a total area of 591,004 square miles, Alaska is larger than
all but 37 of the present 190 nations in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Seward had added to the holdings of the United States a
territory not only rich in valuable furbearers, fish and other
wildlife, but also underlain by vast mineral treasure _ gold,
copper, oil.
</P>
<P>
   And that's not even to mention the breathtaking beauty of what
would become, in 1959, our 49th state. In other words, at a price
of just under two pennies an acre, it was a folly too good to pass
up.
</P>
<P>
   Named for the man that struck the bargain, this town on the east
side of the Kenai Peninsula is a stopping-off place for cruise
ships. In fact, one was in the harbor when we drove down from
Anchorage yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   The immense vessel, larger by a good deal than any structure in
the town itself, seemed an odd sort of behemoth, preposterously
beached.
</P>
<P>
   Seward is young _ as all of Alaska is, in a sense, a youngish
place. Established in the early years of this century, it has the
look and feel of a community still inventing itself.
</P>
<P>
   Its population, about 1,800 in the 1980 census, has nearly
doubled to 3,500 today, mirroring the increase across the state.
During the decade of the '80s, the number of Alaskans grew by 37
percent, to 607,000.
</P>
<P>
   That computes to slightly more than one person per square mile,
although, since well over half of them are concentrated in the
three largest communities of Anchorage, Fairbanks and Juneau, many
of those square miles are empty indeed.
</P>
<P>
   Seward is the departure point for excursions by boat into Kenai
Fjords National Park, a magnificent area of brilliant waters,
looming cliffs and glacier-carved canyons. We went on that outing
today, and after a spell of foul weather the morning cleared and
warmed.
</P>
<P>
   There was, we were told, a fair chance of seeing whales. And,
indeed, whales did present themselves _ a small pod of orcas, or
killer whales, and one solitary humpback.
</P>
<P>
   They weren't breaching or sporting or crooning as whales are
sometimes said to do. These were just cruising sedately,
occasionally blowing. But a whale's a whale, and we were mighty
glad to see them just the same.
</P>
<P>
   Also there were otters, sea lions, seals, cormorants, eagles
wheeling overhead, and on the high cliffsides white specks that
were alleged to be sheep or goats.
</P>
<P>
   A splendid shore lunch of grilled salmon broke the journey. And
after a visit to Holgate glacier and a bit more exploring among the
austere rock formations beyond the mouth of the bay, we turned
north again, back toward Seward, encountering the cruising orcas
once more on the way.
</P>
<P>
   We rode outside on the boat's upper deck, and the day was
perfection.
</P>
<P>
   /{``Otter!''/} someone would cry out then.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone would rush together to the rail on that side, and there
would come to mind those tragedies you read about of capsizing
Asian ferries. But our boat was a sturdy one and hardly listed at
all.
</P>
<P>
   Puffins especially interested us. We'd seen them the evening
before in their enormous glass-walled tank at the Alaska SeaLife
Center, a wonderful research and educational facility that, alone,
would make the trip to Seward worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   The puffin is a comical-looking bird, black with a white head
and a ludicrously oversized orange beak. Those at the SeaLife
Center share the tank with their plainer relatives, the murres.
</P>
<P>
   Both are gifted divers, able to reach considerable depth in
their search for food. But they do not swim underwater in any
ordinary sense. They actually /{fly/} below the surface _ graceful
wingbeats propelling them through the watery medium exactly as if
it were air.
</P>
<P>
   We'd stood in front of that glass wall for most of a half-hour,
marveling at Nature's virtuosity: to have created birds as agile,
as at home, under the sea as above it. So it was interesting to see
puffins in their true environment, riding the light chop of open
water, then plunging below to hunt.
</P>
<P>
   It's evening, now, though not yet dark. And after a good dinner
at a restaurant on a woodland road beyond the edge of town, we've
walked down from our lodging to look a last time across the water
at the mountains rearing on the bay's far side.
</P>
<P>
   The air is bluing, and the salmon fishermen out in small boats
are motoring back in toward shore.
</P>
<P>
   A rising breeze comes off the water, sea-scented and fresh. It
reminds us that we have been three whole days away from the
salacious news _ three days without hearing the names Monica and
Linda and Ken even once spoken.
</P>
<P>
   I can forgive Bill Clinton much. But it's hard to excuse him for
letting those three unsavory characters become fixtures in our
lives.
</P>
<P>
   People here are concerned with real things, though. They have
fish to catch, and winter wood to get in. So the scandal seems not
to be of overpowering interest.
</P>
<P>
   We have another two weeks of this blessed relief. There's no
knowing, at the end of it, how refreshed and cleansed we'll be.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
