r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-DEMOCRATS-KAN     09-15 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-DEMOCRATS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEADING DEMOCRATS URGE FORGIVENESS BUT HARBOR ANGER AGAINST
CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ While leading Democrats are urging forgiveness and
understanding for President Clinton's behavior in the Monica
Lewinsky scandal, they also harbor a growing sense of anger over
the likely damage he has done to the party.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's brought shame on the office,'' said Sen. Bob Kerrey of
Nebraska, one of several congressional Democrats to make the rounds
of the television talk shows Sunday. ``He's let his friends down.
He's let the nation down.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Rep. David Bonior of Michigan, the second-ranking Democrat
in the House: ``Members of our own party are very angry at the
president, and the American people are very angry at the
president.''
</P>
<P>
   But even as these lawmakers scorched him, an effort to push
censure as an alternative to impeachment appeared under way. A
``public rebuke,'' Bonior said.
</P>
<P>
   The talk in Democratic circles seemed to be that independent
counsel Kenneth Starr's report did not deliver the ``fatal blow''
for impeachment. Several Democrats said that, while laden with
lurid sexual detail, it did not offer anything substantially new
about the president's involvement with his much younger White House
subordinate.
</P>
<P>
   Still, regardless of Clinton's fate, many Democrats are
resigning themselves for the worst, come November. If the
president's televised admission last month of his extramarital
affair didn't put a chill in their hopes to avoid a possible
electoral bloodbath, the Starr report was like an arctic blast.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a feeling that all this hard work is down the
drain,'' said an aide to a senior Democrat in Congress. ``Just a
couple of months ago, there was a good possibility that we could
pick up enough votes to recapture the House and there was
absolutely no expectation that we would lose many seats in the
Senate. And we had great issues in the patients' bill of rights and
the minimum wage and education programs. Now that's all but
conceded that it's not going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   But they plan to press ahead. Senate Democrats hope for a vote
this week on a minimum wage increase, and they plan events on
managed care. The president, accompanied by Vice President Al Gore
and leading congressional Democrats, also will hold unity rallies
this week in New York and Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not happy,'' said Joan Menard, chairwoman of the
Massachusetts Democratic Party and president of the Association of
State Democratic Chairs. ``But he is the president, and he has been
our leader. I think most of us are very loyal people and we will
stand by the president.''
</P>
<P>
   A breach between Clinton and the members of his own party in
Congress is nothing new. Though known for his network of friends,
the president has never had smooth relations with the Democrats on
Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has never developed strong personal friendships with
members of Congress,'' a White House aide familiar with Capitol
Hill politics said of the president. ``It's been based on
dealmaking, and I think it's a double-edged sword. Part of what has
made him effective is part of what could hurt him now as
president.''
</P>
<P>
   Many blame him for a number of problems, including making House
Democrats cast costly votes to no avail _ such as the proposed
energy tax in 1993 that Clinton abandoned when the measure got to
the Senate. And many Democrats have never forgiven him for the
Democratic debacle in the 1994 when they lost control of both the
House and Senate.
</P>
<P>
   He also served as the leader of the ``New Democrats,'' a group
of political activists and thinkers dissatisfied with traditional
Democratic politics who were looking for an alternative to
off-the-rack liberalism.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton pushed the North American Free Trade Agreement _
anathema to labor and its Democratic allies in Congress. He signed
a welfare reform bill that many Democrats thought was too
stringent. And he introduced the word ``triangulation'' to the
political lexicon, that is staking out ground away from his own
party, as well as the GOP, to gain public support.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president's pursuit of his legislative agenda in a
Republican Congress requires a level of conciliation with
Republicans, which makes it harder for Democrats to make issues as
sharp as they want them to be,'' said Howard Paster, a former
congressional lobbyist for the Clinton White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Clinton was more conservative than the House
Democratic leadership and more conservative than most of the
members of the Democratic caucus,'' said Jim Slattery, a former
Democratic congressman from Kansas. ``There was a begrudging
respect for Clinton's political skills, but there was a lot of
skepticism about his political philosophy from the liberal
Democrats.''
</P>
<P>
   Now there's skepticism about Clinton's legal strategy, which
still holds fast to the assertion that his testimony in the Paula
Jones case where he denied sexual relations with Monica Lewinsky
was accurate.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Democratic Leader Thomas Daschle on Monday urged Clinton
not to continue ``the legal jousting that serves no constructive
purpose.'' He said people ``have grown inpatient with hairsplitting
over legal technicalities.''
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt of Missouri agreed,
saying, ``The considered judgment of the American people is not
going to rise or fall on the fine distinctions of a legal argument
but on straight talk and the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   That kind of talk within Clinton's own party this week shows the
White House can expect Democrats on the Hill to push only so hard
for the censure idea in the face of more political sacrifice for
their president.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should not rule out any action to meet public demand for a
prompt, appropriate conclusion (in) the public interest,'' Daschle
said, leaving open the possibility of an impeachment inquiry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
