<HEADER>
A6666 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KANSAS-WINERIES-KAN &LR;      09-15 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KANSAS-WINERIES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM THE GRAPEVINES: KANSAS HOME TO SEVEN WINERIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE CARROLL  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUDORA, Kan. _ Think Kansas and drinking, and you might think of
Carry A. Nation, the temperance crusader who smashed illegal
saloons with a hatchet. Or you might recall Vern Miller, the
attorney general who in the early 1970s warned airlines not to
serve drinks as they flew over the state.
</P>
<P>
   For many, Kansas has a conservative reputation when it comes to
alcohol. Perhaps that's because Kansas was the first state to ban
alcohol, 40 years before the national Prohibition took effect.
Perhaps it's because in Kansas, unlike Missouri, people still can't
buy a bottle of wine or a six-pack of beer on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But 120 years ago, Kansas was one of the country's biggest wine
producers. And now, decades after the end of Prohibition,
winemakers finally are making a comeback in the Sunflower State.
</P>
<P>
   Seven wineries have sprung up in Kansas since the state
legalized commercial wineries in 1983. That's not many, compared
with Missouri, which has more than 30. But wine-backers in Kansas
think the fledgling industry has grown enough to warrant the
initiation of the first wine-judging contest at the state fair in
Hutchinson.
</P>
<P>
   It will be at 6 p.m. Wednesday in the Pride of Kansas Building.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we want is just to let people know we are in Kansas and
that the wine industry is starting up in Kansas and to look us
up,'' said Greg Shipe of Eudora, who runs the Davenport Winery
north of Kansas 10 with his wife, Charlee Glinka.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, letting people know the wineries are around is what the
contest is all about.
</P>
<P>
   ``So few people in the state even know you can grow grapes in
Kansas,'' said David Ross, a spokesman for the Kansas Grape Growers
&AMP; Winemakers Association, which is sponsoring the contest. ``People
just don't realize it's even possible here.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, in 1880, Kansas was one of the nation's top 10
wine-producing states, said John Brewer, the owner of Wildwood
Cellars in Mulvane, and the president of the state's winemakers
association. Kansas had more than 7,000 acres of grapes, he said.
</P>
<P>
   That year, however, Kansas became the first state to ban
alcohol. Its vineyards were neglected or torn down. The national
Prohibition was lifted in 1933, but Kansas did not legalize alcohol
until 1949. It was one of the last states to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just taken us a long time to understand that wine is not
a sinful thing,'' Brewer said.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas lawmakers didn't legalize commercial wineries until 1983,
some 20 years after wineries were legalized in Missouri. That's why
Missouri is further along in its wine-producing efforts, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri also had a prosperous wine industry before Prohibition.
Its comeback began in 1965 when Jim and Betty Held began making
wine again at the Stone Hill Winery in Hermann. The winery, which
originally opened in 1837, was the second largest in the United
States before the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the winery offers tours every 20 minutes and a restaurant
where visitors can order wine by the glass. Stone Hill produces
158,000 gallons of wine a year, more than any other winery in
Missouri, said Patty Held-Uthlaut, who helps runs the family
business.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Kansas' largest winery, Fields of Fair Winery,
produces 33,000 gallons a year, said Sue Harris, a winery
spokeswoman. Fields of Fair opened in Paxico in 1988 as the first
licensed winery in Kansas. It has a deli and a gift shop, and many
travelers on Interstate 70 west of Topeka stop in, Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Midwest is just not as attached to wine as other areas,''
Harris said, explaining why wineries are catching on slowly in
Kansas. ``(Midwesterners) maybe have a glass of wine occasionally,
as opposed to people who regularly have wine with dinner.''
</P>
<P>
   The winery run by Glinka, 51, and Shipe, 46, is the state's
newest. They got into growing grapes by chance.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, while visiting Kansas State University officials to
talk about a blight on their pears, Glinka saw a bunch of grapes on
trellises.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `...Aren't these pretty?' '' Glinka recalled. ``I
wanted to plant some.''
</P>
<P>
   Shipe was against the idea. He thought they had enough to do on
their 160-acre farm. They already were growing apples, pears,
peaches and soybeans, among other crops.
</P>
<P>
   So they started out small, with table grapes. Eventually, they
planted varieties. By 1993, they were producing so many grapes that
they tried making wine.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, they were picking up ribbons in amateur contests in
Kansas. Last year, they won first place in an international amateur
contest in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of our friends and relatives had been drinking this stuff
and saying, `Wow, this is really good. When can we buy some from
you?' '' Glinka said.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago in August, they obtained a commercial license. Sales
are good so far, they said. Their wines include Aurore, a dry
white, Norton, a dry red, and Steuben, a sweet red. Visitors can
taste before they buy. (Call the winery at 785-542-2278 for store
hours.)
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the two won first in a statewide commercial
contest for their Foch, a French hybrid that produces a dry red.
</P>
<P>
   The orchard has five acres of grapes and 13 varieties. It's
expected to produce 1,000 gallons of wine this year.
</P>
<P>
   Shipe and Glinka hope their winery will grow. They'd like to get
a financial return for all the hours they spend pruning and
picking.
</P>
<P>
   Ross said he expected that the number of wineries in Kansas
would grow slowly, perhaps by one or so a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's slower taking on than I think it did in Missouri,'' he
said. ``It's not the ground, really, it's more of a political
climate and a tradition.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
