<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6675 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-MILLER-THEATER-ART     09-15 1071
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MILLER-THEATER-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONCERT SEASON AS CRUCIBLE, NOT A BOUQUET TO THE PAST 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By ALLAN KOZINN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Imagine that you've just been put in charge of a
680-seat concert hall that in recent years has presented a season
balanced between new-music concerts and standard repertory recitals
and chamber music. When you finish sketching out your first season
of about 60 performances, you have a handful of concerts that cover
the 14th through 18th centuries, virtually every flavor of
20th-century music, from Serialism and Minimalism to art-rock and
1960s vintage soul _ but not a single work by Bach, Mozart,
Beethoven, Schubert, Chopin, Schumann, Liszt or Brahms.
</P>
<P>
   Will you get away with it?
</P>
<P>
   ``It might be true that in other places I wouldn't,'' said
George Steel, the 31-year-old executive director of the Miller
Theater at Columbia University, whose first season fits that
description.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if you can make the season work, you can do it this
way. It's really a question of where your own priorities are, and
my priorities lie in doing things that I'm passionate about, and
that just aren't the scope in this city otherwise.''
</P>
<P>
   Steel raised the curtain on his season last night with a fully
staged production of Viktor Ullmann's ``Kaiser von Atlantis,'' an
anti-Hitler satire composed in the Theresienstadt concentration
camp, and a centerpiece in the recent revival of works by composers
who were killed by the Nazis. In this opera, a mad king wages a war
so brutal and unrelenting that Death becomes disgusted and goes on
strike, refusing to allow the wounded to die until the king agrees
to die first. There are also performances tomorrow evening and on
Friday and Saturday nights.
</P>
<P>
   Other highlights of the Miller prospectus include Shirish
Korde's ``Rasa,'' a monodrama for soprano, chamber orchestra and
electronic tape, about a woman who moves to the United States from
India and must negotiate the cultural differences, and
``Ravenshead,'' a rock-based work by Steven Mackey and Rinde Eckert
about the ill-fated 1968 attempt of the Englishman Donald Crowhurst
to sail around the world solo.
</P>
<P>
   There are celebrations of Ned Rorem's 75th and Elliott Carter's
90th birthdays, and a concert of music by Marc-Andre Dalbavie, a
young French composer whose works have made waves recently in
Europe. And a series called ``Opulent Music'' looks at what Steel
describes as ``an alternative history of 20th-century music.'' It
includes works by composers from Debussy and Poulenc to Messiaen
and Takemitsu, whose styles touch on Impressionism and various
forms of expanded tonality and musical exoticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want people to look at this theater and expect to see
the entire world encompassed in it,'' said Steel. ``We do a lot of
different things here, but I don't feel the need to do redundant
programming. In other words, this is not about museum style, it's
about trying to make new things. And it's a laboratory, a space
where we can do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Steel, whose oval wire-rimmed glasses give him an air of
seriousness that he likes to undercut with such informalities as
calling people of either sex, and of any age, ``babe,'' and
slipping freely into 20-something colloquialisms, came to Columbia
after working as a managing producer at the 92nd Street Y. There,
he collaborated on programming and scriptwriting with Michael
Barrett, prepared chamber orchestra arrangements of symphonic works
(most notably Leonard Bernstein's ``Songfest'') and conducted part
of a Penderecki concert with the composer in attendance.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, though, Steel's work before Columbia has been singing.
As a child in Washington Grove, a suburb of Washington, he attended
the St. Alban's School, a choir school associated with the
Washington Cathedral, where he sang in five services a week _ first
as a treble, later as a countertenor _ in its men and boys choir.
He also studied the piano and started composing before he was 10;
some of his more recent works are in the Cathedral choir's
repertory, and he had a septet performed at the 92nd Street Y.
</P>
<P>
   After he left St. Alban's _ he said he was expelled for
neglecting his academic studies in favor of music _ he attended the
American Conservatory in Chicago. He taught for two and a half
years at the St. Augustine School of the Arts in the Bronx, then
returned to Washington and studied briefly at the University of
Maryland before transferring to Yale. After he graduated in 1994,
he moved to New York and became a freelance singer.
</P>
<P>
   He still sings: this summer he was the solo bass in performances
of Beethoven's Mass in C in Beirut, conducted by Peter Phillips of
the Tallis Scholars. He is also conducting, and possibly singing
in, one of his Columbia concerts, a program in May of choral works
by the 16th-century English composer Robert Parsons. That concert,
at St. Paul's Chapel on the Columbia campus, is one of several that
Steel has taken outside Miller Theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think when the theater reopened after its renovation in
1988,'' Steel said, ``the idea was to put Miller on the map, and
there may have been a fear that if the Columbia connection was
emphasized, Miller would be buried. I believe that the more the
theater looks like a doorway through which people can come and
experience Columbia, the more successful it will be. And having
concerts in spaces with particular acoustical properties is a
marvelous way to get people in the door.''
</P>
<P>
   Steel seems to have considered not only acoustics, but also
atmosphere in matching programs to spaces. Miller Theater, with its
sleek interior that makes it almost ideal for new-music programs,
would be a sterile place for early music. St. Paul's is better
suited to it, so besides the Parsons program, Steel is presenting
the Huelgas Ensemble's program of 14th- and 15th-century music at
the chapel in April. A concert in the chapel's own organ series,
Michael Bower's reading of Ned Rorem's ``Quaker Reader,'' in
October, will be linked to a celebration of Rorem's birthday by the
Lark Quartet, the pianist Michael Boriskin and the flutist Paul
Lustig Dunkel at Miller a few days later.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the palazzolike Casa Italiana, at 117th Street and
Amsterdam Avenue, is to be used for a performance by the Baroque
ensemble Louis Louis and a concert of piano works composed in Italy
during World War II. And for a performance by Pauline Oliveros and
her Deep Listening Band _ a group that mixes modern Western
instruments with such exotic horns as the Australian aboriginal
didjeridu _ Steel is using the rotunda of Low Library.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pauline Oliveros grooves in these larger spaces,'' Steel said.
``And St. Paul's Chapel is a venue that's on campus, and that we
should use. How many places have that kind of scenario?''
</P>
<P>
   Since he took the job last October, Steel has immersed himself
in the history of Columbia's concert life. If a visitor to the
theater happens to mention works like Virgil Thomson's ``Mother of
Us All,'' Benjamin Britten's ``Paul Bunyan'' or Charles Ives'
``Central Park in the Dark'' or ``The Unanswered Question,'' Steel
will stop them, point to the stage and say: ``Here! Had its
premiere right here!'' And sitting behind his cluttered desk, in an
office just outside the theater's balcony, he proffers a stack of
yellowing program booklets from the 1940s in which one finds early
performances of works by Copland, Barber, Bernstein, Otto Luening,
David Diamond and Jack Beeson, as well as Pete Seeger, who is
listed in a 1948 folk concert as a ``topical ballad singer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They set a pretty serious precedent,'' Steel said. ``It's
hard, when you push the new-music envelope all the time, to look
back and say OK, here are the pieces we've done. But there's an
amazing track record here.''
</P>
<P>
   Steel's new-music plans include a series called New Music
October, which includes the Sonic Boom Festival that the hall has
presented in recent years. It begins with a New York New Music
Ensemble program split between Donald Martino and Matthew
Rosenbaum, and also includes a League of Composers/ISCM concert of
works by Ursula Mamlok and Roger Sessions, a program in which the
Ahn Trio will play world premieres by John Musto, Eric Ewazen,
Kenji Bunch and Michael Nyman, and a recital by Bruce Brubaker of
piano works by Philip Glass, John Cage and John Adams, with live
video by Ian Benton.
</P>
<P>
   The Rorem and Carter celebrations and concerts devoted fully to
George Crumb and Arvo Paert concerts are also part of the October
series, as is a Brecht tribute by Frigg, a German art-rock band.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted our new-music concerts to focus on single composers
where possible,'' Steel said. ``If an audience hears a concert with
one work by composer X, who they've never heard of, and they don't
like it, then they think they don't like composer X. But if they
hear several works, they may like one and dislike another, but
they'll get a more complete picture of the composer.''
</P>
<P>
   There is also plenty of chamber opera, once plentiful at
Columbia but absent in recent decades. Steel is intent on restoring
it, this year in the form of the Ullmann, Korde and Mackey works.
Already on the books for next year is an Offenbach rarity, ``Le
Voyage Dans la Lune,'' which will be presented as a multimedia
paean to the space program. The score and parts _ most of them
handwritten, from the original 1875 production _ arrived from Paris
a few weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every season is a test,'' Steel said, returning to the
question of whether a season devoted mostly to novelties will fly.
``You sit back, you watch the ticket sales, you feel the audience
reaction, you talk to the performers. If nobody shows up, will I do
things differently? Yeah. But I'll do things differently next year
anyway.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-98 1851EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
