<HEADER>
A6693 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-HEALTH-BOS &LR;      09-15 0517
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-HEALTH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEXUALLY TRANSMITTED DISEASES DOWN IN BAY STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Sexually transmitted diseases have been declining
dramatically in Massachusetts, with gonorrhea in 1997 at its lowest
reported level since 1959 and syphilis and chlamydia dropping as
well, according to new data released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the Department of Public Health reported only
somewhat encouraging news on cancer, showing that from 1990 to 1995
(the most recent year for which cancer data are available), the
incidence of several types of cancer rose _ partly from better,
earlier diagnoses _ and death rates remained stable or dropped
slightly.
</P>
<P>
   Better screening, safer sex behavior and use of condoms
apparently have caused the drop in STDs. At the same time, improved
screening and detection are major reasons the apparent incidence of
cancer has risen compared to 1990, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Among several findings in two reports presented to the public
health commission Tuesday:
</P>
<P>
   _The 2,077 new cases of gonorrhea reported in 1997 represent the
smallest number since 1959.
</P>
<P>
   _Compared to 1990, syphilis has dropped 64 percent, to a rate of
1 case per 9,090 residents, and chlamydia _ which can, when
untreated, make women infertile or cause ectopic pregnancies _ has
fallen 45 percent, to 1 per 819 residents.
</P>
<P>
   _Health officials said they need to further improve education
efforts in minority communities, where gonorrhea and chlamydia are
disproportionately high. Compared to white males, black males have
102 times higher rates of gonorrhea and Latino males 37 times
higher, and compared to white females, chlamydia rates are 14 times
higher among black females and 9 times higher among Latina females.
</P>
<P>
   _The overall incidence of cancer _ how many people have the
disease, not how many are diagnosed during the year _ rose 4.1
percent from 1990 to 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Prostate cancer incidence soared 42.8 percent in men, largely
because of more widespread screening for the disease, while lung,
bladder, and colorectal cancers dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Among women, lung cancer incidence soared 15.6 percent, to a
rate of one in every 2,150 women. Breast, ovarian, and uterine
cancers were all up by smaller percentages.
</P>
<P>
   Public Health Commission members Albert Sherman and Bertram A.
Yaffe expressed irritation over the fact that most Bay State
hospitals are failing to provide data on how many people they
diagnose with different cancers. They urged health commissioner
Howard K. Koh to determine whether he could make reporting
compulsory.
</P>
<P>
   ``They make up so many excuses _ they're understaffed,
overworked, underpaid,'' said state Cancer Registry director Susan
T. Gershman.
</P>
<P>
   The registry depends on getting data from 84 acute-care
hospitals to track cancer rates. In the last year, fewer than 1 in
4 fully complied, and 1 in 7 totally ignored requests for data. Koh
called that performance unacceptable, saying ``this information is
too valuable'' for hospitals to fail to report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
