<SLUG> BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BABY ADVICE CAN BE A LOT OF BABBLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - As I write this, I am looking across a living room
strewn with devices designed to calm a crying baby, or at least
soothe her little nerves a bit.
</P>
<P>
   The battery-powered swing _ no winding necessary! _ is silent.
</P>
<P>
   The vibrating battery-powered chair (``That chair is
quivering!'' a worried friend recently noted) sits still.
</P>
<P>
   The contraption in which you lay the baby on the floor and she
plays with objects hanging from a couple of crossed rods lies
folded and snapped shut on the couch.
</P>
<P>
   And the baby? She is sitting contentedly in her stroller. We
aren't going for a stroll. We haven't returned from one. It's just
the only place she'll sit and not cry.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment. But until the moment passes, that's where she'll
stay.
</P>
<P>
   Still a rookie parent, I'm catching on quickly. Before our
daughter was born, my wife and I read lots of books, all of them
full of good advice and priceless wisdom. We talked to lots of
parents. Lots of friends and relatives offered plenty of
well-meaning advice. We watched other parents in action whenever we
could, usually anonymously in malls and the like.
</P>
<P>
   From all of this, I learned the most important lesson so far:
</P>
<P>
   Don't pay any attention to any of it. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
By the book
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A prenatal omen should have told me this. My wife and I were in
one of those gigantic chain bookstores, browsing in the baby- and
child-care section (rivaled only by the self-help section for sheer
number of goofy titles) when we heard a commotion.
</P>
<P>
   Making a high-volume exit from the children's reading room was a
little girl, maybe 3 years old, steaming toward the cash register
and shrieking in no uncertain terms that ``THIS IS MY BOOK! MY
BOOK! MY BOOK!''
</P>
<P>
   I perked up when I saw, following her (but not so close as I
would have liked, which is to say, not within muzzling distance),
the girl's father. Aha. Finally, a good chance to see how a parent
would handle a real-life temper tantrum. As he ambled along, he
spoke in a quiet, polite tone of voice that made him sound as if he
were asking his boss for a raise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Margaret, is this the type of behavior Daddy rewards?''
</P>
<P>
   ``THIS IS MY BOOK! MY BOOK! MY BOOK!''
</P>
<P>
   Who taught this guy to negotiate, Neville Chamberlain?
</P>
<P>
   Actually, I'll bet he learned his technique from a baby-rearing
book. Although you can glean plenty of good information from any of
them _ I especially like the part where Dr. Spock assures you that
if you forget to support your infant's floppy head for even a
second, her head won't fall off and roll down the stairs _ you can
also drive yourself batty with contradictions. &QL; 
 &QL; 
What would Joe do?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Let the baby sleep in your bed, one book says. (begin ital)
Never (end ital) let the baby sleep in your bed, another warns.
Always rush to a crying baby. Let the baby cry it out.
</P>
<P>
   It's like listening to Joe Theismann's color analysis on ESPN's
NFL coverage _ occasionally it's interesting, but when you put it
all together, it doesn't make any sense.
</P>
<P>
   The same thing is true of the advice that friends, relatives and
neighbors offer. They mean well, of course, but that doesn't make
your head spin any less when the baby is screaming and you're
remembering how one person told you this means she needs to be fed
and another said it means she's been fed too much and a third said
you better put her down before you spoil her _ she's never going to
get into a good college if you cater to her every whim.
</P>
<P>
   And somewhere in the recesses of your brain rages the whole
pacifier-vs.-no-pacifier debate.
</P>
<P>
   What? How are you supposed to figure out what to do from all of
this?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is easy: You're not. In almost every case, there's
not a totally right answer or a completely wrong one. It's taken me
only a couple of months to figure out that when it comes to babies,
common sense is your best guide, along with these eight words:
</P>
<P>
   Love them a lot, and do your best.
</P>
<P>
   Everything else is just details. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Bill Goodykoontz can be reached at bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
