<HEADLINE>
BOSNIA ELECTION RESULTS HELD UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The international body in charge of the Bosnian
elections created chaos Tuesday by canceling its announcement of
preliminary ballot results. This led to speculation that moderate
parties had not done well.
</P>
<P>
   The Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe,
scheduled, then inexplicably canceled, a news conference at which
the intial election returns, from the weekend, were to have been
announced.
</P>
<P>
   This led to speculation that the parties supported by the West
had fared worse than expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``They won't release the results because they don't like them,''
said Sandra Coliver, the legal counsel to the International Crisis
Group, one of the independent organizations monitoring the
election.
</P>
<P>
   Western nations had billed the general election as an
opportunity for moderates to make major gains against the
nationalist parties that have fostered so much divisiveness in
Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   But Coliver's group, among others, predicted that the elections
were doomed to be nothing more than an ethnic census, because
Bosnian election laws provide no incentive for candidates to appeal
to voters outside of their own ethnic bloc.
</P>
<P>
   Officials for the Organization for Security and Cooperation in
Europe said that only a tiny fraction of votes had been counted,
and that no clear pattern had emerged.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is that we don't have any coherent information that
would demonstrate trends to share with people right now, and I
don't know when we will,'' the organization's leader, Robert Barry,
said in Sarajevo.
</P>
<P>
   Barry, who said it could be another week before final results
are tallied, denied that the decision first to call and then to
cancel the announcement of preliminary results had anything to do
with the claims by Bosnian nationalist parties that they had
prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody has yet a basis for claiming victory,'' Barry said.
</P>
<P>
   Elections were held for the three-member rotating presidency of
Bosnia, composed of Bosnian, Croat and Serb leaders; the 42-member
Bosnian House of Representatives; the presidency of the so-called
Republic of Srpska, the Serb entity that together with the Muslim
Croat Federation makes up Bosnia, and its 83-member National
Assembly; the 140-seat House of Representatives in the Federation;
and 10 regional assemblies.
</P>
<P>
   Coliver said initial returns monitored by her group suggest that
Biljana Plavsic, the president of the Republic of Srpska, and the
favorite of Western nations for her transformation from militant to
moderate, will probably lose her seat to a Serbian hardliner,
Nikola Poplasen.
</P>
<P>
   The Croat hardliner, Ante Jelavic, is expected to remove the
more moderate Kresimir Zubak for the Croat presidency in Bosnia.
And the Muslim leader and old-style nationalist, Alija Izetbegovic,
is expected to retain his seat as the Bosnian president.
</P>
<P>
   The only obvious good news for the international community,
Coliver said, was the apparent strong showing of the multiethnic
Social Democratic Party in Sarajevo. The party is projected to
garner about 40 percent of the vote in the Bosnian capital, about
four times the vote it got in 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
