<SLUG> BC-MARIJUANA-MEDICAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE RESOLUTION CONDEMNS STATE EFFORTS TO LEGALIZE POT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House is prepared to overwhelmingly approve a
resolution declaring its unequivocal opposition to legalizing
marijuana for medicinal use on grounds that it is dangerous and
addictive.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution, sponsored by Rep. Bill McCollum, R-Fla., is a
response to 1996 ballot initiatives approved in Arizona and
California that allow physicians to prescribe marijuana to treat
symptoms of illnesses. California's Proposition 215 also protects
people who use marijuana for medical reasons from arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Similar initiatives are expected to be on the November ballot in
Alaska, Colorado, Nevada, Oregon and Washington, and possibly the
District of Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   McCollum, who chairs the House Judiciary Committee's crime
panel, said Tuesday that state efforts to circumvent federal
anti-drug laws are ``a backdoor way of legalizing marijuana.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A tragic drug crisis is enveloping our youth,'' McCollum said,
adding that marijuana use among young people ages 12 to 17 rose 120
percent from 1992 to 1997.
</P>
<P>
   McCollum said ``doctors and scientists with the greatest
expertise have determined that marijuana is not a medicine.'' He
said regularly smoking pot can be dangerous for people who are
HIV-positive because it weakens the body's natural immunities and
can accelerate the onset of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Some physicians and advocacy groups contend that marijuana, when
smoked, relieves symptoms of glaucoma; helps slow the wasting
condition associated with AIDS; relieves nausea and vomiting of
cancer patients; improves appetites in patients too sick to eat;
and eases neurological disorders.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists, however, are divided over the medicinal value of
marijuana and are continuing to study it. The Food and Drug
Administration has rejected marijuana for medicinal use. The
National Academy of Sciences is expected to issue a report this
winter on whether marijuana should be used as medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Gerald B.H. Solomon, R-N.Y., a cancer survivor, told the
House he supported McCollum's measure. Solomon said ``marijuana is
a dangerous and addictive drug that should not be legalized for
medical use or any other use.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the resolution is nonbinding, it serves only as a
recommendation and does not have the force of law.
</P>
<P>
   Barry R. McCaffrey, the White House drug policy director, urged
support for the resolution in a letter to Sen. Charles E. Grassley,
R-Iowa, the Senate sponsor. A vote is pending in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Legalizing marijuana as medicine sends a confusing message to
America's children,'' McCaffrey wrote. He added that ``designating
medicine through ballot initiatives'' would undermine the federal
process for assessing the safety of medicines before they enter the
marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., said the resolution says to
states allowing the medical use of marijuana: ``Naughty, naughty,
how dare you differ with us. ... Let a state diverge and they
deserve to be spanked.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry A. Waxman, D-Calif., said the resolution was a slap
at his state. He said supporters of the measure ``think we should
just say no to sick and dying patients because it looks like we're
getting tough on drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lloyd Doggett, D-Texas, said physicians should determine
whether marijuana can relieve a patient's pain.
</P>
<P>
   Should we ``entrust it to the medical community or to turn to
Dr. Newt,'' Doggett said, referring the House Speaker Newt
Gingrich, R-Ga. ``For this Congress to mingle politics into
medicine is a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   McCollum's bill also calls on the attorney general, 90 days from
enactment of the resolution, to report to Congress the quantity of
marijuana seized in the United States from 1992 to 1997 and the
number of arrests and prosecutions for federal marijuana offenses
during those years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Renee Emry of Ann Arbor, Mich., appeared in McCollum's office
Tuesday with members of the Marijuana Policy project, a Washington
advocacy group, to protest the resolution. Emry, 38, has multiple
sclerosis.
</P>
<P>
   The mother of three lighted a marijuana cigarette in front of
McCollum's receptionists and held up a sign saying: ``I use
marijuana for multiple sclerosis.''
</P>
<P>
   As McCollum's aides slipped into a back room to call the police,
Emry explained she was willing to be arrested so that other
patients who benefit from medicinal marijuana won't be.
</P>
<P>
   Emry said regular marijuana use has eased her pain and enabled
her to walk with a cane 19 years after her diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what else I am supposed to do except take care of
myself,'' Emry said. ``What am I supposed to do, become a
criminal?''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty minutes later, Emry was arrested and taken away in a
wheelchair.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
