<HEADLINE>
EX-FBI AGENT TO SEEK IMMUNITY IN MOB PROCEEDINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA NEALON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ After months of testimony that failed to show that
former FBI agent John Connolly had committed any crime within the
statute of limitations, defense lawyers will ask a judge Wednesday
to order federal prosecutors to grant Connolly immunity so he can
testify in ongoing hearings into the FBI's relationship with its
criminal informants.
</P>
<P>
   Connolly, who invoked his Fifth Amendment right against
self-incrimination when he was called as a witness last spring, was
the longtime handler of gangster/informants Stephen Flemmi and
James ``Whitey'' Bulger, and defense lawyers feel Connolly can shed
crucial light on the FBI's relationship with the pair.
</P>
<P>
   Flemmi claims that he and Bulger were given permission to commit
any crime short of murder in exchange for information they gave the
FBI on the Mafia. Although Connolly has refused to testify without
immunity, he has said in interviews that Bulger and Flemmi were
given permission to continue their gambling and loan-sharking
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Although Flemmi has implicated Connolly in wrongdoing, such as
tipping him off to an investigation of bookmakers _ which Connolly
has denied, none of the allegations falls within the statute of
limitations, which is five years for most federal crimes. Connolly
retired from the FBI in December 1990.
</P>
<P>
   The only alleged crime that would have fallen within the statute
of limitations was Flemmi's claim that he and Bulger were tipped
off to their upcoming indictment in January 1995 so they could
flee.
</P>
<P>
   But Flemmi testified that it was Connolly's former supervisor,
John Morris, who alerted him and Bulger to the indictments. Morris,
who testified under a grant of immunity, denied tipping off Bulger
and Flemmi to the indictment.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers, who face an uphill legal battle trying to
convince US District Judge Mark L. Wolf that he should override
prosecutors and immunize Connolly, are expected to argue that only
Connolly can resolve the discrepancies between Flemmi's and
Morris's testimony and spell out the deal Flemmi and Bulger had
with the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   Flemmi's lawyer, Kenneth J. Fishman, told Wolf Tuesday that
there is virtually no chance Connolly would waive his Fifth
Amendment rights and agree to voluntarily testify based on numerous
conversations Fishman has had with Connolly's attorney, R. Robert
Popeo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
