</P>
<P>
   Russia has tried to pay off its wage arrears several times in
the past without addressing the ineffeciency, corruption and
mismanagement of funds that helped cause the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``You still have to address the rotten roots in the system,''
said Marshall Goldman, associate director of Harvard University's
Davis Center for Russian Studies. ``Printing money and introducing
controls is not going to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Primakov also said Tuesday he would avoid solutions that would
lead to hyperinflation. One way to do that would be to enlist the
West's help. John Odling-Smee, the head of the IMF department
dealing with Russia, arrived in Moscow to discuss prospects for the
release of a $4.3 billion installment of a $22.6 billion aid
package agreed in July.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov told Odling-Smee that Russia would meet its debt
obligations and would strive to attract more foreign investment,
the Interfax news agency reported. The trouble: few foreign
business leaders trust the new government.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no credibility left in Russia public authority,'' said
Scott Blacklin, president of the American Chamber of Commerce in
Moscow. ``If they say that tomorrow they are going to approve the
entire package of structural reforms we've been pushing, we're
going to say, ``We don't believe it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But few Russian officials are talking about the things Western
businessmen want _ more transparency and accountability in the
economy. Instead, the buzzword in the new government is ``state
control.'' Gerashchenko called Tuesday for a return to the
Soviet-era practice of requiring exporters to turn in their hard
currency earnings to the government, in exchange for rubles at a
state-determined rate.
</P>
<P>
   One official who had inspired some Western confidence in
Russia's policies, the tough-talking chief tax inspector, Boris
Fyodorov, could soon be replaced, Russian media reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday also marked the end of a week-long recovery by the
ruble, which had fallen from 6 to the dollar to 21 last week, only
to recover early Tuesday to 7.5 to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials have said the ruble's rally showed that the
crisis was not that serious. But bankers and currency dealers said
the ruble increase was deliberately orchestrated by the banks to
lower the rate of the Russian currency to the dollar _ in
anticipation of payment of $2 billion worth of ruble-dollar forward
contracts that came due Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, the ruble dropped to 12.5 to the dollar.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-98 1922EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
