<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6721 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAZIL-MARKETBOS &LR;      09-15 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-MARKETBOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZIL MARKET SOARS ON BAILOUT HOPES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Brazilian stock market Tuesday had its biggest rally in more
than three years as hopes soared that a proposed rescue plan by the
industrialized world would salvage Latin America's most important
economy.
</P>
<P>
   To halt the spread of an Asian and Russian financial crisis to
Latin America, the World Bank promised to back up a pledge last
week by the International Monetary Fund to aid Brazil in paying
debt coming due. The World Bank also confirmed talks with Argentina
to help that country pay debt and finance its budget deficit.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and the Group of Seven industrialized nations
agreed Monday to support fragile emerging markets battered this
year by investor flight. Rumors about the size of a bailout swirled
all day Tuesday, pushing Brazil's stock market up by an astonishing
18.7 percent, sparking rallies in other markets in the region.
Mexico's stock market rose 12.9 pecent; Argentina's rose 8.9
percent, and Chile's rose 8.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But in a shaky financial world, there were no assurances that
the rally would introduce an era of stability in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation is reminding me of what happened with the first
rumors of the Russian (bailout) package when everybody got
excited,'' said Jim Sullivan, associate Latin America analyst for
Thomson Global Markets in New York, an economic research firm.
``Everybody got excited and nothing happened.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely good news'' said Esteban Medrano, Latin
economist for Independent Economic Analysis in New York. ``But so
far fundamentals haven't changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Latin America's biggest economy, Brazil, is grappling
with a growing budget deficit that is now 7 percent of gross
national product. The cost to the government of paying off $75
billion in short-term debt coming due by year's end also rose last
week when the country's central bank hiked interest rates to stem
investor flight, making the government's bonds more attractive.
</P>
<P>
   The country is losing billions a day from investors converting
their holdings from the local currency, the reais, to the US
dollar.
</P>
<P>
   With the United States' biggest trading partner, Japan, in steep
decline, there is growing concern about Brazil. US exports to
Brazil totaled nearly $8 billion in the first seven months of the
year and direct US investment in the country stands at more than
$37 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil's president, Fernando Henrique Cardoso, who is seeking
re-election in October, said he would call President Clinton to
discuss the country's economic affairs. But many Brazilian
economists believe that Cardoso must take the initiative and
quickly cut the deficit. Although the government last week said it
would trim spending, analysts said the savings would be wiped out
by higher debt costs following a hike last week in interest rates
to 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are three weeks left until the elections and Cardoso has
enough momentum and credibility to stand up and say that tougher
cuts have to be made,'' said Denis Parisien, an analyst with
Dresdner Kleinwort Benson bank in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The crisis in emerging economies began more than a year ago in
Thailand. Troubles have spread throughout the world, driving down
currencies and stock and bond markets. In Brazil, shares on Sao
Paulo's exchange, the Bovespa, have lost half their value in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement by President Clinton and other G-7 leaders that
help may be on the way to the world's fragile economies reinforced
the positive sentiment building in Latin America. Last week, the
IMF said it was ready to help Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF was clearly concerned about the stability of Brazil's
currency, which has a fixed exchange rate. If the government is
forced to devalue, there is a growing fear in international circles
of another downward spiral of currencies in Latin American similar
to the one triggered in 1994 by a plunging Mexican peso.
</P>
<P>
   To calm Latin American markets, a World Bank spokeswoman,
reading from a statement prepared by staff in the Latin America
division, said the bank is ``preparing a package of $4.5 billion
for Argentina in the event that the country is unable to access
international capital markets to have financing available to roll
over its debt and to cover any fiscal deficit.''
</P>
<P>
   The IMF said Friday it is prepared to lend money to Latin
America if any nations in the region request aid. And the World
Bank said Tuesday that it would participate in any such loan
program.
</P>
<P>
   An IMF spokesman declined further comment.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wire service materials was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
