<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6731 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEIBOWITZ-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      09-15 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEIBOWITZ-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOSA'S LOVE OF BASEBALL BRINGS US BACK TO THE GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID LEIBOWITZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - The boy, maybe 11, maybe 12 years old , steps to the
plate batting clean-up. He's a gangly kid, legs of a spider, all
elbows and longish neck. He owns the impersonation, though, if not
the physique.
</P>
<P>
   Black bat, wristbands pushed to mid-forearm, black batting
gloves. He taps home with the bat, once, twice, three times. Even
from 100 feet _ and 20 years _ away, I can read his mind.
</P>
<P>
   For me, the dream featured a different outfielder, different
team, different generation. My guy wore 44, Yankees' pinstripes,
and the year I was the kid's age, 1977, he hit three homers on
three swings against the Dodgers in Game Six of the World Series.
All I wanted was to bat lefty, to be like Reggie Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Now, 20 years later, this kid has home run madness like 10
million other kids, a wicked case. You can hear the P.A. announcer
booming in his head.
</P>
<P>
   (begin ital) ``Now batting for the Cubs, Number 21, Sammy
Sooo-sssaaa.'' (end ital)
</P>
<P>
   The first pitch comes in eye-high, fastball. The kid steps in
the bucket, takes a looping flail. Strike one.
</P>
<P>
   He steps out of the box, taps his chest with his fist. A row
above me in the metal bleachers, an older kid laughs. To me, that
chuckle belongs on the diamond every bit as much as the whir of a
line drive or some shortstop shouting ``Hum babe.'' Sadly, the
sound has been too long gone from the game. Until Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   It is his lasting contribution to baseball, more so than that
62nd smash out onto Waveland Avenue the other night. Sosa bubbles,
threatens to burst every time he steps between the lines. In this,
America's most churlish moment, a time where people dole out joy
like it comes with a Benz price tag, one Cub waves his black bat
like a wand. He dares to (begin ital) play (end ital) baseball, not
work at it; (begin ital) love, (end ital) not tolerate it.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa loves the game so much, he brings me back to it, brings me
to a park to witness an anonymous kid love it, too.
</P>
<P>
   The boy fouls the second pitch off, then takes one away and in
the dirt. Another bouncer evens the count, two balls, two strikes.
</P>
<P>
   For me, baseball died on Aug. 12, 1994, the day of the last
strike. The cancellation of the '94 Series, the pathetic '95
season, greedy players, foolish owners, luxury suites, Taj-like
stadiums _ all of it one affront atop the next, a feeling not
unlike coming home to the aftermath of a robbery. All gone,
snatched.
</P>
<P>
   The kid steps out, then back in, taps the plate with his bat.
Again, the pitch is in the dirt. Now the count is full, and you see
it in the way he widens his eyes, licks his lips. Number 21 on the
brain.
</P>
<P>
   (begin ital) ``Three and two to Sosa. Sammy steps in, sets
himself.'' (end ital)
</P>
<P>
   To pretend like that was how I made it through childhood, how a
couple of pairs of patched pants and a three-room apartment in
Queens didn't seem so bad. I had a Sportcraft mitt that I broke in
under my parents' mattress on the fold-out couch, a glove with the
name ``Reggie Jackson'' embossed into the leather. Sometimes, at
night, I would trace over the signature with a marker, so it
wouldn't fade away.
</P>
<P>
   Then the game faded away, until Sosa, with his bunny hop out of
the batter's box and the stutter step as he rounds the bases. He
oozes joy, and I would pay good money to see him whiff, or park his
car, or pack a suitcase.
</P>
<P>
   The payoff pitch is another fastball, belt-high. The kid doesn't
so much swing as twitch, an ungainly lunge at the ball. He gets the
end of the bat on it. A slow roller to shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   The boy runs hard, but he is out by three steps. He peels off
and jogs back to the bench, takes a seat. After a while the grimace
goes away, and again I can read his mind.
</P>
<P>
   (begin ital) ``That ball is out of here. Sammy taps his heart.
Sammy makes a V to the crowd. And they're on their feet at
Wrigley.''
</P>
<P>
   (end ital)
</P>
<P>
   As I am on my feet in this park. On the next diamond over, the
outfield grass is soft and moths buzz the lights. I take one step,
another, a third, and then I am running as fast as I can, as fast
as I have in 20 years. &QL; 
 &QL; 
David Leibowitz can be reached at david.leibowitz(at)pni.com. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-98 1934EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980915.0306 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
