<HEADER>
A6736 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-JONES-BOS &LR;      09-15 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-JONES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JONES' LAWYERS SEEK RENEWAL OF SUIT AGAINST CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Lawyers for Paula Jones Tuesday said they are
preparing to file several motions in an effort to reinstate her
sexual harassment lawsuit against President Clinton, including a
new request that US District Judge Susan Webber Wright find Clinton
in contempt of court.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the appeal has a great deal of chance for success,''
said David Pyke, one of Jones' attorneys. Pyke said Jones feels
``vindication'' from the report by independent counsel Kenneth W.
Starr that alleges Clinton committed perjury by denying a sexual
relationship with Monica S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   John Whitehead, the Rutherford Institute lawyer who is a
co-counsel on the Jones case, said Wright ``was in the room'' when
Clinton gave his January deposition in the Jones case and said he
couldn't remember being alone with Lewinsky and denied having an
affair with her.
</P>
<P>
   ``He lied to her face,'' Whitehead said. ``He is an officer of
the court. She may hold the president in contempt.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Bennett, the Clinton lawyer handling the Jones case, did
not return a call seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Wright dismissed the Jones lawsuit in April, and the case has
been appealed to the Eighth Circuit Court of Appeals in St. Louis.
Jones' lawyers now are hoping that the appellate court will take
the unusual step of summarily deciding that Jones has won the case
based on Clinton's alleged false statements as outlined in the
Starr report.
</P>
<P>
   The Starr report, in addition to alleging that Clinton committed
perjury in the Jones deposition, also says Clinton discussed his
testimony with his secretary, Betty Currie. Wright had ordered
Clinton not to discuss his testimony with anybody.
</P>
<P>
   Jones' lawyers, who plan to file their motions over the next two
weeks, want the appeals court to reinstate the lawsuit or instruct
Wright to consider doing so.
</P>
<P>
   Wright has the option of acting on her own to cite Clinton for
contempt, according to Pyke. Wright, in a footnote to her ruling
released Sept. 3, said, ``The court has concerns about the nature
of the president's January 17th, 1998 deposition testimony given
his recent public statements.'' Wright was referring to Clinton's
public admission on Aug. 17 of having had an inappropriate
relationship with Lewinsky, a former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   In his deposition in the Jones case, Clinton denied having a
``sexual relationship'' with Lewinsky, or an ``affair'' with her.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in his Aug. 17 speech, said he was ``legally accurate''
in the deposition.
</P>
<P>
   Former federal prosecutor Joseph diGenova said the Jones case
could reemerge in two ways:
</P>
<P>
   --Wright could issue a ``show cause'' order, which would require
Clinton and his lawyers to appear in court and explain why she
shouldn't hold him in contempt for submitting false testimony.
Significantly, Wright could hold Clinton in contempt for making
false statements even if she does not determine whether he
committed perjury, which is a a tougher legal standard.
</P>
<P>
   --The US Court of Appeals could send the case back to Wright and
instruct her to reopen it based on new information contained in the
Starr report. It also has the option of deciding that Jones has won
the case and sending the case to trial only to determine how much
damages Clinton should pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``No federal judge should permit the kind of activity that has
gone on in that case without taking some steps to rectify it,''
said diGenova.
</P>
<P>
   Jones alleged in her suit that on May 8, 1991, when Clinton was
the governor of Arkansas, he invited her to a hotel room and made
an unwanted sexual advance.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton denied the allegation and declined an offer to settle
the case out of court. As a result, the Jones case proceeded and
one of her lawyers received an anonymous tip that Clinton may have
had an affair with Lewinsky. Clinton reportedly was surprised when
he learned that Lewinsky was on a list of possible witnesses in the
Jones case. Lewinsky swore in an affidavit for the Jones case that
she did not have a sexual relationship with Clinton, and the
president made a similar statement during his deposition.
</P>
<P>
   All of this helped prompt Starr, who was investigating an array
of other subjects involving Clinton, to look into whether Clinton
did have a sexual relationship with Lewinsky and urged her to lie
about it. Wright eventually ruled that the Lewinsky matter was not
relevant to the Jones case, and later dismissed the entire lawsuit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
