A6743 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROSTATE-TREAT-BOS &LR;      09-15 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROSTATE-TREAT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURGERY SEEN BEST ROUTE IN MORE-SEVERE PROSTATE CANCER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   New data on prostate cancer treatments show that surgery is the
best choice if the tumor is at an intermediate- or high-risk stage
at the time of diagnosis, but the results leave unresolved the
question of how many men with low-risk tumors might benefit from
less drastic treatments.
</P>
<P>
   The findings, published Wednesday, offer partial clarification
in the debate over the best way to treat the number two cancer
killer of American men.
</P>
<P>
   The crux is how many men can safely forgo surgery or high-dose
``external beam'' radiation, with their risks of impotence and
urinary incontinence, in favor of radioactive ``seed'' implants
within the cancerous prostate gland, a less traumatic procedure
that is rapidly growing in popularity.
</P>
<P>
   When seed implants are compared to prostate removal or external
radiation, ``for intermediate- and high-risk patients, there
appears to be a three-fold increase in treatment failure within
five years,'' said Dr. Anthony V. D'Amico of Brigham and Women's
Hospital in Boston, lead author of one new study. ``This apparent
increase in recurrence is frightening, and raises a question as to
whether implants are a feasible alternative for those patients.''
</P>
<P>
   The study looked at blood levels of a prostate cancer marker
called prostate-specific antigen over five years among nearly 1,900
men treated with seed implants (with or without hormone
treatments), prostatectomy, or external beam radiation. D'Amico
noted that the study is the first to compare the effectiveness of
all three treatment types among carefully matched sets of patients.
It appears in this week's Journal of the American Medical
Association.
</P>
<P>
   A study from Seattle, published earlier this month in the
Journal of the National Cancer Institute, suggested that implants
are as effective as surgery for low-risk cases. But experts do not
agree on the size of that group.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the confusion depends on how researchers define low-,
intermediate-, or high-risk cases. Thanks to more effective
screening of men for prostate-specific antigen (PSA), about 70
percent of all such tumors are now diagnosed when they are still
confined to the walnut-sized prostate gland. That's the good news.
</P>
<P>
   However, the absence of malignancy outside the gland is only one
measure of risk. By another yardstick _ a measure of tumor
aggressiveness called a Gleason score _ about 87 percent of
prostate tumors are considered intermediate- or high-risk at the
time of diagnosis, said Dr. William Catalona of Washington
University School of Medicine in St. Louis, an authority on
prostate cancer staging.
</P>
<P>
   By this index, some surgeons say the study by D'Amico and his
colleagues suggests that most of the 200,000 prostate cancer cases
diagnosed this year would best be treated with surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``The study is a warning to men that if they have an
intermediate- or high-grade cancer and they opt for seed implants,
they're choosing inferior treatment,'' Catalona said.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amico agrees in part. But he points out that many men
classified as low-risk in his study actually had Gleason scores
that Catalona would consider intermediate-risk. By this definition,
the proportion of newly diagnosed patients who might safely opt for
seed implants would be larger than the 12 percent or so that the
St. Louis surgeon considers low-risk.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
