<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6750 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON0916     09-15 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON0916 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON TO MEET THE PRESS WEDNESDAY FOR FIRST TIME SINCE STARR
REPORT
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON President Clinton meets the press on Wednesday for
the first time since the release of independent counsel Kenneth
Starr's graphic report on the Monica Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
   At his side will be ailing Czech Republic President Vaclav
Havel, here for a one day meeting with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The two leaders are expected to focus their talks on contingency
plans for possible NATO military action in the strife-ridden Serb
province of Kosovo and other Balkan security matters, as well as
Havel's personal contribution to democracy and freedom in the heart
of Central Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has scheduled the press conference his first since his
summit two weeks ago in Moscow with Russian President Boris Yeltsin
at an auditorium in the State Department, where it is likely to be
attended by scores of diplomats and foreign affairs writers, in
addition to the White House press corps.
</P>
<P>
   That lofty environment, however, is no guarantee that Clinton
won't be peppered with questions stemming from the Lewinsky
scandal. The issue has dogged the president in every extended press
encounter he's ventured into since allegations first surfaced in
January that he had an affair with the former White House intern
and then urged her to lie about it.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton first denied then later admitted to the affair, although
he still denies having coached her to mislead investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to limit the quantity, if not the scope, of questioning,
presidential spokesman Michael McCurry said that White House
reporters should expect to be able to ask a total of only three or
four questions, with Czech reporters being allotted an equal
number.
</P>
<P>
   Havel, who is in declining health, is trying to guide his
country's entry into the North Atlantic Treaty Organization, or
NATO, along with two other Central European countries, Poland and
Hungary.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is also certain to praise Havel's efforts, often
described as heroic, to champion human rights and replace a
generation of authoritarian rule with democracy.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's been an extraordinary voice for freedom and for the
rights of human beings,'' McCurry said, ``and he obviously remains,
I think, a very influential, important spokesman for political
tolerance, civility, and justice in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton met on Tuesday with Defense Secretary William Cohen,
Joint Chiefs of Staff Chairman Army Gen. Hugh Shelton, and two
dozen other high ranking military and security officials, to talk
about the state of the country's military readiness.
</P>
<P>
   Of immediate concern is pending congressional action on a White
House request for emergency supplemental funding of $1.9 billion to
pay for U.S. peacekeepers in Bosnia through the end of next year.
The request is pending before an appropriations conference
committee, made up of lawmakers from both the House and the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Longer term, the Pentagon is concerned that a combination of
budget cuts and downsizing in an era of growing non-combat demands
upon the military in places like Bosnia, Haiti, Rwanda and Latin
America, may be reducing the country's overall war-fighting
capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Shelton and the top officers from each of the armed services are
scheduled to testify on the subject Sept. 29 before the Senate
Armed Services Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our forward-deployed and first-to-fight units are highly
ready, and our overall force is fully capable of carrying out our
national military strategy,'' Clinton said in remarks opening the
meeting. ``But I'm determined that we don't relax our vigilance to
keep our forces ready to protect our security today and well into
the 21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, the military remains capable of fighting, and
winning, two regional wars fought ''nearly simultaneously,'' said
National Security Council spokesman P.J. Crowley.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not a hollow force, it's a very capable force,'' said
Crowley, but ''the long-term trends are something that we're
concerned about.''
</P>
<P>
   In a 90-minute meeting at the National Defense University at Ft.
McNair in Washington, Clinton listened to his top military chiefs
as they discussed issues ranging from the pace of overseas
deployments to the gap between civilian and military pay levels.
</P>
<P>
   In one potentially disturbing trend, the Air Force and Navy have
become concerned that they are losing highly trained pilots in the
prime of their career to higher-paying positions in the private
airline industry.
</P>
<P>
   ''They continue to leave in significant numbers, so that the
services are forced to replace a 10- or 15-year captain or major
with a brand new first lieutenant,'' said Crowley.
</P>
<P>
   Non-combat operations, such as peacekeeping and humanitarian aid
missions, can eat into troops' combat training, said Crowley.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you have your troops deployed to places like Bosnia,''
Crowley said, ''that does cut back on training time.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
