<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-USHER-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   The house of Usher
</P>
<P>
   By Sonia Murray
</P>
<P>
   c. 1998n Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- It's an unlikely setting for the eye of a celebrity
storm: a converted two-car garage in Lilburn. Inside, hundreds of
letters professing passionate love for R&AMP;B vocalist Usher Raymond
are being opened in rather mechanical fashion. After all, at least
300 come every week. This is routine.
</P>
<P>
   Two desks away, another employee is adding another address to
the 16,000-plus already in the database, most of them belonging to
young women who have written. They usually ask the same question:
``Do you have a girlfriend?'' Then again, there is the stripper who
has sent pictures of what others pay to see. And judging from what
she's written, she doesn't seem to care whether the single Raymond,
19, has a significant other.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of this serene atmosphere is a rather casual
Jonetta Patton, Usher's mother and manager, surveying the territory
in jeans and tennis shoes _ a look that fits the scene, if not
Usher's ultra-busy show business career.
</P>
<P>
   After a barely noticed solo bow in 1994, Patton's older son
returned last September with an album that has sold more than 4
million copies, ``My Way'' (LaFace Records). His appeal to teenage
girls and his considerable acting ability have landed him recurring
roles on TV's ``Moesha'' and ``The Bold and the Beautiful.'' He's
been cast in three upcoming movies _ ``The Faculty,'' ``She's All
That'' and ``Light It Up,'' the last with Babyface. And it's been
reported that he just signed a $1 million publishing deal.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the guy who's finishing his third concert tour in the past
year still receives all his business proposals at this modest,
two-story home nestled in the cul-de-sac of an unassuming Gwinnett
County subdivision. Patton, 41, is determined to keep the business
in her converted garage from interfering with the environment she
wants her two sons to come home to. There's one other reason for
all the low-key placidity: ``God blessed us with a fall at the
start of Usher's career,'' explains Patton, who moved to Atlanta
from Raymond's native Chattanooga nine years ago. ``And we've
handled things differently ever since.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we hit the ground running, we might be all frantic, caught
up in the success right now,'' continues the divorced Patton, a
former office manager for Southern Message Center who is also
raising a 14-year-old son, James, as she and Usher develop a label
(Us Records) and a possible dance show for television.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw the ugly side of success first,'' she says. ``We saw
people give up on us because we didn't have a hit in the beginning.
We saw how people who only had one little hit couldn't speak. We
saw how people can get all caught up in this business, the hype. So
there's none of that mess here.''
</P>
<P>
   That's probably why Usher doesn't seem arrogant. Sure, the
singer set to be on Elton John's ``Elaborate Lives: The Legend of
Aida'' soundtrack may have bought a Lincoln Navigator on a whim.
Yes, according to the current cover story in Teen People, he's
taken I-85 at 115 mph in his black Porsche Boxster.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he is one of the most mannerable, together `big stars'
I've ever met, of any age,'' says Keith Clinkscales, president of
Vibe magazine, which featured Raymond on the cover of a summer
issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see how the women come on to him,'' adds fellow Atlanta teen
star Monica. ``He could be really out there if he wanted to.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But nawww, you know, I'm just a young man out here trying to
have some fun,'' says Raymond, who discovered a love for singing
when he was 9. ``I've waited a long time for this. So I'm just
trying to take it nice and slow and appreciate it.''
</P>
<P>
   And such is the pace at his home. Mail is opened. Addresses are
compiled. Autographed pictures are sent to fan club members. And
the personal gifts Raymond receives _ lots of crosses _ are stored
for him to see in those rare moments he actually comes home to his
family, his room and his pit bulls, Star and My King.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gets kind of exciting around here when Usher's headed
home,'' claims 21-year-old product manager Denita Galloway.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, we stop for a few minutes ...''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
