<DOCNO> NYT19980915.0321 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6756 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAVANNAH-CORONER-COX     09-15 1496
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAVANNAH-CORONER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    He's a sleuth with a medical satchel
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAVANNAH, Ga. -- It's 7:30 p.m. in the city morgue, and James C.
Metts Jr. interrupts a cacophony of graveyard banter to don a
rubber glove and briefly halt the autopsy of Savannah's latest
murder victim.
</P>
<P>
   Metts, 67, pokes his index finger into a small, round wound,
feeling for evidence of singed skin or powder burns that might
offer clues as to whether the young man had been shot from
point-blank range. Then he orders tests on the victim's clothes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody else would have thought of that,'' marvels homicide
detective Kenneth Griffin, 36, feverishly taking notes. ``Dr. Metts
knows his stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   An autopsy is ``the last chance he'll get for justice,'' says
Metts, elected Chatham County corner without opposition for the
past 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Metts is not only a respected sleuth, but a character _
literally _ straight out of the best seller ``Midnight in the
Garden of Good and Evil,'' which put this city of 140,000 on the
map worldwide. He fits the stereotype of a Southern gentleman,
right down to his syrupy drawl and light summer suits. He's known
simply as ``Dr. Jimmy'' to friends and hundreds of patients, many
of whom went to his dad, Dr. James Metts Sr., until his death at
84.
</P>
<P>
   He lives on Forsyth Park, the jewel of the city's squares, in a
six-bedroom mansion that was once a funeral home. Passers-by gawk
at its curving two-story portico supported by eight Corinthian
columns, surrounded by towering oaks draped with Spanish moss. They
don't know that when Metts bought the house, it still had embalming
equipment in the basement and caskets in one of its many parlors.
</P>
<P>
   He considers himself a detective, reading scores of EKGs daily,
working 12- to 16-hour days and seeing hundreds of patients,
carefully listening for any clues that might help him figure out
how to make them feel better.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what doctoring is,'' he says, stroking a patient on the
knee and offering a few comforting words. ``It's a detective story,
a mystery. You have to look for clues, and if you miss just one,
you could miss the diagnosis.''
</P>
<P>
   And it's the same with murders, he adds.
</P>
<P>
   It's this same love of mysteries that's kept him going as county
coroner, a job that paid $9,000 annually until this year, when he
got a raise to $12,000.
</P>
<P>
   As a civic booster, history buff and old-line Savannahian who's
proud of his roots and city, Metts is excited about solving what he
sees as perhaps the most challenging mystery of his career.
</P>
<P>
   It involves Count Casimir Pulaski, a Revolutionary War hero from
Poland who was mortally wounded in the Battle of Savannah on Oct.
9, 1779. According to history, the count was buried at nearby
Greenwich Plantation, where the British, who'd placed a bounty on
his head, wouldn't be likely to find him. (Another story contends
the count was buried at sea, but that version doesn't float with
many historians.)
</P>
<P>
   The remains were dug up by admirers in 1852 and reinterred in
1854 in a monument in Monterey Square downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Metts got involved, he says, because ``somebody had to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only is history involved, but money. By 1996, the 55-foot
monument was falling apart, shedding large chunks of granite and
marble. It had to come down, and the city asked Metts to look for
Pulaski's remains and head up an investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The remains are now in a locked vault at a Georgia Bureau of
Investigation crime lab.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're sure this is him,'' Metts says, holding the skull in his
hands. ``But we've got to be even more sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because if the city can prove without a doubt the bones are
Pulaski's, the federal government will kick in funds to help offset
cost overruns involved in putting the monument back up. The
original estimate was $195,400, but that's swollen to $777,000, and
the city doesn't have that kind of money to spend on one monument
when so many need major repair.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need federal help,'' Metts says, his light blue eyes
sparkling. ``And I think we can get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Metts, chairman of the city's Pulaski Committee, leads a
delegation Saturday to Poland to dig up proof. It includes his
sidekick, Charles Powell, who runs a blood pressure clinic;
forensic anthropologist Karen Burns of the University of North
Carolina; genealogist Joan Porter of Florida; and a few
Polish-American leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Porter and Burns flew to Poland in May for preliminary spadework
and soon found a Pulaski relative, Teressa Witkowska, a
great-grandniece who died in 1861. Burns and Polish authorities,
with Metts in charge, will dig up her grave, take what's left of
the body to a nearby university and extract DNA from teeth or
perhaps bones. If successful, that DNA will be matched with DNA
taken from the Savannah bones.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just like Jim,'' says Dr. Preston Russell, 57, a
pathologist and amateur historian who's known Metts for 20 years.
``This Pulaski project is right up his alley; he does like to
figure things out. And he's not going to get a dime for it.'' So
what drives him?
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my life,'' he says. ``I like being busy.''
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Kathy, 47, adds, ``He only knows one speed: full
speed.''
</P>
<P>
   Others say it's philanthropy, a zeal to help his community, his
city, in part to honor his physician father, who practiced medicine
until he died in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   ``Medicine fascinates him, and he's bored when he doesn't have
some mystery to solve,'' Powell says. ``He has a knack for just
zeroing in on things that other physicians miss a lot of the time.
It's a drive to do good, to help people.''
</P>
<P>
   He's paid a price for such zeal.
</P>
<P>
   County Commission Chairman Billy Hair says Metts has lost money
as coroner for 30 years because he's paid for his own secretary and
used his own office space.
</P>
<P>
   ``He believes he is performing a public service, and we're sure
glad he does this,'' Hair says. ``He just enjoys getting to the
truth and doing a service for taxpayers.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Floyd Adams terms Metts ``a great humanitarian. He has a
respect for history. He could have thrown in the towel and sat back
and enjoyed life, but he's continuing to serve a need.''
</P>
<P>
   `I would have shot him'
</P>
<P>
   A ride across town in Metts' white Lincoln Town Car means
constant interruptions from his beeper, which he answers
immediately on a cell phone. At least three calls daily are for
coroner duties, and dozens come from patients he sees at St.
Joseph's/
</P>
<P>
   Candler Hospital; Memorial Medical Center, which his father
founded; a nursing home; and the Community Cardiovascular Council,
which Metts founded 29 years ago to help reduce what then was
Savannah's second-worst-in-the-nation stroke rate. He scurries from
hallway to hallway, hospital to hospital, sitting only to read
stacks of EKG charts, for which he receives $3 apiece.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to love it,'' he says. ``There's no other reason to
do it.''
</P>
<P>
   What else drives him?
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be a detective at heart, a person who wants to
solve puzzles and mysteries, to get to the bottom of things,''
Metts says. ``An EKG can tell you whether a person can handle
surgery. And you have to listen to what people say very carefully
for any hint of a clue. All the vital signs on charts are clues,
too. There are so many things.''
</P>
<P>
   If Metts has detractors, they are hard to find, and Savannah
tradition prevents any from speaking out. Take Spencer Lawton, 55,
who's been district attorney of Chatham County for 18 years and
clashed with Metts during the four trials of Jim Williams, the
chief character in what's known here as ``the Book.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawton pushed for premeditated murder, while Metts said openly
he felt it was a case of justifiable homicide. So Lawton turns away
questions about Metts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel it would be inappropriate for me to comment on this
matter,'' he says. ``It's outside my purview. And there is a
certain code of civility that attaches.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell, 53, director of the Community Cardiovascular Council,
sees Metts as both a father figure and best friend who continually
amazes him. He's amazed ``he's got so much energy,'' even enough to
hunt and scuba dive. Powell says Metts sees dozens of patients for
free and donates much of his salary from the cardiovascular clinic
back to the blood pressure monitoring organization.
</P>
<P>
   Though he seldom gets home before 7 p.m., after rising at 5
a.m., he's often called in the dead of the night, as he was in the
case of Williams, whokilled his lover Danny Hansford, but
eventually went free.
</P>
<P>
   Metts, who ordered that autopsy, too, examined the crime scene
and concluded that Williams ``moved things around'' in a panic, but
that Hansford got what was coming to him after pitching a ``fit''
and putting out a cigarette on a $120,000 desk.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was justifiable,'' he says. ``I would have shot him, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
