</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIBLEY-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wallace had a knack for colorful living
 &HT;    By Celestine Sibley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Alabama Gov. George Wallace wasn't exactly a
stainless knight most of his life. He did some shocking and shabby
things before, disabled and in pain, he took another hold on life.
But I read of his death with sadness.
</P>
<P>
   So much of life in the South has been contending with
demagogues, and, even as you deplored their actions and attitudes,
you valued them for their colorful ways.
</P>
<P>
   When George Wallace could not succeed himself as governor, he
ran in his place his wife, Lurleen, a modest, insecure woman. I
went to Montgomery to cover Lurleen's inauguration, and although
the festivities were geared to make her happy to ascend to the
office, I don't think she was.
</P>
<P>
   George was. He smiled and made jokes and was as set up by the
music and speeches as if he himself were taking office _ and the
word from Montgomery was that he continued to run the state, even
if it was her administration. She died of cancer before finishing
her term.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the inauguration, Wallace got defensive because
one of floats in the inaugural parade carried a sign referring to
an old song, ``I Found a Million Dollar Baby in the Five and Ten
Cent Store.''
</P>
<P>
   What of it? he demanded. Sure, Lurleen worked in a dime store,
but it was respectable and the little pay was needed in her family.
We agreed and tapped our feet in time to the tune.
</P>
<P>
   After Lurleen died, the governor married Cornelia Snively, the
beautiful niece of another colorful governor, ``Kissin' Jim''
Folsom. About that time, Wallace addressed a joint session of the
Georgia General Assembly, delineating some of his plans to run for
president.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jimmy Carter, who introduced him, made mention of Cornelia,
adding that he himself and Alabama's governor had ``the two
prettiest wives in the Southern Governors' Conference.'' Different
types, but I'm sure it was true.
</P>
<P>
   During his run for president, Wallace was campaigning in Laurel,
Md., when a crazy young man with a gun decided to kill him.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Bremer simply wanted a victim prominent enough to get him
headlines. He thought of President Nixon; he once had in mind
Hubert Humphrey.
</P>
<P>
   But he was a cleanliness freak, and on both occasions when he
might have shot one of them, he had to go brush his teeth, he told
the jury at his trial. So almost by accident he opened fire on
George Wallace, killing an innocent bystander and also wounding a
state trooper. Cornelia was by Wallace's side, and as he fell, she
flung herself protectively over his body.
</P>
<P>
   Later, they were divorced, and the governor married for a third
time, a still younger woman who was a country music singer. He
switched from being a segregationist to declaring segregation wrong
and openly courting black voters. He was doing remarkably well in
his race for president, but ultimately withdrew in favor of Jimmy
Carter.
</P>
<P>
   I liked this fellow Alabamian, although I didn't approve of him.
But with politicians, you seldom can approve. You have to like
something in the personality of the man, the humor, the
flamboyance, the color and excitement they bring to what would
usually be a routine news assignment.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't another Jim Folsom, who was funny and outrageous but
surprisingly liberal. He wasn't like our own Marvin Griffin, who
enlivened Georgia politics for a couple of decades. But he was a
uniquely interesting man, and his death saddens me.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
