<HEADER>
A6758 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SURFER16-COX     09-15 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SURFER16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    O'Brien gets a shotmat prime-time viewers
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Our fifth anniversary special,'' Conan O'Brien muses early in
tonight's prime-time retrospective (10 o'clock on NBC (62177)).
``Who woulda thunk it?''
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago? Nobody. Not even NBC, which hired the
then-nobody to replace CBS-bound David Letterman at 12:35 a.m. When
O'Brien's initial six-month contract expired, NBC signed him up
like a rented band instrument, month by month. Garry Shandling,
Greg Kinnear, Jon Stewart _ if you weren't rumored to be O'Brien's
replacement back then, you were nobody.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only is this the fifth anniversary for the show,'' O'Brien
acknowledges tonight. ``It's the fifth anniversary of the `I can't
believe that guy has a show' club.''
</P>
<P>
   Then sometime between years two and three, while almost nobody
was watching (an infomercial out-rated him in Detroit), a funny
thing happened to O'Brien's show: It got funny _ in the sly,
offbeat, uneven way Letterman used to be funny. The best comedy of
the year in 1996, at any hour, was O'Brien's third-anniversary
show.
</P>
<P>
   But even that special aired in the talk show's usual late, late
time slot. Now O'Brien has a five-year contract and a prime-time
venue (the show was taped in the roomier ``Saturday Night Live''
studio) where most viewers can see the funniest man on TV that
they've probably never seen before.
</P>
<P>
   It's a decent introduction, though not the breakthrough hour his
earlier anniversary was. You do notice right away that O'Brien is
the only late-night talk show host who looks like he actually likes
what he's doing. There's no manic-depressive desperation
(Letterman), no signs of ``sell out'' tattooed all over him (Jay
Leno).
</P>
<P>
   It's just skinny, carrot-topped Conan, dough-boy sidekick Andy
Richter and bandleader Max Weinberg, all performing their unartful
shticks: Andy playing quarters with Ed McMahon; Conan interviewing
President Clinton ``Clutch Cargo'' style; a herd of goats brought
on stage to imitate the laugh of guest Fran Drescher.
</P>
<P>
   Guest appearances are made tonight by Adam Sandler, Tony Randall
(the show's very first guest) and Tom Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   But too many bits are repeated from the earlier special, and
while you might not have seen them then, the hour still feels more
warmed over than spontaneous. Conan has a hard time being shocking
anymore _ one sign of how far he's come.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   SEEN AND HEARD
</P>
<P>
   The price tag rises
</P>
<P>
   TBS will ultimately pay about $180 million for the rights to air
``Seinfeld'' starting in fall 2002. Early reports placed the
purchase at more than $100 million or roughly more than $600,000
apiece for 180 ``Seinfeld'' episodes. And more it is. Indications
are now that TBS will fork over about $1 million per episode. That
would also bump the total ``Seinfeld'' rerun gross to more than $2
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Sex in the workplace
</P>
<P>
   Tonight's ``NewsStand: CNN &AMP; Fortune'' (10 o'clock (533142))
places the Clinton controversy in a different light. What if
Clinton were the head of a company rather than the head of the
country? The show will explore the processes corporations use to
reprimand or terminate employees.
</P>
<P>
   Football beats Emmys
</P>
<P>
   How many people watched Sunday's 50th annual Emmy Awards? Well,
not as many as sat in front of ``Monday Night Football.'' About
19.4 million viewers saw the Emmy contest, which finished as the
No. 2 show in the latest Nielsen weekly ratings. About 22.1 million
viewers watched the NFL game between the New England Patriots and
the Denver Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   CBS' TV-MA-rated airing of ``GoodFellas,'' which ran opposite
NBC's Emmy telecast, finished No. 9 for the week with 12.9 million
viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Half a Top 10 list
</P>
<P>
   Here's a recent David Letterman Top 10 with a few items worth
reading: ``Signs You're About to Be Impeached.'' No. 10 _ When you
call to congratulate Mark McGwire, he lets his machine get it. No.
9 _ Your press secretary keeps introducing you as ``President
William Milhous Clinton.'' No. 7 _ Tipper Gore's in your office
measuring it for drapes. No. 4 _ You walk into the Capitol
commissary and 500 people simultaneously say, ``Shhh! He's here!''
And No. 1 _ Your new Secret Service code name: ``Roadkill.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
