<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-BLAST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTHORITIES SAY NO EVIDENCE OF BOMB FOUND IN BLAST THAT KILLED
POLICEMAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PHILIP TRUE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ A month-long investigation of an explosion that
killed Tamaulipas police commander Raul Manuel Ruiz Guerra shows
the blast was caused by a slow gas leak in his Reynosa home, the
Mexican attorney general's office said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But federal investigators want to know what happened to the
portable safe Ruiz kept in his home, the attorney general's office
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Tamaulipas authorities who initially investigated the Aug. 25
explosion removed the safe. Shortly thereafter, state investigators
decided they were not the appropriate agency to continue and turned
everything, including a safe, over to the federal attorney
general's office, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   But the safe the attorney general got was not the one removed
from Ruiz's home, the federal officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The safe (found in Ruiz's home) was substituted for another,
which was given to federal authorities,'' the statement said.
``Penal action will be taken against those who are responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz and his housekeeper, Valeria Roman Sanchez, died in the
explosion, which leveled the home.
</P>
<P>
   Immediate and widespread speculation in newspapers from Reynosa
to Mexico City suggested Ruiz might have been assassinated over
some kind of underworld dealings.
</P>
<P>
   Corrupt Mexican police often provide protection to border drug
smugglers, and a spokeswoman for the attorney general here conceded
that state judicial police frequently are found driving automobiles
stolen in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   At least one report published after the explosion revealed that
several automobiles stolen in Texas had been recovered from
Tamaulipas state police in Reynosa and were to be returned. Reynosa
is across the border from McAllen, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   But the investigation of the explosion at Ruiz's home turned up
no traces of explosives or a crater characteristic of a bomb, the
attorney general's statement said.
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz's death was caused by the roof caving in on top of him, and
Roman apparently touched off the accumulated gas while working in
the kitchen, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation continues into whether the gas leak was an
accident, the statement said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
