<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6763 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROOFIES-COX     09-15 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROOFIES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Date rape' drug made easier to spot
 &HT;    By Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Roofies, the Mickey Finn of the '90s, are now easier
to spy after they've been slipped into a drink.
</P>
<P>
   Drug manufacturer Hoffmann-La Roche has reformulated the
powerful sedative Rohypnol so it turns clear liquids blue and some
dark liquids cloudy, thereby alerting unsuspecting people.
</P>
<P>
   Roofies is a street name for Rohypnol, or flunitrazepam, which
is legal in Europe and South America but not in the United States.
However, the drug is widely available illegally in the United
States, where it's also known as roachies, circles, Mexican valium,
rib, R-2, roopies or rope.
</P>
<P>
   Rohypnol's ugliest moniker, the ``date rape'' drug, comes from
its highly publicized role in several acquaintance rapes, including
a series of videotaped sexual assaults carried out over several
years by twin brothers in Marina del Rey, Calif. George and Stefan
Spitzer were convicted in June of drugging women with Rohypnol,
which is 10 times as powerful as Valium, and raping them while they
slept.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Hoffmann-La Roche began considering altering
Rohypnol to alert the unwary.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company felt horrified that anybody would misuse it, so we
tried to do what we could,'' said spokeswoman Gail Safian.
</P>
<P>
   Arming Rohypnol with a bitter taste proved impractical, as the
enormous amount of flavor additive required would have made the
pills too large to be swallowed easily or would have affected the
drug's pharmaceutical properties. Hoffmann-La Roche had to consider
the more than 1 million people worldwide who legally take Rohypnol,
which belongs to the same family of drugs as Valium, Ativan and
Halcyon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very difficult process, because the most important
thing was that we didn't want to affect the therapeutic value of
the product,'' Safian said.
</P>
<P>
   In October 1997, Hoffmann-La Roche settled on using a coloring
agent to make Rohypnol visible in liquid. The manufacturer also
added a film coating to the small tablets, which are tough to crush
into a powder, so they now take up 40 minutes to dissolve.
</P>
<P>
   The dye isn't completely foolproof, however. An opaque,
milky-colored drink such as a white Russian probably would change
hue, Safian said, but the dye might not show up at all in red wine
and other very dark drinks _ or a cocktail made with blue curacao
liqueur.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffmann-La Roche timed release of the reformulated tablets of
Rohypnol in each of the 80 countries where it is legal to ensure
that supplies of the old version were depleted. The company
believes little, if any, of the old version remains in circulation.
Rohypnol is extremely difficult to manufacture in a home lab, so
the authentic product is preferred among illicit users, according
to the National Institute on Drug Abuse. The drug primarily enters
the United States via overnight mail or delivery services from
Mexico and Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Drug Enforcement Agency isn't satisfied. It wants to
reclassify Rohypnol, intended to treat sleep disorders, as a
Schedule I drug under the Controlled Substances Act. Schedule I
drugs are considered to have no medical purpose and a high
potential for abuse.
</P>
<P>
   But Safian and others are quick to point out that, despite the
enormous negative publicity surrounding Rohypnol, it is by no means
the only drug notorious for its use in sexual assault.
</P>
<P>
   A major problem is GHB, gamma-hydroxybutyrate, an illegal drug
that causes psychedelic effects when taken recreationally but acts
as a sedative in high doses. Its nicknames say a lot: ``Grievous
Bodily Harm'' and ``Easy Lay.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, a sophomore at the State University of West
Georgia unknowingly drank GHB in water and went into a coma. Holly
Harman remains in a nursing home in Carrollton.
</P>
<P>
   GHB, an odorless, colorless liquid, continues to show up at
college parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can get a buzz similar to alcohol, without the calories,''
explains Heather Hepler Surrency, a health educator at Georgia
Tech. ``We've heard that's preferable to some women on campus.''
</P>
<P>
   GHB is arguably a bigger concern than Rohypnol, Surrency said,
because it can be easily synthesized in a home lab with readily
available materials. Recipes for GHB are published on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the most pervasive factor in sexual assault is alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alcohol is probably a part of 90 percent of all campus
rapes,'' said Gloria Varley, a health educator at the University of
Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Since June 1996, Hoffman-La Roche has offered free testing of
U.S. rape victims for the presence of Rohypnol in their urine. Of
1,200 tests performed, only six were positive for Rohypnol, Safian
said. But 700 samples turned up other substances, with the most
common being alcohol, the second marijuana and the third
amphetamines and cocaine. Fifty tests were positive for GHB.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's going on is that people are doing recreational drugs
and losing control of the situation,'' Safian said. ``You can
become vulnerable that way _ far more frequently than somebody
dropping something into your drink.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
