u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AFGHAN-TALIBAN-U.N.-N     09-15 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFGHAN-TALIBAN-U.N.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALIBAN PRESS U.N. TO EASE TENSIONS WITH IRAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also IRAN-AFGHAN) 
(mk) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The Taliban movement, aware of its isolation in
the face of an Iranian military threat, asked the United Nations
again Tuesday to establish a mediation process for defusing
tensions with Tehran over the recent killings of Iranian diplomats
in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   The Taliban's deputy representative in New York, Noorullah
Zadran, said he had presented a fourth request to the United
Nations Tuesday after three previous ones ``fell on deaf ears.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have indicated to the United Nations that we are ready to
sit down with the Iranians and accept the mediation of the United
Nations,'' he said. ``We are asking Kofi Annan to do it for us.''
Annan is the U.N. secretary-general.
</P>
<P>
   Zadran said the Taliban, who do not hold Afghanistan's U.N. seat
even though they control almost all of the country, were also
asking the Islamic Conference organization to mediate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Iranians have chosen the use of force,'' he said in an
interview. ``We would like to pose that question to the conscience
of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   U.N. officials say that they are willing to discuss sending
relief supplies to people in Afghanistan caught in recent fighting
_ if the safety of aid workers can be guaranteed _ but that they
were a long way from intervening to ease tensions.
</P>
<P>
   Alvaro de Soto, assistant secretary-general for political
affairs, said Tuesday, ``There isn't any talk of negotiations, at
least with a role for us, quite yet.''
</P>
<P>
   De Soto said the Taliban could take their own measures to defuse
tensions. ``By investigating properly and dealing with the killings
that apparently have occurred, and making sure that those
unaccounted for are accounted for,'' he said, ``there are a lot of
things that can be done without actual negotiations taking place.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, the Security Council condemned the killing of the
Iranian diplomats and said that the act had seriously increased
tension in the region.
</P>
<P>
   The Taliban have damaged their relations with the United Nations
in recent months by refusing to relax restrictions on women and
refusing to cooperate with U.N. representatives and private relief
organizations in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   Kofi Annan's spokesman, Fred Eckhard, said Tuesday that the
secretary-general would like to send a relief mission ``as soon as
possible'' to the Afghan city of Bamiyan, which fell to the Taliban
on Sunday. But U.N. officials say they need guarantees of safety.
</P>
<P>
   Zadran said all of the roads to Bamiyan were now open and safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who wants to give us humanitarian aid is welcome,'' he
said. He also said the United Nations, the International Committee
of the Red Cross and journalists are invited to go to recently
captured territory around Mazar-i-Sharif and Bamiyan to investigate
allegations of Taliban atrocities against the Hazara, a
predominantly Shiite Muslim ethnic group, and allegations of
atrocities against Iranians trapped in those regions. Iran had been
giving military assistance to the Hazara.
</P>
<P>
   Zadran repeated denials by the Taliban that their forces may
have killed thousands of Hazara last month in the Mazar-i-Sharif
area, where several thousand Taliban troops were slain last year
and buried in wells and mass graves. The Taliban say Iranians were
involved in those killings.
</P>
<P>
   ``They now have indicated that there are new mass graves, and we
would like to see them,'' Zadran said.
</P>
<P>
   No independent confirmation of the massacre report has been
possible. There has been no U.N. presence in the area for months
because of looting by the mujahedeen, the fighters who previously
held the town. The Taliban are asking the United Nations to go back
now that Mazar-i-Sharif is under their control.
</P>
<P>
   The Taliban are clearly unsettled by the scale of the Iranian
military threat since the Taliban's own admission that their forces
killed nine Iranians thought to be diplomats in Mazar-i-Sharif and
reports that it may be holding other Iranians who are not accounted
for.
</P>
<P>
   The Taliban are also reported to be having problems with
Pakistan, an ally. The Pakistanis are split over support for them
and cannot always be expected to act in their interest, some
Taliban officials say. Zadran said two Pakistanis had been charged
Tuesday with the slaying of a U.N. military observer in Kabul in
August, a crime for which the Taliban were being held responsible.
</P>
</TEXT>
