<DOCNO> NYT19980915.0331 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6772 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-POLL-ART-2TAK     09-15 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-POLL-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S JOB-APPROVAL RATING IS HIGH; NOT SO HIS CHARACTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: poll graphics are being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
1-888-603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(th) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE with JANET ELDER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The public's view of President Clinton's moral character has
sunk to the lowest level of his presidency, but most Americans say
they still believe that he is a vigorous leader who should not be
impeached or forced to resign, the latest New York Times/CBS News
Poll shows.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly but steadily, the public's perception of Clinton's
personal image has slipped since January, when Americans first
learned of his relationship with a former White House intern. But
over time, the cumulative shift has been sharp.
</P>
<P>
   In itself, the report released last week by Kenneth Starr, the
Whitewater independent counsel, seemed to have little additional
impact on these attitudes. Americans said that they dislike Starr
and suspect his motives. While only one in 20 respondents said they
had read the full report and about half had read part of it, most
people said the graphic sexual details were unnecessarily salacious
and intended to embarrass the president.
</P>
<P>
   And despite the glare of publicity about his affair, Clinton's
job approval rating stands at 62 percent, which is impressive by
any reckoning.
</P>
<P>
   Still, by several measures, the survey showed that most people
now see Clinton as bereft of the code of ethics that they try to
live by. Sixty-six percent of Americans said Clinton did not share
their moral values, while 29 percent said he did.
</P>
<P>
   In January, the public was divided on Clinton's morals, and
after his re-election two years ago, a majority perceived Clinton
as someone who did share their ethical standards. And for the first
time since Democrats lost the House in 1994 _ and only the second
time in Clinton's six years in office _ more Americans viewed the
president unfavorably than favorably.
</P>
<P>
   While people say they want to put the scandal behind them, they
also want Clinton to be reprimanded for his conduct _ but not
impeached or forced from office. Fifty-seven percent of those
polled said Congress should vote to censure Clinton; 33 percent
were opposed to censure.
</P>
<P>
   More than six of 10 Americans said they thought the best thing
for the country was for Clinton to finish his term. In answer to
another question, 58 percent said it was not necessary for Congress
to hold impeachment hearings at all.
</P>
<P>
   The public's personal view of Clinton has diminished roughly
equally among all groups, rich and poor, urban and rural, young and
old, male and female. For example, the perception that Clinton
shares the moral values of most Americans has dropped by 10
percentage points among men and by 14 percentage points among women
_ not much of a gap.
</P>
<P>
   The poll of 1,813 adults nationwide, conducted Saturday through
Monday, also found that the public blamed Clinton and not his
enemies for the crisis, a change from a few months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-four percent blamed Clinton and 36 percent blamed his
enemies _ figures that have roughly reversed since February. More
and more, people have come to believe that Clinton probably did
encourage Monica Lewinsky to lie under oath.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest survey, 46 percent said he did encourage her to
lie, 18 percent said he did not and 32 percent said they did not
know. When respondents were pressed, the numbers were even more
stark; 61 percent said Clinton encouraged Ms. Lewinsky to lie. The
poll has a margin of sampling error of plus or minus two percentage
points.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even against these harsh judgments, Clinton is protected by
an important bulwark that has confounded the pundits _ as well as
the president's Republican detractors _ since the scandal broke:
the measures of Clinton not as a man but as a president continue to
be strikingly strong. He is seen as an effective leader by 66
percent of those polled.
</P>
<P>
   And Clinton's job approval rating, which White House officials
have clung to as their best evidence that the scandal has not
tarnished his command of the office, stands at 62 percent. Earlier
this month it was 60 percent, and last month, immediately after he
told the nation he had had an inappropriate relationship with Ms.
Lewinsky, it was 65 percent. When the scandal broke in January,
Clinton's job approval rating was 56 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's running the country well,'' said Morley Fogel, 61, a
retired salesman and a Democrat from Tequesta, Fla. ``He's just not
running his life very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Fogel, a poll respondent who was re-interviewed Tuesday, added,
``He's ruined a legacy that he could have left as a president who
turned around the economy. Instead, he'll be remembered as a
philanderer.''
</P>
<P>
   Another respondent, Victoria Livingston, 72, a retired teacher
in Phoenix who is registered to vote as an independent, put it this
way: ``This situation upsets me a lot. But I think he should be
allowed to finish out his term. What he's done is a personal thing.
It doesn't have anything to do with what he's doing for the
country. He's done a very good job for the country.''
</P>
<P>
   The poll showed that people continued to draw a sharp
distinction between the president's personal and public lives.
Fifty-eight percent said they viewed the situation more as a
private matter, while 35 percent said it was more a public matter
having to do with Clinton's job as President.
</P>
<P>
   But presidential approval ratings can plummet sharply. The last
president to serve two terms, Ronald Reagan, also enjoyed high
approval ratings in his second term. But his ratings fell 21 points
from October to November of 1986 _ to 46 percent _ amid public
concern over the Iran-Contra affair. It was the sharpest one-month
drop ever recorded in presidential approval.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
