<HEADER>
A6774 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELIMINATE-TX-IMMIGRAN     09-15 0047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIMINATE-TX-IMMIGRANTS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
Tuesday, Sept. 15, 1998
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Editors: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TX-IMMIGRANTS (undated) _ The TX-IMMIGRANTS story will not move
tonight on the Hearst News wire service. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-98 1959EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980915.0333 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6776 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-POLL-ART-2NDT     09-15 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-POLL-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: presidential approval. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   While people were critical of what Starr included in the report,
they also disapproved of how Congress had handled the matter.
Thirty-seven percent said the House did the right thing in
releasing Starr's report, with all the graphic sexual details,
while 59 percent said the full report should not have been
released.
</P>
<P>
   Despite those concerns about how lawmakers are handling the
crisis, Congress as an institution drew a higher approval rating
for the job it was doing than it had since the Times/CBS poll first
began asking about congressional job ratings, in 1974. Fifty-six
percent of Americans now say they approve of the way Congress is
doing its job.
</P>
<P>
   Those ratings are an encouraging sign for incumbents as their
general election campaigns begin in full force. But the survey
offered few clues as to how the scandal might reverberate on
Election Day. Seventy-four percent said the scandal would have no
effect on whom they supported for Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The Lewinsky matter seems to have had little effect on voters'
images of the two parties, according to a CBS News poll taken
before the Starr report was made public. More than half of the
public said they held a favorable view of the Democratic party,
roughly the same number who said they had a positive view of the
Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   In that poll, the images of the parties remained similar to what
they were in the last election. Democrats were perceived as the
party that would make better decisions on social issues like
education and health care. Republicans were seen as being tougher
on crime and better at upholding traditional family values.
</P>
<P>
   Both parties were seen as offering candidates with similar
levels of honesty and integrity. But over all, the Republican Party
was considered to have higher ethical standards than the Democratic
Party.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the appetite for Clinton to be censured, only 32 percent
in the latest Times/CBS News Poll said it would be better for the
country for him to resign. Asked, in another question, if it turned
out that Clinton did in fact obstruct justice, 22 percent said he
should apologize, 30 percent said he should resign, 19 percent said
he should be impeached and 26 percent said the matter should just
be dropped.
</P>
<P>
   And regardless of what they think should happen, in the end, 18
percent said they expected Clinton to be impeached, 11 percent said
he would resign and 62 percent said neither would happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Congress has the stomach for an impeachment
proceeding,'' said George O'Donnell, 44, a poll respondent from
Marion, Iowa. O'Donnell, an independent who is a motor vehicle
inspector, said censure was a fitting punishment. ``A censure, if
you look at it like a plea bargain or reduced charges, says, `You
lied. We know it. But we're going to let you continue your term.'
''
</P>
<P>
   A Republican respondent from Buffalo, N.Y., who identified
herself only as Marie, also distinguished between the president's
private behavior and public performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``This country seems to be doing very well, and I don't see that
a personal problem has anything to do with running the country,''
said Marie, 66, a retired restaurant owner. ``The stock market is
doing well. There are more jobs for people. Basically, I think the
American people are happier than they've been in many years.''
</P>
<P>
   In another sign that many people are sympathetic with Clinton's
predicament, 53 percent said it would be understandable that he
would lie under oath or encourage Ms. Lewinsky to lie under oath
about their sexual conduct; 41 percent said it would not be
understandable.
</P>
<P>
   As speculation swirls over how Clinton's travails will affect
Vice President Al Gore, the survey found that his favorability
rating has not been noticeably affected. Twenty-four percent have a
favorable view of Gore; 21 percent unfavorable, and most people are
undecided or do not know enough about him.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton's support has been buoyed by the
revelations about her husband's infidelity. Fifty-percent of
Americans have a favorable opinion of her, and 25 percent
unfavorable.
</P>
<P>
   And while Speaker Newt Gingrich has sought to cast himself as a
statesman and above partisanship in dealing with the scandal, he is
still viewed more unfavorably than favorably by the public.
Twenty-four percent give him a favorable rating, 31 percent view
him unfavorably and the remainder are undecided or do not know
enough about the speaker.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's negative ratings, while reasonably consistent, are also
high. Forty-three percent of Americans said their view of him is
not favorable, 23 percent said it was favorable and the rest are
undecided or do not know. Fifty-percent said Starr's report was
mostly a one-sided look at some facts, while 35 percent said it was
fair and balanced.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of it could be politically motivated,'' said a poll
respondent, Marcelline Farris, 47, a nurse in Lenore, W. Va., who
is a Democrat. ``They've been hounding him since he's been in
office. The country needs to move on. He's human.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, many Republican lawmakers say it is their expectation
that the polls will shift to the point where Clinton's job approval
ratings will suffer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything this big has got to have some impact on the polls,''
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., said in an interview.
``But it won't be reflected for days or even weeks. The average man
and woman out there didn't spend the weekend reading the Starr
report.''
</P>
</TEXT>
