<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PENTAGON-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILITARY LEADERS TELL CLINTON OF STRAINS ON ARMED FORCES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Turning his attention to military issues amid the
furor over his personal conduct, President Clinton met Tuesday with
the nation's senior generals and admirals and received warnings
that the armed forces are being stretched thin by increasing duties
and decreasing budgets.
</P>
<P>
   Led by Defense Secretary William Cohen and the chairman of the
Joint Chiefs of Staff, Gen. Henry Shelton of the Army, the
uniformed chiefs of the armed services and the unified commands
laid out what amounted to a plea for more money to address the
strains.
</P>
<P>
   Those strains have manifested themselves, officials at the
Pentagon say, in everything from cuts in training to shortages of
parts for fighter jets to the gap between military and civilian
pay.
</P>
<P>
   The officers did not make specific requests to increase the
Pentagon's $270 billion budget, which Congress is finalizing for
the fiscal year that begins next month. But in a series of brief,
militarily precise presentations, they made the case that the
budget cuts and personnel reductions since the end of the Cold War
had reached a plateau.
</P>
<P>
   Shelton told Clinton that although the Pentagon could carry out
its mission, the strength and ``readiness'' of some of the nation's
forces were ``nosing down,'' especially those that would be called
upon to reinforce front-line troops in times of crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to pull up before it turns into a nose dive,'' Shelton
said, according to a senior defense official familiar with the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's meeting, at the National Defense University at Fort
McNair in southwest Washington, came in the middle of the political
and legal fight over Clinton's relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
The furor added an unusual undercurrent to the visit by Clinton,
whose relations with the military have always been strained.
</P>
<P>
   It has not escaped notice within the Pentagon that the charges
against Clinton _ having a sexual relationship with a subordinate
and lying about it _ would end the career of any officer, including
each of the men who sat around the table with Clinton on Tuesday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the president's behavior, however, nor the prospect of
impeachment hearings came up in the meeting, which officials
described as militarily direct and businesslike. The president also
did not apologize to the commanders, as he did to his Cabinet last
week and has, repeatedly, to the public.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Cohen did address the issue when asked about it at a news
conference at the Pentagon earlier Tuesday. Cohen, the lone
Republican in Clinton's administration, said that while ``everyone
is disappointed in what has taken place,'' the scandal had not had
any discernible impact on the military or Clinton's ability to
function as commander in chief.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how Clinton's situation differed from that of 1st Lt.
Kelly Flinn, the Air Force bomber pilot discharged after lying
about an affair and disobeying orders to stop it, Cohen replied
that the president was bound not by the Uniform Code of Military
Justice but by the electoral will.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people will pass their judgment on the president
in due course,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton meets once or twice a year with the military commanders
to discuss national security matters around the world, but
Tuesday's meeting, conducted behind closed doors, focused almost
exclusively on readiness, the ability of the armed forces to fight
and win a war.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, the leaders of the Army, Navy, Air Force and
Marine Corps have warned that their forces are being strained by
increased deployments overseas and dwindling reserves. Cohen, too,
has highlighted the issue by touring military bases, including Fort
Drum in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Being stretched thin has produced different problems in each
service. The Air Force has faced shortages of pilots and spare
parts. The Army has estimated that it needs $3 billion to $5
billion more each year to pay for things like the Bosnia
peacekeeping mission and modernization of equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We borrowed from the modernization budget to pay for
training,'' a senior Army official said. ``Now we're having to
borrow money from training to pay for operating the bases.''
</P>
<P>
   In public at least, no one has questioned the Pentagon's ability
to go to war, if needed. But another senior Army officer said
recently it was not clear that the Pentagon could carry out its
stated mission to win two major regional wars at once. While
winning the first war would not be a problem, the officer said,
fighting the second would pose a ``big risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has faced increasing pressure from Republicans in
Congress to increase the military budget, but with the balanced
budget agreement capping the total at $270 billion this year, he
has resisted. In the next budget, however, those caps come off.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon said it was premature to
discuss whether Clinton would propose an increase in the next
budget, but at Tuesday's meeting the president told the commanders
that they should make the same point when they go before Congress
later this month for hearings on the issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
