<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET RALLY CONTINUES FOR THIRD DAY  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By KENNETH N. GILPIN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stock prices rose again Tuesday, the first time
prices have risen for three straight sessions on Wall Street in
more than a month.
</P>
<P>
   Extending a theme sounded in recent days, traders and analysts
said equity prices are responding to statements from policy-makers
in Washington and elsewhere that a coordinated response from
industrialized nations and lending institutions like the
International Monetary Fund to what has come to be seen as a global
economic crisis is under serious consideration.
</P>
<P>
   The most likely first step to resolving the crisis, according to
traders and analysts, is a cut in short-term interest rates by the
Federal Reserve Board and other central banks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think investors are encouraged that policymakers are
considering this as a global crisis rather than isolated
brushfires,'' said Christine Callies, chief investment strategist
at Credit Suisse First Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since investors are concerned that falling asset prices are a
symptom of global problems, bouncing asset prices might be a sign
some of those problems are being relieved. In short, the markets
believe the monetary authorities are going to blink.''
</P>
<P>
   Although more stocks rose in value than declined, the bulk of
the gains were concentrated among blue-chip stocks that make up the
Dow Jones industrial average and high capitalization issues in the
Standard &AMP; Poors 500 index.
</P>
<P>
   By the close, the Dow had gained 79.04 points, to 8,024.39, up
just under 1 percent on the day and the highest level so far this
month. It was the first three-day advance for the Dow since Aug. 5
through Aug. 7, and puts the blue-chip index back above 7,908.25,
where it began the year. Still, the index remains about 1,300
points, or 14 percent, below its July 17 peak of 9,337.97.
</P>
<P>
   The smallish advance was noteworthy for another reason: it is
the first time since Sept. 4, when the Dow fell 41.97 points, that
the closely watched index has not registered a gain or a loss
exceeding 100 points.
</P>
<P>
   Among broader market measures, the Standard &AMP; Poors 500 Index
rose 7.96 points, to 1,037.68. The Nasdaq composite index gained
12.42 points, to 1,678.11.
</P>
<P>
   Al Goldman, chief market strategist at A.G. Edwards in St.
Louis, said the market ``was dull as dishwater until the last 20 to
30 minutes,'' when he said some computerized ``buy'' programs came
in to the market and traders began buying stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Fed chairman Alan Greenspan and Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin
are scheduled to testify Wednesday in front of the House Banking
Committee on the global economy and financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman said the market is pricing in expectations of a cut in
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   However, it is unlikely Greenspan will provide clear signals
about the Fed's intentions during his testimony. Analysts said it
is just as unlikely that Rubin will use the forum as an opportunity
to jawbone the Fed.
</P>
<P>
   But the officials may well use the occasion to urge passage of
the $17.9 billion in additional funding for the IMF requested by
the Clinton administration, financing that would trigger more than
$82 billion in contributions from other member nations.
</P>
<P>
   George Soros, the billionaire hedge fund manager, Tuesday urged
legislators to approve the full amount, telling Congress it can no
longer ignore the ``disintegration of the global capitalist
system.''
</P>
<P>
   Anticipation of interest rate relief and a replenishment of the
IMF's financial resources helped to send equity markets in Mexico
and Brazil soaring Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Brazilian stocks, battered since mid-August when Russia
defaulted on international debts, soared more than 18 percent.
Mexican shares rose by nearly 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Asian markets were also strong, but with the exception of
London, most other European exchanges posted declines.
</P>
<P>
   Prospects of a cut in interest rates and help for troubled
developing country economies helped to strengthen stocks of banks
and other financial services that have been battered by rolling
crises in Asia, Russia and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   Among the biggest gainers were Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, which
climbed 3 3/16, to 56 5/16. American Express rose another 3 3/16,
to 84~. J.P. Morgan was up 2 7/16, to 94 7/16. Providian Financial
Corp. shares soared 11{, to 72 15/16 after the credit card
company's chairman said it could increase earnings by as much as 50
percent this year and next, exceeding analysts' forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   Drugmakers, led by Merck &AMP; Co., also posted strong gains.
</P>
<P>
   Merck, which gained more than 3 on Monday, rose another 3{
Tuesday, to 135{. Eli Lilly &AMP; Co. rose 1[, to 77 5/16. And Bristol
Myers Squibb was up 1[, to 106.
</P>
<P>
   Still, investors continued to punish companies with
deteriorating growth prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola Co., which relies on foreign sales for about 75
percent of its profits, fell 2[ Tuesday to 61 3/16 after Lehman
Brothers analyst Michael Branca cut his 1999 earnings estimate
because of slowing sales in Eastern Europe, Asia and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   Branca also cut his 1999 earnings forecast for Pepsico Inc.
Pepsi lost 1 5/16, to 30.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
