<SLUG> BC-GLOBAL-CRISIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US SEEKS SOLUTIONS TO GLOBAL FINANCIAL CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER G. GOSSELIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ While Americans have been preoccupied with President
Clinton's political troubles, the global financial crisis that
started a year ago in Asia has finally reached the nation's
doorstep. Now everybody from the president on down is scrambling
for solutions.
</P>
<P>
   With billionaire money manager George Soros warning Tuesday of a
``disintegration of the global capitalist system'' and
international economists like David Hale predicting 60 percent of
the planet's population is headed for recession, US policymakers
face an abrupt end to an easy era in which nearly every nation
embraced free markets and everybody wanted US products and dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is changing the global financial landscape,'' said Hale,
the widely respected chief economist of Zurich Kemper Investments
Inc. in Chicago. ``What's really troubling,' he added, ``is that
events of the last few weeks have brought memories of the last
time'' the United States faced the double trouble of economic
upheaval around the world and disarray at home _ during the
political demise of Richard Nixon in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, what worries many analysts is that, now as then,
investigations and impeachment threats will so hobble the president
that he won't be able to use his already limited powers to
influence world economic events. ``I don't think this president is
in any position to deliver on a major global rescue package,'' said
David M. Jones, vice chairman of Aubrey G. Lanston &AMP; Co. in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, there are some things that the United States can do
about the problems abroad, and they will be on prominent display
later Wednesday when Treasury Secretary Robert E. Rubin and Federal
Reserve chairman Alan Greenspan are scheduled to testify at a
congressional hearing on the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan has already hinted that the Fed may reduce interest
rates this year, a move that would offer at least some relief to
teetering economies in Asia, Latin America and elsewhere by
boosting US growth and therefore US imports from those countries.
Rubin aides have suggested that something even grander may be in
the works, perhaps a coordinated rate cut by all of the so-called
Group of Seven nations that comprise the world's economic
powerhouses.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the president and a variety of business leaders,
including Soros, are renewing the pressure on Congress to approve
$17.9 billion for the financially depleted International Monetary
Fund, the multilateral organization that is widely seen as having
mishandled the early stages of the crisis in Asia and Russia, but
is the closest thing the world has to global economic manager.
</P>
<P>
   Merely the hint of help has set off a wild frenzy in financial
markets hard-hit by the crisis. In Brazil, the stock market, which
had lost almost two-thirds of its value in the last month, has
reversed course and soared.
</P>
<P>
   But as events in recent days demonstrated, talking about helping
and delivering help are two, quite different, things. For example,
while US and British officials hinted Monday and again Tuesday that
a coordinated interest rate cut was in the offing, German central
bank president Hans Tietmeyer flatly ruled out such a move.
</P>
<P>
   And while Clinton, in a Monday speech in New York, called for
the United States and its allies to ``adapt the international
financial architecture to the 21st century,'' most analysts
dismissed the call as little more than rhetoric, saying the
president has been too weakened by independent counsel Kenneth W.
Starr's investigation and the threat of impeachment to push through
such changes.
</P>
<P>
   ```Reforming the financial architecture is one of those buzz
phrases you use when you can't do much,'' said Ralph C. Bryant, a
former senior Fed staffer who is now at the Brookings Institution
in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the last year, the principal threat the global
crisis posed for the United States was that of damaging countries
that purchased American goods or produced overseas profits for
US-based companies. Analysts said that much of the sudden slowdown
in corporate profits that has sent US stock prices tumbling in
recent months is traceable to disappointing overseas sales.
</P>
<P>
   But as the crisis has spread around the world it has taken on
several frightening new dimensions, according to analysts. It has
begun striking indiscriminately, bringing down both economies with
deep-seated problems like Russia's and those that are widely
believed to be healthy, like Brazil's. And it has struck with
lightning speed, draining away the currency reserves of nations
that would otherwise be capable of paying their bills, much like a
bank run.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's going on in many countries is not a sober response to
changing market conditions, but a financial panic that producing
unnecessary upheaval,'' said Harvard economist Jeffrey Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   In calmer times, the IMF could have stepped in to act a lender
of last resort and provide the funds that reassure depositors and
investors they could witdraw their money if they wanted. But with
so many crises around the world and with the United States refusing
to make additional contributions, the IMF's capital is now largely
depleted. ``It's hard to have a lender of last resort when the
lender is out of money,'' said former Deputy Treasury Secretary
Robert Glauber.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF's failure to stem the crisis is spawning a laundry list
of proposals for revamping the global financial system, including
one advanced Tuesday by financier Soros for a sort of international
deposit insurance. But to sell any of the ideas to Congress and a
balky international community would require strong presidential
leadership, something that most analysts said Clinton has little
ability to provide in the wake of the White House sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that in choosing to focus on the global crisis
Clinton is making a smart political move. Much as he did during his
1992 campaign, when he used former President Bush's conviction the
US economy was on the rebound to make him appear out of touch, the
president is drawing attention to the refusal by House Republicans
to approve additional IMF funding to make them appear isolationist
and extreme.
</P>
<P>
   But substantively, analysts said there is little that Clinton
can do to repair the global mess. ``He has no levers to pull at
this point,'' said J. Bradford DeLong, a former deputy assistant
Treasury secretary in the administration.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
