<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMAN SOCIALISTS TURN FROM SLOGANS TO JINGLES  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By EDMUND L. ANDREWS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ Until recently, Detmar Karpinski's biggest
accomplishment was advertising Lucky Strike cigarettes. Today, he
is producing one of the slickest and most American-style political
advertising campaigns that Germany has ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   Hired by the Social Democratic Party and its candidate for
chancellor, Gerhard Schroeder, Karpinski as created a media
campaign that is an artful dance between cozy images of a happy
Germany and edgy criticism of Chancellor Helmut Kohl.
</P>
<P>
   A commercial playing in movie theaters shows four astronauts in
a Star Trek setting about to be ``beamed'' to another planet. When
the beaming is over, one astronaut is left behind and he turns out
to be a corpulent and befuddled Kohl. The message: the 68-year-old
chancellor is ``not ready for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   In a blitz on television, on billboards and in glossy magazines,
Social Democratic ads combine images of gauzy warmth with a sneaky
punchline. Billboard posters, aimed a provoking fears about cuts in
health care, show a blond boy whose smile reveals a missing tooth.
``We don't want to tell the difference between rich and poor just
through a smile,'' reads the biting caption. A magazine ad centers
on an aging, framed photograph of beautiful children and the
slogan: ``You should have more in your retirement than memories.''
</P>
<P>
   These and a barrage of other ads mark a major departure from the
dull and didactic fare that have usually graced German political
campaigns. They are also a far cry from the old-school ads for
Kohl, whose most ubiquitous campaign poster features his picture
and the slogan ``World Class for Germany.''
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder and his campaign managers have adopted techniques used
by Ronald Reagan, Bill Clinton and Tony Blair. They have focused
relentlessly on feelings rather than facts. They have carefully
honed their themes based on market research. And they began mapping
their strategy more than 18 months ago, before Schroeder even
became the party's official candidate in the election, which is set
for Sept. 27.
</P>
<P>
   ``The SPD had an image that was somewhat old-fashioned and
needed to be modernized,'' said Karpinski, creative director for
the Hamburg-based advertising agency KNSK-BBDO, referring to the
Social Democrats. ``One had the impression that they didn't really
want to win an election, that they just wanted to be in the
opposition.''
</P>
<P>
   Advertising plays a much smaller role in Germany than in the
United States. The Social Democrats say they are spending about 40
million marks ($23.5 million) on paid advertising, though Kohl's
party, the Christian Democrats, insist the spending is much
greater. Their own spending, they say, is about $30 million.
</P>
<P>
   But the Social Democrats say they have systematically used
advertising, sometimes to illustrate a new stylishness. Inasmuch a
the advertising is clever and fast-paced, it appeals to younger and
more video-savvy voters who have grown up watching MTV. Indeed,
party officials used the first wave of campaign posters for the
sole purpose of showing them to journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Negative political advertising, prominent in American campaigns,
has been almost non-existent here. Though Germany's high
unemployment rate under Kohl is the Social Democrats' most
important theme, party officials say that attack ads would have
alarmed voters.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Karpinski has produced a campaign loaded with happy
images and with a critical message at the end. One television ad
describes the things people strive for and shows families and
children, hikers and bicyclists, playgrounds and modern factories.
The screen then abruptly goes black, and a message reads: ``But 4
million unemployed Germans can't.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Negative advertising can work, but it would be wrong in this
country,'' said Karpinski. ``We didn't want to frighten people with
attack ads. We wanted to make them comfortable with the party, so
the images you see are always positive an optimistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Kohl and the Christian Democrats briefly tried negative
advertising but quickly retreated. Known as the ``red-handed''
campaign, Christian Democratic billboards warned darkly that the
Social Democrats might join forces with the successor to East
Germany's old Communist Party, the Party of Democratic Socialism.
Billboards showed two red hands shaking, with the slogan ``Watch
out, Germany!''
</P>
<P>
   But Christian Democrat supporters say the ads repelled many
people because they seemed overly alarmist. Though Kohl continues
to warn about alliances with the Communists, the red-handed posters
have all but disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
