<SLUG> BC-CHINA-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S., CHINA SOLIDIFY PLANS FOR MILITARY EXERCISES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Secretary of Defense William Cohen received pledges
from China's senior military leader Tuesday that China would move
ahead with modest joint military exercises and exchanges with the
United States next year.
</P>
<P>
   Following up on agreements made by Presidents Clinton and Jiang
Zemin at their summit meeting in Beijing in June, Cohen and Gen.
Zhang Wannian also signed a pact at the Pentagon to share
information on tackling environmental problems caused by the forces
of each country. These include cleaning up pollution and dealing
with waste produced by the armies of the United States and China.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen announced that Chinese officers would take part in
exercises in 1999 simulating military responses to natural
disasters or humanitarian crises and would send a naval ship to
visit the United States. The two men also agreed to a series of
exchanges of military students and officers.
</P>
<P>
   Zhang, senior vice chairman of China's Central Military
Commission, met at the White House Tuesday with the president's
national security adviser, Samuel Berger. Clinton met briefly with
the general at that meeting, which focused on a broader range of
issues, including North Korea and the spread of weapons of mass
destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen and the Clinton administration have been eager to increase
contacts with China's military as a way to reduce tensions.
</P>
</TEXT>
