<HEADLINE>
BUSH REFUSES TO OFFER VIEW OF CLINTON TROUBLES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Former President Bush, while acknowledging
``concern,'' refused Tuesday to offer his view of President
Clinton's troubles brought on by an affair with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've tried to stay out of it,'' Bush said at his vacation home
in Kennebunkport, Maine. ``I've said that I feel awkward in
commenting on anything that's going on in Washington now.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a second reason,'' Bush said. ``It relates to the
governor of Texas and to our son in Florida.'' He referred to Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas, who is campaigning for re-election in
November, and Jeb Bush, who is the Republican gubernatorial nominee
in the Sunshine State.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush is rated a prohibitive favorite against Democrat
Garry Mauro, and Jeb Bush is given an edge over Florida Lt. Gov.
Buddy McKay. Like their father, both Bush sons are Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't want to inadvertently complicate their lives by
having people rush down and say, ``Your dad says x, y and z, what
do you think?' and put them kind of on the spot,'' the elder Bush
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've tried for six years not to criticize my successor, and I
think that's been a wise policy,'' said Bush, who was defeated by
Clinton for re-election in 1992. ``I have huge differences and
certainly, as you can imagine, I have concern on what's going
on.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
