<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6803 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-BOOK-HNS &LR;      09-15 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-BOOK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH SAYS SUPPORT OF ISRAEL MAKES U.S. LOSE CREDIBILITY IN MIDDLE
EAST 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration is seen by Arab states
as so ``totally one-sided'' in its support of Israel that U.S.
credibility is ``sinking'' in the Middle East, former President
George Bush said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said lack of Arab trust would make it virtually impossible
to reassemble the U.S.-led coalition that drove Iraq from Kuwait in
the 1991 Persian Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under existing circumstances I don't think we could get it
back together the way it was,'' said Bush, who rallied a number of
Arab nations against Iraqi strong man Saddam Hussein. ``I don't
know what would trigger the need'' to reassemble the coalition,
``but I would be very concerned that we could not patch it back
together under existing views of the United States in that part of
the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The president is awaiting publication on Sept. 28 of the book,
``A World Transformed,'' that he has written with his former
national security adviser, Brent Scowcroft. The book is a
commentary about the tumultuous world events that marked Bush's
four years in the White House, including the collapse of the Soviet
Union and the war against Iraq's invasion of its oil-rich neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   Scowcroft participated with Bush in the telephone interview from
the former president's vacation home in Kennebunkport, Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush was willing to criticize the Clinton
administration's Middle East policy, he refused substantive comment
on his successor's troubles stemming from an affair with Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The Gulf War coalition issue arose from Scowcroft's answer to a
question about why Saudi Arabia seems to be refusing to cooperate
in the investigation of a 1996 terrorist bomb attack on a U.S.
military base near Dhahran in which 19 Americans were killed. Saudi
Arabia was the chief staging area for the war, and a major
rationale for the conflict was to protect the vast Saudi oil
operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say that the Saudis' behavior is understandable from
their perspective,'' Scowcroft, a retired Air Force general, said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it disappointing to us? Yes it is,'' he said. ``But I think
the Saudis look at the situation out in the Middle East and the
Gulf and see what they call a double standard: that we urge them to
support us in beating up on Saddam when he steps out of line, and
yet they look across to the (Arab-Israeli) peace process and see
the Israelis trashing the Oslo accord, not filling it out and we do
nothing but say tut-tut.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I think it is that double standard which gives them a lot
of problems,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Arab leaders have criticized the Clinton administration for
refusing to secure scheduled Israeli pullbacks from occupied
territory, including the West Bank, as well not implementing
power-sharing deadlines with the Palestinian Authority.
</P>
<P>
   Bush picked up voluntarily on his former adviser's theme.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that we are seen, fairly or not ... as totally
one-sided in the Middle East ... is hurting us in our ability to
get things done with those countries,'' Bush said. ``They just
honestly believe that the (Clinton) administration is unwilling to
press for ... (Israeli adherence to) agreements that already have
been made ... and I'm afraid our credibility is sinking in that
important part of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Scowcroft said that reassembling the coalition would be
``inordinately difficult'' but not impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Saddam ``has not become a darling of the Arab world,'' Scowcroft
said. ``They still dislike him. They still would like to get rid of
him. It is this double standard that gives them the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the book-writing process, Bush said: ``I couldn't
remember. I had a bad memory, and it's not anecdotal.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said Scowcroft had ``much better command of the facts and
history than I did'' but ``even he was found wanting from time to
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Both praised their research assistant, James McCall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you see some documents then the whole story starts to
come back,'' Scowcroft said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said his overall world view is ``optimistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite ``some huge problems,'' Bush said: ``I see that there's
no longer a gigantic, almost monolithic superpower enemy. That's
resulted in the fact that there are more market economies, more
democracies, more freedom around the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Scowcroft described himself a ``a contingent optimist.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the world is potentially a better place, but there are
number of little problems, and I fear that we are not taking full
advantage of this respite, if you will, in world conflict to build
the kind of world that we would like to leave to our
grandchildren,'' Scowcroft said.
</P>
<P>
   During their tenure, Scowcroft said, ``there were enormous
forces of history working.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the end of one of the most intense periods in world
history, and its unwinding was inordinately complicated. And as I
look back on it (I am) amazed that it came out almost literally
without a shot being fired.''
</P>
<P>
   Scowcroft cited the end of the Cold War, with the dissolution of
the Soviet Union, as the historic touchstone of the era, and Bush
added the reunification of Germany
</P>
<P>
   Bush recalled having to ``bring the British and French along''
on backing reunification. It was one of the few major points on
which he had a major policy disagreement with Margaret Thatcher,
then prime minister of Britain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she was wary for historical, understandable reasons,''
Bush said. ``We understood that. But I felt that (Germany) had
earned their place in the world and that they would do what
(Chancellor Helmut) Kohl indicated to us that they'd do, and that's
be unified, be free, allied to the West.''
</P>
<P>
   Scowcroft, playing the bad cop, recalled that French President
Francois Mitterrand went a bit farther with his opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``He even worked a bit, tested out (Russian leader Mikhail)
Gorbachev to see if there was something that maybe couldn't be done
to slow down or to stop German unification,'' Scowcroft said. ``But
in the end, Mitterrand was a realist. He said if Germany's
determined to unify, there isn't anything we can do about it. After
all, we're not going to war with Germany.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
