<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-LEGISLATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS HAS FULL PLATE AS IT RUSHES TO ADJOURN OCT. 9 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As Congress rushes to adjourn for the year on Oct.
9, lawmakers are having to make a lot of tough decisions, including
how to keep the government running, as it wrestles with a scandal
that could force President Clinton from the White House.
</P>
<P>
   But chances are, Clinton still will be behind his desk at 1600
Pennsylvania Avenue when Congress finally sends him the remaining
1999 spending bills.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble is, those bills probably won't cross his desk until
after the start of the new fiscal year on Oct. 1, and Clinton may
not be inclined to sign them if they include reductions in
education and other programs he favors and tax cuts that are paid
for with projected surpluses. He has said those must be used to
shore up Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   In order to avoid a veto or standoff that could lead to a
government shutdown, Republicans on Capitol Hill are increasingly
talking about a continuing resolution that would keep affected
federal agencies and departments open and operating at present
funding levels.
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Irving, acknowledged Tuesday
that a temporary funding measure likely will be passed on Sept. 30
to give Congress and the White House more time to negotiate their
differences over issues such as funding for the United Nations and
the International Monetary Fund, not to mention an $80 million tax
cut proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Armey said that the funding measure would run at least through
Oct. 9, the day Congress is to adjourn for the year, and would be a
``plain vanilla'' spending item that would keep the government
operating at ``existing funding levels.''
</P>
<P>
   But by Oct. 9th, he said ``we'll have everything pretty cleaned
up'' in terms of ironing out differences over spending legislation
with the administration.
</P>
<P>
   The cleaning up, however, will depend on whether Clinton is
inclined to go along with Republican demands rather than fight
them.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans are banking on the Monica Lewinsky scandal and
the threat of impeachment to keep him in line. But Democrats are
putting pressure on Clinton not to give in on such issues as
education funding and his opposition to tax cuts from the surplus.
They believe those issues could help them in the November
elections.
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., said recently that
Clinton had assured him that he will not sign a tax cut measure
``that's paid for by the surplus.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe we have the votes to sustain a veto, if it comes to
that,'' Gephardt said.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt also said Congress won't be able to complete all its
work over the next three weeks, making it inevitable that a
continuing resolution of some sort will have to be passed to keep
some government agencies and programs running until next year.
</P>
<P>
   Congress still has a lot on its plate over the next three weeks,
including bankruptcy legislation, HMO reforms, fast-track
negotiating authorities, and various appropriations measures.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest issue emerging in these last days is the $80
billion tax cut proposal being floated by House Ways Chairman Bill
Archer, R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Archer's five-year plan would be financed by part of the $1.6
trillion surplus projected over the next decade. The congressman
insists, however, that most of the surplus would be set aside to
ensure that Social Security doesn't go broke.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as we make it very clear that we are committed to
saving Social Security, the American people think there should be
some of the surplus given back to them,'' Archer said Tuesday. ``We
need to be sure we infuse more money back into the pockets of
taxpayers.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-98 2012EDT &QL; 
