<SLUG> BC-LINCOLN-CENTER-GIFT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LINCOLN CENTER GETS GIFT OF $25 MILLION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo of the Robertsons is being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By RALPH BLUMENTHAL    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A record $25 million has been given to Lincoln Center
for the Performing Arts by a new board member, Julian H. Robertson
Jr., the hedge fund investor. Announcing the gift Tuesday, Lincoln
Center officials said the fountain plaza was being renamed in honor
of Robertson's wife, Josie.
</P>
<P>
   They called it the largest single gift to the center by an
individual and said the money would be divided among Lincoln
Center's own artistic programs and its 12 constituent members, with
the largest share going to members through outright grants.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the gift even more unusual is that it was given in a
lump sum instead of being spread out over several years, as large
contributions often are. Among other things, the money will help
underwrite new series, like one on American popular standards that
is to start in February, said Nathan Leventhal, Lincoln Center's
president.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson, 66, chairman and chief executive officer of Tiger
Management, the multibillion dollar investment fund he and a
partner started with $8 million in 1980, said he intended the gift
as a surprise for his wife, who was not to learn of it until a
ceremony Tuesday night on the south portico of Avery Fisher Hall
overlooking the new Josie Robertson Plaza.
</P>
<P>
   The Revson Fountain will retain its name in honor of a 1962 gift
by the Revlon Foundation in honor of the cosmetics executive
Charles Revson.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson said the gift grew out of discussions with Beverly
Sills, the chairwoman of Lincoln Center, before he joined the
Lincoln Center board this summer. ``I asked Beverly if something
there was appropriate,'' and she suggested the form of the gift.
``It was just perfect,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sharing the money with the artistic constituents seemed
particularly adroit politically in view of Lincoln Center's history
of rivalries over programming and finances.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sills praised the gift, saying, ``I don't expect to have
another $25 million in my hand anytime soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Until now the largest gift to Lincoln Center was $15 million,
given nearly 10 years ago by Fred Rose of Rose Associates, the real
estate developers, to build the Rose building, which houses offices
for Lincoln Center and its film society, dormitories for the
Juilliard School and performance space for the Lincoln Center
Institute, which offers teacher training in the arts.
</P>
<P>
   Of the $25 million from Robertson, Lincoln Center said that $10
million would go to create the Josie Robertson Fund for Lincoln
Center in support of artistic programs presented by the center
itself, including Mostly Mozart, the Lincoln Center Festival,
Midsummer Night Swing and Lincoln Center Out of Doors and the
``Live From Lincoln Center'' and ``Great Performances'' television
series.
</P>
<P>
   Producing these programs costs Lincoln Center $18 million a
year, subsidized in part by an existing $6 million artistic
endowment. With the new gift, this portion of the endowment would
grow to $16 million, officials said. In addition, Lincoln Center
has $109 million in other endowment funds, a spokeswoman, Janice
Price, said.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining $15 million of Robertson's gift is to be divided
among the 12 constituents, including Lincoln Center itself, by an
existing grant- and cost-sharing formula related to size.
</P>
<P>
   The largest constituent, the Metropolitan Opera, would receive
about $4 million, and the others would get diminishing amounts down
to $250,000 each for a number of the small constituents, including
the New York Public Library for the Performing Arts.
</P>
<P>
   The others are the New York Philharmonic, the Chamber Music
Society, the New York City Opera, the New York City Ballet, Lincoln
Center Theater, Jazz at Lincoln Center and the School of American
Ballet, along with the film society and Juilliard.
</P>
<P>
   ``The money can be used for anything,'' Ms. Sills said. ``That's
what makes it so unusual.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
