<HEADLINE>
SENATOR PROPOSES $4.4 MILLION COST OF PROBE AS FINE FOR CLINTON 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The wages of sin may not be death, resignation,
censure or impeachment for President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But if Sen. Frank Murkowski has his way, it may be a $4.4
million fine.
</P>
<P>
   That is independent counsel Kenneth Starr's estimate of how much
his office spent in its nearly eight-month investigation of
Clinton's effort to cover up an extramarital relationship with
former White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Murkowski, an Alaskan Republican, suggested Tuesday that the
Senate pass a resolution stating that Clinton should pick up the
tab for taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   Murkowski said the president alone is responsible for the large
expense due to what the senator called Clinton's orchestrated
effort to prevent the truth of his relationship with Lewinsky from
becoming public.
</P>
<P>
   However, Clinton spokesman Mike McCurry said the president has
no intention of paying for Starr's investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Murkowski, in introducing his symbolic resolution, derided
Clinton's ``plan of public deception and delay'' that needlessly
prolonged Starr's probe. ``Equity demands that the costs of the
delays should be borne by the president and not the taxpayers,''
Murkowski said _ an argument McCurry rejected.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Clinton) has pursued perfectly legitimately the legal
processes that he had recourse to,'' McCurry said. ``And, you know,
we didn't instruct Mr. Starr on how to conduct his investigation.
We would have been happy for him not to spend any of that $4.4
million, so, you know, let's be real.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate has not scheduled a vote on the proposed resolution,
said Murkowski's spokesman Chuck Kleeschulte.
</P>
<P>
   The senator's proposal follows the suggestion of Senate
Judiciary Committee Chairman Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, that Congress
could forgo impeachment proceedings and opt instead to censure
Clinton for his affair with Lewinsky and his subsequent efforts to
prevent public disclosure of the relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Such a censure could include a presidential fine in addition to
a congressional statement of disapproval. However, House Majority
Leader Dick Armey, R-Irving, said censure would trivialize the
seriousness of Clinton's alleged offenses, which include perjury,
obstruction of justice, witness tampering and abuse of power.
</P>
<P>
   Murkowski's proposed fine has precedent, of sorts. Last year,
the House fined Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., $300,000 for
providing false information to the House ethics committee regarding
a financial link between a college course he taught and a political
action committee he led.
</P>
<P>
   However, Congress has never fined a president to recoup taxpayer
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's $4,393,923 estimate covers expenses that began Jan. 15,
when a special three-judge panel accepted Attorney General Janet
Reno's request that he be authorized to investigate Clinton's
alleged efforts to cover up his relationship with Lewinsky. The
cost estimate ends Aug. 31, 10 days before Starr delivered to
Congress a 445-page report alleging impeachable offenses and
containing salacious details about the affair.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's cost estimate might quell Democratic criticism of his
wideranging investigation of the president. In addition to the
Lewinsky matter, Starr has investigated allegations of impropriety
in Clinton's failed Whitewater land deal before he became
president, the firing of staff in the White House travel office and
the acquisition of classified FBI files on Republicans from the
Bush administration.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's failure to issue a report on those non-Lewinsky probes
has not been lost on several Clinton supporters, including McCurry,
who have attacked the independent counsel's investigation with the
alliterative mantra that it was a four-year, $40 million
investigation that merely uncovered an adulterous affair. But
Starr's cost estimate indicates that only 10 percent of the $40
million went to investigating the Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
   According to Starr's expense account, $1,861,456 million went to
pay for the services of attorneys and investigators in the Office
of Independent Counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Travel expenses for office staff and grand-jury witnesses
reached $949,895. Starr also spent $884,110 on consultants and
other contractors, $356,494 on rent, communications and utilities,
$186,021 on capital equipment, $82,653 on supplies and services,
and $73,294 on administrative services.
</P>
<P>
   However, Starr's costs do not include the taxpayer money Clinton
has spent protecting what he regards as a president's prerogative
to keep some conversations confidential. For example, Clinton has
waged unsuccessful legal battles to prevent Secret Service agents,
government lawyers and advisers from having to disclose what they
have seen, heard or been told by the president.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Starr's estimate does not account for money that
taxpayers might need to spend on the legal bills of people
subjected to the investigation but not indicted. The independent
counsel law provides for such compensation. For example, former
President George Bush received $272,000 to help cover his bills
related to the Iran-Contra investigation in the 1980s. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
