<SLUG> BC-CHURCHS-CHICKEN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Church's Chickens sets up camp at Phillips 66
 &HT;    By Mickey H. Gramig
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Church's Chicken's latest development deal will allow
Phillips 66 customers to fill up in more ways than one.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based fast-food chain has signed an agreement for
Phillips Petroleum Co. to put full-service Churchs Chicken
restaurants, complete with drive-thrus, in 25 of its company-owned
gas and convenience store locations.
</P>
<P>
   The partnership will help Churchs spread its wings, because most
of its 1,350 restaurants are in the Southeast and the majority of
the Phillips 66 locations are in the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement is the largest such deal that Churchs has signed
for ``alternative venue'' locations, which, though they bring in
lower annual sales, are less expensive to develop and run than
traditional stand-alone locations.
</P>
<P>
   About 40 percent of the 140 franchised restaurants Churchs is
opening this year are in alternative venues, such as grocery or
convenience stores or under the same roof as another fast-food
chain. Currently, the chain has 147 non-traditional locations,
including 74 Churchs that share space with White Castle hamburger
restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very simple concept to operate, it's a simple menu and
we've got a small footprint,'' said Hannibal Myers, Churchs' vice
president of new business development. ``That translates very
easily into an alternative venue, where space is at a premium and
there's a need to provide a restaurant.''
</P>
<P>
   The chain's growth strategy includes continuing the trend of
partnering with other retailers, said Myers, who added that 40
percent to 45 percent of Churchs' new locations will likely be in
alternative venues over the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with a traditional stand-alone Churchs, an alternative
venue location gives a better return on investment.
</P>
<P>
   A stand-alone location, which averages $605,000 in annual sales,
costs about $700,000 to $750,000 to develop and can take anywhere
from nine months to a year to get up and running, Myers said.
</P>
<P>
   A store inside a convenience store, which averages $440,000 in
annual sales, can carry development costs of as little as $100,000
and be open in 60 to 90 days.
</P>
<P>
   The first of the Churchs locations at Phillips 66 stations will
open later this year. The deal could eventually include more than
25 locations.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
