<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cox Radio pumps up the volume in Fla.
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Cox Radio has struck a deal to expand its already
large presence in the Tampa-St. Petersburg, Fla., area, company
officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based radio holding company has reached an agreement
with Concord Media Corp. Inc. to operate Concord's station,
WLVU-FM. The deal includes an option to eventually buy WLVU-FM. Cox
Radio did not disclose the financial terms of the deal but it
includes both cash and trading ownership of Tampa-St. Petersburg
based WSUN-AM to Concord Media.
</P>
<P>
   With the addition of WLVU-FM, Cox Radio will control three FM
and one AM station in the Tampa-St. Petersburg area, the 21st
largest radio market. Cox's stations represent about 14 percent of
the market.
</P>
<P>
   WLVU-FM is a new adult contemporary station and does not yet
have much market share. But Cox Radio plans to improve and expand
its reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``The addition of WLVU-FM is consistent with our opportunistic
strategy to fill in or improve our station clusters,'' said Robert
F. Neil, Cox Radio's president and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   The company, controlled by Atlanta-based Cox Enterprises Inc.,
has been on a buying spree in the past two years. It is not trying
to be the largest radio operator, but instead to dominate fast
growing markets in the West and South. Cox Radio is one of the
country's 10 largest radio holding companies, owning or operating
59 stations in 13 markets. Those markets include Atlanta, with WSB,
as well as Los Angeles, Miami, Orlando, San Antonio and Birmingham.
Cox Enterprises also owns The Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
