<SLUG> BC-GAS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta Gas rivals to get list of users
 &HT;    By Matthew C. Quinn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The Public Service Commission is making it easier for
rivals of Atlanta Gas Light Co. to compete for its 1.4 million
users by granting the marketers automatic access to the company's
customer profile data.
</P>
<P>
   By a 5-0 vote Tuesday, the commission ordered Atlanta Gas Light
to give marketing companies access to such information as names,
addresses, account numbers and gas usage during the preceding 12
months. Credit information and phone numbers are not included.
</P>
<P>
   Marketers, who will compete once the state deregulates the
natural gas industry Nov. 1, will receive the information on CD-ROM
within 15 days of being certified by the PSC to sell gas.
</P>
<P>
   They applauded the ruling. Twenty-two companies are now seeking
PSC certification; six recently withdrew from competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``This order will reduce the cost, allow marketers to enter the
area with a lot less confusion, without having to call the customer
two or three times to get the information,'' said Bill Randolph,
Southeast manager for Tulsa, Okla.-based Williams Co.
</P>
<P>
   However, Mark D. Caudill, vice president/rates and regulatory
affairs at AGL Resources Inc., Atlanta Gas Light's parent, said the
ruling ``may not bring benefits to all customers'' if marketing
companies use the information to bypass consumers who use small
amounts of gas.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's the potential for haves and have-nots,'' Caudill said.
He added that AGL reserves the right to seek reconsideration of the
PSC order.
</P>
<P>
   Stan Wise, the PSC member who sponsored Tuesday's order, said
such ``cherry-picking'' of the most desirable customers would have
happened with or without the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Under a new state law, Atlanta Gas Light will no longer sell gas
to consumers but will act as delivery agent for marketing companies
that will sell the commodity at decontrolled prices. AGL also will
have a marketing company that will sell gas, Georgia Natural Gas
Services.
</P>
<P>
   The 330,000 customers now served by municipal utilities and
Columbus-based United Cities, a gas utility, are not affected by
deregulation.
</P>
<P>
   Under a previous PSC order, marketers could not obtain any
information about consumers without their permission. Wise said he
sought a change so marketers could approach potential customers
with more information to help them make a choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing a customer will want to know is, 'How much can
you offer this service for?''' Wise said. ``It's one thing to
cold-call a customer and another to be able to quote a price.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The impact will be tremendous for consumers who now won't have
telemarketers calling them when they're not on the AGL system,''
said Deborah Latham, president of Roswell-based Optimum Energy
Sources.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to save us a lot of time and money,'' added
Livia Whisenhunt, president of PS Energy Group, an Atlanta-based
marketing company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, we can tailor individual deals for individual
customers,'' said Warren Darby, senior vice president of South
Carolina-based SCANA Energy, which has already begun radio
advertising in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
