<DOCNO> NYT19980915.0360 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6836 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TELECOM-SUB-COX     09-15 0584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TELECOM-SUB-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Resending to substitute the word ``emerging'' for the word
``engine'' in the graf beginning ``Those who favor . . .''
 &HT;    
 &HT;    NEW TELECOM MEGA-MERGERS MAY FACE FEDERAL ROADBLOCKS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congress may have to move soon to foster
competition in the nation's telephone markets, two key senators
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Mike DeWine, R-Ohio, said after a hearing on a spate of new
major telecommunications deals that he would urge federal
regulators to put the brakes on further consolidations unless the
government can first ``guarantee that any mergers that are allowed
will have some clear pro-competitive benefits to consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   The ranking Democrat on the antitrust subcommittee chaired by
DeWine, Sen. Herb Kohl of Wisconsin, said a joint letter calling
for an early policy review will go later this week to Justice
Department antitrust chief Joel Klein and Federal Communications
Commission Chairman William Kennard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless we see more tangible evidence that consumers have real
choices, the pressure will continue building to reopen the (1996
Telecommunications) Act and break the stalemate,'' Kohl said.
</P>
<P>
   As deep divisions on how best to proceed emerge among the
remaining industry giants, there are signs that regulators are
listening to the go-slow message from Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Kennard questioned whether there should be any more
big mergers in the long distance arena following the pending $37
billion union between MCI Communications Corp. and WorldCom Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once this merger is consummated, the industry will once again
be poised just a merger away from undue concentration,'' Kennard
said. Future mergers ``of this or similar magnitude ... in the near
future should be judged quite differently than the merger before us
today.''
</P>
<P>
   The hearing Tuesday focused on the newly proposed link between
Bell Atlantic and GTE, which, if approved, would control about a
third of U.S. phone circuits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who favor these mergers claim that they will provide
companies with the financial and technical ability to compete in
the emerging domestic and world markets for bundled information
services,'' DeWine said. ``Those who oppose them say these deals
are more of the same _ big companies getting bigger.''
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses then promptly proceeded to voice both points of view.
</P>
<P>
   Ivan Seidenberg, Bell Atlantic Corp.'s chief executive officer,
said industry trends point ``toward the formation of a half-dozen
or so nationwide and worldwide organizations that can give
customers what they want.''
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to retain what Seidenberg called ``artificial geographic
boundaries'' fail, he said, ``to take into account the needs of the
information-age consumer.''
</P>
<P>
   But William Esrey, chairman and chief executive officer of
Sprint Corp., said two planned telecom mega-mergers _ the Bell
Atlantic-GTE deal and one between SBC Communications Inc. and
Ameritech Corp. _ ``are over the line and must be blocked'' because
they would in sum control two-thirds of U.S. local telephone access
lines.
</P>
<P>
   Said Esrey, who heads the nation's third-ranked long-distance
carrier: ``Federal policy makers must step in and stop the local
telephone industry from transforming itself into, basically, a
Bell-West and a Bell-East monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-98 2019EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980915.0361 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6837 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-REPUBS-1STLD-     09-15 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-REPUBS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS WAIT FOR BEST STRATEGY TO TAKE SHAPE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS with 3-graf insert after 3rd graf; adjusts names accordingly
in 2nd references) (See also: CLINTON-POLL, CLINTON-CONGRESS, CLINTON-COUNSEL,
CLINTON-ASSESS, CLINTON-DAY, CLINTON-DONORS) 
(mk) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Although overt attempts to drive President Clinton
from office could backfire, several Republican operatives said
Tuesday that many campaigns were on the verge of fully exploiting
the president's woes in commercials leading up to the Nov. 3
election. Several are conducting surveys now to determine how
forceful the ads should be.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, Capitol Hill was aswirl over whether to make
public the videotape of Clinton's sworn testimony to the grand
jury. Democrats fear that such images are bound to be embarrassing
_ and bound to wind up in Republican campaign commercials. Others
say there is little point in spending precious campaign money
running such footage when the news media will show it for free,
endlessly.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the public appetite for impeachment is fairly low at the
moment, even among Republicans, according to the latest New York
Times/CBS News poll, released Tuesday. Even if more damaging
information comes out about Clinton, the poll found, Republicans
would rather have Clinton resign or have Congress just drop the
whole thing. In the poll, 41 percent of Republicans said they
wanted Clinton to finish his term.
</P>
<P>
   Sentiment among voters for going slow and letting the process
unfold is at sharp odds with the frenzy on Capitol Hill, where
members of the House and Senate have been engulfed in discussions
of the president's fate. This uncommon difference in pace between
the public and the politicians _ usually the politicians wait for
public opinion to guide them _ makes a tricky task of formulating
campaign strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Washington is leading the opinion on this,'' said Whit Ayres,
a Republican campaign consultant based in Atlanta. ``Whether the
country will follow becomes very important.'' He said he expected
many campaigns to take advantage of what he described as the
``opportunity'' that Clinton was presenting. ``There will be some
response to this,'' he said. ``Saying values are important is a
pretty obvious strategy''
</P>
<P>
   Others, like Bob Teeter, who ran George Bush's presidential
campaigns in 1988 and 1992, say it is so obvious it is not
necessary. ``When you hit a sweep against a party in trouble for
some reason, you don't do anything,'' he said. ``You don't have to.
The Democrats in '74 didn't have to run against Watergate.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican political consultants say that the public cares
deeply that the process of investigating the president unfold
deliberately, without Republicans appearing to gloat over it,
exploit it or push it along unnaturally.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the public wants is for kind of a due process to take
place,'' said Teeter.
</P>
<P>
   Teeter said the reluctance for impeachment at this point is
based more on a desire to keep the country stable than on
confidence in Clinton. ``It's not an indication of support for him,
it's that it would be bad for the country,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ayres agreed. ``There's not yet broad public support for
removing the president from office,'' he said. ``We're in a
let-the-process-work stage. The reason isn't that the public
doesn't care; the reason is that voters are wrestling with how to
make the punishment fit the crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Alex Castellanos, a Republican media consultant based in
Virginia, said that voters were feeling some anxiety, but it was
based largely on the volatility of the stock market. ``If this were
about Bill Clinton, the public would fire him,'' Castellanos said.
``But it's about the people. Is it worth the turmoil to put
ourselves and the country through this? The judgment is that Bill
Clinton isn't worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   The investigation of Clinton by Kenneth Starr, the independent
counsel, has done little to move Republicans toward impeachment.
The Times poll found that a third of Republicans said Starr's
investigation has been a partisan crusade bent on destroying
Clinton rather than uncovering wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   These divisions among Republicans have left party leaders
without a clear-cut strategy for how to approach the fall
elections. Several operatives said that the notion of removing
Clinton from office _ unthinkable even just a few weeks ago _ was
now not unexpected but still a surprise and that any strategy was
developing on an ad hoc basis, day by day.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will take care of itself _ that's the larger strategy,''
said Ralph Reed, former executive director of the Christian
Coalition and now a consultant to numerous Republican candidates.
``But Republicans are in a very difficult and delicate position,''
he said. ``If they are going to build on their majority, they have
to show that they are deserving of that majority _ without
enthusiasm.''
</P>
<P>
   He and others said that the go-slow approach could speed up
after the elections, particularly if Democrats sustain serious
losses in the House and Senate. But it would be Democrats, not
Republicans, feeling more urgency for Clinton to go.
</P>
<P>
   One longtime Republican strategist said that candidates simply
needed to be patient and wait for the public to absorb all that has
happened and that then a critical mass of public opinion would
emerge that Clinton is not fit to govern.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, everyone is digesting the sex _ they are not even
on to perjury and abuse of power,'' this strategist said. ``It's
plausible that Clinton is at his high-water mark today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-98 2020EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980915.0362 </DOCNO>
