<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6852 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAGE-FRIGHT-MUSIC-$A     09-15 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAGE-FRIGHT-MUSIC-$ADV20-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING ARMS AGAINST STAGE FRIGHT  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 20) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Colo., Ohio)   (af)  
 By ELEANOR BLAU   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Picture audience members in their underwear. That's
an old trick. Makes them less intimidating.
</P>
<P>
   Fall down as you come on stage. That's an odd trick. Not
recommended. But it saved the pianist Vladimir Feltsman, when he
was a teen-ager back in Moscow. The veteran cellist Mstislav
Rostropovich tripped him purposely to cure him of preperformance
panic, Feltsman said. ``All my fright was gone. You already fell.
What else could happen?''
</P>
<P>
   Musicians report all manner of strategies against stage fright
and its curses: icy fingers, shaky limbs, racing heart, blank mind.
Teachers and psychologists offer strategies, too.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, schools have started addressing anxiety in
courses dealing with performance techniques or career preparation.
The Juilliard School offers a class in stage fright. Medical
circles are also interested.
</P>
<P>
   The attention began in the early 1980s, as people began talking
more openly about health problems. In 1983, Dr. Alice G.
Brandfonbrener organized what became an annual symposium in Aspen,
Colo., on the medical problems of musicians, and she edits a
journal on the subject. Since physical and emotional difficulties
are so often linked, Dr. Brandfonbrener said, anxiety drew
increasing notice.
</P>
<P>
   One cause of the attention, and the anxiety, is a tight job
market. So the field of performance psychology is burgeoning, and
sports psychology is attracting musicians.
</P>
<P>
   Don Greene, a psychologist who used to work with Olympic divers,
has been working exclusively with musicians for the last five
years, and has been asked to create a graduate course in
``performance enhancement'' next year at Juilliard.
</P>
<P>
   With government financing of the arts limited in the United
States, not only are orchestra positions scarce, but even jazz
players can't find work, said Louise Montello, a jazz pianist and
psychotherapist who gives seminars in New York and abroad on coping
with performance stress.
</P>
<P>
   ``People feel like they have to be the absolute best in order to
get a job, and if they make one mistake in an audition, they feel
they've completely failed,'' Ms. Montello said. ``It's so
debilitating for a lot of musicians that they really give it up. Or
they get into compulsive behaviors. A lot of them are taking drugs,
and there's a lot of alcoholism.''
</P>
<P>
   The prescription drugs of choice are beta blockers like Inderal;
they reduce the fight-or-flight effects of adrenaline. Dr.
Brandfonbrener said she had often prescribed small doses to
musicians, with great success. Unlike valium, alcohol or marijuana,
she said, beta blockers do not destroy judgment. Still, they are
not for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Especially not the violinist Elmar Oliveira. Untroubled by stage
fright, Oliveira took Inderal once on the advice of a cardiologist,
to counter a rapid heartbeat. Although his performance of the
Beethoven Violin Concerto went well, he said, ``I felt like I was
completely detached from the fiddle.''
</P>
<P>
   Teachers and therapists offer wide-ranging advice, from basics
like learning pieces inside out to mental disciplines: visualizing
a performance, for instance, and taking steps to relax. Don't deny
that you're jittery, they urge; some excitement is natural, even
necessary for dynamic playing. And play publicly often, for the
experience.
</P>
<P>
   Diane Nichols, a psychotherapist who calms a stage-fright class
in Juilliard's evening division, suggests steps for the moments
before performance, if circumstances allow: ``Take two deep
abdominal breaths, open up your shoulders, then smile,'' she said.
``And not one of these `please don't kill me' smiles. Then choose
three friendly faces in the audience, people you would communicate
with and make music to, and make eye contact with them.'' She wants
to counter notions of the audience as judge.
</P>
<P>
   Greene, the sports psychologist, teaches a ``centering''
strategy that combines Eastern ideas of focusing and breathing with
Western ideas of psychology. He finds his switch to music natural,
he said, since athletes and musicians both perform ``complex,
difficult, challenging skills under extreme pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   Julie Landsman, a principal horn player in the Metropolitan
Opera Orchestra who teaches at Juilliard, likens auditions to
Olympic trials. ``For those 10 minutes that you are given, you need
to show your stuff,'' she said. ``You have to be hot from the
minute you walk in the door, and keep their attention. That's a
very specific skill that I, as a student at Juilliard from 1971 to
1975, was never taught. It took me 20 auditions before I figured
out on my own what I had done wrong in the previous 19, so that I
could win the 20th. I wasn't a better player by that time. But I
learned to play the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever they share, though, athletes and musicians differ in a
key goal. ``If you tell yourself you're a winner, a great
champion,'' the cellist Lynn Harrell said, ``you're going to close
yourself off to some aspect of the vulnerable, soft-belly side of
what music is about. There's a need to feel a great deal of
confidence, but you have to be very sensitive to the inward,
frightened, timid side of human nature.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrell suffered extreme stage fright some 30 years ago in the
Cleveland Orchestra, where, with George Szell as music director, he
became the principal cellist. ``Szell had a way of making people
very nervous,'' he said. ``He wanted to control them, and he knew
so much more than any musician I'd ever known, he was rather
intimidating. In very subtle ways he helped you to develop, but at
the expense of feeling this natural self-assurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were times when I got so nervous I was sure the audience
could see my chest responding to the throbbing. It was just total
panic. I came to a point where I thought, `If I have to go through
this to play music, I think I'm going to look for another job.'''
</P>
<P>
   Recovery, he said, involved developing humility _ recognizing
that whatever his talent, he was fallible, and that a marred
concert was not a disaster. He also worked on focus. ``When you see
a film of Heifetz playing,'' he said, ``you see a concentration and
ferocity of intense living-in-the- present.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Extreme demands by mentors or parents are often at the root of
stage fright, says Dorothy DeLay, Juilliard's best-kwown violin
teacher. She tells young teachers under her wing to pace demands so
that students can always achieve them.
</P>
<P>
   It is not only young artists who suffer, of course. Vladimir
Horowitz's nerves were legendary. ``The great tenor Franco Corelli,
they had to push him on stage,'' the soprano Renata Scotto
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, success can make things worse. ``In the beginning of
your career, when you're scared to death, nobody knows who you are,
and they don't have any expectations,'' the soprano June Anderson
said. ``There's less to lose. Later on, when you're known, people
are coming to see you, and they have certain expectations. You have
a lot to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I never stop being nervous until I've sung my last note,''
said Ms. Anderson, who considers herself a circus performer doing
``my tightrope act without the net.'' Breathing exercises help, she
finds. ``Years ago, my nerves would force my breath to go high, and
I'd be breathing in a shallow way,'' she said. ``Now, even when I'm
petrified, I can keep my breath down, and hopefully my lunch,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   The pianist Louis Lortie can't predict stage fright, he said.
``It could happen in the middle of a phrase. You have a silly
thought, or you feel the instrument is not responding exactly as
you'd like.'' Memory slips may result. In a Mozart concerto
recently, Lortie got lost momentarily, lapsing into a theme from
another concerto in the same key. ``It lasted a few seconds and I
was back on track,'' he said, ``but it seemed it lasted hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Anxiety is heightened, Lortie said, by unrealistic expectations
in the age of the CD. Before the development of splicing
techniques, recordings often contained wrong notes, and it was
standard for live performers to hit them, too. Not now. ``We were
brought up with the idea that there shouldn't be mistakes,'' said
Lortie, who is 38. ``Technical obsession was a part of the
upbringing of my whole generation.''
</P>
<P>
   Touring pianists often play in a hall with unfamiliar acoustics
and an unfamiliar keyboard. ``I try to remember from the rehearsal
how the piano reacts, imagine as accurately as possible a
performance of that piece and the conditions where you're going to
perform,'' Lortie said. ``You feel less estranged. You're trying to
put yourself in a kind of womb up there on stage.''
</P>
<P>
   The soprano Barbara Bonney eases anxiety with self-suggestion
techniques she learned years ago. ``For instance,'' she said, ``you
say that your heart is calm and beating regularly and your breath
is relaxed and deep, and that your solar plexus is relaxed and warm
and your arms are warm, and you breathe gently, sort of a yoga
breath. And between each of these suggestions you just say, `I'm
calm, and I feel loved and secure.' I must say I use that an awful
lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bonney said she is shy, troubled by the thought of ``people
looking at me.'' Yet she likes lieder recitals, partly because she
can see the audience and communicate with it. In opera, ``there's a
void out there,'' she said. And in lieder she is in control. ``It's
when you have to be what other people expect you to be _ they
create this character they want you to be _ that's when I get into
most trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Vivica Genaux, a mezzo-soprano who made a calm debut in ``Il
Barbiere di Siviglia'' at the Metropolitan Opera last December on
short notice, gets rehearsal fright, not stage fright, she said.
``I get really tense and stressed out in rehearsals. When everybody
else is freaking out, then I'm OK, because I've been through it so
many times.''
</P>
<P>
   The soprano Harolyn Blackwell takes fright in the wings. She's
OK once she makes her entrance, thanks, perhaps, to a little owl.
It resides in her purse backstage, providing protection, along with
a card representing St. Anthony, whom she described as ``the patron
saint for losing things.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he will prevent her from losing the owl as well as her
clothes, which, she said, tend to fall off on stage. She dropped
her hat, then her sash (twice) as Oscar in the Met's ``Ballo in
Maschera'' a few years ago. And her fan flew into the orchestra pit
recently as she sang ``Glitter and Be Gay'' in ``Candide.''(The
conductor fanned himself with it.)
</P>
<P>
   Knock wood, it's not only owls that keep things under control.
Renata Scotto, who won't go on stage under a ladder, wear purple or
say certain words, does ``many, many, many other stupid things,''
like every other performer, she said. ``I don't believe a person
who says, `I'm not superstitious.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
