u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMERICANHOME-MARKETPL     09-15 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICANHOME-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: NEW DRUGS OFFSET SOME WOES AT AMERICAN HOME
PRODUCTS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID J. MORROW   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Could it be that American Home Products Corp. has
finally begun to change its luck?
</P>
<P>
   The company, with a stock price up 46 percent this year, is
expected to get the green light Wednesday from a Food and Drug
Administration advisory committee for Enbrel, its new injectable
drug to treat rheumatoid arthritis. Some analysts project that
worldwide sales of Enbrel could eventually top $500 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   That is welcome news for a company that has been prone to
product recalls, liability lawsuits and a weak drug pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, American Home Products had to recall Duract,
a pain killer, because of liver toxicity. Before Duract, there was
controversy over the Norplant contraceptive, leading to lawsuits
from 50,000 women.
</P>
<P>
   And American Home Products still faces lawsuits over its half of
the diet drug cocktail known as fen-phen, which was taken off the
market a year ago. All told, the liabilities could easily run into
billions of dollars, stock analysts estimate.
</P>
<P>
   All is not bright now, either. The company seems headed for a
showdown of a different sort with federal regulators _ over its
pending acquisition of the Monsanto Co.
</P>
<P>
   What has caught the attention of the Federal Trade Commission,
according to stock analysts, is the stranglehold Monsanto and
American Home Products would have over the sedative market.
</P>
<P>
   Monsanto makes Ambien, the leading nonbarbituate sedative, with
85 percent of the United States market. American Home Products will
soon introduce Sonata, a short-duration sleeping pill expected to
be popular with travelers.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the FTC confirmed on Monday that an inquiry
into the merger was under way but refused to comment on its scope.
</P>
<P>
   While the commission is unlikely to derail the acquisition, it
could force American Home Products to drop Sonata or delay its
release. Permanently shelving Sonata would mean eating an estimated
$500 million in research and development costs and would hinder the
company's growth in the sedative market.
</P>
<P>
   Making matters worse, the regulatory scrutiny could delay the
takeover until next year, increasing legal fees and postponing cost
savings.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Essner, the executive vice president of American Home
Products, declined to comment Tuesday on the FTC investigation or
on the acquisition of Monsanto, which will cost $34.4 billion in
stock. Patrick Gage, the president of Wyeth-Ayerst Research, a
division of American Home, said that he expected Sonata to be
released later this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sonata and Ambien do somewhat different things,'' Essner said.
``Sonata has a shorter duration. You can take it, fall asleep and
there's no residual after-effects of the drug.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, many within the industry had expected Ambien and Sonata
to be rivals. Sonata's Phase 3 trial results, released in June at
the annual meeting, in New Orleans, of the Association of
Professional Sleep Societies, showed better results than Ambien had
shown in similar tests with placebos.
</P>
<P>
   Owning Sonata and Ambien would be a powerful combination. Ambien
generated $418 million in sales in the United States in the year
through July, according to IMS Health, a health care consultant,
dwarfing the $17 million in sales of Restoril, the No. 2
nonbarbituate sedative.
</P>
<P>
   In the worst case, if American Home Products was forced to
jettison Sonata, it would still pick up Ambien though its
acquisition of Monsanto. That has convinced many on Wall Street
that American Home's luck has finally changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't really hold American Home Products responsible for
the recall of fen-phen,'' said Neil Sweig, a pharmaceutical analyst
with Southeast Research Partners. ``It could happen to the best of
companies. But with American Home's merger with Monsanto, the
company is a pharmaceutical and agricultural giant. It looks the
most like Novartis of any of the U.S. companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the last two months, investors have snapped up shares of
the stock, cheap by drug industry standards. With pharmaceutical
stocks selling at 40 times earnings, shares of American Home remain
one of the best buys even after the recent run-up. The company's
stock trades at 29 times earnings, a bit higher than the average
for the S&AMP;P 500, but considerably lower than Pfizer's multiple of
52 or Warner-Lambert's 57. Even the drug industry's laggards are
expensive. Shares of Eli Lilly, among the weaker drug issues this
year, are trading at 44 times earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Stock analysts also see signs of encouragement in American
Home's bounty of new drugs. In August, the company received FDA
approval for Rota Shield, a vaccine against rotavirus, the most
common cause of severe diarrhea in children.
</P>
<P>
   The company is expected to receive full approval within several
weeks to market Enbrel, which was developed with Immunex, a
biopharmaceutical company in Seattle. Enbrel will be available only
as an injection, making it difficult for some arthritis sufferers
to use.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone wants an easy-to-take pill because it goes down
easier,'' said David Saks, managing director at Gruntal &AMP; Co. ``But
injections are the fastest way to get medicine into the
bloodstream, and arthritis is a devastating disease where there is
room for improved therapy.''
</P>
<P>
   Several other new drugs are expected to be big sellers. Next
year, American Home Products plans to introduce Protonix, a
gastrointestinal drug available in oral and intravenous forms, and
Rapamune, an immuno-suppressive therapy for organ transplants.
Analysts expect sales of each drug to top $1 billion annually.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to new products, we feel really hot right now,''
Essner said. ``We have one of the best product pipelines that we've
ever had, and certainly we have one of the best in the
pharmaceutical industry. We couldn't have said that a few years
ago.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
