<HEADER>
A6857 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LP-IMAGES-MUSIC-$ADV2     09-15 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LP-IMAGES-MUSIC-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
  
 LPs TO CDs: HIGH FIDELITY MADELEINES  
 (For release Sunday, Sept. 20)  
 (bl)  
 By BERNARD HOLLAND   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Going back to the neighborhood of one's youth and finding
familiar objects smaller than remembered is an experience shared by
most of us. I had the same feeling, not long ago, picking up a CD
of Ravel's piano music and finding on its cover the shrunken image
of an LP record I knew some 45 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Sony Classical's Masterworks Heritage series, of which this
two-CD release is a part, represents a foolproof sales strategy, at
least where the middle-aged market is concerned. For this is our
past, perfectly reconstructed _ nostalgia we can touch in
miniature. If Proust's ode to memory celebrates the power of smell
and taste, those of us who grew up in the postwar hinterlands,
where music inspired not just neglect but also suspicion, well
remember the look and touch of those old cardboard LP covers.
</P>
<P>
   They and their contents emerged month by month from labels like
Columbia, RCA Victor, London, Decca, Mercury and Westminster. We
wore them on our shelves as fragile icons. Roughly 12 inches square
and already prone to disintegration, they were medals earned, or at
least diplomas of advancement.
</P>
<P>
   This particular series _ four LPs now reduced to two CDs _
offered Robert Casadesus, the French pianist with strong American
ties, playing Ravel's piano music almost complete. (The G major
Concerto is the principal omission.) Helping out are his wife,
Gaby, also a pianist; the violinist Zino Francescatti, and the
Philadelphia Orchestra under Eugene Ormandy.
</P>
<P>
   If anyone was wondering how the spirit of the early-music
movement could be transposed to the record industry, look no
further. For here is Columbia's original cover design (ugly, as
most covers were in those days), complete with ``LP'' printed at
bottom right. Early-music's blend of archaeological rectitude and
modern compromise are perfectly mirrored here. Original notes are
retained though now translated for an international buying
audience.
</P>
<P>
   Salvaged even are the inner sleeves. ``A high fidelity recording
designed and engineered at Columbia Sound Laboratories,'' we read
on one. ``Variable groove'' techniques of manufacture are discussed
along with the relative merits of the diamond, sapphire and osmium
needle. On another sleeve is Columbia's ``current'' roster of
artists, from Dimitri Mitropoulos and Pierre Bernac to Bernard
Baruch and Gertrude Berg. Picture period-instrument Mozart in
Vienna's Redoutensaal: authentic materials authentically packaged.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the scratches of those old surfaces have been taken away;
the monophonic sound quality is materially improved. (If Sony had
wanted REAL authenticity, it would be handing out Variable
Reluctance cartridges and Garrard turntables to play these items
on.) Also updated is the listener's sensibility. What sounded like
``right in our living rooms'' a generation ago is now a bit hollow
and distant, but the ear adjusts.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the imagination still remains uppermost in every
high-fidelity adventure, for I doubt that the most splendid
digitalized and stereophonic sound today has any more auditory
impact than what Columbia gave us in 1952.
</P>
<P>
   The performances are pretty much as I remember them: dignified,
careful, deeply caring, sometimes upright to a fault. Small errors
indicate an absence of splicing. Quick pieces like the Sonatine and
``Jeux d'Eau'' are still too fast, a tribute to Casadesus'
extraordinary prowess, but an example, perhaps, of how technique
can acquire an unwanted life of its own. There are in fact moments
between phrases when the music longs to draw a breath and luxuriate
in its activities, but the pianist presses on. If the four-hand
version of ``Ma Mere l'Oye'' seems brisk, at least Casadesus and
his wife have rescued it from the composer's cloying reinvention of
this piece for orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   Today, however, I am most impressed by the simpler music: the
extraordinary leading of inner voices in the familiar ``Pavane Pour
une Infante Defunte,'' and the subtle goads these strands provide
to the overall movement. Casadesus thought through every subtlety
of the ``Valses Nobles et Sentimentales,'' arguably the best music
Ravel ever wrote. Perhaps the true evidence of the pianist's
rectitude lies in the faithfulness of his tempos, which no heat of
the moment is able to disturb.
</P>
<P>
   There is one other inauthentic component in Sony's new
transaction: the listener himself. The 1952 version of these
particular ears was eager and acute; its counterpart 46 years later
is battered around the nerve endings but more reflective because of
it. The blind, white-hot reactions of the young are gone; the
middle-aged receptacle is less capable of the old thrills yet at
the same time less susceptible to being fooled. The trade-off is
wrenching but unavoidable.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 listener-model also has a hard time mentioning Ravel
and Debussy in the same breath, where once it was an easy
assertion. Ravel's several and sometimes contradictory spirits are
all here in Sony's project: the elegant attachment to the Baroque
(``Le Tombeau de Couperin''), the passionate sensuality (the
Sonatine), the affectionate mockery (``Valses Nobles et
Sentimentales''), the fascination with how instruments sound
(``Ondine'').
</P>
<P>
   The classicist and the exotic mix freely, and the composer's
calculating eye is always on himself. Debussy, one better
understands with age, dreamed as Wagner did, of mysterious and
potent worlds far beyond Ravel's earthbound though wonderful art.
Stravinsky called Ravel ``the Swiss watchmaker.'' Debussy with
every passing year seems to rise ever higher above both men.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
