<HEADER>
A6858 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-CLASS-COX     09-15 0531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CLASS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clinton scandal is academic
 &HT;    By Ben Smith III
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- During an esoteric discussion of what Aristophanes,
Shakespeare or Machiavelli would say about the Clinton-Lewinsky
scandal, Steven Bloodworth cut to the chase:
</P>
<P>
   ``She don't look that bad. She don't look that bad,'' the
Oglethorpe University freshman said. ``Compare her to Hillary and
then try to see it through the eyes of a 52-year-old male. She
don't look that bad.''
</P>
<P>
   She, of course, is Monica Lewinsky, and the forum was just one
of millions of discussions on the same subject taking place Tuesday
around soda machines, construction sites and in elevators. But
unlike the rest of the nation's idle gossip, this one inside a
classroom comes with a college credit.
</P>
<P>
   Under the title, ''Love, Sex and Politics: From Aristophanes to
President Clinton,'' 14 Oglethorpe freshmen, five upperclassmen
mentors and political science professor Joseph Knippenberg are
opting for the classics instead of Kenneth Starr's 445-page
non-fiction impeachment report to shed light on the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   The class is part of the university's Fresh Focus program, a
half-semester course in which freshmen tackle nontraditional topics
for a single credit.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, Knippenberg and his students will compare
the affair between the President and his favorite intern, and
William Shakespeare's Antony and Cleopatra, whose affair also shook
an empire.
</P>
<P>
   The students will consider also how Clinton and Lewinsky would
be judged by ''The Ecclesiazusae,'' Aristophanes's comic Assembly
of Women who, disguised as men, invade and take over the government
of Athens, outlaw prostitution and gambling, and give the city's
most ugly and aged women first dibs on the virtue of its young men.
</P>
<P>
   So far, with the possible exception of Bloodworth, class members
are agreed that Lewinsky is no Cleopatra and not worth risking an
empire for. But they're split on what judgment should await
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ''Personally, I don't care what he did with the cigar,'' said
freshman Scott Harris. ''But he lied and he needs to be punished
for that.''
</P>
<P>
   To which classmate Melanie Wong, paraphrasing the philosopher
John Locke, asked, ''Do you punish him because he deserves it, or
do you punish him as a deterrent?''
</P>
<P>
   It was the class' 11 women who seemed more willing to cut the
President some slack.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky, said freshman Colsana Freeman, ''is not only crazy,
she's completely freaky. You have to question if she had it out for
him anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid the student's comments, Knippenberg takes a Socratic
approach with questions such as: ''Say he resigns, should he still
be tried?'' or ''Not all lies are crimes, are all crimes equivalent
to high crimes and misdemeanors?''
</P>
<P>
   Several students seemed more puzzled why Clinton would risk his
presidency over a chunky intern, instead of a movie star or
supermodel.
</P>
<P>
   Bloodworth bluntly replied that the middle-aged President isn't
likely to spark that kind of interest.
</P>
<P>
   ''A model wouldn't get with Bill Clinton,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
