<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6859 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-GADELEGATION-     09-15 1141
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-GADELEGATION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Norwood joins calls for resignation
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- Saying that impeachment proceedings have already
``frozen'' Congress, Rep. Charlie Norwood (R-Ga.) on Tuesday became
the first member of Congress from Georgia to call on President
Clinton to step down.
</P>
<P>
   ``This president should do a noble thing for this country and
resign,'' Norwood said. ``I don't think he has committed treason. I
don't think he has been bribed in any way. I don't know what high
crimes means. But I know what misdemeanors means, and he has most
surely committed misdemeanors, less than felonies, but misdeeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Traumatic as it is for someone to resign, the country would be
better off for it,'' Norwood said.
</P>
<P>
   Norwood joined a handful of Republican members of the House and
Senate who have called on Clinton step down over his relationship
with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky. But so far, the
Augusta dentist is the only Georgian who has urged the president to
take such a dramatic step.
</P>
<P>
   Not even Rep. Bob Barr (R-Ga.), who has been Clinton's most
persistent critic, was prepared Tuesday to urge Clinton to resign.
Barr, one of the three dozen House Judiciary Committee members
allowed to review the evidence against Clinton, said he was
withholding judgment until he has made his way through more of the
documents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not vote to impeach based on the evidence at this
time,'' Barr said.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Republicans were united, however, in saying that they
believe independent counsel Kenneth Starr's report on Clinton
contained enough convincing information to open a formal
impeachment inquiry, the next step in the impeachment process.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just need to move forward with the impeachment hearings and
let the system work,'' said Rep. Mac Collins (R-Ga.).
</P>
<P>
   Most members of Georgia's House delegation said they had read
all or at least parts of Starr's report over the weekend.
Republican members said their offices were overwhelmed with calls
from constituents. Rep. Jack Kingston (R-Ga.) said both his
Washington and Savannah office answering machines were filled to
capacity.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who only read bits and pieces of it, or rushed out to
the Internet, are saying impeach him,'' Kingston said. ``It's
pretty rare for people to be calling their congressman on a
Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Saxby Chambliss (R-Ga.) said he requested his staff to
divide up the calls to determine if his constituents were angry
over Clinton's sexual behavior, or because he did not own up to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The feeling among the people in my district is very strong
that the country should not tolerate this kind of behavior from its
president,'' Chambliss said. ``Most of them just want him gone.
They don't say we want him impeached or we want you to make him
resign, they just want him gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Chambliss said he believed the president perjured himself when
he told the grand jury on Aug. 17 that he did not have sexual
relations with Lewinsky. But Chambliss, a lawyer, said obstruction
of justice charges will ``take more substantiation.''
</P>
<P>
   Most members are paying particularly close attention to calls
from their constituents in gauging how to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If (people) expresses their revulsion and the Democrats
respond, he'll be impeached,'' said Rep. John Linder (R-Ga.). ``But
if the public supports him, I think the Democrats will continue to
support him, and then there's not enough votes.''
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Democrats, meanwhile, said they were far less
persuaded by Starr's report. Rep. Sanford Bishop (D-Ga.) said there
was a ``strong likelihood that (Clinton's) statements were at
variance with the facts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now whether that constitutes perjury, that's a legal
conclusion that has to embody a whole lot of case law and legal
interpretation,'' said Bishop, an attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop acknowledged that the Clinton scandal could have an
impact on his second District re-election bid this November.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would certainly not beat my chest and say there is nothing
to worry about,'' Bishop said. ``I try to change the things I can
... that's something I have no control over.''
</P>
<P>
   Bishop's spokesman, Selby McCash, said calls to the
congressman's office were running two to one in favor of taking
some action against Clinton, with the majority saying the president
should be impeached.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Cynthia McKinney (D-Ga.) was one of two dozen female
members of Congress who met with first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton
in the residential quarters of the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were inspired by her strength and courage,'' McKinney said
of the meeting. ``Ironically, given all that she must be going
through, the first lady offered us words of inspiration and
motivation. She will represent both our national courage and our
national strength in the days ahead and as we gear up for our
various races this fall.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the president, McKinney referred reporters to a statement
issued Friday in which she said his ``reckless behavior'' had
brought the country to ``the brink of a constitutional crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Lewis (D-Ga.), who has stood by the president, said a
careful reading of Starr's 445-page report did nothing to change
his view that it was ``one-sided'' and well short of the standards
for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was not trying to circumvent our system of government,''
Lewis said. ``He was trying to cover up a personal love affair, a
sexual affair that had taken place over a period of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Max Cleland (D-Ga.) declined to comment on the Starr
report, saying he might eventually be required to judge the
president's actions in a Senate impeachment hearing. Cleland said
that in Georgia over the weekend he heard from a number of
constituents, with the majority critical of the president's conduct
but opposed to the idea of impeaching him.
</P>
<P>
   Cleland declined to ally himself with the comments of Senate
Minority Leader Tom Daschle (D-S.D.), who said Clinton's lawyers
should abandon their legal ``hair-splitting'' about whether the
president had sex with Lewinsky and ``accept that continued legal
jousting serves no constructive purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   Norwood, who has sponsored major legislation to regulate health
maintenance organizations, said he became convinced Clinton should
resign because of the enormous distraction the impeachment question
already is posing for Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got business to attend to,'' he said. ``Where is my
health care bill?... I'm not even talking about foreign policy.
We've got problems around the world, and we need a leader who can
stand up, and we need a credible leader. I want people to see the
president of the United States and continue to think he is the
leader of the free world.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
