<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 20:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6867 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEORGIA-FILMS-ART-$AD     09-15 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEORGIA-FILMS-ART-$ADV20-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POETIC AND SURREAL, GEORGIAN CINEMA IS TRUE TO LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Sept. 20)  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (Stephen Kinzer is chief of the Istanbul bureau of The New York
Times.) 
(bl)  
 By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TBILISI, Georgia _ This small nation nestled under the towering
Caucasus Mountains, which has a history stretching back several
millennia but which emerged from the debris of the Soviet Union
only seven years ago, has a rich creative tradition based on the
mixture of fantasy and reality.
</P>
<P>
   In the 20th century that tradition has been expressed most
vividly in film, and today a hardy group of more than a dozen
filmmakers is struggling against severe economic constraints,
trying to preserve, extend and deepen it.
</P>
<P>
   Georgian cinema _ like, some would say, the Georgian soul itself
_ is built largely on surrealism and poetic intensity. So it is
entirely appropriate that Nana Djordjadze is one of the country's
leading filmmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you ask me why I make films, I ask you why you breathe,''
Ms. Djordjadze (pronounced jor-JAD-zeh) said recently at the
cavernous sound stage that she and three other directors bought in
1993. ``I cannot imagine my life without film.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Djordjadze has six feature films behind her, including ``A
Chef in Love,'' which was nominated for an Oscar as best foreign
film of 1996. It features a chef with a nose so sensitive that he
can instantly identify wine vintages and the ingredients of
elaborate dishes; the kidnapping of a pig; and a communist
commissar who orders the closing of the best restaurant in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Ms. Djordjadze bridled at the suggestion that it is anything
other than realistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is no more unreal than my own life and imagination,'' she
insisted.
</P>
<P>
   That life and imagination, however, are extraordinary even by
Georgian standards.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Djordjadze was born aboard an airplane over the Caucasus,
and as a child aspired to be a pilot because to her that job
epitomized freedom. As a child in Tbilisi, the Georgian capital,
she lived above a fire station and was adopted by the fire brigade
as a sort of mascot, often dressing in a firefighter's hat and
rubber coat. She spent many afternoons walking through the old
city, not on the streets but on rooftops.
</P>
<P>
   ``My childhood was full of secrets and surprises,'' she said,
jumping up from her seat every few minutes to illustrate her
memories. ``My family was full of crazy people. When the Red Army
arrived here in 1921, my grandmother told her servants: `Close the
window. They must go away.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``My grandfather came back from the gulag after 25 years. He
confused everything, and since I was the only nongrownup in the
house, I was the only one he could communicate with. Once he
suddenly insisted that we go to visit the place where he grew up.
He pointed to a spot and we began to dig. After a few minutes we
felt some cloth, and there was a package that turned out to contain
three volumes of Byron and one of Shakespeare. He had buried them
there before he was arrested. I still have those books. They're
very important to me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Every moment of my life is full of these romantic things. In
my family, tragic stories were always told with humor. I also have
this style. Today we have problems, but tomorrow will be much
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Djordjadze discovered movies at so-called ``cinema clubs,''
where officially banned foreign films were shown late at night with
a wink from the authorities, who were never as dogmatic as their
bosses in faraway Moscow. Transfixed by Jean Renoir, Robert
Flaherty, John Ford, Luis Bunuel, Federico Fellini and others, she
resolved to follow in their footsteps.
</P>
<P>
   In 1968, at the age of 16, she traveled to Prague to attend that
city's Academy of Art. She was caught up in the excitement of the
``Prague spring,'' but when Soviet troops invaded in August of that
year she was arrested and sent home. She began experimenting with
film, and in the 1980's two of her films won prizes at the
festivals in Berlin and Cannes.
</P>
<P>
   Together with her husband, Irakli Kvirikadze, who has written
the scripts for most of her films, Ms. Djordzadje is among the most
active Georgian filmmakers. Today she is involved in several
projects, the details of which she declined to discuss. What makes
her remarkable is not simply her body of work, which includes ``A
Journey to Sopot'' (1980) and ``Robinozaida'' (1987), later
released in English as ``My English Grandfather,'' but the fact
that she and her contemporaries represent one of the world's most
interesting cinematic traditions.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's film industry emerged soon after the first moving
pictures were shown in Paris and Berlin. Shorts were first made
here in 1908, with the first full-length documentary following in
1912 and the first full-length feature in 1916. During the Soviet
period, Georgian films won prizes around the world. Officials in
Moscow often claimed them as examples of the brilliance of Soviet
art, but strictly limited their distribution within the Soviet
Union.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for their ambivalence was, not surprisingly,
political. Many early Georgian films were obliquely critical of
Soviet rule. During the years of Stalinist power, filmmakers here
had no chance to make anything other than films extolling the
wonders of collective farming and industrialization. Later,
however, they adopted the indirect language of parable and metaphor
to convey iconoclastic messages.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Some Georgian films of the 1960s and '70s won awards at Moscow
festivals, among them Sergo Parajanov's widely praised ``Shadows of
Forgotten Ancestors'' and Eldar Shengelaya's ``Samanashvili's
Stepmother'' and ``Blue Mountains.'' Others, however, were all but
completely repressed.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most memorable of these were three silent shorts by
Michael Kobakhidze, all made in the 1960s: ``Wedding,''
``Umbrella'' and ``Musicians.'' Shot in black and white, they have
no direct political content but are utterly anti-Soviet in their
lightness, sly humor and tragicomic refusal to accept the
conventions of heroism or social obligation. Today they are shown
regularly on Georgian television.
</P>
<P>
   Kobakhidze, along with several other Georgian directors, has
emigrated and now lives in Paris. He has told recent visitors that
he is working on another film, his first in many years, but will
say no more.
</P>
<P>
   One Georgian film towers above all others as a political
landmark. ``Repentance,'' directed by Tengiz Abuladze, who died in
1994, was released in 1986 as the reforms of Mikhail Gorbachev were
beginning to take hold. It is a deeply penetrating critique of
Stalinism, though on the surface it is only about a benevolent
small-town mayor who, desperate to hold onto his post, slowly
becomes cruel and repressive.
</P>
<P>
   ``This film is antityranny, antipower, in other words, against
barbarism,'' Abuladze said after ``Repentance'' won the special
grand jury prize in 1987 at Cannes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Repentance'' could not have been made without the connivance
of Eduard Shevardnadze, who then headed the Georgian Communist
Party and is now the nation's president. After reading the script,
Shevardnadze frankly told the filmmakers that Moscow would never
approve it. He suggested that they write another, very bland script
with the same title and send it to Moscow. After it was approved,
he told them, they should go ahead and make the film they
originally planned.
</P>
<P>
   The ruse worked, and by the time the film was completed the
Soviet political climate had loosened so much that it became a huge
hit throughout the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Abuladze's influence is still being felt. Directors like Ms.
Djordjadze absorbed his techniques and philosophy of life as his
students at the Tbilisi film academy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a very strong cultural tradition and a devotion to the
concept of individual creativity,'' said Irina Gogoberidze, a film
historian and critic in Tbilisi. ``Neo-realism, symbolism and other
forms of intellectual filmmaking are deeply rooted here. Directors
look in that direction rather than toward pleasing the masses.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Traditionally, our best films have been very light and open,''
Ms. Gogoberidze said. ``Unfortunately our economic troubles, not to
mention the political difficulties, have turned some of our
filmmakers toward nihilism. But I believe that someday we will
produce a great Georgian blockbuster. We have all the
ingredients.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
