<HEADER>
A6869 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SCANDAL-HNS &LR;      09-15 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SCANDAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SQUABBLING ERUPTS OVER REPUBLICAN EFFORTS TO RELEASE CLINTON
TESTIMONY VIDEO 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
and GREG MCDONALD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Partisan squabbling erupted in the House Tuesday
over Republican efforts to release a videotape of President
Clinton's grand jury testimony about his affair with Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Before the House votes on proceeding with an impeachment probe,
they must decide what evidence to release in addition to the
summary that was made public last week after independent counsel
Kenneth Starr delivered his report to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The report contended there is credible evidence the president
committed a number of impeachable offenses from perjury to
obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are pressing to release a video of the president's
August testimony in which Starr and his prosecutors aggressively
questioned Clinton on his relationship with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials fear the release of the video will be used
by Republicans in campaign commercials. Many Democrats believe it
is wrong to make public piecemeal parts of the supporting evidence
submitted by Starr. They say the original agreement called for the
committee to review all of the material and then selectively make
public pertinent information.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we proceed in leaking and releasing documentation we will
not have the dignified process this nation deserves,'' said Rep.
Sheila Jackson Lee, D-Texas, a member of the Judiciary Committee,
which would hold any impeachment hearings. She also warned ``that
we are about to begin a Salem witch hunt. I will not participate in
a witch hunt.''
</P>
<P>
   Committee members have now had an opportunity to review the tape
of the president's testimony. Some said Tuesday that it would
likely prove a further embarrassment to the president because it
shows him ``squirming'' and ``responding angrily'' to graphic
questions put to him about his sexual trysts with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Mike McCurry said that Clinton and his
advisers have been bracing for the tape to be released in some
form, either through leaks or a decision by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just hope that it's not misused,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, grand jury testimony would be kept secret. But now
that Starr has sent his report to Congress, lawmakers can do
whatever they want to with the evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga., said that the public has a right to see
the Clinton testimony, even if it includes sexually graphic
material.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who have a problem with graphic testimony, they ought
to complain to 1600 Pennsylvania Avenue,'' Barr said.
</P>
<P>
   The Judiciary Committee may meet as soon as Thursday to discuss
the release of additional material, according to a committee aide.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to media reports that White House officials were
trying to collect and spread damaging information on House
Judiciary members, Chairman Henry Hyde issued a memo to the
committee saying such attempts would be viewed as a violation of
federal law.
</P>
<P>
   The White House also indicated that it is readying for the fight
over impeachment by appointing Greg Craig as a special counsel to
coordinate response to the Starr report. Craig is a senior State
Department official who once worked for Sen. Edward Kennedy,
D-Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Craig will join a White House legal and public relations team
that has been trying to convince Democrats on Capitol Hill to
continue their support for the president. Top administration
officials, including chief of staff Erskine Bowles and political
aide John Podesta, spoke to Democratic senators at a closed door
luncheon on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   At the reportedly tense meeting, the senators said the aides
largely reiterated the president's defense strategy, which twins a
personal acknowledgment that he has sinned with a vigorous defense
that he committed no impeachable acts. Lawmakers refused to comment
specifically on their exchanges with the White House team.
</P>
<P>
   In the morning, a number of Democratic women lawmakers met with
Hillary Rodham Clinton and urged the first lady to maintain a
visible role in the coming months, particularly in terms of pushing
the party's agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want her voice to be silenced. We want to hear
her,'' said Jackson Lee, who attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The White House also confirmed that the president has asked two
ministers for guidance regarding his problems. The clergymen are
Tony Campolo, a liberal Baptist from Pennsylvania and Rev. Gordon
MacDonald, a senior pastor of a non-denominational church in
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's capital has been in an uproar since the release of
the Starr report last week, with lawmakers daily calling for the
president's resignation. But that sentiment is not shared by most
of the public, who by a 2-1 margin in most polls, do not view the
president's behavior as serious enough to warrant his ouster from
office.
</P>
<P>
   One of Texas' two Republican senators, Phil Gramm, said he was
not going to be influenced by the views of his constituents on this
matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I swore an oath to the Constitution and not to public
opinion,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Jeff Sessions, R-Ala., suggested that Americans ought to
``think this thing through a little more.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the chief law enforcement officer in this country, and he
lied,'' Sessions said.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans, including Sen. Orrin Hatch of Utah, have
floated the idea of censuring Clinton, a solution that has the
support of a majority of Americans in some polls. Democrats would
likely go along with a move to publicly reprimand Clinton without
removing him from office.
</P>
<P>
   But House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, said Tuesday that
a growing number of his GOP colleagues believe that censure would
``trivialize'' Starr's conclusion that Clinton committed perjury
and obstructed justice.
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, echoed the disdain for
censure as way out of the current controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who considers censure and makes decisions based on
polls, believes the rule of man is above the rule of law,'' he
said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
