<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6875 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-1200(2TAKES)-     09-15 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-1200(2TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP LAWMAKERS SAY REPRIMAND NOT SEVERE ENOUGH FOR CLINTON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RON HUTCHESON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congressional Republicans served notice Tuesday
that President Clinton cannot escape impeachment proceedings by
accepting a formal rebuke for his affair with former intern Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Proposals floating on Capitol Hill include the suggestion that
Clinton could avoid impeachment by accepting censure and
reimbursing the federal government $4.4 million, the estimated cost
of the Lewinsky investigation. House Majority Leader Dick Armey
dismissed such talk as ``blathering'' by Clinton's ``spin team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Republican said cutting a deal for a reprimand is
``not an option that holds a lot of attraction'' for Republicans.
Rep. Tom DeLay of Sugar Land, the Republican whip, also denounced
censure proposals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The time for that is well past,'' DeLay said. ``For now, the
House has no choice but to proceed with an impeachment inquiry.''
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Mike McCurry ridiculed the idea that
Clinton should reimburse the federal government. He joked that
Clinton might consider the proposal if independent counsel Kenneth
Starr picks up the tab for the rest of the four-year, $40 million
examination of Clinton's actions as president and as governor of
Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   With impeachment hearings looking increasingly likely, members
of the House Judiciary Committee debated privately whether to
release copies of Clinton's videotaped grand jury testimony as
early as Friday. Starr contends that the president committed
perjury on Aug. 17 by lying about his sexual affair with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   In other developments, the White House confirmed that Clinton is
receiving weekly spiritual counseling; the president beefed up his
scandal-response team; and a group of about two dozen Democratic
lawmakers, all women, offered emotional support to first lady
Hillary Rodham Clinton at a White House meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Sheila Jackson Lee, D-Texas, said the women agreed to work
together in trying to shift public attention from the sex scandal
to problems confronting the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a sisterhood in that meeting, and the sisterhood
said that women know what's right,'' said Jackson Lee, one of
Clinton's chief allies on the Judiciary Committee. ``We're
nurturers. We're wives, we're mothers, we know what the deal is. We
know what fairness is about.''
</P>
<P>
   But those words of comfort for the Clintons were overshadowed by
blistering critiques of the president's behavior by two House
Democrats. In remarks that underscored Clinton's political
problems, Rep. James Traficant Jr. of Ohio accused Clinton of
trying to place himself above the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Joe Q. Citizen lied to a grand jury, he'd go to jail,''
Traficant said on the House floor. ``Let's tell it like it is. Joe
Q. Citizen can't apologize. Joe Q. Citizen isn't censured. Joe Q.
Citizen is prosecuted. An America with two legal standards is an
America with no legal standards.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Harold Ford of Tennessee, normally a Clinton ally, urged
the president to ``come clean'' about his misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is difficult for those of us in this party and this House
to continue to give the president the benefit of the doubt,'' Ford
said.
</P>
<P>
   In an ironic twist, Republican leaders cautioned the Memphis
Democrat that his pointed remarks violated House rules against
direct personal criticism of the president.
</P>
<P>
   Armey said calls to his office are running overwhelmingly
against the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an awful lot of anger coming over the phone lines,''
the GOP leader said. ``We've had a flood of phone calls. They've
been pretty reflective of the anger and disappointment the American
people feel, the sense of betrayal.''
</P>
<P>
   But polls indicate that the angry calls may not reflect majority
opinion. Three separate polls for television networks in recent
days found that about two-thirds of voters think Clinton should
complete his term. If the findings are accurate, the mood in the
country bears little relationship to the mood in Congress, where
impeachment hearings are considered all but certain by many
lawmakers in both parties.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's immediate problem is how to deal with the expected
release of his videotaped testimony, which could come later this
week. The president's allies fear that the video will be used,
possibly in campaign ads, to embarrass Clinton and his defenders.
</P>
<P>
   The tape reportedly shows Clinton losing his temper as
investigators ask him about his relationship with Lewinsky. The
president admitted an inappropriate affair, but declined to provide
details.
</P>
<P>
   MORE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, in this case, the president was choosing his words
very carefully,'' said Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, who watched the
video in his role as a Judiciary Committee member.
</P>
<P>
   Although testimony to a federal grand jury is supposed to remain
secret, the independent counsel law requires Starr to report any
evidence of impeachable offenses to Congress. Starr also cleared
the delivery with a federal judge.
</P>
<P>
   In sending the material to Congress, Starr told lawmakers that
it ``may not be publicly disclosed unless and until authorized by
the House of Representatives.'' The House voted last week to
release Starr's 445-page report summarizing his findings and
directed the Judiciary Committee to decide how much additional
material should be made public.
</P>
<P>
   The bulk of the remaining evidence _ 17 boxes of testimony,
transcripts, audio tapes and other materials _ could be released
with the Clinton video tape this week.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky's lawyers met with Judiciary Committee members Tuesday,
urging them to delete some of the more graphic portions of her
testimony before releasing it to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things in Starr's report is a statement that Clinton
may have violated a judicial gag order in discussing his testimony
in the Paula Jones deposition with his secretary, Betty Currie.
</P>
<P>
   At Clinton's Jan. 17 deposition, U.S. District Judge Susan
Webber Wright issued a protective order ``that prevented the
parties from discussing their testimony with anyone else,'' Starr's
report said.
</P>
<P>
   Wright even went further, specifically addressing the admonition
to the president just before he finished.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of Clinton's determination to fight, the president
recruited Gregory Craig, a top State Department official, to direct
the White House response to Starr's report. Steve Ricchetti and
Susan Brophy, Democratic operatives with experience on Capitol
Hill, also joined the White House response team.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is using a mix of public and private money to defend
himself. The White House lawyers are supposed to focus on defending
the president in his official capacity. David Kendall, the
president's private attorney, handles personal issues.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said that Clinton is also receiving weekly
spiritual counseling for what the president has called his ``broken
spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   The spiritual advisers include the Rev. Tony Campolo, an
American Baptist pastor in St. Davids, Pa., and the Rev. Gordon
MacDonald of Grace Chapel Protestant church in Lexington, Mass.
MacDonald is the author of ``Rebuilding Your Broken World,'' which
recounts the religious leader's efforts to put his own extramarital
affair behind him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want him to understand what went wrong with him personally
that led to the tragic sins that have so marred his presidency,''
Campolo said. ``We want to provide all the help that we can to
spiritually strengthen him against yielding to the temptations that
have conquered him in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
