u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-CLINTON-CONGRESS-AR     09-15 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-CLINTON-CONGRESS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOICES FROM HOME REFLECT RAGE, DISMAY, FRUSTRATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating to add art note)  (ART ADV: PHOTO is being sent to NYT photo clients. GRAPHIC _
breaking down the costs of Kenneth Starr's investigation _ is being
sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(See also: CLINTON-POLL, CLINTON-REPUBS, CLINTON-ASSESS,
CLINTON-DAY) 
(JT) 
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ and ERIC SCHMITT    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For many liberal Democrats and conservative
Republicans, getting a fixed reading on what the folks back home
think about President Clinton's behavior was not too tough a task.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Meagher Northup, R-Ky., attended a parade near Louisville
over the weekend to a chorus of, ``Impeach him. Impeach him.'' It
sounded, she said, like ``Crucify him, crucify him.''
</P>
<P>
   And on the East Coast, Rep. Jerrold Nadler, D-N.Y., said it took
him 90 minutes to walk five blocks in Manhattan's Upper West Side
because people were so furious about all this impeachment talk. His
answering machine ran out of tape by mid-afternoon. ``What they
were saying was a variation of, `Stop this nonsense. Don't impeach
the president. This is absurd.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But for the rest of the House, members from swing districts or
from places where reactions tend to be more muted and tempered, the
messages from home about the independent counsel's report have been
decidedly more mixed and difficult to sum-up in a simple sound
bite. That makes their jobs considerably more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``Opinion is still very split and very fluid,'' said Rep. Philip
English, R-Pa. ``A fair number of people are uncomfortable with the
situation. They don't like what the president has done, but they're
not sure what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the release of Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr's report
last Friday, lawmakers say they have heard from constituents in
record numbers, at supermarkets, synagogues and political rallies.
Their offices have been deluged with phone calls, e-mail messages,
and letters from citizens venting their rage and disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   Many lawmakers say they have noted a distinction between people
who are actively calling their offices, most of whom voice
overwhelming support for Clinton's ouster, and voters who engage
members of Congress in conversation at picnics and barbecues and
breakfast meetings.
</P>
<P>
   These voters are furious with Clinton, who they believe has
debased the office of the presidency, and offended by his behavior.
The problem is that they can't figure out what sort of punishment
is appropriate for a president who lied about a sexual romp with a
21-year-old former intern but who many believe has done a
relatively good job.
</P>
<P>
   And it is the opinions of people who represent this broad swath
of the public that will likely determine Clinton's fate in the
Congress. Back in Tennessee, Rep. Bob Clement, a Democrat, said a
whole cross-section of his constituents are torn over whether the
president's actions warrant impeachment, resignation, censure or
anything besides personal and historical humiliation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no consensus,'' said Clement. ``Among the general
population it's mixed. But they do want us to move expeditiously.
They don't want it dragged out.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Sherwood Boehlert, R-N.Y., said he had received 105 calls,
running two-to-one in favor of impeachment. But of the people back
home who Boehlert spoke to after church or at the corner store,
many seemed to hold less extreme positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are kind of shaking their heads in disbelief,''
Boehlert said. ``Nobody likes the idea of going through
impeachment. The majority of people I represent who have spoken to
me feel that the president has lost his moral compass. More want to
have him removed from office.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, ``there are a number of people who are genuinely
torn.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Mrs. Northup said that among certain communities in her
district there is a sense of uncertainty. ``More people were
saying, get him out,'' she said, adding that her office received
180 phone calls by Monday with 135 of the callers gunning for
impeachment. ``But not everybody, especially communities with a
deep abiding allegiance to this president. They don't want to
imagine it has to go there.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, she said, the gyrations of the president's lawyers over
his statements and whether they are legally accurate appear to be
counter-productive. ``In Middle America they don't see that as
anything other than telling a lie,'' she said. ``Any other
equivocation makes them mad.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ray LaHood, R-Ill., said he made his rounds at a parade, a
breakfast meeting and a hog roast over the weekend. While many
people, including some Democrats, wanted to order-up instant
impeachment, he was surprised to hear so many constituents express
doubts about what Congress should do by way of punishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the people saying, the guy is sick,'' LaHood said.
``But they are simply not sure. People are confused about whether
these are impeachable offenses.''
</P>
<P>
   Senators from across the country echoed the sentiments of many
House members.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bob Kerrey, D-Neb., said that people are furious at Clinton
but they are also furious at Starr. ``There is still signs among
people of confusion,'' he said. But, he said, many of them ``wish
this wasn't happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Susan Collins, R-Maine, said she is hearing the same kind
of ambiguity from voters in her home state, although she noted she
received 95 phone messages going 6-to-1 in favor of impeachment.
``People did not recommend to me a specific course of action,''
Collins said. ``They didn't, in most cases, call for his
impeachment. I don't think they've decided what ought to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite this lack of consensus, however, House members and
senators said that even among this wishy-washier, broad middle
cross-section of the population, people are disgusted and appalled
about the turn-of-events. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``People in Maine are offended by nature of relationship and the
lying,'' said Collins. ``One woman came up to me at a rally and
said, 'If my boss did that, he'd be out of there.'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-98 2045EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
