<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6880 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-DAY-2TAKES-NY     09-15 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-DAY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TAKES NEW STEPS TO DEFEND HIMSELF ON CAPITOL HILL 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: 2nd take is scheduled to move by 9:15 p.m. ET.) 
(See also: CLINTON-POLL, CLINTON-REPUBS, CLINTON-CONGRESS,
CLINTON-ASSESS) 
(sw) 
 By JAMES BENNET and ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton hired a raft of fresh advisers
and dispatched his top aides to placate congressional Democrats on
Tuesday, as members of the House Judiciary Committee bickered over
whether to release a videotape of his grand jury testimony about
Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   House Democrats accused Republicans of needlessly rushing to
release embarrassing television images of the president, but the
Republicans, who have the votes in the Judiciary Committee to force
the disclosure, argued that the testimony would help the public
judge whether the president had lied under oath.
</P>
<P>
   That question _ whether the president lied and whether he is now
trying to dodge behind a wall of legalistic language _ continued to
bedevil him, as several House and Senate Democrats angrily
criticized the White House in private meetings on Tuesday. Erskine
Bowles, the chief of staff, and other top aides tried to reassure
the congressional Democrats that Clinton was not resorting to
thinly sliced legal distinctions in rebuffing accusations of
perjury by Kenneth Starr, the Whitewater independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Clinton should be worried that renegade Democrats might
call for Clinton to resign, Sen. Bob Kerrey, D-Neb., said: ``They
should worry.''
</P>
<P>
   In a series of television appearances on Sunday, Clinton's
lawyers insisted that the president had not lied under oath in
denying a sexual relationship with Ms. Lewinsky, but many Democrats
as well as Republicans dismissed their remarks as finely nuanced
nonsense.
</P>
<P>
   Kerrey said that Bowles repeated the White House message of
recent days _ that the president had made a terrible mistake and
was sorry. But Kerrey continued to express concern that the White
House was relying on distinctions that would be lost on most
voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``There might be a necessity to make a legal case,'' he said,
``but his most difficult case is the political case.'' That was a
reference to the possibility of impeachment proceedings in the
House.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the private meetings, the White House took other
steps on Thursday to try to put its relationship with Capitol Hill
on a firmer footing. It announced that Clinton had hired Gregory
Craig, director of policy planning at the State Department, to
serve as special counsel coordinating the reponse to Congress over
the Lewinsky matter. Clinton also brought back two former
legislative aides, Steve Ricchetti and Susan Brophy, as senior
advisers.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's advisers expressed concern about the release of his
videotaped testimony. The Judiciary Committee may meet on Thursday,
and if it decides to release the tape, it could do so as early as
Friday. Last Friday, the House released Starr's report. On Tuesday,
Congress was told the Lewinsky matter cost $4.5 million to
investigate.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has not reviewed the videotape, because Clinton
and his lawyers do not have a copy, White House officials said. But
one aide said that a tape of any person's hours-long grand jury
testimony would produce unflattering moments.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can imagine the way TV will play it, they'll pick a piece
of it and play it over and over and over again,'' the aide,
speaking on condition of anonymity, said. ``It's not a pleasant
thing to think about.''
</P>
<P>
   Only one camera filmed the testimony, so the prosecutor are not
shown. Clinton's advisers have said that he became quite angry and
even erupted at a couple of points during the questioning, which
was often confrontational. Clinton's allies in the White House and
on Capitol Hill are concerned that television news programs will
show the displays of anger without first showing the many minutes
of questioning that preceded them.
</P>
<P>
   The videotape will also show Clinton repeatedly refusing to
answer some questions and offering carefully calibrated answers to
others, according to descriptions of his testimony in Starr's
report.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House on Tuesday morning, Clinton's senior aides
received some reassuring news in a meeting with pollsters and other
outside advisers. Three Democratic pollsters _ Mark Mellman, Geoff
Garin and Mark Penn _ told the group that there was no evidence
that Clinton's troubles would suppress Democratic turnout this
fall, people who were present said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, they said that some elements of the Democrats' loyal
base, including black voters, may be more likely to go to the polls
because of a perception that Clinton was unfairly under attack.
They also noted that Clinton's job approval ratings remained
strong, people who were present said.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting included Loyd Cutler, the longtime Washington
lawyer, and Peter Kadzick, another Washington lawyer who is playing
an informal advisory role at the White House. One participant said
the group discussed how the White House should mount a defense as
the case moves to Congress. ``The consensus is that public opinion
is really going to drive this process now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
