<SLUG> BC-TV-ROSEANNE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE ROSEANNE SHOW': LESS GUM, MORE BRAINS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Broadcast notes at end of review. Time, channel are for New
York area. Check local listings.) 
(mk) 
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For some of us, daytime talk shows, with their celebrity puffery
and soap-sister schmaltz, are as enticing as poison ivy. And the
prospect of a talk show starring Roseanne seemed as unnatural as
poison ivy with sound effects, notably a loud cackle. Never
predict, because the show on Monday was surprisingly smart and
winning, a mix of sharp topical conversation, occasional comedy
sketches and social work without sentimentality.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Roseanne Show'' (syndicated nationally and seen in New
York City weekdays at 3 on Channel 4) reveals the intelligence that
has so often been hidden behind the crude, gum-snapping Roseanne of
the hit blue-collar sitcom and the cosmetic surgery that
transformed her face. This calmer Roseanne makes jokes and has
pointed opinions, but she also listens to her guests. After her
many publicity-seeking metamorphoses, she may have found her best
and truest role yet.
</P>
<P>
   Her entrance on the first show on Monday led to the worst
expectations, as she played the cackling diva. She appeared from
above riding in a cherry picker, wearing a boa, strewing rose
petals over the audience and snapping her own photograph with a
Polaroid. But that self-absorption quickly vanished.
</P>
<P>
   With her first guest, Whoopi Goldberg, she discussed the Clinton
affair (``There isn't one person in the country who can live up to
the standards we set,'' said Ms. Goldberg), marriage (``You've been
married four times and I've only been married three,'' said
Roseanne) and motherhood. Unlike most talk-show interviews, this
was truly a two-way conversation as they sat on a stage designed to
look like a comfy, spacious living room, with leopard-print chairs
and a fireplace.
</P>
<P>
   The conversation grew more serious when Ms. Goldberg recalled
getting a phone call some years ago, when her daughter was only 14,
saying she was pregnant and wanted to have the baby. Ms. Goldberg
supported her. ``I would kick my kid's butt,'' said Roseanne,
voicing a more typical reaction without pressing the point.
</P>
<P>
   There was a point to this conversation. Later, she and Ms.
Goldberg sat on the edge of the stage, eye to eye with three
teen-age mothers in the audience. ``In the '70s, we were both
welfare mothers,'' Roseanne said, as she and Ms. Goldberg exploded
stereotypes and pointed out how lives can change. Sympathetic and
questioning, they asked the teen-agers to become each other's
support group and to come back in a month. Such dry-eyed social
awareness may turn out to be one of the show's most significant
features.
</P>
<P>
   (Ms. Goldberg was plugging her own show, a new version of the
old ``Hollywood Squares'' game, syndicated by the same company as
``Roseanne.'' This strained new version may feature hip guests like
Andy Dick, but it is more painful than funny. It also began Monday,
and is seen in New York weeknights at 7:30 on Channel 2.)
</P>
<P>
   So far, comedy on ``The Roseanne Show'' has included a mock
interview, with Nora Dunn playing a familiar character with a blond
wig, brown pant suit and sneering mouth. The intentionally
misspelled identification on screen called her, ``Linder Tripp, Big
Fat Snitch.'' The writing was not as sharp as it could have been,
but the fact that a political sketch existed was encouraging.
</P>
<P>
   There's no telling whether ``The Roseanne Show'' will live up to
its best potential or stumble fast. Tuesday's show was far less
impressive, devoted almost entirely to an interview with Jerry
Springer and a parody of his hair-pulling interviews. Even while
she was throwing bouquets at Springer, though, Roseanne managed to
pose a question that was both jokey and supremely trenchant. ``Why
do we all love your show so much?'' she asked. ``What's wrong with
us?''
</P>
<P>
   Roseanne obviously does not mean her show to become a model of
decorum. And she does not mean it to be like anything else on the
air. It promises to be as shrewdly conceived as the many earlier
stages of her career, and a lot more intriguing.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE ROSEANNE SHOW'
</P>
<P>
   Weekdays at 3 p.m. on NBC (Channel 4 in New York)
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Smith, head writer; Ken Fuchs, director; Linda Beal,
Mark Keizer and Kelly Newby, co-producers; Pam Burke, coordinating
producer; Allan Stephan, producer; Judy Pastore, supervising
producer; Roseanne, Jeff Wald and Eddie October, executive
producers. Produced and syndicated by King World Productions Inc.
and Full Moon and High Tide Productions. Andy Friendly and Steven
Nalevansky, president and senior vice president of King World
Programming and Production.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
