u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-CONAN-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      09-15 0416
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CONAN-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LATE NIGHT WITH CONAN O'BRIEN': 5 YEARS OF AMIABLE WIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Broadcast notes at end of reviews. Time, channel are for New
York area. Check local listings.) 
(mk) 
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Conan O'Brien's funny, inventive ``Late Night'' arrives in prime
time with a special of highlights from the first five years. An
opening routine perfectly captures the show's self-mocking tone, as
O'Brien presents a montage of his changing hairstyles, a standard
anniversary-show gimmick that here takes a swift, silly turn into
parody. O'Brien often makes fun of his pasty white skin and
shocking red hair, but he has never looked goofier than he does
with flowing, corn-rowed red locks.
</P>
<P>
   When O'Brien took over ``Late Night'' after David Letterman
moved to CBS, he inherited more than the title. Letterman, from a
generation raised on television, is still the master of the style
that satirizes the old talk-show format. (Chronologically, Jay Leno
belongs to the Letterman boomer generation, but psychologically
he's a throwback to the Carson days, and his straightforward
approach seems increasingly stale.)
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien shares the ironic Letterman approach of goofy taped
routines and mock guests. But he has developed his own style as an
amiable, quick-witted interviewer. He is a Letterman without the
dark side, a Leno not afraid to show some smarts.
</P>
<P>
   The anniversary show includes the signature ``Late Night''
routine in which fake talking lips are superimposed on still
photographs, putting unlikely words in famous mouths. O'Brien
interviews the fake Bill Clinton (a hog-hollerin' good old boy),
Vernon Jordan and Bob Dole. There are also clips of video parodies
featuring O'Brien and his sidekick, Andy Richter, whose
straight-faced sincerity provides a mordant foil to O'Brien's
high-pitched energy.
</P>
<P>
   What matters about a talk show, of course, is how well it wears
night after night; a clip-filled special cannot capture that. And
this anniversary show seriously underplays the importance of the
``Late Night'' band, the Max Weinberg 7, which leaves television
viewers wishing they were in the studio to hear more. But the
special includes enough comic highlights to explain why ``Late
Night With Conan O'Brien,'' famously on life support in its early
days, has become addictively entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `Late Night With Conan O'Brien Fifth Anniversary Special'
</P>
<P>
   10 p.m. ET Wednesday on NBC
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
