<HEADER>
A6895 &Cx1f; gen-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-DEWINE-IMPEACH     09-15 0509
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-DEWINE-IMPEACHMENT-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     
 &HT;    
 &HT;      DEWINE COULD BE ON IMPEACHMENT TASK FORCE
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Ronald F. Eckstein  
 &HT;    c. 1998 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Sept. 15 -- If, and that is a big IF, the U.S.
Senate holds the first impeachment trial of a sitting U.S.
president in 130 years, Ohio Republican Mike Dewine is likely to be
on a task force researching protocol.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., is mulling over the
possibility of a task force to study Senate procedures in a
presidential impeachment trial, Roll Call, a Capitol Hill
newspaper, reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
   A top Senate Republican told the newspaper that a task force
would likely be heavy with ``legal beagles'' like DeWine, Sen.
Arlen Specter, R-Pa., and Sen. Jeff Sessions, R-Ala. All three of
those senators are former prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   DeWine, a member of the Senate Judiciary Committee, served as
Greene County's prosecuting attorney from 1977 until 1981. He was a
member of the House Judiciary Committee while serving in the U.S.
House of Representatives from 1983-90.
</P>
<P>
   DeWine also has experience with impeachment matters that few
members of Congress can claim: he was instrumental in the 1986
impeachment of a federal judge who refused to resign from the bench
despite being convicted of tax evasion.
</P>
<P>
   Chief U.S. District Judge Harry E. Claiborne of Nevada was the
first sitting federal judge to be convicted of a felony. Claiborne
drew the attention of Congress because he continued to accept his
$78,700 annual salary while being held in a federal prison. Because
federal judges are appointed for life, Claiborne could only be
removed via impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Procedure for any federal impeachment -- of a judge or of a
president -- is the same. First, the House Judiciary Committee must
weigh the case and vote to have the entire House pass judgement.
The impeachment vote in the House is similar to the indictment of a
defendant by a grand jury. If the House votes to indict, then the
U.S. Senate ultimately acts as a jury and makes a final decision on
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   After the House voted 406-0 to impeach Claiborne, DeWine helped
prepare the case before the Senate and served as one of the
presenters to the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Lott stressed that it is premature to begin
talking about the Senate's role in any impeachment trial of
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not close to that point. The majority leader will wait
to see what will happen when, and if, the House acts,'' said John
Czwartacki, a spokesman for Lott. ``It is not like a task force is
inevitable ... We are not acting as if we are expecting anything
(from the House). We don't want to prejudice the process.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lott will be talking to Democratic and Republican colleagues
to find a constitutional role for the Senate, Czwartacki added.
</P>
<P>
   And DeWine wants to be prepared. DeWine's spokesman said the
senator has been reading books about preparations for the
impeachment trials of Presidents Andrew Johnson in 1868 and Richard
Nixon in 1974 -- just in case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-98 2058EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
