A6901 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANADA-BANKS-NYT &LR;      09-15 0409
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-BANKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL SUGGESTS BANK CHANGES FOR CANADA 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By KALYANI VITTALA    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ A national task force has endorsed mergers of large
Canadian banks and has recommended easing rules for foreign banks
to operate here as long as the public interest is protected.
</P>
<P>
   The Task Force on the Future of the Canadian Financial Services
Sector issued 124 recommendations Tuesday for overhauling the
banking industry. The report comes amid debate over two recently
announced mega-mergers _ the Royal Bank of Canada and the Bank of
Montreal, and Toronto Dominion Bank and the Canadian Imperial Bank
of Commerce, four of Canada's top five banks. The four banks
contend that merging is the only way to remain competitive in the
global marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   Canada's fourth-largest bank, Scotiabank, and consumer groups
insist ownership concentration will become dangerously high,
competition will be squeezed out and too many jobs and local
branches will be lost in the merger process.
</P>
<P>
   ``There should be no absolute ban on mergers among large banks,
insurance companies or other financial institutions,'' the report
said. ``However, no such merger should take place if it is not
consistent with the public interest.''
</P>
<P>
   It recommended that each merger should be subjected to a public
interest review, that recommendations could be made based on the
review and that banks that act against those recommendations be
subject to some kind of penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not put up a red stoplight, nor have we issued a green
light,'' said Harold MacKay, the chairman of the task force. ``What
we have done is put up a flashing yellow light.''
</P>
<P>
   In November, the national competition bureau and the Office of
the Superintendent of Financial Institutions will present their
recommendations to Paul Martin, the finance minister, on whether
the two mergers should proceed.
</P>
<P>
   The task force also seeks to simplify legislation for foreign
banks operating in Canada, allowing branches here through the
parent company rather than a unit. And the task force suggests a
framework be established so that foreign companies can lend to
Canadians without first having a presence in the country.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the task force recommends allowing banks to merge
with insurance companies, mutual fund companies and investment
dealers. It wants to allow bank branches to offer insurance and
auto-leasing services. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-98 2101EDT &QL; 
