A6902 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK16     09-15 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rookies in on fight for best record
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- When the lineup was posted Tuesday afternoon, the
only thing missing was what time the bus left for Kissimmee. A day
after clinching the NL East, Bobby Cox predictably emptied the
bench, giving rookies third baseman Wes Helms and outfielder George
Lombard their first major league starts, as well has starting Marty
Malloy at second base for the sixth time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll talk to the pitchers today and tomorrow about what they
want to do,'' Cox said of balancing the work load. ``We'll plan
that out and then try to get everybody enough at-bats to keep them
sharp and keep winning. I mean, we still have to keep winning.''
</P>
<P>
   That becomes the club's next concern _ rest the starters, play
the kids but also keep apace of division champions Houston and San
Diego for the best record and home-field advantage through the
playoffs. Kevin Millwood drops out of the rotation after Tuesday
night to move to the bullpen, John Smoltz may skip a start and
rookie Bruce Chen fills in. But at the same time, the Braves are
not excited about handing away a chance for the best record in the
league.
</P>
<P>
   ``No. 1, you want to be ready for the playoffs, no matter who
you're playing,'' Cox said. ``But we want to have the best record.
We'll try to do both. It's kind of a difficult task to do it this
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Local lad makes good
</P>
<P>
   Lombard made his first start one day after his 23rd birthday and
five years after being drafted in the second round out of the
Lovett School. He does not view this as an isolated incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next year is the year I'd like to come up and hopefully get up
here for good,'' said Lombard, who hit .310 with Class AA
Greenville with 22 homers, 65 RBIs and 34 steals in 39 attempts.
``I definitely think I can play at this level but I know I have a
lot of learning to do. That's one advantage of being here now, to
learn from some guys who have been here five or 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   It was hardly a coincidence Lombard started in right field,
despite playing left and center field in the minors. With
left-handed hitting left fielder Ryan Klesko under contract for the
next three seasons, Lombard's best chances to make the team is in
right, where Michael Tucker is hitting a career-low .248 and will
be eligible for salary arbitration for the first time next winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think at this point, I just need to learn all the
positions,'' Lombard said. ``I haven't play too much right field.
In fact, I haven't played any right field, to tell you the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Ready Rudy?
</P>
<P>
   Rudy Seanez, sidelined since Sept. 5 with a micro-muscle tear in
his right forearm, will throw from a mound for the first time
today, after which the club will have a better read on when he can
return to the bullpen. Seanez, who has 44 strikeouts in 31 innings,
threw fastballs and breaking pitches off flat ground Monday at
better than 60 percent and reported no soreness.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a good possibility I could throw (in a game) over the
weekend,`` Seanez said. ``I'd like to get back in the swing of
things.``
</P>
<P>
   Singing for Lou Gehrig
</P>
<P>
   Fans at Turner Field received a treat Tuesday night when Seattle
resident Mark Reiman sang the national anthem. Reiman is afflicted
with Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis (ALS), previously known as Lou
Gehrig's disease. Reiman is scheduled to sing at all 30 parks and
Turner Field is 28th as he makes his way around the country as part
of a awareness campaign for the fatal disease that attacks
specialized nerves which control the muscles.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
