<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6904 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD16-COX     09-15 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Real Deal's real hometown
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATMORE, Ala. -- When Evander Holyfield announced that he was
bringing the next heavyweight championship fight to his hometown,
he could have caused a panic down here.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly where did he think he'd plop down his boxing ring? The
gym at Escambia County High seats only 3,000. The YMCA is busy with
football. The Strand Theater is booked with ``How Stella Got Her
Groove Back.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield had Atlanta in mind all along. He's always considered
Atlanta his hometown, though his birth certificate says Atmore,
Ala. ``That's because all the opportunities came from (Atlanta),''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Atmore, however, is the answer to a trivia question in the
Holyfield scrapbook.
</P>
<P>
   It's the town where he was born 35 years ago. Where his father,
from whom Evander has been estranged for most of his life, still
lives in a trailer. The champ lived here only his first three
years; they called him Chubby then. But what he has done in his
boxing career earned him the key to the city and a place in its
collective heart.
</P>
<P>
   He's been back a couple of times as an adult, trying to piece
together moments of his childhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're a kid, you're in the house, on the porch and in
the front yard,'' he said. ``That's as far as you went, then back
into the house. We never did go nowhere, just right there on that
porch. We had to sit there on that porch with my grandmama until my
mama come home from work.''
</P>
<P>
   One of his most vivid memories is of the bug truck that rumbled
through the neighborhood producing clouds of insecticide. ``It
always scared me,'' Holyfield said. ``It would come down the street
spraying, and you couldn't see your whole house.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the house where he and his brother saw a strange man
standing in their kitchen several mornings in a row, a figure that
seemed to vanish in thin air. His mother, the late Annie Holyfield,
saw the man, too, and passed out. ``My grandmama said it was
probably our guardian angel,'' Holyfield said.
</P>
<P>
   Atmore's population has doubled to 8,000 since then _ minus
Annie Holyfield and her eight children, who moved to Atlanta _ but
the place looks the same. It's a blue-collar, sawmill town with a
dress code. ``Your pants must be pulled up to your waist or you can
stay out!'' says the sign in the window of Spudd's BP.
</P>
<P>
   Since it was established in 1866, Atmore has accumulated several
claims to fame.
</P>
<P>
   According to a resolution by the state House of Representatives,
it's the purple martin capital of Alabama, annually welcoming
thousands of the ``highly desirable birds, due to their graceful
flight pattern, their pleasant songs and the fact that a purple
martin eats 2,000 mosquitoes per day.''
</P>
<P>
   It's home to the Yellow Mama, the still-working electric chair
at Holman Prison, south of town, where hardened inmates pick cotton
in fields patrolled by shotgun-armed guards on horseback.
</P>
<P>
   One of Atmore's factories makes lingerie for Victoria's Secret.
The Creek Indians run a bingo parlor three nights a week. And then
there's Evander Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
   He is often in the conversation of the Atmore citizenry, even if
no one's thought to put up a sign in tribute to its native son.
``Old Friends and New Beginnings'' reads the sign at the city
limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be a good place to put `The Birthplace of Evander
Holyfield,''' Mayor Rodney Owens said. ``There's nothing planned,
but maybe we should take the initiative and ask him to come down.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be just fine with Bryant Smith, the football coach at
Escambia County High. He mentions Holyfield in his pep talks. ``Oh,
at least once a week,'' Smith said. ``We talk to the kids about
what's right and wrong. They know what's right, but sometimes they
forget what's wrong. Evander is a true-blue, great American.''
</P>
<P>
   He wishes Holyfield could find his way to the school. ``I've got
64 kids on the team, and about 74 percent come from broken homes,''
Smith said. ``Evander is a great example of succeeding.''
</P>
<P>
   Atmore celebrated Evander Holyfield Day in 1984 after he
competed in the Olympics. When he won the heavyweight championship
in 1990, they gave him a parade and named him the city's athlete of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was in one of those big, long, fancy cars they have at the
funeral home,'' Lexana Locke recalled. She and his mama once cooked
together at the City Cafe.
</P>
<P>
   Now 78, Locke remembers little Chubby going around with his
fists up, pretending to be a fighter, when he was 3. ``He was a
little boy about that high. And when he would play, he'd do
something like this,'' she said, striking a fighter's pose.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to tell Annie Laura that Holyfield is going to be a
boxer. She didn't pay me no attention; she'd just laugh. When I
first heard he was boxing, I said, well, that little boy always did
be jumping, holding his fists out like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for the paved road, Union Street looks pretty much the
way Holyfield left it 30-something years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley Forney still lives across from 111 Union, where
Holyfield spent most of his three years here. The house in which
the champ was born, on King Street, no longer exists.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to put a rocking chair in a wagon, and I'd put Chubby
in the chair and pull him down the dirt road,'' Forney said. ``His
brother Lightning (Bernard) was a friend of my nephew, Tony. He had
a very religious grandmother. All the kids stayed together in this
neighborhood. If she could get to 'em on Sunday, she'd take 'em to
church.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's from a good family. He was raised up in a way that you're
supposed to be, to have respect for your mama.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is a story going around about Atmore, first told in
Holyfield's biography by Bernard, with which Forney takes
exception. They claimed that a drunk wandered in their yard, was
bitten by their dog, Lassie, and returned with a sheriff, who shot
the dog.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was no drunk,'' Forney said. ``That was David McKenzie,
an old man who used to cut my hair. He was walking by on his way to
town and the dog ran out and bit him on the butt. They mostly kept
the dog chained up. But he would bite everybody. He even bit me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even so, the Holyfields were good people. And now Chubby's the
best in the world. It will take a hell of a man to beat him.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
