<SLUG> BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD-NOTES16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia boxing commission selects Tampa referee
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- In the first major test for the recently restructured
Georgia State Boxing Commission, executive director Thomas Mishou
wanted to avoid the appearance that Evander Holyfield has a
home-ring advantage. Hence, the referee for Saturday's fight with
Vaughn Bean will not hail from Fayetteville, Dawsonville or Smyrna.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Garry, a 16-year referee from Tampa, Fla., will work his
first heavyweight title bout at the Georgia Dome. The state
commission was allowed to pick two of the officials for the
Holyfield-Bean fight and selected Garry and Al Devito, who will
serve as a judge. The other two judges were assigned by sanctioning
bodies IBF (Leroy Brown) and WBA (Duane Ford).
</P>
<P>
   ``I purposely wanted to avoid local officials in Georgia,''
Mishou said. ``It would hurt our chances of ever getting another
world championship bout if we had to worry about (charges of
impropriety).''
</P>
<P>
   Garry, who will make about $2,200, has worked 34 title bouts but
never a heavyweight championship. Some of his profile bouts include
heavyweights Riddick Bowe vs. Oliver McCall and Roy Jones vs. Mike
McCallum.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the biggest, high-profile fight (in my career), and
it's a real honor,'' said Garry, who also was a ringside official
during the 1996 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia commission also has absolved itself of any
responsibility for the ``Thai'' boxing event on the card between
Jerome LeBanner and Espedito Da Silva. The commission, which now
operates under the Georgia secretary of state's office, no longer
oversees ``non-generic'' boxing events, such as kick boxing and
Toughman Contests. All officials, therefore, will be assigned by
promoter Don King. Thai boxing is similar to kick boxing, except
that it allows kicks below the waist.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not responsible, and we're not informed,'' Mishou said.
``If it's not boxing, it might as well be arm-wrestling.''
</P>
<P>
   Lights, camera...
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield held his second and final lunch-time workout at CNN
Center Tuesday, drawing about 1,000 people. He sparred with Gary
Bell for three rounds. Holyfield will take today off, then have
light workouts Thursday and Friday, 10:30 a.m. both days, at the
Holyfield Arena, 1000 Beecher St. in West End.
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   More than 23,000 tickets had been sold for the fight as of
Tuesday afternoon, and promoters said they think that sales could
push the crowd well over 30,000. ``I feel very good right now about
what we're doing,'' Georgia Dome general manager Kaiil Johnsonsaid.
``The workout at CNN Center (last week) really helped, and I think
the one (Tuesday) will help, too. People are getting excited.''
Capacity is just under 42,000. . . . Saturday's card has swelled
to14 fights, with the addition of two bouts involving women's
champion Christy Martin and unbeaten Atlanta middleweight Lawrence
Chapman. . . . The fight is three days away, hasn't begun, but the
post-bout partying already has started. The Holyfield Foundation is
planning a ``Homecoming Celebration'' immediately after the fight
at the Georgia World Congress Center. Holyfield and other notables
are expected to attend. Tickets are $25 and $50 and can be
purchased at the door or by calling 800-777-4681, extension
317-3519.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
