<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6907 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-GATECH-COX     09-15 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GATECH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cameron leads by example
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Delaunta Cameron is no stranger to responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Tech's outside linebacker is the first member of his
family to attend college, has spent his entire life as the man of
the house in a single-parent home in Arlington, Va., and is
surrogate big brother to 16 first cousins, including the children
of his two aunts who died of AIDS in the last year and a half.
</P>
<P>
   As Tech's only returning linebacker, a senior and elder
statesman at age 23, Cameron was a natural to take over defensive
leadership responsibilities from departed linebackers Keith
Brooking and Ron Rogers. But what Cameron already knew in his
personal life, he had to learn in football on Sept. 5: Leadership
doesn't come easy.
</P>
<P>
   In the 41-31 loss to Boston College, Cameron had a disappointing
game, as did the rest of Tech's defense. But it didn't take him
long to learn from his mistakes. Cameron was the difference on
defense in Tech's 42-7 win over New Mexico State on Saturday night,
scooping up a fumble and returning it 25 yards for a touchdown. He
followed that up with the first interception of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leadership comes by performance,'' Cameron said. ``You've got
to show up to lead the pack, which Keith and Ron did. I didn't know
it was going to be that (tough).''
</P>
<P>
   To make it more difficult, Cameron separated his shoulder
lifting weights during the summer and missed the first two weeks of
contact in fall practice. Halfway through those two weeks, on the
day of the final preseason scrimmage, Cameron was back in Virginia
dealing with a different kind of pain, comforting his mother,
grandmother and his cousins at his Aunt Martha Cameron's funeral,
after she lost her fight with AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've actually seen up close what it does to people,'' Cameron
said. ``It's pretty scary. ... Stuff like that happens in life. I
just try to take it in stride.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't seem like it bothers him too much, but I know it
does,'' said Elizabeth Cameron, Delaunta's grandmother, who said
Delaunta was closest to his Aunt Mary, who died 15 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Cameron was recruited out of high school by Maryland, Virginia
Tech and Kentucky and signed with Wake Forest. But he failed to
make the necessary SAT score and had to spend a year at prep school
at Hargrave Military Academy. After his year there, he decided to
go for a fresh start at Georgia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a real disappointment in my life,'' Cameron said.
``But everything worked out for the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, in his first full year as a starter, Cameron made
his mark in the first defensive play of the first game of the
season, busting into the backfield and tackling a Notre Dame
running back for a loss.
</P>
<P>
   But for Cameron now, the New Mexico State game is the highlight
of his career. Even if his cousins couldn't see the game _ it
wasn't televised _ and it wasn't in the limelight of Notre Dame
Stadium, it came when big things were expected of him. Usually he
takes his young cousins Georgia Tech T-shirts. This time, ``Tay''
as they call him, is sending a videotape.
</P>
<P>
   The highlights are from about a 30-second span in the second
quarter. First Cameron came on a blitz from the left side as Jesse
Tarplin came from the right and sacked Ty Houghtaling, forcing the
fumble that Cameron ran in for a touchdown. Then, three plays
later, Cameron caught a pass intended for and tipped by New Mexico
State tight end Dustin Guinn and returned it seven yards to the
Aggie 28, setting up a Tech touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Cameron single-handedly helped Tech stretch a 14-0 lead to 28-0
and put the game away. He says it was a matter of being in the
right place at the right time. But as his family knows, Cameron was
the one who put himself in the position to be there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like a millionaire and don't have a dime,'' Elizabeth
Cameron said. ``I'm so proud of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
