<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-LEWIS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jamal Lewis won't skip Florida this year
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOXVILLE, Tenn. _ Jamal Lewis remembers watching the
Tennessee-Florida game last season like a caged tiger _ full of
energy just waiting to be sprung loose. He was a freshman and just
dying to show what he could do on the big stage. And there are few
stages anywhere bigger than the Volunteers' annual war with the
Gators.
</P>
<P>
   But it was not to be. Lewis would play a very small role in the
game _ five carries, 11 yards _ and the reasoning was pretty sound.
The Tennessee coaches had determined that Lewis, for all his
obvious ability to run the football, had not yet mastered the
complicated reads necessary to block Florida's vast array of
blitzes. One rookie mistake in that area and the franchise _
quarterback Peyton Manning _ could have been leveled by a Gator
avalanche.
</P>
<P>
   ``Against that particular team, with the way they pressure the
quarterback, we didn't think it was worth the risk,'' coach Phillip
Fulmer said. ``It wouldn't have been fair to Jamal. He had only
played in two games.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said, ``I knew going in that I wasn't going to play much
because I didn't know my pass protection stuff that well. But it
was still hard to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis didn't know it at the time, but the game would be the
turning point of his career. After the Volunteers lost 33-20 and
gained only 45 yards rushing, Fulmer met with his staff Sunday
morning and made a change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided we were relying on one guy (Manning) too much. We'd
become too predictable,'' Fulmer said. ``It was time to get Jamal
ready to play.''
</P>
<P>
   The rest, of course, is Volunteer history. After an open date,
Lewis carried 22 times for 155 yards in his first start against
Mississippi. Then on Oct. 11, the whole country learned about Jamal
Lewis when he ran for 232 yards on 22 carries in a nationally
televised 38-13 win over Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   By year's end, Lewis was the nation's leading freshman rusher
with 1,364 yards. Tennessee went on to win the SEC championship,
and Lewis was named a freshman All-American. Lewis no longer was a
rookie when he returned for the 1998 season. He added considerable
muscle to his 6-0, 220-pound frame and is poised for what many
believe could be an All-America season.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't disappoint in the opener against Syracuse. In what
turned out to be a dogfight in the Carrier Dome, Lewis ran for 64
of his 140 yards in the fourth period and set up the last-second
field goal in the 34-33 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jamal is one of those guys who makes the difference with the
game on the line,'' Fulmer said.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis will get a golden opportunity Saturday when No. 6
Tennessee hosts No. 2 Florida in a prime-time game (8 p.m., CBS) at
Neyland Stadium. The Vols have lost five in a row to the Gators and
have been outrushed in four of those losses. The hope at Tennessee
is that if Lewis can present a serious running threat, it might
slow down the Gators' fierce pass rush, which will be directed
toward quarterback Tee Martin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know they want to put a lot of pressure on Tee because he's
new,'' said Lewis, who has four career games of more than 150
yards. ``My job is to give them something else to think about.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis makes no secret of his desire to play in the NFL later. He
spent the summer working out in Atlanta with current and former pro
players, learning what it takes to play at the next level. To his
way of thinking, people like backs who come up big in big games.
And this, for Tennessee, is the biggest game.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the kind of games where you really get a chance to
prove yourself,'' Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   Fulmer says that, as good as Lewis has been since becoming a
starter, his best games are still ahead of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we've seen his best,'' Fulmer said. ``He's just
beginning to scratch the surface of his ability.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
