PRISON DOCTOR IN McDOUGAL CASE COULD LOSE HIS JOB 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JACK DOUGLAS Jr. 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ A prison doctor could lose his job at the
prison if he does not adequately explain why he did not check on
the medical welfare of Whitewater witness James McDougal only hours
before McDougal died, an official said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Renewal of the doctor's contract with the Federal Medical Center
prison in Fort Worth hinges on his written report to supervisors
about what happened during the last hours of McDougal's life, said
Tom Gore, associate vice president of the University of North Texas
Health Science Center. The center provides doctors to work under
contract for the prison.
</P>
<P>
   The doctor's name was not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   An internal report prepared by the federal Bureau of Prisons
indicates that the doctor did not respond when McDougal, 57,
complained of being dizzy on March 7, the evening before he died.
Two physician assistants were also notified, but neither checked on
McDougal, saying they were ``treating other inmates and were
scheduled to get off duty,'' according to the report.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of his death, McDougal, a former friend of President
Clinton's and a key witness for Whitewater prosecutors, was serving
a three-year federal prison sentence for fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Craig, spokesman for the Bureau of Prisons in Washington,
said Tuesday that the two physician assistants are still working at
the prison. The doctor's future there, however, is less certain,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The doctor gave a satisfactory oral explanation of why he did
not see McDougal when the prisoner complained of being dizzy, Gore
said, but then turned in a written report that was ``legalistic,''
``defensive'' and hard to understand.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Marlo, a spokeswoman for the federal prison system in Fort
Worth, said she could not comment on whether policies have changed
as a result of the internal review of McDougal's treatment at the
prison.
</P>
<P>
   Prison officials considered giving McDougal, who had a bad
heart, his prescribed medication on the night of March 7, but a
nursing supervisor decided to wait until the next morning, the
report says. It also notes that McDougal did not appear to be
following doctor's orders on when to take his medicine, even when
it was easily accessible.
</P>
<P>
   At 8:30 a.m. on March 8, about two hours before he collapsed,
McDougal said he ``was in need of his scheduled medication,'' the
report says. Asked what types of medicine McDougal had asked for,
Craig said: ``I'm not going to comment on that.'' The report says
McDougal was given three 20 milligram pills of the antidepressant
drug Prozac.
</P>
<P>
   His other medication remained in a different part of the prison,
including tablets of nitroglycerin that he was to take ``as
needed'' when he experienced chest pains, the report said. At 10:55
a.m., McDougal was found unresponsive and on the floor of an
isolation cell, where he had been taken after he could not provide
urine for a drug test.
</P>
<P>
   McDougal died of a heart attack, authorities ruled.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
