<SLUG> BC-AOL-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: FORMER TV EXECUTIVE TO PROVIDE WEB CONTENT FOR WOMEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By SAUL HANSELL    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a bow to advertisers marketing products to women,
America Online said Tuesday that it had agreed to sell three of its
women-oriented services to a new venture formed by Geraldine
Laybourne, the former head of cable television operations for Walt
Disney Co. and ABC Inc., who will develop them for the online
service's new Women's Channel.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Laybourne, long considered one of the most successful women
in the television industry, left Disney/ABC in May to form Oxygen
Media, a company devoted to creating programs for women and
children, both on the Internet and on television. Before joining
Disney/ABC, she built up Nickelodeon, the children's cable network.
</P>
<P>
   The terms of the deal were not disclosed. But a person close to
both companies said that America Online would retain an equity
stake of about 10 percent in Oxygen and would receive millions of
dollars in cash.
</P>
<P>
   In return, Oxygen will get three content services: Electra, a
service aimed at women; Moms Online, which is for parents; and
Thrive, a service devoted to health issues. Under terms of the
deal, these sites will be displayed prominently on America Online's
new Women's Channel and other places on its service and on its
World Wide Web site, AOL.com.
</P>
<P>
   Thrive was part owned by Time Warner Inc., but America Online
bought out that stake before selling the service to Oxygen.
Similarly, Moms Online had several other investors, which Oxygen
bought out.
</P>
<P>
   The deal attests to the growing importance of women to online
marketers. According to America Online, about 51 percent of its 13
million users are women, up from only 16 percent in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``The traditional media have missed the boat with modern
women,'' Ms. Laybourne said. ``There is nothing that serves women
the way ESPN serves men or Nickelodeon serves kids. We want to
create a brand on both television and the Internet that brings
humor and playfulness and a voice that makes a women say, `You
really understand me.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Oxygen and the other women's services hope they can sell ads to
makers of the sort of package goods that have typically been
promoted on soap operas and other women-oriented television
programming.
</P>
<P>
   America Online, for example, has an extensive deal to develop
new forms of advertising for Unilever, the maker of Wisk detergent
and Lipton tea. Some of the Unilever ads are expected to be placed
on the services being sold to Oxygen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eighty five percent of purchases are made by women,'' Ms.
Laybourne said. ``We can be a real facilitator of commerce.''
</P>
<P>
   The move also represents yet another flip-flop for America
Online on the question of whether it wants to create its own
programming or rely on outside companies for what the Internet
industry calls ``content.''
</P>
<P>
   Initially, America Online was dependent on outside publishers
for content. Then it began taking partial stakes in content
companies, including iVillage Inc., another service aimed at women.
About a year ago, it began to bring some content more directly
under its control. It created Electra as its own women's area,
competing directly with iVillage.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the latest about-face is a longstanding
professional relationship between Robert Pittman, the president of
America Online, and Ms. Laybourne. Having hired Ms. Laybourne 20
years ago when he was an executive of MTV Networks, which started
Nickelodeon, Pittman called her the day her resignation from
Disney/ABC was announced to explore potential deals.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, America Online has now decided it wants to pull back
from operating its own content areas, in part because it has
discovered that it can exact multimillion-dollar payments from
content companies to display their services prominently to its
members. As a result, the service would rather offer a menu of a
handful of featured content areas in each topic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our audience tells us they want us to do the hard work of
finding the best content online and putting a context around it,''
said Barry Schuler, president of America Online's interactive
services unit. ``We need to own the top level, but when it comes
down to the hard-core editorial stuff, we think that's a game of
consolidation and critical mass, and we don't need to own all of
that.''
</P>
<P>
   While America Online now calls Oxygen the ``centerpiece'' of its
Women's Channel, the company also has relationships with most of
the other players in programming for women. It is the largest
shareholder of iVillage, with a stake of just under 20 percent. And
its service also has links to Women.com Networks, Hearst Corp.'s
Homearts service and the online complements of the Oprah and Rosie
O'Donnell talk shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Competition is healthy for the marketplace,'' Schuler said.
``Our audience wins when there is more than one strong player out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Candice Carpenter, the chief executive of iVillage, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's crazy to think that what may be the biggest category
online will only have one player,'' she said of women's
programming. ``I'd rather have a few good competitors who will
develop the space intelligently and aggressively.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Carpenter denied industry reports that the relationship
between iVillage and America Online had become strained.
</P>
<P>
   ``AOL has been fabulous,'' she said. ``They called me the day
that this deal was discussed the first time. And I've signed a lot
of big deals with AOL's competitors, and they have given me no flak
for it.'' Moreover, she added, ``We were offered Electra and Moms
Online, and we turned them down.''
</P>
<P>
   At this stage, it is hard to discern much difference between the
strategies of the two companies. Ms. Carpenter said that iVillage
was designed to have more places for advertising than the existing
Electra and Moms Online services. And iVillage is less interested
than Oxygen in pursuing television programming, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Laybourne said the deal with America Online would be the
first of many partnerships Oxygen would forge with big media and
online companies. In the coming months, she said, she will decide
whether to create television programs for an existing network or
make the high-stakes bet on forming a new cable network. Oxygen is
also already selling sponsorships to companies that seek to sell
goods to women. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
