<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS' TOP DRAFT CHOICE IMPRESSES  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By JOE LAPOINTE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURLINGTON, Vt. _ The defenseman skated the puck to his blue
line, where Manny Malhotra was waiting. Malhotra anticipated the
pass, intercepted it with his shin pad, scooped up the puck on his
stick and dashed in alone to score on a backhander to give his team
a 1-0 lead during a scrimmage Tuesday at the University of Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   Malhotra, the Rangers' 18-year-old first-round draft choice,
went on to assist on three more goals to lead his side to a 4-1
victory. When the game was over, he remained on the ice to practice
face-offs and work on his lateral stops and starts. He was the last
to leave, walking to the bench carrying a big bucket of pucks.
</P>
<P>
   Although he has not yet driven the Zamboni to resurface the ice,
Malhotra has done just about everything else well in his first
professional training camp. Everyone is closely watching this
6-foot-2-inch, 210-pound prospect. On draft day last June, General
Manager Neil Smith predicted Malhotra could make the team and play
regularly as a third-line center.
</P>
<P>
   Although few rookies play well at that age in the National
Hockey League, some do, including Boston's Sergei Samsonov, last
season's rookie of the year. The question, according to Coach John
Muckler, is how well Malhotra can handle the pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is peer pressure, fan pressure, media pressure, pressure
from the coach, pressure from management,'' Muckler said Tuesday.
``Sometimes, we're hesitant to play 18-year-olds. I don't happen to
be one of those people. He's a very conscientious person. He's very
intelligent. He's not afraid to ask questions. Mentally, is he
strong enough? We'll see.''
</P>
<P>
   Malhotra grew up in a suburb of Toronto. His mother is from
French Canada, his father from India. Both parents have doctoral
degrees in chemistry. Scouts who watched Malhotra at his junior
team in Guelph of the Ontario League praised his poise and his
leadership qualities. He speaks with quiet confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a little bit of pressure, obviously,'' Malhotra said.
``But that's part of the game. I've come into camp knowing that it
doesn't matter where I was drafted or what's been said. What
matters is how I perform on the ice and who I'm beating out for a
position.''
</P>
<P>
   One player he won't have to beat out is Wayne Gretzky, the
first-line center. Behind Gretzky, the pivot position on every line
is open as the Rangers try to rebuild after missing the playoffs
for the first time since 1993. Malhotra said his jaw dropped when
he met Gretzky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to look at him in awe,'' Malhotra said of
Gretzky. ``But it's really hard not to stare sometimes. I find
myself getting caught up in watching him. I had the opportunity to
speak with him for a few brief moments. It was kind of weird. You
don't know what to think or what to say. You're looking at a living
legend. I was just kind of standing there wide-eyed and my jaw on
the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   He got to move his jaw more a couple days later when Gretzky
invited him to dinner. More than some veterans, Gretzky eschews the
hazing rituals for rookies that are a dwindling part of the hockey
culture. Through word and deed, Gretzky has indicated Malhotra will
be treated with professional respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``The players have taken him in not as a rookie but as part of
the team, a guy on our squad,'' Gretzky said. ``He looks really
solid, excited, a heads-up player, a big boy. He's the kind of guy
in six, seven, eight, nine, 10 years, you can build a hockey team
around him. He'll be the focal point on the Rangers. He carries
himself with a lot of class. We expect him to get a shot. He's
going to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
