<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MINORS-BROOKLYN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY REACHES AGREEMENT WITH METS TO MOVE CLASS A TEAM TO BROOKLYN  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)   By ANDY NEWMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's plan to bring professional
baseball back to Brooklyn moved forward Tuesday with the
announcement that the city had reached an agreement in principle
with the New York Mets to move their Pittsfield, Mass., minor
league team to a new ball park in Coney Island.
</P>
<P>
   The $20 million stadium, to be built on the site of the
abandoned Steeplechase Park amusement area, would be paid for by
the city, the mayor said.
</P>
<P>
   Although there is money in the city budget to build the stadium,
the deal requires the approval of the New York Yankees, which, like
all major league teams, can veto any attempt to move a minor league
team into their territory. Tuesday, a Yankees official said that
talks to get around that potential roadblock had recently broken
off.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not here willy-nilly saying no to the mayor, no to the
city and no to the Mets,'' said Lonn Trost, the Yankees' executive
vice president. ``There was an attempt to negotiate agreement with
the city, which has failed.''
</P>
<P>
   Trost refused to say why negotiations had broken down.
Nevertheless, Giuliani said in his comments Tuesday that the
Yankees' principal owner, George Steinbrenner, had in fact pledged
not to stand in the way of a Mets minor league team moving to
Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been told by both owners, directly, that they would not
stand in the way of the other team coming,'' Giuliani said,
referring to Steinbrenner and Fred Wilpon, the Mets' co-owner.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor said he hoped that plans to build a stadium for a
Yankees franchise on Staten Island would remove any obstacles.
</P>
<P>
   Plans date back to at least 1986 for building the Coney Island
stadium, which under this proposal would hold 6,500 people, in the
city's long-decaying resort capital, whose amusement area has
shrunk to 3 blocks from 20 blocks over the last 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 12-acre stadium site is an overgrown vacant lot. The
only structure still standing on it, just past where the
right-field foul pole would be, is the Parachute Jump, a tall,
spidery skeleton with cables drooping from it that has not seen a
jumper since Steeplechase Park closed, in 1964.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement announced Tuesday, the Mets would oversee
the construction of the stadium and would then rent it from the
city for a sum not yet agreed upon.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor said that if the stadium got the go-ahead, it could be
built in as little as two years. In addition to getting the
Yankees' approval, the project must still go through the local
land-use review process and be approved by the city's Franchise and
Concession Review Committee, Major League Baseball and the New
York-Penn League, in which the Pittsfield Mets play.
</P>
<P>
   The New York-Penn League is a short-season Class A league, which
is one level above the rookie league and just below full-fledged
Class A. Its teams play 76 games a year. This year, the Pittsfield
Mets finished six games under .500 and were third in their
division.
</P>
<P>
   In Pittsfield, a city of 46,000 in western Massachusetts that
has seen a succession of farm teams come and go over the years _
the Mets moved in 10 years ago _ Mayor Gerald Doyle was
disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``if the Mets do leave,'' Doyle said, ``it's obvious that it
will be a major blow to our tourism numbers.'' But he said the city
had been remodeling its 80-year-old stadium and hoped to attract
another team.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-98 2117EDT &QL; 
