<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-PRINCETON-STADIUM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRINCETON TO DEDICATE NEW STADIUM  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM N. WALLACE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRINCETON, N.J. _ Tearing down venerable Palmer Stadium, where
Princeton teams had performed since 1914, was an easy task. Steve
Tosches, the football coach, was there watching the Mercer Wrecking
Co.'s giant claws rip apart the grandstand and Tuesday he recalled
those moments from December 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``Down it came,'' he said. ``The concrete was like sand. The
wreckers said it was one of the easiest jobs they'd ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   The moment also justified the decision by university officials
to abandon expensive preservation of Palmer and build a new
facility, a decision mourned, if not questioned, by many
sentimental alumni.
</P>
<P>
   That this was the right decision will be affirmed and celebrated
on Saturday, when the new Princeton Stadium is dedicated and the
first game, the Tigers against Cornell, is played.
</P>
<P>
   For $45 million, a small sum relative to that of stadiums being
built for National Football League teams costing at least four
times as much, Princeton gets a lot in a facility that is clearly
different.
</P>
<P>
   The standout feature is a tall colonnade curving above and
around most of the four-sided grandstand, and the stadium's beige
precast concrete matches the nearby university buildings.
</P>
<P>
   The playing field is grass. The stands have a sharp incline that
offers excellent sight lines from backless metal benches. There are
no sky boxes, and Princeton never found a $25 million donor who
could have named the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is in every way a stadium of many uses and purposes,''
said Gary Walters, the director of athletics and a Princeton
alumnus. ``It's here not only for football, but for the university
as a whole, and the entire community.''
</P>
<P>
   Walters had championship lacrosse and soccer games in mind,
perhaps even commencement ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   The seating capacity is 27,500, which makes it the
fourth-largest stadium in the Ivy League. Palmer Stadium had space
for 45,750 but had not been filled in 30 years. In recent seasons,
Princeton has been fortunate to average 11,000 spectators for five
or six home games.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to pull people into what Walters calls ``a
back-to-the-future stadium,'' he and Richard Spies, vice president
for finance, set a price of only $5 for all tickets, or $20 for a
season ticket. That is about a third of the customary Ivy League
price. Season-ticket sales have jumped six times, Walters said, to
6,600.
</P>
<P>
   Cheers for the home team in this more intimate stadium will
benefit the players, Tosches said. Jim Salters, a senior
linebacker, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always like to hear the crowd behind you,'' said Salters,
who remembers how quiet Palmer Stadium could be on game days during
his freshman and sophomore seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Princeton played all 10 games on the road last season, winning
half of them, while the new stadium was being built on the site of
the old one. In Palmer Stadium, the Tiger teams in orange and black
won 283 games, lost 161 and tied 17 over 83 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The Princeton Stadium architect was the renowned Rafael Vinoly
of New York, who used input from various committees that included
such football luminaries as Dick Kazmaier, the 1951 Heisman Trophy
winner, and his teammate John Emery of the development office.
</P>
<P>
   Whether this stadium will help Princeton, and the Ivy League in
general, to regain more of their audience remains to be seen. Last
season, the Ivies had an attendance decline of 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The other Ivy schools _ all but Columbia playing in stadiums at
least 73 years old _ may be envious of Princeton.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
