A6932 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SCANDAL-BOS &LR;      09-15 1452
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SCANDAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS WRANGLE OVER CLINTON GRAND JURY VIDEOTAPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER AND BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Tensions roiled Capitol Hill Tuesday as House
Republicans rebuffed attacks on their plan to make public President
Clinton's videotaped grand jury testimony and Senate Democrats
privately blasted White House officials over Clinton's sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   With a showdown looming as early as Thursday over the videotape,
the preliminary skirmishes erupted despite warnings from party
leaders for lawmakers to avoid rancor that would diminish the
public's faith in the House to conduct a fair review of 11
impeachment allegations against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   At stake in the struggle over the videotape, which showed the
president angered by the questioning and is described by a source
close to the House Judiciary Committee as being peppered with
``X-rated'' material, is the likelihood that its release would
unleash another wave of revulsion over Clinton's affair with former
White House intern Monica S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The Judiciary Committee is expected to meet behind closed doors
Thursday or Friday to approve releasing the tape, according to
several panel members.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republicans are clearly drooling at the prospect of using the
tapes in campaign ads,'' said Representative Martin T. Meehan, a
Massachusetts Democrat who serves on the Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, there is a chance of this process breaking down in
terms of bipartisanship'' if the tape is released, said Meehan, who
faces no opposition in November.
</P>
<P>
   As House Democrats fought to keep the tape sealed until the
impeachment inquiry is completed, their Senate counterparts vented
anger over the scandal in a private lunch meeting with a delegation
of White House aides led by Erskine B. Bowles, the chief of staff.
About 40 Democratic senators attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some very angry people, some very disappointed
people, and it's hard to sort it out,'' said Senator John F. Kerry,
in his first public comments since Congress received the report
last week from the independent counsel, Kenneth W. Starr. ``People
are still sorting it out. They are upset.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Senate Democrats went to unusual lengths to keep the
encounter private, including expelling their staff from the meeting
and leaving through a back door to avoid the news media, sources
said several members were blunt.
</P>
<P>
   Impeachment allegations aside, times are perilous for
congressional Democrats, who are trying to wrest back control of
the House and prevent Republicans from gaining a filibuster-proof
majority in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Sources said the angriest senators appeared to be those who are
up for reelection this year, especially women such as Senator
Barbara Boxer of California, who are being repeatedly questioned
and criticized at home for their allegiance to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   There also was concern about potential harm to the Democratic
Party's bid to retain the White House in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``The political fallout is obvious,'' said Senator Bob Kerrey of
Nebraska, who is chairman of the Senate Democratic election effort
and a possible presidential contender in 2000. ``It's either going
to hurt us or help us, and it's not likely to be the latter.''
</P>
<P>
   Several senators who attended the meeting said their colleagues
did not raise the possibility of Clinton negotiating a less
damaging punishment from Congress than impeachment, such as
censure. Instead, they focused on Clinton's actions, particularly
lying about the Lewinsky affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trust is certainly an issue that is on the table with all of
my colleagues,'' Kerry said. ``He would have to earn my trust
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerry said that Clinton ``absolutely'' should be punished for
his behavior in some way, but he said any talk of impeachment or
censure was premature. ``You cannot just pretend this did not
happen,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry also said he thought Clinton would be ``significantly
diminished'' as president if he stays in office.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Democrats also received a private briefing on the House
inquiry from Abbe Lowell, the chief minority counsel on the
Judiciary Committee. Lowell told them the immediate battle centers
on the videotape.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans on the committee defended releasing the tape, noting
the House voted, 363-63, last week to empower the panel to decide
by Sept. 28 how much of the sealed information in 17 boxes of
materials from Starr's investigation to release. Democrats do not
have enough votes on the committee to block the move.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's information the public has a right to know,'' said
Representative Bob Barr, a Georgia Republican who serves on the
committee and was one of the first House members to call for
Clinton's impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people have a problem with the graphic testimony,'' Barr
said, ``they should complain to 1600 Pennsylvania Avenue.''
</P>
<P>
   Representative Sheila Jackson Lee, a Texas Democrat and member
of the Judicicary Committee, said the apparent GOP rush to release
the videotape is a sign ``that we are about to begin a Salem witch
hunt.''
</P>
<P>
   A senior Republican on the committee, Representative George W.
Gekas of Pennsylvania, expressed concern about tensions surrounding
the tape. ``We do want the process to have the print of
bipartisanship,'' Gekas said. ``If we split on a lot of things, we
are straying from the goal.''
</P>
<P>
   A source familiar with Clinton's testimony said Clinton appeared
volatile in the videotaped session, repeatedly becoming enraged as
he was asked to address specific details of his sexual exploits
with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, when prosecutors asked Clinton about a specific
episode with Lewinsky, Clinton became so angry that the proceeding
was halted for more than an hour as the president left the room and
met privately with his lawyers, the source said.
</P>
<P>
   The session began with Clinton reading a brief statement to the
grand jurors acknowledging an inappropriate and intimate
relationship with Lewinsky. From there, prosecutors pressed
repeatedly for more details, confronting him time and again with
Lewinsky's recollections of their 10 sexual encounters near the
Oval Office as well as their numerous telephone calls that included
sexually charged conversations.
</P>
<P>
   The spectacle of Clinton's secret testimony being served to the
public is one that some within the White House still find galling.
But those same aides believe there is little they can do to stop
the release, and little political benefit in even making an effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had fully expected that the president's deposition before
the grand jury would be released in some fashion _ certainly the
transcript,'' said Michael D. McCurry, the White House press
secretary. ``The House is going to have to employ the video however
they see fit. We just hope that it's not misused.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the White House feared that snippets of Clinton's
testimony might find their way into political advertisements
against supportive Democratic lawmakers this fall, McCurry said,
``One could imagine that might happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Regarding the public's reaction, McCurry said, ``I think that
they've seen just about all there is to see on this, so I don't
think it'll be of any greater shock or surprise than what they've
already seen.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House also began assembling a new team of
congressional lobbyists to try to stem any impeachment proceedings
before the process gets too far along. The team will include
Gregory Craig, a State Department aide, former foreign policy
adviser to Senator Edward M. Kennedy, and a former law partner of
Clinton's personal lawyer David Kendall. Craig currently serves as
the director of policy and planning at the State Department.
</P>
<P>
   It will also include former White House congressional liaison
Susan Brophy of Quincy, Mass., who plans to return to Washington
temporarily from her new home in Portugal, where she lives with her
husband, the US ambassador.
</P>
<P>
   The lobbying effort, White House officials said, is expected to
begin almost immediately, starting with Bowles and his deputy, John
Podesta, attending Tuesday's meeting with Democratic senators.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Senator Frank Murkowski, an Alaska Republican, called
on Clinton to pay for Starr's investigation of the Lewinsky matter,
which Clinton appeared to prolong by refusing to acknowledge his
relationship with the former intern. Murkowski estimated the cost
at $4.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   McCurry, asked if Clinton owes taxpayers the funds, replied,
``No, the president does not owe the taxpayers that money.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Chris Black of the Globe staff contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
