<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTEL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Intel chief executive tells the industry to simplify   By Dan Fost  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Palm Springs 
 
The computer was small, triangular and blue, but it wasn't an iMac.
Intel Corp. chief executive Craig Barrett displayed the computer at
an Intel conference here yesterday in an attempt to inspire
computer-makers to produce distinctive  and easy-to-use machines.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``If we're going to get to 1 billion connected PCs, there's
clearly a lot the industry has to do,'' Barrett said, invoking a
long-standing goal of his predecessor Andrew Grove. ``We need to
make these easier to use.''
</P>
<P>
   The colorful post-modern machine ran a video conferencing
demonstration using a graphics chip, code-named Katmai, that Intel
plans to release next year. The box itself, which looked more like
a lamp one might find in a trendy South of Market furniture shop,
won't ever make it to the marketplace, but Intel has high hopes for
the Katmai chips supplanting the company's popular MMX multimedia
technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think even Steve Jobs might start to get jealous with this
type of design,'' Barrett told his audience of more than 1,000
people.
</P>
<P>
   Jobs' Apple Computer may have pioneered the notion of a computer
that's easy to use, but its Macintosh machines don't run on Intel
chips _ even though more than 85 percent of the PCs sold today do.
</P>
<P>
   That's why, when Barrett calls for simple machines, designers
listen. ``We all want it to happen, to sell lots of computers,''
said Kameron Ayati, a designer for Compaq Computer's workstation
group. Asked if Intel is doing a good job leading the industry,
Ayati said with a laugh, ``Who's the alternative?''
</P>
<P>
   Barrett delivered the keynote at the Intel Developer Forum, a
twice-a-year event for the company's customers that even Intel
officials describe as a ``geekfest.''
</P>
<P>
   He said people should be able to turn their computers on
instantly, to plug objects in with ease, to feel comfortable with
Internet security, and to have a fast connection to the World Wide
Web.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Mike Feibus with Mercury Research said Barrett was
merely reiterating what the industry has known, and been trying to
implement, for several years. But, Feibus said, it's a message
computer-makers still needs to hear.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this industry is going to tap the next layer of the
iceberg, it's going to have to do things differently,'' Feibus
said.
</P>
<P>
   Intel has already developed features like the Universal Serial
Bus, or USB, which enables people to easily plug printers, scanners
and other devices into computers. Even the iMac uses USB ports.
</P>
<P>
   Intel develops such technology and licenses it broadly to help
grow the entire market. The more people who use computers, then the
more chips Intel is likely to sell.
</P>
<P>
   Intel, based in Santa Clara, is the world's largest chip
company, with profits of $6.9 billion on sales of $25 billion last
year. Yet a chip industry slump has slowed the firm's sales this
year, and the company also faces increased competition and a
federal antitrust prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett, who assumed the reins of Intel in May, said the
industry must reach out to new markets to continue its phenomenal
growth. ``The main reason people my age don't want to use a
computer is they're afraid they'll break them,'' said Barrett, who
turned 59 last month.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Barrett highlighted some of the increasing
complexity of personal computers at the same time he called for
their simplicity. The complexity, however, is in the increasing
options available to consumers, who can now choose among machines
that sell for $800 or much more expensive models that can display
complicated videos and flashy graphics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our job is to hide the complexity,'' Barrett said in an
interview after his speech. ``We have to hide the complexity to
make the system easier to use.''
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Nathan Brookwood of Dataquest said the growing
popularity of the Internet may help grow the market as well.
``What's important for growing the industry is making PCs more
relevant for people that don't already have one. It's not just,
`Can I plug in a scanner?' but `Is the Internet so compelling that
if I don't have access, I'll be really out in left field?' ''
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1960s, Brookwood said, he had friends who
``resisted having a television. They said, `The stuff on TV is
junk, who needs it?' Following the Kennedy assassination, the last
holdouts realized they'd better have a TV. I suspect that last
week's episode with the Starr report may persuade a few people the
Internet is no longer a thing for geeks and technophiles.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
