<SLUG> BC-INTELSIDE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 What Craig Barrett Had to Say   By Dan Fost  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
In a speech and interviews this week, Intel chief executive Craig
Barrett shared his thoughts on some key issues:
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; On rumors Intel will acquire 3Com for $9 billion: &LR;  ``We never
comment on speculation about speculation. ... We're very interested
in networking. One billion connected PCs means 1 billion processors
all connected. ... We have a lot of cash. Our credit line is
reasonably good. I could borrow $9 billion without hurting the
company, speaking hypothetically.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; On the Federal Trade Commission's antitrust prosecution of &LR; 
 &UR; Intel: &LR;  ``If we were the monopolists that we're claimed to be,
after seven quarters of declining revenues and flat earnings, we're
pretty crummy monopolists. We can't even capitalize on our
monopoly. ... We both are in agreement over what happened
factually. The basic disagreement is on the legality of our
actions.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; On the need for the industry to change its mind-set: &LR;  ``You
can't be an egghead engineer and expect the common person to
follow. One of the great challenges of the world is to give the
consumer what the consumer wants, as opposed to selling technology
for technology's sake.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; On Asia: &LR;  ``All the growth will be in emerging economies. China
and India today are growing like wildfire. ... It's very important
for Intel to be out there, establish a presence, establish `Intel
inside.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
