<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOFA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 BofA Loss In Trading Soars 50%   By Peter Sinton  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
BankAmerica raised its estimates yesterday of trading losses from
Russia and other emerging markets by 50 percent to about $330
million.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Less than three weeks ago, BofA announced that it would write
off $220 million this quarter, primarily to cover securities and
currency trading losses in Russia. BofA's stock slipped yesterday
$1 to close at $63.81.
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts, though, weren't bothered by the sudden revision
of estimated losses, and both BofA and NationsBank reaffirmed their
merger plans. ``It's not a total surprise,'' said Van Kasper
analyst Jeff Runnfeldt. ``With the shareholder vote on the merger
coming up (September 24), they want to have full disclosure. Other
banks are likely to wait until the end of the quarter to provide
new loss numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   BofA said its consumer business remains ``solid'' and it still
expects after-tax profit, excluding merger-related charges, to top
$500 million in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But earnings per share could be only half of early estimates.
``We were looking for about $1.20 and are now expecting 60 cents a
share,'' said Raphael Soifer of Brown Brothers Harriman.
</P>
<P>
   Included in the current quarter's results will be a $480 million
pretax gain from the sale of the bank's BA Housing Services unit
that will be offset in part by a $200 million write-down of the
bank's investment in South Korea's KorAm Bank and other charges.
</P>
<P>
   To put BofA's $330 million in third quarter trading losses in
perspective, it earned $223 million in the same quarter last year.
</P>
<P>
   Soifer said the additional losses since BofA's August 28
announcement probably reflect problems in Latin America and Asia
rather than additional exposure in Russia. The bank declined to
provide more specifics on trading losses.
</P>
<P>
   However it did say that noninterest income from equity
investments is also down. In the past two months, investment income
was $30 million compared to $125 million in the entire second
quarter. The bank also lost $12 million in interest income from
buying and holding securities in July and August, compared to $53
million in the previous quarter.
</P>
<P>
   BofA's trading losses since Russia's financial meltdown are the
largest recorded by a U.S. bank so far. Soifer suggests total U.S.
bank losses are well above $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But U.S. bank exposure to Russia is ``not humongous,'' he says.
It's only about $7.7 billion, or less than half the loans to
Brazil. Total U.S. bank loans to foreign borrowers are well above
$300 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-98 2121EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
