<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-BLACKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACK VOTERS STILL LOYAL TO CLINTON, POLLS FIND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER S. CANELLOS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Love is not a word that comes easily to James
Nyanfore, of Washington's Mt. Pleasant neighborhood. But when he
saw the president go to Africa and speak of the havoc wreaked by
slavery, Nyanfore knew in his heart that ``I will always love Bill
Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   In Clinton's summer of betrayal, one bond remains unbroken; one
relationship untrammeled. Clinton long ago won the loyalty of much
of the black community. Polls indicate blacks remain solidly behind
the man whom many portray as a brother of the rural South and a
president who put racial healing near the top of his political
agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as the Congressional Black Caucus discusses whether to
issue a sweeping statement backing the president, black support
could be crucial to Clinton's political survival. With even such
conservatives as Patrick J. Buchanan demanding that any impeachment
effort be bipartisan, Clinton's fate will depend in part on the
loyalty of Democrats in Congress; and any Democrats who waver may
risk the wrath of black voters, a core constituency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Black voters feel deeply that President Clinton has been there
for them. People see that he's in need. He stood up for us, and now
we'll stand up for him,'' said Representative John R. Lewis,
Democrat of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said that whether or not the black caucus issues a formal
endorsement of Clinton, ``the caucus will be unified in its support
of the president. And we're only reflecting the views of the black
community. When I was home this weekend, black women and black men
came up to me saying `Is the president going to be all right?' A
little old lady said, `Is my man going to be all right?'''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, where blacks make up nearly two-thirds of the
population, voters went to the polls to nominate a new mayor. Those
who campaigned outside Abraham Lincoln Junior High, the most
politically active residents of the Mt. Pleasant/Columbia Heights
area, backed different mayoral contenders, but only one president.
Many said that Kenneth W. Starr's investigation actually
intensified their loyalty to Clinton, for reasons that don't
necessarily resonate with the white community.
</P>
<P>
   Some said they did not want to risk losing a president who has
presided over an economy that has benefited blacks as well as
whites. Others see a rarity in a public figure who counts blacks
among his closest friends and advisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have to look any further than Vernon Jordan as his
golfing partner and Betty Currie as his secretary,'' said Valerie
Mitchell-Sigwalt, noting how many black people were in Clinton's
inner circle.
</P>
<P>
   For Soncarae Thornton, the moral issues surrounding the Clinton
scandal that so vex much of the country seem rather simple _ and
mundane _ to her, only emphasizing the distance between black
America and Washington's largely-white power structure.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people here feel like, `If a man cheats, he's going
to lie about it,''' Thornton said. ``That's common knowledge here
on the streets. I don't know about higher up.''
</P>
<P>
   And there's another reason, alluded to by Thornton's 12-year-old
son, Tariq Abdul Latif, who complained, ``They're always going
after Clinton for everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Whitehead, a University of Massachusetts professor, said,
``A lot of African-Americans, for perfectly legitimate reasons,
don't like prosecutors. To the degree that this is a battle between
Bill Clinton and Ken Starr, the choice for black America is awfully
easy to make.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a point also made, with trademark sarcasm, by black
comedian Chris Rock. Wildly popular in Washington, Rock has made
the bond between Clinton and many blacks a part of his standup
routine. He has said Clinton is ``the first black president of the
United States. They don't give him any slack, you know. Clinton
will spend a $100 bill, and they'll put it up to the light.''
</P>
<P>
   The similarities between Clinton's background and that of many
blacks from the South was not lost on voters.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Palmer, of Mt. Pleasant, explained, ``Even though he's
white, his background is no different than ours. He grew up in the
rural South. He was in poverty in many ways. He rose above that.
And those are things that are greatly respected in the black
community. Even though he's white, he's a person that a lot of us
identify with.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's familiarity with black culture has two roots _ the
experience of living shoulder to shoulder with blacks in Hope,
Ark., despite segregated institutions; and his position at the
vanguard of a generation that broke the chains of the Jim Crow era.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his young adulthood, Clinton had many black friends,
including a black roommate for a time. A black friend showed him
around Moscow during a visit to the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   As president, Clinton's gestures reflect his knowledge and
affection for black culture. His speeches often echo the cadences
of the black church. He sometimes seems more comfortable before
black audiences than white. His first elaborated apology for the
Lewinsky scandal was in Oak Bluffs, Mass., a vacation home to many
blacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of white liberals know the words, but they don't seem to
feel the music,'' said Whitehead. ``Clinton does.''
</P>
<P>
   William T. Coleman Jr., a black friend of Clinton's from Yale,
told Maraniss that he had a theory about black and white
southerners who have transcended segregation: ``They feel some part
of the soul that touches each other. There is something about the
rhythm that creates a compatability. Bill had it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nyanfore, the Washington voter who loved Clinton for going to
Africa, actually sensed a gleam of recognition in Clinton's eye
when the president visited his church in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time I got to see the president and shake his
hand like another human being,'' he said. ``We're all human beings.
He has said he was wrong. He asked God for forgiveness. He asked
the whole country to forgive him. And it's time the country forgave
each other and went on to do the work God wants us to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
