<HEADER>
A6950 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REFUGEE-COX     09-15 1131
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFUGEE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dayton congregation helps Vietnamese's family to come America
 &HT;    By Jim DeBrosse
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio -- As he speaks, Diep Hoang Le's eyes narrow with
an intensity that his limited English can't fully express.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can work anything,'' the Vietnamese immigrant and former
political prisoner said. ``If I have enough money to feed my family
_ any job.''
</P>
<P>
   Le, 52, his wife, Hong Thi, and his 18-year-old daughter arrived
in Dayton a week ago with little more than the clothes on their
backs and the two precious items they had kept hidden for years
from the communists _ a tattered paperback edition of the Oxford
Dictionary and a small Vietnamese-English translation book.
</P>
<P>
   For Le, a former South Vietnamese army officer, defying the
communist ban on English texts was worth the risk. The books had
become symbols of the new life he planned someday for his family in
America _ a dream for which he slaved and schemed some 22 years.
Five of those years were spent doing hard labor in a communist
re-education camp.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Le considers himself and his family lucky. Thousands of
other former political prisoners still languish in Vietnam, waiting
for American sponsors to help bring them over and for a grudging
and corrupt Vietnamese government to approve their passage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pay over 1 million Vietnamese money (about $72) for
passport, but still I must wait four years'' before receiving the
document, Le said.
</P>
<P>
   That $72 bribe paid to passport officials took Le years to
accumulate from his meager earnings, first as a bicycle taxi driver
and later as a waiter in a Chinese soup kitchen. The average pay in
Vietnam is $4 a day.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of the College Hill Community Church in Dayton,
Le's dream of reaching this country at last came true. The
congregation has provided his family with sparsely furnished but
tidy two-bedroom apartment. The church will continue to assist the
family with food, clothing and transportation until they can
support themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Ba Nguyen, president of the Vietnamese Veterans Association of
the Dayton Area, said sponsors for refugee families are needed. The
15 members of his local chapter have assisted so many families
they've depleted their funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the time we use money out of our own pockets to do
this work,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Only 20 churches in Ohio are sponsoring refugees for
resettlement in the state, according to the Interfaith Refugee
Services of Ohio, a Columbus-based group that coordinates the
placement of refugees. Last year, it found sponsors in Ohio for 350
people from 14 countries.
</P>
<P>
   Rosie Ward, who heads the refugee committee for College Hill
Community Church, knows why so few churches are involved. ``It
takes a lot of work _ a lot of planning, a lot of networking, a lot
of time _ to really get (the refugees) where they need to go.''
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, refugee families need three months to six months
of assistance before they can find jobs and become self-sufficient.
But money isn't always the biggest problem, Ward said.
</P>
<P>
   Often with only a few days' notice from authorities, sponsors
must find a suitable apartment, a landlord willing to forgo a
credit check and donations of furniture, bedding and clothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I end up doing a lot of begging and harassing of my friends,''
Ward said.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,000 South Vietnamese have settled in the Dayton area
since the end of the war in 1974, but only about 50 of those are
families of former political prisoners such as Le. The latter
didn't start coming to this country in large numbers until 1991,
well after the United States and the Vietnamese government reached
an agreement in 1980 to permit their emigration.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of the pact, the prisoners must have spent a minimum
of three years in a communist re-education camp and have an
American sponsor willing to help them relocate in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Le says the Vietnamese didn't begin living up to the agreement
until after the Soviet Union disintegrated in 1991 and the
Vietnamese government lost its Soviet economic aid and turned to
America for help.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Soviet Union isn't broken down, they would never follow
America,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Most Vietnamese families who come to the Dayton area are
independent within six months, Nguyen said. ``They have a very
strong work ethic.''
</P>
<P>
   Pat Lewis, production manager of the Morning Pride sewing
factory in Dayton, concurs. Her company has hired 70 Vietnamese
refugees since 1985 ``and we have had 99 percent success with
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Many arrive with the sewing skills needed by her company, where
employees are paid by the piece to make protective clothing for
firefighters.
</P>
<P>
   ``They work very fast, so they make good money,'' she said.
``And they are very loyal.''
</P>
<P>
   Nguyen, 49, said he was fortunate to have been a pilot in the
South Vietnam air force. During the final hours before the
communist takeover, he escaped by flying his plane, an A-1
Skyraider, to a U.S. base in Thailand and soon after emigrated to
America. He has worked as a researcher at Wright-Patterson Air
Force Base since 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Besides facing language and cultural barriers, the former
political prisoners _ many now in their 50s and 60s _ have other
challenges as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not old enough to retire but not young enough to find
a job,'' Nguyen said. ``The (U.S.) government has done a lot for
these POWs, bringing them into this country. But they need to do
more, because jobs are very difficult for them to find.''
</P>
<P>
   Le faces that struggle now.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years ago, he was a young businessman with a promising
career as an interpreter for one of the largest American companies
in South Vietnam. Then, in 1968, he joined the South Vietnam army
to fight the communists. He served as a platoon leader and as an
intelligence liaison to the Americans.
</P>
<P>
   But when the GIs pulled out and the communists took control,
Le's life plummeted into slavery and deprivation. For five years,
he was held prisoner in what the communists called ``a training
camp.'' He was assigned hard labor _ clearing trees and building
roads with the crudest of tools from dusk to dawn _ and fed less
than three bowls of rice per day. He never spoke English again.
</P>
<P>
   Families were permitted to visit the prisoners _ and, more
important, bring them supplemental food _ once every three months.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it were not for my family, I must die,'' Le said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, holding his worn Oxford Dictionary almost reverentially in
the palms of both hands, he said he wants to create a new life for
his wife and daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``If after I learn English well, I can do any job _ anything,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
