<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-NEW-ADVISER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ADDS NEW ADVISER TO WHITE HOUSE STAFF 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: CLINTON-POLL, CLINTON-REPUBS, CLINTON-CONGRESS,
CLINTON-ASSESS, CLINTON-DAY) 
(th) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   More than 25 years ago at Yale Law School, Gregory Craig was
struck by a rare burst of pessimism from a fellow student, Bill
Clinton, who argued in a seminar one day that corporate America had
too much power and money to ever be tamed, even by the democratic
institutions that the young man from Arkansas believed in and
wanted to help lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you had dreams, that was a terrible time,'' Craig recalled
of that era of Vietnam-induced despair in David Maraniss' biography
of Clinton, ``First in His Class.'' ``If it was a tough time for
him, an angry, hostile period of his life, it was consistent with
what a lot of us felt.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Craig has worked as a public defender, a Senate
staff member, helped win an insanity defense for John W. Hinckley
Jr. in his assassination attempt on President Ronald Reagan,
advised Sen. Edward M. Kennedy in the investigation growing out of
the William Kennedy Smith rape trial and served as a senior aide to
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
   Now, at another tough and angry time in Bill Clinton's life, the
president has tapped his old friend to join the White House staff
as quarterback of its efforts to deal with _ and, he hopes, avert _
an impeachment inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   White House aides say it will be Craig's task to cut through the
legalisms about sex and lies that have beleaguered the president's
lawyers and argue Clinton's case with the constituency that counts
now: Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very low key, very steady, very cool, very smart,'' said
Bill Carrick, a Democratic political consultant in Los Angeles who
worked with Craig in the mid-1980s when Craig was Kennedy's foreign
policy expert. ``He has a good mix of political judgment and savvy
and legal ability. He's going to know what will pass the smell test
on the Hill and what won't.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig, 53, who since last year has been director of the Policy
and Planning Staff at the State Department, comes to the job with
an established pedigree as a Friend of Bill.
</P>
<P>
   At Yale, he surrendered his $75-a-month apartment in New Haven,
Conn., to Clinton and his girlfriend, Hillary Rodham, who were a
class behind him, and he remains especially close to Mrs. Clinton,
friends say. Since Yale days, he has also been a friend of the
president's private lawyer, David Kendall, whose recent approach to
Clinton's troubles has rankled White House political advisers as
overly narrow and legalistic.
</P>
<P>
   In accepting the new job, Craig was said to have wanted a clear
definition of his role, and clear responsibility for dealing with
Congress, not just the largely public relations duties of the White
House's former point man on scandals, Lanny Davis, but a negotiator
who could cut a deal. Associates said they expected him to play
just such a clear role.
</P>
<P>
   Like Kendall, Craig cut his teeth at the Washington law firm of
Williams &AMP; Connolly, where he was a particular protege of the
powerhouse name partner, Edward Bennett Williams. With Vincent
Fuller, he helped win a verdict of not guilty by reason of insanity
for Hinckley in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   Craig will take up duties in a White House where the press
secretary, Mike McCurry, has recently been forced to publicly deny
queries on whether the president has been receiving psychiatric
care.
</P>
<P>
   Craig did not return telephone messages seeking comment for this
article. But in a discussion of the Hinckley defense on ``Rivera
Live,'' on CNBC in 1996, Craig noted that the insanity plea has a
``very, very good pedigree,'' and ``represents the belief, I think,
that society will not hold someone responsible for his acts or her
acts if he doesn't have the capacity to make a decision,'' or
``cannot distinguish between right and wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Gregory Bestor Craig was born in Norfolk, Va., and graduated
magna cum laude from Harvard University, where he was a leader in
student antiwar movements and made a Class Day speech that drew
national attention. He also holds a degree from Cambridge
University in England.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his career, Craig kept up an interest in politics,
and has said he could not think of a political event that excited
him more than Clinton's first inaugural as governor of Arkansas. On
Kennedy's staff, Craig coordinated policy on Latin America and
South Africa, and organized the senator's trip to South Africa at
the height of world concern over apartheid.
</P>
<P>
   Craig is no stranger to controversy. Besides defending Hinckley
and advising his old boss, Kennedy, in the aftermath of a bout of
partying in Palm Beach, Fla., that led to his nephew's encounter
with Patricia Bowman _ and ultimate acquittal on rape charges _
Craig represented the Mevs family of Haiti in their efforts to
persuade the Bush and Clinton administrations to protect their
business interests in the face of political turmoil on the island
in the wake of the overthrow of Jean-Bertrand Aristide.
</P>
<P>
   He also represented the government of Panama that succeeded Gen.
Manuel Antonio Noriega in a federal civil racketeering suit
contending that the ousted leader betrayed his country through
fraud, murder and theft.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is an excellent strategist, a skilled politician and a man
who understands the various crosshairs of Washington,'' said his
longtime partner Robert Barnett, who himself has been the
president's private lawyer in the past. ``He understands how to
deal with the press, Congress and legal issues.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
