</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DYING-GAUL-THEATER-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HOLLYWOOD SATIRE THAT REFUSES TO STAY DOWN  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 20) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By STEVEN DRUKMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The return of ``The Dying Gaul'' to the Vineyard
Theater, where it closed in June, conjures up titles befitting a
parody of a bad movie sequel _ ``The Gaul That Would Not Die,''
perhaps, or ``The Dying Gaul: Resurrection.'' And on one level,
that's fine with the author, Craig Lucas.
</P>
<P>
   ```The Dying Gaul'  &UR; is &LR;  a Hollywood satire,'' said Lucas, who
knows that world well as the adapter of several of his own plays to
film _ ``Prelude to a Kiss'' and ``Reckless'' _ and the author of
the screenplay for ``Longtime Companion.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' he added, ``Hollywood is not the real subject matter
here. My play uses that world of high-rolling big money _ that
crazy-making business _ to examine a whole range of subjects.''
These include Buddhism, psychoanalysis and, in particular, the
Internet. Much of the action occurs while actors type on invisible
keyboards and communicate as if in a computer chat room.
</P>
<P>
   The title refers to the ancient sculpture of a slain soldier
that the author Craig Lucas saw in a Rome museum. In the play,
``The Dying Gaul'' is also the title of a film script that Robert
(played by Tim Hopper) has written about the death of his lover,
who had AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Robert sells the script for a million dollars to a jaded
producer, Jeffrey (Cotter Smith), who wants to change it radically.
With his integrity unraveling as fast as his script's original
intent, Robert soon becomes the third point of a nasty love
triangle between the bisexual Jeffrey and his wife, Elaine (Linda
Emond). What begins, then, as parody ends as a disturbing tale
that, the author said, ``is so full of rage it is difficult for
some audiences to take.''
</P>
<P>
   For those involved in the production, the play's first
performance, on May 8, was itself difficult to take. Earlier in the
day Smith suffered a herniated disc.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were literally calling critics at 4 o'clock, saying: `Uh,
there's a problem. Don't come to the theater tonight,' '' said
Douglas Aibel, the artistic director of the Vineyard. Smith was
quickly replaced by Tony Goldwyn, rehearsals were extended and the
play opened on May 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the lost time at the beginning, and because this is
the most important play Craig has ever written, I was determined to
bring it back,'' said Aibel, who views the play as ``new terrain
for Craig.'' ``Luckily, Cotter recuperated over the summer, and the
cast and director, Mark Brokaw, were determined to return.'' The
play, which reopened on Friday, is scheduled to run through Oct.
25.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dying Gaul'' received reviews as mixed in tenor as the
play itself. The Wall Street Journal called it ``the best American
play of the year.'' The New Yorker complained, ``You can't figure
out what it is.'' The New York Times was split: Peter Marks called
the play ``a minor tantrum''; Vincent Canby found it
``fascinating'' and the production ``flawless.''
</P>
<P>
   For Aibel, ``The Dying Gaul'' functions on many levels. ``It's a
thriller, a morality play,'' he said. ``It's a crackling yarn, but
it's challenging, too. Audiences aren't used to the Internet as
both a setting for the play's action and as a dramatic tool. I
think we'll see more of this.''
</P>
<P>
   Audiences may indeed see more of it. In Patrick Marber's new
British play ``Closer,'' which is expected to come to New York
later this season, two characters communicate using keyboards,
typing words that the audience sees on a large rear screen.
</P>
<P>
   To Aibel, the computer as dramatic device is simply a matter of
theater keeping up with the times. ``What was, in past plays, a
knock on the door or a cocktail party is now an e-mail or a chat
room,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
