<HEADER>
A6966 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-COWBOYS-NYT &LR;      09-15 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARRETT TO START IN PLACE OF AIKMAN  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By TIMOTHY W. SMITH    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Troy Aikman went down with a fractured left clavicle
against Denver on Sunday, it looked as if the Dallas Cowboys'
playoff hopes went with him. Aikman's scramble for extra yards
knocked him out for at least four weeks and possibly as many as
eight weeks.
</P>
<P>
   With Aikman out, the Cowboys have entrusted their new offense to
Jason Garrett, who has been a backup in Dallas for all of his six
National Football League seasons. And though Garrett lacks Aikman's
arm strength and experience, his teammates are rallying around him
as the team prepares to face the Giants at the Meadowlands on
Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like he's new to the players,'' Emmitt Smith, the
Dallas running back, said of Garrett. ``He's just new to the
system. But Jason is an intelligent individual. Everybody feels
confident that he can get the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Jones, the Cowboys' owner, said he would not try to bring
in an experienced quarterback to replace Aikman. Jones said he
would go with Garrett as the starter and Mike Quinn as the backup
until Aikman returned.
</P>
<P>
   Garrett, who still looks like the undergraduate history major he
was at Princeton, has a tough assignment. The Giants and the
Cowboys are heated rivals in the National Football Conference East.
The game will be broadcast for a national audience. Both teams are
1-1, after losses and want to avert early-season slides that could
hurt their playoff chances.
</P>
<P>
   Stepping in for Aikman is not completely new to Garrett, who is
2-0 as a starter. When Aikman injured his left hamstring against
the Giants in November 1993, Garrett came in and guided two scoring
drives, completing 4 of 5 passes for 34 yards in the Cowboys' 31-9
victory. The next week he got his first start against Arizona and
helped lead the Cowboys to a 20-15 victory. When Aikman and his
backup, Rodney Peete, were injured in a game against the Redskins
in 1994, Garrett finished up in the Cowboys' 31-7 victory. The next
week he started against Green Bay on Thanksgiving Day and led one
of the greatest comebacks in Cowboys history. Garrett guided the
Cowboys to six straight second-half scoring drives, including five
consecutive touchdowns, in a 42-31 victory over Green Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you're a backup quarterback, you have to put yourself
in the position mentally that you have to come in at any moment
during the game,'' Garrett said. ``That's the mind-set that I have
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Garrett is not awed by stepping into the starter's role. He was
raised in a football environment. His father, Jim, who is now a
scout with the Cowboys, had coaching stops in New Jersey, Florida,
Pennsylvania, Dallas, Houston, Cleveland and New Orleans while
Garrett was growing up; Garrett transferred from Princeton to
Columbia in his sophomore year when his father was briefly the
Lions' coach, then transferred back. Two of Garrett's brothers are
assistant coaches in the NFL, Judd in New Orleans and John in
Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in his tenure with the Cowboys, Garrett
entered training camp this season as the No. 2 quarterback. Not
having to worry about competing for a job allowed Garrett to
concentrate on learning the offensive system installed by Coach
Chan Gailey. But because Aikman was also learning a new system,
Garrett's practice snaps with the first team were limited. In
preparation for the Giants this week, he will get the majority of
them. Aikman said he will try to help Garrett as much as possible,
but neither of them is completely comfortable with the offense yet.
</P>
<P>
   Garrett believes his ability to run the offense against Denver
in the second half last Sunday will give his teammates confidence
that he can handle the starting role. Garrett did move the offense
down the field against the Broncos, but the Cowboys were not able
to score any touchdowns. Garrett led them to three field goals.
Smith said he and the other veteran players from past Super Bowl
teams, like receiver Michael Irvin, guard Nate Newton and tackle
Erik Williams, will have to pick up the slack in Aikman's absence.
``If I have learned anything from my career in Dallas, it is that
these guys will go on,'' Aikman said. ``Jason will do fine. And I'm
not out for the season. I'll be back after a few games.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
