<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEAMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEAMS IN THE NEWS: SYRACUSE, FLORIDA, PENN STATE, RUTGERS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By RON DICKER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYRACUSE, N.Y. _ Eight-man fronts intended to contain
quarterback Donovan McNabb were also stopping fullback Rob Konrad,
so Syracuse expanded Konrad's role as a receiver this season. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The results have been promising. Konrad caught two touchdown
passes in the Orangemen's 38-28 victory over Michigan last week,
and he has 10 receptions for 122 yards in 2 games. He is drawing
comparisons to the former Syracuse fullback Daryl Johnston of the
Dallas Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something that's rather natural to me,'' Konrad said
Tuesday. ``I was a tailback in high school and I'm used to handling
the ball.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Konrad's other duty is to plow defenders out of the way for the
running backs and to pick up blitzing linebackers who are aiming
for McNabb, a contender for the Heisman Trophy. Pass blocking is
easier because McNabb can elude defenders who make it into the
backfield, Konrad said.
</P>
<P>
   After a brutal two weeks, the No. 13 Orangemen (1-1) get an
apparent Big East breather this weekend against Rutgers (1-1).
Konrad, perhaps in an effort to avoid an appearance on Rutgers'
bulletin board, said: ``What people don't understand about
Rutgers-Syracuse is that there's a rivalry there. The fact is,
Rutgers always plays Syracuse tough. At the same time, they're not
going to be a Tennessee or Michigan.''
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA _ Tamaurice (Tee) Martin has succeeded Peyton Manning at
quarterback for Tennessee, but Tim Beauchamp's mission remains the
same.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to rush hard, every play,'' Beauchamp, a Gators
defensive end, said Tuesday in preparation for No. 2 Florida's
Southeastern Conference clash at No. 6 Tennessee (1-0) on Saturday.
The loser can probably say goodbye to its national championship
hopes.
</P>
<P>
   Martin ran for 80 yards in a 34-33 victory over Syracuse two
weeks ago. Beauchamp said he would still charge at the quarterback,
and react if Martin moved out of the pocket.
</P>
<P>
   The Gators (2-0) have won five straight games in the series, and
Beauchamp was a key contributor in the last two. Last year, he
forced a fumble and sacked Manning in the Gators' 33-20 victory in
Gainesville, Fla. However, the Volunteers went on to win the
Eastern Division of the SEC and beat Auburn in the conference
championship. Beauchamp said a victory in Saturday's game is
imperative because the Gators believe they must win all 13 games to
capture the national championship.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday could be the most difficult step. Florida, which has
beaten up on the Citadel and Northeast Louisiana, faces a quick
team before more than 100,000 fans in unfriendly territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of young guys who have not played in an
environment like that,'' Beauchamp said. ``We'll try to get them
out of the game early, but if that's not happening, we'll have to
be mentally tough.''
</P>
<P>
   PENN STATE _ Running back Cordell Mitchell is not playing
favorites when it comes to the Nittany Lions' platooning
quarterbacks, Kevin Thompson and Rashard Casey. ``Honestly, I
really don't care,'' he said Tuesday. ``We don't get the ball
thrown to us that often. A handoff is a handoff.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell is making the most of his handoffs after two years of
being Curtis Enis' backup. He has rushed 22 times for 203 yards and
a touchdown. That one of those runs was for 77 yards should come as
no surprise. The 6-foot, 199-pound Mitchell was a track standout at
Corcoran High School in Syracuse, and it was his speed that kept
the interest of Coach Joe Paterno through a difficult recruiting
battle against Syracuse Coach Paul Pasqualoni.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's slowly getting better and better,'' Paterno said of
Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell admitted that before the season he was not fully
confident that he could fill the role of primary ball carrier. He
said he learned a strong work ethic from Enis, now a Chicago Bear,
but he does not imitate Enis' punishing style. Mitchell thinks more
about following his blockers to the opening and exploding for a big
gain.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't look for the home run every play,'' he said. ``If it
comes my way, I'll try to take it all the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell's maturation comes at a crucial time for the No. 8
Nittany Lions (2-0). After Saturday's game at Pittsburgh (1-0) and
an open week, Penn State travels to No. 1 Ohio State for its first
Big Ten game.
</P>
<P>
   As for his two quarterbacks, Paterno said: ``They've been
careful with the football and I think they've been efficient. Where
I think we need to do a better job is quicker reads. We've had five
sacks in two games; part of that is the quarterbacks' fault.''
</P>
<P>
   As in the first two games, Thompson (18 of 28 for 273 yards and
a touchdown) will get the starting assignment over Casey (7 of 10
for 67 yards).
</P>
<P>
   RUTGERS _ Michael Barr, a freshman punter, expected to spend his
first year learning from the starter, Charlie Titus. In fact, Barr
was not with the team for Rutgers' loss at Boston College last
weekend, when Titus broke his jaw after being blocked in the face
on a punt return. Now Barr will get on-the-job training as the
starting punter against No. 13 Syracuse this Saturday at the
Carrier Dome. What a way to break in.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
