<HEADER>
A6969 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRUITTE-DANCE-$ADV20-     09-15 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRUITTE-DANCE-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMEMBERING A MENTOR WHO SOUGHT PERFECTION  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 20) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ohio)   (af)  
 By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There was no one quite like James Truitte. Lean and
craggy faced, intense yet calm, Truitte brought a quietly dramatic,
powerful presence and maturity to bear on Alvin Ailey's earliest
dances.
</P>
<P>
   He had come to Ailey after dancing with Joseph Rickard's
Hollywood Negro Ballet and with Lester Horton, the West Coast
modern-dance pioneer, in the late 1940s and early 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   After retirement from the stage, Truitte became an active and
passionate disseminator of the little-known Horton technique and
repertory in dance companies and schools across the nation. An
old-school gentleman, Truitte looked back with remarkable
detachment _ and wry wit _ on a creative life circumscribed by
racial bigotry.
</P>
<P>
   Cultural history is filled, of course, with gifted individuals
whose stories and contributions have become lost in time. But Kevin
Ward, the resident choreographer of the Dayton Contemporary Dance
Company, has not forgotten Truitte, an early and beloved mentor,
who died in 1995 at age 72.
</P>
<P>
   Ward's new ``Offering,'' an homage to Truitte, will be performed
by the Dayton troupe starting Tuesday at the Joyce Theater, in a
one-week season that also includes revivals of dances by Asadata
Dafora and Talley Beatty and works by Donald Byrd and Sharon Leahy.
</P>
<P>
   Truitte's life and career will also be touched on in ``For
Jimmy,'' a photographic exhibition at the New School through Sept.
28, and in a panel discussion on Sept. 26, also at the New School.
</P>
<P>
   Ward first came into contact with Truitte in the early 1970s as
a dance and music student at the University of Cincinnati College
Conservatory of Music, where Truitte was teaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just scared to death of this man,'' Ward said in a
recent interview. ``He was going on and on about this Horton
technique. What was he going to do next? He was imposing. This
tall, regal man with this mane of hair like a lion.'' Nonetheless,
he was drawn to Truitte's teaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't exactly strict. You could (italics)live(end italics)
in his classes. But he was very particular about the technique that
he was teaching. You didn't do it wrong in his class; he made sure
you didn't do it wrong. You went back and back and you kept doing
it until you got it right. He was very methodical. I hadn't run
into a teacher so thorough and committed, at that point.'' Truitte
quickly became a friend.
</P>
<P>
   Another attraction was the living dance history that Truitte
offered through his stories and comments in class and rehearsal.
Ward was an apprentice with the Cincinnati Ballet at a time when
Truitte was reviving Horton dances for the company. ``Truitte would
go on and on about what Lester Horton was doing over on the West
Coast, to give the dancers a better idea of the technique and what
was involved in performing the pieces,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As he got older he told more and more stories. I hooked up
again with Truitte in Dayton, at DCDC. He had been with the company
for a number of years as an artistic adviser and mentor. DCDC was
reviving a lot of classic African-American choreography and he had
been on the scene with a lot of those events. He'd danced a lot of
those works. He was able to tell us not only the technique but the
nuances, the wherefore and whys of what was being done.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he also gave us all this backstage gossip. He talked about
his own problems with performances and with working with Alvin.
Lots of great stuff about being on the road, and dancing with all
these people. It was all useful. And he talked about the black
vaudeville acts, the black ballet companies of the 30s, the black
shows of the '40s.''
</P>
<P>
   Truitte's death was sudden and unexpected. ``I wanted to give
him something posthumously,'' Ward said of ``Offering.'' ``I guess
that happens a lot when you lose people you have grown to love,
when you didn't get a chance to say goodbye. I didn't get a chance
to say how much he meant to my life. All the encouragement, the
information, the affection that he was.''
</P>
<P>
   Ward, who is also a composer, set ``Offering'' to music from
Glazounov's ``Seasons'' and Delius' ``Songs of Farewell.'' ``I
wanted to say something about the seasons of a dancer's life. I
always liked the Delius. And it's a send-off. To say I hope you
have the best trip you can have in eternity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-98 2150EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
