<HEADER>
A6970 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGO-KOSOVO-1STLD-WRI     09-15 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGO-KOSOVO-1STLD-WRITETHRU-485&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. APPEARS TO BE UNDECIDED ON KOSOVO CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (changes Milosevic's title from Serbian president to Yugoslav
president, in 7th graf)  (bl) 
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As evidence mounts of a human catastrophe in
Kosovo, the United States is still far from a decision over whether
to use military force to put an end to the Serbian assault that has
forced hundreds of thousands of people to flee their homes, senior
Clinton administration officials say.
</P>
<P>
   The growing crisis in Kosovo is likely to pose an early test of
President Clinton's resolve and his ability to take decisive action
in foreign policy in the wake of the scandal surrounding his
personal conduct.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation is awful and getting worse,'' said a senior
administration official, speaking on condition of anonymity. ``If
we don't want thousands of people to starve to death this winter,
the White House will need to make a decision very quickly on
whether to use firepower.''
</P>
<P>
   Charity groups say the situation in Kosovo grows more desperate
virtually by the hour, with nearly continuous Serbian shelling of
villages populated by ethnic Albanians, who make up about 90
percent of the population of the southern Serbian province. More
than 900 people have been reported killed in the fighting this
year, most of them ethnic Albanian guerrillas and civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Former Sen. Bob Dole, the 1996 Republican presidential nominee,
described a ``human catastrophe in the making'' after visiting
Kosovo earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw them up close and in person: women and children, the
elderly living in fear without adequate food and shelter,'' he
said. ``These hungry masses will within weeks face winter and the
freezing conditions that come with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Clinton administration officials say they are pressing the
White House to make a direct threat to Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic that the United States will use military force against
Serbian targets _ most likely, by air strikes with U.S. cruise
missiles _ if the onslaught is not halted. They said that NATO
contingency planning for the attacks was all but completed.
</P>
<P>
   Similar strikes in 1995 were credited with helping end three
years of war in neighboring Bosnia and bringing the warring parties
to the peace table.
</P>
<P>
   But other aides to the president are more cautious, fearing that
military force by the United States and its reluctant NATO partners
might only embolden Serb forces into a more violent campaign in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting Tuesday with reporters in Washington, Gen. John
Jumper, the commander of U.S. air forces in Europe, said the
situation in Kosovo was in some ways more complex than the
situation three years ago in Bosnia, and that air strikes is Kosovo
might not have the same effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``The air campaign can be done,'' he said. ``The air campaign is
just like before. It is one that is easy to put together, and it's
not difficult to execute.'' But he added: ``The solutions that we
saw work before are not necessarily the solutions that the
leadership thinks will work in this case.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Administration officials say they are also fearful that air
strikes might encourage the Kosovo Liberation Army, the rebels who
are seeking independence of Kosovo from Serbia, a goal not shared
by the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to be the Kosovars' air force,'' said a senior
U.S. official. ``It's not the same dynamic as in Bosnia, because we
don't recognize Kosovo's independence. We recognize the Kosovo
region as an important part of Serbia.''
</P>
<P>
   While the United States contemplates military action against
Serbia, it continues to press for a diplomatic solution.
</P>
<P>
   The effort is being overseen by Christopher Hill, the U.S.
ambassador to Macedonia, who has been shuttling between Belgrade
and Kosovo in hopes of brokering a cease-fire, so far without
success.
</P>
<P>
   Hill has been forced to tangle not only with Serbian and Kosovo
leaders, but also with European leaders angered by recent public
comments in which he criticized Europe for doing too little to end
the fighting. German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel has described
Hill's comments as ``cynical and condescending.''
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials involved in policy-making in the
Balkans say they are working against a de facto deadline of
mid-October in deciding what to do next in Kosovo, since that is
when winter begins to set in.
</P>
<P>
   If the Serbs continue their offensive and refugees are kept from
their homes, tens of thousands of them will be at risk of freezing
to death in the forests where they have hidden, the Americans say.
</P>
<P>
   A more immediate concern for the United States are reports that
Serbian forces have begun rounding up men and boys from ethnic
Albanian villages and refugee camps in Kosovo, an act that U.S.
officials fear could be the prelude to their execution, as happened
during the war in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   ``American and European leaders have pledged not to allow the
crimes against humanity which we witnessed in Bosnia to occur in
Kosovo,'' Dole said after his visit this month. ``But from what I
have seen, such crimes are already happening.''
</P>
<P>
   John Shattuck, the assistant secretary of state for human
rights, who accompanied Dole in Kosovo, said the U.S. delegation
had found evidence of ``horrendous human rights violations,
violations of humanitarian law and acts of punitive destruction on
a massive scale.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
