<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-PRIMARY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELLUCCI, HARSHBARGER SET TO SQUARE OFF FOR GOVERNOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK PHILLIPS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Setting up a race that will decide whether the
Republicans will extend their eight-year hold on the governor's
office, Acting Governor Paul Cellucci Tuesday handily won the GOP
gubernatorial nomination and Attorney General Scott Harshbarger
glided to a strong victory over his two Democratic rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Early returns and surveys taken of voters exiting polls showed
Cellucci leading state Treasurer Joseph D. Malone by about 60 to 40
percent, thwarting his challenge from the right and ending the most
bitter Republican gubernatorial battle in recent state history.
</P>
<P>
   The initial results in one of the nation's most closely watched
congressional campaigns _ the Democratic race to replace US
Representative Joseph P. Kennedy II _ in the crowded 10-person
race, showed Somerville Mayor Michael Capuano building a commanding
lead. The Democratic nominee is heavily favored to win the seat.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the hard-fought Democratic race for attorney general
was going down to the wire with initial returns and exit polls
showing state Senator Lois Pines of Newton holding an early lead
over Middlesex District Attorney Thomas F. Reilly of Watertown. But
Reilly was rallying as the ballots were being counted late Tuesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Despite and acrimonious fight in the GOP governor's race,
Malone, after conceding defeat, closed ranks behind Cellucci
Tuesday night. Aides said he intended to appear at Cellucci's
victory party and pledge his support in the general election.
</P>
<P>
   On the Democratic side, the same returns and surveys showed
Harshbarger cruising to an easy victory, winning just over a
majority of the primary vote in a three way race and giving him a
strong send-off in his battle to regain the governor's office for
the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Harshbarger's closest rival was former stater Senator Patricia
McGovern of Andover who was expected to get just over 30 percent of
the vote, while US Representative Brian J. Donnelly of Dennis,
lagged behind with about 15 percent. Both pledged their support to
Harshbarger and vowed work for his election.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want a Democrat, with Democratic values to run
Massachusetts,'' McGovern told supporters gathered at a Boston
hotel as she vowed to campaign for the attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   State Senator Warren Tolman of Watertown was also holding a lead
in his contest for the Democratic nomination for lieutenant
governor with Governors Councilor Dorothy A. Kelly Gay of
Somerville.
</P>
<P>
   On the Republican side, Cellucci's choice for lieutenant
governor, Jane Swift, a former state senator from North Adams,
appeared to be beating out Malone's choice for a running mate,
former radio talk show host Janet E. Jeghelian of Westwood.
</P>
<P>
   The primary results will set up a clear choice for Massachusetts
voters in November: whether to keep the Republican team that can
claim credit for the state's economic renaissance in the 1990s, or
return the Democrats, with promises of a more activist government,
to power.
</P>
<P>
   Both Cellucci and Harshbarger, who are known as moderates in
their own parties, will battle for the middle ground as they court
a large population of voters for the Nov. 3 election.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't look like a compelling contrast between the two,''
said Todd Domke, a Republican political analyst. ``This is not like
John Silber versus Bill Weld in 1990.''
</P>
<P>
   The major differences will be over the death penalty and taxes.
Cellucci strongly supports the death penalty and has built a career
on antitax positions. He has already accused the attorney general
of supporting tax hikes.
</P>
<P>
   But Domke said what really is at stake is who will control the
governor's office and whether the Democrats will regain their
domination of Massachusetts politics.
</P>
<P>
   If Cellucci loses to Harshbarger, it's not likely the party will
win other statewide offices or the two congressional seats it is
seriously contesting, Domke said. ``That would mean, the state
would be a one-party oligarchy once again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If he wins, Cellucci would be able to drop the ``acting'' from
his title, and claim a huge victory all his own.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since William F. Weld handed over the office to him by
resigning 14 months ago, Cellucci, who first went to Beacon Hill as
a legislator in 1977, has had to carry out his duties as acting
governor under the pressure of Malone's challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Early on, Malone, who declared his candidacy in early July 1997,
made it clear he would attack Cellucci from the right, particularly
on fiscal issues. His most persistent theme was that the acting
governor failed to keep state spending increases at the rate of
inflation, a level the treasurer advocated.
</P>
<P>
   Although he held almost of the same liberal positions as
Cellucci on such social issues as abortion, gun control,
affirmative action, and raising the minimum wage, Malone laid claim
to being the only true conservative and repeatedly referred to
Cellucci as a ``liberal.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone also accused Cellucci of being a Beacon Hill insider,
saying he was too close to the Democrats who run the Legislature
and had hired too many Democrats to run his administration.
</P>
<P>
   The first indication that Malone's theme was not resonating with
Republican activists came at last April's GOP state convention in
Worcester, where Cellucci trounced the state treasurer by an almost
three-to-one ratio to win the party's endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   A pre-primary Boston Globe/WBZ-TV poll of likely GOP voters
showed Malone was unable to make the liberal label stick to
Cellucci, who has strong ties to the Republican Party grassroots
networks.
</P>
<P>
   Domke said Malone failed to make a compelling case for
Republicans to reject Cellucci, who he said proved to GOP voters
that he is competent and capable as governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Malone's campaign also failed to adequately convey his own
accomplishments and likability and his ads calling Cellucci a
liberal seemed like name-calling _ harsh, unfair and
unconvincing,'' Domke said.
</P>
<P>
   On the Democratic side, Harshbarger emerged as the likely
front-runner after US Representative Joseph P. Kennedy II, bruised
by family scandals and his first wife's accusation he verbally
bullied her for an annulment, unexpectedly withdrew from the
governor's race in August 1997.
</P>
<P>
   McGovern, who was campaigning for state treasurer, decided
several weeks later to challenge Harshbarger, hoping Democrats
alienated by the attorney general's style and his refusal to step
aside for Kennedy, would rally to her candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   But Harshbarger proved too resilient, never making a major
misstep she could exploit and continuing to build a campaign
organization and to far outmatch her in fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, there were few differences between Harshbarger,
McGovern and Donnelly to spark much voter interest in the race,
something McGovern badly needed if she hoped to gain traction for
her candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Donnelly, who entered the race in January, put himself at a
serious disadvantage by his late start, one from which he never
recovered. He had not been politically active in Massachusetts
since the early 1990's and that was only in his South Shore-based
congressional district.
</P>
<P>
   The former congressman, who had $712,000 in his federal campaign
account at the beginning of the year, was only able transfer a
portion of those funds to his state campaign. He was unable to
raise any serious amounts of campaign cash.
</P>
<P>
   Most observers agreed Donnelly's candidacy all but ended in July
when he decided against a scheme by which he would personally take
possession of the $300,000 or more balance and donate it to his
state account. As veteran congressman, Donnelly is able to use his
campaign funds for personal use after paying income tax.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-98 2158EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
