<DOCNO> NYT19980915.0443 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6987 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-DELAHOYA-NYT &LR;      09-15 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-DELAHOYA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DE LA HOYA TAKES A RISK, TAKING TOUGHER FIGHTS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By TIMOTHY W. SMITH    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Oscar De La Hoya, promoted as the Golden Boy, has
felt for several years as if he has had to carry the tattered sport
of boxing on his shoulders. Now, at the age of 25, another
realization has struck him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not just a fighter,'' De La Hoya said Tuesday. ``I'm an
enterprise. I support a lot of people.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``It's overwhelming. But I can handle it.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year De La Hoya, the World Boxing Council welterweight
champion, earned $38 million from five fights and his endorsements,
making him the second-highest-paid athlete in the United States,
behind Michael Jordan. For his rematch against Julio Cesar Chavez
(101-2-2) at the Thomas and Mack Center here on Friday night, De La
Hoya (28-0) will earn $12 million, plus a percentage of the
pay-per-view sales that could bring him up to $3 million more.
</P>
<P>
   The promoter Bob Arum said the 18,000-seat arena is sold out,
and the pay television audience could approach the 850,000 viewers
for the De La Hoya-Pernell Whitaker welterweight championship bout
in April 1997. The pay-per-view gross for that bout was $36
million, making it the biggest non-heavyweight boxing show in
pay-per-view history.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's why they call De La Hoya the Golden Boy.
</P>
<P>
   However, De La Hoya's image began to tarnish over the last year
when he was criticized, mainly by the news media, for not fighting
tougher opponents in the welterweight division. And recently his
luster was dulled somewhat when an article in The Los Angeles Times
portrayed him as a hard-drinking skirt chaser who dropped loads of
money at casino gaming tables between bouts.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya has met his boxing critics head on by ordering Arum
to make a fight with Ike Quartey, who was recently stripped of his
World Boxing Association welterweight championship for not
defending it in a timely fashion. That fight is scheduled to take
place Nov. 21. It will be De La Hoya's toughest bout since he
defeated Whitaker for the WBC title in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   It will be a step up from his recent opponents. De La Hoya's
defense against Patrick Charpentier on June 13 was an
embarrassment. Charpentier, the WBC's No. 1 contender and thus a
mandatory opponent for De La Hoya, was outclassed, landing just 5
of 111 punches and hitting the canvas three times before the fight
was stopped in the third round. And De La Hoya's rematch with
Chavez, who cuts easily and at age 36 is definitely on the downside
of his once great career, is a big mismatch. De La Hoya has been
made an 8-to-1 favorite.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya said no one in his camp, including his father, Joel,
and Arum, wanted him to fight Chavez again. The last fight, in June
1996, was stopped in the fourth round after De La Hoya cut Chavez
over the left eye. De La Hoya didn't feel that Chavez, who said the
outcome would have been different were it not for the cut, had
given him the proper respect. ``It's personal,'' he said. ``If it
was up to me, I wouldn't even put it in the record books. It's him
and me in the ring, and I'm fighting to get the respect.''
</P>
<P>
   After the fight, for which Chavez will earn $6 million, it will
be all business. De La Hoya said he realized that in order to be
considered a great champion he had to fight, and beat, the best
fighters. It took a while to convince those around him that he was
ready to step up to a higher class of opponents, he said.
Apparently, only the Golden Boy was willing to risk the golden
goose.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is the one who has been pushing it,'' said Mike Hernandez,
a Los Angeles auto dealer who is De La Hoya's longtime adviser.
``Yes, he's ready to take that step. He's more experienced now. He
showed us a lot in his fight against Wilfredo Rivera. He showed a
lot of self-control.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, there are times outside the ring when that
self-control is not as evident. The article in The Los Angeles
Times detailed an incident in Cabo San Lucas, Mexico, this past
spring when a drunken De La Hoya behaved badly at a bar with
several American college students who were there on spring break.
The article also reported on De La Hoya's admitted problem with
gambling.
</P>
<P>
   The article angered Hernandez and De La Hoya's father, who
called it nonsense. Initially De La Hoya said he was angry as well.
But he could not deny the accuracy of the article and the accounts
of his behavior. After his anger subsided, De La Hoya said he had
thought about it and taken a different view.
</P>
<P>
   ``This article woke me up and made me realize that I'm human,''
he said. ``I'm 25 years old and I have a lot of money. Anybody else
in my situation would just blow up. It was not learning a lesson.
It was a reality check: `Hey, I'm doing something wrong. Stop.'''
</P>
<P>
   Arum said that he had established a limit of $25,000 a night on
the amount De La Hoya could gamble.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, De La Hoya has begun to change from a cardboard
cutout to a more three-dimensional character. Still, he is guarded
about his image.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job is to fight, stay focused and be a role model,'' De La
Hoya said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-98 2200EDT &QL; 
