<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6988 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELECT-STATES-BOS &LR;      09-15 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELECT-STATES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHUMER GAINS EASY WIN OVER FERRARO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Former vice-presidential candidate Geraldine Ferraro
seemed headed toward a landslide defeat in her attempt at a
political comeback, with early returns Tuesday night showing her
badly trailing Representative Charles Schumer in the Democratic
primary for a Senate seat.
</P>
<P>
   News services declared Schumer the winner just seconds after the
polls closed at 9 p.m. Exit polls during the day showed Schumer
leading by a 3-1 margin in New York City, where three-quarters of
state Democratic primary ballots are usually cast.
</P>
<P>
   Reports also signaled Betsy McCaughey Ross _ the Republican
lieutenant-governor turned Democratic rebel _ would lose her race
to be the party's nominee for governor. New York City Councilman
Peter Vallone seemed to be the victor.
</P>
<P>
   If the early returns are borne out, the race could mark the end
of Ferraro's electoral career. She lost the same race six years
ago, placing second in a bitter four-way race that hinged on shady
allegations of her husband's business connections. Those
accusations were not re-aired this time around. In fact, the race
was most noted for its tameness.
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro was seen as a sure winner when she entered the Senate
race a year ago. Over the months, though, her name recognition was
nullified by what many observers deemed a lackluster campaign. She
never offered a rationale for her candidacy, except that she had
the best chance of beating the Republican incumbent, Senator
Alfonse D'Amato. It wasn't enough to rally supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer also raised far more money, aired more TV commercials,
had the backing of party and labor organizations that could get
voters to the polls, and campaigned with zest. He also ran on a
strong record of 18 years as a congressman from Brooklyn and
sponsor of numerous popular laws, most notably the Brady Bill on
gun control and a bill to put 100,000 policemen on the streets.
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro ran mainly on her history as the first woman to be
nominated vice president, which happened 14 years ago and on a
ticket _ Walter Mondale's against Ronald Reagan's reelection _ that
was one of the century's great losers.
</P>
<P>
   McCaughey Ross may also beat a hasty retreat from the political
arena. A former think-tank scholar, she was tapped as George
Pataki's running mate in the governor's race four years ago _ then
grew disillusioned when Pataki, after winning, ignored her advice
on policy.
</P>
<P>
   After switching parties, she built her campaign on the financial
largesse of her husband, wealthy financier Wilbur Ross, but then,
just a few weeks ago, he withdrew the $2.5 million he had lent her
campaign, leaving her with virtually nothing. Her erratic
personality also sent most of her staff fleeing. With no money,
scattered staff, and an unheard message, her once-leading status in
the polls was sent reeling.
</P>
<P>
   Vallone, meanwhile, gained support in New York City and its
surrounding suburbs by campaigning, however unsuccessfully, for a
referendum on Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's unpopular proposal to move
the Yankees to a new stadium on Manhattan's West Side.
</P>
<P>
   Turnout was seen as historically low, which also gave the edge
to the candidates with the best organizations.
</P>
<P>
   In other races, Republicans settled a bitter Senate primary in
Washington state, nominating an opponent for Democratic Senator
Patty Murray.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats nominated a candidate for governor in Minnesota,
hoping to end Republican control in the state.
</P>
<P>
   In Maryland, Democratic Governor Parris Glendening and
Republican Ellen Sauerbrey, who almost beat him four years ago, won
their nominations easily.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma Democrats decided not to make a dead woman their Senate
nominee. Jacquelyn Ledgerwood, who died July 15, lost to air
conditioning repairman Don E. Carroll on a Democratic runoff
ballot. Carroll will face Senator Don Nickles, considered a shoo-in
for reelection.
</P>
<P>
   In House races, Washington state Republicans chose from a field
of three to face Democrat Brian Baird. In North Carolina,
Republicans were picking a nominee to face Democratic
Representative Melvin Watt, weakened by redistricting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
