<DOCNO> NYT19980915.0446 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 22:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6996 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-ELECT-NYT &LR;      09-15 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ELECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOTER POLLS GIVE SCHUMER BIG LEAD OVER FERRARO IN SENATE RACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (DUPLICATION WARNING: Also moving in ``a'' news file.) 
(th) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Charles Schumer, a U.S. representative who had never
run for office outside his Park Slope, Brooklyn, neighborhood,
appeared headed Tuesday night toward winning the Democratic
nomination in New York to challenge Sen. Alfonse D'Amato,
overwhelming Geraldine Ferraro in her second attempt to return to
public office, according to interviews with voters leaving the
polls.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer, reaping the fruits of a decade of fund-raising and a
campaign marked by rigorous discipline and ceaseless television
advertising, easily defeated both Ferraro and the third major
candidate, Mark Green.
</P>
<P>
   The scope of Schumer's victory, as found in surveys of voters
leaving the polls, indicated strength that crossed geographic, sex
and ethnic lines, despite a low turnout. The results suggested he
had gone some distance in erasing doubts many Democrats had about
his viability to defeat D'Amato.
</P>
<P>
   The results also appeared to signal an end to one of the most
notable political careers of the last 20 years. Ferraro, who ran
for vice president in 1984, said she decided to run again this time
because she felt she had been unfairly deprived of the 1992
nomination for Senate, by just 11,000 votes, because of unfounded
attacks on her ethics.
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro was spared such treatment this time, yet surveys
suggested that she was losing by a far larger margin this time than
in 1992. Schumer's victory came as Democrats also chose Peter
Vallone, the New York City Council speaker, to challenge Gov.
George Pataki, in a primary that turned out to be less competitive
than had been expected, according to interviews with voters.
</P>
<P>
   Vallone easily defeated three candidates, including Lt. Gov.
Betsy McCaughey Ross, the former Republican running in a Democratic
primary for the first time. McCaughey Ross' name will appear on the
Liberal Party line in November.
</P>
<P>
   Voters in seven other states and the District of Columbia also
went to the polls Tuesday. In the capital, voters chose Anthony
Williams, who moved to Washington less than three years ago, as the
Democratic nominee for mayor in an election likely to determine who
will succeed Marion Barry. In Massachusetts, Acting Gov. Paul
Cellucci won the Republican primary for governor.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota was nominating candidates for governor, while
Maryland, North Carolina, Oklahoma, Rhode Island and Washington
State were selecting nominees in several races.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome of the Senate vote sets the stage for what is almost
sure to be one of the most ferociously fought races in the country
this fall. Schumer and D'Amato are both known in Washington as
streetwise, ambitious politicians who share talents for raising
funds, getting publicity and assailing their opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer has spent much of this decade quietly preparing himself
for the statewide stage, and D'Amato, facing what polls have long
suggested would be an extraordinarily difficult bid for a fourth
term, has been in effect running for re-election for almost two
years.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the polls were closed Tuesday, Schumer's media
consultant, Hank Morris, was in a television editing booth,
producing advertisements directed at D'Amato that will be broadcast
in the next two days.
</P>
<P>
   In other races, Sandra Frankel, a town supervisor from a suburb
of Rochester, was leading in the race to run with Vallone as the
Democratic candidate for lieutenant governor. And Eliot Spitzer, a
lawyer who used his family fortune to finance a campaign that was
also heavy on television advertising, was leading in the nomination
for state attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   The results, as signaled by the survey of voters, were a sharp
setback for women who have been seeking to break into the upper
ranks of New York state government.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, it seemed that the Democrats might have three
women on the statewide ticket: Ferraro for senator, McCaughey Ross
for governor and Catherine Abate for attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   It now appears that the only women running for statewide offices
will be Ms. Frankel and the Republican candidate for lieutenant
governor, Mary Donohue, a judge Pataki chose to be his running
mate. He is heavily favored, both because he has raised a huge
amount of money, over $15 million since July, and because McCaughey
Ross is likely to split the anti-Pataki vote.
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro and McCaughey Ross explicitly presented their
candidacies as appeals for women to gain political stature in New
York, a state that has never elected a woman as senator or
governor. But voter surveys found that most women disregarded those
appeals, voting instead for Schumer and Vallone.
</P>
<P>
   The contest to challenge D'Amato was remarkable for its lack of
open conflict, as the candidates avoided the kind of exchanges that
characterized the 1992 primary.
</P>
<P>
   One benefit of the decorous race will become clear Wednesday
morning, when all three Democratic Senate candidates are scheduled
to appear at a breakfast together with the state party chairwoman,
Judith Hope. In 1992, by contrast, Ferraro did not endorse the
Democratic candidate, Robert Abrams, until the last week of the
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer's strong performance was a clear tribute to the
influence of money on American politics today. Schumer, who is a
member of the House Banking Committee, raised $13 million for the
race, more than five times as much as either Ferraro or Green. The
benefits of Schumer's fund-raising could be seen on television
stations across the state: an advertising campaign that began at
the start of the year and built up in the final two weeks of the
race.
</P>
<P>
   The television advertisements proved to be particularly
significant this year because of the chronic lack of attention paid
to the race by the New York media. The candidates often found
themselves giving major speeches or press conferences with only a
single television camera in sight. Ferraro characterized the
contest Tuesday as ``a fight between money power and people
power.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-98 2204EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980915.0447 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 22:05 </DATE_TIME>
