<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7005 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEECEE-ELECT-ART-NYT &LR;      09-15 1089
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEECEE-ELECT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYORAL CANDIDATE CHOSEN IN WASHINGTON 
</HEADLINE>
  (Duplication warning: Also moving in `w' category) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By IRVIN MOLOTSKY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a striking break with the established political
order, Anthony Williams, a government technocrat who moved to
Washington less than three years ago to help lift the city out of
its fiscal mess, won the Democratic nomination for mayor Tuesday
over three opponents who are longtime City Council members.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' victory gave him the inside track to election as mayor
in November because of the Democrats' 10-to-1 enrollment advantage
over Republicans and because he is a black candidate in a
predominantly black city. If elected, he will succeed Mayor Marion
Barry, the man who dominated politics in this city for a
generation.
</P>
<P>
   But the Republican candidate, Carol Schwartz, who is white, said
Tuesday that she should not be underestimated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may be overwhelmed by the numbers, but there is an
overwhelming response to me in the community,'' she insisted.
</P>
<P>
   In the early tally in the Democratic primary Tuesday night,
Williams had 54 percent of the votes. He easily outdistanced the
three City Council members who opposed him: Kevin Chavous, who had
31 percent; Jack Evans, with 10 percent, and Harold Brazil, with 4
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Because an outsider was nominated by the Democrats, the primary
could be read as a repudiation of the current city government,
which has been largely subordinated by a control board imposed by
Congress in response to a combination of out-of-control spending
and failure to collect all taxes owed that led to hundreds of
millions of dollars in deficits.
</P>
<P>
   Barry did not seek re-election after having won four of the
first five elections under the limited home rule that the city had
been given by Congress. The only time he did not win was after he
was sentenced to a six-month jail term for possession of cocaine
that interrupted his third term.
</P>
<P>
   His administration was marked by turmoil. Until recent
improvements imposed by the control board started to take root,
many residents held Barry and the City Council responsible for the
failing schools, budget deficits and a decline in city services.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony Williams' victory will mean that the District of Columbia
will have a real new beginning in terms of leadership,'' said Prof.
Charles Harris, a political scientist at Howard University who
specializes in the relationship between Congress and the city
government.
</P>
<P>
   ``His success will depend on how well he can build a consensus
among his constituencies and win support from Congress,'' Harris
said, adding what is often left unsaid by political candidates,
``There is a racial divide in this city.''
</P>
<P>
   Barry, his one-term replacement, Sharon Pratt Kelly, and
Williams are black, and the 1990 census said the black population
was 66 percent, with recent estimates putting it at closer to 60
percent, still the majority.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Schwartz, then, is in two minorities: whites and
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican candidate, who was unopposed in her party's
primary, said in an interview Tuesday: ``I am not a partisan
person. I am not a racial person. They forgive me those perceived
handicaps.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Schwartz, 54, a former special education teacher and a
resident of Washington for the past 32 years, warned against
writing her off. She received 33 percent of the vote in her first
campaign for mayor against Barry in 1986 and increased that to 42
percent against the mayor in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am going to get far more than that this time,'' Ms. Schwartz
said. ``I've won citywide office in this town twice.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Schwartz's reference was to her elections as an at-large
member of the City Council. In both her mayoral races, her vote was
far greater than the 7 percent enrollment of Republicans in the
city.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, the outsider, could turn Ms. Schwartz's City Council
experience against her, as he did in campaigning against the City
Council members he defeated in the primary.
</P>
<P>
   He has held public office only once, as a member of the Board of
Aldermen in New Haven in the early 1980s, and has spent the rest of
his career in government agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, 46, has been chief financial officer for the
Department of Agriculture, deputy state comptroller of Connecticut,
executive director of the Community Development Agency in St. Louis
and assistant director of the Boston Redevelopment Authority.
</P>
<P>
   He came to Washington in 1995 as chief financial officer and has
taken credit for eliminating the city's budget deficit and bringing
it to a surplus of $185 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   Williams grew up in Los Angeles and then set upon his
peripatetic career. He has an undergraduate political science
degree from Yale University, a law degree from Harvard University
and a master's degree in public policy from Harvard's Kennedy
School of Government.
</P>
<P>
   Only rarely mentioning Barry's name, the candidates all harkened
to the need to turn things around.
</P>
<P>
   At a candidates' forum last week, one of Tuesday's losers,
Brazil said that, as mayor: ``I will work with Congress. I will
work with the Control Board. I will insist on accountability. I
will make Washington work again.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans said: ``Philadelphia, Cleveland and New York all went
through control boards. They turned things around. What did they do
to accomplish that? They elected a good mayor. Having a new mayor
in the District of Columbia will leap us ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   The third Council member seeking the nomination, Chavous, did
not attend the forum. He said in a campaign statement, ``This
election gives us an opportunity to reform our government and
restore our democratic rights.''
</P>
<P>
   A noncandidate at the mayoral forum, Wilbert Washington 2d, gave
this summation of the election, ``This is the first time that we
will have an election in the post-Barry era.''
</P>
<P>
   Primaries were also held Tuesday in Maryland, Massachusetts,
Rhode Island, Minnesota, North Carolina, Oklahoma and Washington
state.
</P>
<P>
   In the Massachusetts governor's race, Acting Gov. Argeo Paul
Cellucci defeated state Treasurer Joseph Malone by almost 2-to-1
for the Republican Party's nomination. He will face Tuesday's
winner of the Democratic primary, state Attorney General Scott
Harshbarger, in a contest that political experts consider a
toss-up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-98 2209EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
