u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-HOMERUNS-BOS &LR;      09-15 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-HOMERUNS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCGWIRE EDGES AHEAD WITH NO. 63 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: Combines budgeted McGwire, Sosa stories.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ With a four-homer performance over the weekend, it
appeared that the momentum in the Great Home Run Chase had swung to
Sammy Sosa, who caught Mark McGwire _ for the third time this
season _ at 62.
</P>
<P>
   But then McGwire broke a weeklong drought with No. 63 in the
first game of a doubleheader in St. Louis to nose back in front.
The two sluggers each had another game to play Tuesday night. With
Sosa's Cubs in the thick of a wild-card race and McGwire still the
center of attention for the Cardinals, does either one have an
advantage down the stretch?
</P>
<P>
   ``I have had an advantage this year because I've had more
opportunities,'' said Sosa before Tuesday night's game against the
Padres. ``Mark was injured and didn't have as many chances to go
out and play. That made me work even harder. No matter what
happens, I've got to get ready every day; I'm not only looking for
home runs, but also to the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa has answered the challenge all season. Don't forget that he
once trailed McGwire in homers, 24-9, but caught him at 47. In his
first game after tying the record, Sosa struck out four times in a
4-3 loss here Monday night. It was his first 0-for-4 game this
season. And not only did he lose the homer lead, but he had to face
San Diego's 18-game winner, Kevin Brown.
</P>
<P>
   The schedule all by itself could make a big difference in the
final results. Starting tonight, both the Cardinals and Cubs have
10 games left. But St. Louis plays seven at home, while the Cubs
have only three in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something about playing at home,'' said San Diego's
Tony Gwynn, who knows about late-season pressure, having flirted
with .400 down the stretch. ``There's a source of energy there. You
may recall that when (Sosa) was playing in St. Louis, it looked
like he started to tire or whatever. But when he got home in
Chicago, the crowd just electrified him. Four home runs later,
they're both tied again.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa likes to talk about the pressure of the playoff race. To
him, it is a plus.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not as big a deal to him as you might think,'' said
Gwynn. ``He's said all along that he wants to win. He wants to get
to the playoff. But everywhere he's going, there are packed houses
and they're not coming to watch him try to get to the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   On the way to No. 62, McGwire was perceived to have an
intangible advantage, and indeed he got there first. But Sosa can
beat him out for the season title and the record.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire has been having back spasms, an old problem, though he
said he was feeling fine.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa has the built-in incentive of the wild-race race to keep
him pumped. He is looking forward to getting back to Wrigley Field
for three games with the Reds this weekend, the Cubs' final
homestand. Sunday has been declared Sammy Sosa Day in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might have a letdown,'' said Sosa. ``We're all human. We
never know what happens tomorrow. But I'm not going to be
struggling the rest of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Advantage, Sosa?
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a good chance,'' said Gwynn. ``There is a thin line
that separates a good hitter from just a guy who is able to put the
bat on the ball. But when it becomes something that people come out
and expect you to do, it's got to be one of the most difficult
things to do. It becomes even more magnified when people come to
the ballpark and that is what they want to see.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here in San Diego, fans have been talking about this for about
a week. They knew he was coming here for four games and they wanted
to see him get hot. And he did. We had over 50,000 show up for a
Monday night game with school in session. That never happens.
Never.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa remains confident.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I know is I got to No. 62 and I caught Mr. McGwire, my
man,'' said Sosa. ``I can't stop now. I know I have to go out and
compete and do my job. I did what everybody was waiting for me to
do. It's a pretty heavy responsibility to go out and finish strong
and take the team to the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's see what happens.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-98 2209EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
