<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-HYDE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HYDE WARNS AGAINST INTIMIDATION TACTICS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By DAVID STOUT    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The chairman of the House committee that will weigh
possible impeachment charges against President Clinton promised
swift action Tuesday against any efforts to use smear tactics to
intimidate committee members.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to rumors that some Clinton supporters may be trying
to gather embarrassing personal information about members of the
House Judiciary Committee, the chairman, Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill.,
said the panel would refer any accusations of wrongdoing to the
Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   Any effort to intimidate members of Congress or interfere with
them in an impeachment proceeding could constitute a federal crime
and be punishable by up to five years in prison, Hyde, warned
committee members in a memorandum.
</P>
<P>
   ``I request that you immediately notify me if you learn of any
activity or information relating to this concern,'' Hyde wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The Judiciary Committee, made up of 21 Republicans and 16
Democrats, is about to consider whether the accusations against the
president arising from his relationship with former White House
intern Monica Lewinsky are grounds for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Starr, the Whitewater independent counsel who has been
investigating the Lewinsky matter, filed a report with Congress
asserting that there was ``substantial and credible'' evidence that
Clinton perjured himself, obstructed justice and misused his office
in trying to thwart the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde's committee will decide if there is a basis for a full
impeachment inquiry. If the committee decides that there is, and
the full House agrees, hearings would be held and the House would
vote on whether to approve articles of impeachment. A ``yes'' vote
by a simple House majority would bring a Senate trial, where a
two-thirds majority would be required to convict and remove the
president. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-98 2211EDT &QL; 
