<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 22:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7016 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BO     09-15 0648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WATCHWORD FOR PENNANT RACE IS `TECHNOLOGY' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Whether you take your scores fast or slow, the
scoreboard-watching season is upon us. Players and coaches no
longer attempt to mask their interest. The Red Sox want to know
what the Blue Jays and Rangers are doing. And they're not afraid to
admit they're watching.
</P>
<P>
   Every night is exciting now. The Cubs and Mets are
shoulder-to-shoulder in the National League. Red Sox Nation is
nervous, the depleted Angels are struggling to hold on, and the
Indians are trying to win enough games to keep them away from the
Yankees in the first round of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and then we've got Sammy Sosa and Mark McGwire marching
toward history in a place where no ballplayers have gone. Who'll be
next to set the record?
</P>
<P>
   But scoreboard-watching just isn't what it used to be.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, I sat in Earl Weaver's office and, at his request,
dialed the press box in Milwaukee's County Stadium (on a rotary
phone, I might add) to see how the Brewers were doing. It was late
September, the Orioles had a commanding lead in the American League
East, and a Milwaukee loss would clinch the division for Baltimore.
My spy in the press box delivered play-by-play and I relayed the
information to Earl until the Brewers finally lost, and the race
was officially over.
</P>
<P>
   Fenway's hand-operated left-field scoreboard offers the same
old-timey process. For most of this century, Boston fans have held
their breath, waiting for the man behind the green wall to post a
big fat loss for the Yankees. Fenway grounds crew pranksters have
been known to slide a bogus ``10'' into the Yankee slot, just to
give Red Sox Nation a little heartburn.
</P>
<P>
   But now the sweet science of scoreboard-watching has gone
high-tech. Fans with Internet access can track every pitch of any
game. ESPN seems to deliver scores faster than the speed of light.
Red Sox pitching coach Joe Kerrigan carries a hand-held gizmo that
gives him updated scores instantly. For those who need information,
there are no more phone calls to other stadia, no more waiting for
the guy behind the wall to get out of his chair and update the
Yankee score. And the kids who answer the phone in the Globe sports
department are spared the dozens of calls we used to get from
barrooms late at night.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Yankees and Red Sox took the field Tuesday night, the
Blue Jays aleady held a 2-0 lead over the Indians. The prospect of
Boston's wild-card lead shrinking to two games seemed real. A
half-hour later, the Indians led the Blue Jays, 3-2, and Jason
Varitek crashed a three-run homer (his first of two homers) to give
the Sox a 3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   We also knew that McGwire was not starting the first game of a
doubleheader against Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox inflated their lead to 7-0 in the fourth and the
Indians were up, 6-4, on the Jays. Just like that, it felt like the
Sox' lead had gone from two to four games. The Yankees were
trotting out a series of faceless pitchers (New York writers
believe it may have been a conspiracy _ the Yankees laying down to
punish the Blue Jays, who brawled in New York last week) and the
Red Sox' magic number had a chance to drop to 9 with a lucky 13 to
play.
</P>
<P>
   And then it was learned that McGwire had hit No. 63, a pinch
homer in the ninth inning of Game 1 in St. Louis. The Yankee
Stadium crowd, like so many others in this feel-good baseball
summer, roared its approval when the news was flashed on the big
board.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Red Sox were leading, 9-0 (maybe Jimy Williams
was right, that getting shut out Monday was a good thing), the Blue
Jays and Rangers were still losing, and all seemed right for the
scoreboard-watchers from Boston.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
