On the television monitor is Rep. Bill McCollum, R-Fla., who is
speaking on the floor of the House. McCollum is also a member of
the House Judiciary Committee that will consider possible
impeachment charges against the president. (Stephen Crowley/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) MONTGOMERY, Ala. -- Sept. 15, 1998 --
WALLACE-FUNERAL-FLOATER, 9-15 -- Mourners pay their respects
Tuesday to former 4-term Alabama Gov. George Wallace as his body
lies in state in the rotunda of the Capitol in Montgomery. A bust
of his wife Lurleen, sits above his casket. Wallace, who used a
wheelchair after he was paralyzed from the waist down in an
assassination attempt in 1972, died Sunday of a heart attack. He
was 79. (Daniel Giles/Florence Times Daily Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 15, 1998 -- CLINTON-PENTAGON, 9-15
-- The military's readiness was at issue Tuesday at a meeting
between President Clinton and the leaders of the armed forces,
including Defense Secretary William Cohen, left, and Gen. Henry
Shelton of the army, the chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.
(Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) DENVER -- Sept. 15, 1998 -- DENVER-AIRPORT, 9-15 -- An
old hanger at Stapleton International Airport in Denver crumpled
under the methodical assault of a demolition crew. When its work is
finished, seven square miles of land near downtown Denver will be
open to residential and commercial development in a city undergoing
explosive growth. (Kevin Moloney/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- Sept. 15, 1998 -- LINCOLN-CENTER-GIFT-B&AMP;W,
9-15 -- Julian Robertson's $25 million donation to Lincoln Center
honors his wife, Josie. Robertson, 66, is the chairman and chief
executive officer of Tiger Management. Lincoln Center officials
call it the largest single gift to the center by an individual and
say the money will be divided among Lincoln Center's own artistic
programs and its 12 constituent members. (New York Times Photo)
*LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- Sept. 15, 1998 -- LIVENT-HAIMES, 9-15 --
Todd Haimes, artistic director of Livent, the only major publicly
traded company exclusively devoted to theater. He dropped 55 pounds
several years ago in order to see his two children grow up. This
goes a long way toward explaining how Haimes, 42, has become a
success in the theater: through dogged, painstaking work. ``Maybe
these insecurities and these self-doubts make me work harder,'' he
says. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- Sept. 15, 1998 -- MADMAN-BOOK-REVIEW, 9-15 --
The subtitle of Simon Winchester's new book, ``The Professor and
the Madman: A Tale of Murder, Insanity and the Making of the Oxford
English Dictionary,'' suggests one of the odder thematic
combinations in recent publishing history. One might even suspect
that no true story could bring these three elements together. But
in fact, this story of two oddly matched figures entirely fulfills
its subtitular promise. (Andrea Mohin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- Sept. 15, 1998 -- NY-MILLER-THEATER, 9-15 --
George Steel, executive director of the Miller Theater at Columbia,
whose first season focuses on a wide range of 20th-century music.
``It's really a question of where your own priorities are,'' he
says. ``And my priorities lie in doing things that I'm passionate
about, and that just aren't the scope in this city otherwise.''
(Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Sept. 15, 1998 -- FOOD-NOTES, 9-15 -- Copper
pans and $28,000 stove by Alain Ducasse. The pans are part of a new
line of cookware, tableware and food products bearing the
imprimatur of Ducasse, the multistarred French chef. The line has
just been introduced into this country and is available only at
Bergdorf Goodman. The stove is almost too gorgeous to cook on.
(Ruby Washington/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- Sept. 15, 1998 -- RUGELACH, 9-15 -- Zigmond
Lugowski, left, and Cheskel Herman preparing braided hallah bread
at the Israel Beigel Baking Co. in Williamsburg, Brooklyn. With
Rosh ha-Shanah beginning on Sunday evening, the business, like
other classic Jewish bakeries in New York City, is in its high
season for rugelach, honey cakes and the traditional round New Year
challahs - more than 10,000 of them. (Andrea Mohin/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Sept. 15, 1998 -- MANHATTAN-CHERRY, 9-15 --
When sour cherries came on the market this summer, Peter Hoffman,
owner of Savoy restaurant in SoHo, began preserving them, using
traditional techniques. ``We make a simple sugar syrup with
pomegranate molasses and add lemon juice, allspice, black pepper
and a few other spices,'' he says. The result is a delicious
natural cherry with a wonderful balance of sweet and sour. (Fred R.
Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) QUINCY, Mass. -- Sept. 15, 1998 -- OPEN-ROAD-BOS, 9-15 --
``It's not easy to explain,'' says Goldie Muise about her
attraction to convertibles. Ms. Muise, a postal clerk who owns both
a 1976 Chevrolet Corvette and a 1980 Ford Mustang convertible, is
spending this evening driving Route 128 in her Mustang. (Tom
Herde/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) UNDATED -- Sept. 15, 1998 -- WINE-TALK, 9-15 -- Excellent
chardonnays come from many wine regions around the world. Among the
best are those from the Edna Valley vineyard in Northern
California, and from the Cloudy Bay winery in New Zealand. (Boyd
Hagen/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- Sept. 15, 1998 -- KITCHEN-WARES-2, 9-15 --
Michael Lomonaco, the chef at Windows on the World, uses a
bottomless paper cup as a salad mold. Chefs are always devising new
ways to execute their ideas. So when conventional kitchen equipment
can't accomplish what they want it to do, they look for other ways
to get the job done. (Marilynn K. Yee/New York Times Phone)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- Sept. 15, 1998 -- KITCHEN-WARES-1, 9-15 --
Jacques Torres, the pastry chef at Le Cirque 2000, uses a notched
trowel, left, to form slice sticks of chocolate. He later places
them on a dessert, right. It is a clever little trick, one of many
in the restaurant world. (Don Hogan Charles/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
