<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980915.0460 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 22:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7030 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-BUSH16-COX     09-15 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-BUSH16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush says ``The process in Washington is a sullied process''
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas -- The son of the man who raised the character
thing in a 1992 presidential race against Bill Clinton said Tuesday
he finds nothing redeeming about the very public airing of
Clinton's very personal life.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a very depressing time for me,'' Gov. George W.
Bush said. ``The process in Washington is a sullied process, and I
take no joy in any of this going on. It's sullied. It's not good
for America.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush aligned himself squarely with the party line, siding with
Republicans urging cautious expediency in sorting out the Clinton
scandal. No calls for resignation, no high-volume moral
indignation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the honorable outcome is for everybody to take a deep
breath and allow the process to work,'' Bush told the Austin
American-Statesman. ``It is a very serious business when the
impeachment proceedings are now taking place in the United States
House of Representatives.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican Bob Dole, who was in San Antonio Tuesday for a speech
at Trinity University, also cautioned against a rush to judgment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The founding fathers didn't have in mind that you remove
somebody very easily,'' Dole said. ``It's time for everybody to let
the House do what it has to do under the Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   Dole, who raised the character issue against Clinton in 1996,
said the scandal has not made him bitter about his defeat. ``The
election is over and it's history,'' Dole said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, an early-line top contender for the GOP presidential
nomination in 2000, said Clinton's woes put a new focus on the
downside of seeking his dad's old job.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a troubling period,'' he said. ``I think running for
president is a commitment to the bubble (of public scrutiny) and
I've got to make up my mind at the right time if that's what I want
to do.''
</P>
<P>
   And Bush, who has seen _ up close and personal _ how the system
can spit out a once-popular president, likened a White House race
to loading the kids into the car for a long drive on an unknown
route to an uncertain destination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this something I want to put my family through?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   For Bush, a presidential run would mean high-pressure scrutiny
of a baby-boomer's past not up to the high moral standards he now
pushes.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, as Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr's report was
scorching the Internet, television cameras captured the moment in
Richardson as yet another reporter asked Bush if there was anything
in his 52 years that could call his character into question.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not since I've been the governor of the great state of
Texas,'' said Bush, who, without citing chapter and verse, has said
``when I was young and irresponsible I was young and
irresponsible.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who preaches pre-marital abstinence and personal
responsibility, said he has learned from his mistakes of his
younger days. He acknowledges that he pushes a do-as-I-say, rather
than a do-what-I did, message on the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   The governor insists re-election is his only political goal.
Polls show him running way ahead. A Texas Poll completed last month
gave Bush a 47-point edge.
</P>
<P>
   Democrat Garry Mauro. Bush backers would like him to run up big
numbers that sweep other GOP candidates into office and show
strength across demographic lines.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Bush continues his push for Hispanic votes with stops in
San Antonio, Corpus Christi, Harlingen and El Paso, accompanied by
Tejano music star Emiliano Navaira.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Bush said he has not read the entire Starr report,
but is up to speed enough to take sides in the Clinton vs.
Independent Counsel Ken Starr skirmish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm more troubled by the president's behavior,'' he said when
asked if Starr had overstepped his bounds.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he is more troubled by Clinton's affair with Monica
Lewinsky or the presidential lies about it, Bush paused and
responded with, ``All of the above.''
</P>
<P>
   Mauro, a longtime Clinton friend, says Starr is the bad actor in
the national soap opera.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have said repeatedly I started out embarrassed for the
president, for Hillary,'' Mauro said Monday. ``Then I got mad at
him. Now after reading the Starr report I'm still embarrassed, but
I'm mad at Starr. That was an outrageous format and, as a lawyer, I
read the so-called high crimes and treason, and there is no
evidence to back that up.''
</P>
<P>
   Mauro is counting on Clinton to help him raise about $1 million
at Sept. 27 fundraisers in San Antonio and Houston. Dole, who spoke
to reporters Tuesday before his speech, reiterated his opposition
to the law that created the independent counsel. But he didn't
criticize Starr. He said he hasn't read all of the Starr report,
but he suggested that its graphic detail was necessary to prove
that Clinton lied under oath about having a sexual relationship
with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Dole warned that the sex scandal will harm his credibility as a
world leader but he wouldn't say if Clinton should resign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's a judgment he has to make,'' Dole said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush took a similar tack. ``That's up to him,'' Bush said when
asked if Clinton should resign. ``He is going to have to ask how
effective he is as the president of the United States. I'm
certainly not going to be out here on the sidelines chirping away,
giving him advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can figure out whether he is capable of being the president
of the United States much better than I can. I am counseling people
to allow the process to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
