<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-LIVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FERRARO SEEKS LEVERAGE 
FROM SOCCER TO ROCKER 
UNLIKELY THESPIAN
</HEADLINE>
   (mk) 
 By JAMES BARRON with ANDREW C. REVKIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Geraldine Ferraro had problems with the most basic of
primary-day rituals Tuesday. Arriving at Public School 101 in
Forest Hills, Queens, she signed the register and stepped into the
voting booth.
</P>
<P>
   A crowd of photographers gathered in a semicircle, waiting for
her to emerge and do whatever a candidate for the Democratic
nomination for governor does after voting: give a thumbs up, smile,
whatever.
</P>
<P>
   The photographers heard the pull of the lever once, twice, three
times. Then they heard Ms. Ferraro's voice say, ``It doesn't
work.''
</P>
<P>
   She stepped out. Election personnel reset the machine. She
stepped back in, voted and left, trailed by the cameras.
</P>
<P>
   Dual Careers
</P>
<P>
   Alexi Lalas, who is already famous in soccer, is hoping to make
it big as a rocker.
</P>
<P>
   He is already about the closest thing there is to an American
soccer star. A two-time member of the U.S. Olympic and World Cup
teams, Lalas was also the first American player to compete in
Italy's Serie A, which aficionados consider the best professional
soccer league in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Lalas' fame is derived not only from his defensive play for the
New York/New Jersey MetroStars, but also from his flaming red hair
and bushy goatee, which gave him a kind of brand-label recognition.
</P>
<P>
   Will looks help him draw rock fans? After the soccer season,
Lalas plans to hit the road on a concert tour promoting his first
commercial rock-and-roll album, ``Ginger,'' released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Other athletes have tried to cross over into music, but only a
few have succeeded, most notably Shaquille O'Neal of Los Angeles
Lakers. But Lalas, 28, said that music is not a passing thing for
him. He has been writing songs and playing guitar since he was a
teen-ager, and released two CDs on small labels, one in Italy and
the other here.
</P>
<P>
   His longtime soccer fans seem to like his sound. The first
person in line Tuesday was Tara Legates of Glen Ridge, N.J., who
took a day off from work and rode two trains in her quest for
Lalas' autograph at the Official All-Star Cafe in Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just great,'' she said eagerly as Lalas arrived. ``Plus
he's a total babe on top of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Who, Scrooge?
</P>
<P>
   And then there is Roger Daltrey, the rock musician who wants to
make the transition to the stage. Daltrey, the lead singer of the
Who, will play Ebenezer Scrooge in ``A Christmas Carol'' at Madison
Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Is this casting against type? Perhaps. ``He seems about as
un-Scroogelike as possible,'' said Tim Hawkins, the producer of ``A
Christmas Carol,'' who approached Daltrey about the role a couple
of years ago. ``Roger is really great fun. He's a regular guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, Daltrey is showing every sign of being a spirited
performer. One Garden executive said that when Daltrey was
introduced at a promotional event at the Garden on Monday, he
pulled the microphone from its holder on the podium and started
swinging it.
</P>
<P>
   From there, Daltrey went to lunch. Then he wanted to go to his
hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had had a car for him,''the Garden executive said. ``He
said, `There was so much traffic getting here, let's take the
subway.' He said, `We're going uptown to the West Side.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `All right, I'll put you on the 1 and 9.' I slid my
card through twice so they didn't have to deal with the whole card
issue and said take the 1 and 9 local and get off at 57th
Street.'''
</P>
<P>
   He paused, then said, ``I hope they figured out that the stop
after 50th Street was 59th.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
