<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLEEPWARE-SAFETY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOUGHER STANDARDS FOR KIDS' SLEEPWARE SOUGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn.)  (mk) 
 By STEVEN A. HOLMES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Over the vehement opposition of the cotton
industry, a coalition of consumer and fire-prevention organizations
is seeking to restore what they say are tougher flammability
standards for children's sleepware.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is essentially a fight about the profits of the cotton
industry verses our children's safety,'' Rep. Rosa DeLauro,
D-Conn., said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. DeLauro has attached an amendment to a spending bill for the
Veterans Administration and the Department of Housing and Urban
Development, preventing the enforcement of new federal standards
governing the fire-resistance quality of pajamas, bathrobes and
other sleeping garments for children over the age of nine months.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. DeLauro and consumer and fire-prevention advocates are
seeking to overturn an April 1996 vote by the Consumer Product
Safety Commission that allowed polyester and snug-fitting cotton
garments to legally be sold as sleepwear. Under federal
regulations, only clothing that is fire-resistant can be sold as
sleepwear.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of fire-resistant sleepwear has been a highly
contentious and highly emotional one. Research by the commission
found that many parents prefer cotton garments for their children
because they are more comfortable than polyester clothing.
</P>
<P>
   But cotton clothing is much more dangerous than polyester since
it is much more combustible. Between 200 and 300 children are
seriously burned each year when cotton garments, primarily
T-shirts, catch fire. In contrast, polyester is self-extinguishing,
though it can melt and produce burns when heated by an open flame.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a great demand by consumers to buy untreated cotton
for their kids,'' said Ronald Medford, the commission's assistant
executive director for hazard identification and education.
</P>
<P>
   In changing the regulation, the commissioner said they wanted to
give consumers another alternative _ snug-fitting garments that
tend to be fire- resistant _ for consumers who wanted to buy cotton
sleepwear for their children. The change was supported by the
cotton industry who saw it as a way to help maintain market share
in the face of the onslaught of synthetic fibers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is a lot of misinformation on the part of people
who think this should be changed back,'' said Phillip Wakelyn,
senior scientist for the National Cotton Council.
</P>
<P>
   But in voting for a change in the regulations, the commissioners
also requested that the cotton industry mount a public education
campaign to convince parents not to use 100 per cent cotton
clothing such as T-shirts as sleep wear. To date, commissioners and
staff say they have been disappointed with the industry's efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. DeLauro and consumer advocates say they there was no valid
reason to change the federal standards on sleepwear. In 1970, two
years before the flamability standards were adopted, 60 children
died annually from garments that caught on fire. By 1991, that
figure had dropped to six children a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``These standards have been in place for 25 years and they were
working,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-98 2225EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
