<DOCNO> NYT19980915.0468 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 22:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7044 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-CARDS-PIRATES-NYT     09-15 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CARDS-PIRATES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 McGWIRE HITS 63rd HOMER IN 8-6 LOSS TO PIRATES  
(th) 
 By IRA BERKOW    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ In a sleeveless blue T-shirt, his prodigious arms
folded casually, Mark McGwire said Tuesday that he was only
beginning to understand what the pursuit of the single-season home
run record by him and Sammy Sosa had meant to the country _ and,
maybe, the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing,'' he said, standing in the Cardinals' clubhouse
at Busch Stadium. ``I've seen the editorials and the front-page
stories about what this means to people. Just today I got a letter
from the prime minister of Japan, and from Bob Dole.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm slowly realizing the impact. And I don't think I'll
totally realize it until like a month after the season, when it can
all sink in.''
</P>
<P>
   Going into Tuesday night's doubleheader against the Pittsburgh
Pirates, McGwire had not hit a home run in six games, since he hit
No. 62 on Sept. 8 to break the record held by Roger Maris for the
last 37 years. Sosa, who was at 58 homers on that day, has hit four
since and tied McGwire for the major league lead.
</P>
<P>
   The homer deadlock, however, changed abruptly Tuesday night.
McGwire, who had been rested in the first game of a doubleheader,
was called into action by Cardinals Manager Tony La Russa to
pinch-hit for Delino DeShields in the ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   With the Cardinals trailing, 8-5, with one out and no one on,
McGwire swung at a 1-0 pitch from left-hander Jason Christensen and
sent one of his classic, arching blows into the left-center-field
stands for his 63rd home run of the season. It was also his 450th
career home run.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier at his locker, McGwire pointed to a nearby St. Louis
Post-Dispatch headline. ``McGwire Stuck on 62,'' he read aloud, and
laughed. ``Imagine. `Stuck on 62.' I think we've spoiled these
people. Last night I got two singles, and, `Boo, boo!' ''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't quite that way, though fans are invariably
disappointed when McGwire does not belt a ball over the fence. The
boos come more for the umpire who calls a strike on McGwire, and
for the pitcher who cannot throw in the strike zone to McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   The two home run hitters have put a new face on competition.
Compared with all the players who taunt and talk trash, McGwire and
Sosa have been as close to brotherly love as possible under the
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have looked at athletes these days as greedy or
arrogant and then they see Sammy and I truly respecting one
another, and liking one another,'' McGwire said. ``Two guys from
two different backgrounds and countries appreciating what the other
is doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Tuesday night's games _ Sosa's Cubs played in San Diego _
McGwire had only three hits, all singles, in his last 18 at-bats.
He had back spasms on Sunday, but he said his back was now
``outstanding.''
</P>
<P>
   The longest he had gone without a homer this season was, as he
said, ``20-something at-bats.'' It was in early August, and he
recalled telling reporters, ``There's more important things in the
country than worrying about my hitting a home run.''
</P>
<P>
   About that statement, McGwire said: ``I got kind of testy. But
I'm human. It's a six-month season. And if you average 10 homers a
month, you can break the record. And I had been averaging that. But
I also hadn't yet realized just what all this meant to people. That
reaction by me never happened again.''
</P>
<P>
   Players told McGwire to enjoy the experience, and pointed to
Sosa, who was taking pleasure in it. ``But Sammy wasn't like
Griffey and me,'' McGwire said. ``He hadn't gone through all the
questions before.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire had 58 homers last season and Ken Griffey Jr. had 56;
Sosa had 36. ``So Griffey and I have been getting it since last
year, `Can we break the record?' '' McGwire said. But on the
weekend of Aug. 7, the Cubs and Sosa were here for a series.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was before a game and Sammy and I looked at each other,''
McGwire said, ``and I guess we both thought, `All right, all the
cameras are around, let's make them happy.' '' They ran at each
other and embraced.
</P>
<P>
   And then some 10 days later, in a series between the two teams
in Wrigley Field, they did it again. When McGwire broke Maris'
record, it was against the Cubs, and Sosa ran in from his position
in right field to hug McGwire. After Sosa hit his 61st and 62nd
homers last Sunday, McGwire called to congratulate him.
</P>
<P>
   A woman called the office of La Russa. The woman had heard that
McGwire was going to play in one of the two games, but didn't know
which one. If it's the first, she told La Russa, she would leave
work early.
</P>
<P>
   ``She left her number with me,'' said La Russa, ``and if Mark
was playing the first game, I was supposed to call her.''
</P>
<P>
   La Russa had decided to play McGwire in the second game because,
he said, ``All things being equal _ and they are, with
right-handers starting both games _ more people will be at the
second game than the first, and that would just give more people an
opportunity to see Mark.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire was asked if he would be disappointed if Sosa finished
ahead of him in homers at the end of the season, thereby
establishing the record.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not at all, not one iota,'' he said. ``It's been an
unbelievable year so far. All I can do is control what I can do.
I've done what I've done. However we end up, how can anybody say
anything negative if one is ahead of the other at the finish?''
</P>
<P>
   And if the two are tied for homers at season's end?
</P>
<P>
   ``That,'' he said, ``would be wonderful.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-98 2227EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
