u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-DEATH-PENALTY-DEFE     09-15 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DEATH-PENALTY-DEFENSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN ALLOWED TO ACT AS OWN LAWYER IN DEATH PENALTY CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Tenn.)   (bl)  
 By SOMINI SENGUPTA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For the first time since capital punishment was
reinstated in New York three years ago, a defendant facing the
death penalty will be allowed to represent himself in court, a
Queens judge ruled Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   State Supreme Court Justice Thomas Demakos said the defendant,
James Allen Gordon, a 26-year-old convicted drug dealer, had made
his request knowingly, unequivocally and in a timely fashion,
satisfying what the judge said were the three criteria under the
law for a defendant to represent himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are an intelligent person, an articulate person,'' Demakos
told Gordon, a tall, lean man who was wearing gold-rimmed glasses
and a blue-and-white checkered shirt. ``Your right to represent
yourself is granted.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, who said in court that he had a 10th-grade education, is
accused of killing three women and bludgeoning a fourth with a
hammer in Jamaica, Queens, in July 1996. Jury screening in the
case, the third death penalty trial in the city since capital
punishment was reinstated in 1995, began last week.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon's unusual request to dismiss his court-appointed lawyers,
Russell Morea and Chris Renfroe, came five months after he
dismissed lawyers sent by the state Capital Defenders Office,
created by the Legislature and financed by the state to insure that
defendants in capital cases are adequately represented. In his
request Monday, Gordon complained about their defense and about the
judge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the one who is sitting in this chair,'' Gordon said in
court Monday. ``I'm the one who is facing such an ugly situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the law, a defendant has the right to self-representation
so long as the court finds the person to have made an intelligent
request and to be aware of its ramifications. ``The judge really
has no choice,'' Morea said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, the U.S. Supreme Court upheld the right of a defendant
in a death penalty trial in Nevada to represent himself. The
defendant, Richard Moran, who pleaded guilty to three murders, was
executed in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers experienced in capital cases Tuesday lamented
Gordon's request. Kevin Doyle, a lawyer with the State Capital
Defenders Office, declined to comment on Gordon, whom his office
represented until April, but said it was highly unusual for a
defendant facing the death penalty to represent himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Capital litigation is extraordinarily complex,'' he said.
``It's a challenge even for an experienced criminal-defense
lawyer.''
</P>
<P>
   Avoiding the death penalty, the lawyers said, requires
convincing jurors of mitigating circumstances in a defendant's
background _ for example, having been abused as a child.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a case goes to trial with someone refusing to put on any
evidence about their psychological background, they are more likely
to get the death penalty,'' said Ronald Tabak, who is a lawyer with
Skadden, Arps, Slate, Meagher &AMP; Flom and the president of New York
Lawyers Against the Death Penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Demakos' ruling Tuesday came after he repeatedly asked Gordon
whether he understood the ramifications of his request. ``Voir dire
of individual jurors can be very complex,'' he told Gordon,
referring to the jury selection process. ``You would be at a
tremendous disadvantage. Do you understand that?''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon replied in a barely audible voice, ``Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   In a 33-count indictment, the Queens district attorney's office
charged that Gordon entered an apartment building in Jamaica,
Queens, early on the morning of July 10, 1996, and terrorized five
women. The authorities said that Gordon first went to the
first-floor apartment of Darlene Johnson, 28, with the intention of
robbing her. Instead, the indictment charged, he raped and
sodomized her and then fatally shot her in the head.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment charged that Gordon then went to a second-floor
apartment and fatally shot two women, Mary Mouzon, 33, and Hadiyah
Holliman, 18, and beat Ms. Holliman's twin sister, Zakkiyah
Holliman, with a hammer. A fourth woman, Latisha Crite, 19, a
visitor, escaped by jumping from a window, the indictment said. At
the time, police said Gordon killed the women while trying to
collect a $50 cocaine debt.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon was arrested in Memphis a month after the murders in
Queens.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
