<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 22:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7051 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANONYMOUS-4-ALBUM-2TA     09-15 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANONYMOUS-4-ALBUM-2TAKES-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HELP WANTED: FOURTH SINGER, ABLE TO MAKE A SINGULAR SOUND  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 20) 
</HEADLINE>
   (Cori Ellison is a singer and the dramaturge at the New York City
Opera)  
 (af)  
 By CORI ELLISON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Anonymous 4 has just released its eighth recording,
and it will not be surprising if this CD, ``A Lammas Ladymass,''
sails to the top of the classical charts as most of the group's
earlier efforts have. But this new album of chant and polyphony for
the Roman Catholic feast of the Assumption, which celebrates the
Virgin Mary's passage into heaven, is itself a rite of passage.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Lammas Ladymass,'' from Harmonia Mundi France, marks the end
of an era for Anonymous 4, the New York-based female vocal quartet
specializing in medieval music.
</P>
<P>
   In April, Ruth Cunningham, a member of the group since 1988,
suddenly announced that she was leaving to pursue a career in
healing through sound. With no successor in mind, Anonymous 4 faced
a daunting task: to recruit a new singer and have the ensemble
running like clockwork again by July, when it was to make its debut
at the Tanglewood Festival in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   For any small ensemble, the departure of a member is a seismic
shift. It can result in a substantial change in sound, as it did
with the Tokyo String Quartet, or even dissolution, as it did with
the Cleveland Quartet.
</P>
<P>
   For an a cappella vocal ensemble, the repercussions are
especially serious. Human voices are far more variable in timbre
and thus harder to blend than other musical instruments.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, since this instrument comes housed in a case
susceptible to such indignities as phlegm, indigestion, fatigue and
age, and is governed by a circuit board vulnerable to vagaries like
moods, hormones and domestic discord, the challenges multiply.
</P>
<P>
   The women of Anonymous 4 knew that their personnel search would
demand more than placing want ads and vetting resumes. They relied
on word of mouth, disseminating the news of their quest through the
early-music grapevine.
</P>
<P>
   Sooner than you can say Perotin, they received some 20 demo
tapes. After ruling out applicants with a sound too radically
different from their own, they arranged to hear nine sopranos in
live auditions, several as many as three times.
</P>
<P>
   And on a sultry afternoon in May, the remaining members of
Anonymous 4 _ Susan Hellauer, Marsha Genensky and Johanna Maria
Rose _ convened for an audition at St. Michael's Church on the
Upper West Side of Manhattan, where the group, as ensemble in
residence, has presented an annual concert series since its
founding in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   In that year, Ms. Rose was inspired by a workshop in medieval
culture at Holy Cross Monastery in Poughkeepsie, N.Y., to
experiment with women's voices in medieval music, an area then
dominated by men. She teamed up with other singers, including Ms.
Hellauer and Ms. Genensky, to form Anonymous 4, taking its name, in
eggheaded jest, from an unsigned medieval treatise describing
musical practice at the Cathedral of Notre Dame in Paris around
1200.
</P>
<P>
   Thus began an intense, slow-cooking process of forging a
singular sound that critics have ecstatically praised, notable
especially for a unison so precise that it sounds positively
supernatural. This uncommon accord is rooted in a spiritual unison,
achieved through hard-won consensus.
</P>
<P>
   ``We practice a lot,'' said Ms. Hellauer, a wry, no-nonsense New
Yorker. ``Even back in the days when we were doing four concerts a
year. ...''
</P>
<P>
   ``We rehearsed as if we were doing 80,'' Ms. Rose chimed in,
blissfully unaware that she, like her companions, habitually
completes the others' sentences. ``And in rehearsal, we take time
to try everyone's ideas and every possibility. With four very
strong personalities, that takes a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Genensky, a sprightly, meticulous Californian, picked up the
thread: ``You might call it the obsessive-compulsive approach.''
</P>
<P>
   Until signing with a major management firm in 1993, the group
handled its own bookings and publicity. The members still share
administrative tasks. Ms. Hellauer, a formidable musicologist, does
most of the musical research and translates Latin texts.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Genensky and Ms. Rose deal with literary research _ the
quartet often incorporates contemporary readings into its musical
programs _ as well as with the group's manager and publicity agent.
Ms. Cunningham was responsible for the printed programs and travel
arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   All this micromanagement has apparently paid off, for by now the
singers are anything but anonymous. By 1992, they were able to quit
their day jobs and jettison their pickup gigs. Their first
recording, ``An English Ladymass,'' also for Harmonia Mundi, was
named classical disk of the year by CD Review in 1993, and it clung
tenaciously to Billboard's classical top 10 chart for almost two
years.
</P>
<P>
   The group now boasts a repertory of a dozen programs, developing
a new one each season. It spends four months of the year on the
road, singing some 70 concerts.
</P>
<P>
   On that May afternoon, Anonymous 4 welcomed a hopeful singer for
her second audition, a pure lyric soprano whose spectacular musical
skills have made her familiar on New York's freelance vocal scene.
The audition took the form of a full-fledged rehearsal, with the
candidate tossed into a torrent of chant and polyphony to sink or
swim.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hellauer first sat in a pew to listen, while the two other
veterans joined the candidate in the sanctuary, testing different
voicings and configurations. Ms. Hellauer gave pitches on a tiny
Casio keyboard and recorded the results on digital tape. After her
three colleagues tore through a motet, she offered comments ranging
from the purely technical (``The tuning is great, the blend not so
great'') to the poetic (``Make the duplets and triplets more
elastic than metrical, not like lazy Schumann triplets'') or the
outlandish (``Make it more like a Viking funeral'').
</P>
<P>
   To a listener accustomed to Anonymous 4's fabled blend, it was a
shock to discover how disparate the singers' voices really are, and
how closely they mirror their personalities.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rose's dusky soprano and Ms. Genensky's silvery one are
counterweights, and Ms. Hellauer's solid alto serves as anchor.
Clearly, their new fourth would have to be someone who was more
than a prodigious musician with a supple voice. She would have to
possess a sound, and a disposition, that could bridge the diversity
around her.
</P>
<P>
   By early June, the Anonymous 4 singers were in decision-making
mode, huddled over lattes at a favorite haunt on the Upper West
Side. ``We've been agonizing over this,'' said the quietly
smoldering Ms. Rose.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've analyzed it to death,'' Ms. Genensky said in another of
those rapidly circulating conversations. ``Now we have to go with
our gut feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   MS. ROSE: It boils down to which color we want to go toward. We
had goose-bump moments with each candidate, but in different
pieces. We could choose any one of them. Each person would bring in
her own color, and we found ourselves adjusting.
</P>
<P>
   MS. HELLAUER: The bottom line is, what did it feel like to sing
with that person?
</P>
<P>
   MS. GENENSKY: And what will it feel like to be stuck in an
airport layover with her?
</P>
<P>
   MS. ROSE: What will it feel like after the fifth hour in the
rental car?
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, back at St. Michael's, the women of Anonymous
4 giddily introduced the newest member, Jacqueline Horner. Ms.
Horner, a petite, saucer-eyed native of Belfast, Northern Ireland,
pounded London cobblestones as a freelancer until two years ago,
when fate, in the form of a green-card lottery, sent her to New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours of her anointing, Ms. Horner was deluged with sheet
music and CD's. Recently, on the verge of her eighth rehearsal, she
had already weathered powwows with the group's manager, publicist
and photographer as well as a group excursion to Bloomingdale's to
hunt for new concert frocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's causing us all to re-evaluate our own singing,'' Ms.
Genensky said. ``I'd call our new sound rich but light, with depth
yet float. We're happy not to lose our ethereal sound, but now
there could be some moments of sexiness, which is especially nice
for the Hildegard program we're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   If her colleagues gush like blushing brides, Ms. Horner sounds
as if she were taking a veil of another sort. ``Of course, there is
some fear of the unknown,'' she said. ``I am giving up the
familiar, but it feels so right, so clear.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Horner might well tremble, with Anonymous 4 plunging into a
full schedule of European and American tours as well as concerts at
St. Michael's and the Metropolitan Museum of Art. For now, she is
singing the parts vacated by Ms. Cunningham, but after
experimentation the singers may revoice some numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Between tours, the reconstituted group will tackle its first new
project, a program of music by Francesco Landini, a 14th-century
Italian poet and composer, scheduled for a European tour next May.
By then, Ms. Horner will have six programs under her belt.
</P>
<P>
   ``My aim is to make everything as easy as possible for them, not
to cause a great tidal wave,'' she said. ``To a longtime
freelancer, it's a luxury to not have to scatter my energies, to
work in such detail, to focus in with colleagues I can grow and
develop with.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides, I like touring. I love hotels.''
</P>
<P>
   It may be worth checking back with her on that point in a year
or two.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
