<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 22:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7053 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN     09-15 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRICE IS RIGHT AS BRUINS FULLBACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Sunday-evening conversation turned immediately
to Durell Price's mind and body. Price, UCLA's junior fullback,
described to his mother, Debbie, an exhaustion so complete he had
spent much of the day on the couch. He felt stiff and sore and
spent _ and he felt great.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm exhausted,'' he told her. ``But it's the exhaustion I
want.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the exhaustion of contribution, of six carries and two
catches and countless blocks in the Bruins' 49-31 victory over
Texas on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   It was the exhaustion of Price's first career start, which might
sound surprising considering his college prospects looked bright
after his senior season at Sylmar High.
</P>
<P>
   One minute, he's bound for Ohio State. The next _ after a
facsimile mix-up nullified his letter of intent _ he reconsiders
and signs with UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   One minute he's a tailback. Twenty pounds later, he's a
fullback.
</P>
<P>
   One minute he's planning to redshirt during the 1998 season. A
few bug bites later, he's starting in front of 73,000 in the Rose
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``People ask me why Durell hasn't panned out,'' said Bruins
assistant Gary Bernardi, who recruited Price to Westwood. ``I tell
them it's not that, it's just he hasn't had the chance the other
kids have.''
</P>
<P>
   Until now. Until Craig Walendy's allergic reaction to mysterious
bug bites shelved his training camp and thrust Price into the
starting role. Now, after converting four short-yardage runs into
first downs, after catching two passes for 11 yards and blocking
like a pulling guard, Price believes he's here to stay.
</P>
<P>
   Walendy returns to practice this week after a month of
spectating. Once he's ready for competition, he'll get plenty of
it. Fullback shy for years, the Bruins now must make room for two
in their tailback-oriented offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key to coaching is to do things the players do best,''
coach Bob Toledo said. ``We can do things with Durell that we
haven't done before.''
</P>
<P>
   Price rushed for 1,666 yards and 36 touchdowns as a Sylmar
senior in 1995, and his UCLA career began with a seamless
transition. In his second game, against Northeast Louisiana, he
rushed for 110 yards. He had good balance and vision, and he could
catch. He compensated for modest speed with size and strength, or
so it seemed.
</P>
<P>
   Against Pacific-10 competition _ and sometimes in practice _
Price seemed a step slow hitting the hole. Added weight accentuated
the problem and he started the '97 season behind Skip Hicks,
Jermaine Lewis and Keith Brown.
</P>
<P>
   He reluctantly moved to fullback and played sparingly behind
Walendy, a part-timer himself. With Hicks gaining 1,200 yards and
Cade McNown emerging as a pinpoint passer, the offense barely had
time for one fullback, much less two.
</P>
<P>
   Price returned from a midseason ankle injury and was left off
the travel squad to Stanford, initiating a heated post-practice
conversation with Bernardi. Price ranted for several minutes, then
listened as Bernardi explained the math: With a 60-man limit,
there's no room for a backup fullback who doesn't play special
teams.
</P>
<P>
   Price spent the weekend alone in his apartment, pondering the
present and questioning the future. He moped for weeks until
running-backs coach Skip Peete pulled him aside after a team
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me that if I played tailback, I'd never make it (in
the NFL),'' Price recalled. ``It really caught me off guard. He
explained that there are tailbacks faster than me and that there
are 1,000 people trying to play tailback.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `You need to bring something to the table that other
guys don't have.' He said I could play fullback but have tailback
speed and hands and running ability, and I'd be different. It would
increase my chances. That really hit home. I had never had anybody
look me in the eye and say, `You're not going to make it in the NFL
as a tailback.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Price was convinced of his future, but when would it begin? If
he redshirted in '98, he'd have two years remaining _ two years
without Walendy, two years as the only fullback in a system that
uses only one fullback.
</P>
<P>
   But when spring practice concluded, Toledo warned Price to make
the most of his summer. He had to give the coaches a reason to
redshirt him, and reporting out of shape was not it. Besides,
Toledo said, Walendy could get injured, or ill, or bitten by an
unknown insect.
</P>
<P>
   Price attacked the summer conditioning program as if he were
going to play, then learned of Walendy's illness the day he
reported for training camp. His reaction: ``Thank God I didn't take
the summer off.''
</P>
<P>
   About that, there is no dispute.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early on, it was tough for Durell when he realized tailback
wasn't his position,'' Toledo said. ``Until he bought into it, he
didn't give the effort he needed. But once he decided to be a
fullback, he worked hard. He sees the light.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-98 2237EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
