<SLUG> BC-U.N.-IRAQ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRAQI OFFICIAL CRITICIZES U.N. CHIEF OVER ROLE IN ARMS INSPECTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ A senior Iraqi official close to President
Saddam Hussein leveled an unusually direct attack on
Secretary-General Kofi Annan on Tuesday, apparently trying to draw
Annan into a growing confrontation over arms inspections.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq is on the verge of cutting off all cooperation with U.N.
inspectors and could either expel inspectors or force a situation
in which they would have to be withdrawn, ending years of
painstaking disarmament and raising questions about how Iraq can be
prevented from rearming.
</P>
<P>
   The crisis has demoralized the U.N. Special Commission, which is
responsible for dismantling Iraq's prohibited weapons and insuring
that Baghdad cannot build new ones.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq wants a restructuring of the paralyzed commission and more
initiatives by Annan, who met on Monday with representatives of the
five permanent members of the Security Council _ Britain, China,
France, Russia and the United States _ and this month's council
president, Hans Dahlgren of Sweden, to discuss a review of Iraqi
relations with the United Nations if and when cooperation resumes.
</P>
<P>
   In Baghdad on Tuesday, the Iraqi official, Hamed Youssef
Hummadi, an adviser in the president's office, said in an article
in an official newspaper, al-Qadissiya, that Annan had failed to
honor a promise the Iraqis said he made in February, ``which called
for ending the embargo imposed on Iraq.''
</P>
<P>
   Annan's agreement, reached in a meeting with Saddam in Baghdad,
opened formerly closed sites to inspectors, a requirement for
moving toward the end of inspections. But it did not promise an
automatic end to sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Annan is ``not enthusiastic'' about involving himself in this
crisis, at least not at this point, a Western diplomat said here
Tuesday. Diplomats say that it is impossible to know whether the
Iraqis really believe in their interpretation of events or are
merely trying to provoke reaction.
</P>
<P>
   Hummadi's comments reflected Iraqi annoyance with Annan's
insistence that Baghdad must reverse its decision, made on Aug. 5,
to stop on-site inspections, a clear violation of the
secretary-general's accord. Annan told diplomats from the Security
Council on Monday that he agrees with them that no review of
relations with Iraq can be conducted until the decision is
reversed.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Burleigh, the acting chief U.S. representative at the
United Nations, said in an interview Tuesday that if the Iraqis
wanted a comprehensive review of their relations with the United
Nations, that is exactly what they will get.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very comfortable about what the bottom line of that
review would be,'' Burleigh said.
</P>
<P>
   In Cairo, Egypt, another senior Iraqi official renewed the
attacks on U.N. inspectors Tuesday. Foreign Minister Mohammed Saeed
al-Sahaf, who is seeking support at a meeting of the Arab League,
said that Iraq had ``no confidence in the arms inspection committee
and in the policies of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Sahaf is expected to have some success in Cairo, because
attitudes have been hardening against sanctions and the problems
they are causing Iraqi civilians, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``We face a rising tide of anger in the streets in many Middle
Eastern cities, which our friendly countries in the region are
finding harder to control,'' said Phebe Marr, a historian of modern
Iraq at the Woodrow Wilson Center in Washington who has returned
from several months in the region.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-98 2240EDT &QL; 
