<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARKETS CONTINUE TO RISE AS DOW CLIMBS 79 POINTS
</P>
<P>
   Stocks rose for the third consecutive day. Traders and analysts
attributed the continued increases to optimism about a coordinated
approach to the global economic crises.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average gained 79.04 points, or 0.99
percent, to 8,024.39, its highest close this month. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index rose 7.96 points, to 1,037.68, and the
Nasdaq composite index gained 12.42 points, to 1,678.11.
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the 30-year Treasury bond increased to 5.25
percent, from 5.22 percent on Monday. Bellwether 30-year bond
yields have dropped about half a percentage point in the last two
months.
</P>
<P>
   PROSECUTION UPHELD IN INSIDER CASE
</P>
<P>
   A New York state court upheld the right of Robert Morgenthau,
the Manhattan district attorney, to prosecute insider-trading
cases. Defendants' lawyers called the ruling a dangerous
application of state law that could increase all stockbrokers'
liability.
</P>
<P>
   HEAD OF FCC RESPONDS TO CRITICS
</P>
<P>
   William Kennard, the chairman of the Federal Communications
Commission, lashed out at critics who have blamed his agency for
the problems plaguing the introduction of digital television
services. The FCC had decided to let the telecommunications
industry set the standards for high-definition television sets.
</P>
<P>
   TASK FORCE CALLS FOR BANK CHANGES
</P>
<P>
   A task force has recommended approval of mergers of large
Canadian banks and the easing of rules for foreign banks to operate
there as long as the public interest is protected.
</P>
<P>
   FUTURE OF AMERICAN HOME IMPROVES
</P>
<P>
   Things are starting to look up for American Home Products, which
has suffered product recalls, liability lawsuits and a weak drug
pipeline recently. But its proposed merger with Monsanto will make
the new company a pharmaceutical and agricultural giant. Analysts
also see signs of encouragement in American Home's bounty of new
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   A NEW ONLINE WOMEN'S SERVICE
</P>
<P>
   America Online is selling three of its women-oriented services
to a new venture formed by Geraldine Laybourne, the former head of
Walt Disney's cable unit and the former president of Nickelodeon.
She will develop them for a new women's service offered on America
Online.
</P>
<P>
   RETAIL SALES ROSE JUST 0.2 PERCENT IN AUGUST
</P>
<P>
   Retail sales rose two-tenths of a percent in August, less than
had been expected. Gains in apparel and furniture sales were offset
by a drop in auto sales. Retail sales at stores open at least a
year rose 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE OIL INDUSTRY, TALES OF WOE
</P>
<P>
   The world's energy-industry luminaries are in Houston for the
triennial meeting of the World Energy Council Congress, but despite
a lavish Texas-style welcome, they have little to cheer with oil
prices at about $14 a barrel.
</P>
<P>
   OLD DENVER AIRPORT'S NEW LIFE
</P>
<P>
   Three and one-half years after Denver's $5 billion new airport
drew the nation's attention, the old airport is grabbing back the
spotlight. A development project one-third the size of Manhattan is
taking shape at what once was known as Stapleton International, a
reflection of Denver's continuing economic boom.
</P>
<P>
   GROUP SEEKS NEW SLEEPWEAR RULES
</P>
<P>
   A coalition of consumer and fire prevention groups is seeking
tougher fire-protection standards for children's sleepwear. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
