<SLUG> BC-CRASH-RDP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWISSAIR 111 BLACK BOXES STOPPED WORKING 6 MINUTES BEFORE IMPACT  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANTHONY DePALMA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALIFAX, Nova Scotia _ Both ``black boxes'' recovered from the
wreckage of Swissair Flight 111 stopped recording about six minutes
before the jet crashed into the ocean, investigators said on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The failure in the final minutes of the flight of both the
cockpit voice recorder and the flight data recorder leaves
investigators with no way of knowing exactly what the pilots said
or did as they frantically tried to keep the aircraft from plunging
into the ocean, about five miles off Peggy's Cove, a fishing
village near here, on Sept. 2.
</P>
<P>
   But investigators at the Transportation Safety Board of Canada
said that they had ``significant information'' about how the
emergency on board the MD-11 jet developed before the failure of
the recorders that would help determine what caused the crash.
</P>
<P>
   Although the safety board did not announce the simultaneous
failures of the recorders until Tuesday afternoon, officials had
hinted in the last few days that it was very likely that both had
stopped working at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   The flight data recorder was recovered on Sept. 6. The Swissair
MD-11 had one of the most sophisticated data recorders available,
capable of tracking technical data on hundreds of aspects of the
flight. The voice recorder, recovered Friday, contained a closed
loop tape that recorded 30 minutes of the pilots' conversations.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators are looking at the possibility that the jet's
electric system, or parts of the system, failed, which could partly
explain why some instruments on the jet emitted increasingly
unreliable information before stopping completely. The simultaneous
failure of both recorders would strengthen the suspicion that the
jet suffered a devastating electrical breakdown.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators know from the pilots' conversation with air
traffic controllers that the cockpit filled with smoke before the
crash. And they have recovered some bits of wreckage that indicate
something had caused enough heat to scorch parts of the cockpit.
</P>
<P>
   John Maxwell, director of air investigations for the Canadian
board, said at a briefing on Saturday that it would be wrong to
conclude that the absence of information about the final six
minutes of the flight on both recorders would stymie investigators.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many reports have been suggesting that we would be in somewhat
desperate straits without the last six minutes, but that is
certainly not the case,'' Maxwell said. He added that the problems
that caused the emergency were evident well before the last six
minutes of the flight.
</P>
<P>
   The Transportation Safety Board said that the false signals
picked up by the data recorder before it stopped operating were
being investigated by an international team of experts. The
information on the recorder is confusing and could take weeks to
decipher, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   But to pursue the investigation further, officials said, it will
be necessary to take apart and study the wiring and components of
the MD-11 that are lying in badly damaged pieces on the ocean
floor.
</P>
<P>
   American and Canadian divers have been working the frigid waters
of the Atlantic to retrieve the human remains of the 229 victims.
Once that work is substantially completed, the USS Grapple, a
specially equipped heavy salvage ship with a 300-ton-capacity
crane, will be able to hoist up the large pieces of fuselage so
that they can be brought ashore for study.
</P>
<P>
   The Grapple has been moored in place over the site since Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
