<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USCNOTE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRATCHARD MIGHT START
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Former Canyon High lineman David Pratchard was
USC's No.3 center three days ago, but he might be the Trojans'
starter against Oregon State.
</P>
<P>
   Pratchard moved up the depth chart because starting center Matt
McShane injured his knee Tuesday and had to be carted off the
field. McShane's injury was not determined by Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows? He sprained his knee,'' USC coach Paul Hackett
said. ``It's too early to tell. I didn't see it. I think he just
twisted it. In 48 hours, we'll know.''
</P>
<P>
   USC is already missing its other top center, Eric Denmon, who
sprained his knee against San Diego State and is out this week.
This opens up an opportunity for Pratchard, who practiced sparingly
at center last season but has primarily been a guard. The biggest
obstacle facing USC will be getting Pratchard comfortable snapping
the ball to quarterbacks Mike Van Raaphorst and Carson Palmer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even today, we had a couple problems at first during the run
drill,'' Pratchard said. ``But then you start getting used to the
quarterbacks and it's no problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Left guard Jason Grain also worked out at center Tuesday, and
left tackle Brent McCaffrey is the emergency No. 5 snapper.
</P>
<P>
   It's all reminiscent of Hackett's first tenure at USC, when
injuries forced the Trojans to use sixth-string center Ray Peters
in a 20-7 loss to Arizona State that cost USC an undefeated season.
Quarterback Paul McDonald fumbled six snaps and lost four.
</P>
<P>
   __ Abrams not discouraged: Kicker Adam Abrams has tried to put
his 0-for-3 performance against San Diego State behind him,
something that might not have been so easy the previous two
seasons, when his starting role was not so secure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I missed all three kicks by a yard each,'' Abrams said. ``I'm
hitting the ball solid. I just didn't do my job on Saturday.''
</P>
<P>
   Abrams made 12 straight field goals before his hat trick last
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this was maybe a situation where maybe he outthought
himself,'' Hackett said. ``I don't think we have a kicker
controversy. He just has to settle down. We'll continue to kick
field goals.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year's backup kicker, Adam Rendon, remains suspended with
almost no hope of returning to the team.
</P>
<P>
   __ Limited playbook: If USC's offense appears a little on the
plain side, there's a reason. Hackett said the Trojans are using no
more than 30 percent of his playbook, terming the offense
``vanilla.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're probably comfortable with 25-30 percent. At Irvine, we
put a huge burden on them because we introduced them to two years
of football,'' Hackett said. ``How it unfolds depends on the
maturity and development of the offense. I think the offensive line
and the tight ends, we need to be very conscious of them and build
slowly.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing Hackett said he would like to do is throw the ball
deep more often, especially with wide receiver R. Jay Soward
playing again.
</P>
<P>
   __ No favors: Oregon State coach Mike Riley had a request for
his former pupil, Soward, on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you think you can skip this one?'' Riley asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't do that. I have to do what you taught me,'' Soward
replied.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
