CLINTON-ASSESS) 
(sw) 
 By JAMES BENNET and ALISON MITCHELL    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton hired a raft of fresh advisers
and dispatched his top aides to placate congressional Democrats on
Tuesday, as members of the House Judiciary Committee bickered over
whether to release a videotape of his grand jury testimony about
Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   House Democrats accused Republicans of needlessly rushing to
release embarrassing television images of the president, but the
Republicans, who have the votes in the Judiciary Committee to force
the disclosure, argued that the testimony would help the public
judge whether the president had lied under oath.
</P>
<P>
   That question _ whether the president lied and whether he is now
trying to dodge behind a wall of legalistic language _ continued to
bedevil him, as several House and Senate Democrats angrily
criticized the White House in private meetings on Tuesday. Erskine
Bowles, the chief of staff, and other top aides tried to reassure
the congressional Democrats that Clinton was not resorting to
thinly sliced legal distinctions in rebuffing accusations of
perjury by Kenneth Starr, the Whitewater independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of the meeting with Senate Democrats, which took
place over a caucus lunch, Sen. Joseph Biden of Delaware declared
that some Democrats believed that the party would be better off in
the fall elections if Clinton resigned, one person who was present
said. This person said that Biden added that he did not necessarily
agree with that view but that regardless Clinton would not resign,
so the Democrats should accept reality and make the best of it.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement released by Biden on Tuesday evening, he said:
``I did not say the president should resign. I did not say the
country would be better off if he resigned. I do not think he will
resign.'''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Clinton should be worried that renegade Democrats might
call for Clinton to resign, Sen. Bob Kerrey, D-Neb., said: ``They
should worry.''
</P>
<P>
   In a series of television appearances on Sunday, Clinton's
lawyers insisted that the president had not lied under oath in
denying a sexual relationship with Ms. Lewinsky, but many Democrats
as well as Republicans dismissed their remarks as finely nuanced
nonsense.
</P>
<P>
   Kerrey said that Bowles repeated the White House message of
recent days _ that the president had made a terrible mistake and
was sorry. But Kerrey continued to express concern that the White
House was relying on distinctions that would be lost on most
voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``There might be a necessity to make a legal case,'' he said,
``but his most difficult case is the political case.'' That was a
reference to the possibility of impeachment proceedings in the
House.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the private meetings, the White House took other
steps on Tuesday to try to put its relationship with Capitol Hill
on a firmer footing. It announced that Clinton had hired Gregory
Craig, director of policy planning at the State Department, to
serve as special counsel coordinating the reponse to Congress over
the Lewinsky matter. Clinton also brought back two former
legislative aides, Steve Ricchetti and Susan Brophy, as senior
advisers.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans had their own disagreements on Tuesday. In the
Senate Republican lunch, according to several lawmakers, Sen. Trent
Lott of Mississippi, the majority leader, and half a dozen
Republicans suggested that Sen. Orrin Hatch of Utah, chairman of
the Senate Judiciary Committee, was being too conciliatory toward
the president and too public.
</P>
<P>
   After the lunch, Hatch, said, ``Does everyone agree with
everything I've said? No. Many people feel I've been too fair.
We've got to let the House work its wheel. I've been saying that.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Frank Murkowski, R-Alaska, disclosed on Tuesday that Starr
had spent $4.4 million investigating Clinton's relationship with
Ms. Lewinsky. He introduced a resolution demanding that Clinton pay
that cost.
</P>
<P>
   Mike McCurry, the White House press secretary, said that the
president did not owe the taxpayers that money, but added that if
there was a ``serious effort'' to pass along a bill ``we'll
consider it when the time comes.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's advisers expressed concern about the release of his
videotaped testimony. The Judiciary Committee may meet on Thursday,
and if it decides to release the tape, it could do so as early as
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has not reviewed the videotape, because Clinton
and his lawyers do not have a copy, White House officials said. But
one aide said that a tape of any person's hours-long grand jury
testimony would produce unflattering moments.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can imagine the way TV will play it, they'll pick a piece
of it and play it over and over and over again,'' the aide,
speaking on condition of anonymity, said. ``It's not a pleasant
thing to think about.''
</P>
<P>
   Only one camera filmed the testimony, so the prosecutors are not
shown. Clinton's advisers have said that he became quite angry and
even erupted at a couple of points during the questioning, which
was often confrontational. Clinton's allies in the White House and
on Capitol Hill are concerned that television news programs will
show the displays of anger without first showing the many minutes
of questioning that preceded them.
</P>
<P>
   The videotape will also show Clinton repeatedly refusing to
answer some questions and offering carefully calibrated answers to
others, according to descriptions of his testimony in Starr's
report.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Craig's appointment as special counsel is likely to result in a
lower-profile role for David Kendall, the president's private
lawyer, whose tight control of information has often angered the
president's other advisers. Several aides blamed Kendall's
appearance on an ABC news program Sunday for angering congressional
Democrats about legal dodges.
</P>
<P>
   Craig will report directly to the president, relieving John
Podesta, the deputy chief of staff, of day-to-day responsibility
for fending off impeachment hearings in the House, and, should the
hearings begin, impeachment itself.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Lockhart, a White House spokesman, said that it was
appropriate bring a new defense team onto the White House payroll.
``This is a constitutional process in which the House is
considering some serious issues,'' he said, ``and the office of the
presidency has an obligation to work closely with the House as they
move through this process and to defend the prerogatives of the
office of the president.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Clinton's aides continued the politically delicate task of
describing the president's mistakes in lacerating terms while
defending him from congressional criticism. McCurry, the White
House press secretary, insisted that Clinton was not resorting to a
legalistic defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't think of anything that is more profound than the
president admitting a mortal sin, asking for forgiveness, saying
how he has wronged people,'' he said. ``If anything, he has
confessed to far worse than the narrow legal question his lawyers
were being asked.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meetings with Democrats on Capitol Hill, White House
aides got an earful about the legal tactics employed so far. After
meeting over a caucus lunch with senators, they gathered for an
hour in a basement meeting room with two dozen centrist Democrats,
and then with a group of House leaders in Minority Leader Dick
Gephardt's office. ``The leadership was a little tougher,'' said
one official who attended both meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Robert Menendez, D-N.J., said that one message the
congressmen delivered on Tuesday was that, ``In terms of the public
discussion, the average American does not understand the legalisms
and doesn't view them as being forthright.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said that the members also urged the White House not to
cave in to the Republicans over health care, education, and Social
Security.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid reporters, most Democratic senators slipped out a side
door from their meeting. Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan of New York
said that the overall message was ``let's stand up and get through
this. There was no suggestion that we were not in any difficulty.''
</P>
<P>
   At the White House on Tuesday morning, Clinton's senior aides
received some reassuring news in a meeting with pollsters and other
outside advisers. Three Democratic pollsters _ Mark Mellman, Geoff
Garin and Mark Penn _ told the group that there was no evidence
that Clinton's troubles would suppress Democratic turnout this
fall, people who were present said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, they said that some elements of the Democrats' loyal
base, including black voters, may be more likely to go to the polls
because of a perception that Clinton was unfairly under attack.
They also noted that Clinton's job approval ratings remained
strong, people who were present said.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting included Lloyd Cutler, the longtime Washington
lawyer, and Peter Kadzick, another Washington lawyer who is playing
an informal advisory role at the White House. One participant said
the group discussed how the White House should mount a defense as
the case moves to Congress. ``The consensus is that public opinion
is really going to drive this process now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Away from the meetings with White House officials, members of
Congress sparred on Tuesday over whether to release Clinton's
videotaped testimony. Rep. John Conyers Jr., D-Mich., who is the
ranking minority member of the Judiciary Committee, said that if
the Republicans were to force the disclosure they would
``jeopardize the process and demean our activity.''
</P>
<P>
   Conyers said that members who are not on the committee ``are
telling me strenuously that it would be a violation of the
bipartisan spirit if we were to let the video tape be released.''
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans said that the public ought to be able to judge
for itself whether Clinton was misleading. Rep. Edward Pease,
R-Ind., said, ``What I saw of the video deposition, I did not see
anything that we should withhold.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaker Newt Gingrich said on Tuesday that the House would not
formally adjourn this year, which would allow the Judiciary
Committee to keep working after the election.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
