<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS TRAVEL: COMPETING STRATEGIES; CROWDED SKIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (Duplication warning: Also filed in ``t'' category) 
(mk) 
 By JANE L. LEVERE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Singapore Airline and Delta Air Lines announced two differing
strategies to upgrade their long-haul in-flight service for
business travelers.
</P>
<P>
   Singapore Airlines, which wins frequent plaudits for its
service, is investing about $300 million to upgrade its first-,
business- and economy-class offerings. Delta, meanwhile, is totally
eliminating its first-class service and upgrading its
business-class service on trans-Atlantic, trans-Pacific and United
States-Brazil routes.
</P>
<P>
   Singapore Airlines' new services are being phased in over the
next 18 months on its long-haul fleet of 37 Boeing 747-400s. The
new first class will feature airport check-in at a special lounge
and a redesigned airplane cabin with 12 so-called mini-suites
equipped with seat-beds, power outlets for computers, retractable
desks and 14-inch video monitors; previously there were 16 seats in
first class. Passengers in this cabin will be able to dine when
they wish.
</P>
<P>
   Singapore Airlines' new business-class service will have seats
that the airline says are based on a first-class seat frame; the
cabin will have 58 seats, down from 65. Seats will also have
privacy dividers and power outlets. The new business-class food
service will also be available whenever passengers wish.
</P>
<P>
   Singapore Airlines' economy-class passengers will have upgraded
seats and will be offered champagne throughout flights.
</P>
<P>
   Delta's new business class, which will be introduced next
spring, will feature new seats, upgraded wine and food, and a
modern entertainment system. Delta is investing $125 million in its
new business-class cabins, which will be offered on its MD-11 and
Boeing 767-ER and 777 aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Choong Kong Cheong, deputy chairman and chief executive
officer of Singapore Airlines, said the carrier had opted to
upgrade all three of its in-flight cabins because ``Singapore's
passengers always expect the best from us.'' He added: ``We're
determined to stay ahead of the competition.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said Singapore Airlines had been planning these changes
for two years and that it would proceed with them, despite the
recent crisis in the Asian economy. ``We're a global airline,'' he
said. ``The Asian economy has affected Asian airlines quite badly,
but other airlines are in the pink of health. We're continuing to
upgrade our product and service because we can't afford to be left
behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Delta officials said they had chosen to entirely eliminate
international first-class service because the demand for business
class far exceeded that for first class. According to data released
by the carrier, in 1997 the intercontinental business-class market
grew four times faster than that for first class; it also said
there were seven times the number of passengers in the industry's
business-class market than in the first-class market.
</P>
<P>
   Pointing out that on many nonstop trans-Atlantic routes Delta
has no competitors, Stephan Egli, vice president of Delta's
Atlantic and Pacific business unit, predicted that travelers on
these routes who have to choose between Delta's business-class
service and one-stop, first-class service on another carrier might
well pick Delta for its greater convenience.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Buttrick, aviation analyst for Paine Webber, said, ``The
paying first-class customer is limited to a relatively narrow
number of markets, which is why we see different carriers coming
out at different ends of the spectrum.''
</P>
<P>
   900 Million by 2007
</P>
<P>
   The number of passengers on U.S. air carriers is expected to
jump by 50 percent in the next nine years, according to the
Federation of Travel Clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Citing projections from the Federal Aviation Administration,
Mark Brown, executive vice president of the travel club group, told
Reuters that airline ridership would reach 900 million by 2007.
</P>
<P>
   According to the American Automobile Association, there were 599
million passengers in 1997, a 34 percent increase from a decade
earlier.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
