u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-REDSOX-NYT &LR;      09-15 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-REDSOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX DROP YANKEES 9-4 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Yankees could write this one off to their desire
to have their starting pitchers well rested for the playoffs.
Manager Joe Torre, giving his starters an extra day of rest, used
the Kiddie Corps on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Or they could explain it away by saying they encountered an
aberration, Tim Wakefield, whose knuckleballs dipped and darted so
unpredictably that his own catcher could not catch two consecutive
pitches in the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   Whichever excuse is preferred, the Yankees lost another game,
this one a 9-4 decision to the Boston Red Sox, who are thankful for
small favors. The victory enabled the Red Sox to add a full game to
their wild-card lead for the first time since Aug. 25. A four-game
margin with 13 games to play looks a lot better to them than a
three-game lead.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Varitek, at 26 no senior citizen himself, served as a
one-man wrecking crew against the Yankees' young pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Jerzembeck, making his first major league start, threw a
second-inning pitch to Varitek that wound up in the right field
stands for a three-run home run. Jerzembeck's replacement, Mike
Buddie, threw a fourth-inning pitch to Varitek that wound up
colliding with the facing of the third tier of the right field
stands, a two-run home run.
</P>
<P>
   Varitek also was the victim of Wakefield's first-inning pitches,
one up and one down, that he could not control. But the catcher was
flawless thereafter, and so, for long enough, was Wakefield.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees had battered him for five runs in four innings last
week in Boston, but Wakefield fluttered his way through their
lineup for six innings Tuesday night, baffling them on three
singles. That they rapped four hits against him in the seventh,
including a three-run home run by Scott Brosius, proved to be
immaterial in the overall scheme of things.
</P>
<P>
   Jerzembeck should have lasted so long.
</P>
<P>
   The rookie right-hander, who pitched an inning of relief in his
major league debut on Aug. 8, retired the Red Sox in order in the
first inning and retired two of the first three batters in the
second.
</P>
<P>
   But with Nomar Garciaparra at second base on a single and a
stolen base, the rookie walked Damon Buford, and Varitek followed
with the first of his right field blasts.
</P>
<P>
   Jerzembeck did not survive the third inning. Darren Lewis led
off with a single, went to second on a wild pitch and scored as
John Valentin singled. A groundout and a balk moved Valentin to
third, and a walk to Garciaparra sent Jerzembeck to the showers.
</P>
<P>
   Buddie, a more experienced member of the Kiddie Corps (two
starts, 20 relief appearances), entered the game and allowed
Valentin to score on a sacrifice fly, but his more critical
contribution to the Red Sox victory came in the fourth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Buford began the inning with a single to left field, and Varitek
instantly showed that he was an equal opportunity slugger. Bringing
a total of five home runs and 26 runs batted in into the game,
Varitek hit his second home run of the game, the pair accounting
for nearly one-fifth of that pre-game RBI total.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Yankees were able to zero in on Wakefield's
knuckleball, the Red Sox added another pair of runs in the seventh
inning on three singles against a member of the older generation of
Yankees pitchers, Mike Stanton. Mo Vaughn drove in the runs with
the third single.
</P>
<P>
   This was not what Tino Martinez had in mind when he talked
before the game about the Yankees' late-season skid, which has
resulted in a 12-15 record in the last four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody's too concerned about anything right
now,'' Martinez said. ``If it was a couple days or a day before the
playoffs, maybe we'd be concerned, but we have plenty of time to
get things in order, get right and get ready for the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   The skid, however, has made it virtually impossible for the
Yankees to break the major league record for most victories in a
season. With a 104-45 record, the Yankees would have to win all of
their remaining 13 games to surpass the 116-victory total of the
1906 Chicago Cubs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
