<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 23:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7139 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WENATCHEE-NEWTRIAL-SP     09-15 1224
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WENATCHEE-NEWTRIAL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH COURT FREES TWO MORE WENATCHEE CHILD SEX DEFENDANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANDREW SCHNEIDER  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The convictions of Harold and Idella Everett, among the most
controversial of the Wenatchee child sex-abuse cases, were thrown
out Tuesday by a Washington State appeals court.
</P>
<P>
   The court ruled that Wenatchee Police Detective Bob Perez used
intimidation and false information to get the couple to say they
had raped and molested their children.
</P>
<P>
   The three-judge panel also ruled that Perez and state Child
Protective Services workers used improper methods to obtain
accusations from the Everett's children.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal had been pending for more than a year. Idella learned
of the court's decision exactly 24 hours after she had completed
her sentence and had walked through the prison doors as a free
woman.
</P>
<P>
   She stood in the front yard of a small house where she'd spent
her first day of freedom and screamed with joy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter when the decision came, as long as it
came,'' the 45-year-old woman said minutes after receiving word.
``Now Harold has a chance to get his freedom and that's
wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   With tears streaming down her cheeks, she added: ``The real
important thing is that we can get our names cleared and we can
prove to everyone that we're not the sex fiends that Perez said we
were. That's real, real, real important.''
</P>
<P>
   Harold, who is 69 and in poor health, is being held in a prison
near Spokane. He has two decades remaining on his 23-year-sentence.
</P>
<P>
   The Everetts and 43 others were charged with 29,726 counts of
child rape and molestation during the controversial Wenatchee
investigations of 1994 and 1995. Their cases are especially
significant because their daughters, Donna and Melinda, were the
principle accusers in most of the cases. The fact that CPS allowed
Perez to act as the girls' foster father while he developed the
sex-abuse cases has raised additional questions about the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The couple's lawyers, Robert Van Siclen and Kathryn Russell,
wasted no time filing motions on their behalf.
</P>
<P>
   As Russell produced papers to get Harold quickly released, Van
Siclen was trying to ensure police in the small town where Idella
is staying don't publicly notify residents that she had been
convicted of a sex crime. Officials and lawyers have asked that the
town not be identified by news media.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be very unfair to tar her with that label because
she's no longer a convicted offender,'' Van Siclen said. ``The
appellate court ordered a withdrawal of the guilty pleas, so there
is no longer a conviction.''
</P>
<P>
   The path to Tuesday's ruling was torturous. Last December, the
appeals court agreed to examine the couple's request to withdraw
their guilty pleas and for a new trial, but said it needed more
information.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman County Superior Court Judge Wallis Friel was asked to
hold a rare fact-finding hearing. In a six-day hearing in April,
Friel was unflappable in keeping order and getting at facts as the
Everetts, their children, Perez, CPS workers and a dozen others
told their versions of what happened in Wenatchee.
</P>
<P>
   Friel submitted to the court a 64-page report that did not mince
words. He concluded the Everetts ``probably would not be found
guilty if tried again'' on more then 6,000 charges of child rape
and molestation.
</P>
<P>
   In their decision, the Division 3 Appeals Court judges in
Spokane _ John Schultheis, Frank Kurtz and Kenneth Kato _ echoed
most of Friel's findings, saying that:
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)``The evidence of Detective Perez's tactics is sufficient
on its face to support a finding of impropriety. Based upon our
common life experience, we know that type of conduct has the
potential of eliciting inaccurate and untruthful responses.''
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Melinda's 1996 recantation of her acusations was
``believable.'' She had said she was forced by Perez and CPS
workers to accuse her parents and other adults of sexual abuse.
They questioned the impact of the state's control on the child and
the fact that her stories changed while she was in state custody.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Statements from Melinda and the other children ``were
obtained by the state's use of improper interrogation techniques
including pressuring the children into accusing their parents and
others and lying to the children about what other witnesses had
said regarding the abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``No rational trier of fact would believe the children's
allegations,'' the decision said.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Several factors would support suppression of Idella's
confession if she were allowed to withdraw her guilty plea.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is in poor health, illiterate, low-functioning, in the
range of mild retardation, and quite naive. She initially denied
the allegations, but was bullied by Detective Perez, who repeatedly
stated she did it because her children said she did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Idella believed she could go home if she confessed, and that
if she did not, something would happen to her children ... Improper
interview techniques undermines the reliability of ... the
children's statements and Idella's confession.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision, Van Siclen said, ``shows that there are problems
in all of Wenatchee sex cases, and it should make it easier for
those still in prison because of this (investigatorial) misconduct
to get a chance at a new trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court of appeals has shown that it understands what
happened in Wenatchee and how justice system failed.''
</P>
<P>
   Chelan County Prosecutor Gary Riesen now has to decide whether
he will file new charges against the couple or allow Harold to go
free.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the prosecution has the courage now to accept the court
of appeals' decision and stop wasting state resources trying to
keep these innocent people in jail,'' said Russell, who wrote the
appeal with Van Siclen.
</P>
<P>
   Riesen did not return calls to his office for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Idella said the couple's ordeal won't be over until Riesen
announces his decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to get on with our lives. We knew that Perez was bad
and it's great that the court knows it too. But I want it all
behind us,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She said she hadn't spoken to her daughters, who are now
teen-agers in state custody,``because the state won't let me.'' She
has no information regarding Donna but has heard that ``Melinda
isn't doing too good ... She needs a mommy and I want her back.''
</P>
<P>
   She has no anger towards her girls because of their false
accusations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurt bad at first because I didn't understand it,'' she
said. ``Now I know it wasn't their fault, it was Bob Perez who
forced them to lie about everything. I just love them and I want it
all over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of all, I hope this decision can help those other people
still in prison who shouldn't be.''
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen people convicted in relation to the Wenatchee sex-abuse
investigations remain in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Two defendants, Carol and Mark Doggett, were previously ordered
released by a higher court and are awaiting a decision by Riesen on
whether they will face new charges. Several other cases have also
been overturned on appeal.
</P>
<P>
   For those still in prison, more than 50 lawyers, many of them
experts in appellate law, have joined with the University of
Washington's Innocence Project to try to win new trials.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
