<SLUG> BC-NY-ROCKEFELLER-CENTER-245&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCALED-BACK PLAN FOR ROCKEFELLER CENTER APPROVED 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MONTE WILLIAMS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Preservation officials approved a scaled-down plan on
Tuesday to expand the windows of Rockefeller Center's
boutique-sized shopfronts, allowing a compromise that they believe
will maintain the architectural spirit of the tourist magnet.
</P>
<P>
   The complex had sought to enlarge the boutique windows to two
stories and make several other changes to make it more attractive
to retailers. But after sharp criticism of the proposals,
Rockefeller Center officials modified their plans, reducing the
changes in scope and asking, for instance, that the boutique
windows be heightened by only 3 feet 3 inches.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the city's Landmarks Preservation Commission voted
overwhelmingly to approve the latest changes. Among the most
significant changes that were approved was the relocation of the
restaurant Savories so that the entrance to the concourse on the
north and south side of the statue of Prometheus can be enlarged.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, two smaller statues also sculpted by Paul Manship,
Maiden and Youth, will be moved from the plaza level to the Channel
Gardens. And the three square blocks of Rockefeller Center will be
repaved in bluestone and sandstone.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have always been circulation and retail problems at
Rockefeller Center, and our proposal will solve those problems,''
said Richard Metsky, an architect with Beyer Blinder Belle, a
Manhattan firm. ``We're going to make adjustments to draw people
into the complex, then down into the concourse.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Michael Gabellini, the project's other architect and the owner
of Gabellini Associates, another Manhattan firm, said the plan
would ``polish'' Rockefeller Center, yet keep all ``the scale,
proportion and majesty of the center.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, the chairman of the Landmarks Commission,
Jennifer Raab, called Rockefeller Center ``one of city's most
significant architectural treasures.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Changing this icon must be done with great care,'' she said.
``We are pleased that the owners responded to the commission's
concerns at the June public hearing and came back with a
scaled-back, more modest proposal. The approved plan emphasizes
simple, clean design while respecting the buildings' historic
materials and massing.''
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone was happy with the vote. Joyce Matz,
co-chairwoman of the Landmarks Committee of Community Board 5, said
she opposed the alteration to the Fifth Avenue windows. ``We wanted
to preserve the architectural integrity of this world-famous
landmark,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Matz said she was perturbed that she and other
preservationists were not heard before the vote. ``In a proposal
this significant there should have been more discussion,'' she
said. ``I'm not saying you should never alter a landmark, but the
character and uniqueness of the landmark should not be permanently
altered.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the other approved alterations, the aluminum flagpoles
that flank the sunken plaza _ which serves as an ice-skating rink
in winter and as an outdoor garden restaurant the rest of the time
_ will be changed to bronze ``to be consistent with the tone of
most of the metal in Rockefeller Center,'' said Steven Rubenstein,
a spokesman for the complex.
</P>
<P>
   A large metal-and-glass marquee at 30 Rockefeller Plaza, whose
primary tenant is NBC but which also houses the Rainbow Room, will
be permanently removed. ``It was put up in the '80s and is not
original to the center,'' Rubenstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Rockefeller Center's owners are in a consortium that includes
Goldman Sachs, Tishman Speyer, David Rockefeller, Troutlet
Investments and the Exor Group. Rubenstein said the owners always
expected some give and take with the Landmarks Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``They thought this was an ongoing process,'' he said. ``They're
excited about what this means for the center. At no time did they
want to compromise the landmark during their stewardship.''
</P>
</TEXT>
