<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ELECT-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN NEW YORK, SOME JUST HELD THEIR NOSES AND VOTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jean Mandel describes herself as cynical about a lot
of things, among them American politics in general and specifically
the report by Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr detailing President
Clinton's alleged sexual peccadillos.
</P>
<P>
   But it would take more than mere turmoil in Washington to keep
even a confirmed cynic like Ms. Mandel at home on Election Day. Ms.
Mandel, a 33-year-old freelance writer, marched straight to her
neighborhood polling place in Chelsea on Tuesday at lunchtime and
voted.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole disgusting Starr report makes me more cynical about
our larger cultural sickness,'' she said. ``But I'm not cynical
about voting. I'm not cynical about elections. And I'm not cynical
about the elected officials.''
</P>
<P>
   But whether it was cynicism in the aftermath of the release of
the Starr report or just plain indifference, many voters did not
share Ms. Mandel's determination to participate in the electoral
process. Tuesday's New York primaries, in fact, were noteworthy for
their low voter turnouts.
</P>
<P>
   Conversations with some of the no-show voters did not make a
clear case that the details of the president's liaisons with Monica
Lewinsky turned off large numbers of New Yorkers. Some said they
stayed away because they were bored by the largely somnolent
campaigns. Others said they were afflicted with garden-variety
political apathy unrelated to recent events.
</P>
<P>
   And it is evident that, for all the clamor they have created in
political circles, Clinton's troubles seemed little more than the
muffled rumble of faraway thunder to many of the New Yorkers who
did rouse themselves to vote on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always vote _ otherwise it gets worse,'' said Mike Grady, an
administrator with Met Life, who voted near his home in the Bronx
after work.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always get people who are easily turned on and turned off
by this or that thing,'' he added with a shrug. ``Then there are
the others, like me, who go and express their views no matter
what.''
</P>
<P>
   There is also a third category, as illustrated by the case of
Anthony Salimeni. The 32-year-old school-bus driver said he is
registered to vote but never does because, Lewinsky saga or not, no
politician is trustworthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``They always say one thing and do another,'' Salimeni said as
he sat on the steps of the Asser Levy Recreation Center at 501 East
23rd Street in Kips Bay, watching the steady procession of voters
going to the polling place inside. ``It's been going on hundreds of
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Kim Robertson, 32, a fashion photographer who spent the day
playing with her 2-year-old daughter, Drew, in Riverside Park, said
the past few months of watching the news out of Washington has
brought her around to Salimeni's point of view. She said she did
not vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so dishonest, politics, I'm turned off by all of it,''
she said. ``Clinton, Monica and Starr _ that was the final straw.''
</P>
<P>
   Florence Manness, voting at a polling place in the Peter Cooper
Village apartment complex, said she has a few friends who expressed
the same cynicism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't agree with what Clinton did, for sure,'' she said.
``But I vote just the same. I select those people who have some
degree of integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   For many like her, an election invokes a sense of obligation in
the civics-textbook sense of the word and, no matter what, they
vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father is a World War II veteran, and so everyone in my
family votes,'' said Martin Howard, 39, of the Bronx. ``People gave
their lives just so we could be here to vote.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that he is registered as a Conservative but that most of
his relatives were registered Democrats and they all voted Tuesday.
The controversy swirling around President Clinton could not tarnish
the electoral process in the eyes of his family or other voters,
Howard said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to matter one hill of beans,'' he said. ``It
might become an issue in November. But since it's not a
presidential election year, I doubt it.''
</P>
<P>
   Shirley McCain, a fund-raiser for AIDS programs who lives in
Stuyvesant Town, said she was fed up with both Republicans and
Democrats, but would not dream of staying away from the polls for
much the same reasons as Howard. ``Being black, I'm not going to
let anybody take that away from me,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Lewinsky matter has changed her outlook on the
elections. ``It will be interesting to see if people look at the
Republicans now as the great moral party,'' Ms. McCain said, adding
that personally she finds ``plenty of hypocrites'' in both parties.
</P>
<P>
   If the Lewinsky-Clinton story influenced Tuesday's voters at
all, it was to make some of them vote strategically. Ms. Mandel,
the Chelsea freelance writer, said she came out especially to vote
for Rep. Charles Schumer in the primary race for the U.S. Senate in
hopes he could beat Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, the Republican incumbent,
in the general election.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been a D'Amato fan,'' Ms. Mandel said. ``And with
presidential elections coming up, it's important to have a strong
Democratic presence in the Senate, especially because there is a
leadership crisis in the Democrats.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
