<HEADLINE>
BIG GAMES HAPPEN IN SMALL PLACES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ UCLA has played in several of the nation's most
renowned stadiums in recent years, from Michigan's Big House to
Nebraska's Memorial Stadium and Tennessee's towering Neyland
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend, the Bruins visit Robertson Stadium on Houston's
downtown campus. With a capacity of 20,500, it's little more than a
glorified high school facility. By comparison, the Pac-10's
smallest venue, Oregon State's Parker Stadium, holds 35,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's cozy,'' said Houston coach Kim Helton, whose team is
playing all its games at Robertson for the first time since 1949.
``It's easy to get to. It's good to be back.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins aren't so sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of a dismal atmosphere,'' UCLA coach Bob Toledo
said. ``We're used to playing in big stadiums. But the important
thing is to be ready to play anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   __ High praise: Quarterback Cade McNown, tailback Jermaine
Lewis, receiver Freddie Mitchell and linebacker Brendan Ayanbadejo
(two sacks) were obvious contributors against Texas. Who else
played well? Toledo named names:
</P>
<P>
   Inside linebacker Ramogi Huma, who led the team with eight
tackles.
</P>
<P>
   Receiver Danny Farmer, who was equally impressive with his
blocking as with his receiving (four catches, 81 yards).
</P>
<P>
   Defensive end Pete Holland, whose consistency serves as a model
for talented sophomore Kenyon Coleman.
</P>
<P>
   __ Same play, different result: Tailback Lewis' 7-yard touchdown
run came on the same off-tackle power play as his botched
fourth-and-1 attempt last year at Washington State.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of turning upfield before the hole developed, Lewis
stayed behind his blockers and eventually found a huge opening over
right tackle.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a difference a year makes and what a difference a play
makes,'' Lewis said. ``As soon as it went wrong (last year), the
coaches lodged it in my head not to do that again.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Odds and ends: Toledo awarded a scholarship to junior
fullback Mark Verti, a Rowland Heights native who was a walk-on in
1996 and 1997. Verti is one of UCLA's top special-teams
performers.... Mitchell was named Pac-10 Offensive Player of the
Week for his 233 all-purpose yards. That does not include a 34-yard
touchdown pass to Brian Poli-Dixon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
