<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-MAIN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Millwood wins 16th before heading to 'pen
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The Braves let Kevin Millwood make one more start
Tuesday night. In turn, he gave them something to remember him by.
</P>
<P>
   The best fifth starter a team could have, Millwood threw seven
shutout innings to pitch the Braves past Philadelphia 3-0, giving
Atlanta five wins in the last six games. Slated to move by week's
end to the bullpen, where he will spent the postseason, Millwood
improved to 16-8, having won five of his last seven decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Playing a watered-down lineup the night after clinching the
division, the Braves did all their scoring in the third, when Tyler
Green walked in two runs and Gerald Williams brought in the third
with a 45-foot single.
</P>
<P>
   Millwood hardly fooled the Phillies but he still threw seven
shutout innings before yielding to the bullpen. He allowed eight
hits _ three of them to Wendell Magee _ and three times let
Phillies leadoff men reach base but was able to control the damage.
</P>
<P>
   But he countered with the fastball. Of Millwood's first nine
strikeouts, six came after Phillies had reached base. In the fourth
and sixth innings after Philadelphia put men on first and second,
Millwood allowed just one ball to be put in play (a Bobby Estalella
foul-out) and recorded the rest of the outs with strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves got a 3-0 lead out of nowhere in the third inning,
when Phillies starter Tyler Green temporarily misplaced the strike
zone. After zipping through the first two innings and throwing 10
strikes in his first 11 pitches, Green was off the plate with 12 of
his next 14 in the third and allowed Atlanta to bat through the
order.
</P>
<P>
   Green should have escaped the inning with no damage when, with
one out and men on first and second, rookie George Lombard hit a
potential double-play ball to first. But Lombard displayed his
outstanding speed in beating Desi Relaford's throw to first and
Green proceeded to unravel.
</P>
<P>
   He first walked Greg Colbrunn on five pitches to load the bases,
walked Ryan Klesko on four pitches to bring in the first run and
then walked Javy Lopez on five pitches to force in a second run.
Gerald Williams next chopped a ball off the plate and outran third
baseman Scott Rolen's throw for an RBI on a single that went 45
feet, giving Atlanta a 3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-98 2314EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
