<HEADER>
A7211 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASHION-DKNY-COX     09-15 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-DKNY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Karan's cornucopia of colors suggests indecision
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Donna Karan assumed two curious stances Tuesday night
during the runway presentation of her spring/summer '99 DKNY
collection.
</P>
<P>
   The first came in her decision to sit, then squat, then stand
among the editors and buyers who'd come to the 14th floor of a
Hudson River warehouse to preview the collection for their
newspapers, magazines and stores.
</P>
<P>
   The second stance was Karan's choice of colors for the
collection. More accurately, DKNY showed an odd inability on the
designer's part to decide on a color scheme.
</P>
<P>
   Her loosely cut clam-diggers, her knee- to floor-length skirts,
her sheer pullovers and cardigans and her form-over-function rain
jackets were offered up in a range of 72 colors.
</P>
<P>
   Come next season, that could prove an equally daunting number of
choices _ for everyone but New Yorkers, that is. Notes provided to
the show's audience declared that this was ``A collection that
says, `New York City.''' But New Yorkers in general _ and fashion
critics in particular _ wear black.
</P>
<P>
   The closest anything in the DKNY collection came to black were
pieces in the shade Karan calls ``mud.'' The bulk of the collection
came either in white or shades Karan refers to as ``melon,''
``limeade,'' ``citron,'' ``cement'' and ``sorbet.''
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the collection didn't look nearly as marketable as the
new ``sexy and naive'' DKNY underwear that was unveiled for the
show's finale. The bras and panties looked stretchy, comfortable
and sturdy. The clothes looked fabulous, but far too fragile for
the active lifestyles women lead.
</P>
<P>
   The sweaters, with their complicated cowl necks, looked like
they were made of mist rather than fabric. The dresses and skirts
were see-through _ with or without a ``lining'' skirt worn
underneath them. And the wispy, hooded rain jackets looked about as
useful during a cloudburst as a Kleenex would be.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Karan approached next season's DKNY collection in the
spirit of experimentation. Then again, she should sit, squat or
stand out in public more often to remain in closer touch with what
regular women and the unapologetically trend-conscious alike want
to wear.
</P>
<P>
   Jones New York chief designer Robin Howe emerged from the
drawing room where she was sketching ideas for her fall/winter '99
collection just long enough to grab a heaping plate of food and to
offer assurance that her focus on realistic careerwear remains
intact.
</P>
<P>
   Such assurance was unnecessary since the evidence of Howe's
intent _ the sensible suits and separates coming from Jones New
York for spring/summer '99 _ hung on every square inch of her
labyrinthine showroom's walls.
</P>
<P>
   The extensive array of clothes Howe designed for next season
might be short on innovation, but working women will find much in
the collection that's both stylish and suitable for the office.
</P>
<P>
   The prevailing trends in color (gray, blue, mossy greens and
rich reds), shape (long, looser skirts and coats), patterns
(florals and strips) and pieces (jackets and sweater sets) are all
well represented in the collection. The shortest skirts coming from
Jones New York will graze the knee, but most of the skirt and dress
hemlines extended to the ankle. The best among them may be the
washed silk mock wrap skirt, which, as one staffer was overheard
observing, ``rules out worrying about the wind.''
</P>
<P>
   Adrienne Vittadini designs for the mature, moneyed woman are
always tasteful and always rendered in luxury fabrics, whether
they're considered the ``in'' thing or not.
</P>
<P>
   Vittadini's spring/summer '99 collection of contemporary style
casual classics is no exception. In it, she infuses healthy doses
of pale gray with the traditional warm weather color combinations
(navy and white, tan and cream, red and white). Much of what she
showed had a leisurely, yachting-life look. There were nautical
stripe sweaters, oversized windbreakers and short sailor pants. Her
dressier sweaters and shells were embroidered, loosely woven and
paired with Shantung silk Capri pants or A-line skirts. For
dressed-down occasions, she designed gray and white cashmere
separates that looked athletic and affluent.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a casual expression in the collections,'' Vittadini
said, ``but I also think it's quite chic.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
