<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 23:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7220 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-FRENCH-COLUMN-LAD     09-15 1206
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-FRENCH-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDIA GIANTS COULD SWALLOW UP BRITISH SOCCER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   First Manchester United. Then Arsenal. Then Liverpool,
Newcastle, Tottenham soon every soccer club in Britain could find
itself on media giants' shopping lists, a prospect that terrifies
fans of the beautiful game.
</P>
<P>
   Spurred by media tycoon Rupert Murdoch's $1.05 billion bid for
Manchester United, a move that has shaken the foundations of
English soccer, other companies are already seeking to get involved
in what they believe will be a lucrative enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   There's a lot of reasons to believe that: Soccer, especially in
Europe, has become a big-money enterprise, the product of satellite
and pay-per-view television and the big clubs' realization of the
cash that's theirs for the asking.
</P>
<P>
   Murdoch, who made the ManU offer through British Sky
Broadcasting (in which his News Corp. owns a controlling interest),
already owns the Dodgers and has been a major player in world
rugby. His television empire, of which BSkyB (which owns the rights
to broadcast the English Premier League through 2001) is only a
part, could disseminate England's No.1 club throughout the world,
reaping huge profits.
</P>
<P>
   It's too early to know whether or not the sale will go through.
U.S. investment bank Soloman Smith Barney confirmed that one of its
clients asked for information on the club, leading to talk that a
rival bid approaching $1.2 million would soon be made. And rumors
are that Interpublic Group of Cos., the planet's third-largest
advertising agency holding company, will bid for the team, although
it says it has ``no plans'' to do so. Manchester United's board of
directors, who have approved the Murdoch bid, say they legally
would have to listen to a higher offer.
</P>
<P>
   The British government is expected to investigate the offer
BSkyB's Premier League broadcast contract will be a starting point
and might refer the matter to the Monopolies and Mergers
Commission, which could lead to a drawn-out regulatory review.
United officials might prefer a rival bid to such an investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Murdoch, however, is close to Prime Minister Tony Blair; that
could pay off for him, even as United fans plead for government
intervention. They fear that Murdoch cares nothing for the club's
tradition and performance, just for its potential profits.
</P>
<P>
   Reigning champion Arsenal, meanwhile, is in talks with Carlton
Communications, one of Britain's largest TV and film companies; a
$464 million bid is expected.
</P>
<P>
   Granada, another TV company, has been rumored to be after
Liverpool, although the club's directors deny it. And Newcastle,
Aston Villa and even unfancied Sheffield United are being pursued.
</P>
<P>
   All this movement has sent stock prices soaring (Manchester
United is a publicly traded company; Arsenal is not). And if the
offers are approved, it could bode well for the proposed European
Super League, which is about nothing more so than money.
</P>
<P>
   And cash is what all of this is about. Soccer, like other
sports, has always revolved around the almighty dollar (or pound),
but that's often been obscured by the traditions of the game,
particularly in England, home to the sport's roots. Whether
Murdoch's, or any other company's, involvement is good or bad for
the game, it will alter the sport's landscape.
</P>
<P>
   __ A revolving door: The resignations last week by Germany's
Berti Vogts, Spain's Javier Clemente and Bulgaria's Hristo Bonev
leaves just 10 of the 32 men who guided teams into the World Cup
still on the job. That's how it works at soccer's highest levels
even winners don't last long but the past few months have been
murder on coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Vogts stepped down following a disappointing pair of games in
Malta, citing unceasing media pressure and wanting to maintain
``any remnants of dignity left over for me.'' It was a sad finish
for the man who was once one of Germany's greatest defenders, and
who guided the Germans to the European title just two years ago. He
was replaced by Erich Ribbeck after Jupp Heynckes (fired at Real
Madrid after winning the European Champions Cup in May) turned down
the job and after an offer to former star player Paul Breitner was
rescinded.
</P>
<P>
   Clemente, who failed to get Spain out of the first round of the
World Cup, resigned under pressure after the stunning 3-2 loss to
lowly Cyprus in a 2000 European Championship qualifier 11 days ago.
Luis Aragones declined the job when the Spanish federation wouldn't
give him the control he craved, and Jose Antonio Camacho is
expected to get the assignment.
</P>
<P>
   Bonev, who quit after a one-sided Euro loss to Poland, was
replaced by Dimitar Dimitrov. Other new hirings: Japan, Philippe
Troussier (South Africa's coach in France); Argentina, Marcelo
Bielsa; and Iran, Mansour Pourheidari.
</P>
<P>
   __ Corner kicks: One of the candidates for the vacant U.S.
national team coaching job might not be available for long. Former
U.S. coach Bora Milutinovic is negotiating to take charge in Costa
Rica, according to reports in the Central American country. Bora
took the Ticos to the second round of the 1990 World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   - The Orange County Zodiac's first ALeague playoff appearance
was a short one, but it generated one superb moment: Cerritos
native Eddie Soto dribbling through the Seattle Sounders' defense,
then rolling the ball under goalkeeper Dusty Hudock and into the
net. That bit of brilliance gave the Zodiac an early lead, but it
wouldn't last; the Sounders got goals from Peter Hattrup and Dick
McCormick, the last a 76th-minute penalty kick, to knock O.C. out.
</P>
<P>
   - Mia Hamm, who moved within one goal of 100 in the U.S. women's
team's 9-0 romp over Mexico in Saturday's U.S. Women's Cup opener,
has always had high standards, sometimes ridiculously so. Consider
her comments after scoring twice and assisting on four other goals
against the Mexicans: ``I think I struggled. I didn't think that I
was mentally focused. We had a hard week of practice, and I was
physically drained. That was my fault. I missed way too many
opportunities to put the ball away.'' She can make amends Friday
against Russia in Rochester, N.Y., and Sunday against Brazil in
Richmond, Va.
</P>
<P>
   - USC and UCLA's heated rivalry has carried over to women's
soccer, not in the least because of Troy's refusal (following
Pac-10 inter-conference transfer rules) to allow UCLA (and former
Trojan) defender Rhi Tanaka a fourth year of eligibility. But the
Bruins and Women of Troy will get together this weekend for a
superb pair of doubleheaders. No.11 Nebraska and 25th-ranked Baylor
are in town for USC's Fila Challenge. The action kicks off at
UCLA's Spaulding Field on Sunday, with USC taking on Baylor at 6
p.m. and the Bruins hooking up with the Cornhuskers at 8. On
Sunday, they head to the Coliseum and switch opponents, with UCLA
playing at 11 a.m. and the Women of Troy at 1 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   - The European Champions League kicks off today, and we get a
biggie: Inter Milan, with Ronaldo and Roberto Baggio, takes on
reigning champion Real Madrid, with Roberto Carlos and Davor Suker,
in a Group C clash at Seville. ESPN2 will carry the clash at 11:30
a.m.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
