<SLUG> BC-CT-ELECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN CONNECTICUT, DEMOCRATS GET THEIR BALANCED TICKET  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ Denise L. Nappier won the Democratic Party
nomination for Connecticut treasurer on Tuesday, much to the relief
of party leaders who had feared that without a minority candidate
like her, Democrats would wind up with an all-white slate in a year
that the Republican ticket includes three minority candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Nappier, who is black, seemed well aware of those concerns
as she spoke to a multiracial crowd at her victory party on Tuesday
night. ``What we have is a slate of candidates that reflects the
face of Connecticut,'' said Ms. Nappier, who is treasurer of the
City of Hartford. ``Ain't no stopping us now.''
</P>
<P>
   She defeated Frank A. Lecce, a securities broker from West
Hartford who outspent Ms. Nappier and won the support from some
old-guard Democratic leaders who objected to what they saw as a
quota system for the party's ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's other statewide race was between two state
representatives seeking the Democratic nomination for secretary of
the state. As of 10 p.m., Susan Bysiewicz of Middletown had a lead
over Ellen Scalettar of Woodbridge, who had been endorsed at the
party convention in July.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Nappier also had won the party's endorsement at the
convention, although by a narrow margin, but Lecce immediately
began working on the primary election. In fact, in both statewide
races, the candidates running without the party's endorsement
bought advertisements on television, while the two endorsed
candidates could not afford to, and instead depended on local
Democratic workers.
</P>
<P>
   The primary was open only to registered Democrats, who make up
about 700,000 of the state's approximately 2 million registered
voters.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic candidate for governor, Barbara B. Kennelly,
threw her support to Ms. Nappier after Gov. John Rowland began
boasting about the diversity of the Republicans' slate of statewide
candidates, which includes two African-American men and a Hispanic
woman.
</P>
<P>
   With some Democratic officials playing down the importance of a
racially diverse ticket, black leaders within the party formed a
Connecticut African-American Democratic Organization that they said
would stay in business to promote black candidates in the future.
The group's chairman, Maurice B. Mosley, a former state
representative from Waterbury, suggested on Tuesday the depth of
the rift that developed between black leaders and the party
establishment over the possibility of an all-white ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one ever gives up power _ you have to take it,'' Mosley
said. ``But we are at our best when we're down _ when we're
slapped, when we're kicked.''
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. William R. Dyson, a Democrat from New Haven who is
co-chairman of the Appropriations Committee, warned that without a
minority candidate on Mrs. Kennelly's ticket, ``She would not have
credibility with a large segment of the public.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said that members of many town committees had not agreed
with him about the gravity of the issue for the party. ``There is a
segment of the population that said, `We've been dwelling on this
long enough,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In campaign appearances, Ms. Nappier stressed her qualifications
and played down the issue of race. ``This is not a campaign about
black and white,'' she said. ``It's about green, and how to get
someone in office who will protect the state's assets and make them
grow.''
</P>
<P>
   Lecce said that he resented the need to constantly answer
questions about diversity on the ticket, noting that he had started
campaigning two years ago and that party leaders could have found
another slot for a black candidate. He told audiences how he had
immigrated from Italy at age 11, and bolstered the point by
displaying the Statue of Liberty on his campaign literature.
</P>
<P>
   In the race for the Secretary of the state nomination, Mrs.
Scalettar stressed her endorsement by leading state Democrats,
while Ms. Bysiewicz spent about $100,000 on television ads
featuring her family.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the two statewide contests, the other race that drew the
most attention and spending was a four-way contest for the
Democratic nomination to replace Mrs. Kennelly as the U.S.
representative from the 1st Congressional District, which covers
the Hartford area.
</P>
<P>
   In that race, John B. Larson, 50, a former president pro tem of
the state Senate, defeated his main competitor, Miles S. Rapoport
the secretary of the state.
</P>
<P>
   After what had been a low-key campaign, the two front-runners
engaged in a ferocious television battle last weekend. Rapoport,
48, accused Larson of voting to cut services and raise taxes when
he was in the state Senate. Larson said that the advertisements
were a gross distortion of his records. He took ads branding
Rapoport ``desperate.''
</P>
<P>
   Rapoport, who has built his career as an advocate of campaign
finance reform, defended his ads. ``A close race in the final days
_ you can't be so nice that you're undone,'' he said as he voted on
Tuesday morning. Rapoport offered a last-minute truce in the
television war. Larson, who had accused Rapoport of abandoning his
principles for expediency, refused the offer. ``That's like bombing
Pearl Harbor and then saying, `Oh, never mind,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rapoport won the endorsement of many labor unions, who helped
him field more than 1,000 poll workers and telephone canvassers
today. The other two candidates were James R. McCavanaugh, 58, a
16-year state representative, and Joseph M. Suggs Jr., 58, a former
state treasurer.
</P>
<P>
   The 1st District is strongly Democratic, so the winner of the
party's nomination generally is assured election in November. But a
Republican candidate, Kevin J. O'Connor, signaled that he planned a
scrappy campaign by buying television ads on Hartford newscasts on
Tuesday night, finishing with the slogan: ``You gotta believe.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-98 2325EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
