<SLUG> BC-FBC-TROJANS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIBSON GETS DEFENSIVE ABOUT CHALLENGES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE IRVINE  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Even David Gibson admits the temptation to run his
way should crawl into the mind of an opposing offensive
coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the slender Gibson of USC, a Mater Dei High graduate,
is a bit undersized - 6-foot-2, 215 pounds for his weakside
linebacker position. Sending a 300-pound lineman to block a
215-pounder seems to make pretty good sense.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Tollner and the San Diego State offense took that approach
on Saturday evening when the Aztecs visited the L.A. Coliseum. San
Diego State directed running back Jonas Lewis toward Gibson on the
Aztecs' first two offensive plays. The result was four yards and
the need for a new approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I proved to them early that I could make the play,''
Gibson said.
</P>
<P>
   If he didn't, then the final result certainly did. Gibson, who
is a junior, finished with eight solo tackles, three sacks, three
forced fumbles and a fumble recovery to earn Pac-10 Defensive
Player of the Week honors.
</P>
<P>
   This week's opposing head coach noticed.
</P>
<P>
   ``David Gibson is really playing good football for them,'' said
Oregon State coach Mike Reilly, whose team tangles with USC at the
Coliseum on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson's most spectacular play against San Diego State may have
been a five-yard sack of Brian Russell when Gibson missed the
initial tackle, quickly hopped up and chased Russell down before he
could reach the line of scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had the opportunity at a clean shot and missed,'' Gibson
said. ``There was no way I was letting the guy get away from me.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there was another five-yard sack of Russell when Gibson
leaped over an offensive lineman and got back in the backfield so
quickly that running back Larry Ned, in his haste to pick up the
blitz, knocked the ball out of Russell's hands. Gibson, who was
credited with the forced fumble, finished off the play by falling
on the loose ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just expect Gibby to make plays,'' middle linebacker Chris
Claiborne said. ``He brings to the (weakside) linebacker a lot of
speed. He's very tenacious. It would be terrible not having him on
the field all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibson started at the rover safety position in the 1997 season
opener against Florida State but was replaced as the starter by
Antuan Simmons during the next five games. He rarely saw the field
in two of those games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's weird,'' Gibson said. ``One game you're starting and
everybody's talking about you. The next game you're not even
playing. That's pretty tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibson came off the bench in the fifth week to make nine tackles
against Arizona State and followed that with a marvelous 13-tackle
performance in a win at Notre Dame. At that point, he became a
starter again and was selected as Pac-10 Defensive Player of the
Week after contributing nine tackles, three sacks and two forced
fumbles against Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   He finished the year with 66 tackles, a team-high 20 tackles for
loss and a Pac-10 best five forced fumbles.
</P>
<P>
   However, with the return of a healthy Grant Pearsall, who missed
last season with a knee injury, Gibson was slated to start the year
as a backup strong safety. A few days into the team's fall training
camp at UC Irvine, though, USC Paul Hackett realized, ``We needed
to get them both on the field at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   So Gibson, who is one of the team's biggest hitters, moved
closer to the line of scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fine with me,'' said Gibson. ``It was either split time
with Grant Pearsall or become a linebacker. To tell you the truth,
it's a good spot for me.''
</P>
<P>
   It was also a chance to spend more time at the training table.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked hard to stay slim as a safety,'' said Gibson, who
estimates he's added from 5-7 pounds since the position change.
``This allows me to eat more. I used to wake up and not eat
breakfast. Now, it's three meals a day. (Unfortunately) most of it
is in the mid-section.''
</P>
<P>
   Pearsall had to leave the Purdue game after twisting his knee in
the first quarter and hasn't been back on the field since. While
Ifeanyi Ohalete has filled in nicely at strong safety, Gibson, who
had five solo tackles, two assists and a key fumble recovery in the
victory over Purdue, has been a star at linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   ``David Gibson is going to make plays,'' linebacker coach Shawn
Slocum said, ``no matter what position he's at.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, he's happy to be playing linebacker and regularly
mixing it up with the big boys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can use my speed to get away from the lineman when I need
to,'' Gibson said. ``But I'm not afraid to come up and smack
someone in the mouth. When they're expecting me to run around them,
I'll come up and smack 'em. That is an advantage for me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-98 2326EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
