r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN     09-15 0531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELANGER MIGHT MISS UP TO SIX WEEKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ During last year's National Hockey League
preseason, the Los Angeles Kings were expecting to take a long look
at young winger Pavel Rosa, who they were hoping would be able to
step in and provide some spark to their offense.
</P>
<P>
   But Rosa suffered a concussion in an exhibition game, and it
wound up ruining his season.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings suffered a similar though less severe setback on their
third day of practice Tuesday, when they lost 20-year-old prospect
Eric Belanger, a fifth-round draft choice two years ago. Belanger,
a playmaking center, suffered a broken left hand that is expected
to sideline him for up to six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Belanger, one of a number of youngsters given a strong chance of
making the Kings' roster, had 51 points in 56 games last season
playing for Fredericton in the American Hockey League. The injury
occurred when Belanger jammed his hand into the midsection of
another player during practice.
</P>
<P>
   Also ailing are centers Jozef Stumpel (sprained ankle) and Jason
Morgan (knee tendinitis) and winger Dan Bylsma, who is recovering
from foot surgery. None are expected to play when the Kings open
the exhibition season with games against the Colorado Avalanche on
Saturday and Sunday in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   __ Rosy outlook: The good news for the Kings is that Rosa, 21,
appears to have put his post-concussion syndrome problems behind
him.
</P>
<P>
   Rosa, who the Kings are hoping will prove to be the natural
goal-scorer they need, had 63 goals and 153 points in his final
year of junior hockey two years ago. But last season, he played in
only three minor-league games, two of them with the Long Beach Ice
Dogs of the IHL.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard to not play hockey for so long,'' said Rosa, who
spent the summer working out in his native Czech Republic. ``I
played hockey for 15 years every day. I didn't want to stop, but I
had to stop. I thought about my health first.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Al Murray, the Kings' director of amateur scouting, ``I
have only seen Pavel Rosa be one of the elite players at every
level he's played at. I don't know if Pavel can play at the NHL
level (this year), but I'm not going to shortchange him. He's a
very focused, self-motivated individual who is used to succeeding,
and he doesn't expect anything less of himself than success.''
</P>
<P>
   __ At a standstill: There was no hint of progress Tuesday in
negotiations with the four unsigned Kings, defensemen Rob Blake and
Aki Berg, goalie Jamie Storr and enforcer Matt Johnson. Among the
Kings' offers to the latter three have been one-year deals with
10-percent raises, which would bump Berg's salary to $467,500,
Storr's to $605,000 and Johnson's to $440,000.
</P>
<P>
   Berg's agent, Larry Kelly of Ottawa, said late Tuesday afternoon
that it's almost certain his client will sign a contract to play
professionally in Europe, possibly late this week. Berg is
scheduled to fly to his native Finland today.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost definite in my mind,'' Kelly said. ``We're fed up.
It's unfortunate and absolutely unnecessary.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-98 2328EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980915.0501 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 23:34 </DATE_TIME>
