A7225 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN     09-15 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARTMAN HAS EMERGED FROM CAMPOS' SHADOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Kevin Hartman's emergence this season as one
of Major League Soccer's more capable goalkeepers has been
obscured, perhaps, by the brilliance of the Los Angeles Galaxy's
attack, but his play in the nets has plenty to do with why they're
a favorite to capture the MLS crown next month.
</P>
<P>
   The former UCLA standout has provided the backbone for the
Galaxy (22-7, 64 points), who continue their countdown to the
playoffs tonight in San Jose against the last-place Clash (11-18,
27), and if that's a surprise, well what's new?
</P>
<P>
   After a season spent in Jorge Campos' shadow, Hartman, 24, has
performed beyond all expectations this season, but that's just
habit. Everywhere he's played, he's been doubted, and each time
he's demonstrated his worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's proven a lot this season,'' says Zak Abdel, the Galaxy's
goalkeeping coach and a former netminder for Egypt's national team.
``I told everyone he'd be special. ... He wants to play in England,
and to be honest, I think he's good enough to make it right now. If
he gets a little more experience, he'll be big-time.''
</P>
<P>
   Credit an undying confidence and an unerring work ethic, which
has carried him through difficulties in high school (he was only a
part-time starter at Peninsula in Palos Verdes), in college (he
settled for Division II Cal State Dominguez Hills, then moved to
Westwood to be the Bruins' No.3 'keeper), and leading to the pros
(he had to pay his own way to Umbro's goalkeeping camp, where he
turned heads with his work habits and shot-stopping abilities).
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everything Kevin's gotten and that he's done with the
Galaxy is attributable to his work ethic, his professional approach
to the game,'' says Sigi Schmid, Hartman's coach at UCLA.
``Everybody gets addicted to Kevin once they see him work. You
know, here's somebody who really wants it. He's constantly had to
prove it, but he's always had the confidence in himself that he can
do it. More than that, he's got the work ethic to build up that
confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   It's led to a sensational sophomore season in MLS, where he
ranks third with a 1.48 goals-against average and first with 20
wins.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Kevin came into the league, he was a little
helter-skelter,'' Galaxy coach Octavio Zambrano says. ``His natural
ability, I think, carried him a lot through college, it got him
through at that level. When he came into the pros, I think he
realized it's a lot more about control, about being in control and
transmitting and radiating that to your defense and teammates.''
</P>
<P>
   He's added nuance to his game, learned how to manage his defense
and control his box, and he's emerged as another fine goalkeeping
prospect for America's future.
</P>
<P>
   He's not surprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never lacked confidence in myself,'' he says. ``Sometimes
I believe I'm not playing well or I'm not in form, but I've always
had a belief in myself and I always will. I believe I can play at
this level, and I believe there's a level beyond this I can play
at. As I get older and I progress toward the peak of my career, I
hope I find myself there.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Galaxy notes: Defender Robin Fraser and midfielder Clint
Mathis will miss tonight's match, serving suspensions for yellow
card accumulation, and midfielder Martin Machon is playing for
Guatemala in an exhibition against a South American all-star team.
It is Machon's first chance to impress new Guatemala coach Lujan
Manera. ... In addition, defender Ezra Hendrickson and midfielder
Wellington Sanchez are slowed by ankle injuries. ... Lawrence
Lozzano, acquired Aug. 7 from San Jose, is expected to make his
Galaxy debut tonight, teaming with Steve Jolley in central defense.
A hamstring injury has sidelined the Cerritos native since June.
... No English-language radio yet: Attorneys for the Galaxy and
One-on-One Sports are poring over contracts, and a deal could be
announced later this week. ... San Jose's faint hopes to reach the
MLS playoffs will die with a loss in any of their last three games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-98 2334EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980915.0502 </DOCNO>
