   In campaign appearances, Ms. Nappier stressed her qualifications
and played down the issue of race. ``This is not a campaign about
black and white,'' she said. ``It's about green, and how to get
someone in office who will protect the state's assets and make them
grow.''
</P>
<P>
   Lecce said that he resented the need to constantly answer
questions about diversity on the ticket, noting that he had started
campaigning two years ago and that party leaders could have found
another slot for a black candidate. He told audiences how he had
immigrated from Italy at age 11, and bolstered the point by
displaying the Statue of Liberty on his campaign literature.
</P>
<P>
   In the race for the Secretary of the state nomination, Mrs.
Scalettar stressed her endorsement by leading state Democrats,
while Ms. Bysiewicz spent about $100,000 on television ads
featuring her family.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the two statewide contests, the other race that drew the
most attention and spending was a four-way contest for the
Democratic nomination to replace Mrs. Kennelly as the U.S.
representative from the 1st Congressional District, which covers
the Hartford area.
</P>
<P>
   In that race, John B. Larson, 50, a former president pro tem of
the state Senate, defeated his main competitor, Miles S. Rapoport
the secretary of the state.
</P>
<P>
   After what had been a low-key campaign, the two front-runners
engaged in a ferocious television battle last weekend. Rapoport,
48, accused Larson of voting to cut services and raise taxes when
he was in the state Senate. Larson said that the advertisements
were a gross distortion of his records. He took ads branding
Rapoport ``desperate.''
</P>
<P>
   Rapoport, who has built his career as an advocate of campaign
finance reform, defended his ads. ``A close race in the final days
_ you can't be so nice that you're undone,'' he said as he voted on
Tuesday morning. Rapoport offered a last-minute truce in the
television war. Larson, who had accused Rapoport of abandoning his
principles for expediency, refused the offer. ``That's like bombing
Pearl Harbor and then saying, `Oh, never mind,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rapoport won the endorsement of many labor unions, who helped
him field more than 1,000 poll workers and telephone canvassers
today. The other two candidates were James R. McCavanaugh, 58, a
16-year state representative, and Joseph M. Suggs Jr., 58, a former
state treasurer.
</P>
<P>
   The 1st District is strongly Democratic, so the winner of the
party's nomination generally is assured election in November. But a
Republican candidate, Kevin J. O'Connor, signaled that he planned a
scrappy campaign by buying television ads on Hartford newscasts on
Tuesday night, finishing with the slogan: ``You gotta believe.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
