<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 23:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7229 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-ELECT-AG-NYT &LR;      09-15 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ELECT-AG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPITZER WINS NEW YORK AG RACE; WILL BATTLE VACCO IN NOVEMBER
ELECTION  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Eliot Spitzer, a wealthy Manhattan lawyer who spent
millions of his own money to finance a campaign for state attorney
general, won the Democratic Party primary nomination on Tuesday,
and will take on the Republican incumbent, Dennis Vacco, in the
November election.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer beat back a challenge from three other Democrats: state
Sen. Catherine Abate; G. Oliver Koppell, a former attorney general;
and Evan Davis, a former counsel to Gov. Mario Cuomo.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer, a former Manhattan prosecutor who has never held public
office, showed he was a fierce campaigner and a moderate on social
issues.
</P>
<P>
   With 71 percent of the precincts reporting, Spitzer received
179,257 votes, or 41 percent. Ms. Abate received 120,731 votes, or
28 percent; Koppell 94,229 votes, or 22 percent; and Davis 39,198
votes, or 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Because of his immense personal wealth, Spitzer was able to
mount the kind of aggressive media campaign that won him the name
recognition that other candidates appeared to lack. He spent about
$3 million in his primary campaign and plans to spend millions more
for the general election.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer's money itself became an issue during the campaign, as
the three other candidates repeatedly accused him of trying to buy
the election. His father is a wealthy Manhattan real estate
developer and lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   For Spitzer, Tuesday's victory was an affirmation of his costly
efforts to rise from political obscurity. In 1994, he spent roughly
$3 million, much of it his own money, in a failed attempt to win
the Democratic nomination for attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long road to get here,'' he told supporters
gathered on Tuesday night at the Broadway Ballroom at the Grand
Hyatt Hotel in Manhattan. ``But tonight, we begin a campaign to
return the majesty and dignity of the attorney general's office.''
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer's opponent in November, Vacco, was elected attorney
general in 1994, and is widely viewed as the weakest of the
statewide incumbents up for re-election this year.
</P>
<P>
   Vacco has been accused of undermining the integrity of the
office. Among the complaints are that he fired dozens of lawyers
and replaced them with less experienced ones with ties to the
Republican and Conservative Parties. On at least seven occasions,
his office was criticized for missing filing deadlines and court
dates.
</P>
<P>
   Vacco has also come under attack because he resisted joining a
lawsuit that many other states had filed against tobacco companies
to recoup Medicaid dollars they had spent treating tobacco-related
illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   He eventually sued, but only after nearly two years of criticism
accusing him of being soft on tobacco companies because they are
major donors to the state Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   More than that, though, poll after poll indicates that Vacco is
not very well known among many New Yorkers. His challenger will
have the opportunity to conduct an aggressive advertising campaign
intended to define Vacco in the minds of voters.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Vacco could prove to be a formidable candidate. He has
more than $3.1 million in his campaign coffers and will no doubt
receive more money from the state party should he need it.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, he has shown a talent for getting good publicity on
a variety of consumer-related issues like cracking down on ticket
scalpers and abuses by health insurers. He may also benefit greatly
from the coattails of the popular Republican governor, George
Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes in the race are high. The attorney general's office
has an annual budget of $139 million and a staff of 450 lawyers who
defend the state from hundreds of lawsuits, from charges against
government officials to complaints over accidents on state
property.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge for both Vacco and Spitzer will be generating
interest in a race that threatens to be overshadowed by the other
major races, primarily those for governor and U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the primary, the four Democratic candidates for
attorney general complained that they were having a hard time
getting voters to pay attention, let alone choose a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   In a race in which there were few ideological differences
between the candidates, the central issue became who had the right
credentials for the job.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer, a partner at a New York City law firm, founded a
nonprofit group, the Center for the Community Interest, that seeks
to help community organizations combat crime and other problems.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Abate, who represents Manhattan in the state Senate, has run
a number of major agencies, including the city's Probation and
Correction Departments.
</P>
<P>
   Davis has a long legal background that includes a Supreme Court
clerkship, work on the House Watergate inquiry, and a partnership
at a large New York City law firm.
</P>
<P>
   Koppell, who represented the Bronx in the state Assembly for 23
years, was selected by his colleagues in 1993 to complete the
unexpired term of Robert Abrams as attorney general, though he was
defeated in his bid for a full term in office.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
