<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 23:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7232 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-ELECT-GOV-NYT &LR;      09-15 1184
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ELECT-GOV-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VALLONE WINS DEMOCRATIC GUBERNATORIAL NOMINATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Trouncing his opponents in the Democratic
gubernatorial primary, Peter Vallone, who has spent a
quarter-century on the New York City Council and 12 years as its
leader, propelled himself Tuesday into a far more daunting struggle
against Gov. George Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki, a first-term Republican, enjoys widespread popularity
and faces none of the voter unrest that sent scores of incumbents
into retirement in 1994. Vallone, the speaker of the Council, has
less than $1 million left in his campaign treasury, while Pataki,
one of the most prodigious fund-raisers in the nation, has well
over $10 million. And Vallone does not have the Liberal Party
nomination, without which no Democrat has won statewide office in
half a century.
</P>
<P>
   As a moderate on social issues who preaches fiscal conservatism,
Vallone, 63, is his party's most centrist gubernatorial nominee in
a generation or more, a potential advantage at a time when many
voters have turned away from the left.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the name recognition his primary victory will gain
him, he enters the general election campaign with less stature
statewide than any Democratic gubernatorial nominee since at least
1966. Since then, the party's standard-bearers have been Arthur
Goldberg, a former justice of the Supreme Court, Hugh Carey and
Mario Cuomo.
</P>
<P>
   Such obstacles could not temper Vallone's delight at his
election-night headquarters at the Grand Hyatt hotel in
mid-Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels really, really good,'' Vallone said in an interview
Tuesday night, an hour after the polls closed. ``What I've been
talking about for over a year, putting New York first again and
jobs and education, has been well received, whether it's in Erie
County or St. Lawrence County or Bronx County.''
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged that he faced an uphill fight, and with a tweak
at Pataki's paid speechmaking, challenged the governor to a series
of debates. ``I'd like to see him debate me as often as he gave
these speeches out of state,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Interviews with voters leaving the polls indicated that Vallone
had taken three-fifths of the vote, to one-fifth for Lt. Gov. Betsy
McCaughey Ross. Charles Hynes, the Brooklyn district attorney, and
James Larocca, a former state transportation commissioner, finished
a distant third and fourth, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   McCaughey Ross conceded defeat in an interview within minutes of
the polls' closing Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing that my supporters and I have been
able to do in this race is to define the agenda, to identify the
issues that will be the focus of this gubernatorial campaign,'' she
said. In particular, she cited her calls for improved schools and
expanded kindergarten and prekindergarten education.
</P>
<P>
   She said there was ``no question'' she would continue
campaigning as the nominee of the Liberal Party. Many of the
Democrats who were working for her campaign planned to abandon it
if she lost the primary, rather than risk being blackballed from
party politics.
</P>
<P>
   McCaughey Ross never managed to shake off the unsavory images
left by her unorthodox history in politics, or her well-publicized
money troubles in the stretch run. Her campaign was also hobbled by
a dissension that saw several top officials depart.
</P>
<P>
   Once the lieutenant governor's campaign began to fade in
midsummer, Vallone was left with no real competition.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to seize the interest of voters who seemed either
distracted from the contest or bored by it, McCaughey Ross turned
in the final week to attacking Vallone, questioning his commitment
to abortion rights and education.
</P>
<P>
   In the primary for lieutenant governor, Sandra Frankel, a town
supervisor from the Rochester area, easily bested Charlie King, a
Manhattan lawyer, and Clyde Rabideau, the mayor of Plattsburg, whom
Vallone had tapped as his preferred choice. Ms. Frankel had 52
percent of the vote to 32 percent for King and 16 percent for
Rabideau.
</P>
<P>
   Vallone's victory was strikingly broad, cutting across all
divisions of race, sex, age, income, education, religion, region
and political beliefs. Exit polls indicated that he even defeated
McCaughey Ross by almost 2-1 in upstate New York, a region where he
was virtually unknown six months ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Council speaker may actually be better known than Pataki was
at this time four years ago, when he was a first-term state
senator. But Vallone lacks a crucial advantage Pataki had in 1994:
the backing of Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, who helped his fellow
Republican raise $14 million.
</P>
<P>
   Vallone carries into the seven-week general election campaign
the burden of the assumption, shared even by many in the party,
that the governor is unbeatable.
</P>
<P>
   That pessimism has hung like a pall over the Democratic side of
the race from the start. Last year, the two Democrats who were
viewed as the strongest potential challengers to Pataki bowed out,
Rep. Charles Schumer to run for Senate and State Comptroller H.
Carl McCall to run for re-election.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign against Pataki could be further complicated by the
presence of two well-known, minor-party candidates on the Nov. 3
ballot who could splinter the anti-Pataki vote. McCaughey Ross is
the Liberal Party nominee, and B. Thomas Golisano, a wealthy
Rochester businessman, is running for the second time on the
Independence Party line.
</P>
<P>
   The contest has stirred great interest only through the
soap-operatic travails of McCaughey Ross, Pataki's one-time
protegee, who engaged in a highly public feud with him and who
switched only last year from Republican to Democrat. Throughout the
primary contest, the three other candidates have questioned the
sincerity of her conversion and her positions.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 2, she confirmed what Democrats had long suspected,
that her husband, Wilbur Ross, an investment banker, would not
provide anywhere near the $10 million for her campaign that she had
predicted. Ross withdrew half the $4 million he had given to her
candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Ross, who has had little to say publicly about the
matter, released a terse statement saying, ``My office has received
a number of phone calls from reporters today, so I wanted to let
members of the media know that I voted for Betsy today prior to
going out of state on a business trip.''
</P>
<P>
   Vallone, a lifelong resident of Astoria, Queens, has spent most
of his years in and around city politics. The son of a judge, he
was a lawyer in private practice, ran for Congress in 1972 _ his
only electoral loss _ and was elected to the City Council in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1986, he has been chief of the Council, the
second-most-powerful post in city government. Through much of the
year, even as polls showed McCaughey Ross leading, Vallone largely
ignored her, confident that voters would conclude that he was the
only viable Democratic candidate. Primary voters may have got the
message; in exit polls, they overwhelmingly chose him as the
Democrat with the best chance of beating
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
