<SLUG> BC-NY-ELECT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-580(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHUMER BEATS FERRARO IN SENATE PRIMARY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs to reflect that Schumer has definitely won, and for general
refinements) (DUPLICATION WARNING: Also moving in ``a'' news file) 
(th) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Charles Schumer, a nine-term Brooklyn congressman who
had never before run for office outside his Park Slope
neighborhood, won the Democratic nomination to challenge Sen.
Alfonse D'Amato on Tuesday night, overwhelming Geraldine Ferraro in
her second attempt to return to public office.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer, reaping the fruits of a decade of fund-raising and a
campaign marked by rigorous discipline and ceaseless television
advertising, easily defeated both Ferraro and the third major
candidate, New York City Public Advocate Mark Green. The scope of
Schumer's victory showed strength that crossed geographic, sex and
ethnic lines, and suggested that he had gone some distance in
erasing doubts many Democrats once said they had about his
viability as a challenger to D'Amato.
</P>
<P>
   The results also appeared to signal an end to one of the most
notable political careers of the last 20 years. Ferraro, the 1984
Democratic vice presidential nominee, had said she decided to run
for the Senate again this time largely because she felt she had
been unfairly deprived of the 1992 Senate nomination, because of
unfair attacks on her ethics. Ferraro was spared such treatment
this time, yet a voter survey conducted by Edison Media Research
suggested that she was losing by a far larger margin this time than
in 1992, when she was defeated by just under 11,000 votes.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer's victory came on a day of notably low voter turnout,
reflecting an absence of interest in the contests.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic primary voters also chose New York City Council
Speaker Peter Vallone to challenge Gov. George Pataki, in a primary
that turned out to be far less competitive than had been expected,
according to interviews with voters. Vallone easily defeated three
candidates, including Lt. Gov. Betsy McCaughey Ross, the former
Republican running in a Democratic primary for the first time. Ms.
McCaughey Ross' name will still appear on the Liberal Party line in
November.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki is heavily favored, both because he has raised a huge
amount of money, more than $15 million as of July, and because Ms.
McCaughey, who pledged Tuesday night to campaign aggressively on
the Liberal Party line, is apt to split the anti-Pataki vote.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer's opponents called to concede even before the final
results were tallied. Green called Schumer at 9:02 Tuesday night,
and Ferraro conceded at 9:34, Schumer's aides said.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer, in the prepared text of his acceptance speech, signaled
that after a primary in which he avoided attacks on his opponents,
he intended to run aggressively.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we've learned one thing in his last 18 years in the Senate,
it is that Al D'Amato has been there too long,'' Schumer said.
``You just can't trust him to do the right thing, and New Yorkers
deserve a senator we can be proud of.''
</P>
<P>
   As Schumer's remarks suggested, the outcome of the Senate vote
sets the stage for what is almost sure to be one of the most
ferociously fought races in the country this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer and D'Amato are both known in Washington as streetwise,
ambitious politicians who share talents for raising money, getting
publicity and assailing their opponents. Schumer has spent much of
this decade quietly preparing himself for the statewide stage, and
D'Amato, facing what polls have long suggested would be a difficult
bid for a fourth term, has been preparing for this re-election
almost from the moment he won his third term in 1992.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Even before the polls were closed Tuesday, Schumer's media
consultant, Hank Morris, was in a television editing booth,
producing advertisements directed at D'Amato that will be broadcast
in the next two days. And even before Schumer had made his way out
to declare victory Tuesday night, the D'Amato campaign issued a
withering statement reprising what has been the senator's standard
attack on Democratic candidates: that they are too liberal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once again, the Democratic Party has nominated the most
left-of-center candidate they could,'' said D'Amato's campaign
manager, Jon Lerner. ``In November, the voters will have a clear
choice between Chuck Schumer, who believes in old-style
tax-and-spend liberalism, and Al D'Amato, who has a proven record
of fighting for the forgotten middle class.''
</P>
<P>
   In other statewide races, Sandra Frankel, a town supervisor from
a suburb of Rochester, was leading in the race to run with Vallone
as the Democratic candidate for lieutenant governor. And Eliot
Spitzer, a lawyer who used his family fortune to finance a campaign
that was also heavy on television advertising, was leading in the
nomination for state attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 primary shaped up as a sharp setback for women who have
been seeking to break into the upper ranks of New York state
government. Earlier this year, it seemed that the Democrats might
have three women on the statewide ticket: Ms. Ferraro for senator,
Ms. McCaughey Ross for governor and Catherine Abate for attorney
general. It now appears that there will be only two women running
for statewide office. Ms. Frankel and Mary Donohue, a Republican,
will oppose each other for lieutenant governor, a position of
virtually no importance in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro and Ms. McCaughey Ross explicitly presented their
candidacies as appeals for women to gain political stature in New
York, a state that has never elected a woman as senator or
governor. ``If they turn out, I win this,'' Ferraro said of women
during a last campaign appearance Tuesday. But voter surveys found
that most women disregarded those appeals, voting instead for
Schumer and Vallone.
</P>
<P>
   The contest to challenge D'Amato was remarkable for its lack of
open conflict, as the candidates avoided the kind of exchanges that
characterized the 1992 primary. One benefit of the decorous race
will become clear Wednesday morning, when all three Democratic
Senate candidates are to appear at a breakfast together with state
party chairwoman Judith Hope. In 1992, by contrast, Ms. Ferraro did
not endorse the Democratic candidate, Robert Abrams, until the last
week of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Schumer's strong performance was a clear tribute to the
influence of money on American politics today. Schumer, who is a
member of the House Banking Committee, raised $13 million for the
race, more than five times as much as either Ferraro or Green. The
benefits of Schumer's fund-raising could be seen on television
stations across the state: an advertising campaign that began at
the start of the year and built to a crescendo in the final two
weeks of the race.
</P>
<P>
   The television ads proved to be particularly significant this
year because of the chronic lack of attention paid to the race by
the New York media. The candidates often found themselves giving
major speeches or press conferences with only a single television
camera in sight.
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro on Tuesday characterized the contest as a ``a fight
between money power and people power.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Ferraro and Green blamed their losses, to a large extent,
on Schumer's formidable fund-raising advantage. For his part,
Schumer implicitly pointed to his campaign bankroll as evidence
that he would be able to mount the challenge to D'Amato that Abrams
had failed to make.
</P>
<P>
   On the morning after the 1992 Democratic primary, Abrams
immediately began trying to raise money, while D'Amato's aides
headed for television stations, where they bought time to broadcast
a flood of ads attacking Abrams.
</P>
<P>
   The survey of voters leaving the polls suggested some areas of
strength for Schumer. Schumer defeated Ms. Ferraro among female
voters, a critical New York constituency that D'Amato has
aggressively courted for much of the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer received about 40 percent of the upstate vote, an area
where the Brooklyn Democrat was assumed to be weak, and where
D'Amato must do well to win a fourth term. Similarly, Schumer, who
is Jewish, received about 40 percent of the Roman Catholic vote,
another constituency at the heart of D'Amato's base.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-98 2350EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980915.0507 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 23:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7246 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-ELECT-1STLD-WRITET     09-15 1075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ELECT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-580(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHUMER BEATS FERRARO IN SENATE PRIMARY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs to reflect that Schumer has definitely won, and for general
refinements) (DUPLICATION WARNING: Also moving in ``p'' news file) 
(th) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
