A7252 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     09-15 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QB PAIN REIGNS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   He bounced around professional football for a decade before
signing a free-agent contract with his current team a year ago. He
has never played in a Super Bowl. He started one game last season.
</P>
<P>
   He is smaller than most quarterbacks though probably smarter,
and if he makes a lasting mark on the sport, he will do it as a
coach or executive.
</P>
<P>
   He gets by on a detailed knowledge of the playbook and a
dependable if unspectacular arm. He won't throw it to the other
team too often. He won't throw it 70 yards in the air either.
</P>
<P>
   He is the average backup quarterback. And, be he ever so humble,
this season he is the most valuable player in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   In the first two weeks, big-name starters were bruised, broken,
torn, sprained, strained and brained at the most alarming rate
since the alarming rate of !ital!last!off! September.
</P>
<P>
   And in their place, nameless, faceless, graceless second
stringers have shucked their clipboards and NFL Properties baseball
caps and tried to keep playoff hopes alive.
</P>
<P>
   Already, 12 backup quarterbacks have seen action because of
injuries, and they're a more varied bunch than our ``average''
would suggest. There are aging former starters: Randall Cunningham,
who directed Minnesota's winning touchdown drive at St. Louis on
Sunday, and Dave Krieg, who earned the save in Tennessee's opening
victory at Cincinnati, and Bubby Brister (Denver), John Friesz
(Seattle), Rich Gannon (Kansas City) and Steve Walsh (Tampa Bay).
There are young guys eager for a shot: Danny Wuerffel, who survived
the Carolina rush to lead New Orleans to a second straight victory,
and Trent Green (Washington), Eric Zeier (Baltimore), Jason Garrett
(Dallas) and Donald Hollas (Oakland). And there's Doug Flutie, who
nearly pulled out a victory for Buffalo at San Diego in his return
from the Canadian Football League.
</P>
<P>
   Together, they are proving that as long as quarterback injuries
seem to be unpreventable, an NFL team had better have something in
reserve.
</P>
<P>
   ``The challenge for personnel people and coaches is the same''
from year to year, Randy Cross, the former UCLA and San Francisco
49ers lineman who is now a network analyst, said from his home in
Georgia. ``This just emphasizes the need to have a guy on the bench
who knows your system.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the Year of the Quarterback only in the medical journals.
</P>
<P>
   One quarterback's season ended late in the opening game: New
Orleans' Billy Joe Hobert (torn right Achilles' tendon).
</P>
<P>
   Two are expected to miss as much as half the season after
hurting themselves Sunday: Dallas' Aikman (broken left collarbone)
and Minnesota's Brad Johnson (broken right leg).
</P>
<P>
   Two were injured in week 1 and sat out week 2: Kansas City's
Elvis Grbac (sprained right shoulder) and Washington's Gus Frerotte
(sprained left shoulder).
</P>
<P>
   Five were injured in week 1 and returned to action in week 2:
Oakland's Jeff George (hyperextended left elbow), Tampa Bay's Trent
Dilfer (bruised right thigh), Tennessee's Steve McNair (bruised
right elbow), Buffalo's Rob Johnson (concussion) and Baltimore's
Jim Harbaugh (broken right ring finger).
</P>
<P>
   And two quarterbacks could join the casualty list in week 3
after getting hurt in week 2: Denver's John Elway (strained right
hamstring) and Philadelphia's Bobby Hoying (sprained right knee).
As of Tuesday, each planned to play Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL office wants you to think this is nothing unusual. It
reports that 26 of the 30 teams had the same starting quarterback
in games 1 and 2, the same number as the first two weeks of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime quarterbacks get hurt, somebody wants to write a story
declaring a trend,'' said Greg Aiello, the NFL's vice president of
communications. ``We could show you stories people wrote 20 years
ago about the quarterback being an endangered species.''
</P>
<P>
   But the NFL's accounting of injury-related substitutions doesn't
count Washington's, even though it was Frerotte's injury that gave
Green the chance to outperform him and win the start Monday night.
And it overlooks the fact the 12 teams that have been forced to use
backup quarterbacks in '98 are two more than in '97.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever.
</P>
<P>
   The consistency of the problem only goes to show it's
unsolvable. A series of rule changes in recent years, banning head
hunting, defining late hits and liberalizing the grounding-the-ball
rule, have failed to make the world of faster, stronger
pass-rushers safe for quarterbacks.
</P>
<P>
   What can possibly be done to help a quarterback running for
extra yardage instead of sliding down (Aikman), hitting his passing
hand on a rusher (Harbaugh), rolling out, untouched (Elway), or
fading back, untouched (Hobert)? The only ``preventable'' injury in
the first two weeks was Brad Johnson's; the play should have been
whistled dead after a Minnesota lineman's false start.
</P>
<P>
   What to do?
</P>
<P>
   Sign the best backup you can afford.
</P>
<P>
   Which was easier before free agency and salary caps, when Miami
could back up Bob Griese with Earl Morrall, and Dan Marino with Don
Strock, and San Francisco could have future Hall of Famers Joe
Montana and Steve Young in the same locker room. Now, a
second-stringer makes one (1) solid start, as Rob Johnson did for
Jacksonville last year, and somebody else wants to pay him $25
million to start.
</P>
<P>
   It was Buffalo that traded for Johnson and paid him all that
money last summer. And you know what the Bills also did last
summer? They signed Flutie as a backup.
</P>
<P>
   These days, when you can't be safe, you don't want to be sorry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
