</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-ASTROS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASTROS' DIM METS' WILD-CARD HOPES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ For two games in a row, the New York Mets rallied here
on ninth-inning home runs to stay alive in games crucial to the
National League wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, they went on to beat the Houston Astros in 13
innings, and when Chicago lost later that night the Mets and Cubs
were tied for the wild card. But Tuesday, in the first game of a
doubleheader, it was Houston's turn, as the Astros hit a pair of
extra-inning home runs in a 6-5 12-inning victory.
</P>
<P>
   The first, by Jeff Bagwell in the bottom of the 11th, erased the
lead Carlos Baerga and Rey Ordonez had given the Mets with
back-to-back doubles in the top of the inning. The second, by Derek
Bell leading off the 12th, gave Houston a franchise-record 97
victories and left the Mets a half-game behind the Cubs with both
teams scheduled to play later Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have played two tough games here yesterday and today,''
said John Franco, who gave up Bagwell's home run. ``At least
everyone knows we're here.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time the Mets and Astros played as significant a series
here was October 1986, in perhaps the greatest National League
championship series ever.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, the stakes are a little lower for the Astros,
who clinched the NL Central on Monday night. But they are not
necessarily lower for the Mets, and the last two days have been
eerily reminiscent of the sixth game of that 1986 series, when the
Mets outlasted the Astros in 16 innings to advance to the World
Series.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Mets are trying to advance to the post-season for the
first time in a decade. And for the second consecutive game in the
Astrodome, they rallied from a 4-2 deficit with a two-run
ninth-inning home run to force extra innings.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the big hit was by Carlos Baerga, whose dramatic shot
came off of Scott Elarton. And in the bottom of the ninth, the
rookie Jay Payton, who has had his elbow rebuilt twice, made a
perfect one-hop throw from left field to Todd Hundley to cut down
Tim Bogar at the plate with the potential winning run.
</P>
<P>
   Turk Wendell came on to bail the Mets out of further trouble in
that inning. Baerga, who had been in a terrible slump, doubled to
left center with two out in the top of the 11th for his fourth hit
of the game. And when Ordonez, who in the second inning had hit his
first homer since Sept. 2, 1997, followed with a run-scoring double
to right-center field, it looked as if the Mets were headed for
their second improbable comeback victory in a row.
</P>
<P>
   All they needed was three outs. But Franco, who had closed out
Monday night's victory for his franchise-record 37th save,
surrendered a lead-off home run to Jeff Bagwell on his fourth pitch
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to get the ball in on Bagwell and it sunk away,'' said
Franco, who had converted 16 straight saves since the last time he
failed, on Aug. 4. ``And he's a low-ball hitter.''
</P>
<P>
   Franco, who warmed up in the bullpen three times today and three
times Monday, added, ``I just missed my location, and it may have
come from a little bit of a tired arm.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Franco eventually struck out Carl Everett with runners on first
and third to end the 11th. But when Bell led off the bottom of the
12th by belting a full-count pitch from the rookie right-hander
Jeff Tam, the Mets faced the second game Tuesday night knowing had
fallen behind the Cubs, if only for a few hours, in the post-season
chase.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of ball game,'' Mets manager Bobby Valentine said
between games. ``It was a really good one. A good hitter got a home
run off a good pitcher. We did everything we could.''
</P>
<P>
   No one could remember the last time Baerga had delivered as
meaningful a hit. Actually, no one could recall Baerga's last
significant hit at all.
</P>
<P>
   The second baseman's average had shriveled to .266 before the
game from .292 on Aug. 6. On Monday night, Valentine had pinch-hit
for the switch-hitting Baerga _ who is better from the left side _
with the left-handed hitting Matt Franco in a close game, something
Valentine would probably not have done earlier in the year.
</P>
<P>
   So there was Baerga standing in against the right-handed Elarton
with one out and one on in the top of the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Baerga had singled off Shane Reynolds with two out in the second
and scored on Ordonez's shot to left, which snapped a streak of 527
homerless at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Like Baerga, Ordonez, who has now homered once in each of his
first three major league seasons, was due. And the shortstop's
blast gave the Mets a 2-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Baerga nearly gave the Mets a two-run lead when he grounded a
shot toward the hole between short and third with Lenny Harris on
second and two out in the fourth. But the ball hit Harris in the
right foot, and Harris was automatically out.
</P>
<P>
   That came back to haunt the Mets in the bottom of the fourth
when Armando Reynoso bounced a pair of wild pitches off Hundley,
which led to a pair of Houston runs, giving the Astros a 3-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell singled past a diving Ordonez for a two-out insurance
run off Greg McMichael in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   But then Monday's hero, Brian McRae, drew a walk off the
6-foot-8-inch Elarton. Harris followed with a fielder's choice
grounder but beat the relay to keep the Mets alive.
</P>
<P>
   Up stepped Baerga, who lined his sixth homer of the season into
the right-field corner, setting the stage for Bagwell and Bell.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-98 2352EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
