r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-STARS-TEX     09-15 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MODANO, HULL AND LEHTINEN ON TWO-WAY STREET FOR STARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VAIL, Colo. _Through the mundane workings of a 50-player NHL
training camp, the trio of Mike Modano, Brett Hull and Jere
Lehtinen shines like an Eric Clapton guitar solo at a high school
talent show.
</P>
<P>
   Even during the Stars' sometimes cattlelike workouts, it's easy
to discern the dominance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Holy cow,'' center Brian Skrudland said. ``You can sure tell
when they step on the ice.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Stars' deadliest offensive line has yet to score a
goal in the first two days of scrimmage action at training camp,
the Modano-Hull-Lehtinen combination has been making slick breakout
moves, finding each other with no-look passes and tossing some
pucks blindly into areas of the ice just in time for a linemate to
outrace a defender for possession.
</P>
<P>
   In short, the trio has been a burst of playmaking electricity on
a team that has a history of doing things the simple way.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is strong chemistry on finding each other, on getting
open,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``It's really evident.''
</P>
<P>
   But as much as the chemistry might be potent, Hitchcock isn't
about to crown the triumvirate the NHL's top scoring line. Instead,
the Stars' coach is warning that the line has to find its niche as
a combination of great offense with great defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Modano has to be our best checking center iceman,'' Hitchcock
said. ``He has to go out and play against the other team's best
players, match their intensity level and be prepared to outplay
them. And not just offensively, but defensively.''
</P>
<P>
   The temptation, of course, is to wind them up and turn them
loose. After all, Hull, who was a free-agent pickup in the summer,
has averaged 55 goals a season throughout his career, Modano was
ranked this year as the No. 8 player in the NHL by ``The Hockey
News'' and Lehtinen is last year's winner of the Selke Trophy for
top defensive forward in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, they can work this two-way hockey thing out for
themselves, can't they?
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't afford for Mike to get away from'' his defensive
role, Hitchcock said. ``We've had discussions with him and
discussions with Hull.''
</P>
<P>
   And both say they are on board. Modano swears by his new status
as a player who emphasizes defense as much as offense. It's that
change that has catapulted him to his high standing in the NHL. In
the seven seasons before Hitchcock installed him as a defensive
demon, Modano carried a career minus-34 ranking _ meaning that when
he was on the ice, there were 34 more even-strength goals scored
against his team than his team scored.
</P>
<P>
   In the past two seasons under Hitchcock's plan, Modano is a plus
68.
</P>
<P>
   ``The system works,'' Modano said.
</P>
<P>
   And Hull also is buying in. He's bucking his reputation as a
defensively deficient player by working hard on both sides of the
ice in training camp. Hitchcock even was so bold as to call Hull
``one of the best forecheckers in the NHL.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought Hitch was a smart coach,'' Hull said with a
laugh. ``Honestly, forechecking is just part of the game, and I've
always done it.''
</P>
<P>
   So if the chemistry is there and all three players are on board
with Hitchcock's philosophy to play them against the other team's
top offensive players, what can be accomplished in training camp?
Let's start the regular season, already.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to be fun to watch, and who knows how good they
can be,'' said Skrudland, a checking-line center who has seen his
share of offensively talented lines. ``And the funnest part is that
I'm not on the other team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
